<HEADLINE>
FISHER'S HOT HAND LEAVES UTAH SINGING THE BLUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; SALT LAKE CITY _ When the Lakers at last ended their five-game
funk against the Utah Jazz, it was supposed to be on the back of
Dennis Rodman's rebounding and confounding defense against Karl
Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Instead it was on Derek Fisher's jumpshots and Elden Campbell's
turnaround jumpers and !ital!his!off! defense of Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, the Lakers' starting point guard the first nine games of
the season before being demoted behind veteran Derek Harper,
provided 20 points in his best performance since last year. His
11-point second quarter keyed the run that staked the Lakers to a
game-high 14-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's huge,'' coach Kurt Rambis said of Fisher's breakout.
</P>
<P>
   He started slowly, with a couple of buckets to close out the
second quarter, then came furiously, scoring 11 straight, including
a three-point play and two 3-point shots, in a span of three
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When did he know the numbers were coming?
</P>
<P>
   ``The first shot,'' Fisher said. ``I could just tell the way I
let it go, I was in the flow of the game. I knew I wanted to have a
good game mentally, I just had to go out physically and put it
together.''
</P>
<P>
   He finished 6 for 8 from the field and 6 for 7 from the foul
line, adding three rebounds and a big, diving steal to ignite a
fast-break basket and three-point play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harp (Derek Harper) was telling me, `Stay aggressive.' I knew
in my mind that I wanted to stay aggressive, but priority one for
me has always been doing what's best for the team, trying to get
other guy the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Just another win:!off! Beating the Jazz certainly doesn't
solve all the Lakers' problems, but coming as the seventh win in
seven games, it certainly makes for a strong argument that the
Lakers are on the right track. And perhaps not in need of the Eddie
Jones-for-Glen Rice trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely feel like it,'' Fisher said when asked if the
team had enough weapons to win. ``The one thing we've recognized
lately is what we control is how we play when we're on the
basketball floor. I think once we start to focus on that,
everything else fell by the wayside.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Kobe Bryant of the trade, which will happen this week, if
at all, ``I don't think we can think about that, honestly. We're
playing some excellent basketball right now. It's important to
concentrate on that.''
</P>
<P>
   And no one was about to place too much significance on one win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good step, it's a confidence booster,'' Rambis said,
``but we still made a lot of mistakes tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
