<SLUG> BC-BKW-TEXAS-NCAA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGHORNS WOMEN `ECSTATIC' OVER NCAA INVITATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas coach Jody Conradt couldn't help it. With only 16
victories, she resigned herself to the fact that the Longhorns
might miss the NCAA Tournament for a second consecutive season. If
asked, she said her team would play in the Women's National
Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But with 75 percent of the field announced, the Longhorns were
seeded 12th in the East region and will face fifth-seeded Auburn
(19-8) on Friday in Blacksburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   While Conradt was pleasantly surprised, there was no suspense in
selecting the top four seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, Purdue, Louisiana Tech and Connecticut are the top
four seeds. Only UConn's (27-4) selection, which came over
higher-ranked Colorado State and Old Dominion, was surprising. CSU
and ODU earned No. 2 seeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team is absolutely ecstatic right now,'' Conradt said of
her 16-11 team. ``There is a renewed excitement among the players.
They are so fired up right now that they probably could fly into
Blacksburg right now on their own power.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns tied North Carolina State with the fewest number
of victories for any at-large selection. Only Appalachian State
(14-14), which received an automatic bid by winning the Southern
Conference tournament, won fewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Texas deserves to be in the NCAA, no doubt about it,''
said Nebraska coach Paul Sanderford, whose team is the 11th seed in
the West. ``If \Rthe Big 12\S can't justify sending five teams to
the NCAA Tournament, then how can the SEC get seven or eight?''
</P>
<P>
   Heading into this past weekend, the only Lone Star state team
thought to be a tournament lock was No. 9 Texas Tech. After winning
the Big 12 regular-season and conference tournament titles, the Red
Raiders earned the Midwest's second seed and will play host to
first- and second-round games.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen F. Austin (17-11) surprised everyone by winning the
Southland Conference tournament, earning its 12th consecutive NCAA
Tournament appearance. The 15th-seeded Ladyjacks face the Red
Raiders (28-3) at 8:30 p.m. Saturday on ESPN 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in the NCAA makes everything better,'' said Royce
Chadwick, whose team overcame injuries, more losses than in any
other season this decade and the death of a former teammate. ``We
haven't played well until this weekend and we are just excited to
be playing good basketball at this time of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   SMU was the final selection from Texas. The Mustangs (19-10)
stunned fourth-ranked Colorado State in the Western Athletic
Conference title game to earn their fifth appearance in the past
five seasons. The 11th-seeded Mustangs play sixth-seeded Toledo
(25-5) at 5 p.m. Saturday in Athens, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed in our seed,'' said SMU coach Rhonda
Rompola. ``I thought we'd be higher than that after our win over
the No. 4 team in the country. I don't think we are getting the
respect we deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   No other team from the WAC made the field. Last season the WAC
had a record five teams entered but none advanced beyond the second
round. New Mexico and Utah, thought to be strong candidates, did
not receive bids.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Lady Vols (28-2), the three-time defending NCAA
champions. prepare to defend their title as the top seed in the
East. It's the 11th time in 12 seasons that the second-ranked Lady
Vols have been a top seed.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last season, they aren't ranked No. 1 and they aren't
going in with the burden of being undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting \Rthree consecutive titles\S in perspective is hard,''
said Tennessee coach Pat Summitt, who seeks her seventh title. ``My
biggest concerns are not to get overanxious and quick-shoot the
ball. We can't get behind early against a tempo control team. That
happened against Purdue and LSU,'' the two teams to defeat the Lady
Vols.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue (28-1), ranked No. 1 in the nation, earned the top seed
in the Midwest. Coach Carolyn Peck's team defeated Tennessee early
in the season and appears to have one of the best chances of
dethroning the Lady Vols.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't put any undue pressure on ourselves,'' said Peck,
who is leaving Purdue after the season for the WNBA. ``That
Tennessee game was a great measuring stick. But it was just one
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Techsters (26-2) have arguably the toughest road of any
top seed with a possible second-round date against either No. 18
Penn State (21-7) or No. 19 Virginia (20-8).
</P>
<P>
   The Southeastern Conference was awarded an NCAA-record eight
bids, while the Atlantic Coast Conference and Big 12 earned five
spots.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament begins Friday at eight campus sub-regional sites.
/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
