<HEADLINE>
TROJANS, WAVES GET ANOTHER SHOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Some teams, like Mississippi State and Xavier,
were visibly disappointed to be relegated Sunday to the National
Invitation Tournament. But that wasn't the case for USC, which was
thrilled at its inclusion in the venerable, if not elite,
postseason tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans play Wyoming in Laramie at 6:30 p.m. (PST) on
Wednesday, in their first NIT appearance since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' USC coach Henry Bibby said. ``It's not a
second-rate tournament. It's for teams like us that didn't get off
to a strong (conference) start but are finishing strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans weren't the only local team to receive a berth in
the tournament. Pepperdine received its first NIT bid since 1993
and first postseason berth of any kind under coach Lorenzo Romar.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves (19-12) will play at Colorado (17-14) on Wednesday at
a time to be determined. The Buffaloes are led by 6-foot-4 guard
Kenny Price, who averages 15 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   If the Waves win, they would play the winner of the Mississippi
State-Colorado State game either next Monday or Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As for USC (15-12), it will face a Wyoming team that hasn't
played a game since defeating UNLV 79-76 on Feb. 27. The Cowboys
did not qualify for the Western Athletic Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys (17-9) feature 6-8 forward Ugo Udezue of Nigeria,
who averages 20.5 points and 7.7 rebounds. Freshman point guard
Chris McMillian of Brea averages 9.5 points and 4.9 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a game we can win,'' Bibby said. ``We don't know what
kind of team they are or what they run offensively or defensively,
but we'll find out.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Trojans win, they will play the winner of the Georgia
Tech-Oregon game either Monday or Tuesday. That means a possible
third meeting of the season with the Ducks, who have split with USC
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was some doubt whether the Trojans would qualify
for the NIT, even after Saturday's victory over Arizona State,
Bibby said he never worried that USC would not be selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt we would get in. I was very confident. I thought
we played well at the end,'' Bibby said. ``We beat some quality
teams. We're young and survived the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started playing better the last seven or eight games. I
think people say `They have been much better at the end.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This is USC's second postseason appearance in Bibby's three full
seasons as coach. USC went to the NCAA Tournament in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is excellent for the program. For recruiting. It's
excellent exposure,'' Bibby said. ``This is our championship. It's
a tournament we can go in and do some damage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
