<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S APT TO LOOK MUCH DIFFERENT OUTSIDE DOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ After a week observing spring training, it's
apparent that changes in the Mariners' team on the field for 1999
are of the size detectable by forensic microscopes instead of
sportswriters.
</P>
<P>
   As it has been for the last half of the decade, the Mariners
have a flair for longball and a prayer for pitching.
</P>
<P>
   The only substantive change for the Mariners on the field is the
field.
</P>
<P>
   The midseason switch of home ballyards is a rare thing in
baseball. In the 20th century, only four teams have intentionally
had two fields in one season _ Cincinnati, St. Louis, Pittsburgh
and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   None involved going, as the Mariners will, from inside to
outside.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Mariners have had some experience at other
outdoor parks, so it won't be quite like the graveyard shift
getting first-time day jobs.
</P>
<P>
   And the game remains the game _ so far, no one has indicated
that any Mariner will be required to run a post pattern into zone
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But the subtleties will be different. And baseball, with the
exception of spitting and labor strikes, is all about the little
things.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, most Mariner players share the view of catcher Dan
Wilson:
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only been in Seattle five years, but I can't wait to see
sun shine on the grass in the outfield, surrounded by a big
crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   But a quick survey of Mariner veterans _ each was asked what he
is most excited about and most apprehensive about in the new park _
made it clear that the hitters wondered if their strength won't be
sapped, while the pitchers think they might get small assists.
</P>
<P>
   To a man, none of them worried about the cost overruns at Safeco
Field or the expense to the taxpayer _ proof again that a
ballplayer's life is indeed a good one, as utterly free of
conscience as one can be outside of childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably will be the most exciting new stadium in any
sport, and it should be exciting for the fans and energize us,''
shortstop Alex Rodriguez said. ``I hope it's not a moist field.
With all the water we get in Seattle, I hope when you pick up a
ground ball, it doesn't feel like it just came out of a pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing is, hopefully the ball will carry. But in the
thick air, maybe it won't.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the experience of Edgar Martinez, who despite making a
living indoors has become knowledgable about Puget Sound's marine
climate and its impact on a spinning spheroid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The apprehension is that the ball won't go anywhere,'' he
said. ``Years ago I played in Tacoma and Bellingham, and the ball
didn't go very far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, when the roof is closed, I'm not sure how the wind and
drafts will affect the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Jamie Moyer worries how fly balls will look against the
retractable roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought they had the roof worked out in the Metrodome,
too,'' Moyer said of Minneapolis's translucent, baseball-colored
fabric roof. ``But it's a very common occurrence for visiting teams
to take two days to adjust. If it's a sunny day, forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   The new roof's metallic underside should offer sufficient
contrast with the ball. What it can also do is help mimic at least
partially what Moyer considers the greatest loss leaving the
Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans will still be loud, but the new park won't be as noisy,''
he said. ``The acoustics can't be as good. It's too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   In his ninth big-league season, the Mariners' No. 1 starter,
Jeff Fassero, will get to play mostly outdoors for the first time,
after six seasons indoors at Montreal. He thinks the M's might
catch a little break because of the grass field instead of turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a team with much footspeed,'' he said. ``Grass will
slow the ball down a bit and give the infield an extra half-step.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer and Fassero weren't sure about the park dimensions, but
they did know that when the fences were moved closer, it developed
from consultations with Mariner sluggers, not pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Another guy the ballpark pushers didn't consult was first
baseman David Segui.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed we're leaving the Kingdome,'' he
said. ``I've always liked it there. The dimensions are smaller, and
it's loud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure the new park will be an advantage or a
disadvantage. I think, for awhile, it's going to be strange for us.
Except for the fans cheering, it will be like a road stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   As always, Ken Griffey Jr. had a different take on things.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's the excitement of something special that's ours,''
he said. ``When we go to new stadiums in Toronto, Texas, Baltimore,
Cleveland, we walk around staring. Now people can come to our
stadium in awe.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey pointed out the concerns about air, light, grass and
roof become secondary to the peculiar urgency of this spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't go into the new stadium with a good start on the
field,'' he said, ``it won't be long before there's empty seats.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's fear is that, at about 15th in major-league payroll
this season but No. 1 in ballpark price, club management has
indulged cost overruns on the wrong thing.
</P>
<P>
   Which might be the most unforeseen subtlety of all.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
