<SLUG> BC-SAG-AWARDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENIGNI, PALTROW TOP WINNERS AT SCREEN ACTORS GUILD AWARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREG GITTRICH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- &UR;  &LR; Life was beautiful for actors Roberto Benigni
and Gwyneth Paltrow at the 5th Annual Screen Actors Guild Awards.
</P>
<P>
   The two took home ``actor'' statuettes Sunday evening for their
work in ``Life is Beautiful'' and ``Shakespeare in Love,''
respectively, in what has become a closely watched indicator of
Academy Award prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The show was held at Los Angeles' Shrine Auditorium, and was
broadcast live on TV's TNT Network.
</P>
<P>
   In categories not covered by the granddaddy of awards shows, the
Oscars, ``ER'' won for outstanding ensemble in a TV drama series,
and ``Shakespeare in Love'' won the award for best film ensemble
cast.
</P>
<P>
   Other awards went to a combination of veterans _ such as Robert
Duvall for his supporting role in the film ``A Civil Action.'' _
and relative newcomers, such as Angelina Jolie for her star turn as
a troubled model in the HBO TV movie ``Gia.''
</P>
<P>
   The Screen Actors Guild is a relative latecomer to the awards
show business, but organizers have made up for lost time by
attracting top talent to their show. The program is unique in
honoring actors from both film and television with awards voted on
by their peers: other actors.
</P>
<P>
   Even veteran actor Kirk Douglas, who was presented with a life
achievement award by Karl Malden, Lauren Bacall, Janet Leigh and
Dan Aykroyd, said he was honored to ``have an award from my fellow
actors.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas, 82, was feted with numerous clips from his films, and a
standing ovation from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare'' was a clear favorite, garnering both top female
actor and cast awards. The film is nominated for more Academy
Awards this year than any other film.
</P>
<P>
   Also receiving more than one award was TV drama ``ER,'' for its
cast and for female star Julianna Margulies.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Bates, who took home the supporting female actor award for
her role in the film ``Primary Colors,'' admitted she'd be happy if
it portended bigger things at the Oscars ceremony later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to win another Academy Award, especially for this
part,'' she told the press backstage.
</P>
<P>
   Several presenters and award winners commented sadly on the
death of legendary director Stanley Kubrick, who passed away in
London early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I envy a friend of mine who got to work for him recently. It's
a sad time for the industry,'' Bates said.
</P>
<P>
   Benigni described the director of such films as ``2001: A Space
Odyssey'' and ``A Clockwork Orange'' as ``a genius,'' likening him
to Italy's Federico Fellini and Japan's Akira Kurosawa.
</P>
<P>
   Other TV honors went to Sam Waterston for his role in ``Law &AMP;
Order''; to Michael J. Fox for ``Spin City''; to comedienne Tracey
Ullman for ``Tracey Takes On''; to Christopher Reeve for ``Rear
Window'' and to the cast of ``Ally McBeal'' for comedy ensemble
work.
</P>
<P>
   In all, it seemed a night of camaraderie for the actors present.
Accepting her award, Kathy Bates said giddily, ``I'm so excited. I
get to sit at the same table as Meryl Streep.''
</P>
<P>
   Streep, nominated for her role in ``One True Thing,'' reared her
head with laughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
