<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES GLADLY GO TO BIG DANCE WITHOUT CINDERELLA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ CBS had it right. Last year, the official network of
the NCAA tournament sent cameras to Montlake because Washington, a
bubble team, promised to make excellent theater during the
announcement of the 64-team draw.
</P>
<P>
   Get overlooked, and there is live footage of Husky heartbreak to
beam across the land. Call it the ``agony of defeat'' live shot.
</P>
<P>
   Get in, however, and there is that spontaneous eruption of
unbridled emotion _ the kind of feel-good cameo by an elated
bubblicious team that goes far to affirm that the NCAA tourney is
one of the biggest, zaniest, funnest, let-'er-rip sporting events
in the galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies circa 1998, those unheralded under-Dawgs, hooted,
hollered and relished their call to the Big Dance.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then. This is now.
</P>
<P>
   CBS cameras were at Montlake again Sunday, but not for a live
shot. The Huskies, no longer a ``bubble team,'' did not promise to
go bananas just to hear their name called.
</P>
<P>
   CBS had it right again. The Dawgs got their invite. They are the
No. 7 seed in the Midwest Region. Their first-round opponent is
Miami of Ohio. They did not even seem to care that Utah, Kentucky
and Kansas are entrentched like landmines in their bracket.
</P>
<P>
   And just as significant, no one went crazy inside the Hec Ed
Hall of Fame room when the Huskies got their call.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more business-like,'' said Slick Watts, father of UW
senior guard Donald. ``It was like some of the guys were saying,
`OK, we know where we're going, now let's go take care of
business.'''
</P>
<P>
   Expectations are a funny thing. The Huskies can no longer live
on the hope of being a Cinderella entry. Nor do they want to. Not
that there wasn't a good scene at Huskyville. As soon as CBS went
into a commercial break after the UW berth was announced, Donald
Watts got up from his chair and walked across the room. The first
person the Washington guard wanted to give a high-five to was his
father.
</P>
<P>
   Slick had called it: A first-round NCAA game for the Huskies in
New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had a feeling about it,'' the elder Watts said, adding
that once the Huskies had a 10-8 Pac-10 record to their credit and
a fourth-place finish in sight, the Huskies were deserving.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's going to be a Bourbon Street shuffle for the Dawgs.
It's going to be a few deserved helpings of gumbo, jambalaya and
crayfish etouffe, too.
</P>
<P>
   And, naturally, it will take a decided effort on the part of
Washington's chaperone contingent to keep the young Dawgs out of
the jazz and blues bars because the only thing more important than
food and music in New Orleans is, well, the booze.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a few family reunions down in New Orleans. It's an
old city. It's a fun place to hang out, walk down Bourbon Street,
party,'' Donald Watts said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Watts family knows its way around New Orleans. Slick
played college there. Slick's mother, father, aunts, uncles and
cousins are just a few hours away in Jackson, Miss. And the other
side of Donald Watts' family is all over in Mobile, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are about 80 to 100 family and friends'' all within a
three-hour drive of The Big Easy, the elder Watts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that doesn't even include the 20 or so I'm going to call
and tell not to even bother asking for tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   Slick Watts and his well-spoken son have become the most
familiar symbols of Washington's basketball rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   Having been there just last year, when the Huskies upset Xavier,
beat Richmond and lost a heartbreaker to Connecticut that kept them
out of the Elite Eight, the Huskies are promoting the fact that
this time around, they'll be used to things.
</P>
<P>
   ``There won't be any nervous jitters that can lead to sloppy
play and turnovers in the first five minutes,'' Watts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what to expect about tournament security, the open
practices, the media sessions, all the stuff that comes with the
tournament,'' UW coach Bob Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the tournament progresses and the further you go, there are
fewer teams still around so I was aware (last year) that we were
getting some pretty good looks and some discussion,'' UW center
Todd MacCulloch said. ``That has certainly heightened expectations
(for this year.) We have the higher seed and now Donald, Deon
(Luton) and I have to take on that responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Having been there already is going to help these Huskies
navigate their way to New Orleans. But how much does having been
there, done that really mean? Not all that much in a
single-elimination tournament where madness is all about the moment
_ seizing it and rolling with it down to the last, anxious buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies have already showed they can do that with the best
of them.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 0049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
