</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-KINGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERIMENTS NOT WORKING FOR MAVS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Don Nelson has tried just about every
gimmick he can think of during these past three games. But none of
them has resulted in a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, the Mavericks coach benched his top two point guards
for most of the second half. That strategy worked to a degree, but
the results were still the same: another loss for the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   The Sacramento Kings got 18 points and 13 rebounds from Chris
Webber en route to holding off the Mavericks before 14,715 at ARCO
Arena, 94-89. After winning five of seven games, the Mavericks have
now dropped their past three games and are 6-13.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas starts a four-game homestand tomorrow against old nemesis
Jason Kidd and the Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks had another horrible night from the floor,
shooting 38.5 percent against a Kings team not known for its
defense. Nelson said he is surprised his team is having shooting
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been there,'' he said. ``I've learned to live with
it now. I don't know if it's just us, or the league.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (8-8) had control of the game until Michael Finley
converted a 360-degree circus shot inside the paint to get the
Mavericks to within 92-86. And the Mavericks had a chance to cut
the deficit to three or four.
</P>
<P>
   But Tariq Abdul-Wahad stripped the ball from Finley as he was
going up for a shot with less than 35 seconds left to end Dallas'
hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he went with Hubert Davis at point guard for most of
the second half _ while benching Steve Nash and Robert Pack _
because ``it was just a feel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought for this particular game to maybe have two shooters
in,'' Nelson said. ``And we were going to more postups at that
time, so it was something I wanted to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks attempted 59 field goals in the first half. That's
the team's second-most all-time, trailing only the 60 they
attempted against Denver on Apr. 8, 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Bradley drew his fourth foul less than three minutes into
the second half, and Nelson chose to leave him in the game. A
little over two minutes later, Nelson had no choice but to bench
Bradley after the center drew his fifth personal.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he never thought about benching Bradley after he was
tagged with his fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I thought about keeping him in,'' Nelson said.
``There was a situation a few games ago where I protected him on
fouls _ he got his third, I took him out, and he got his fourth and
I took him out _ and by the time I put him back in the game was
lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I wanted to protect him a little, but not too much,
because often times he can play a whole quarter or a half and never
even commit a foul.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley returned with 8:04 left in the game and the Mavericks
behind, 81-72. But then, he had to play tentative.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks led, 19-12, late in the first period after a
jumper by A.C. Green. But the Kings, led by Chris Webber, Predrag
Stojakovic, Vernon Maxwell and rookie sensation Jason Williams,
bolted to a 46-41 lead at the half.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who had 13 points and five assists, banged in a
3-pointer at the third-quarter buzzer as the Kings increased their
lead to 72-64.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was definitely a momentum for them going to the bench,''
said Gary Trent, who had 18 points and 14 rebounds. ``That might
have fired them up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we competed really hard and stay right in it,''
Nelson said. ``It was maybe a long shot, but I think we were close
enough to have a chance, and I thought it was a good game.''
\Ntagtop:Dwain Price, (817) 390-7760
\Ntagbottom:ice\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
