<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES TO OPEN NCAA AGAINST MIAMI (OHIO) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ They soared at times and staggered at others, but the
Washington Huskies were rewarded for their 17-11 season Sunday with
an invitation to the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The respect was evident, the selection committee giving
Washington a seventh seed and the favorite's role against No. 10
Miami of Ohio. The first-round Midwest Regional game will be played
Friday night at the Superdome in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's UW team stunned Xavier and Richmond to advance to
the Sweet 16, attracting national attention and creating high
expectations for this year's team.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bob Bender wants the Huskies to focus on the first game,
but now that they are on the road to St. Petersburg, Todd
MacCulloch momentarily looked off in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been to the Sweet 16,'' said the Husky senior center.
``Now I want to see what it's like in the Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   The other senior on the team, Donald Watts, hopes for redemption
in the tournament. He has struggled most of the season because of
an ankle injury. The New Orleans draw means a lot to him _ his
father's family lives in Jackson, Miss., his mother's in Mobile,
Ala., both within a comfortable drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's showcase time,'' Watts said. ``The farther we go, the
better I'll feel about the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Huskies were inconsistent this season, the players
believe they will be better prepared for this year's tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the travel and atmosphere, we know what it's like,'' said
sophomore forward Thalo Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came together and sacrificed our individual needs and
wants,'' MacCulloch said. ``I hope we'll be able to do that
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies gathered around a big-screen TV in the Husky Hall of
Fame room to watch Sunday's selection show. They reacted with
cheers, but it was a muted celebration compared to last year.
Uncertainty has been replaced by unfinished business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt a little more comfortable sitting here,'' MacCulloch
said. ``Guys started thinking about not just getting in the
tournament but making a statement when we get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami of Ohio, 22-7 overall and 17-4 in the Mid-American
Conference, is led by senior forward Wally Szczerbiak, who averages
23.6 points and is projected to be a top-10 pick in this year's NBA
draft.
</P>
<P>
   If they prevail, the Huskies will play Friday's Utah-Arkansas
State winner on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
