<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOUDE'S DEBUT CASTS SHADOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ Ken Cloude's rocky first outing didn't start a
panic in Mariner camp, but it also did nothing to diminish the
club's interest in trading for a starting pitcher, as well as a
left-handed reliever.
</P>
<P>
   While Manager Lou Piniella dismissed concern about Cloude's
debut Saturday against San Diego, in which he gave up seven hits, a
walk and five runs in two innings, Woody Woodward, the club's vice
president of baseball operations, had a different view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed,'' he said. ``He's got enough experience
that he should be better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloude is scheduled to be the No. 3 starter behind Jeff Fassero
and Jamie Moyer. As the No. 4 starter a year ago, Cloude had an
8-10 mark with a 6.37 ERA. With no clear claimants to the fourth
and fifth spots, it's apparent the rotation remains the club's No.
1 vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward said he has had contact with at least two clubs that
might be in position to deal pitching. But he knows that with so
many other clubs in the same position, competition will be heavy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we aren't able to find those two (starter and reliever) in
a trade, someone (among the younger pitchers) is going to have to
step up,'' Woodward said.
</P>
<P>
   The best early prospects to meet that possibility are
right-hander Brett Hinchliffe, 24, who was 10-8 with a 4.00 ERA in
Tacoma last year, and left-hander John Halama, 27, one of three
pitchers acquired in the Randy Johnson trade.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mariners do want to trade, options are limited. The eight
position starters are virtually set, and the reserves are
journeymen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a little depth in the outfield that some clubs are
interested in,'' Woodward said. ``And we have some pitching
prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   The club is loath to part with its promising youngsters such as
Ryan Anderson and Gil Meche. But neither is it eager to stumble out
of the seasonal gate and have no emotional momentum going into the
July 15 move into the new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward said that regardless of what happens in spring
training, the owners won't increase the player payroll budget,
which remains near the $53 million level of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get it done,'' he said, ``with what we have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
