<SLUG> BC-BKC-STARS-BLUES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS REBOUND FROM LOSS WITH VICTORY AGAINST BLUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Stars have followed nine of their 12 losses this
season with a victory, so it was no surprise yesterday when they
outlasted the St. Louis Blues, 4-3, before the 27th consecutive
sellout crowd of 16,928 at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Despite coming off a 2-1 loss in Buffalo 40 hours earlier,
despite playing their fourth game in less than six nights, despite
missing Brett Hull with a pulled hamstring and losing Darryl Sydor
to a knee strain (day-to-day) during the game, the Stars did what
it took to dispose of a struggling Blues team in desperate need of
a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was good for us. To come off the road and score four
goals, it was good,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``We saw this
as a game that we wanted to put a lot into. Whatever we had, we
wanted to put into today. And the tradeoff was we'll take some time
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Today and tomorrow mark the first time the Stars have
consecutive open dates since Feb. 10-11 _ a span of 24 days and 14
games. Yet, during that 14-game stretch _ one of the Stars'
toughest _ they went 10-2-2 and separated themselves from the rest
of the Western Conference, if not the entire NHL.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars move to 40-12-10 with the victory, good for 90 points.
They are 18 points better than the next-closest team in the Western
Conference and 10 points better than the Ottawa Senators, who lead
the East. While other leaders battle occasional slumps, the Stars'
worst was 2-4-2 in January.
</P>
<P>
   A good reason for the consistent winning has been the play of
goalie Roman Turek. While the backup to No. 1 goalie Ed Belfour,
Turek boasts some of the best statistics in the NHL. With
yesterday's victory, he moves to 12-2-2 with a 1.96 goals-against
average and a .921 save percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, he's a backup in name only,'' Hitchcock said. ``He has
all the qualities that a good starting goalie has. It's a great
luxury to have that, and I think that's a big part of your team. We
have two goaltenders we feel confident in.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Turek stopped 31 shots, including 14 of 15 in a
hectic first period in which the Blues had three power-play
chances. The Blues couldn't solve Turek until Al MacInnis hit on a
five-on-three power play at the 18:31 mark of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Stars had scored twice on Blues goalie Jim Carey, a
free-agent addition making his first start for St. Louis. The
24-year-old Carey, a Vezina Trophy winner as top goalie, is trying
to make a comeback after fizzling out with the Washington Capitals
and Boston Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock put together the line of Mike Modano, Jere Lehtinen
and Joe Nieuwendyk for the power play yesterday, and that line
scored the first two goals. Modano fed Lehtinen in the slot for an
easy goal 18 seconds after the Stars' first power-play opportunity
had expired, and Modano then whipped a wrister in from 30 feet
away, 19 seconds into their second power-play chance for a 2-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The second goal broke a Stars' 0-for-30 power-play drought that
stretched back eight games.
</P>
<P>
   After the MacInnis score, Jamie Langenbrunner scored off a
perfect feed from Tony Hrkac at the 3:06 mark of the second period
for his 11th goal of the season, and Verbeek whipped in his 15th
goal of the season off a feed from Nieuwendyk at the 16:41 mark of
the second to give the Stars a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   While the Blues scored twice in the third, including a
long-distance shot from Chris McAlpine that was fumbled by Turek
and made the game's final three minutes a lot more exciting, the
Stars were able to earn a day of rest with the victory that dropped
the Blues to 26-26-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting a day off feels like a week,'' Hitchcock said. ``It's
real important for our group right now. The tank is a little low,
our energy is a little down, and that's why I feel it was good that
we battled hard against a desperate team today.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
