<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-PALMEIRO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMEIRO OUT 4 TO 6 WEEKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Rangers first baseman Rafael Palmeiro is
in peril of going on the disabled list for the first time in his
major-league career. He could find backup first baseman Mike Simms
right there with him.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro underwent surgery yesterday to repair torn medial
meniscus cartilage in his right knee. Dr. John Conway, who
performed the surgery in Fort Worth, said Palmeiro could be
sidelined four to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a little better,'' Rangers general manager Doug Melvin
said. ``I was sort of expecting the worst to happen. Conway doesn't
rule out him being ready for Opening Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Conway said the medial meniscus cartilage isn't related to the
articular cartilage that was repaired surgically Feb. 10. Conway
said there was evidence at that time that the medial meniscus
cartilage was showing ``some degeneration,'' but they decided
against surgery, believing it could be years before Palmeiro might
injure it.
</P>
<P>
   But Palmeiro, who was about a week away from playing in
exhibition games, felt more pain in the knee jogging in the
outfield Thursday and returned to Texas to have the knee examined.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are four weeks away from their April 5 opener
against the Detroit Tigers. The Rangers signed Palmeiro to a
five-year, $45 million contract in the off-season in part because
he had a much better history of staying healthy than Will Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be easy for us, but that's part of the
game,'' outfielder Juan Gonzalez said. ``We just need him to come
back strong as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers heard worse news on Simms, their right-handed
designated hitter. A second doctor looked at his X-rays and
determined he could have a more serious tear in his Achilles'
tendon, causing him to miss a substantial amount of time. He is
expected to undergo more tests this week.
</P>
<P>
   Simms' injury leaves Lee Stevens as the only healthy first
baseman/designated hitter with major-league experience in camp.
Scott Sheldon could play first base in an emergency. Roberto Kelly
and Luis Alicea could fill in at designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said it's unlikely the two injuries would open up a spot
for the younger prospects such as Ruben Mateo, Shawn Gallagher,
Mike Zywica and Carlos Pena.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're better off going out and playing, but I won't rule it
out,'' Melvin said. ``It's still to early to say that.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said he might try to pick up a right-handed bat off the
waiver wire or in a minor trade, but it's unlikely the Rangers
would make a major move.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't make a trade and two weeks later have to get rid of
someone,'' Melvin said. ``You'd like to keep your trade inventory
for pitching. It may come down to Stevens playing against
left-handers for a couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens is a career .265 hitter against right-handers but only
.214 against left-handers. He and Simms were expected to platoon at
designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be nice to have the opportunity to play against
left-handers, but we need to put the best lineup on the field
possible,'' Stevens said. ``Mike and Roberto Kelly have great
numbers against left-handers. I want to play against left-handers.
I look at it as a challenge. Hopefully they'll have confidence to
throw me out there, but Johnny has to put his best team out
there.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
