<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-NIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORNED FROGS' BUBBLE BURSTS AND OUT FALLS NIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ TCU forward Shannon Long listened intently
as NCAA Tournament brackets were being announced on CBS yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   He smiled as soon as he heard Gonzaga and Southwest Missouri
State were in, two teams TCU defeated this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured we were in, too,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   He figured wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, TCU (19-10) settled for a trip to Manhattan, Kan., to
play Kansas State (20-12) in the National Invitation Tournament at
8 p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just put it this way,'' Horned Frogs coach Billy Tubbs
said. ``I know politics enough to know not to expect to see TCU in.
... Did we deserve to be in? I don't think so, but I saw a lot of
people up there who didn't deserve to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU had a stronger Ratings Percentage Index than two bubble
teams selected for at-large slots _ Mississippi (19-12) and New
Mexico (24-8).
</P>
<P>
   The RPI is derived from three factors: Division I winning
percentage, schedule strength and opponents' schedule strength.
Games against non-Division I opponents are not used in calculating
the RPI.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs and his Horned Frogs had an RPI of 41, yet they lost six
of their final 10 games and lost to Brigham Young in the first
round of the Western Athletic Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   TCU was among 49 teams listed on the tournament committee's
``other teams considered'' list. The Frogs' 19-10 record didn't
stack up well. Of those 49 teams, there were 18 with 20 or more
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three weeks or a month ago, TCU was one of those teams you
would have figured would make the field,'' said committee chairman
C.M Newton, athletic director at Kentucky. ``They just needed to
win a game or two late, particularly in their tournament. BYU just
drilled them. They finished on a down tick.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs said he had been hoping for an NCAA bid, though hardly
expecting one.
</P>
<P>
   He figured TCU would at least be given an NIT game at
Daniel-Meyer Coliseum. He also figured wrong there.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, fellow WAC schools Colorado State (17-10) and Wyoming
(17-9) were given home games while TCU travels.
</P>
<P>
   ``This hasn't been a good year as far as breaks go,'' Tubbs
said. ``Maybe, we're better off on the road to start off.''
</P>
<P>
   He has to play a Wildcats squad that just returned from a pretty
strong Big 12 tournament performance, getting victories over Texas
A&AMP;M and Missouri before losing to Kansas in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've got a terrific team, and why they didn't play
as well down the stretch, I don't know,'' Wildcats coach Tom Asbury
said. ``A game that I remember was when \RTCU\S played Iowa State
in Puerto Rico last season. They absolutely dismembered Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got an NCAA-caliber team in my way of thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs thought so, too.
</P>
<P>
   A season marked by a suspension to Lee Nailon, a four-game
losing streak, injuries to Nailon and Marquise Gainous and
back-to-back, season-ending losses to Tulsa and BYU conspired to
prove him wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not a bubble team at one time,'' Tubbs said. ``We put
ourselves on the bubble.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
