<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIG-12-NCAA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG 12 TEAMS FACE TRYING MATCHUPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In what many considered a down year, the Big
12 nevertheless landed five teams in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Five conference teams also made the field of 64 in 1997, but
only four were in last year's tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Big Ten with seven and the Southeastern Conference with
six gained more berths this year. The Big East also had five. But
judging by the seeding, the NCAA Tournament committee doesn't
expect either Kansas (No. 6), Texas (No. 7), Missouri (No. 8),
Oklahoma State (No. 9) or Oklahoma (No. 13) to survive past the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   If Kansas survives its opening game against 11th-seed
Evansville, the Jayhawks will likely be looking at second-seeded
Kentucky in the Midwest. Texas has 10th-seeded Purdue, but then
would look to a probable game against the East's No. 2 seed in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like our seeding,'' Kansas coach Roy Williams said. ``I just
wanted to be there. I thought we might have played our way to a
five seed, but I thought going in we would probably be a six.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks are accustomed to playing as a much-higher seed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is different when you're a No. 1 or No. 2 seed,'' Williams
said. ``You're always going to get someone who is not as gifted or
doesn't have the same number of scholarships. But we're not in that
situation right now. We're happy going to New Orleans, and I just
hope we play well.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas guard Ryan Robertson said he also likes the Jayhawks'
slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of years everyone expected us to be in the
Final Four or win the national championship,'' he said. ``Now we
have a chance to go in without those expectations and do
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State is in a toss-up game with eighth-seeded Syracuse,
but then likely would go up against the South's No. 1 seed in
Auburn. Missouri faces the same dilemma in the West, opening
against No. 9 seed New Mexico in the same part of the bracket with
the region's top seed, Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just happy to be in the tournament,'' Cowboys coach
Eddie Sutton said. ``Had we not played well the past three weeks,
we wouldn't be in it. And I was happy to see the conference get
five teams in.
</P>
<P>
   ``That eight-nine is not the right place to be. I've seen Auburn
play, though, and if we're fortunate enough to get by Syracuse, I
think our team can play with Auburn.''
</P>
<P>
   Selection committee chairman C.M. Newton explained his nine-man
group doesn't look at conferences once the automatic bid has been
determined. But he did say that in his mind, both Oklahoma State
and Kansas improved their eventual seeds by advancing to the finals
of the Big 12 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, who entered the week as a tenuous bubble team,
gained the most by winning three games in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question they won their way in,'' Newton said.
``They certainly didn't hurt themselves any this weekend. They did
what they had to do _ win some basketball games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas \Ralso improved\S by winning the tournament. We never
had them seeded anywhere, actually, but in my own mind Kansas did
improve themselves. You never hurt yourself by winning basketball
games. I never saw an ugly win'' in the selection process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
