<P>
   FOXTV-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ One way those networks can try to
retain the viewers they had attracted with the ``all Monica, all
the time'' formats is to promote their regular programs and the
anchors, reporters and correspondents who work for them. The goal:
tempt channel surfers to tune in whether or not there is a major
continuing news story being covered. One network, MNC _ er, FNC,
Fox News Channel _ has begun doing just that with a $4 million
campaign centered on its prime-time programming. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-MONITORS (Undated) _ Corporations have long paid
so-called clipping services to monitor their appearances in the
conventional news media. But several companies have taken the
practice online and a step further. This new generation of monitors
goes beyond news publishers and instead trolls for rumor and
innuendo in the Net's virtual back alleys _ in thousands of chat
rooms and discussion forums where, some say, unchecked scuttlebutt
can damage corporate reputations and stock prices. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE-DROPOUTS (Undated) _ Internet shoppers may be at the
vanguard of a retail revolution, but as with anyone on the front
lines, they are a jittery bunch. Those who shop on the Internet
abandon one-half to two-thirds of the purchases they begin,
industry executives and analysts say. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-WARNINGS-MEDIA (Undated) _ A year after the gossipy Web site
run by Matt Drudge became a bookmark in Washington computers,
other, more partisan Web sites are becoming early warning systems
for the mainstream press. Like talk radio, they are filled with
free-form invective. Like trailers from a new X-Files movie, they
offer previews of coming attractions from places where conspiracy
is king. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   SAT-TV-MEDIA (Undated) _ Basketball fans in Denver know that to
see local television broadcasts of Nuggets games, they had better
stay home. A signal from a network affiliate in the city cannot be
picked up in Vail, 100 miles away, even though special maps used by
regulators to predict a television signal's reach say it should.
Drawn in the 1950s to prevent signal interference, the maps are at
the center of a legal battle between broadcasters and the satellite
television industry that resulted in 750,000 viewers nationwide
losing programming from CBS and Fox last weekend. By Andrea
Adelson.
</P>
