<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARCH MADNESS IS COMING TO TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
 TOURNEY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The final destination is St. Petersburg, Fla., and the
Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   For No. 1 Duke, the opening act will begin Friday, much closer
to home, in Charlotte, N.C., against 16th-seeded Florida A&AMP;M in one
of the more notable David vs. Goliath battles in NCAA Tournament
history.
</P>
<P>
   But before Duke can get that far, it will have to contend with a
couple of teams who will be involved in a historic occasion as the
NCAA Tournament makes its first-ever stop in Boston, which will
host first- and second-round games in the East Regional at the
FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   It should be quite a show, with No. 2 seed Miami heading a
regional grouping that is as physical as any in memory, ranging
from No. 3 seed Cincinnati, the only team to beat Duke this season,
to such physical clubs as No. 6 Temple, No. 7 Texas, and No. 10
Purdue. Even No. 11 seed Kent is not afraid to mix it up.
</P>
<P>
   Count on next Sunday's doubleheader in Boston to have the
feeling of a heavyweight title fight. The two winners will move on
to the regional finals at the Meadowlands, where the prospect of
meeting Duke looms large.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Blue Devils make it to the Final Four, as most
everyone figures they will, they could very well be banged up and
worn down by one of the teams playing in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998-99 college basketball season, following a course that
has emerged the last several weeks, has become a curious challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Duke, so overwhelming against so many opponents for so long. And
. . . the rest of the NCAA Tournament field.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is questioning that Duke is the No. 1 team,'' said
Connecticut coach Jim Calhoun, who has a pretty good team himself,
one that will begin its quest for its first Final Four appearance
in the West Regionals in Denver Thursday against No. 16 seed
Texas-San Antonio. ``But we think we can play the game ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   So can teams such as Auburn and Michigan State, the tournament's
other No. 1 seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Some other teams who can play the game will have to come from
off the pace, such as Ohio State (23-8), the No. 4 seed in the
South. The Buckeyes have staged a stunning turnaround from last
year's 8-22 mark under former Boston College coach Jim O'Brien, who
was named Big Ten coach of the year and has an outside chance at
being named national coach of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Or there is a team like Miami, which, under coach Leonard
Hamilton, has gone from worst to nearly first in the Big East,
chalking up some remarkable road wins against UConn, St. John's,
and Syracuse in roaring to a 22-6 record. The Hurricanes are a No.
2 seed who will play in Boston, facing Patriot League champion
Lafayette Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For those looking for someone other than Duke to place as the
final team in your bracket (for recreational purposes only, of
course), consider teams with experienced guards.
</P>
<P>
   In the one-and-done format of the NCAA Tournament, guard play is
critical.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why a team like Ohio State, which has former BC star
Scoonie Penn and the multitalented Michael Redd in its backcourt,
could emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps Maryland, which became much better with the arrival
of guard Steve Francis, a junior college transfer from Alleghany.
</P>
<P>
   Look out for Arizona, which may have the best player in the
country in guard Jason Terry. As the No. 4 seed in the Midwest, the
Wildcats can make another run if they can get past No. 13 Oklahoma
in the first round, then a tough second-round game against the
winner of UNC-Charlotte-Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count out defending national champion Kentucky, which is
led by former Beaver Country Day standout Wayne Turner, who is
looking to be one of the few players in NCAA history to participate
in four consecutive national championship games. The Wildcats are
finally playing well, coming off their victory over Arkansas Sunday
in the Souteastern Conference tournament championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps it will be Utah, which comes in as one of the hottest
teams in the country and is counting on 6-foot-2-inch senior Andre
Miller to lead it to back-to-back national championship games.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a UConn fan, don't count on the Huskies breaking the
Final Four frontier without strong peformances from point guard
Khalid El-Amin and Ricky Moore, who may be the best defensive guard
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, it all probably will come back to Duke, which does
not appear to have any weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   Duke comes into the tournament as the most prohibitive favorite
since unbeaten Nevada-Las Vegas in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, lost to . . . Duke and coach Mike Krzyzewski.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
