<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-RANGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR MIDDLE MANAGEMENT BY BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Coach Pat Burns has dubbed this ``The Week.''
</P>
<P>
   During that time, and especially after this Saturday's game in
Buffalo is in the books, it's likely the Bruins will get a good
idea just what kind of shape they're in with regard to the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Boston blew a golden chance to gain some much needed
breathing room on its challengers for the final spot in the Eastern
Conference playoff hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored a pair of goals in the second period and
added another in the third and goalie Mike Richter had 37 saves on
the way to a 3-1 New York victory at the FleetCenter. The Rangers
are unbeaten since Wayne Gretzky went out of the lineup with a neck
injury (4-0-1).
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, now just 2 points ahead of the Rangers, have lost
two of their last three and it doesn't get any easier. Tuesday
night they host the Florida Panthers, who are 3 points behind them.
Then they have a rematch with the Rangers in New York Friday and
face the Sabres in Buffalo the next night to round out the week.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday the Bruins just didn't get the job done. They played a
so-so first period, which ended scoreless. The highlights included
a couple of great saves by Byron Dafoe on Adam Graves on the
doorstep, Jason Allison missing an open net, and Ken Belanger being
tossed out for boarding defenseman Ulf Samuelsson, knocking
Samuelsson out of the game, and giving the Rangers a five-minute
power play that was knocked down to three when Kevin Stevens took a
goaltender interference penalty.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, John MacLean put the Rangers ahead with a goal at
4:32 and Niklas Sundstrom made it 2-0 at 15:14 on a shorthanded
goal. Boston had plenty of chances, including during a two-man
advantage, but couldn't make them count.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed in the second period,'' said Burns. ``I think
that was the turning point of the whole game. The first period we
came out all right. The third period was too little, too late. The
second period was the killer. This time of year, you've got to put
three periods together. You can't have a 20-minute break. For some
reason or another, I'd like to know why in a game of such
importance, in the second period, we just weren't on top of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third, the Bruins outshot New York, 15-4, but only got
one past Richter. Landon Wilson made it 2-1 at 12:25 but just over
a minute later, former Bruin Stevens sealed it with a goal at
13:51.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of looked at this week,'' said Dafoe, who had 15
saves. ``Obviously, it's not the start we wanted for it, but now
we've got Florida, the Rangers and Buffalo; they're three huge
games and we've got to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Richter was named the No. 1 star of the game but the fact of the
matter was, the Bruins made him look even better than he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very good goaltender and he's been known to win big
games,'' said Dafoe. ``You knew that none of the goals were going
to come easy and he definitely didn't give us anything.''
</P>
<P>
   What was most disappointing for the Bruins was the lack of
production from the top line of Allison, Dmitri Khristich, and
Anson Carter. The three combined for a total of four shots.
Khristich played just over 20 minutes, Carter a little under that,
and Allison played 22 shifts for a total of 27:26, second only to
Ray Bourque in ice time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need contributions from our big players,'' said Burns.
``Our big players didn't contribute a lot (Sunday). We need them to
win hockey games.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque said it was frustrating to not be able to build on their
big victory over the Devils in New Jersey Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a game that we blew and it was a big game for us and a
big loss for us,'' he said. ``No excuse, we didn't play good enough
to win it. We made it easy for them.''
</P>
<P>
   And harder on themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
