<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-STEVENS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVENS GOAL IS A SNAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Snap your fingers. That's how quickly Rangers center
Marc Savard gave Kevin Stevens the puck on a play in the third
period against the Bruins Sunday. Savard was racing down the left
side, and he fed a pass to Stevens in the right slot.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, the former Bruin, snapped in his 16th goal of the
season, the final tally in the Rangers' 3-1 win over Boston at the
FleetCenter. The goal, at the 13:51 mark, came just a minute and a
half after the Bruins had made it 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   With the win, the Rangers are just 2 points behind the Bruins in
the fight for the eighth and final playoff spot in the Eastern
Conference. The teams meet again Friday in New York, and the
Rangers, who are 4-0-1 in their last five games, have six of their
next eight at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came out over the blue line and I noticed that (Bruins
goalie Byron) Dafoe was kind of cheating, like he thought I was
going to shoot the whole time,'' Savard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I looked for another option, and I saw Kevin. I faked a
shot and slid it to Kevin and he put it in. Kevin's just a good
player and he was in the right position at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Stevens, Rangers left wing John MacLean helped on
the play by driving hard to the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``That opened the side, and I was able to one-time it,'' said
Stevens, the former Boston College standout who lives in Duxbury
and is from Pembroke. ``That was a turning point in the game. If
the Bruins had five or six minutes left, they would have gotten
rolling, they'd get some room there and we might have had
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe was hugging the post. On the pass to Stevens, Dafoe darted
to the right side, and Stevens had a lot of net to shoot at.
``Savard is a good passer,'' said Stevens, who notched his 35th
point. ``He's a guy who gets a lot of points that way. He's an
up-and-comer; he makes big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who has 11 points (six goals) in his last 14 games,
actually never noticed how open the net was. ``I never even
looked,'' he said. ``If you don't look, it's awfully tough to see
the hole. It was a bang-bang play. You get rid of the puck, that's
what you've got to do. You sit there and you let them set up, then
you've got problems. The quicker you get rid of it . . . that's
what I did, just try to get rid of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said it wasn't more special because of his struggles
while with the Bruins in 1995-96, when he had 10 goals and 23
points in 41 games before he was traded to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it means anything extra, but it's nice to beat
them,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's a team I like to beat and it's a team we have
to beat at this point of the year. We have them again Friday, and
if we can keep climbing, that's another big game. This is a team
we're chasing, this is a team we have to catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a game we needed to win. Would you rather be behind 6
points or behind 2 points? This was the biggest game of the year
for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
