</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALVADOR-VOTE-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATE OF RULING PARTY DECLARES VICTORY IN PRESIDENTIAL
ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating and rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador _ The candidate of the conservative
governing party, a philosopher with a reputation for consensus
building, declared victory in Sunday's presidential elections,
based on early official results and the party's own sampling
showing him in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Flores, 39, the candidate of the governing Nationalist
Republican Alliance, known as Arena, campaigned on promises to
solve problems of crime and unemployment that afflict the country
seven years after the end of its civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a crowd of supporters shortly before midnight,
Flores thanked them for their work and then seemed to embrace the
party's murky past despite his fresh-face image.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's remember the values of our founder,'' he said. ``Let's
remember Roberto d'Aubuisson,'' he said of Arena's main founder, a
cashiered army major who died in 1992 and who was repeatedly cited
by human rights groups as an organizer of the death squads that
accounted for many of the civil war fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   The elections were held on the eve of President Clinton's
four-day visit to Central America to survey the damage inflicted by
Hurricane Mitch late last year and, according to a senior State
Department official, to celebrate the region's democratic
transformation after the civil wars of the 1980s, particularly the
elections in El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   Arena said it had taken an early ballot sampling showing that
Flores had won about 53 percent of the vote, enough to avoid a
runoff election, and his chief opponent, Facundo Guardado, 44,
getting about 27 percent. Guardado was the candidate of a coalition
led by the country's former guerrilla movement, the Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front
</P>
<P>
   Arena's figures closely matched early official results, based on
tallies from almost one-quarter of the balloting places. Of the
286,000 votes counted, Flores received about 51 percent and
Guardado about 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition party rejected Arena's numbers, saying it would
wait for the official count.
</P>
<P>
   Among five other candidates, Ruben Zamora, the coalition's
choice in the last election who this year ran under his own
Democratic Center Union, was third, with about 11 percent of the
vote according to Arena's figures and 9 percent based on early
returns.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout among 3.1 million registered voters appeared low after a
campaign dominated by the grave problems that Salvadorans have
inherited since their 12-year civil war ended, including rampant
crime, unemployment and poverty. The presidential vote was only
their second since the war's end.
</P>
<P>
   Such apathy, political analysts said, demonstrates a loss of
faith in the effectiveness of government since peace arrived in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel that despite the end of the war, the fundamental
problems of the country have not been solved like they had
expected,'' said Jose Miguel Cruz, the director of the Public
Opinion Institute at the Central American University. ``They say
we've had war, elections, peace accords and more elections, and we
still have violence and problems of unemployment and poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Two out of three Salvadorans had little or no interest in this
election, according to a survey last month by the public opinion
institute. The reasons, it found, ranged from mistrust of
politicians to skepticism that the vote could make a difference in
solving the country's problems or improving living conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But the disillusionment of Salvadorans was not enough to turn
many voters away from Arena, which suffered serious losses to the
party of the former guerrillas in municipal and legislative
elections in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the polls opened on Sunday, Flores, a philosopher
with a fresh face and no ties to the civil war, was favored to win,
though it was unclear whether he would gain enough votes to avoid a
runoff.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition party led by the former rebels, after much
infighting, had rejected broadening its appeal and settled on
Guardado, a moderate ex-guerrilla commander who had pushed for the
selection of a centrist candidate from an allied party. Guardado's
war credentials and Flores's resume, which includes studies in
Indian philosophy and a bachelor's degree in political science from
the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, seemed to leave many
voters unable to see an alternative beyond Arena, however
dissatisfied they might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Francisco Flores seems to me more capable, better educated,''
said Raul Avila, 68, a tailor who said he had been held up twice in
recent years during the day. ``No government is ideal but the hope
we all have is that he can begin solving the most serious problems
of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Avila voted at the fairgrounds here where 69,000 Salvadorans
were registered to vote. If the overall turnout was low, spirits
were high on Sunday, as throngs filed into cavernous pavilions to
cast their ballots at cardboard podiums.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
