<HEADER>
A1395 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-DORALOPEN-BOS &LR;      03-08 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DORAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONSTER ROUND AT DORAL 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ As Steve Elkington's caddie, Gypsy Grillo, walked off
the tee Sunday after his boss split the fairway on the first hole
of the Doral Open over the storied Blue Monster course, he gave a
thumbs-up sign to someone he recognized in the gallery. ``Nothing
to it,'' Grillo said later. ``I just knew we had to shoot a low
round.'' So they did.
</P>
<P>
   Elkington began the day in a group of 10 tied for 21st place.
But even though he finished with a bogey on the infamous 18th hole
and had to sit for an hour, Elkington's 64_275 totals brought him
the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Elkington, who won this tournament two years ago and the PGA
Championship in a playoff against Colin Montgomerie in 1995 at
Riviera in addition to a pair of Players Championships in Ponte
Vedra, Fla., had six straight birdies starting at the par-4 sixth.
``I never thought of winning until I was leading,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no lack of challengers in a field that the area media
played up as below Doral's normal standards in the wake of the
World Match Play Championship, with its $5 million purse, last week
at La Costa. But they all destructed, with Ernie Els (70_277)
taking a six on the 18th and runner-up Greg Kraft (71_276) hitting
a fat 5-iron into the pond on the closing hole.
</P>
<P>
   This turned out to be a beguiling final round, even if Els was
the only one of the world's Top 7 to show up, and he did so only
because he lost to Paul Azinger in the first round of match play
the previous week. Els ended up tied for third with David Toms
(67), who started with two consecutive eagles, Tommy Armour III
(68), Jay Haas (68), and Scott Dunlap (69). Elkington earned
$540,000.
</P>
<P>
   With light breezes and temperatures approaching 80, it was a
picture-perfect round.
</P>
<P>
   Elkington, who long has owned one of the game's best swings but
has had a series of ailments that have affected his play, started
by nailing a 3-wood second shot to 50 feet on the inviting par-5
opening hole and taking two putts for birdie. He then lofted a
wedge to 10 feet on the second for another birdie.
</P>
<P>
   The longer birdie string started on the sixth when his wedge
second shot nestled in 2 feet from the cup, and he followed it with
birdies on the seventh (8-iron, 20 feet), eighth (bunker, 1 foot),
ninth (8-iron, 10 feet), 10th (two putts, 20 feet), and 11th
(7-iron, 12 feet). He three-putted the 13th for bogey, then
penciled in two more birdies on the 16th (sand wedge, 15 feet) and
17th (8-iron, 2 feet) before his second putt on the 18th rimmed
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little upset,'' said Elkington after the bogey on 18.
``I felt I let everybody back in. It was never my tournament to
start with, then I got a hold of it and dropped the ball. I didn't
putt that bad. It was a straight putt, and Gypsy and I felt it just
may curve a little bit. I played it just inside the center. I felt
I hit it pretty good. It was a pretty severe lip-out.''
</P>
<P>
   Elkington has been known to storm out of the pack. ``The first
tournament I won was the Greater Greensboro Open in 1990,'' he
said, ``and I finished early so they didn't have me on TV.'' He was
actually in danger of missing the cut, but made birdies on four of
the last six holes. ``I wanted to keep it tidy,'' he said of
Sunday's finish. ``I didn't want to leave any crumbs out there.''
</P>
<P>
   He did, but Kraft's finish cost him a chance at a playoff to
possibly win for the first time on the PGA Tour. ``I just hit a fat
5-iron into the water,'' he said. He had struggled early in his
round, making the turn in 36, but birdies on the 10th and 12th
brought him into a tie with Elkington. The bogey on the 18th did
him in.
</P>
<P>
   Els also saw his chances of victory go by the boards when his
second shot on 18 went left and into the rough just above the
water. He tried to chop it out, but it rolled back and almost went
into the water.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Horgan of Newport, R.I., finished 68_278 to tie for eighth
and earn his biggest paycheck of $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Sisk of Marshfield, Mass., tied for 19th with 69_281
totals, and picked up $29,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
