<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1398 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      03-08 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX GOOD FIT FOR FISK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ ``I'm sweating,'' Carlton Fisk said,
fingering the Red Sox cap on the table before him.
</P>
<P>
   He looked to his wife, Linda, for help. ``How's it look?'' he
said, fitting the cap snugly on his head. ``This is the longest my
hair has ever been any time I've worn a cap. Do you put your ears
inside it?''
</P>
<P>
   It was, of course, a perfect fit, just as it was from the time
he first put one on 30 years ago. Carlton Fisk, who may be 51 and
the grandfather of five-month-old Grace McAvoy but still has days
he's certain he still could play, is back with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The title: Special assistant to general manager Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud to reintroduce him to the fans of New England,''
Duquette said Sunday at the press conference that made Fisk's
hiring official.
</P>
<P>
   The job: It's evolving, but for now, Fisk's plans are to work
with the team's young catchers and do some public relations work
for the club. ``You'll find I'm not politically correct,'' he said.
``I'm somewhat blunt at times. But all the time it will be the
truth. I don't think I'll ever skirt an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   He expects to be on the field in a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Yogi-ism if there ever was one,'' said Fisk,
invoking the master of baseball malapropisms, Yogi Berra, ``but I
told my wife as we were driving down here, `There are a lot of
things I know that I didn't even know I knew.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I know where I can make a contribution, and that's with the
catching corps.''
</P>
<P>
   The benefits: Obvious to the Red Sox. There is no downside to a
future Hall of Famer and New England native son setting aside the
bitterness he once harbored toward the Olde Towne Team and claiming
it as his own again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlton's presence,'' Duquette said, ``upgrades the entire
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisk had so much leverage to make this deal, he should have
asked Duquette to throw in Fenway's left-field foul pole, the one
on which he placed the stamp of history with his 1975 World Series
home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to let you keep it,'' Fisk said to Duquette. ``Just
put it somewhere I can see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette told Fisk that in all likelihood, the foul pole will be
part of any new stadium the Red Sox build. And Fisk, for all that
Fenway Park has meant to him, made it clear that while he hasn't
been asked to be front man for the team's push for a new ballpark,
he supports the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't drive a car that's 100 years old,'' he said,
``because it wouldn't work very well. And you don't want to
continue to play in a ballpark that doesn't work very well. Bring
the memories with you to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette already has figured out how Fisk can help usher in a
new era of Sox baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to groom Steve Lomasney to be our Opening Day
catcher in the new ballpark,'' Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   Lomasney, the 21-year-old son of the Peabody (Mass.) Lomasneys,
hit a game-tying home run in the bottom of the ninth inning of
Sunday's 7-6, 10-inning win over the Texas Rangers. Not only was
Fisk in City of Palms Park for that one, but so were Ed and Joyce
Lomasney, the rookie's parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you said that you were going to give a sign for the boys
back home,'' said winning pitcher Derek Lowe, who gave up the tying
run on a bloop hit in the ninth inning but struck out four of the
six batters he faced. ``And you forgot all about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lomasney, who was an All-Scholastic football player at Peabody
High, knew that Sunday's exhibition was televised back to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did tell Derek that I wanted to do something special for my
friends to let them know I'm out there,'' he said. ``Hopefully,
they saw the home run.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been 19 years since Fisk's separation from the Red Sox,
when Haywood Sullivan forgot to put his contract offer in the mail
during an ugly salary dispute, an omission that made Fisk a free
agent. He went on to finish his career with the Chicago White Sox,
but his parting there left an equally acrid taste, as he warred
with owner Jerry Reinsdorf and was unceremoniously released in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Other than serving as a volunteer coach for his son Casey's
college team at Illinois State, Fisk stayed away from the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was bitter and angry at both of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he couldn't resist the siren's call forever. Duquette has
been talking to him about a job for five years, and Sunday, Fisk
said the idea of actually accepting may have taken root 18 months
ago, when he was inducted into the team's Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a long time ago,'' Fisk said of his falling-out with
the Sox. ``The people who caused that situation are not here
anymore, as opposed to the Red Sox or the people of New England or
the game of baseball. This is a new start, a fresh start. There's
no part of the previous regime behind doors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you,'' he added, ``just carrying that cap in here,
my hands and arms were sweating. What will I feel, putting the
uniform on again? Thinking about it, my heart started beating and
the adrenaline started pumping.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
