<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODOM GETS SHOT AT FULFILLING DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
 ISLAND-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSTON, R.I. _ Lamar Odom remembers sneaking out of bed past
curfew 10 years ago to find out who won the 1989 national
championship rather than wait to hear about it in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   That was when dreams of playing in the NCAA Tournament began for
the University of Rhode Island sophomore sensation. Saturday, he
made his dream come true with a winning 3-point shot to lift the
Rams past Temple in the Atlantic 10 championship game in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the forward from New York discovered how his dream will
unfold: URI (20-12) is seeded 12th in the Midwest Region and will
meet fifth-seeded North Carolina-Charlotte (22-10) at the Bradley
Center in Milwaukee Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Odom, who is still battling flu symptoms he had over the
weekend, didn't mind that the Rams were a 12th seed, he was just
pleased to have his childhood dream come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember watching (former Michigan guard) Rumeal
Robinson against Seton Hall, and I had to sneak to watch that
game,'' said Odom, referring to the 1989 title game. ``I remember
it was late at night, and I was supposed to turn the television
off. But I had to watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom and his URI teammates were silent throughout Sunday's
tournament pairings show. Even when Rhode Island's pairing was
flashed across the screen, they sat motionless.
</P>
<P>
   Most players said they were silent because they knew they were
in the tournament after beating Temple to gain the Atlantic 10's
automatic bid. Last season, they were more emotional because they
made the tournament as an at-large team.
</P>
<P>
   The players' excitement was also tempered by the seed they
received.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we deserved a higher seed,'' said senior guard
Preston Murphy. ``I think most of us would have been satisfied with
a 10 seed.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior forward Antonio Reynolds-Dean said the venue tempered his
excitement, too. ``Orlando would have been nice. Charlotte would
have been nice,'' said the Atlanta resident. ``I've never been to
Milwaukee. The only thing I know about Milwaukee is that the
Packers play there.''
</P>
<P>
   When told that the Packers play in Green Bay, about two hours
north, Reynolds-Dean replied, ``Then, I don't know anything about
Milwaukee.''
</P>
<P>
   As for North Carolina-Charlotte, the Conference USA tournament
champs, URI players say they know the 49ers twice beat Cincinnati,
a team that trounced URI, 67-49, at the Providence Civic Center
Nov. 19. Both URI and N.C.-Charlotte beat Virginia Tech and George
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``(N.C.-Charlotte) is a tough team, a talented team,'' said
Odom. ``They go seven or eight deep and they really defend. They're
up-tempo and they shoot the three a lot. We'll scout them, but when
you step on the floor, it's about handling your business.''
</P>
<P>
   Should URI win Friday, it would be only the sixth time this
season the Rams beat a team with a winning record. URI, however,
enters the tournament 5-0 in games this season played at neutral
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Rams say the momentum they gained in their
conference tournament victories should carry over into the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Odom, who said having to sit out last season while trying to
meet eligibility requirements was the ``longest period of my
life,'' said he is well aware he will be the focal point of media
attention in Milwaukee this week. But he said he will not allow
that to distract him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time last year, I was watching (former URI players) Tyson
Wheeler and Cuttino Mobley lead this team to the Final Eight,''
said Odom. ``Hopefully, I can do the same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
