<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-TOURNAMENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLDOGS TO FACE GOPHERS AT KEYARENA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When the Gonzaga Bulldogs won 24 games last season and
weren't invited to the NCAA tournament, they barked long and loud.
</P>
<P>
   Someone must have been listening.
</P>
<P>
   The West Coast Conference champions, who secured an automatic
NCAA bid last week by winning the WCC tournament in Santa Clara,
Calif., Sunday landed what coach Dan Monson called another home
game when the tournament bracket was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga, making its second NCAA tournament appearance, faces
Minnesota Thursday at KeyArena in one of four West sub-regional
games there. Pac-10 champion Stanford, which blew any shot of being
a No. 1 seed by losing at Oregon State Saturday night, is seeded
second in the West and plays Alcorn State. Also, high-profile North
Carolina battles Weber State and Florida meets Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Game times will be announced today.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs and nearly 400 boosters gathered at a Spokane hotel
to watch the selection process unfold. Some 20 minutes and three
regions later, Gonzaga still hadn't been mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had flashbacks to last year and I had to keep reminding
myself that we were an automatic,'' Monson said. ``A big roar went
up when we knew we'd be staying in the West, and an even bigger
cheer came after the field in Denver had been announced. We knew we
were going to Seattle, and you can't get a much better homecourt
advantage than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't ask for more,'' he added. ``Most of our kids are
from that side of the mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga, seeded 10th, brings a 25-6 record to Seattle, including
an 82-71 victory over the tournament-bound Washington Huskies. The
Bulldogs lost to Kansas, Purdue and Detroit, who also made the NCAA
field.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Saturday's loss in Corvallis, Stanford coach Mike
Montgomery said he is happy about playing in Seattle as the No. 2
seed. The Cardinal made it to the Final Four with virtually the
same team last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what we wanted, what we earned, what we deserved,'' he
said. ``We couldn't be happier. I didn't think we would get a No. 1
seed under any circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery downplayed Gonzaga's homecourt advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tickets already have been sold, so it's not like they will
be filling (KeyArena) with Gonzaga people,'' he said. ``But they
are Washington people.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of them figure to support Gonzaga. Eight of the 10 Bulldog
players are from the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota (17-10) is one of seven Big Ten teams in the
tournament and features conference scoring leader Quincy Lewis,
averaging nearly 25 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't anybody in this tournament we can't play with,''
Monson said of his 10th-seeded team.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara coach Dick Davey agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought they would be a higher seed, perhaps a
seven,'' he said. ``But my math is not the same as the (selection)
committee's math.''
</P>
<P>
   But Monson doesn't mind being a No. 10 seed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing in Seattle soothes whatever number they put in front
of us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Davey said the Bulldogs, who beat his Broncos three times this
season including the WCC tournament finale, said, ``They have good
shooters, play smart basketball and can beat you in a number of
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Gonzaga has four starters who score in double
figures.
</P>
<P>
   Junior forward Richie Frahm leads the way with 14.2 points a
game, then comes Matt Santangelo, a junior guard (12.7), senior
center Jeremy Eaton (12.1) and senior guard Quentin Hall (11.4).
All were selected to the 10-player All-WCC first team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are one of the best-shooting teams around, and I don't
think they are missing much,'' Davey said. ``They have a lot of
weapons and are capable of beating most teams any night. Minnesota
will have its hands full. They will be tested.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
