A1409 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-LAFAYETTE-BOS &LR;      03-08 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LAFAYETTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICTURE-PERFECT DAY FOR LAYFAYETTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EASTON, Pa. _ Normally, the 104-seat Limburgh Theater in the
bowels of the Lafayette College student union is reserved to import
current films for the benefit of those undergrads who otherwise
might not pry their heads from their engineering texts.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday night the cinematic bill of fare was decidedly
different. They showed a hit revival _ ``Leopards: Back From
Extinction.''
</P>
<P>
   As the team's players clustered expectantly in the first two
rows and coach Fran O'Hanlon stood impassively at the back of an
auditorium ringed by about 60 family members, supporters, and
media, the Leopards' basketball rebirth assumed definite shape.
They'd known since Friday, when they outscrapped Bucknell, 67-63,
in the Patriot League tournament final, that the nation's
second-longest NCAA Tournament drought had ended at 42 years
(exceeded only by Harvard's 53-year wait between dances).
</P>
<P>
   But when CBS's Michele Tafoya announced on Limburgh's big screen
during the selection show that 15th-seeded Lafayette will be coming
to Boston's FleetCenter Friday to face No. 2 seed Miami in the East
subregional, the Leopards clapped their hands, stomped their feet,
and emitted cheers between bites of the cheese, pepperoni, and
sausage pizza catered for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great,'' said guard Brian Ehlers, the league scoring
champion, player of the year, and tournament MVP, who hails from
Bay Shore, N.Y. ``It's nice to stay on the East Coast because my
friends and family can come watch.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Lafayette hopes to stock the FleetCenter with Leopards.
``This means more of our fans hopefully will be able to follow us
up there,'' said O'Hanlon.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Tim Bieg was pleased to realize that he'll have at
least one rooter on hand, guaranteed. ``My older sister goes to
Boston College,'' he said. ``I've been to Boston a lot and I love
it. It's such a nice city, a great sports town.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, the Leopards are thrilled to be going anyplace,
considering that they offer no athletic scholarships and a mere
five years ago, they went 2-25 and were ranked next-to-last among
the 306 NCAA Division 1 basketball schools. Add to that the fact
that not since 1957, almost before talkies were invented, had they
had an opportunity to put on an NCAA show in March and their
euphoria is understandable.
</P>
<P>
   While they were thrilled with this turn of events, the bounty of
a 22-7 season, they certainly weren't surprised. Try as CBS might
to turn the selection show into suspense theater, there are no
bombshells in this age of technopunditry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I checked my computer right before I came over here,'' said
Ehlers. ``That's exactly what it said _ that we'd be going to
Boston to play Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone kind of projected that we'd get Miami in Boston,''
said O'Hanlon.
</P>
<P>
   How long they'll be hanging out at Quincy Market is another
matter. The Leopards are well aware that the lot of 15th seeds is
to serve as first-round appetizers for the high and mighty, and
they are duly impressed with Miami, another program up from the
netherworld.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a very athletic team, very good defensively, and Tim
James is a great player,'' said O'Hanlon.
</P>
<P>
   To counter that, he'll rely on Lafayette's motion offense,
matchup zone, and ensemble approach in which all 12 players see
significant action.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not a real big team,'' said O'Hanlon. ``They don't
have anyone 6-11. That might help us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes may not be big, but they are relentless.
``They're a typical Big East team,'' said Ehlers. ``They're going
to try to push the ball. We know we're going to have to be real
strong in taking care of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the Leopards could offer only generalities about
Friday's challenge. They'll be consumed by film of a different
nature Tuesday when they begin scrutinizing Miami game tapes, after
the coaching staff has broken them down and done reconnaissance
work with its contacts who have done battle with the Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll say this,'' said O'Hanlon. ``Give Miami a lot of credit.
I'm very impressed with how far they've come. Never mind come.
They've arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like Sunday night's Lafayette theater audience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
