<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 0148EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1414 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-BLAZERS-H     03-08 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-BLAZERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PORTLAND, Ore. _ The good news was that no one got punched.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Portland Trail Blazers claimed the NBA's best record with
the finesse of a sledgehammer Sunday night, scoring an early
knockout without ever really letting up until they had beaten the
Rockets 111-71. The defeat was the Rockets' worst since a 56-point
whipping in Seattle in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the Rockets' previous worst loss to the Blazers, a
38-point collapse in 1995 in which Vernon Maxwell went into the
stands to slug one of the customers, Sunday's beating was
restricted to the court.
</P>
<P>
   The rout was so thorough that Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich
pulled his regulars with nine minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``They beat us, but I'm not going to look at the score and say
it's reality,'' Tomjanovich said. ``When the dam broke, I had to do
some damage control with my team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets described their complete collapse as a freakish
combination of their fatigue and the Trail Blazers' depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good team, but they're not that good,'' Rockets
forward Othella Harrington said. ``They have good starters and a
deep bench, but that good? C'mon.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Trail Blazers described the rout as something of a
fluke. Before 20,062, the largest Rose Garden crowd of the season,
they won their sixth consecutive game and 10th in 11, with the only
loss coming to lightweight Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the rout of the Rockets, the Blazers have scored wins
this season against Utah and Indiana. But even while holding the
league's best record for the first time since the 1990-91 season,
even the Trail Blazers (13-3) would not claim to be that much
superior to another presumed Western Conference contender, at least
not in early March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get it twisted,'' Trail Blazers forward Brian Grant
said. ``They had a game last night. We were just hitting shots.
Everything went right for us. Was it a fluke? Maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Portland guard Greg Anthony, ``It was one of those nights
where we played as well as we played all year. They probably played
as poorly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets shot worse than they had all season, making just
31.1 percent (23 of 74) of their shots. And even that was not their
biggest problem. The Rockets' defense was worse, allowing the Trail
Blazers to make 55.3 percent of their shots and leaving them so
alone outside that they made nine of 16 3-pointers. The Trail
Blazers ran up assorted misprint-quality numbers, outscoring the
Rockets 36-18 in the paint, 28-2 on the break and 16-5 on
second-chance points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like we gave up in the second half,'' Rockets
forward Scottie Pippen said. ``We didn't come out with any sense of
urgency to get back into the game. We didn't have any defensive
intensity. That's the only way to get back in a game, but we didn't
play with any intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had remained within 48-36 by halftime, but Isaiah
Rider scored nine points in four minutes of the second half to help
push the margin to 19 at 61-42. The Rockets got back within 13 with
as little as four minutes left in the third quarter but could not
begin to slow the Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   While Portland's defensive intensity was unrelenting, the
Rockets' faded fast. Stacey Augmon started at forward specifically
to hound Pippen, who made just three of 11 shots and had as many
turnovers, four, as assists. Charles Barkley drew only occasional
double teams, preventing him from sparking the Rockets' offense
with passing as he had in Vancouver a night earlier. After getting
six assists before his first field-goal attempt Saturday, he had
one assist Sunday and made just four of 12 shots for 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd certainly like to bottle this one,'' said Trail Blazers
coach Mike Dunleavy, who used 11 players in the first half. ``The
whole four quarters were terrific. I especially liked the defensive
pressure we applied, and we didn't let up.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Blazers began the fourth quarter with an 8-0 run to an
84-57 lead, the only thing the Rockets could hope to accomplish was
to rest their regulars, who had become as worn as your favorite
pair of jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Even that didn't work out quite as planned. Barkley drew a
technical foul four minutes after he left the game and several
minutes later was run over by Rodrick Rhodes, who was chasing a
loose ball _ naturally, in vain.
</P>
<P>
   Long before then, however, the mass substitution only served to
make the damage cut deeper while turning Pig Miller into the
Rockets' go-to low-post threat. The Blazers, however, were so deep
that they had no way to call off the rout. They gave third-team
point guard John Crotty some minutes and even found a way for
Jermaine O'Neal to break a sweat. But Dunleavy also played some of
the players, Jim Jackson and Walt Williams, who had turned the game
into a rout.
</P>
<P>
   It took five minutes for the Rockets to get a fourth-quarter
field goal, a Miller jump shot cutting the deficit to 31. And while
everything the Rockets tried failed, the Trail Blazers' night ended
somehow appropriately with Kelvin Cato, a 6-11 defensive
specialist, swishing the first 3-pointer of his two-season career
at the buzzer to cap Portland's most lopsided victory in the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no extra points for how many you win by,'' Barkley
said. ``You can win by one or win by 30; you only get one win.
We'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   And this time the Rockets can forget it, having restricted the
beating to the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
