<HEADER>
A1417 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAAEASTPREVIEW-B     03-08 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE'S BIGGEST CHALLENGE: SURVIVING 
</HEADLINE>
 EAST PREVIEW-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Naturally, any discussion of the East Regional begins
with Duke. But the top-seeded Blue Devils will have a mere
scrimmage in their opener against Florida A&AMP;M. Beyond that,
however, things could get interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the first-round game between the Nos. 8 and 9 seeds,
College of Charleston and Tulsa. Charleston may have been seeded
too low, and if it can knock off Tulsa _ and the guess is that it
can _ Sunday's second-round game against the Devils should be a
doozy. Charleston has beaten North Carolina and Massachusetts this
season, so it's not afraid of big-name opponents, both good and
bad.
</P>
<P>
   The other half of the Charlotte, N.C., bracket is pretty
pedestrian. Wisconsin has not been impressive for a couple of
months, and Tennessee is one of the yo-yo teams of all time. One
potential shocker: No. 13 Delaware could emerge as the other team
to advance, along with Duke.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston half of the draw should be a matter of survival. The
basketball might not be pretty, but it will be physical.
</P>
<P>
   Miami, which has showed it could play with the elite of the Big
East, is the most athletic team in the bracket. The second-seeded
Hurricanes should handle Patriot League champion Lafayette in the
first round, but then it gets tough. Awaiting would likely be
Texas, which looks like a better team than first-round foe Purdue,
and that could be an interesting matchup, though the Hurricanes
probably have too much speed for the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati should knock off both George Mason and either Temple
or Kent, setting up a nice regional semifinal against Miami in the
Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   Once the regional moves to East Rutherford, N.J., the
entertainment quotient should be high. Let's assume Duke avoids a
second-round upset and takes care of our sleeper, Delaware. A
regional final pitting the Blue Devils against either Miami or
Cincinnati should be a keeper.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati already has proven it can beat the Devils, although
that victory came in Alaska back around Thanksgiving. Miami, with
players like Big East Co-Player of the Year Tim James and Boston
product and former Boston College recruit Elton Tyler, would not be
intimidated, either. The Hurricanes, after all, have a pair of
victories over St. John's and a split with Connecticut on their
resume.
</P>
<P>
   These could be the toughest matchups in the tournament for the
Blue Devils. At the very least, the Devils will face a challenge
rather than getting a walk-through to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Teams to watch: Delaware, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Upset special: Delaware over Tennessee, Kent over Temple.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to East Rutherford: Duke, Delaware, Miami, Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Regional champ: Duke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
