<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR AUBURN TO PUT, OR ... 
</HEADLINE>
 SOUTH PREVIEW-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Now it's showtime for Auburn. The Tigers had a great
regular season, which earned them the No. 1 seed in the South
Regional. But this is a new season, and the spotlight is going to
be bright. Can the Tigers handle it? We think not.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take a look at the danger spots. There isn't one in the
first round, as No. 16 Winthrop, while a nice Cinderella story,
will be more dazzled than the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Move to Round 2. Watch out. The survivor of the No. 8 Syracuse
vs. No. 9 Oklahoma State game will be waiting. It'll likely be the
Orangemen, who, free from the Carrier Dome (where they had trouble
winning, amazingly) and the Big East, will be frisky. Auburn's
athleticism will not bother Syracuse, and Orangemen coach Jim
Boeheim will throw up a few defensive wrinkles. We smell upset.
</P>
<P>
   In the other half of the Indianapolis bracket, Ohio State is one
of the turnaround stories of the season. Jim O'Brien can outcoach
just about anybody, and his No. 4-seeded Buckeyes have a strong
backcourt in Scoonie Penn and Michael Redd.
</P>
<P>
   If the Buckeyes can avoid a jittery opening-round game against
Murray State _ and the Racers are dangerous _ they can handle
either Detroit or talented but erratic UCLA in what could be a
high-speed game.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say Ohio State keeps it going and O'Brien finds old Big
East rival and golfing buddy Boeheim his foe in a regional
semifinal. With those guards, Ohio State can win that matchup as
well.
</P>
<P>
   In the Orlando bracket, No. 3 seed St. John's should get past
Samford, then handle either Indiana or George Washington. No. 2
Maryland will not be intimidated by Valparaiso, especially in
Orlando, and Louisville and Creighton are not threats.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland and St. John's should advance to Knoxville along with
Syracuse and Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Then it will become interesting, with two Big East teams and two
other teams whose coaches (O'Brien, Maryland's Gary Williams) have
Boston College connections.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a nice little reunion, especially since Williams,
O'Brien, and Boeheim all play golf together in the summer. Of the
three, Williams has the best team and O'Brien is the best coach,
while St. John's Mike Jarvis (another Boston connection) has a team
that comes closest to matching Maryland in talent.
</P>
<P>
   What's going to happen? Ohio State will beat Syracuse, but
that's as far as the Buckeyes can go without their opponent
self-destructing.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland and St. John's is a tough matchup to fathom. Both teams
have to prove they can win big games.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's should win a close final over Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Teams to watch: Ohio State, Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Upset special: Syracuse over Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to Knoxville: Syracuse, Ohio State, St. John's, Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Regional champ: St. John's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
