<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1427 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-DORAL-HNS &LR;      03-08 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DORAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ Steve Elkington had just planted one of his size-12s into
the outside wall of the scoring trailer, leaving a good-sized divot
in the corrugated metal surface.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He thought he had just booted away the Doral-Ryder Open by
missing a four-foot par putt on the famed 18th hole, capping a
fantastic round of golf on a downer.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out Elkington's Al Del Greco imitation was just the last
symbolic gesture after he kicked Doral's Blue Monster and a lot of
his PGA Tour brethren's tails Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Elkington won Doral for the second time in three years, shooting
a final-round 8-under-par 64 to pass 19 players who started the day
in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   Playing nearly two hours in front of the third-round leaders,
Elkington had forged ahead almost before Greg Kraft and friends had
teed off. He strung together six birdies in a row during the middle
of his round and finished at 13-under 275.
</P>
<P>
   And then he waited, thinking his gaffe on No. 18 had left him
one stroke shy of the score that would be needed to qualify for a
playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of hoping for a playoff,'' the Houstonian said,
figuring that was the best he could expect at 13-under. ``I really
thought somebody would get to 14-under.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why he kicked the scoring trailer when he was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little upset at myself,'' he said. ``I felt like I had
let everybody back in. I had a pretty severe lip out, and I was
upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really angry, because I'd just had one of the
greatest rounds I've ever played. I was just frustrated when I came
off because I had done all that work. I had the tournament. Not
sewn up, by any means. But I didn't want to leave any crumbs out
there. I wanted to send a message.''
</P>
<P>
   The message was this: 2-under-par on the back nine would have
been good enough for a win by Ernie Els. If Kraft, David Toms,
Scott Dunlap or Jay Haas had shot 2-under on the back, they could
have forced a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   None could do it.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, the hole that cursed Elkington ended up saving him.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the leaders who became chasers fired and fell back.
Els hit two awful shots on No. 18 for a double bogey. Kraft, who
had a two-shot cushion over Els and Glen Day when play began
Sunday, hit a fat 5-iron into the water on No. 18 for a bogey. If
either player had parred the treacherous 443-yard finisher, he
would have been in a playoff with Elkington. But neither got the
chance to putt for the tie.
</P>
<P>
   Elkington took control of the tournament when he birdied Nos. 6
through 11, making long putts (a 20-footer) and short putts (two
inches and a foot) and even two-putting the par-5 10th for birdie
during the binge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling no pain at all,'' Elkington said. ``I was sort
of counting my birdies a little bit. Then, I stopped my momentum on
that hard 13th hole.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Elkington's lone bogey until the 18th, when he
three-putted from 50 feet.
</P>
<P>
   But Elkington already had seized control. He slowly made his way
up the leader board until getting ahead just after Kraft and Els
had hit their first shots of the day. When it was over, Elkington
confessed he was a bit surprised by the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty lucky, wasn't it?'' he said. ``But I'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Elkington's 10th victory on the PGA Tour, and the
$540,000 winner's check put his career earnings over $7.5 million.
He had started the day six shots behind Kraft, making this the
fifth time Elkington had come from at least four shots off the pace
to win a tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The second shot at No. 18 was the culprit in Els' demise. After
a good tee shot, the 18th is a hole where the only place disaster
can strike is left of the green. So what did Els do? He pulled an
8-iron from only 154 yards about five yards left of the pin. It
trickled down the short cut of grass into deep rough, less than
three feet from the water's edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to really step on the 8-iron,'' Els said. ``I tried to
hit it too hard and just came over the top of it. I wanted to hit
it right of the pin.''
</P>
<P>
   When he didn't, the result wasn't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was up against the thick cut, stuff that really kept it
from going in the water,'' Els said. ``It was almost unplayable,
really. I tried to just get it on the green, and I couldn't get
myself to hit it hard enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you do? You need par, so you try and play a miracle
shot from there. It just didn't come off.''
</P>
<P>
   Els said he felt he lost momentum in his round when he
three-putted the par-3 ninth hole for a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought 15 under was going to be the score (needed
for victory),'' Els said. ``I was right on track until the
three-putt threw me off.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Kraft, he overcame a rocky start with birdies at Nos. 9
and 10, then got to 13-under with a four-foot birdie putt on the
17th.
</P>
<P>
   After he drove it perfectly on 18, he thought he could finish
the tournament with a birdie and a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking of birdie,'' Kraft said. ``The hardest part of
that hole is the tee shot. And I hit that perfect. Then I played an
aggressive shot, and a very poor one. I was telling my caddie,
`Let's end it right now.' And I did.''
</P>
<P>
   But not the way he hoped. The 5-iron shot was hit fat and went
only about 100 yards, plopping into the lake. It was the sort of
shot a weekend hacker hits, not a PGA Tour pro.
</P>
<P>
   Once that shot hit water, Elkington had survived the long
afternoon of waiting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
