<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING SEEMS IN ORDER FOR UCONN 
</HEADLINE>
 MIDWEST PREVIEW-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Jim Calhoun should be smiling this morning. The
University of Connecticut coach got the seed he wanted. He got the
region he wanted (if not the location). And, most important, he got
the bracket he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Let's look. Top-seeded UConn's first-round game in Denver
against Texas-San Antonio should not be a problem. Its second-round
game would be against the Missouri-New Mexico winner, perhaps the
weakest No. 8 vs. No. 9 matchup in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom half of the draw features Iowa and
Alabama-Birmingham. Forget about it. Arkansas and Siena? Watch out
for Arkansas, at least when it gets on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   The Razorbacks may join the Huskies in Phoenix for the regional
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Now examine the other half of the bracket, in Seattle. Stanford
vs. Alcorn State. Stanford is too big, too talented. Minnesota vs.
Gonzaga. Gonzaga can win that one. North Carolina vs. Weber State.
The Tar Heels are too talented. Florida vs. Penn. Penn can
frustrate the Gators.
</P>
<P>
   So, for the sake of argument, UConn and Arkansas would likely be
joined by North Carolina and Stanford, a chalk matchup. But it's
soft chalk.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina isn't the team it was a year ago, and if you don't
think Calhoun and the Huskies want a payback for last year's
regional final loss to Carolina in Greensboro, you don't know your
Huskies or Calhoun. Stanford is a nice team that can get back to
the Final Four, but the Cardinal have a tough time matching up
against the Huskies and Carolina might knock them off before UConn
does.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious obstacle UConn faces is Arkansas. If the Hogs
are playing defense and running, and Pat Bradley is making
3-pointers, they can be 40 minutes of hell for any team.
</P>
<P>
   But Nolan Richardson's team has been inconsistent. Not long ago,
Arkansas was worried about even making the tournament. Now the
Razorbacks are a No. 4 seed. But the only reason they are seeded
that high was that the committee couldn't find another worthy team.
</P>
<P>
   Strange things can happen. Players can get hurt, as Calhoun
knows very well. But this regional looks very favorable for Calhoun
and the Huskies, which could lead to their first Final Four trip.
</P>
<P>
   Let's put it this way: UConn is the best team, with the most
talent and the best coach, although Stanford's Mike Montgomery will
battle you all the way.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest opponent UConn will have out West is UConn. If the
Huskies stay focused and healthy, they're heading to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Teams to watch: Arkansas, Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   Upset specials: Gonzaga over Minnesota, Penn over Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to Phoenix: Arkansas, UConn, Stanford, North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Regional champ: UConn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
