<SLUG> BC-BKW-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC MUST WEATHER NEW CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The dozen pizzas were being devoured, sodas were being
passed around, and snapshots were being taken as the Boston College
women's basketball team gathered at Conte Forum Sunday not to play
a game but to see where and against whom they'll be playing their
next game when the NCAA Tournament starts next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Paula Bacso had comforting words for her teammates as
they waited for word. ``OK, if we go east, we have a lot of fans,''
she said. ``If we go south, we have warm weather.''
</P>
<P>
   The warm weather won.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles will travel to Knoxville, where the University of
Tennessee will host the first and second rounds of the East
Regional. But with the warm weather comes the possibility of facing
defending champion Tennessee in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   BC (21-7), seeded No. 8, will face No. 9 Ohio State (17-11)
Saturday night. Top seed Tennessee (28-2), ranked No. 2 in the
country and champion of the Southeastern Conference, will face
16th-seeded Applachian State (14-14) later that night. The winners
will meet next Monday, and the winner of that game will go on to
Greensboro, N.C., to decide the East Regional the following
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The BC players watched ESPN's telecast of the bracket
announcements in nervous anticipation as hosts Robin Roberts, Mimi
Griffin, and Rebecca Lobo went through the seedings for the West,
then the Midwest, then the Mideast. Finally, hoots and hollers
erupted and the players began hugging when the BC vs. Ohio State
matchup flashed on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   It marks the first time in the 27-year history of the program
that the BC women have made it to the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Cathy Inglese acknowleged that ``we're in a tough
bracket,'' but said she's ready for the competition. ``Ohio State
is probably pretty like us, and I think it's going to be up for
draw,'' she said. ``And whoever plays the better game is going to
have the opportunity to play Tennessee.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State has been to the NCAAs three times, and has beaten BC
in each of their five meetings.
</P>
<P>
   But Tennessee is a far more formidable hurdle. The Lady Vols,
who have won the NCAA championship the past three years, are led by
Chamique Holdsclaw (20.9 points per game), Tamika Catchings (14.8),
and Semeka Randall (13.9).
</P>
<P>
   However, not even the prospect of having to face Tennessee could
damper spirits of a BC team that won 20 games for the first time in
school history, including an upset of another regional top seed,
the University of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Inglese and her players did not seem concerned. In fact, they
seemed to relish the chance to play one of the top teams in the
country. ``I want to play Tennessee,'' Inglese said. ``Tennessee
could be making a record this year with four titles, and we have
the opportunity to play them on their home court. I mean, how much
more exciting can that be?''
</P>
<P>
   Bacso said she felt the same way. ``It's a great place to play _
when are you going to get a chance to play in Knoxville?'' she
said. ``It's a great opportunity. Of all the places, I would love
to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   As for her fans vs. warm weather statement, Bacso said she
thinks the Eagles will have both in Knoxville. ``My parents are
going to go,'' said Bacso, from Long Island. ``I think a lot of
parents will go.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it's up to the BC players to see just how long _ or short _
a trip to Knoxville it will be for their family members and fans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 0152EST &QL; 
