<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-NEWTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWTON PLANTED THE SEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For the last seven years, C.M. Newton has convened the
NCAA Division 1 Men's Basketball Selection Committee and
sequestered it on the 40th floor of the Hyatt hotel in downtown
Kansas City, Mo. There he and the other selection committee members
have evaluated reams of data _ ranging from ratings percentage
indexes to strength of schedules to won-loss records _ and picked
the 64-team field for the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In his last year as chair of the committee, Newton, the athletic
director at the University of Kentucky, fondly recalled during a
conference call Sunday that ``the first time I came here, I
couldn't even find the 40th floor, hardly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those things where you didn't know anybody and I
was scared to death, and the whole process was just almost
overwhelming,'' he added. ``But I was able to do a hell of a job
eating all the ice cream and the meals and all that kind of thing
and watch a lot of games.''
</P>
<P>
   While he witnessed quite a number of upsets among the Top 25
teams in the last 48 hours of his term, Newton indicated it never
hindered the selection process. At no time was the committee
compelled to re-do brackets. All that was required, really, was
some pencil sharpening.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we weren't close to tearing it up, because of all the
constraints,'' Newton said. ``The upsets delayed what we were able
to do, and what we did do, and it made us a little later than we
would like to be. But we were able to do it in a timely fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, shortly after the Big 12 tournament championship was
decided by Kansas's 53-37 victory over Oklahoma State, the
committee finalized the field _ putting it down in ink _ by naming
Duke, Connecticut, Michigan State, and Auburn as the No. 1 seeds in
the East, West, Midwest, and South regions, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Auburn, by losing (in the SEC tournament), created a situation
where you might have had those four (No. 1s) penciled in with your
eraser still on your pencil,'' Newton said. ``As with any of those
_ other than probably Duke or UConn losing _ I think if Michigan
State had gotten upset today, just as Auburn got upset, then you'd
see about Maryland and Stanford. But when both of those teams lost,
the committee felt that Auburn should retain its No. 1 standing.''
</P>
<P>
   No upset there.
</P>
<P>
   But if there appeared to be one, it was the fact that UConn,
which won the Big East tournament championship Saturday night with
an 82-63 romp over St. John's (a No. 3 seed in the South), was
dispatched well beyond its natural geographical area. The Huskies
(28-2) will face No. 16 seed Texas-San Antonio, champions of the
Southland Conference, in a first-round meeting Thursday at Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason is because Duke is the No. 1 seed,'' Newton said of
Connecticut's move to the West. ``UConn came out second, but had to
go out of region because Duke was the top seed.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the committee's general philosophy on keeping
lower-seeded teams closer to home _ which appeared to be the case
with No. 10 Gonzaga of Spokane, Wash., in its first-round West
Region matchup against No. 7 seed Minnesota in nearby Seattle _
Newton said: ``We want to play teams as close to their homes as
best we can without disadvantaging, in a significant way, a high
seed. We've made a concentrated effort to keep teams as close as we
can to their geographical area, so that their fans can go see them.
In the first-round game, the teams get 350 tickets or whatever and
we didn't feel it would disadvantage anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The only team that would appear to face a huge disadvantage by
its bracket placement would be No. 16 seed Florida A&AMP;M. The
Rattlers, the only team in the field with a sub-.500 record
(12-18), won an automatic bid by winning the Mid-Eastern Athletic
Conference. Their spoils? A first-round date in the East Region
against top-seeded Duke _ in Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good for the tournament and good for college
basketball to have teams like that,'' Newton said of the Rattlers.
``Just think of the experience that those young people are going to
have. It's the absolute experience of a lifetime to make that
field. That's the beauty of this national tournament _ it's truly
national.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 0154EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1431 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-NCAA-NEWENGLAND-B     03-08 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-NCAA-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINE LANDS AT-LARGE BID 
</HEADLINE>
 ENGLAND-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY VAN HANDLE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Since the NCAA women's basketball tournament expanded
to 64 teams six seasons ago, one fact has been very clear to teams
from lower-profile leagues: If you don't win your postseason
conference tournament, expect to stay home, regardless of record.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, after Maine lost to Northeastern by 2 points in the
America East final Saturday, the Black Bears left Vermont's Patrick
Gym with heads hung low and even heavier hearts. Despite a 23-6
record and regular-season conference title, it appeared the Black
Bears would be left on the sideline for this year's NCAA event.
</P>
<P>
   So when the team gathered Sunday for the NCAA selection show, no
one was expecting much to cheer about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all showed up kind of somber,'' said Maine coach Joanne
Palombo-McCallie. ``I was prepared to tell the team why teams don't
get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the reaction in Orono was anything but somber when
Maine learned it was chosen as an at-large team, given the 10th
seed in the East Regional, and matched against seventh-seeded
Stanford Friday in a first-round game at Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Bears are one of a record-tying six New England teams
that will play in this year's tourney, along with another at-large
selection, Boston College, plus league champions Northeastern,
Connecticut (Big East), Holy Cross (Patriot League), and Dartmouth
(Ivy League).
</P>
<P>
   ``Your stomach was in knots. When Maine flashed up (on the
television screen), we screamed. It was a very special moment, one
I'll never forget,'' said Palombo-McCallie.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ended the season as a good team, and their loss in the
playoffs was narrow,'' said Bernadette McGlade, chairman of the
women's selection committee. ``There's no rule we can't have two
from the America East.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine's Rating Power Index (RPI) ranking of 42, only one spot
below perennial power Virginia, played a part in its selection. An
18-2 record over its last 20 games and four straight NCAA berths
also helped.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Dartmouth figured it wouldn't be going anywhere but
to downtown Hanover, N.H., during the NCAA tourney. A game behind
Princeton in the Ivy standings, the Big Green had to win their
final game at Harvard, then hope the Tigers somehow lost at home to
Penn to conclude the regular season and force a one-game playoff
for the league title.
</P>
<P>
   The day after all parameters were met and Dartmouth concluded
its unlikely run by winning the Ivy championship with a playoff
trouncing of Princeton, the Big Green (19-8) gathered to learn that
they drew the No. 14 seed in the East and will play host Rutgers,
the third seed, Friday at Piscataway, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very excited to be in the tourney, especially as a 14th
seed,'' said Dartmouth coach Chris Wielgus. ``We have tremendous
backing in the community, and a game this close allows those people
to be able to make the trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Holy Cross knows the NCAAs; the Crusaders will be making their
seventh trip to the Dance when they play host Duke in Durham, N.C.,
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never gets old, it only gets better,'' said coach Bill
Gibbons.
</P>
<P>
   Holy Cross (21-7) takes a 10-game win streak into the tourney.
</P>
<P>
   ``No athletic scholarships and a 14 seed,'' said Gibbons. ``It
gets sweeter every year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
