<HEADLINE>
FOCUS ON GLITTER COULD END UP UPSETTING 
</HEADLINE>
 MIDWEST PREVIEW-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ From a historical perspective, the Midwest Regional
appears to be overloaded. In the field are Kansas, defending
national champion Kentucky, Big Ten champion Michigan State, and
Western Athletic Conference champion Utah.
</P>
<P>
   But appearances may be deceiving. Upsets could abound here,
because at varying stages of the season all of these teams looked
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with the bracket in Milwaukee, which includes No. 1
seed Michigan State. In the first round, the Spartans should
prevent venerable Mount St. Mary's coach Jim Phelan from getting
victory No. 801. And neither Villanova nor Ole Miss looks
frightening as a second-round obstacle. Both were considered bubble
teams on the NCAA board.
</P>
<P>
   Pencil Michigan State into the regional semifinals in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's look at the other half of the Milwaukee bracket. Rhode
Island is there, courtesy of Lamar Odom's last-second shot to beat
Temple in Saturday's Atlantic 10 tournament final. The Rams are a
tough team to figure out. Had they not beaten Temple, they were
headed to the National Invitation Tournament, not the NCAA. But
when they play, they can play with anyone, including Michigan
State.
</P>
<P>
   But will they play? They had better. The 12th-seeded Rams' first
opponent is No. 5 North Carolina-Charlotte, a streaking team that
knocked off Cincinnati and Louisville, back to back, on the way to
the Conference USA championship.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rams survive that test, they'll really need their ``A''
game in the second round, since fourth-seeded Arizona likely will
be waiting. And that means national player of the year candidate
Jason Terry.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rams make it out of Milwaukee, it'll be a major upset.
</P>
<P>
   The other half of the draw has the sexy teams, which is not
surprising since the NCAA was hurting in ticket sales in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   That shouldn't be the case anymore. Kentucky's presence will
draw a crowd, and a possible second-round matchup between the No. 3
Wildcats and No. 6 Kansas would have the feel of a Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas coach Roy Williams is likely to experience some big-time
emotions next weekend. He could see his team's season end
prematurely once again. Or he might knock off the defending
national champion, something his Jayhawks were unable to do in the
Great Eight in Chicago in December.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom half of that draw must have Utah coach Rick Majerus
wondering what he has done wrong. Three times in the last four
years he has had Kentucky on his NCAA dance card. Last year, he
didn't see the Wildcats until the national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Utah, the No. 2 seed, should knock off Arkansas State, then
either Washington or Miami of Ohio. That would bring Majerus face
to face with Kentucky again. Can he beat the Wildcats?
</P>
<P>
   It looks like a chalk regional final. It's just a question of
which chalk you use.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State might have problems with the speed of Arizona,
while Utah has to overcome the mystique of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Teams to watch: Arizona, UNC-Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Upset specials: Miami of Ohio over Washington, Evansville over
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to St. Louis: Kentucky, Utah, Michigan State, Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Regional champ: Kentucky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
