<HEADER>
A1433 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-NCAATOURNAMENT-BO     03-08 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-NCAA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN WOMEN LAND NO. 1 SEED 
</HEADLINE>
 TOURNAMENT-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY VAN HANDLE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A year ago, the Connecticut women's basketball team was
discovering how many ways the loss of its best player could affect
it.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did an injured Nykesha Sales's uncontested, staged
layup to set a school scoring record set off a national
controversy, it put coach Geno Auriemma's temper on display for all
to see.
</P>
<P>
   Soon thereafter, the loss of Sales to a torn anterior cruciate
ligament also was responsible for the Huskies' No. 2 seed in the
NCAA Tournament after landing four straight top seeds.
</P>
<P>
   But this March, all has been made right in Storrs. Sixth-ranked
UConn is the No. 1 seed in the Mideast Regional, with its first two
games at Gampel Pavilion and potential third- and fourth-round
games at the University of Cincinnati, only a half-hour from
freshman forward Tamika Williams's hometown of Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's 27 wins, our schedule,'' said Auriemma of his
team's return to a No. 1 seed. ``We've won a lot of really good
games on the road, and our conference had a really high rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a problem last year not being a one (seed). You
take any team in the country and take away their best player,
they're not the same team. You can't reward a team for their
season; you have to project going into the tournament who the top
four teams in the country are.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the fact that UConn is ranked sixth means that two
schools ranked higher _ Colorado State and Old Dominion _ were
bypassed as top seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Bernadette McGlade, chairman of the women's selection committee,
told ESPN: ``The committee really analyzed all the aspects _ the
overall won-lost records as well as the conference championships.
Then the committee started to take a look at the number of games
against the Top 25 teams, and certainly Connecticut rose to the top
in that category to earn that No. 1 seed.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn lost to Tennessee, Old Dominion, Boston College, and
Louisiana Tech, dropping three of six games during a midseason
slump. But the Huskies have won 12 of 13 since, capped by cutting a
three-game swath through the Big East tournament.
</P>
<P>
   UConn (27-4) plays St. Francis (18-11) in a first-round game
Friday. If the Huskies dispose of the Northeast Conference
champion, they'd play the winner of Xavier-Florida International.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is looking forward to a trip home if UConn makes the
Sweet 16. ``I want to go back home and play in front of a home
crowd. But we need to prove we can play in Ohio,'' said Williams,
who leads the Huskies with 6.9 rebounds and is averaging 13.5
points per game.
</P>
<P>
   While UConn, making its 11 straight trip to the Dance, tries to
get to its first Final Four since 1996, Chamique Holdsclaw will be
trying to finish her glittery career with a fourth national
championship in four years at Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Vols and Louisiana Tech, the only schools to have
appeared in all 17 previous NCAA tourneys, also earned top seeds.
Top-ranked Purdue, which handed Tennessee one of only two losses in
the Boilermakers' first game of the season, is the other No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee has won six titles, while the Lady Techsters won their
only title in 1982, the year the NCAA took control of the tourney
from the Association of Intercollegiate Athletics for Women.
</P>
<P>
   This year's lesson in how a team's seeding can fall due to a key
injury: When point guard Niele Ivy's knee caved in during Notre
Dame's Big East semifinal win over Rutgers, the Irish fell to a
fifth seed despite its status as a Top 10 team.
</P>
<P>
   And if anyone thinks the host schools, who play their first two
games at home campus sites, have it easy, check out UCLA. The
Bruins would play four straight in Los Angeles, should they advance
that far.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any doubt about the location of the women's
collegiate basketball power base, look south. The Southeastern
Conference has eight participants and the Atlantic Coast five. The
Midwest/Southwest has five from the Big 12, four from Conference
USA, and four from the Big Ten. The West Coast's Pacific 10 is also
sending four teams.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cal State Northridge, winner of the Big Sky tourney,
righted itself after suffering major trauma. Its former coach,
Michael Abraham, resigned following his arrest in October on
charges that he sold crack cocaine in Omaha, Neb. Assistant Frozena
Jerro led the Matadors to a 21-7 record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
