<HEADER>
A1435 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-WOLVES-SPI     03-08 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-WOLVES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMBERWOLVES TRIP SONICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ And the Sonics' struggles continue.
</P>
<P>
   The less-than-super Sonics dropped their third straight game
Sunday night and the fifth in their past seven. This time it was a
ho-hum 88-77 setback to the Minnesota Timberwolves at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   It was disturbingly similar to the Sonics' loss to the Phoenix
Suns at home last Thursday and Friday night's exciting, but still
losing, effort to the Lakers in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it wasn't pretty. It's getting to be more like a
trend,'' coach Paul Westphal said after his team slipped to 9-7 as
it heads to the Midwest for a three-games-in-three-nights road
trip. ``Minnesota came in here and kicked us, just like Phoenix
did. It seems like a trend. In order for us to get back into it,
we've got to start working together as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   The disjointed Sonics failed to get it done on either end of the
court against the Timberwolves, who improved their record to 11-6
to keep pace with the Utah Jazz in the Midwest Division.
</P>
<P>
   On offense, the Sonics shot 40.3 percent, but they were a
horrendous 4 of 23 on 3-point attempts. Gary Payton, the team's
leading scorer, finished with a game-high 20 points. But he missed
18 of his 27 shots and was just 1 of 9 on treys.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, the Sonics looked tired and like the older team as
they struggled to stay with the younger, fresher Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics did a respectable job on Kevin Garnett, holding the
T-Wolves' 6-foot-11 jumping jack to 19 points. They did an even
better job on Stephon Marbury, who scored only 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   But the T-Wolves' bench proved to be the difference in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Malik Sealy, who played last season with the Detroit Pistons
after four seasons of NBA purgatory with the L.A. Clippers, hit 8
of 13 shots in scoring 18 points. Sam Mitchell, who played his
501st game with Minnesota, chipped in 16 points as the sub-Wolves
contributed 41 points.
</P>
<P>
   In stark contrast, the Sonics' bench scored only 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bench, we try to bring it whether it's on the defensive
end or the offensive end,'' Sealy said. ``Tonight, fortunately, we
were able to get it cooking on both ends. We were able to contest
their shots on one end and hit the open shots we got at the other
end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I was looking to shoot tonight,'' he said. ``I
was open. And when you're open you have to make them pay for
leaving you open.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what made Sunday night's loss especially distasteful for
the Sonics. It's one thing to play poorly on offense. It's
un-Sonic-like to let the lackluster effort carry over to the
defensive end of the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to do a better job on defense,'' said Dale Ellis,
who had an interesting evening with a blocked shot and a tip-in,
but was only 2 of 7 at shooting 3-pointers, his speciality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had guys come in and play good selectively, but we need
to play more as a team,'' he said. ``Gary has carried us most of
the way, and we need for the rest of us to get on the same page.
We're not going to make every shot, but as a team it can be
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts like the one Sunday night are making it harder for
Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not play with much emotion in the first half, but we
did a lot better in the third quarter,'' he said. ``In this league,
you've got to play 48 minutes and not just quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dragging offensively,'' he added. ``We need to work a
little harder at that end.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics did make several runs at the T-Wolves, tying the
score at 47 with just under eight minutes left in the third quarter
and then cutting Minnesota's lead to three, 67-64, at the start of
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But every time they made a run, the Sonics would follow it by
stumbling on one end or the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight, we were just flat,'' said Vin Baker, who scored only
nine points but did contribute 10 rebounds and three blocked shots.
``For what reason, I don't know. ... The thing we have to realize
is that going through this period of time we can't get down on each
other or the coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   If performances like the one Sunday night and the one against
the Suns continue, that will become more and more difficult.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
