u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     03-08 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DUKE. You're welcome. That takes care of March 29 in St. Pete.
</P>
<P>
   Now all you have to do is plug in the winners of the other 62
games in the NCAA Tournament, and you collect on your pool.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you'll only have to beat out the computer geek who's
been up each night since the opening round of the Maui Classic and
the Great Alaska Shootout feeding new data into his circuitry and
letting the microchips give him the latest power ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Or you'll have to outthink the office intern, the one with
Scotch tape on his glasses and gum stuck to the bottom of his shoe,
who works out the pairings the old-fashioned way, like those NASA
engineers back in the days of the Apollo program, with a slide
rule.
</P>
<P>
   Or the giggly young woman in the accounting department who fills
out her bracket according to her favorite colors. Or the crotchety
lady in personnel who lets her pit bull chew on Milk-Bones labeled
with the names of all the teams in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Or your grandmother, who looks like she's been napping since
November but actually has a copy of Hoopin' It Up With Dick Vitale
hidden under that afghan and is going to take you to the rack like
she always has since the days when you were just a droolin' diaper
dandy, bay-bee!
</P>
<P>
   Duke. Coach K and the Blue Devils cutting down the nets on a
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   After that, you're on your own to handicap a tournament that
gets tighter and tighter and tougher to figure out each year. And
we're just talking about the seedings and the placements.
</P>
<P>
   How does Kansas, which spent the winter trading on its past
reputation, get a No. 6 seed and a berth in the geographically
friendly Midwest Regional when Texas, the Big 12 regular-season
champ, is seeded No. 7 and shipped up to Boston in the East
Regional?
</P>
<P>
   You figure the selection committee must have given considerable
weight to the relative performances in the Big 12 postseason
tournament. That is, until you notice that Oklahoma State, which
defeated Texas in the semifinals, drew only a No. 9 seed in the
South Regional.
</P>
<P>
   If you're Rick Barnes' bunch, a first-round date with slumping
Purdue could be a good matchup. But looking ahead to the second
round, the Longhorns would likely have to encounter Miami (Fla.),
which has been a terror all year long in the Big East.
</P>
<P>
   The season began, and nobody gave Auburn a second look. Now the
Tourney begins, and the Tigers have a No. 1 seed in the South even
after a ripping by Kentucky in the SEC tournament. What's the
answer?
</P>
<P>
   Duke. Elton Brand, Trajan Langdon, Shane Battier, William Avery.
</P>
<P>
   They call this March Madness because this is supposed to be such
an easy stroll for the Blue Devils, and yet you know that
somewhere, somebody along the road to the Final Four will leap out
of the shadows _ maybe just for a few minutes _ and give them a
scare or all they can handle.
</P>
<P>
   The last team so heavily favored to waltz its way through the
Big Dance was UNLV in 1991. And the Rebels waltzed right into a
stunning upset in the national semifinals. By Christian Laettner
and Bobby Hurley and Grant Hill and Coach K.
</P>
<P>
   The Dookies would seem to have clear sailing through the first
two rounds of the Tournament, and their only real hurdle along the
road to St. Pete could be a possible rematch with Cincinnati _ the
only blemish on a perfect record. The assumption there is that Bob
Huggins' team doesn't suffer through one of its regular early-round
meltdowns, which then triggers a meltdown of a different sort by
Huggins himself.
</P>
<P>
   As for annual Tournament events, we will wait for the tears to
spill out of Roy Williams when Kansas makes another early exit. If
the Evansville Aces don't do the trick in the first round, then
Kentucky will likely turn on Roy's faucet in the second-round clash
of big-name programs.
</P>
<P>
   Every year a No. 5 seed is tripped by a No. 12 seed, and those
possibilities do abound. While in the West, Iowa (No. 5) should be
able to handle Alabama-Birmingham, the South has always-fragile
UCLA (No. 5) tangling with Detroit, the East pits slumping
Wisconsin (No. 5) against dangerous Southwest Missouri State, and
the Midwest has North Carolina Charlotte (No. 5) matched with
NBA-ready Lamar Odom and Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   The subregional with the most real depth, rather than just
names, is in the West at Denver, where No. 1 seed Connecticut gets
Texas-San Antonio in the first round but then must pick its way
through a minefield of Missouri, New Mexico, Iowa and a tough bunch
from Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Valpo's back, this time without Bryce Drew. Lafayette is back
for the first time since 1957. Kent is in for the first time ever.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, there are only two sure things:
</P>
<P>
   Duke.
</P>
<P>
   And there are no sure things.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
