<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1438 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     03-08 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ROBERTSONCOLUMN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Maybe this is the ticket for the Jayhawks. Maybe
it's better for them to enter the NCAA Tournament as mostly chalk
instead of rock. Less pressure plus lower expectations equals more
fun?
</P>
<P>
   Given their recent sad history, it surely can't hurt to try a
backdoor approach. They have already perfected the art of getting
the front door slammed on their fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will be saying one of two things,'' Kansas' put-upon
coach, Roy Williams, noted sardonically. ``Either we're finally
peaking at the right time, or we're setting everybody up for
another bad fall.''
</P>
<P>
   A bit of bitterness aside, that KU won another Big 12 Conference
tournament Sunday in the role of underdog instead of big dog had to
have ranked among Williams' more prized accomplishments. For a
change, the playing field was Great Plains level going in, with any
of four or five teams capable of clipping the Kemper Arena nets at
the end.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be the well-rehearsed Jayhawks who found a way to
make the honor theirs again. Was it a coronation, though? Hardly.
Royalty they aren't. Williams was in full agreement on that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just kids,'' he said. ``But even when they've
`failed,' I've never once stopped believing that they're great
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   After what Roy called ``maybe my most difficult'' regular
season, the 22-9 Jayhawks fought through the pack here as the No. 3
seed and won less on talent surplus against Nebraska, Kansas State
and Oklahoma State than on sheer determination and gumption,
although the hapless Cowboys, playing for the fourth day in a row,
didn't have the legs or bullets to properly seek the vengeance they
sought.
</P>
<P>
   A brutal referee's call sealed Oklahoma State's fate in Lawrence
recently, giving KU a winning free throw with no time left. There
was nothing unjust, however, about the 53-37 rematch except the
back-to-back-to-back-to-back circumstances the Cowboys found
themselves in. Unfortunately, that's how it has to be when you fail
to procure a first-round bye.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Sutton's slow Pokes simply had nothing in their tanks. How
else, pray tell, do you explain 23 percent shooting at the
major-college level?
</P>
<P>
   The fearless Jayhawks freshman, Jeff Boschee, said KU's defense
deserved the credit. It didn't. It was good _ but not that good.
You know how freshmen are.
</P>
<P>
   As for Kansas only shooting 36 percent?
</P>
<P>
   ``What you saw out there today,'' Williams said, ``were two
tired basketball teams.''
</P>
<P>
   If the NCAA Tournament selection committee, convening nearby,
had judged the Big 12 solely on the merits of the championship
scuffle, the conference wouldn't have placed five schools in the
field of 64. There couldn't have been a more raggedy title bout
staged anywhere in the country over the weekend. No, these were
hardly the Jayhawks of lore, of Raef LaFrentz, Paul Pierce and
Jacque Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Because of names such as those, Williams has won more games
faster than any coach in history. He passed 300 three weeks ago,
and his .810 winning percentage is the highest among active members
of his profession. But his satisfaction with himself and his
program has been tempered by KU's inability to go the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not many bad things about coaching,'' Williams says.
``It's a short list. But the worst thing is that the highs aren't
nearly as high as the lows are low, nor do they last as long.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, he's a tormented guy, haunted by failure more than
he's energized by success. And the last two seasons produced the
biggest disappointments of all. Both teams, the former 34-2 and the
latter 35-4, had valid national championship aspirations, yet
neither came close. A year ago, the Jayhawks were beaten in the
second round. By Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair,'' Williams argues. ``The past couple seasons,
expectations have been so high that it's been impossible to feel
good about yourself, because you don't win a national title or get
to the Final Four. Yet deep down inside, I know we did a good job
with those teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The most crazed of Jayhawks fans would roundly disagree, of
course. But they should, nonetheless, love the current team. So
what if it has been out of the rankings for four of the last five
weeks and had to settle for a ho-hum sixth seed in the Midwest
Regional bracket?
</P>
<P>
   These kitty Hawks, for now, aren't hot NBA prospects or
consensus All-Americans, which routinely pepper Williams' rosters.
They're a somewhat anonymous lot, a collection of fresh-faced works
in progress who return next season en masse save for Ryan Robertson
and T.J. Pugh.
</P>
<P>
   Kids. Yes, that's all they are _ kids. And Kentucky, the
defending national champion, the program that grabbed what Kansas
wanted in 1998, now looms in the second round in New Orleans. The
Wildcats may be concluding something of a down year, too, but you
do sort of hate to have to mess with them the first weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, on second thought, that might be the perfect matchup
for the Jayhawks. How mad could Kansans be about their losing early
to almighty Kentucky?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Williams, for one, fears the worst. Guess he's conditioned
to it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
