<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1440 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-HNS &LR;      03-08 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Duke gets to stay on Tobacco Road before heading for the Big
Apple. Michigan State has a short trip to Milwaukee. Auburn stayed
in the South, even if the NCAA seems to think Indianapolis is in
the ``South'' these days.
</P>
<P>
   So who was the big winner when the NCAA men's selection
committee wrapped up the arduous business of picking and seeding
Sunday afternoon and announced its four No. 1s for this year's
foray into March Madness?
</P>
<P>
   How about Connecticut?
</P>
<P>
   Jim Calhoun's Huskies, 28-2 and the nation's No. 1 team for much
of the season, find that the Road to the Final Four leads through
Denver and Phoenix, hardly a hop, skip and jump from Storrs, Conn.
All things considered, however, they may not mind a trip out West.
</P>
<P>
   There are, it appears, some advantages to taking the long way to
St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, there's that first-round game with Texas-San
Antonio. Arkansas, seeded fourth in the West, stands as the biggest
roadblock, and the Razorbacks won't come up until the regional
semifinal. The No. 2 seed in the region, Stanford, is a team the
Huskies already have beaten soundly on the Cardinal's home floor
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Other than tacking on a few extra frequent-flier miles,
Connecticut may have a good thing going here. Surely it has to be
better than last season, when the Huskies got to play North
Carolina in Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   This draw even offers a chance to settle that, since the Tar
Heels are the No. 3 seed in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder, then, that Calhoun was able to see a silver
lining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more interested in brackets than geography,'' he said
Sunday. ``It's who's gonna be where you're gonna be, who you have
to beat to go where you want to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know where we want to go. We'd like to go to Florida. We
think we're good enough, but we know the trials and tribulations of
trying to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no shortage of trials and tribulations in setting this
64-team field, selection committee chairman C.M. Newton admitted
when the work finally was done. The biggest one involved what to do
with Connecticut, the Big East regular-season and conference
champion.
</P>
<P>
   Logically, the Huskies belonged in the East, but No. 1-ranked
Duke (32-1 and winner of 27 straight) was an even better fit.
Michigan State (29-4), in turn, had earned its spot in the Midwest
as Big Ten regular-season and tournament champion and the logical
fit geographically.
</P>
<P>
   The committee then tinkered with putting Calhoun's team in the
South.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't work, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the conference constraints, we disadvantaged so
many teams, moving so many other teams out of regions, that we went
back and did another bracket with UConn in the West, and it was
much fairer,'' Newton said.
</P>
<P>
   So Auburn (27-3) got the South, where No. 2 seed Maryland and
No. 3 St. John's don't figure to go away without an argument. Even
on their own side of the bracket, the Tigers must contend with No.
4 Ohio State or No. 5 UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been worse, of course at the very least,
different. Auburn got the final No. 1 seed only after Maryland (a
loser to North Carolina in the Atlantic Coast Conference tournament
semifinal) and Stanford (upset Saturday night by Oregon State)
failed to make appropriate last-minute bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``When both of those lost,'' Newton said, ``the committee felt
Auburn should retain its No. 1 standing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the East, Duke got the sort of ride befitting its status as
the nation's No. 1 team and the clear favorite to wind up cutting
down the nets at Tropicana Field on March 29. The Blue Devils open
against 12-18 Florida A&AMP;M in Charlotte, then get the winner of the
Tulsa-College of Charleston game in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't win, we'll know that we did everything we could to
try to win it and we didn't let the pressure stop us,'' coach Mike
Krzyzewski said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Midwest, meanwhile, Michigan State clinched the top seed
by ending Illinois' surprising run in the Big Ten tournament final.
Illinois was hoping to make the field at 15-17 but ran out of gas
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   While that didn't do much for spirits in Champaign, it raised
them considerably in Norman, Okla., where the Sooners (seeded No.
13 in the Midwest) appear to have been the last team chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's safe to say they were pretty late,'' Newton said.
</P>
<P>
   Better late than not at all, of course, as TCU (19-10), Xavier
(21-10), Fresno State (21-11), Mississippi State (20-12) and
Rutgers (18-12) _ to name just a few _ would surely attest.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Big Ten got seven bids (with bubble boys Minnesota
and Purdue each surviving), followed by the Southeastern Conference
with six. The Big East and Big 12 got five each, while the Pac-10
and Conference USA managed four apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Among the day's big losers: The mighty ACC received only three
spots _ the same as the Missouri Valley, Western Athletic and
Atlantic 10 _ as potential No. 4s Wake Forest and North Carolina
State ultimately were found lacking.
</P>
<P>
   Others helped their stock near the end.
</P>
<P>
   Utah, the WAC champion, got a No. 2 seed in the Midwest, a trip
to New Orleans and a first-round game with Arkansas State as a
reward for its strong finish.
</P>
<P>
   Miami (Fla.) drew that honor in the East, while Maryland and
Stanford settled for the second spot in the South and West,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky overcame a late-season slump to win the SEC tournament
and grab a No. 3 seed in the Midwest, joining Cincinnati (East),
St. John's (South) and North Carolina (West) on the third line.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas' strong finish _ the Hogs beat Auburn and Kentucky late
in the season before losing to the Wildcats in the SEC title game _
got Nolan Richardson that No. 4 in the West, while Tennessee
(East), Arizona (Midwest) and Ohio State (South) completed the top
16 seeds.
</P>
<P>
   As for games to watch?
</P>
<P>
   Duke-Charleston could be fun (for a while, at least) in a
potential second-rounder. A Cincinnati-Temple second-round match,
meanwhile, could provide some fun in the coach-watching department
as mild-mannered Bob Huggins and laid-back John Chaney get
together.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina Charlotte went from bubble team to No. 5 in the
Midwest by winning the C-USA tournament, and a second-round meeting
with No. 4 seed Arizona might be entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas and Kentucky also are on a course for a second-round
showdown in the Midwest, and St. John's Mike Jarvis could see his
old team (George Washington, coached by Tom Penders) in Round Two
in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom, however, is that those will merely be
sideshows leading up to another Duke title. The Blue Devils are as
hot as can be and poised to take a lot of the fun out of the next
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to be part of something bigger than themselves,''
Krzyzewski said.
</P>
<P>
   That other team that spent much of the season at No. 1 still
dreams of cutting the Blue Devils down to size.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut may find that a tall order. At least getting there
this time has a chance to be a little more fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
