<HEADER>
A1460 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAIPAN-SEAFARING-SFCH     03-08 1411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIPAN-SEAFARING-SFCHRON(W/SIDEBAR) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP OF ISLANDERS ON SAIPAN SALVAGE THEIR SEAFARING PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT COLLIER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;   &LR;   &LR; SAIPAN, Northern Mariana Islands _ Lino Olopai strode up to
the counter at the McDonald's, and he didn't even have to order.
<P>
   ``The usual?'' the woman behind the counter asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' he replied with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   But despite his friendly smile, his eyes were creased as if they
were looking at an empty ocean horizon. He didn't quite fit in a
fast-food joint, even one on Saipan, a small, tropical piece of the
United States in the western Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   When he sat down at a table with his vanilla milk shake, Big Mac
and fries, he shook his head apologetically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong just because I'm here, eating this. We
Carolinians are Americanized, but our hearts aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Olopai is a leader of a movement among Saipan's two local
indigenous groups, the Carolinians and the more-numerous Chamorros,
that is trying to rescue traditional islander culture from the
advance of modern consumerism.
</P>
<P>
   The movement stretches far beyond Saipan to Hawaii and hundreds
of inhabited atolls and volcanic peaks scattered across thousands
of miles of Pacific Ocean. On some islands, the old ways are still
alive, with grass skirts and a subsistence lifestyle, but on
others, such as Saipan, indigenous culture has been largely
overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   As he munched on his Big Mac, Olopai explained that the key to
protecting indigenous identity is to revive the ancient art of
canoe navigating. For 6,000 years, Pacific islanders have steered
sailing canoes on long voyages without instruments or charts. The
navigators, or palu, guide themselves unerringly by the stars, wave
and wind direction, mid-ocean clusters of fish _ and, they say, the
guidance of ocean goddesses.
</P>
<P>
   Olopai and his cousin, Mau Piailug, one of the last master
navigators of the entire Pacific, are teaching the old ways of the
Refalawasch, or people of our land, as Carolinians call themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The 66-year-old Piailug, from the tiny Caroline Islands atoll of
Satawal, 500 miles southeast of Saipan, has given classes in
navigation in Saipan's high schools and is acting as a mentor for
young, would-be navigators. He also spends several months a year in
Hawaii, where he has helped native Hawaiians revive their long-dead
navigating tradition.
</P>
<P>
   On February 10, Piailug, his son and a Carolinian apprentice
embarked from Hawaii on a 6,220-mile, three-month canoe journey
through Micronesia, accompanied by 13 Hawaiian crew members. They
made their first landfall March 2, at Majuro in the Marshall
Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The study of traditional navigating is a slow, painstaking task,
involving the memorization of a huge amount of astronomical and
marine data that has been passed on orally from generation to
generation. Most youngsters decide it's not for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a gift from our ancestors over many, many years,''
said Piailug in an interview on Saipan before starting his voyage.
``It is courage. Courage is memory. I watch which person
comprehends, which one listens. Very few do. Many just want to run
off to America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, decades ago, the palu were respected because we
brought food from the sea. Now, the food comes in boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that when he was a child, there were about 45
traditional navigators in Micronesia, a broad area of the western
Pacific that includes the Mariana, Caroline and Marshall Islands.
Now there are only 15.
</P>
<P>
   In few cultures outside Micronesia is memory tied so closely to
survival. If a navigator at sea fails to remember the correct
formula of stars, currents or locations of fish clusters, he _ and
all those on board _ will fail to find land and thus perish. For
many Carolinians, therefore, there is a collective compulsion to
remember the old traditions.
</P>
<P>
   In the Northern Mariana Islands, the Carolinians are a small
minority. Carolinians total only 3,500, outnumbered by 17,000
members of the more Westernized Chamorro indigenous group, as well
as 4,000 U.S. ``mainlanders'' and 40,000 Asians who work in
Saipan's hotels and garment factories.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 10,000 Carolinians live in the Caroline Islands,
from where the Saipan Carolinians migrated after a huge typhoon in
1810.
</P>
<P>
   Although all navigators and almost all canoe crew members are
men _ part of the rigid gender divisions of traditional islander
culture _ Carolinian women activists are supportive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Navigating is the one thing that united our people, spread out
as we are on so many islands,'' said Cinta Kaipat, an aide in the
local legislature and the first Carolinian woman ever to become a
lawyer. ``You can't buy it, you can't sell it, and no one else can
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   A strong streak of anti-materialism prevails among the
Carolinians, in part because they have long lagged behind the
Chamorros in economic development and are especially vulnerable to
the harsh side of progress.
</P>
<P>
   Carolinian unemployment on Saipan is estimated at 20 percent,
and alcoholism, drug abuse (mainly of crystal methamphetamine),
domestic violence and obesity are widespread.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing that has happened to our people is money,''
Kaipat said, referring to the U.S. government's multimillion-dollar
payments of claims for World War II combat damage and the even
larger payments, in the 1980s and 1990s, by Japanese hotel
developers to the lucky few with beachfront property.
</P>
<P>
   ``It began setting families against each other, brothers versus
sisters. The wealthier people got, the poorer they got,'' she said.
``It's all about fast food and convenience. You open up a can of
Spam, as opposed to going out to the reef to fish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectation of striking it rich pervades almost the whole
society and has done enormous damage, while raising the standard of
living of the lucky ones,'' said Samuel McPhetres, a historian of
the Pacific Islands who teaches at College of the Northern
Marianas, Saipan's community college. ``Wishful thinking is the
rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Carolinians' traditional concept of tipiyeew, or
solidarity, has dissolved. ``Now, Joe Blow over there needs help,
but so what, I don't know him from Adam,'' Kaipat said, mimicking
the modern attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Kaipat is the leader of several hundred Carolinians and
Chamorros who are lobbying the local government to lift its ban on
habitation of a chain of small islands north of Saipan, which were
evacuated after a volcano erupted there in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   She wants to lead a collective return to her home island, Pagan,
and other northern islands to re-establish traditionalist
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Historians say that the loss of identity among the Carolinians,
who had less contact with Western society until recent years, has
been much less severe than among the Chamorros, who underwent
significant mixing with Filipino garrison soldiers under Spanish
colonialism in the 18th and 19th centuries and have been relatively
Westernized ever since. As a result, there is little support for
old traditions among the Chamorros.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, the home was the center of life,'' Kaipat said. ``Now,
can you imagine, grandma and grandpa have to be schlepped off to
play bingo all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Saipan's local government has helped the Carolinian
traditionalist movement grow, aiding cultural activities and the
navigation classes. Recently, however, the money has dried up, and
the government's Carolinian Affairs Office is now seeking federal
funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to reach kids nowadays, with all the TV and
drugs and everything else,'' said Frank Rabauliman, the office
director.
</P>
<P>
   But even the traditionalists like a dose of modernity every now
and then. Like Olopai, who admits that his craving for fast food
``pretty much contradicts'' his beliefs, they want the best of both
worlds: material progress and cultural identity.
</P>
<P>
   Kaipat returned to Saipan two years ago from the Midwest, where
she spent 20 years working, going to college and law school.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the University of Minnesota, where she got her law
degree, the sub-zero cold didn't faze her. In fact, it seemed
exotic. Despite the strong loyalty that pulled her home, ``I liked
it, you know,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A faraway look came over her face, but she clearly wasn't
thinking about her people's ancient traditions or sailing the open
ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked it because it was really different from here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
