<HEADER>
A1461 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAIPANSIDE-NAVIGATOR-     03-08 0366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIPANSIDE-NAVIGATOR-SFCHRON(SIDEBAR) </SLUG>
  
 A VOYAGE FROM THE PAST  &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAIPAN _ On February 10, master Carolinian navigator Mau Piailug
and 15 navigators and crewmen from Micronesia and Hawaii set sail
aboard the Makalii, a 54-foot, double-hulled traditional sailing
canoe, on a three-month, 6,200-mile voyage joining the past and the
present, Hawaii and Micronesia.
</P>
<P>
   Although Piailug is virtually unknown on the U.S. mainland, his
name is a household word in Hawaii and elsewhere in the Pacific,
where he is known as having single-handedly rescued the dying art
of traditional navigating.
</P>
<P>
   In Hawaii, he has acted as teacher and mentor to Nainoa
Thompson, who has become a well-known navigator and an influential
spokesman for native cultures.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, Piailug, a Micronesian, was recruited by the Hawaiians,
who are Polynesian, to navigate a canoe from Hawaii to Tahiti, in
the first such voyage by traditional navigational methods since the
settlement of Hawaii centuries before. Piailug had never sailed in
Polynesia, but he was able to combine his own sailing knowledge
with Hawaiian traditions to get the canoe to Tahiti safely.
</P>
<P>
   Since that trip, Piailug and Thompson have led long voyages
through the Pacific, crossing thousand-mile empty stretches without
sextants, lorans or other modern navigating tools. Instead, they
use lore handed down orally from generation to generation over the
centuries: complex astronomical formulas, the types of waves,
location of schools of fish.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the first time, Piailug's proteges are accompanying him
back to the atoll of Satawal, his home in the Caroline Islands, and
to Saipan. The trip aboard the Makalii will make eight stops in the
Marshall, Caroline and Mariana Islands _ ranging from atolls where
the only garments are the men's thu, or loincloth, and the women's
lava-lava skirt, to the modern hubbub of Saipan and Guam.
</P>
<P>
   But even on the tiniest islands, canoe navigating and other
traditions are dying out. Piailug and the others hope to rally the
people at each stop to return to the old ways.
</P>
<P>
   The Makalii voyage Web site is: www.bigisland-hawaii.net/
home.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 0402EST &QL; 
