<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 04:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1462 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CENTAM-SFCHRO     03-08 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CENTAM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CLINTON TRIP TO CENTRAL AMERICA AIMS TO HEAD OFF IMMIGRATION  &HT;     By LOUIS FREEDBERG 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton begins a four-day trip to Central
America Monday for a first-hand look at the region's efforts to
recover from Hurricane Mitch and highlight the administration's
plan to prevent a mass migration from the devastated area.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of that proposal is an administration plan to
send $650 million in emergency aid to the region, on top of $350
million already spent. The aid is intended to contribute to the
immediate repair of the region's infrastructure, as well as assist
the long-term rebuilding of a shattered economy in Honduras and to
a lesser extent in Nicaragua and El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the rebuilding proceeds quickly _ and provides hope to
the millions of Central Americans whose lives have been disrupted
by the most devastating natural disaster to strike the region in
modern history _ large numbers of Central Americans could decide to
migrate north.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a matter of grave concern to us,'' said Benjamin Zapata,
the interim chief of the Honduran mission in Washington, D.C. ``It
is in the forefront of discussions at the highest levels between
the governments concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Mitch cut a brutal swath through Central America in
November, killing 9,000 people, leaving thousands homeless and
causing as much as $10 billion in damage. The reconstruction effort
will be a complex task that will go far beyond providing shelter or
rebuilding roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will be needed is providing people a makeshift school for
their kids, a health clinic _ a sense of community and a semblance
of ordinariness,'' said Demetri Papademetriou, director of the
international migration program at the Carnegie Endowment for
International Peace. ``But if people feel they can't feed their
families, or the aid is too little or too late, they will start
looking at other options.''
</P>
<P>
   If they do decide to move northward, increased migration would
put an added strain on social services, especially in California,
Texas and New York, and it would place even more pressure on the
heightened efforts by U.S. immigration authorities to prevent
illegal migration across the U.S.-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton attempts to persuade Central Americans that the
United States will help rebuild the region, he also must find a way
to persuade Congress to approve the money that would do that,
providing would-be migrants with an incentive to stay put.
Republicans in Congress are reluctant to approve the emergency
funds, although they say their concerns are strictly budget
related. ``It's not politics at all,'' said House Majority Leader
Dick Armey, R-Texas, last week. ``It's called budget
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, concerns about a wave of illegal immigration have been
unfounded. Despite media reports in recent weeks indicating that
large numbers of Hondurans say they intend to head to the United
States, there is scant evidence of a mass migration. Apprehensions
of Central Americans on the U.S.-Mexico border increased
substantially immediately after the hurricane, but the numbers of
are still tiny compared to apprehensions of Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three months of 1998, 6,064 migrants classified as
``other than Mexicans'' _ mostly Central Americans _ were
apprehended by the U.S. Border Patrol on the southwest border. That
contrasts with 4,734 apprehensions during the same period the
previous year. During the same period in 1998, the Border Patrol
apprehended 234,000 Mexicans, compared to 205,000 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The figures do suggest that more Central Americans are heading
north, however, and the administration is nervously eyeing the
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a mistake for us not to be concerned,'' said Russ
Bergeron, a spokesman for the Immigration and Naturalization
Service. ``There is no one who can predict with a high level of
certainty what will or will not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Others within the INS are much more alarmed. In fact, a
classified report prepared by the INS' own intelligence unit refers
to ``an expected mass influx'' from Central America and describes
the attempts of several groups of migrants from the region to cross
the U.S.-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, which was obtained by Copley News
Service, a group of seven Hondurans apprehended in Laredo, Texas,
said that ``emergency aid is only getting to the big towns and not
the rural areas, and this is the reason why they attempted to get
to the United States. Further questioning revealed that more groups
of people from Honduras were headed toward the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the hurricane has placed Central America back
on the agenda of U.S. foreign policy concerns.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the 1970s and 1980s, Central America was racked by
wars pitting leftist guerrilla groups against authoritarian
regimes. Caught in the crosswinds of Cold War politics, the region
was at the receiving end of massive amounts of military and other
aid.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 1990s, the amount of aid to Central America has
slowed to a trickle. In 1985, for example, the United States Agency
for International Development spent $1.2 billion in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Before the hurricane, the entire region was due to receive only
$145 million.
</P>
<P>
   An unknown factor is what the Mexican government will do if
large numbers of Central Americans cross into Mexico on their way
to the United States. Mexican officials annually apprehend and
return between 80,000 and 90,000 Central American migrants to their
home countries.
</P>
<P>
   But whether Mexico would be willing or able to deter a mass
migration of Central Americans is another question. Currently,
Mexico only has 150 agents posted on its 650-mile border with
Guatemala and Belize.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
