<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 08:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1530 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIMAGGIO-OBIT09-COX     03-08 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIMAGGIO-OBIT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DiMaggio's rich life ends
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe DiMaggio, the fisherman's son who came to define not just
baseball but all of sport for generations of Americans, once said
of his life's work, ``There's no skill involved. Just go up there
and swing at the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   At once modest and aloof, the words described how he lived his
life as well, a rich and full existence that ended when the Yankee
Clipper succumbed to a brief but vicious fight with lung cancer. He
was 84 when he died at home in Hollywood, Fla., after surgery Oct.
14 for the removal of a cancerous tumor from his right lung.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio, who celebrated his last birthday Nov. 24 in the
hospital, was expected by many not to make it home. His lungs were
drained at least twice after surgery and he was given last rites
Nov. 16, when his blood pressure plummeted. But he did make it
home, and lived long enough to see a premature report of his death
on television.
</P>
<P>
   Until his hospitalization, DiMaggio had remained vibrant and
made regular ceremonial visits to Yankee Stadium, where he was last
honored Sept. 26 on Joe DiMaggio Day and presented copies of the 10
World Series rings the Yankees won over his 13-year career.
</P>
<P>
   But he was unable to accept the club's invitation to throw out
the first pitch of the 1998 World Series and already had been
hospitalized five days when the Yankees-San Diego series began. He
was among the last links to the World War II-era Yankees dynasty,
having broken in with the team in 1936. He played three seasons
with Lou Gehrig.
</P>
<P>
   Though linked forever to the 56-game hitting streak that endures
57 years after he set it, DiMaggio's grace in center field left a
stronger imprint on New York, which watched him rise as the first
Italian-descended sports super hero the nation had produced. The
fly ball never seemed to fall until DiMaggio arrived beneath it,
prompting his detractors to gripe he'd never had a tough chance out
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``No outfielder is a real workman unless he can turn his back on
the ball, run his legs off and take the catch over his shoulder,''
DiMaggio once instructed. ``Back-pedaling outfielders get
nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   He had come up a shortstop, one of three baseball playing sons
of Joseph DiMaggio, an Italian-born fisherman who settled in San
Francisco. He was just 17 when he signed with the Pacific Coast
League's Oakland Seals and the following year, DiMaggio put
together a 61-game hitting streak. He made it to the Bronx to stay
in 1936 at age 21. Save for three years of military service, he was
the Yankees' constant presence into the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   A career .325 hitter, batting average hardly described his
exactitude at the plate. He went the entire 1941 season with just
13 strikeouts in 541 at-bats. He finished his career with but 369
strikeouts to go with 361 career homers. A three-time American
League MVP, some of his statistics suffered from playing at
spaceous Yankee Stadium. But then again, DiMaggio's game was far
more than numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball isn't statistics,'' New York writer Jimmy Breslin
said. ``It's Joe DiMaggio rounding second base.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 14, 1941, he singled off Chicago's Eddie Smith, beginning
a run that may never be equaled. Nearly a month later, another
single against the White Sox gave him a 29-game hitting streak,
breaking the Yankees' club record. Rogers Hornsby's NL record of 33
fell as did George Sisler's AL mark of 41. And when historians
insisted Wee Willie Keeler had recorded a 44-game streak in 1887,
DiMaggio broke it too before three groundouts July 17 in Cleveland
ended the run at 56 games.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, DiMaggio had 56 singles, 16 doubles, seven
triples and 15 home runs and the following day, he began a 16-game
streak which did not include a hit recorded in Detroit in the 1941
All-Star game. Pete Rose summoned a 44-game streak in 1978, but no
one else has yet approached 56.
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, DiMaggio's shadow was purposely diminished. He
often dined alone, was polite but distant with teammates and,
partly as a result of public criticism he received in a contract
dispute, he was also wary of the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he said hello to you,'' Detroit's Hank Greenberg once said,
``that was a long conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know him well,'' New York columnist Jimmy Cannon
wrote, ``although I've killed a lot of time in his company.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 37, slowed by back and foot injuries, DiMaggio turned
down a new $100,000 contract and announced his retirement in 1951
by simply saying, ``I no longer have it.'' But in his last World
Series that fall, he shared the Yankees outfield with a brutishly
built Oklahoma kid, at least until he waved Mickey Mantle off a fly
ball in Game 2. Mickey Mantle slipped and hurt his knee on the
play, opening a new chapter in Yankees lore.
</P>
<P>
   A failed marriage to Marilyn Monroe broke his heart but only
increased his public persona in retirement. Celebrated in song
(Simon and Garfunkel's ``Mrs. Robinson'') and in the written word
(a non-present hero in Ernest Hemingway's ``The Old Man and the
Sea''), DiMaggio's name came to represent new things to each new
generation, even as he was trying to hawk a coffee maker.
</P>
<P>
   He sold a lot of them, too, which only fit a larger pattern.
When asked once how DiMaggio excelled, New York teammate Tommy
Heinrich replied, ``He does everything better than anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
