<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 08:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1533 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-TV-PBS-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-08 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TV-PBS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PBS: CLINGING TO A DISAPPEARING NICHE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until recently, ``contentious'' was not a word associated with
``Washington Week in Review,'' the solid or stolid weekly PBS
get-together of mainstream journalists who never raised their
voices in disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   While over at the cable stations, a gabble of strong-lunged
television personalities were making reputations with passionate
encounters over the latest crowd-pleaser, ``Washington Week'' kept
doing what seemed in the cable commotion to come unnaturally,
reporting on subjects of consequence that its panelists knew
something about.
</P>
<P>
   But then Ken Bode, who had been the program's moderator since
1994 (and continues to serve as dean of Northwestern University's
Medill School of Journalism), quit or was bumped from his
television job, along with his producer Elizabeth Piersol. The
details are not agreed upon, but it appears that Dalton Delan, the
new head of programming at WETA, the Washington public station
responsible for ``Washington Week,'' was suggesting adding
ingredients like man-on-the-street interviews, appearances by
students and liberal-conservative clashes to give the half-hour
what has been described as more ``edge'' and ``attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   The forces of righteousness came quickly to Bode's defense, and
whatever Delan's plans, they were put on hold or muddied
sufficiently to quell the indignation of the program's panelists
and its fans. Yet the dust-up leaves a nagging question: What is
the mission of public television these days, and who needs it?
</P>
<P>
   Delan, who came to PBS by way of cable, may reasonably have felt
that he had a mandate to refurbish the 32-year-old talking-head
program. The profusion of cable stations, some of which are doing
the sort of programming that Public Broadcasting could once call
its own, has sent the so-called noncommercial broadcasters into
something of an identity crisis. Looking for wildlife and wild
scenery? Try the Discovery Channel any week. Looking for children's
shows? There's Nickelodeon. In the mood for hard-edged
documentaries? HBO may come through. Old movies are never in short
supply. And if it's Washington news you're after, CNN has plenty of
that.
</P>
<P>
   PBS can make a case that its fare is by and large better, as
well as free to people without cable. Offerings like ``Nova,''
``Frontline'' and ``The American Experience'' have long been
network showpieces and remain the PBS vision of what it should be
doing. But the old-time monopoly of virtue is over. These days, the
once-proudly commercial-free network has plenty of commercials.
Tuning into ``The Newshour with Jim Lehrer'' or ``The Nightly
Business Report'' provides a cornucopia of silly slogans on behalf
of financial institutions. (The ``Newshour'' staff may have earned
its audience's trust that editorial blandishments from, say, Archer
Daniels Midland, will be resisted, but can one trust the innovative
Delan?)
</P>
<P>
   Whether ``Teletubbies'' is a sly plug for the gay life remains
in dispute, but it is indisputably a merchandising bonanza that
exploits the youngest viewers of all.
</P>
<P>
   And if there is any claim that PBS refuses to pander to a
certain sort of audience taste, the fare during the current pledge
period _ self-help stuff, easy-to-take music and this and that _
tells a different story. The prolonged and witless pitches manage
to make network commercials seem almost intelligent even as they
test the patience of viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet PBS retains a loyal and influential cadre of fans addicted
to ``The Newshour,'' ``Masterpiece Theater,'' ``Mystery'' and other
favorites. It's a classy constituency that has proved to be a
potent force when appropriation time comes around, and _ as
demonstrated by the Bode affair _ can join effectively in the
defense of endangered species like news programs about news.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the pledge period's upbeat pitches (``Wow, folks,
the fact that you are watching PBS confirms how special you
are!''), the future is shaky. Producers know, for example, that the
BBC and other British suppliers of the up-market goods that
American viewers have come to credit to PBS can now make their
deals with commercial cable networks that have deeper pockets than
public stations. And they also know that PBS serves a relatively
older audience in a time when youth is ascendant.
</P>
<P>
   So a new executive producer of, say, ``Washington Week in
Review,'' with its over-50-something viewers who by the
demographics of mortality are not likely to move in a happy
direction, may be tempted toward ``edge'' and ``attitude'' and
anything else that might conceivably lure a few more 30-somethings
if not high-schoolers.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of this pledge period, while ``Washington Week'' is
preempted by programs providing health hints, money management and
Andrew Lloyd Webber, the producers may enjoy a respite from
controversy. But the forces operating on public television to keep
pressing the limits of commercial appeal remain compelling. Not
only is the fate of ``Washington Week'' far from settled, but, more
unsettling, the ideals that sparked PBS in the first place are
afloat in limbo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 0851EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
