<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-COUNSEL-TEXT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT A DIFFERENCE A SCANDAL MAKES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last week the Clinton administration completed a
remarkable turnaround in its thinking about the independent-counsel
law.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying before a House judiciary subcommittee, Deputy
Attorney General Eric Holder said the law should be abandoned when
it expires this summer because it is so badly flawed that it cannot
be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   The statute, originally passed in 1978, a few years after the
Watergate scandal, lapsed in 1993. Republicans were reluctant to
extend the law in the shadow of the Iran-Contra investigation, but
were ultimately persuaded by President Clinton and Attorney General
Janet Reno to renew the legislation. Five weeks after Clinton
signed the law, Kenneth Starr became the first of seven independent
counsels to be appointed under the act.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEPHEN LABATON &QR;
</P>
<P>
   THEN: Public trust in government is at stake, so keep the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely essential for the public, in the process of
the criminal justice system, to have confidence in the system, and
you cannot do that when there is conflict or an appearance of
conflict in the person who is, in effect, the chief prosecutor.'' _
Janet Reno, May 14, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opponents called it a tool of partisan attack against
Republican presidents and a waste of taxpayer funds. It was
neither. In fact, the independent-counsel statute has been in the
past and is today a force for government integrity and public
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   _ President Clinton, June 30, 1994. &QR;
</P>
<P>
   NOW: Public trust in government is at stake, so ditch the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The act has failed to accomplish its primary goal: the
enhancement of confidence in the rule of law by the American
people. The act was supposed to increase trust in our government;
unfortunately it has diminished it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Eric Holder, March 2, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   THEN: No one should be above the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This law, originally passed in 1978, is a foundation stone for
the trust between the government and our citizens. It ensures that
no matter what party controls the Congress or the executive branch,
an independent, nonpartisan process will be in place to guarantee
the integrity of public officials and ensure that no one is above
the law.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Clinton
</P>
<P>
   NOW: No one should be above the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law vests immense prosecutorial power in an inferior
officer who is not subject to the ordinary controls of any branch
of government.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Holder
</P>
<P>
   THEN: It's worth the price.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there are legitimate concerns about the costs and
burdens associated with the act, I have concluded that these are
far, far outweighed by the need for the act and the public
confidence it fosters.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Reno
</P>
<P>
   NOW: It's too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very expensive way to do business. As the body that
passes the federal budget each year, you have responsibility of
deciding whether or not this cost is justified.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Holder
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 0853EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 08:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6378 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-COUNSEL-TEXT-REVIEW     03-08 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-COUNSEL-TEXT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT A DIFFERENCE A SCANDAL MAKES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last week the Clinton administration completed a
remarkable turnaround in its thinking about the independent-counsel
law.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying before a House judiciary subcommittee, Deputy
Attorney General Eric Holder said the law should be abandoned when
it expires this summer because it is so badly flawed that it cannot
be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   The statute, originally passed in 1978, a few years after the
Watergate scandal, lapsed in 1993. Republicans were reluctant to
extend the law in the shadow of the Iran-Contra investigation, but
were ultimately persuaded by President Clinton and Attorney General
Janet Reno to renew the legislation. Five weeks after Clinton
signed the law, Kenneth Starr became the first of seven independent
counsels to be appointed under the act.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEPHEN LABATON &QR;
</P>
<P>
   THEN: Public trust in government is at stake, so keep the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely essential for the public, in the process of
the criminal justice system, to have confidence in the system, and
you cannot do that when there is conflict or an appearance of
conflict in the person who is, in effect, the chief prosecutor.'' _
Janet Reno, May 14, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opponents called it a tool of partisan attack against
Republican presidents and a waste of taxpayer funds. It was
neither. In fact, the independent-counsel statute has been in the
past and is today a force for government integrity and public
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   _ President Clinton, June 30, 1994. &QR;
</P>
<P>
   NOW: Public trust in government is at stake, so ditch the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The act has failed to accomplish its primary goal: the
enhancement of confidence in the rule of law by the American
people. The act was supposed to increase trust in our government;
unfortunately it has diminished it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Eric Holder, March 2, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   THEN: No one should be above the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This law, originally passed in 1978, is a foundation stone for
the trust between the government and our citizens. It ensures that
no matter what party controls the Congress or the executive branch,
an independent, nonpartisan process will be in place to guarantee
the integrity of public officials and ensure that no one is above
the law.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Clinton
</P>
<P>
   NOW: No one should be above the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law vests immense prosecutorial power in an inferior
officer who is not subject to the ordinary controls of any branch
of government.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Holder
</P>
<P>
   THEN: It's worth the price.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there are legitimate concerns about the costs and
burdens associated with the act, I have concluded that these are
far, far outweighed by the need for the act and the public
confidence it fosters.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Reno
</P>
<P>
   NOW: It's too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very expensive way to do business. As the body that
passes the federal budget each year, you have responsibility of
deciding whether or not this cost is justified.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Holder
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
