<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-TOP-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP 100 STORIES SHOULD HAVE GONE BEYOND THE FRONT PAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   That newly compiled list of the century's top 100 stories got so
much media coverage that I designated its release the 101st top
story. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not that I was trying to avoid this story, but because it was
yet another pseudo-event I eventually got as weary of it as I did
the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal. By the way, that scandal, with its
attendant impeachment trial, did not even rank in the top half of
the 100 stories, settling in at No. 53, one ahead of the Marshall
Plan and one behind the 1901 transmission of a radio signal across
the Atlantic Ocean. Go figure. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It all proves what Joe Urschel, executive director of the
Newseum media museum, said: ``News judgment is not an exact
science.'' (The Newseum, in Arlington, Va., sponsored the survey of
journalists and scholars that came up with the 100 list.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hoo-boy, is Urschel right. Heck, news judgment isn't a science
at all. From more than 30 years in the newspaper business, I can
testify that news judgment is an occult art of impenetrable mystery
that it's best not to scrutinize. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, the 100-story list was interesting, even if none of the
six events from 1945 included on it was my birth. Well, perhaps not
enough time has yet elapsed to allow my life to compete with events
connected to World War II. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 100-story list stands as proof that this has not been a slow
news century. Indeed from Max Planck proposing the quantum theory
of energy in 1900 (No. 78 on the list) to the official end of
apartheid in South Africa in 1993 (No. 49), the 20th century has
been a journalist's dream. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the list, however, is that it tends to focus on
the front page of the newspaper. I've got nothing against Page One.
But the stories that shed the most light on the human condition
often get buried inside with what young journalism students used to
call (and maybe still do) the truss ads. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I can't tell you the last time I saw an actual truss ad in a
newspaper, but it's been a long time. One reason may be that I
almost never read any ads. I know that will come as a huge
disappointment to folks in the advertising department at my
newspaper, but maybe not. The chances are probably pretty good that
they don't read my (or anyone's) column, so we're even. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All of which is beside the point. The point, if any, is that I
think a much more interesting list of stories could be fashioned
out of the inside pages of of the 20th century's newspapers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a big story now is about the Y2K computer bug. But
did you know that use of the word bug to describe a computer glitch
goes back to the famous year 1945? Rear Admiral Grace Murray
Hopper, a Navy computer pioneer, says her team members coined the
phrase when they found a two-inch moth stuck in a switching contact
in Mark II, the first large-scale American computer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Admiral Hopper's bug didn't deserve to make the top 100 list.
But it's on my list of revealingly odd stories. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few 1968 stories made the top 100 list, such as the
assassinations of Martin Luther King Jr. and Robert F. Kennedy and
the Chicago police riot at the Democratic National Convention in
Chicago. Fine, but did you know that it was with the 1968 release
of ``The Graduate'' that we all began to sing, ``Here's to you,
Mrs. Robinson''? And speaking of engaging women of a certain age,
do you recall that Jackie Kennedy married Aristotle Onassis in
1968? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm not arguing that these and similar stories are more
important than wars and rumors of wars, which much make up nearly
the whole of the 100 list, but they do provide some things to fight
wars about. And without things to fight about the list of 100 top
stories would be shortened to maybe five. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
