<HEADER>
A1558 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CLINTON-FOREIGNPOLI     03-08 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CLINTON-FOREIGNPOLICY-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S FOREIGN POLICY LACKS COHERENCE, BUT SO DOES THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the space of a week, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright has searched for a way to use the threat of U.S.
military power to end civil war in the world's smallest would-be
nation, Kosovo, and for a way to use U.S. economic power to change
the behavior of the world's largest and oldest nation, China.
</P>
<P>
   As foreign-policy conundrums, the two have little in common,
except that both are familiar and both have grown more resistant to
U.S. influence. Neither the last-ditch efforts to salvage a peace
proposal for Kosovo nor the ritualistic exchanges in Beijing last
week are likely to be recalled warmly in Albright's memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   But these radically different encounters have something odd in
common: They have come to mark the two extremes of the Clinton
administration's six-year struggle to bring coherence to U.S.
foreign policy in a time that often seems incoherent itself _ a
time of confusing ethnic and economic rivalries, of elbowing for
position in the pecking order of power.
</P>
<P>
   So as it begins the final quarter of its eight-year game,
President Clinton's team still trips over itself setting
foreign-policy priorities or fully explaining them to Americans, or
seeking leverage over foreign potentates, whether in a tiny corner
of the Balkans or the vastness of China.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder that throughout the 1990s, both the
administration and its critics have flailed about for some grand
Unified Field Theory of Foreign Relations _ something as neat as
the concept of containment during the Cold War _ to define what it
should be doing, and in what order.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Michael Mandelbaum, a Johns Hopkins University
professor, issued a searing critique of the administration's
troubles separating the peripheral from the central; it resonates
more loudly today than ever. Kosovo, he says, is ``the ultimate
social work'' and has become ``something between a hobby and an
obsession'' for the administration. In contrast, he says, ``China
is truly important, the most strategically vital foreign-policy
problem we face.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, China policy _ like Japan and Russia policy _ is
endlessly bounced between the State Department and the Treasury,
and efforts at coordination are sporadic. Perhaps it is no surprise
that Albright's interchanges with Beijing last week about human
rights and China's integration into the world economy appeared to
have barely moved the conversation much beyond where it was in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, the administration thought it had found something
approaching a Unified Theory _ that comprehensive economic
engagement and ``enlargement'' with great and small powers would
lead, sooner or later, to the spread of both free-market capitalism
and democracy. In Clinton's speeches, the two were usually tightly
linked, part of a web of global forces that was moving history
America's way. China was the great example, followed immediately by
Russia. But it didn't stop there:
</P>
<P>
   Economic engagement explained why peace talks in Northern
Ireland or the Middle East were always followed up by an economic
conference focused on creating jobs and ``enterprise zones'' in
hopes that prosperity would bring contentment, then hope, then
lasting peace.
</P>
<P>
   But these are tough times for unified theories of all kinds.
``It's fair to say,'' one of Clinton's longest-serving aides mused
recently, ``that over time we have learned and relearned the lesson
that other countries shape their own destiny to a far greater
extent than we believed.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that explains why Clinton offered no grand theories in a
speech 10 days ago that was billed as an outline of his agenda for
the remaining two years of his presidency. The president delivered
what amounted to a list of agenda items: supporting peace (with the
use of as few U.S. troops as possible), supporting financial
stability (with the use of as little U.S. money as possible),
containing weapons of mass destruction and the countries and
terrorists who are trying to get hold of them.
</P>
<P>
   What was missing was any attempt to describe which items on the
list went to the heart of U.S. interests, or how they interrelated.
Even Clinton's critics expressed some understanding. ``Trying to
get the bumper sticker term for our foreign policy is a waste of
time,'' said Robert Zoellick, a former Bush administration official
who now heads the Center for Strategic and International Studies
here. ``But you can have a foreign policy with priority values,''
he said, ``rather than one that is case by case, reactive and
designed to immunize political threats at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, there are plenty of grand theories kicking
around Washington. That, after all, is what out-of-power
foreign-policy wonks do. Samuel Huntington, the Harvard political
scientist, writes constantly about how ethnic tensions are the
nexis of the post-Cold War world. Others argue that the key to
modern U.S. hegemony is leadership, and thus the United States must
get involved in the Bosnias of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle of contagious economic failure has given rise to
prescriptions for expanding the powers of international
institutions like the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund, so that they can dictate domestic economic policy to
countries on the brink.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the old Cold Warriors, some of whom met over
lunch last week and raised the possibility of re-creating the
Committee on the Present Danger, a Reagan-era anti-communist group.
They spent the rest of lunch debating what constitutes the Present
Danger. A weakened Iraq? A starving North Korea? China in the midst
of its economic high-wire act?
</P>
<P>
   Their confusion arises from the difficulty in defining national
interest these days. And that is the real meaning of the Bosnia to
Beijing bookends.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration came to power far from convinced that
Bosnia was a central interest of the United States, then decided
that the Balkans (along with Somalia and Haiti) must be, as the
horror of it all unfolded on television. But the reality is that
while Americans are perfectly happy to see the secretary of state
jetting around the world to strike peace agreements, their
willingness to put lives at risk for such causes is limited.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, though, both the public and Congress have come to
recognize a second type of national interest: averting economic
implosions that could affect U.S. prosperity. Congress screamed
when the administration bailed out Mexico, a move that most now
believe avoided a long, ugly recession on America's border. By the
time the Asian crisis hit, the objections began to dissipate, and
there was barely a peep when the Treasury helped organize the
rescues of South Korea and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration's luck ran out when it came to Russia.
Ever since the $17 billion IMF package failed last summer, both the
Russian economy and Moscow's relationship with Washington have been
in a downward spiral.
</P>
<P>
   And now comes China, the most complex case. No one doubts that
Chinese are enjoying greater economic freedom. Or that China is
cracking down on political organizers, reverting to elements of a
state-run economy and adding to the missiles facing Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   So Washington has reverted to a mixed message, encouraging moves
to get China into the World Trade Organization _ part of that web
of economic engagement _ while talking about building a regional
missile defense that drives the Chinese up the wall. The Chinese
say they recognize America's real strategy and it is both old and
familiar: containment. They may be wrong, but at least it's a
coherent theory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
