<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 09:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1564 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CANADA-NEWSPAPERS-T     03-08 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CANADA-NEWSPAPERS-TEXT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW CANADIANS STOPPED WORRYING AND LAUGHED AT A JOURNALISTIC BOMB 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (editors: text that should be italicized is marked with (BEGIN
ITALICS HERE) and (END ITALICS HERE)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ It's not easy being in the news business in Canada.
You stare at juicy American stories nearly every day while your own
pages fill with curling scores and wheat quotas. Oh, for a big,
page one blockbuster!
</P>
<P>
   In February, one of the two Canadian national newspapers now
locked in vicious competition thought it had a real scoop when it
breathlessly reported: ``U.S. believes North Korea would target
Montreal for a nuclear strike.''
</P>
<P>
   Incredible! The front-page article quoted Canadian legislators
just back from a NATO conference at the United States Army War
College. If tensions between North Korea and the United States
escalate, the Canadians said, Washington expected the wily
communists to pick a fight with America's wimpy non-nuclear
neighbor, knowing that dropping a nuke on say, Hoboken, would earn
them a nuclear drubbing.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few problems with the story. For one, the Army
College has no such scenario involving North Korea. ``Where it came
from, I don't know,'' said Lt. Col. Pete Pierce of the college
staff.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just the American press that hates to let go of a
good yarn. Even when the Canada bomb article bombed, newspapers
kept it going with the only weapon left in their arsenal _ humor.
Excerpts follow.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ANTHONY DePALMA
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE)The original report appeared Feb. 12 in The
National Post, the new flagship of the Southam newspaper chain. The
article had more prominence on the front page than news of the
expected acquittal of President Clinton that day:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. Army officials say they expect Canada would be the first
target of a North Korean nuclear attack if tensions were to
escalate between the communist power and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   According to a war scenario being developed at the U.S. Army War
College, Montreal would be the Canadian city likely to be hit by
North Korea, which is suspected of having nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Three Canadian MPs were briefed about the war scenario during a
meeting of elected representatives from the 16 NATO countries in
Carlisle, Pa., last week, the National Post has learned.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Army officials told the MPs they doubt North Korea would
attack the U.S. directly because it would result in massive nuclear
retaliation that would wipe the Asian nation off the map.
</P>
<P>
   American officials therefore think it more likely for North
Korea to hit U.S. interests indirectly by attacking a close ally
and a friend _ Canada _ that does not have nuclear weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) The next day, the news hadn't exactly
stoked panic in Montreal. Au contraire, The Post reported:
Residents saw an opportunity to rid themselves of a debt-plagued
relic of the 1976 Olympics:(END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``Montrealers, perhaps inured to doomsday scenarios by three
decades of dire warnings over the consequences of Quebec
separation, took news of their status as a potential nuclear target
in stride yesterday. Some callers to CJAD, a private English radio
station, pointed out the bomb would end the never-ending debate
over what to do with the Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   `That actually came up a couple of times,' said Lisa Durron, the
program's producer. `Over all, people thought it was a joke.' ...
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone thought it was funny. ``One woman chastised me for
doing a show that might scare the children,'' said Tommy
Schnurmacher, CJAD morning host.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS HERE) The Globe and Mail, The Post's national
competitor, stayed away from the story. But The Montreal Gazette
went after it, albeit skeptically: (END ITALICS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that North Korea is likely to target Montreal in a
nuclear attack, as reported on the front page of the National Post
yesterday, was debunked yesterday by experts across the country.
</P>
<P>
   `It's absolutely bizarre, ' said Jim Bayer, director of the
Conflict Analysis and Management Program at Royal Roads College in
Victoria, B.C., `for any number of reasons, including picking on
poor old Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   `It seems to be one of these Dr. Strangelove scenarios that the
American military develop from time to time.'
</P>
<P>
   `Obviously the North Koreans can't reach Montreal,'' added David
Rudd, executive director of the Canadian Institute for Strategic
Studies. ``Their missiles can't even reach Hawaii.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
