<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Special prosecutor law finds few friends in high
places
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has a hammer raised to drive another nail
into the coffin of the special prosecutor law. The air was leaden
with skepticism when the justices recently reviewed the conviction
of Sun-Diamond Growers of California for giving illegal gratuities
to then-Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy.
</P>
<P>
   The case is an outgrowth of independent counsel Donald Smaltz's
madman pursuit of Espy. Smaltz filed a panorama of criminal charges
and tried to put the secretary in prison for what could have
amounted to a couple of lifetimes _ all because of a scatteration
of usually small indulgences.
</P>
<P>
   Espy had no business taking favors from agricultural companies
and associations. (He forgot he was no longer in Congress.) But the
favors were mostly trivial _ a ride in a company limo, Super Bowl
tickets, invitations to parties. There was never any evidence Espy
traded policies for the trinkets.
</P>
<P>
   A judge threw out eight counts and a jury quickly found against
the remaining 30. Smaltz, however, had earlier browbeat some
agribusinesses into guilty pleas and had convicted Sun-Diamond by
insisting any little gift to a public official is criminal even if
no bribery occurs or even is intended.
</P>
<P>
   It is that expansive reading of a vague statute that, judging
from their questions, most Supreme Court justices find dubious at
best. Sandra Day O'Connor suggested Smaltz's interpretation would
make it a crime to bake cookies for a senator or knit socks for a
public official.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr, of course, has created the most telling case for
scrapping the independent counsel law, with investigations that
have spread like a virus through the political and private lives of
President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton. Starr's excesses
against reluctant witness Susan McDougal have managed to make a
questionable character into a national martyr and are, in their
prosecutorial disproportion, almost alone reason enough for
chucking the statute. (As his roughhousing of Monica Lewinsky is,
too.)
</P>
<P>
   But Smaltz's outrages and the similarly overwrought prosecution
of former Housing and Urban Development Secretary Henry Cisneros by
David Barrett are equally damning. Barrett is pressing 18 criminal
accounts against Cisneros for underreporting _ lying about, if you
insist _ how much he had paid a onetime mistress, as if the
difference mattered.
</P>
<P>
   There have been seven independent counsels sicced on the Clinton
administration, often on little more than speculation, and there
would have been more if Attorney General Janet Reno hadn't balked
at a few of the endless Republican demands to have still more
hounds unleashed.
</P>
<P>
   In questioning the Sun-Diamond conviction, Justice Stephen
Breyer wondered if, in matters such as questionable gifts, ethics
regulations aren't preferable to ``bringing the blunderbuss of
federal law into the prosecutor's arsenal, where they can prosecute
trivialities.''
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't make sense to you, it's probably because you
haven't heard a sane voice for so long.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
