A1588 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN10-CO     03-08 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Haiti, and its people, are still drowning
 &HT;    (For release March 10, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ I have not seen anything as graphically gripping as the
infamous photograph published worldwide in 1981 of 33 Haitian
refugees' bodies washed up on a South Florida beach.
</P>
<P>
   What made it so gripping was that you could see them.
</P>
<P>
   But the greater part of the continuing Haitian refugee tragedy
are those you cannot see _ like the 40 or so who are presumed dead
after their boat capsized Satruday off the Florida coast. They
didn't wash up on a beach to shock the tourists; they simply
slipped beneath the waves and we really never knew they existed.
</P>
<P>
   There is no telling how many hundreds have drowned attempting to
escape the hellish depressiveness of Haiti, a country that has
little to no economy and has had no working government for almost
two years and likely has no prospect of one until November, if
then.
</P>
<P>
   Haitian President Rene Preval has been unable to form a
government since June 1997. The parliament in Port-au-Prince simply
cannot agree on a new prime minister and another round of elections
may be called _ with or without success.
</P>
<P>
   It is becoming quite apparent that Haiti is not capable of
governing itself, at least democratically. So many attempts have
failed. The U.S., at center stage when it came to making a show of
landing troops in Haiti in 1994 to dispense with a military coup
leader, has been unsuccessful in founding an economy or
establishing political stability in the Caribbean nation.
</P>
<P>
   Like the uncontrollable child, the adopting parent shares the
blame for this dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, we didn't have enough of a mix when we just sent
soldiers to flex our muscles at dictator Raoul Cedras. We forced
him to flee the nation he took over, also by strength, from elected
President Jean-Bertrand Aristide, who, once returned to power,
proved to be a bust.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we should have flown the U.S. Chamber of Commerce in right
behind those troops, because if Haiti needed any fixing after it
was rid of Cedras, it was in its economic base. There was talk, and
promise, of something like that when Aristide returned to office,
but no results really show.
</P>
<P>
   The one constant of the country, while its politics slide from
here to there, is poverty. Few natural resources remain, there are
no jobs, there is no economy, people cannot eat _ but they can
build crude boats and sail off to wash dead on a Florida beach or
drift lifelessly through the deepest waters of the Gulf Stream.
</P>
<P>
   The awkward and deadly Haitian boat departures began back when
the agony of Haiti could be blamed on the brutal Duvaliers. But
they haven't been around since 1986. Most of the refugees come
today just as they came earlier, not so much to escape a brutal
regime, but in search of a way to put clothes on their backs, food
on their tables.
</P>
<P>
   As we all know, the solution lies back in Port-au-Prince.
Internecine political squabbles, far more serious than the erotic
silliness that has captured Washington, D.C., prevent a government
from being formed.
</P>
<P>
   While the U.S. tries to dictate government in Kosovo, Baghdad
and elsewhere, one doesn't exist in Haiti and we don't seem to be
taking a serious interest in it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, those are Haitians, not Kosovars, washing up on our
shores and drowning in our waters. It is under the immediate U.S.
sphere of influence and needs to be addressed at least as
diligently as we do the others.
</P>
<P>
   If it means some more arm-wrestling by the U.S., another
intrusion into Haitian affairs, then so be it _ because,
eventually, Haitian affairs become U.S. affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Those were U.S. Coast Guard boats out there looking for the 40
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
