<HEADER>
A1612 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN09-C     03-08 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Increasingly, our homes have become our castles
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coach-class airplane seats are more cramped than ever.
Freeways are packed, and restaurants are squeezing in more tables.
Offices have been downsized into cubicles.
</P>
<P>
   But at least there's one place where the elbow room is growing:
home sweet home.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the shrinking size of families and the aging of the
population, homes are getting more spacious. Now home builders are
watching consumers closely, trying to figure out whether the demand
for floor space will keep growing as rapidly as it did in the final
decades of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   At this century's midpoint, the average household size was 3.5
people. The typical home built in America's new suburbs in the
1950s was a one-story box with about 1,300 square feet. The average
veteran returning from World War II was delighted to get his family
into a home, even if it had just one bathroom and three tiny
bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 1960s and early 1970s, as affluence rose, so did
square footage. By the mid-1970s, the average new home had about
1,700 square feet and enough garage space for two cars.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, an economist might have predicted that home sizes
would start to shrink. After all, baby boomers were moving into
adulthood and striking out on their own, so their parents no longer
needed multiple bedrooms. And when they started their own families,
boomers had relatively few children. So why would they want homes
bigger than their parents had?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they could afford it,'' said Gopal Ahluwalia, director
of research for the National Association of Home Builders. Even
though the average household size has decreased to 2.6 people and
the bulk of the population is moving into middle or old age, square
footage is still rising because of two-income families,
better-paying jobs and lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1970s, one new house in five had four or more
bedrooms. Today, a third have at least four bedrooms. The average
house being built this year will sprawl to 2,200 square feet and
have three bathrooms, Ahluwalia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are cocooning more these days,'' he said, referring to
the tendency to spend more time at home. The trend is to build
houses with media rooms, exercise areas and huge kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   Home builders also report that many middle-aged
``empty-nesters'' are rejecting the notion of downsizing. Instead
of preparing for retirement, many people in their 50s and early 60s
are planning for a ``second adulthood,'' complete with a humongous
dream house.
</P>
<P>
   Builders are promoting these suburban castles as ``entertainment
houses'' that can help empty-nesters attract children and
grandchildren for visits, using bait that includes swimming pools
and basements full of pingpong tables, video games and exercise
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But can this trend toward bigness continue into the next
century? Will we be living in houses the size of strip shopping
centers by 2050?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Ahluwalia said. ``I think the average size
will stop at about 2,300 (square feet) in a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   That prediction is based on demographics and common sense. Once
boomers start to move into their 70s and 80s, they finally will
start to downsize. Also, at some point, most people begin to feel
uncomfortable rattling around in a house that feels like a barn.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of bigger, more will do. Ahluwalia predicts the next
trend will be to buy two 2,300-square-foot houses, rather than one
4,600-square-foot mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people are buying second homes ... either at the beach or
in a ski area,'' he said. Why? ``Because they can afford it, and
they want to say, 'We have it.'''
</P>
<P>
   SOME YEAR 2000-RELATED WEB SITES
</P>
<P>
   http://www.mille.org/index.html
</P>
<P>
   http://www.year2000.state.ga.us
</P>
<P>
   http://www.2000.com/millennium/world.html
</P>
<P>
   http://www.countdown2000.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.nationalgeographic.com/features/2000/index.html
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mgeewax(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
