<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1614 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANE-COLUMN09-COX     03-08 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Cheap gas fuels call for monster cars
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ I used to fear I was shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   What other explanation is there? I am driving a car that is
about the largest I've owned _ a four-door sedan that someone from
the passenger seat once dismissed as ``a relaxed-fit car'' _ yet I
feel small in the saddle.
</P>
<P>
   On either side of me is a moving wall of fiberglass, miracle
plastic and steel. I look out my side window at these cars and
stare squarely into their hubcaps. When they pass me, it's like
going into a tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   But size is a relative thing. It turns out I am not getting
smaller. The traffic around me is getting bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Proof: A milestone in car size was reached recently when Ford
unveiled the Excursion. So-named because walking around it to check
the tires feels like being on a hike.
</P>
<P>
   The Excursion is just short of 19 feet and weighs three and a
half tons.
</P>
<P>
   (Q: Where does a three-and-a-half-ton vehicle park? A: Anywhere
it wants.)
</P>
<P>
   It's 6.6 feet wide, which is just a little narrower than your
average Mr. Slurpee ice cream truck. Chimes that play ``Turkey in
the Straw'' endlessly are not part of the options package, although
I suppose you could add them if you really wanted.
</P>
<P>
   At 10 miles per gallon, the car is a rolling monument to the era
of 89-cents-a-gallon gasoline. Just as earlier cars with fins and
bumpers like chrome canoes were shrines to dime-a-gallon times.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect grandchildren who will be paying top dollar for fossil
fuels in bad neighborhoods around the world and great-grandchildren
who will wonder how the planet got so hot will wonder what we were
thinking. For right now, though, this is about the hottest thing on
the market.
</P>
<P>
   If they bellyache, we'll just tell them their soccer practices,
camping trips and garage bands made us do this. They should stop
whining and getting all moral because we needed serious bulkhead
room to shuttle them, their snotty-nosed friends and their equipage
all over town.
</P>
<P>
   By the time this level of explanation is necessary, we'll be old
and nobody will care about our excuses. We'll just complain until
they are sorry they asked.
</P>
<P>
   Kids.
</P>
<P>
   The Excursion seems too bland a name for such an imposing
behemoth. I suppose, though, calling it the Ford Godzilla would
invite all kinds of niggling copyright and marketing complications
from attorneys. Calling it the Land Barge would understate the
power of a V-10 engine. The Party Barge would seem irresponsible in
our selectively serious age.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford Dreadnought would work for me. Surely, this is a car
that could accommodate gun turrets. Customizers take note.
</P>
<P>
   The Battlestar Suburbia, the Road Rhino, the Jurassic Ark ...
there are so many better possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, people who are paid a lot more than I came up with the
Excursion. The Excursion sounds like a walk in the park. This car
is more like a major deployment. There you go: the Deployment, the
Mobilizer, the Deterrent ... .
</P>
<P>
   Every age of great prosperity has its excesses. Some flush
societies use their windfall to build pyramids and cathedrals and
extravagant public buildings. Some build armies and work at taking
over their corner of the world. Some dress everyone up funny and
commission imposing objects of great beauty. Some have even built
decent schools for their children. It is the legacy of our time
that we used our wealth to build and buy the biggest, fattest cars
that have ever fallen into private hands.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I am no road-Puritan. When gas is cheap,
cars will be big. This is a law of nature and the Invisible Hand of
consumer economics. But I suspect our kids will find this a strange
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   They will look at the monster cars of the sport utility vehicle
showroom much as we once viewed the finned and chrome-spangled
Batmobile-looking artifacts that appear in old family photos.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, I expect to continue feeling smaller on the
highway with each passing model year. If gas gets too much cheaper,
I'll have to scurry away to side-roads to stay out of the path of
the big creatures.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost enough to make you miss the old days when there was
something to the left of the decimal on gas-station signs.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
