<HEADER>
A1615 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN09-COX     03-08 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No ifs, ands or `buts': Professor needs to cover it up
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ An associate professor at Ohio's Miami
University has taken exception to the school's ban on thong-style
swimwear and filed a civil rights suit charging that the recreation
center advisory committee who nixed his scanty attire is stifling
his First Amendment freedom of expression and his 14th Amendment
right to equal protection. My obvious question: What exactly is he
wanting to express, and from what (or whom) might he need
protection?
</P>
<P>
   This called for a legal opinion, but since lawyers charge more
for phone consultations than the psychic hotline, I did the next
best thing. I pulled out some of my old college textbooks and set
to work searching for the part about the rights of folks to let it
all hang out, but came up empty. I found freedom of religion,
speech, and the press, under the First Amendment, and the 14th even
mentioned ``gesturing and mimicking, belonging to organizations,
wearing buttons or raising signs, and handing out leaflets to
passersby.'' But nowhere did it address a citizen's right to prance
around a university pool decked out like September morn.
</P>
<P>
   As I read it, the associate professor and the committee are
having a difference of semantics. His definition of ``appropriate
swimwear'' is at odds with theirs and so far, they're winning.
Cover it up, they told him, or find yourself a new swimming hole.
Instead, he's decided to sue. Now, nobody's happy but the lawyers,
and a whole lot of money is going to be flushed down yet another
frivolous lawsuit toilet.
</P>
<P>
   This situation does not require litigation. All it needs is a
little common sense, a couple of bucks worth of film, and a Pentax
with a zoom lens. Result: One living color shot of the good
professor's nude backside posted on the rec center's bulletin
board, and even he would have to admit that the only bare bottoms
that don't ugly up the landscaping belong to 2-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   We've all seen photos of people strutting around with their bums
hanging out and it ain't pretty. I even saw a real one once in a
yacht club restaurant in the Florida Keys. There I was, just
minding my own business, polishing off a bowl of conch chowder,
when I felt something brush my shoulder. I turned to see what it
was and there was one BIG nekkid (southern word for naked) butt
backed up right in my face while its owner chatted with the folks
at the next table. Talk about an appetite suppressant. Put me off
of conch chowder for the longest time.
</P>
<P>
   I still can't figure out what it is with folks who think that by
leaving half their clothes on the bathroom floor they're going to
provoke unbridled passion in all who take the time to cop a look in
their direction. Don't they
</P>
<P>
   know that imagination is far kinder than reality?
</P>
<P>
   Now, should comfort be the professor's priority (which I doubt
because who could be comfortable doing the butterfly stroke with a
string of dental floss stuck where it doesn't belong), then why not
join a nudist swim club? That makes a lot more sense. It always did
seem kind of a silly notion to get dressed just to get wet.
</P>
<P>
   Although I'm not suggesting everyone run out and shuck their
jeans and jump in the pond, I do believe that's a much more honest
and straightforward approach to comfort than taking off just enough
to incite a riot but stay out of jail.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect to the august professor; cover it up
fella'. Bare butts on big people are nothing but UGLY! If it's
dimples we want, we'll rent a Shirley Temple movie.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
