<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Portal craze was '98 news; now it's all about content
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Portals are like, you know, so over.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that New York-based Internet research firm Jupiter
Communications packed panel after panel with e-commerce and portal
players, like At Home, Excite, Lycos, Drugstore.com and
Ticketmaster Online, at its flagship conference last week in New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter Chairman and CEO Gene DeRose nevertheless told the
1,600-plus attendees that a ``content renaissance'' on the Web is
right around the corner. The trick, he said, is for the media
companies that post editorial content on the Web to rip a page from
Amazon.com, so to speak, and provide some e-commerce features to
transform mere readers into a fiercely loyal audience that will
drop by every day to read and spend money.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, portals were the key to Web profits. Portals such as
Yahoo!, Excite and Lycos were generating millions of page views
daily with what one analyst called ``sticky products'' designed to
keep users on their site for minutes, maybe even hours, at a time.
Portals offered search, e-mail, news, sports scores, weather
reports, stock quotes, live chats, free Web pages, local news and
shopping. Suddenly everyone wanted to be a portal, even sites that
had no business being portals in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   However, this is a new year, and like high-fashion dress
designers in Paris, it's time to toss last year's must-have trendy
frocks in favor of this year's trendy frocks that will be the
hippest and the coolest ever _ that is until next year rolls
around.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jupiter, this year's trend is compelling content
from media players such as newspapers, magazines, television
networks and cable companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, so content is king again,'' sighed New York Times new
media guru Martin Nisenholtz, a veteran conference speaker who has
seen content go in and out of fashion more than once.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not using the expression `Content is king,''' a Jupiter
analyst told him patiently. ``We're calling it a `content
renaissance,''' he said, hoping the new buzzword would catch on.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right,'' said Nisenholtz, ``can we say that content is
prince?''
</P>
<P>
   For those of you whose high school French is a bit rusty,
renaissance is French for ``rebirth.'' Jupiter's DeRose says media
companies that are expert storytellers have the potential to be big
Web winners in the end. People will eventually tire of reading
``just the facts m'am,'' news reports on the portal sites, and will
actively seek out more comprehensive and lively sources of news,
analysis and information.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, most content sites don't charge for their
content. (The Wall Street Journal Interactive is a notable
exception. Slate tried charging for content, but abandoned the plan
after only a year.) While good storytelling and other compelling
content can and will attract Web users, the trick, according to
Jupiter, is for content sites to start acting like commerce sites.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if media companies borrow some of the chat,
search and community features stuck all over the portal sites and
apply them to their own ventures, they'll build readership and make
money.
</P>
<P>
   There's no need to invent the wheel, and there's certainly no
need for every Web site to become a portal site. Strong content _
combined with a way of capturing data about readers and using that
data to offer e-mail news alerts, contests, chat and commerce _ is
the way of the future for media companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Find out all you can about the people who visit your
service,'' said CBS SportsLine Chairman Mike Levy.
</P>
<P>
   Invite users to register so they can receive news flashes,
special offers or special commerce opportunities. Give them the
opportunity to post messages and chat with authors about breaking
news or special programming. Offer prizes to users who frequent an
area the most during a certain time period. Sell them mugs,
T-shirts, books related to special series or by writers who
contribute to the site. Jupiter also has research showing online
users aren't as bothered by a mixture of news and retailing online
as they are in offline media.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wake-up call to media sites,'' said Jupiter analyst
Mark Mooradian. ``Some commerce sites are better at delivering
content than traditional media are. They have the demographics, and
they have the credit card info. Look at Amazon.com. Look at Land's
End. They have repeat users and millions of unique registered
users.''
</P>
<P>
   Mooradian's words weren't lost on Washingtonpost.com President
and Publisher Marc Teren, who said one of the Post's goals was to
build regular online users, as Jupiter suggests. ``We want to build
a relationship (with readers) and hold them over time and deliver
them to advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems that content is not only prince, but the ultimate
``sticky product'' of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
