<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Attention music fans: Guitar advice available for the plucking
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the most popular instruments for amateur
musicians is the guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you played as a youngster, or maybe you'd like to learn.
But the notion of music lessons and the agony of being a beginner
may have discouraged you from trying to learn or relearn the
guitar.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the Web is a terrific resource for would-be
guitar players.
</P>
<P>
   Let's make some beautiful music together today, with the help of
the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   To prove it really is ``worldwide,'' we'll start with a German
site called Guitar Online. Unless you feel like learning both
German and the guitar at the same time, go to http://guitaronline
</P>
<P>
   .notrix.de/ to get the English version of this page. You'll get
tips on playing the guitar, be able to download software that'll
help you learn the guitar and use it, and find links to other Web
sites devoted to the guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Our next site is called the Rob Balducci Web site, and it's a
terrific general purpose guitar enthusiast's site with some
commercial offerings thrown in. You'll find it at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .robbalducci.com/Overview.html. You'll be able to download music
or take online music lessons for free. Just click on the chord you
want to learn, and you'll get on-screen help.
</P>
<P>
   While you are there, make sure to drop by the links page at
http://www.robbalducci.com
</P>
<P>
   /links.html. That's where you'll find a lot of free and helpful
information (along with some links that offer lessons for money).
But there's enough free stuff here to keep you busy for a long
time. If you follow every link, you'll get information on playing
chords, picking, selecting a guitar, downloading chord charts, and
finding newsgroups and discussion areas where you can, uh, compare
notes with other guitar players.
</P>
<P>
   Our next site is called the Easy Guitar Download page and is at
http://www.music-company.co
</P>
<P>
   .at/easyguitar/download.html. Some of the content here is in
German (all I can figure is that the Germans love the guitar), but
there are English labels on most links and most of the content is
decidedly un-German. For instance, you'll find computerized help
for learning country-western and gospel songs here.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of downloading, there are plenty of places on the Web
where you can download useful programs and tools for the guitar.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, most guitar players use an electronic tuner that
allows them to tune each string perfectly, instead of relying on
the ear. These electronic gadgets listen to the sound of a strummed
string and then use a meter to indicate when the string is tuned
perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   But you'll pay $20 or so for a cheap tuner at the store and a
lot more for a good one. You can save some money and use your
computer, a sound card and a microphone to do the same thing. Just
go to 
http://www.hitsquad.com/smm/programs/Windowsguitartuner/download.sht
ml to download a program that will do all that for you.
</P>
<P>
   Finally let's stop by Jazz Guitar Online at
http://www.jazzguitar.com/.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find a link there (or go directly to
http://www.jazzguitar.com/lessons.html) that offers a series of
free lessons you can download. This page also has commercial
products for sale, but just as is true with television or a
magazine, you can enjoy the free content without paying a penny.
</P>
<P>
   Now, let's play together.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
