<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book profiles movers, shakers of Web
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you're looking for a fun read about the recent rise
of the Internet, check out ``Architects of the Web.'' Written by
venture capitalist Robert Reid, the book chronicles the people and
companies that have powered the Internet's rising popularity in the
past five years. You'll find profiles of Marc Andreesen and Rob
Glaser, co-founder of Netscape and founder of RealNetworks and a
former Microsoft big shot, respectively. In a review, Fortune
magazine called the book ``well written and rich with detail.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking for some new games? You might want to check out the
latest issue of PC Gamer. The magazine this month features its
fifth annual PC Gamer Awards. The awards are divided into
categories, with a winner in each. The magazine did choose one
overall winner, and that was Sierra's ``Half-Life,'' a first-person
war game. Other winners included ``Rainbow Six,'' ``Grim
Fandango,'' ``StarCraft,'' ``Falcon 4.0'' and ``NBA Live 99.''
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   In its never-ending effort to turn famous old board games into
computer CDs, Hasbro Interactive has released several new titles.
They include ``Battleship,'' ``Scrabble'' and ``Grandmaster
Chess.'' Each is based on the board game of the same name and
retails for $15. These games are only available for Windows PCs.
</P>
<P>
   In the past several years, Disney has been exporting its famous
animation to computer CDs. The latest title is ``Winnie the Pooh &AMP;
Tigger Too.'' It's an animated storybook that features Christopher
Robin, Pooh and the gang. There are games, and the story of Pooh is
read aloud for little kids. Designed for ages 3-6, ``Winnie the
Pooh'' is available for both Macs and PCs.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever thought about traveling to Ireland, you might
want to check out the country's official Web site. It is loaded
with information about travel there, hotels, sites to see and other
information. There's information about the country's weather and
sports. You'll find this site, officially called Ask Ireland, at
http://www.askireland.com:8080/.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
