<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get your pheromones, better sex life via e-mail
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``BOOST YOUR SEX APPEAL AND CHANGE YOUR SOCIAL AND SEX
LIFE FOREVER,'' said the message header.
</P>
<P>
   Doubtless you've gotten e-mail like this, too. Maybe you read
it. Maybe you sent off for the stuff. Maybe you just ignored it, as
I did until just now.
</P>
<P>
   After all, an august computer columnist ought not to be nosing
around things like this. No telling where it might all end, but
given my luck it would end in the emergency room, the police
blotter or the gossip column.
</P>
<P>
   But I was feeling pretty down. My social life revolves around my
wife, my guinea pigs, and, blessedly but only occasionally, my
granddaughters. Sex appeal? In the eyes of a matronly walrus,
perhaps. Sex life? Well, that's private, and I wish it needed to
be.
</P>
<P>
   So, what the hey. Let's see what these sleazebags are peddling.
</P>
<P>
   What they are peddling are ``the natural human male/female
pheromone attractants and they are NOW available to YOU, legally.''
</P>
<P>
   I never knew pheromones were available to me at all, even
illegally. I never heard of the DEA raiding an underground
pheromone lab, or had anyone sidle up on a dark street corner and
whisper, ``Hey, big 'un, wanna dime bag 'a pheros? Finest kind _
Bolivian blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Pheromones, of course, are sexual attractants, but I assumed
they were limited to Mediterranean fruit flies. Florida, which is
bedeviled by these bugs, is always trying to use pheromones to lure
them to their deaths. I cannot see how my life would be improved by
my own personal cloud of fruit flies.
</P>
<P>
   But the aptly named purveyor of this stuff, Euphoria Products,
located, predictably, in Florida, claims humans have pheromones,
too, and all one needs for a wildly busy love life is an abundance
of them.
</P>
<P>
   According to my e-mail, this product, called HI-octane, contains
both male and female pheromones in a ``clear, odorless liquid,''
and the lovelorn are supposed to add it to their ``favorite perfume
or cologne.'' Despite this, the Euphoria folks say, ``This will not
attract same sex; but works as nature intended, attracting the
opposite sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Kind of like computer software. ``Hey, some clown back in
production dumped the male vat and the female vat together. We got
to figure out how to make this a feature and not a bug.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course it might work just fine, but I wouldn't want to send
mixed signals.
</P>
<P>
   There's another problem. I don't have a favorite cologne. I
tried it when I was a kid. It stings when you put it on, it tends
to smell like old saddle leather steeped in cheap whiskey, and if
girls got close to me their eyes watered and they sneezed.
</P>
<P>
   Although the e-mail claims a little dab'll do ya, since the
stuff sells for $40 per 1/8-ounce bottle (buy two, get one free),
the likelihood of overdosing seems inevitable. A testimonial from
Dave J., who can scarcely be heard over the clamor of women, says,
``I'd like to know if your product is available in a larger
quantity so I can make sure I'm never without it!''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, you should beware of peddlers offering substitutes,
like maybe water buffalo pheromones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be careful,'' cry the folks at Euphoria. ``Animal pheromones
do NOT attract humans.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't e-mail wonderful?
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
