<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Boys of Summer fly south for spring training
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Professional baseball players from
around the country have headed south for the winter.
</P>
<P>
   They're not there to play on the beach or to perfect their tans
_ they are there to work.
</P>
<P>
   Teams flock to warm havens such as Florida and Arizona for their
yearly ritual of spring training. They'll stay until around Easter.
</P>
<P>
   Almost since major-league baseball began, players have traveled
to warm climates in the late winter to practice their pitching,
hitting and fielding to get ready for the upcoming season. Babe
Ruth did it, Ty Cobb did it, Jackie Robinson did it.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Atlanta Braves are doing it. Javy Lopez, Tom Glavine,
Andruw Jones and teammates are in their new spring training
ballpark in Orlando, which is near Walt Disney World. They're
getting ready for opening day on April 5. They get to play in a
relaxed setting where fans are invited in to watch their practices.
The ballpark is much smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Being in Orlando works out nicely for the Braves' children too,
who get to go to the nearby theme parks.
</P>
<P>
   For the Braves who have families here, especially ones with
young children who don't have to be in school, spring training is a
chance to spend time together. Families come down and stay with
players in rented houses for weeks at a time. While the Braves have
to be at the ballpark in the morning and early afternoon, they can
spend time with their families in the evenings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have kids, it makes it a lot easier,'' said pitcher
Rudy Seanez, who's staying in a house with his wife Dianna and two
daughters _ Katrianna, who's 2, and Lilianna, who's 6 months.
``Sometimes if you're in a house by yourself and you've had a hard
day, you go home and sulk. You've got no one to talk to. It's a lot
easier when your family is here. It makes you forget about the bad
things and keeps you busy.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of spring training, the Braves have to narrow down
the roster from 40 players to 25. Twenty-five is the number they'll
keep until Sept. 1. In September, teams can expand the roster back
to 40, so they can give young players experience in real games and
rate their performances.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few questions about which relief pitchers the Braves
will keep to join Kerry Ligtenberg, John Rocker, Seanez and
newcomer Mike Remlinger in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   One problem the Braves now have is trying to adjust to the loss
of first baseman Andres Galarraga. ``The Big Cat'' has been
diagnosed with lymphoma, a form of cancer, in his lower back. He is
expected to get well eventually, but he will miss the entire 1999
season.
</P>
<P>
   Without him, the Braves have moved Ryan Klesko from left field
to first base, and 40-year-old former Brave Otis Nixon _ who signed
during the offseason as a free agent _ will play left field.
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS TO WATCH
</P>
<P>
   Some new faces to look for in this year's lineup are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Right fielder Brian Jordan signed with the Braves in the
offseason after spending the last seven years playing for the St.
Louis Cardinals. Jordan is known for playing great defense in the
outfield and being a solid power hitter. He had a career-high 25
home runs last year. He used to play safety for the Atlanta Falcons
and has been living in Atlanta during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bret Boone is the Braves new second baseman, who came over
from the Cincinnati Reds in a trade for pitcher Denny Neagle. Boone
is a seven-year veteran of the major leagues whose father (Bob
Boone), grandfather (Ray Boone) and brother (Aaron Boone) have all
played big-league baseball. Boone won a Gold Glove for playing
outstanding defense at second base last year and is coming off one
of his best offensive seasons ever: 24 home runs and 95 runs batted
in.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bruce Chen is a 21-year-old rookie pitcher who will be the
Braves fifth starter behind Tom Glavine, Greg Maddux, John Smoltz
and Kevin Millwood. Even though Chen is young and has only pitched
four games in the major leagues, the Braves think he is good enough
to get major-league hitters out night after night.
</P>
<P>
   SPRING SCHEDULE
</P>
<P>
   The Braves pitchers and catchers have been working out since
Feb. 18 and the remaining position players started working out on
Feb. 23. The Braves began a monthlong exhibition season with a game
against Georgia Tech on March 4. The Braves will return home to
Turner Field to play two exhibition games on April 2 and 3. The
season officially starts April 5 with a home game against the
Philadelphia Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
