<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former Justice dead at 90
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Harry A. Blackmun, a retired U.S. Supreme Court
Justice, died last week in Arlington, Va. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   Blackmun, a Republican, was appointed to the court by President
Nixon in 1970. He served 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rendering many decisions over the years, Blackmun is
remembered most for writing the Roe vs. Wade ruling. In it, he
stated women have a constitutional right to have abortions. He
received more than 60,000 pieces of hate mail from people who
didn't agree.
</P>
<P>
   To those who didn't know him, Blackmun might have seemed a
cranky old guy. On the bench, he often scowled and could snap at
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   But when he took off the judicial robe, he was warm and funny.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife and three daughters.
</P>
<P>
   POLIO ON VERGE OF EXTINCTION
</P>
<P>
   Polio, a disease that has paralyzed hundreds of thousands of
children around the world, will be eliminated by next year,
scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   Polio is already extremely rare in the United States, where most
children are vaccinated. But children in other countries, such as
India, haven't gotten the vaccine. Now medical teams are blanketing
those countries, vaccinating children.
</P>
<P>
   In several more years, when it's clear the polio virus has been
wiped out worldwide, children will no longer be vaccinated.
</P>
<P>
   Laboratories around the world are being asked to destroy or lock
up remaining stocks of polio virus. Scientists don't want a lab
accident or theft of the virus to start new infections.
</P>
<P>
   DISABLED STUDENT WINS CASE
</P>
<P>
   Schools around the country could be affected by a U.S. Supreme
Court ruling that an Iowa school should pay the cost of nursing
care for a disabled student.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year-old student, Garret Frey, is in a wheelchair and
needs a nurse's assistance throughout the school day. The court
ruled that federal law requires public schools to provide special
education services, including medical care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has a chance to have a free education,'' Frey said.
``It's going to help a lot of other kids. Not just me and other
kids in Iowa. It's going to help all over.''
</P>
<P>
   But school districts are worried that they can't afford to cover
those costs. Frey's school says it will cost about $40,000 a year
for the nursing care.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENTISTS TELL HOW WE SMELL
</P>
<P>
   Scientists believe they have figured out how the nose knows.
</P>
<P>
   For years they've wondered how creatures can distinguish
thousands of odors with only about 1,000 smell sensors. Now, a
study of mice has found that mammals use multiple sensors to
identify different smells. The same sensors are triggered in
different combinations to identify different smells.
</P>
<P>
   The sensors can be compared to letters, which are used in
different combinations to create different words.
</P>
<P>
   The team of scientists reported the discovery in a medical
journal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
