A1655 &Cx1f; tad-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMENTARY-BJT09-COX     03-08 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMENTARY-BJT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Tuesday, March 9, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN _ Marilyn Geewax's weekly column looking at
issues raised by the coming of 2000. This week: Will houses
continue to get bigger in the next century? (Geewax, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ An associate professor at
Ohio's Miami University has taken exception to the school's ban on
thong-style swimwear and filed a civil rights suit charging that
the recreation center advisory committee who nixed his scanty
attire is stifling his First Amendment freedom of expression and
his 14th Amendment right to equal protection. My obvious question:
What exactly is he wanting to express, and from what (or whom)
might he need protection? (Elizabeth Schuett, a teacher and writer
in Gibsonburg, Ohio, writes twice a week for Cox News Service)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KABAT-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ From the moment ``the babies'' in
the family are born, someone is telling them what to do, how to do
it, and when to do it. Much of it doesn't come from the parents,
either. It's the siblings. Whether it's big brothers or sisters,
they're there. And they resent you for popping into their world
uninvited. So, they get even . . . in little, deceptive, hidden
ways. (Kabat, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ When gas is cheap, cars will
be big. This is a law of nature and the Invisible Hand of consumer
economics. But I suspect our kids will find this a strange legacy.
They will look at the monster cars of the sport utility vehicle
showroom much as we once viewed the finned and chrome-spangled
Batmobile-looking artifacts that appear in old family photos. In
the meantime, I expect to continue feeling smaller on the highway
with each passing model year. If gas gets too much cheaper, I'll
have to scurry away to side-roads to stay out of the path of the
big creatures. (Lane, Daytona Beach News-Journal) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ I was AFAD before Susie Blair ever told me
about AFAD. Maybe you are, too. AFAD stands for A Fool About Dogs.
AFADs cherish one another almost as much as we do our dogs.
(Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ I fell asleep during Monica Lewinsky's
famous interview on ABC. Two hours listening to strangers talk
about sex is more tedious than might be supposed. (Rosenfeld, Cox
News Service) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
