   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   TECH-CENTERPIECE-CHIP _ Weekly centerpiece on personal
technology, from products to trends to advancements. This week: Why
you shouldn't buy Intel's new Pentium III chip. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Popular column about personal computing written for
the average user. This week: How cable modems put the fun back in
the Net. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ Software reviews. This week: Get your pheromones
and a wildly busy love life through e-mail. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCHER _ What's new on the Web. This week: Content's
comeback. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ What's new on the Web. This week: Tips for playing
guitar on the Web. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ What the tech magazines are writing about. This
week: ``Architects of the Web,'' and online board games. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ Tech briefs on new products and developments. This
week: A site for headache sufferers; Tim Duncan's Web site; and
cell phone upkeep tips. (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ This column will not move tonight. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POWERUSER-COLUMN _ This column will not move tonight. (Yandel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOGAMES _ AUSTIN _ Why games matter _ Nobody buys a $2,000
computer system loaded with 3D sound and accelerated graphics
capabilities because they want to run Word or Excel faster. Games,
especially advanced 3D shooters, are usually the reason for the
high demands computer users place on processors and graphics on
their computers. And as Origin Systems found out in the past,
upping the demands for a game can make users flock to new
technologies. (Gallaga, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED
GOOFY-PHONE _ Gadget profile: The Goofy Telephone is made in the
shape of the Disney cartoon character Goofy. And in addition to the
normal phone functions, the Goofy Telephone speaks five phrases in
the character's voice and has three animated motions. (Cummings,
Dayton Daily News). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   BARBIE _ Lordy, Lordy, Barbie's 40. The teenage fashion doll
hits middle age today on what Mattel is calling her 40th
anniversary (they don't like to use the b-word for what's supposed
to be an ageless toy.) But is it any coincidence that this year
Barbie's out with a younger-looking face, a new group of teen pals
(one with a nose ring) and a resculpted body? (Lizlee, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 23. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMERQ&AMP;A _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Consumer Q&AMP;A. This week:
Requisites for joining the Alaska State Troopers, and other
consumer questions. (Greig, Austin American-Statesman) (l, a) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Periodicals on the newsstands this week. (Emerson,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
