<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SENATE (Albany, N.Y.) _ First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton would not have a free ride to the Senate is she decides to
run for the seat being vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan in 2000,
according to a recent Siena College poll. Only 43 percent of those
polled approved of the First Lady's possible bid for a Senate seat
in 2000. By TADHG DOOLEY.
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRONMENTALIST-BOMB (San Francisco) _ When radical
environmental activist and organizer Judi Bari died of cancer on
March 2, 1997, the question that obsessed her for the last seven
years of her life remained unanswered: Who built and planted the
bomb that blew up in her car and nearly killed her? By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY-CZAR (Albany, N.Y.) _ When Peter P. Swire was a student
at the Albany Academy, he excelled in math and half a dozen sports.
But at home one of his biggest interests was computers. Twenty-five
years later, Swire will have a big say in the use of electronic
information in the United States because of his appointment by Vice
President Al Gore to be the nation's first ``privacy czar.'' By
ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   MIDLAND-DECLINE (Midland, Texas) _ After being clobbered by the
swift oil price collapse of 1986, the Permian basin made an equally
swift recovery. The current depression in prices _ longer, slower
and deeper _ is more pernicious. Some communities fear they will
lose their hospitals, maybe their schools. Midland, at the
epicenter, is holding its breath. Unemployment is going up, tax
valuations are going down, bankruptcies are high. By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PHARMACISTS (San Antonio) _ Although job satisfaction has
improved, the nation's staff pharmacists continue to report
burdensome workloads and many say they would not enter the field if
given a second chance, a survey of the American Pharmaceutical
Association has found. By CECELIA BALLI.
</P>
<P>
   VALLEY-ALLEY (San Francisco) _ Hoping to drum up funding from
some of the world's preeminent venture capital firms, New York City
multimedia start-ups are expected to strut their wares before Bay
Area venture capitalists at a conference titled ``Alley to the
Valley.'' The name was taken from Silicon Alley _ the region of
Manhattan from the Flatiron Building on 41st Street to the southern
tip of the city _ and Silicon Valley, the mother lode of
technology. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOMER-BOOKS (Undated) _ Memoirs were once for presidents,
retired generals, and Cher. But in recent years, baby boomers have
decided that their stories are at least as interesting as those of
politicians. The first-person genre is perfectly suited to a
generation that has grown up talking about itself and expecting the
world to listen. By CELINA OTTAWAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLIDERS-VETERANS (San Antonio) _ They flew clunky-looking,
blunt-nosed aircraft and took part in some of the biggest battles
of World War II. They wore silver wings with a ``G'' in the middle
that designated them as glider pilots. By TOM BOWER.
</P>
<P>
   CHORES (Albany, N.Y.) _ American boys and girls do the same
number but not the same kind of chores, according to a survey in
the March/April issue of Zillions, the excellent magazine for kids
from Consumer Reports. According to the survey of 1,000 children,
gender roles continue to apply in the assigning of tasks. By STEVE
BARNES.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-DiMAGGIO (San Francisco) _ Nobody ever said Joe DiMaggio was
the greatest player in baseball history. That honorific might go
for differing reasons to Honus Wagner, or Ty Cobb, or Babe Ruth, or
Jackie Robinson, or Willie Mays. DiMaggio's command of our
attention for fully six decades was due to something else. He was
the shining example of that rarest kind of athlete, a man who
evoked words like ``elegant,'' ``stylish,'' and ``regal.'' By RAY
RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The Black Diamond Mines
Regional Preserve is like no other park in the San Francisco Bay
area. Now reopened nearly 10 years after the Loma Prieta earthquake
damaged the park's tunnels, this is a very unusual destination _
and one you will never forget. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ If you want to know why the
schools don't work any more _ why kids you see everywhere seem
ruder, cruder and disturbingly dopier _ just look in the mirror.
And, while you're at it, stop complaining about how much teachers
get paid. How else could they afford the legal fees? By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   CLACK-COLUMN (San Antonio) _ The great list of books, articles,
photographs and broadcasts representing the top 100 of American
journalism in the 20th century, as assembled by New York
University, reminds us that for all the unpopularity and distrust
of journalists, this century has produced a trove of journalistic
excellence. By CARY CLACK.
</P>
<P>
   BERNSTEIN-BUSH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush's
announcement that he will form a committee to explore whether he
will run for president has virtually nothing to do with his
decision on whether he will run for president. He has already
decided to run. And he has said so. By ALAN BERNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Sorting out the impressions of
a two-week trip, or safari in Swahili, through rural Kenya will
take time. The assimilation of a multitude of sensations and
feelings of the ranging countryside, the bountiful variety of
wildlife, the people, and, most elusively, the culture that
embraces and rationalizes them, requires time. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Texas parole board chairman
Victor Rodriguez was on target last week when he questioned the
need for creating a life-without-parole sentencing option for
Texas' most heinous criminals. But he missed the point when he
defended the secretive way in which the Board of Pardons and
Paroles handles requests for commutations of death sentences. By
CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
