<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 11:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1721 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-KUBRICK-APPRECIA     03-08 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-KUBRICK-APPRECIATION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUBRICK: THE RECLUSIVE MOVIEMAKING GENIUS 
</HEADLINE>
  By IVOR DAVIS 
 World rights 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    If Stanley Kubrick had never been born, a masochistic Hollywood
would have had to invent him: A remote and godlike figure with a
formidable intellect and a cold heart, who every 10 years or so
made a movie his way just to show up the dummies in Los Angeles for
the money-grabbing, yes men he thought they were.
 &HT;    Kubrick died Sunday at the age of 70 in his home outside London
leaving a $100-million legacy_his latest film, ``Eyes Wide Shut,''
a psychological thriller starring Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman
which is due to open in July, two years later than expected.
 &HT;    Steven Spielberg called him ``The grand master of filmmaking. He
copied no one while we scrambled to catch up with him.''
 &HT;    The eccentric director of such unforgettable films as ``Dr.
Strangelove'' (l964), ``2001: A Space Odyssey'' (l968) and ``A
Clockwork Orange'' (l971), made movies his way. It is ironic that
producers of the Oscars are now scrambling to do a segment for the
awards ceremony, which airs March 21, while in his lifetime Kubrick
paid scant attention to Hollywood.
 &HT;    In l997, all of film town turned out to honor Kubrick with the
D.W. Griffith Award from the Directors Guild of America, putting
him in the company of Orson Welles, Alfred Hitchcock and Akira
Kurosawa. That night Kubrick was 6,000 miles away in England. He
sent them a taped thank you.
 &HT;    He hasn't set foot in his native United States since 1968. He
lived with his third wife, German artist Christiane, in
Childwickbury Manor, Hertfordshire. One reason he kept his distance
from Hollywood is his refusal to fly. He was most comfortable on a
bicycle. Despite having been nominated for an Oscar countless times
he never won the statuette and seemed happiest when he was furthest
from other filmmakers.
 &HT;    His life was a bundle of contradictions: A man in love with
technology and the future who was not even a comfortable passenger
in an automobile; a licensed pilot who wouldn't step into an
airplane; a Jew married to a woman who as a child was a member of a
Hitler youth group.
 &HT;    In an interview with Playboy magazine in 1960 he attributed his
fear of flying and his other phobias to his growing sense of the
fragility of life and his own mortality, an obsession which he
shared with that other great though very different auteur
filmmaker, Woody Allen.
 &HT;    ``This shattering recognition of our own mortality,'' he told
the magazine, ``is at the root of far more mental illness than I
suspect even psychiatrists are aware.''
 &HT;    Despite the fact that his work was often dark, pessimistic, even
misanthropic, his films were wildly anticipated by film buffs and
seldom disappointing. His last released film was ``Full Metal
Jacket'' (1987).
 &HT;    His ``Eyes Wide Shut'' was supposed to be shot in a year. But
Kubrick shot the film for over two years_calling the stars back to
England for countless new scenes. He ordered his stars to say only
that the picture was about sexual obsession and jealousy.
 &HT;    ``Mr. Kubrick has written that line down for us,'' Kidman said,
``and that's all we are allowed to say. If I say anything else I'll
get in trouble.''
 &HT;    The rumor mill of course has been working overtime. Is the story
really about Cruise and Kidman themselves? Does Cruise, the darling
of the American box office, actually appear in one scene in a
dress?
 &HT;    But the question that interested Kubrick fans worldwide was why
it took so long for him to work again. The answer was as simple as
bad luck_and maybe even worse timing.
 &HT;    Kubrick planned to come back to the screen early in the '90s
with a pet project, his take on the Nazi era and the German sweep
across Europe. He was well into the planning phase of shooting his
epic in Denmark when Steven Spielberg's ``Schindler's List'' came
along, and Kubrick dropped his project like a hot blini.
 &HT;    It was a question of ``once bitten.'' In 1986 Oliver Stone's
Vietnam film ``Platoon'' picked up seven Oscars and took the shine
off Kubrick's ``Full Metal Jacket'' which came out a year later.
Though many critics thought ``Jacket'' the more profound of the two
films, the public response was disappointing.
 &HT;    Such perhaps were the penalties of working so far from the
mainstream. A biographer, New York-based film teacher Vincent
Lobrutto, admitted he never got to meet Kubrick: ``I wrote to him
but he never responded. I've always appreciated that he didn't make
it difficult for me to talk to other people about him.''
 &HT;    Lobrutto has great admiration for Kubrick. ``He is arguably one
of the greatest film directors ever,'' he says. ``What he does is
create his own world. People don't understand him as a person.
There's a lot of The Bronx in him. All the myths and rumors spread
on the Internet about how remote he is, how he doesn't communicate
with the outside world, I found it to be the opposite. He does
contact people but only in connection with his films. His entire
life is funneled into his films.''
 &HT;    The cast in ``Full Metal Jacket'' was taken to an abandoned
factory on the edge of London, had their heads shaved and were
drilled and humiliated for weeks in best Marine style before they
even began rehearsals.
 &HT;    Top actors still want to work with Kubrick for the chance to be
part of cinema history. Cruise said recently of ``Eyes Wide Shut'':
``It's just a damned miracle that he wanted me and Nic to do
this.''
 &HT;    Kubrick was an original offscreen as well as on. His defiance of
the conventional and the bureaucratic was consistent. Former Marine
drill instructor Lee Ermy, who starred in ``Full Metal Jacket,''
tells of how he learned his lines as he was pelted with tennis
balls and oranges by a Kubrick aide to improve his concentration.
 &HT;    Ermy also remembers scouting locations with Kubrick in a new
$50,000 Mercedes. ``Stanley spotted a place. He got so excited he
turned the car over in a ditch with us all trapped inside. Totally
ignoring us, he clambered out yelling, 'Mark that spot. That's the
one I want.'''
 &HT;    In Kubrick's world one played by the maestro's rules, which
meant long, long hours of rehearsal, all of it videotaped, followed
by more long hours of discussion over what the tape reveals.
 &HT;    ``When people say, 'Oh Stanley is so controlling, he doesn't
allow anything, he makes all the decisions.' It's not so,'' Kidman
says. ``He's actually quite open. He creates an environment where
obviously it's the director and his vision. But he wants to hear
your ideas. He's so very into improvisation and working together.
He listens and then obviously, he makes the decisions and guides
you.''
 c.1999 Ivor Davis 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
