<HEADLINE>
ACADEMY AWARDS QUIZ: OSCAR GOES TO WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Gwyneth Paltrow and Joseph Fiennes in a
scene from ``Shakespeare in Love.'' 
 By S. BURELISON  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    What does it take to win an Oscar?
 &HT;    Well, if you're an actor it helps to be very, very good. But to
a considerable extent what counts is not what you do but what your
character does. Certain lines of work are much more Oscar-worthy
than others.
 &HT;    Given the choice between a physician and an insurance adjustor,
for example, go with the doctor _ if Edward G. Robinson didn't get
even a nomination for ``Double Indemnity'' (1944), chances are no
insurance man will ever win a statuette.
 &HT;    Likewise, pick the whore with a heart of gold over the airline
stewardess, and the self-sacrificing mother over nearly any other
job you can think of.
 &HT;    So, in a year in which jobs such as beleaguered G.I., ruler of
England and classical musician seem to be on the upswing, test your
knowledge of past occupational pluses and minuses with this handy
quiz. 
 -0- 
 HEART OF GOLD OPTIONAL  
 &HT;    This is a rare year in which no woman has been nominated for
playing a prostitute. But playing ``bad girls'' has been a good way
for actresses to hook up with Oscar since Helen Hayes first
committed ``The Sin of Madelon Claudet'' (1931).
 &HT;    But what about these other performances involving the oldest
profession?
 &HT;    1. Call girl Bree Daniel was an Oscar-winning role in a 1971
film named after the detective investigating her. Who was the
actress, and what was the movie?
 &HT;    2. Before she became a demure television mom, Shirley Jones was
good-girl-gone-bad Lulu Bains in what 1960 film?
 &HT;    3. ``Butterfield 8'' (1960) took its name from a call girl's
telephone number. Name the Oscar-winning actress and the character.
 &HT;    4. Woody Allen discovers that his adopted son was the biological
child of a prostitute in a 1995 film which he wrote and directed.
Name the film, and also the actress _ daughter of another
well-known actor _ who took home an Oscar.
 &HT;    5. Jo Van Fleet deserts her son to become a madam _ and an Oscar
winner _ in a 1955 film. What was the film, and who played the son?
 ORDER IN THE COURT  
 &HT;    John Travolta and Robert Duvall both hoped to be the latest in a
line of Oscar-winning attorneys for their work in ``A Civil
Action'' (1998), but only Duvall was nominated, as Best Supporting
Actor.
 &HT;    The odds were always better for defense attorney Duvall than for
plaintiff's attorney Travolta, however: All the Oscar-winning
lawyers were male defense attorneys _ no prosecutors need apply,
nor any women.
 &HT;    If you love movies, you should overrule any objection to
answering these:
 &HT;    6. Walter Matthau won a Best Supporting Actor statuette as
disreputable lawyer Willie Gingrich in 1966. What was the movie,
and what was his area of practice?
 &HT;    7. Attorney Hans Rolfe, defending accused Nazis in 1961's
``Judgment at Nuremberg,'' won an Oscar for which actor?
 &HT;    8. The Best Actor award for 1993 went to an actor who played
attorney Andrew Beckett in a film named after Beckett's city of
residence. Name the actor and the film.
 &HT;    9. Gregory Peck became the screen's iconic lawyer as the hero of
a 1962 adaptation of a classic novel. Name the movie and the
character.
 &HT;    10. In ``A Free Soul'' (1931), lawyer Stephen Ashe delivers the
longest uninterrupted monologue in American film history. What
actor won the Oscar for his pains?
 WRITER'S BLOC  
 &HT;    It was an upset when Joseph Fiennes didn't get nominated as the
title character in ``Shakespeare in Love,'' since screenwriters
naturally do well depicting other writers.
 &HT;    Can you place these other, luckier actors who played writers?
 &HT;    11. What actor had a tough time, as author Don Birnam, getting
through ``The Lost Weekend'' (1945), and why?
 &HT;    12. Who won his only statue as a reporter chasing a story from
Florida to New York in a 1934 comedy classic?
 &HT;    13. What actor won his only Oscar as a tabloid reporter in ``The
Philadelphia Story'' (1940), and what did the character really want
to do?
 &HT;    14. What real-life author did Jason Robards portray in 1977's
``Julia?''
 &HT;    15. George Sanders won as a cynical theater columnist in the
Best Picture of 1950. What was it?
 ACTING UP  
 &HT;    The Academy seems to favor performers who play stage actors over
those who play screen actors, perhaps because the latter hits too
close to home. So, at least, the theory has gone since the snubbing
of the classic ``Sunset Boulevard'' (1950).
 &HT;    Can you pick up on the following cues?
 &HT;    16. Who won for playing an actor in 1977's ``The Goodbye Girl,''
and what role did he play within the movie?
 &HT;    17. Who won a Best Actor award in 1947 for playing an actor
consumed by his onstage persona in ``A Double Life,'' and what role
did he play within the movie?
 &HT;    18. Who won as a hammy stage diva in ``Bullets Over Broadway''
(1994)?
 &HT;    19. What real-life actor did Martin Landau portray in ``Ed
Wood'' (1994), and what film was he making at the end of the movie?
 &HT;    20. What noteworthy actress won her first Oscar as a young
actress in ``Morning Glory'' (1933)?
 AND THE FIELD  
 &HT;    21. Name the only Oscar-winner ever to cop a statue for playing
an accountant.
 &HT;    22. What actress won an Oscar as a maid-turned-congresswoman?
 &HT;    23. Who won the Best Actor Oscar for playing a butcher?
 &HT;    24. Who won a Best Actress Oscar as a janitor?
 &HT;    25. Who won a Best Supporting Actor Oscar as a valet?
 -0- 
 ... AND THE ANSWERS, PLEASE  
 &HT;    1. Jane Fonda played Bree Daniel in ``Klute'' (1971).
 &HT;    2. Shirley Jones won an Oscar as Lulu Bains in ``Elmer Gantry''
(1960).
 &HT;    3. Elizabeth Taylor played prostitute Gloria Wandrous in
``Butterfield 8.''
 &HT;    4. Mira Sorvino, daughter of Paul, struck gold as ditzy Linda
Ash in ``Mighty Aphrodite'' (1995).
 &HT;    5. In ``East of Eden'' (1955), James Dean played Jo Van Fleet's
son.
 &HT;    6. Personal-injury lawyer Willie Gingrich _ no relation to Newt
_ appeared in Billy Wilder's ``The Fortune Cookie'' (1966).
 &HT;    7. Maximillian Schell won his Oscar for ``Judgment at
Nuremberg.''
 &HT;    8. Tom Hanks won the Best Actor Oscar for his role as an
attorney dying of AIDS in ``Philadelphia'' (1993).
 &HT;    9. Gregory Peck played attorney Atticus Finch in ``To Kill a
Mockingbird'' (1962).
 &HT;    10. Lionel Barrymore, as Ashe, delivered the memorable
14-minute-long speech.
 &HT;    11. Ray Milland won an Oscar as the alcoholic writer in ``The
Lost Weekend.''
 &HT;    12. Clark Gable played reporter Peter Warne in ``It Happened One
Night'' (1934).
 &HT;    13. As tabloid scribe Macaulay Connor, James Stewart dreamed of
writing short stories instead.
 &HT;    14. Robards won his second consecutive Best Supporting Actor
Oscar as detective-story author Dashiell Hammett.
 &HT;    15. Sanders won as Best Supporting Actor in ``All About Eve''
(1950).
 &HT;    16. Elliott Garfield (Richard Dreyfuss) played a gay Richard III
in ``The Goodbye Girl.''
 &HT;    17. In ``A Double Life,'' Ronald Colman played an actor whose
onstage performance as the suspicious, murderous Othello led to
offstage murder.
 &HT;    18. Dianne Wiest played the flamboyant Helen Sinclair in
``Bullets Over Broadway.''
 &HT;    19. Landau played Bela Lugosi, who died while making ``Plan 9
From Outer Space'' (1956).
 &HT;    20. Katharine Hepburn won her first of four Best Actress awards
as actress Eva Lovelace in ``Morning Glory.''
 &HT;    21. As accountant Loretta Castorini, Cher won the Best Actress
Oscar for ``Moonstruck'' (1987).
 &HT;    22. Loretta Young won in 1947 for ``The Farmer's Daughter,'' in
which she played a maid who was elected to Congress.
 &HT;    23. Ernest Borgnine played a gentle butcher in ``Marty'' (1955).
 &HT;    24. Marlee Matlin played a janitor at a school for the deaf in
``Children of a Lesser God'' (1986).
 &HT;    25. John Gielgud played the title character's valet in
``Arthur'' (1981).
 c.1999 S. Burelison  
