<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATTHEW-MCCONAUGHEY-IN-EDTV-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 MATTHEW McCONAUGHEY: ONE SPECIAL `ED'  
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Matthew McConaughey in a scene from
``EDtv.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Life in the fast lane actually began in an express lane.
 &HT;    Matthew McConaughey was in a Texas A&AMP;P store the first time he
really felt famous.
 &HT;    ``I was getting some produce and I went to the quickie checkout
line,'' the actor recalls. ``Suddenly I was staring at myself on
the cover of Vanity Fair.''
 &HT;    McConaughey approached the checkout girl, who didn't bother to
look up. He tossed down the magazine near the register and said,
``Good-looking kid, huh?''
 &HT;    ``Oh yeah,'' the girl gushed. ``He's really a babe.''
 &HT;    Then she looked up into those steel-blue eyes and nearly passed
out.
 &HT;    ``I said, `Darlin', I'll be buying that magazine,''' he recalls
with a chuckle.
 &HT;    The checkout girl exclaimed, ``I'll be buying one, too.''
 &HT;    Three years later, the only thing that hasn't changed is
McConaughey's laid-back attitude. He's been up in Hollywood, and
he's been down. He's been on every cover and in every magazine.
 &HT;    Now he's Ed in ``EDtv,'' a guy who consents to have his entire
life filmed for a television show _ a subject about which
McConaughey knows a little something.
 &HT;    The Texan actor arrives for a day of interviews at the San
Francisco Ritz-Carlton wearing tight, faded jeans and a T-shirt
that reads, ``I Survived Matthew's Birthday Party and All I Got Was
This Lousy T-shirt.''
 &HT;    Just turned 30, McConaughey tosses off a beaming smile and sits
down. He's got those same deep-blue eyes and the same molasses-slow
drawl as ever _ the only thing missing is what used to be a head of
luscious brown locks, now replaced by half-inch stubble.
 &HT;    And no, it isn't for ``U-571,'' the submarine movie he's
currently filming.
 &HT;    ``I actually cut it all off before signing for the film,'' he
admits. ``I just get these hankerings.''
 &HT;    The former hair is still on display in ``EDtv,'' the Ron Howard
film set to open on March 26. It's a quirky film, sort of the flip
side to ``The Truman Show'' (1998), and McConaughey is very high on
it.
 &HT;    ``I think this movie is about how the public thinks they can
interfere in the life of someone who is famous,'' McConaughey says.
``It's like if you come into someone's living room or if you're up
on that big screen, people feel like they know you. They don't know
you, but they still have an opinion on what your life should be.
They have an opinion on who you should date. Your life becomes a
real-life soap opera.''
 &HT;    McConaughey speaks from experience. Ever since he caught the
public eye in ``A Time to Kill'' (1996) _ in fact, as soon as he
was cast _ he has been a fan magnet.
 &HT;    ``I remember walking through the Third Street Promenade in Los
Angeles the Friday afternoon that `A Time to Kill' came out,'' he
recalls. ``Out of 1,000 people, I'd say 999 ignored me _ they
didn't even look at me.''
 &HT;    Three days later, he walked down the same street.
 &HT;    ``Suddenly 999 people were staring at me,'' the actor says. ``It
was very unnerving. I was like, `What's going on?' In an instant my
life had changed, and suddenly I wasn't comfortable.''
 &HT;    The press has relentlessly tried to dig into his personal life,
which McConaughey insists on keeping private. A particular focus
has been his relationship with Sandra Bullock, his ``Time to Kill''
co-star and, since last year, fellow resident of Austin, Texas.
Both have repeatedly said that they're friends and nothing more.
 &HT;    ``Sandra and I laugh about the rumors,'' he says. ``Sandy and I
say, `If all the talk was true, I guess we have five kids by now
and we've been married a couple of times.'
 &HT;    ``I do want to get married someday,'' he adds, ``but right now
I'm having a good time. I live in Texas, Louisiana and Los Angeles.
I like to wander around in my van with my dog _ I'm not ready to
settle down yet. If it happens, it happens.''
 &HT;    If it does, McConaughey has plenty of good role models for
settling down. He grew up the youngest of three brothers in Uvalde,
Texas, where his father was in the oil business and his mother was
a teacher.
 &HT;    ``My parents had a real love affair and created a warm group,''
he recalls. ``We were a family in cutoffs, building tree houses.''
 &HT;    As a child, he adds, he cared more about football than about
acting.
 &HT;    ``I wasn't a dramatic kid,'' he says. ``You weren't really
allowed that many moods in our family. If you came to breakfast
with a frown on your face, Mom would pop the table.''
 &HT;    He smacks the coffee table to demonstrate.
 &HT;    ``Mom would say, `What's your problem?''' he recalls. ``You'd
see the dust on the table flying. And Mom would say, `Go back to
bed, get up and start over, young man.'''
 &HT;    McConaughey enrolled in the University of Texas at Austin, where
he was a psychology and philosophy major heading toward law school.
 &HT;    ``Law school was something I was expected to do,'' McConaughey
says. ``I could understand why my parents wanted me to become a
lawyer, I could justify it to myself _ but I wasn't sleeping well
with it. I didn't have this passion for it.''
 &HT;    Instead he wound up playing lawyers in ``A Time to Kill'' and
``Amistad'' (1998). He'd already changed his major to directing for
his junior year when another option came to the fore, in the form
of a role in the low-budget ``Dazed and Confused'' (1993).
 &HT;    McConaughey took to acting like a duck to water.
 &HT;    ``I just fell in love with it,'' he says. ``I appreciated that
it was an art.''
 &HT;    A couple of years spent scuffling for his next big role ended
when novelist John Grisham vetoed Woody Harrelson as the star of
the film version of his book, ``A Time to Kill.'' Director Joel
Schumacher decided to try a new face, and suddenly McConaughey was
on the cover of that supermarket Vanity Fair.
 &HT;    ``I made an immediately splash with this intense kind of boom
and all this hype,'' he says. ``It's like I had a banner on me
saying, `Here's the New Guy.' I had to prove myself as an actor.''
 &HT;    That wasn't always easy. ``Contact'' (1997) did big box office,
but ``The Newton Boys'' (1998) flopped. ``Amistad'' was more
successful, but still counted as a disappointment.
 &HT;    ``I had all the hoopla when I started acting,'' McConaughey says
matter-of-factly. ``It's only natural that I would have a drop. All
I can say is that I did some films I was really happy about, and I
was proud to be a part of them.''
 &HT;    Next up is the World War II submarine film ``U-571,''
co-starring Bill Paxton and Jon Bon Jovi. After that, McConaughey
hopes to finally tackle a long-delayed role as motorcycle-stunt
star Evel Knievel.
 &HT;    In the meantime, though, he'll settle for being able to make
movies and at the same time live a somewhat private life. Which
doesn't mean that he doesn't like to meet his fans once in a while.
 &HT;    ``There's still a `Dazed and Confused' subculture that's kind of
the coolest group to get recognized by,'' he says.
 &HT;    Are they conscious?
 &HT;    ``Just enough,'' McConaughey says, laughing. ``I was in a pub in
Amsterdam and someone across the room screamed, `I think I just
heard that Matthew guy, man.'
 &HT;    ``Another guy said, `Man, you sound just like this guy in this
film, ``Dazed and Confused.'' You don't look like him, but you
sound just like him.'
 &HT;    ``I just said, `Nah, you've had too much to drink.'''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
