<HEADER>
A1774 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BACKSTAGE-AT-SESAME-S     03-08 1493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKSTAGE-AT-SESAME-STREET-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STREET'-SMART: A BEHIND-THE-SCENES LOOK AT `SESAME STREET' AT 30 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Big Bird and assorted Muppets in a scene
from the children's television series, ``Sesame Street.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``Muppets, where are you?'' Max Spelling asks. ``I think you're
hiding.''
 &HT;    Max, age 3, has been pacing the halls of the Kaufman-Astoria
Studios in Queens, N.Y., for 15 minutes, and if he has to wait
another second he'll burst. He wants to meet Big Bird, Elmo and
Rosita.
 &HT;    Finally, a Children's Television Workshop publicist emerges from
an elevator.
 &HT;    ``Who's your favorite Muppet?'' the publicist asks.
 &HT;    ``All of them,'' Max says instantly. ``I love all of them.''
 &HT;    Down a couple of halls and through a few doors we walk, with Max
growing increasingly excited. And then ...
 &HT;    ``Hey, Daddy!'' Max shouts, his eyes open wide. ``Look!''
 &HT;    Before him stands the beloved ``Sesame Street'' universe.
There's Maria's Fix-It Shop, Mr. Hooper's store, the famous 123
Sesame Street stoop, Oscar the Grouch's garbage can and Big Bird's
nest.
 &HT;    ``This is so cool,'' Max says breathlessly.
 &HT;    Over in an area called The Arbor, the ``Sesame Street''
production crew is preparing to shoot a scene featuring Big Bird,
three children dressed as ``birdkateers,'' two Muppets _ Tully and
Rosita _ and Maria, a human character played for 27 years by
actress Sonia Manzano. They're rehearsing a scene in which Bolo the
parrot is trying to learn the ``A-B-C'' song.
 &HT;    Max races over to Manzano.
 &HT;    ``Do you remember me?'' he asks. ``I see you on the television
all the time.''
 &HT;    ``Sure, hi, how are you?'' Manzano says with equal enthusiasm.
``I'm glad you could come today.''
 &HT;    Max sits down to watch everyone work, and everyone prays that
Max doesn't ruin any takes by laughing, whining or trying to help
Bolo sing.
 &HT;    ``OK,'' the director says. ``Let's bird up.''
 &HT;    And with that Caroll Spinney, the man inside the Big Bird
costume, dons Big Bird's head. The puppeteers operating Bolo,
Rosita and Tully assume their positions beneath a table.
 &HT;    They perform the scene several times. At one point, Big Bird
flubs a line.
 &HT;    ``Oh, poo,'' he says.
 &HT;    ``You said `Poo!''' Rosita says, as puppeteer Carmen Osbahr
laughs in character.
 &HT;    ``I'm so embarrassed,'' Big Bird says, burying his head in his
feathers.
 &HT;    Max smiles and laughs along with everyone else, not realizing
that he's just witnessed an outtake never to be seen on television.
Ever.
 &HT;    Fortunately, there are thousands of charming, thoughtful,
amusing and educational moments to be found in the nearly 4,000
``Sesame Street'' episodes aired to date. And, hard as it may be to
believe, ``Sesame Street'' celebrates its 30th anniversary this
year, with no end in sight.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, two generations of children have been raised on
``Sesame Street.'' The show has won 71 Emmys and spawned countless
spinoff products. It reaches 10 million American viewers a week,
and airs in 38 other countries as well.
 &HT;    This year, the show introduced a new 15-minute, stand-alone
segment, ``Elmo's World,'' while the Muppets _ created by the late
puppeteer Jim Henson _ are appearing in ``A Brief History of Motion
Pictures,'' a two-minute short running in movie theaters
nationwide.
 &HT;    Why keep fiddling with something so successful?
 &HT;    ``We revamp it every year,'' says Joan Ganz Cooney, CTW
co-founder and originator of ``Sesame Street'' and its classic
sibling, ``Electric Company.''
 &HT;    ``Constantly changing the show is a big reason why it's an
evergreen,'' she adds, speaking by telephone from her home in
Southampton, N.Y. ```Sesame Street' remains the only children's
show that's truly curriculum-based and researched every year to
make sure it's doing what we want it to do and what it should be
doing.
 &HT;    ``I think the characters are so impactful on children,'' Cooney
says. ``The Muppets are real to children and they're devoted to
Elmo, Big Bird and Cookie Monster. The genius of Jim Henson was to
infuse the Muppets with human qualities, and that creates a
devotion children don't quite have to other characters like the
Teletubbies or Barney.''
 &HT;    The computer generation is as interested in ``Sesame Street'' as
were the children of 1969, Cooney believes.
 &HT;    ``Children still like to learn, and they know `Sesame Street' is
teaching them something,'' she says. ``Parents find something
interesting, too. Some of them grew up on the show and they trust
it, trust us. There's something for them in watching the show with
their children.''
 &HT;    Now 69 and a grandmother of five, Cooney serves as chairman of
CTW's board and remains ``Sesame Street's'' guiding force. She does
not, however, consider herself responsible for educating millions
of kids.
 &HT;    ``I don't have much hubris about that,'' she says. ``I do think
we changed childhood in America in the following way: Kindergarten
started teaching much more after the first `Sesame Street'
generation arrived in school.
 &HT;    ``Children definitely began to learn more about numbers and the
alphabet in kindergarten, because they learned them on `Sesame
Street,''' she explains. ``I'm very proud of that, but don't take a
lot of bows. Part of that has to do with my wishing we'd had a
greater impact on inner-city schools. There are still problems
there.
 &HT;    ``On a personal level,'' she adds, ``I'm always happy to meet
people who talk about growing up on `Sesame Street' or `Electric
Company,' who talk about their kids growing up on `Sesame Street.'
 &HT;    ``That's wonderful. Sitting with my granddaughter, who's 2,
brings it home for me more than anything else.'''
 &HT;    Michael Loman, a former public-school teacher, is currently in
his sixth season as ``Sesame Street's'' executive producer. His
background also includes stints as a writer/producer of ``Happy
Days'' and ``Newhart.''
 &HT;    ```Sesame Street' works because it has a collaborative
imprint,'' he says. ``It involves the writers, producers and
performers. It also involves our research department _ we
constantly test the show with children at day-care centers. We
watch how they react, what they like and don't like and, most
importantly, we watch what they learn.
 &HT;    ``It's a huge responsibility when you present a show for little
children,'' Loman says. ``Everything has to be safe _ nothing can
lead to the wrong conclusion and nothing should scare the kids.
Finally, we have to make the show entertaining.
 &HT;    ``That combination _ educational, safe and entertaining _ is why
`Sesame Street' has been on for 30 years and why it's still
popular.''
 &HT;    The 65-year-old Spinney has been with ``Sesame Street'' since
its inception. In addition to portraying Big Bird, he manipulates
Oscar the Grouch and provides Oscar's voice.
 &HT;    Though such friends and collaborators as Henson, songwriter Joe
Raposo and writer Jeff Moss have died, Spinney says, the thrill of
puppeteering and the joy of educating children remain as powerful
as the day Henson hired him.
 &HT;    ``It's still wonderful,'' he says. ``I didn't take the courses
one needs to become a teacher, though I'd thought about teaching
when I was a kid. I always did want to be a performer, though.
 &HT;    ``As it turned out,'' Spinney says, ``I'm kind of both teacher
and performer, and I can't beat the audience _ the children of the
world.
 &HT;    ``I can't picture stopping.''
 &HT;    Back on set, Max is running out of steam. He's met his Muppet
pals, posed for pictures, shaken Big Bird's hand and sat on a stool
in Mr. Hooper's store.
 &HT;    As Maria and Big Bird wave goodbye, Max smiles.
 &HT;    ``I'll see you soon,'' he says. ``Bye-bye.''
 &HT;    In a taxi heading back to Manhattan, Max recounts his favorite
parts of his ``Sesame Street'' visit. He can't wait to tell his
friends at school about his day.
 &HT;    ``That was so cool, Daddy,'' he says. ``Can we do it again
tomorrow?''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
