<HEADER>
A1775 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROMA-DOWNEY-IN-TOUCHE     03-08 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROMA-DOWNEY-IN-TOUCHED-BY-AN-ANGEL-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMA DOWNEY, AN ANGEL ON A ROLL 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Roma Downey in a scene from ``Touched by
an Angel.'' 
 By BRIDGET BYRNE  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is one angel who's having a good time.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? Roma Downey's year has started well: ``Touched by
an Angel'' continues as a hit, and she herself is widely recognized
as a key to the show's success. The media frenzy surrounding her
divorce from director David Anspaugh has died down, and she's
enjoying a morning at a Los Angeles hotel, alternating between
being interviewed and playing with her 2-year-old daughter, Reilly
Marie.
</P>
<P>
   Downey, who plays Monica on the hit CBS series, is also a witty,
bright-spirited woman, as quick with her lip as she is easy on the
eyes. Monica may be a bit of a goof, a touch naive and in need of
guidance from her boss, Tess (Della Reese), but the actress who
plays her has a pretty sensible head on her shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Over ``a nice cup of tea'' at the hotel, where she's staying
while attending an awards show, Downey finds herself, inevitably,
talking about fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so important that whatever your sense of identity is not
be wrapped up in something that fleeting,'' the Irish actress says.
</P>
<P>
   Her own fame caught her more or less by surprise. When she
auditioned for the role in 1994 Downey didn't expect much, even
after winning the part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be just a pilot and a few shillings in my
pocket and on to the next thing,'' she recalls. ``I had no idea it
would totally transform my life.''
</P>
<P>
   That pilot episode, in which Monica actually wore wings and
flew, never aired. But CBS had sufficient faith in the chemistry
between Downey and Reese to give the show another chance to get off
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had you told me several years ago that I would become a kind
of a double act with this larger-than-life black singer from
Detroit, I would have thought you were crazy,'' Downey says,
laughing. ``And yet that day I met her ... There is a Van Morrison
line where he says `Hey, I recognize your soul,' and I really felt
that with her.''
</P>
<P>
   The two actresses clicked right away _ they're close enough that
Reese, who moonlights as a minister, is Reilly's godmother _ but
Downey is quick to credit the show's success to executive producer
Martha Williamson, who revamped it after the pilot was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gave it a spiritual base,'' Downey says. ``She's for real.
The pilot had a slightly more tongue-in-cheek approach, as if it
was saying `If there were angels, they could be like this.' Her
show says, `There are angels, there is a God.'''
</P>
<P>
   The show, now the network's top-rated drama, is in its fifth
season. Downey admits that she has trouble evaluating it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel that my life has changed,'' she says, ``but in
the middle of it all I had a child, so it's often hard for me to
try to distinguish between whether the change in my life occurred
because I became a television star or the more profound change in
my life occurred because I became a mother. And the fact they
happened simultaneously ... you know, I really couldn't tell you
how one defines the other.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress lives in Salt Lake City, where the series is shot,
and she's convinced that the double transition would have been even
harder if she had remained in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   However, she admits that she likes some of the trappings of
Tinseltown _ ``limousines and flowers and everything you would
associate with star treatment. But my day-to-day life isn't made up
of that,'' says the actress, who admits that she's always loved to
dress up.
</P>
<P>
   These days, she can do so in beautiful couturier clothes, such
as the strapless, midnight-blue gown by Richard Tyler that she wore
to the Golden Globes. But beyond the glamorous surface, she says
with a laugh, her life is actually at times a little lonely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been single and famous before,'' she says, ``and
it's very strange. You would think it would be the time of your
life. You would think `God, you could have your pick,' but `Where
and when am I ever going to meet anyone?' is the question that
screams in my head.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if I ever were to,'' she adds, ``how can I trust that it's
me that he's interested in and not the perception of me? So, sweet
surrender, I'm putting it out there _ I'm not looking for anyone,
but ... ''
</P>
<P>
   And she finishes the sentence with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Home life with Reilly _ who, while her mother is being
interviewed, successively watches videos, plays with her nanny and
takes a bath _ is Downey's greatest joy, she says, but she also
finds great satisfaction in her work as an actress, a career which
once seemed an impossible dream.
</P>
<P>
   Born in the Northern Ireland township of Derry, she grew up in
an era blighted by the region's sectarian violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing to do,'' she recalls. ``There was no cinema
_ gone. There was no theater _ burnt down. There never had been an
ice rink. There were no bowling alleys. There was very little even
in the way of sports arenas.
</P>
<P>
   ``So one's energies were taken up, really, sitting in people's
living rooms, making conversation, listening to music, reading,
hanging out on the corner and making up stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Downey's first memories of acting are of being in the chorus of
a pantomime ``Aladdin'' as a child, and then of dancing the role of
the Beast opposite Beauty in a ballet duet, wearing a homemade
papier-mache head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember getting to take it off at the end when she kissed
me,'' she recalls, ``and I was always kind of red and
bothered-looking. As I'd been oxygen-deprived for 15 minutes, it
was hard to look handsome and triumphant.''
</P>
<P>
   But that part of her life ended when her mother died. Downey was
only 10, and though she continued to perform in school plays, her
teachers didn't encourage her to aspire to an acting career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nuns said `You could be a great art teacher,''' she
recalls. ``And you go `Oh, they must know.'''
</P>
<P>
   Downey did in fact study at Brighton Art College in England, but
found art too solitary an experience. She soon realized that she
preferred the more collaborative process of acting.
</P>
<P>
   Now in her mid-30s, Downey has played Monica in more than 100
episodes, and she believes that the character has evolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, frankly, she has to show some maturation,'' the
actress says. ``Otherwise, if it does last another five years, I'm
going to look like the stupidest used-to-be-ingenue on the block.''
</P>
<P>
   In one episode this season, Downey played not only Monica but
also her counterpart Monique, ``a devil in a black business suit
and high heels _ with an American accent.''
</P>
<P>
   Another offbeat episode in the works is tentatively titled
``Black Like Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past,'' Downey explains, ``Monica has found herself in
various situations where she takes the audience with her on a
journey with some lesson to be learned, and we are going to do a
show very specifically about racism where Monica will become black.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we have been doing a series of makeup tests because,
obviously, we don't want to look foolish and, obviously, we don't
want to insult _ and, of course, we're running it all by Della!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Bridget Byrne is a Hollywood-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
