<HEADLINE>
PAROLE BOARD CHIEF MISSES POINT, MAKES ONE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas parole board chairman Victor Rodriguez
scored a hit and a miss in testimony before two House committees
last week on two emotional issues _ murder and clemency.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was on target when he questioned the need for creating
a life-without-parole sentencing option for Texas' most heinous
criminals. But he missed the point when he defended the secretive
way in which the Board of Pardons and Paroles handles requests for
commutations of death sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a misconception that I suspect is pretty widespread,
Texas doesn't have a life-without-parole sentence _ at least in a
literal sense.
</P>
<P>
   But it is an issue that comes up every time the Legislature
meets, and it is attracting some interest again this year.
</P>
<P>
   Some death penalty opponents may view the life-without-parole
option as an opportunity to reduce the number of executions in
Texas. Under that theory, some juries may be encouraged to sentence
fewer capital murderers to death if they had assurances a convict
who was spared the death chamber would never again be released into
the free world.
</P>
<P>
   Other advocates of the option have a different viewpoint. They
consider it another way to ``get tougher'' on crime. Short of
lethal injection, what sounds tougher _ in a constitutional sense,
anyway _ than locking up criminals and throwing away the key?
</P>
<P>
   But, in reality, as Rodriguez pointed out in his testimony to
lawmakers, a life-without-parole option would have little impact on
public safety because Texas law already requires capital murderers
sentenced to life in prison to serve 40 calendar years before they
can even be considered for parole. And _ depending on the political
climate of the distant future _ those who are still alive may not
even be released then.
</P>
<P>
   Most other violent offenders have to serve at least half of
their sentences _ or 30 years of a life sentence _ before they can
be released.
</P>
<P>
   Most of today's death row inmates, had they been sentenced to
life, would be in their 60s or 70s before they could become
eligible for parole.
</P>
<P>
   While that's not exactly a life sentence, it would come pretty
close for many convicts. And most convicted murderers, having
reached their senior years after decades of incarceration, would no
longer be considered a major threat to other people.
</P>
<P>
   Remaining behind bars, however, they would increase the
taxpayers' cost for health and nursing care in the state prisons.
</P>
<P>
   But since public safety is one thing and retribution is another,
the debate will continue.
</P>
<P>
   One important thing that the Legislature should do, regardless,
is change state law to require all juries to be informed of how the
parole laws can affect incarceration time. Some judges already are
letting juries know, for example, that a capital murderer sentenced
to life in prison has to serve at least 40 years, but other juries
remain in the dark and can only guess what ``life'' or any other
prison term may actually mean.
</P>
<P>
   During his tour of House committees, meanwhile, Rodriguez also
continued to defend the parole board's secretive way of deciding
clemency requests from death row inmates, which the panel almost
never grants.
</P>
<P>
   The board's long-standing practice of voting on clemency
applications over the telephone or by fax machine without holding
public meetings was sharply criticized in two high-profile capital
cases last year, including the execution of Houston pickax
murderess and professed born-again Christian Karla Faye Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   Both a federal judge and a state judge recently ruled that the
clemency process was constitutional, but both judges also
criticized the secretive way the parole board operated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every other state board and commission must meet to take any
action, however insignificant, yet the Board of Pardons and Paroles
decides a plea for mercy from death without ever meeting,'' state
District Judge Scott McCown of Austin wrote.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Elliott Naishtat, D-Austin, has filed bills that
would open up clemency proceedings, require board members to state
reasons for their decisions and establish criteria _ including a
convict's rehabilitation _ for granting clemency.
</P>
<P>
   Although the parole board has taken steps to make minor changes
in its proceedings, Rodriguez told legislators that the board
didn't intend to meet in public because the courts had ruled the
panel wasn't constitutionally required to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would we want to do more for someone who has committed the
most heinous crime against our people?'' Rodriguez asked the House
Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez missed the point, as state Rep. Robert Puente, D-San
Antonio, reminded him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that it's the inmate's right to a hearing
necessarily. It's the public's right to know how your board makes
decisions,'' Puente said.
</P>
<P>
   If the people of Texas are going to take the lives of convicted
murderers, the people have every right to know how their
representatives on the parole board decide whether a murderer
deserves mercy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
