<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHAKESPEARE,' NOT SPIELBERG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- The great Steven Spielberg, it seems, is starting
his victory lap a tad early. Before heading west for another
coronation in Hollywood, the movie maker is planning a swing
through here.
</P>
<P>
   Major face time with Vice President Al Gore is envisioned, as
befits one of the Clinton administration's most dilligent
supporters. And then _ can this be true? _ he wants to lay a wreath
at the Tomb of the Unknowns.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing wrong with that. For the impressario of ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' it is a nice gesture, but it's hard not to sense more than
a morsel of self-equation with a head of state on an official visit
here, the traditional movie world's confusion about its place in
the American pantheon. Such a gesture, after all, would not occur
to a poet or a giant of the theater.
</P>
<P>
   This is Spielberg, however, and this is the movies. Moreover,
this is the end of the century, the middle of another cycle of
multi-media awe (every bit of it appropriate and ultimately
inadequate) for the people who fought World War II. And I haven't
talked to a soul who knows movies from the inside who isn't
positive ``Saving Private Ryan'' is a cinch to get the Oscar for
best picture this month.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from its immense merits, it is simply inconceivable that
the Academy could reject it, given its reverential and realistic
depiction of Omaha Beach and Normandy. And yet, it is hard to find
movie people who truly believe it is the best picture.
</P>
<P>
   To use last year as analogy, ``Saving Private Ryan'' is
``Titanic.'' It uses D-Day as James Cameron used the long-ago
tragedy as the setting for another story that would not be up for
an Oscar by itself, even if Academy Awards were free of their
business and political taint. They are triumphs of cinematography
in the service of honest depiction.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, if you want to see the full story of Titanic or of
Normandy told for their intrinsic merit, ``A Night to Remember''
and ``The Longest Day,'' hold up just fine after more than three
decades, and each keeps its sub-plots in their place.To use this
year as analogy, ``Private Ryan'' is like ``Elizabeth'' in the
sense that each is a great movie in a setting of which Hollywood
never tires: the costume drama and the war picture. Indeed, the
best picture choices, all five, are in one or the other this time
around.
</P>
<P>
   The difference with ``Elizabeth'' is that film maker Shekhar
Kapur couldn't give a hoot about history. He has used classic movie
form _ costume, palace intrigue, pageantry, atrocity _ to the
fullest in the service of a vision of England's great queen through
the lens of today's feminism.
</P>
<P>
   And the reason his movie is up for best picture really has less
to do with its look or story than with the astonishing success of
Cate Blanchett in portraying Elizabeth with a depth that goes miles
beyond the basically boilerplate nature of the movie itself.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know anyone who thinks ``Elizabeth'' will win, just as I
don't know anyone who thinks ``Private Ryan'' will lose. But I also
don't know anyone who thinks ``Private Ryan'' will win for reasons
beyond its shattering first half-hour and what that tribute in
blood represents as depicted in its last half-hour. And I also
don't know anyone who doesn't see superior art and drama, as well
as greater depth, in the other nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg has done what he's done and bless him for it, but his
film doesn't come close in creativity, meaning, and achievement to
his own ``Schindler's List.'' And it doesn't touch ``Life is
Beautiful'' or ``The Thin Red Line.'' ``Private Ryan'' simply,
though powerfully, is. But Roberto Benigni's clownish father
shielding a son from the horror of the Holocaust celebrates the
human spirit in direct conflict with evil. And Terrence Malick has
taken Guadalcanal (as horrific as Normandy) and both respected it
as well as used it to dramatize the assault war represents on
nature as well as the nature of man.
</P>
<P>
   But the ultimate achievement last year for my money is what
happened a few years ago after writer Marc Norman's son, studying
Elizabethan drama, wondered how Shakespeare was motivated to write
``Romeo and Juliet'' and whether he might have been in love.With
the aid of Britain's genius playwright, Tom Stoppard, and John
Madden's direction that cut their what-if script like a diamond,
``Shakespeare in Love'' is a tribute to inventive creativity, to
imagination itself.
</P>
<P>
   It is bawdy and beautiful, hilarious and profound, a great play
about an even greater play. My movie moment of the year comes not
on Omaha Beach but at an Elizabethan theater in London, as the
premiere of Romeo ends and the audience is stunned into silence
before the cheers start.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's Academy is like the rest of us in this country.
Uncomfortable with art, we take refuge in the celebration of
extravagance or of patriotism most of the time.Even as we know
better. No matter what the already cast votes say, ``Good Will
Hunting'' was the best picture last year and ``Shakespeare in
Love'' is everything a movie can be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
