<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERNSTEIN-BUSH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S LATEST COMMITTEE OFFERS MORE PROSPECTING THAN EXPLORATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush's announcement that he will form a committee
to explore whether he will run for president has virtually nothing
to do with his decision on whether he will run for president.
</P>
<P>
   He has already decided to run. And he has said so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to run,'' he told a historian for the Daughters of
the Republic of Texas in Austin last week, according to an
Associated Press report. And that's just one example.
</P>
<P>
   But the unveiling of an exploratory committee was a big deal
anyway, for at least three reasons: money, cash and checks.
</P>
<P>
   With the documents on file and the bank account open, Bush can
start raising and spending money on polling and travel and on other
early phases of a national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The governor told reporters in the back yard of the governor's
mansion last week that he has ``a compelling reason to consider
running for president: I want the 21st century to be prosperous,
and I don't want anybody being left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement could just as easily apply to his budding
campaign: Other candidates have made it clear that they will run
for the Republican nomination for president, and Bush doesn't want
to be left behind in the last fund-raising sweepstakes of the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   If he can quickly raise the $25 million that oddsmakers say is
the threshold for a healthy White House contender, he will be even
more of the dominant force that early voter surveys show him to be
in the GOP contest.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's timing creates an ethical wrinkle, though. Like the
state's lawmakers, Bush can't accept political contributions for a
state campaign while the Texas Legislature is in session. That rule
went into effect a few years ago after a wealthy businessman with
an interest in pending legislation passed some fat checks to state
senators right there in the Senate chamber.
</P>
<P>
   But now that he has an exploratory committee for a federal
campaign, Bush can receive contributions of up to $1,000 each from
the same people who can't give money to the account he can use as
governor or as a candidate for re-election to the governor's
office.
</P>
<P>
   It means that lobbyists involved in the electric utility
deregulation fight, or any other issue on the griddle in Austin,
can show their utmost respect and admiration for Bush's
presidential aspirations by sending a $1,000 check right about the
time Bush decides whether to sign the bills they are interested in.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there would be any connection between supporting Bush
for president and hoping he takes preferred action on a new law. No
connection at all. No sir.
</P>
<P>
   Because Bush has already decided to run, why the ruse, the
charade, the gamesmanship involved in saying that he is merely in
the exploring mode? And why the media frenzy every time he takes an
incremental step?
</P>
<P>
   Well, in the current setup, Bush can stay true to his pledge
that he will concentrate on Texas and its lawmaking process until
the legislative session ends in May _ while signaling supporters
and contributors and pundits, all the way to New Hampshire and
Iowa, that the race is definitely on.
</P>
<P>
   And because those voter surveys show Bush reaping so much
political profit by carrying out this slow seduction _ while other
candidates make their umpteenth campaign stop at the coffee shop in
Derry, N.H. _ why not keep the tease going a little bit longer?
</P>
<P>
   Even more, the gradual unfolding of the ``Another Bush For
President'' campaign provides the news media with the kind of
prefabricated drama that makes for easy video and easy headlines.
We know what is going to happen, but that doesn't stop it from
being a screamer when it happens, because it still means so much:
``Clinton Acquitted.'' ``Racist Convicted In Dragging Murder.''
``Bush Kicks Off White House Campaign, Part III.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, speculation about Bush running for president is at
least a year and a half old. After Bob Dole's loss to President
Clinton in 1996, Republicans started looking around for fresh,
successful faces and found one whose father had already occupied
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   From 1996 to last month, the biggest political development for
Bush was his landslide re-election in 1998. It showed that he could
be a record-breaking winner in a multiethnic state. His worries
about how a presidential race might mess up his family's life and
expose him unfairly to scandalous allegations, look like they
weren't substantial after all.
</P>
<P>
   The news, therefore, is that the fellow slotted to run for
president is now collecting money to do just that. Updates will be
posted as they occur.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
