<HEADLINE>
HOW MUCH CHLORINE IS IN SEA WATER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I recently read that the most plentiful element in sea water
is chlorine. If this is true can you please explain how it is
possible?
</P>
<P>
   T.B., Nashua, N.H. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why is the ocean salty?
</P>
<P>
   J.B., Newton, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. With thanks to Dr. David Ross, Senior Scientist at the Woods
Hole Oceanographic Institution in Falmouth, Mass.: When it comes to
sea water, the Os have it. And then the Hs. Then come the Cls. The
oxygen in H20 makes up 85.7 percent of sea water by weight.
</P>
<P>
   The hydrogen is 10.8 percent. Chlorine is the next most
plentiful element. But it's a distant third, only a meager 1.9
percent of sea water. Its molecular partner in salt, sodium, is
about 1 percent of sea water. Together with other salts like
magnesium chloride (.13 percent), and calcium chloride ( .04
percent), the total salinity in sea water averages 3.5 percent. In
areas of high evaporation like the Persian Gulf or Red Sea, the
total can be as high as 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some inland bodies of water have much higher salinity. Utah's
Great Salt Lake ranges between 10 and 17 percent salt. The Dead Sea
is between 30 and 33 percent salt.
</P>
<P>
   All that salt in the water came from land, eroded out of rocks
and soil and washed into the sea for billions of years. Other
elements like iron, aluminum, strontium, cobalt, even gold, also
washed out of rocks and into the oceans. But most of those elements
are reactive. They tend to attach to organisms through biological
processes. So they're hard to find in sea water as independent
elements. Salt, on the other hand _ or sodium chloride _ is not as
reactive, so it isn't absorbed by organic reactions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How fast do snowflakes fall?
</P>
<P>
   A. ``The really rimed crystals can buzz right along like a blur,
at a lightning-like nine miles per hour.'' says Nolan Doesken,
Assistant Climatologist for the state of Colorado and author of
``The Snow Booklet. ``A nice little stellar crystal, the favorite
magical snowflake with the arms that everybody draws, will float
down more gently, at one to one-and-a-half m.p.h.''
</P>
<P>
   How does he know? Doesken and his fellow flake freaks photograph
falling flakes, factoring in wind conditions, and figuring out how
fast snow falls.
</P>
<P>
   So what's a rimed crystal? That's a snowflake that picked up one
or more tiny particles of supercooled water on it's way down.
Supercooled water is colder than 32 degrees Fahrenheit but not yet
frozen. If it's really pure and doesn't have any imperfections to
serve as condensation nuclei, water can get down to 40 degrees
below zero Fahrenheit before freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Doesken says that in clouds, supercooled droplets often occur at
temperatures of 10 to 15 degrees Fahrenheit. But when a snowflake
bumps into them on its descent, those droplets attach to the
crystal and freeze. That kind of ice is called rime. The more rime
that freezes onto a snowflake as it drops, the heavier the flake is
and the faster it falls.
</P>
<P>
   It's still not sleet or hail, which are bigger, more solid
pellets of ice. It's still a snowflake crystal, with a kind of a
crust frozen on.
</P>
<P>
   ``East Coast storms are usually heavily rimed, with high fall
velocities,'' Doesken adds. ``Your snow in New England isn't so
much drifting down as hightailing it down.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the air that brings snow to the East Coast is
rich in moisture compared with snow clouds elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1816 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-PROTECTION-BOS &LR;      03-08 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-PROTECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MILITARY: WAY OUT OF HARM'S WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a policy with roots that go back to Vietnam, wind their
way through the Marine barracks in Beirut, the streets of
Mogadishu, and into Khobar Towers. It is called, in the peculiar
parlance of the military, ``force protection.''
</P>
<P>
   It's meaning is clear enough: that our military objective should
be to avoid having US service members killed in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Any sane person would applaud efforts to keep the casualties of
war to a minimum. But there is a concern that the US commitment to
force protection _ built in part on fear of the public's reaction
to loss of life _ has undercut our foreign military presence. In
short, are we becoming a nation that speaks loudly and carries a
small stick?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a pervasive feeling in the Pentagon that we cannot
tolerate casualties,'' says Bernard Trainor, a retired Marine Corps
general and former director of the national security program at
Harvard University's John F. Kennedy School. ``Force protection . .
. is an integral part of the planning process.''
</P>
<P>
   The effects of the force protection policy can be seen in our
refusal to go into Rwanda to stop the massacre of as many as
800,000 Tutsis and moderate Hutus by Hutu rebels in the mid 1990s;
it was present in America's reluctance to send troops to Bosnia,
and in our decision not to go into Afghanistan and hunt down Osama
bin Laden, the Saudi millionaire terrorist believed to be the
mastermind of the bombings of US embassies in Kenya and Tanzania,
and the man some think responsible for the bombing of Khobar Towers
in Dhahran that killed 19 US soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   And many believe it is why we have not sent troops to Kosovo _
an issue that may well take center stage again soon, depending on
the outcome of the peace talks that resume March 15. Says Trainor,
``The planning for Bosnia and Kosovo has been heavily influenced by
force protection.''
</P>
<P>
   If the military becomes too cautious, it can be a detriment to
implementing policy, whether strategic or moral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internationally, one would be on safe ground to say there are
questions about the wherewithal of the United States to act like a
superpower,'' says Richard Shultz, director of the international
security studies program at the Fletcher School of Law and
Diplomacy at Tufts University.
</P>
<P>
   John Hillen, a senior fellow in political military studies at
the Center for Strategic and International Studies, says allies in
Bosnia ``derisively refer to the US contigent as the turtles
because we have to go around in full battle rattle and have to
travel in convoys of at least four.''
</P>
<P>
   Many believe our decision not to go to Rwanda in 1994 to stop
the genocide of Tutsis by Hutu rebels as the result of the death of
18 servicemen in Mogadishu, Somalia, in 1993. We had gone there as
part of a United Nations effort to bring food and stability to the
East African country torn apart by civil war.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that our aversion to casualties led us to a
major mistake in not intervening in Rwanda,'' says Michael
O'Hanlon, a fellow in foreign policy studies at the Brookings
Institution. ``And the behavior was shameful, and it is a blight on
the the Clinton administration and Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is suggesting that a good strategic and moral foreign
policy needs to be built on a foundation of corpses, but by simply
risking casualties _ rather than steering clear of hot spots or
relying exclusively on high technology, stand-off weapons like the
cruise missile that can be fired hundreds of miles from the target
_ a different message is sent to friend and foe alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is definitely the view in some Persian Gulf
states that the US won't be willing to back them up for the long
term,'' says Shultz at the Fletcher School.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the October 1993 case of the Navy vessel USS Harlan
County, which was attempting to dock in Port-au-Prince with 218 US
and Canadian military advisers to help restore ousted Haitian
president Jean-Bertrand Aristide to power. When confronted with an
anti-American mob of pistol-waving goons, the ship came about and
sailed away. That humiliation resulted in another year of military
rule, another year of murder and rape in Haiti before American
troops _ in much larger numbers _ returned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So why is our military so averse to casualities? What underlies
this dramatic change in attitude from, say, the days of World War
II?
</P>
<P>
   Much of it stems from Vietnam where more than 58,000 Americans
died in a war that became increasingly unpopular at home and was
broadcast into living rooms every night. The outrage over the
deaths of Americans for a seemingly meaningless country half a
world away is something that haunts the military to this day.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, military operations are evaluated for the
likelihood of success, the amount of time it will take to achieve
success, and the risk of casualties in order to accomplish the
mission.
</P>
<P>
   The military's objection to putting our troops in harm's way is
often obscured in rhetoric that does not even mention force
protection. ``They start asking what our exit strategy is going to
be,'' says Trainor. ``It used to be you would go in and deal with
the immediate future. Figuring out when to get out comes in due
course, but that is just absolutely part of the Pentagon culture
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon will also bristle at becoming involved in
humanitarian missions that do not have readily apparent strategic
importance. ``They will say, `This is not what we are about. We are
about fighting wars. These humanitarian or peacekeeping missions
are our operations,' '' says Shultz. ``The one service that has a
different view about this is the Marine Corps. They are willing to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon is not alone in its recently found aversion to
shedding any American blood overseas; on this matter, it is in sync
with the White House and President Clinton who, after all, opposed
the Vietnam War and, while he was Rhodes scholar, wrote to an ROTC
colonel thanking the officer for ``saving me from the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, arguably, times the Pentagon could be prodded into
action by a leader able to make a forceful argument to the public.
``It takes PR campaign by a president to set the bar higher,'' says
the Brooking Instition's O'Hanlon. But Clinton is disinclined to
play that role.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps nowhere could that type of argument been made better
than in a pursuit of bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   ``With someone like Osama bin Laden, one can make strong
argument we should have risked special forces last summer and gone
in and seized him, and instead we fired cruise missiles, that if we
got very lucky, would have accomplished something,'' says O'Hanlon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Clinton was feckless to do anything more, he could not
afford a tragedy in the desert. Our special forces are far better
than they were in 1980 (when the military was humiliated in a
botched attempt to rescue American hostages in Iran). We might have
had some casualties, but bin Laden is really dangerous,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Many specialists believe Americans would be more willing than
politicians and generals to sacrifice many sons and daughters for a
worthy goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear of casulaties prevents us from doing things we could
do,'' says Shultz. ``If you would say to the American public,
`Osama bin Laden is a problem. He will support people who blow up
the World Trade Center and try put chemical weapons in there. This
is what is at stake and we need to go after him and it may put
Americans at risk,' they would understand and we could use
something other than cruise missiles to go after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no one articulates it because inside the Beltway culture
there is a view that _ short of being invaded _ the country will
not tolerate losses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The question,'' says Hillen, ``that a lot of Americans have
trouble answering is: What is worth dying for?'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Matthew Brelis is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
