<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1817 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-RACISM-BOS &LR;      03-08 1671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-RACISM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK BRITONS SEE A NATION BLIND TO RACISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Michael Cole, a native of Nigeria who lived briefly in
the United States but has called London his home for most of his
life, says there is a difference between American racism and that
which he has experienced here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw what happened to that poor man in Texas,'' said Cole,
referring to James Byrd Jr., who was chained to the back of a
pickup truck and dragged to his death, an attack for which one
white man has been convicted and two others face trial. ``That
would never happen in Britain.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he feels physically safer in Britain, Cole believes
there is more opportunity for blacks to scale the educational and
economic pyramid in the United States, which is why he sent his
children to live there. His son is studying at the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst, while his daughter is at the University
of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racism is more entrenched in Britain,'' said Cole, who makes
his living as a limousine driver. ``It's at the bottom of
everything. My two children would never be as successful here as
they are in America. America has big problems, but America has
confronted its racism. England won't do it. They pay lip service.''
</P>
<P>
   Rare though it was, it was an act of racial violence that has
led many people here and the British government to confront racism
like never before. In 1993, Stephen Lawrence, 18, a black high
school student, was attacked and stabbed to death by a gang of
whites as he stood at a bus stop in South London. The police
bungled the investigation, allowing the suspects to escape
prosecution and galvanizing a minority community that has long
complained that police treat violence against them less seriously
than crimes against whites.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a government inquiry into the Lawrence slaying
concluded that London's Metropolitan Police, the largest police
force in Britain, is ``riven with pernicious and institutionalized
racism.'' Former High Court judge William Macpherson, who led the
probe, made a further point, saying the institutional racism of
London police is a symptom of a wider problem in British society.
</P>
<P>
   Cole's views are echoed by many black people here.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews and informal conversations over the last six
months, there was a consensus among blacks that while the United
States has far more racial violence and racial polarization,
Britain's racism is more subtle and more pervasive, and is
exacerbated by a class system that limits access to education and
jobs and blocks social advancement.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities in Britain say subtle racism here excludes them from
many institutions of a society that is 94 percent white and defines
itself by those institutions and their traditions. Blacks complain
that they are in, but not of, British society.
</P>
<P>
   Those who hail from former British colonies, such as Jamaica,
say Britain was more than willing to exploit their homelands during
the heady days of the British Empire, and to use them to rebuild
after World War II, but is not willing to embrace them as anything
but second-class citizens.
</P>
<P>
   According to government statistics, blacks are stopped randomly
and searched by police at a rate five times that of whites. But
Carl Joseph says those statistics do not convey the reality he
lives with. Last month, Joseph, a 27-year-old black butcher in
Birmingham, sued the police after they stopped and questioned him,
but never charged him, 34 times in two years.
</P>
<P>
   He lost.
</P>
<P>
   There are many who share the views of Enoch Powell, the great
parliamentary orator who died last year and whose political career
fell into disrepute in 1968 when he warned that Britain would
collapse if it continued to allow minorities from the colonies to
settle here. But when whites who share Powell's view that the
arrival of minorities since the 1950s has contributed to Britain's
loss of power and status were interviewed, they declined to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true, but if you say that, everyone says you're a
racist,'' said one woman, a realtor in Highgate, a middle class
London neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Yasmin Alibhai-Brown, author of ``True Colours,'' a recently
published book about race relations in Britain, said denial is
common. She said most British people compare themselves favorably
with more overtly racist societies, and they believe that because
so many minorities are trying to emigrate here, complaints about
racism must be exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been writing on race for 12 years and I have never met
anyone who believes that he or she is a racist,'' she said. ``We
black Britons are constantly reminded that we never had slavery,
apartheid, gas ovens, or lynching, that this country is not nasty
Germany or violent, racist America.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, since 1991, there have been at least two dozen racially
motivated murders in Britain, most of them in London. Civil rights
activists believe the true figure is much higher.
</P>
<P>
   At one level, Britain is a much more integrated and tolerant
society than America. The most popular TV newscaster is Trevor
McDonald, a black man born in Trinidad. Interracial couples are
common. As Alibhai-Brown points out, more than half of British-born
black men have a white partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have de facto integration,'' she said. ``There is a third
race emerging which will be reflected for the first time in next
year's census.''
</P>
<P>
   This is impressive in a country of 58 million that is so white,
and which has had a sizable minority population for only a
half-century. And yet racial and ethnic stereotyping, xenophobia,
and epithets are tolerated here and often appear in the popular
press, especially the tabloids that sell the most. Japanese are
routinely referred to as ``nips,'' the Irish as ``paddies,''
Germans as ``krauts.''
</P>
<P>
   Minorities are concentrated in English urban centers, with few
in Scotland and Wales or the English countryside. In London, where
more than 7 million people live and where 20 percent of the
population is minority, there are few black faces in the news
media, which are concentrated in London. Less than 2 percent of the
National Union of Journalists membership is nonwhite. Among the
staffs of 16 national newspapers, there are only 30 minority
reporters. Alibhai-Brown, who writes for The Independent, is the
only nonwhite columnist.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald, the anchor on Independent TV, is an anomaly. At the
British Broadcasting Corp., 1,550 of its 20,000 employees, or 7.4
percent, are minorities, but its only black TV anchor, Moira
Stewart, has just been demoted. BBC insiders say the numbers are
deceiving, as few minorities are involved in programming.
</P>
<P>
   As Gary Robertson, who hosts a current affairs program on BBC
radio, put it, ``Most of the black people here are serving us
coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   In London's myriad courthouses, the only black faces are usually
in the defendant's dock. Only about 5 percent of lawyers are
minorities, and only nine of some 1,000 judges in the highest
courts. Only 3 percent of London's police officers and 4 percent of
its firefighters are minorities. The National Health Service is is
more reflective of the population it serves. In London, 31 percent
of doctors and 29 percent of nurses are minorities.
</P>
<P>
   But nowhere are blacks more conspicuous by their absence than in
the military and the police; minorities make up less than 2 percent
of the nation's police officers and 1 percent of its soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative action is illegal here, considered reverse
discrimination. But minorities complain that the police, military,
and other institutions have never proved they really want them to
join the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The military last year launched a campaign to recruit more
blacks. But as white soldiers handed out leaflets and chatted with
passersby in Brixton, London's traditional black neighborhood,
blacks seemed more bemused than interested.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Rose, 19, a black student from Brixton, said he wouldn't
join the military because he does not believe he would have the
same opportunity as whites. Instead, he wants to become a civil
rights lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Like many blacks here, Rose was offended when, as part of the
recruitment drive, Prince Charles was dispatched to talk to some
black recruits. As the cameras rolled, Charles told the black
soldiers he knew how they felt, because he had been teased for
being a royal when he joined the army.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to compare his situation to the way black people are
treated in this country shows just how much in denial the British
establishment is about racism,'' said Rose.
</P>
<P>
   If Rose becomes a civil rights lawyer, he will find far fewer
statutes at his disposal than his American counterparts. The police
and other governmental agencies, for example, are excluded from
anti-discrimination laws, something the government has vowed to
change. Civil damages in discrimination suits, meanwhile, are
paltry compared with those in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking privately, a London lawyer said that when he advises
corporate clients on their liability if they are found to
discriminate in hiring or business practices, ``most often the
reaction is, `We'll take our chances.' '' The risk of litigation is
so low that most companies don't worry about whether they are being
discriminatory, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are signs that increasing numbers of Britons are
acknowledging that racism is a major problem. Recent polls show
that a majority of whites believe they receive better treatment
from the police than blacks. There are more newspaper articles and
radio and TV documentaries about racism than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hottest plays in London is ``The Color of Justice,''
which uses transcripts from the Lawrence inquest to paint an
unsettling portrait of official indifference and subtle racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think we're becoming more enlightened,'' said
Alibhai-Brown. ``We'll have to wait and see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
