u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-08 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT IS WISE TO USE SAVINGS TO PAY A DEBT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My question is the classic dilemma: Should I use my savings
to pay a debt? I have a $53,000 CD paying 6.13 percent and maturing
in May 2000. At maturity, the value will be $59,000. This money is
not earmarked for any particular purpose, and I have other funds
for emergencies and retirement. I also have a mortgage at 7.125
percent with a current balance of $80,000. If I continue my current
schedule of regular payments plus prepayments, the balance will be
down to about $60,000 by the time the CD matures. I am seriously
thinking that I should take the CD proceeds and eliminate the
mortgage debt. That would mean losing the tax deduction, which came
to $6,000 in 1998. I am in the 28 percent tax bracket. Do you agree
with my thinking of paying down the debt?
</P>
<P>
   J.J., Sharon, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. At least at this point, this one's pretty easy to figure out.
Most people who present this question add an element of
uncertainty, which entails the debatable question of the likely
return on the funds that would be used to pay off the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   But since CD rates are locked in, this one's pure mathematics.
Of course, you'll have to wait until May 2000 to see what the rates
on CDs are at that point, and also recalculate the tax benefit as
of that date, but it sounds to me that you'd probably be best off
keeping the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   But let's suppose you could do the deal right now, having
$59,000 in the bank and $60,000 due on the mortgage. You would be
getting $3,616 from the CD, plus a tax deduction that's worth
$1,177 in your 28 percent tax bracket. That comes to $4,783. In
contrast, you would pay $4,203 in mortgage interest if you
maintained the mortgage. The upshot? You would be $580 ahead by not
paying off the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   But there's one additional wrinkle that you'll have to calculate
yourself. This involves the standard deduction that you would get
if you didn't itemize deductions. For tax year 1998, most people
who don't itemize will get a standard deduction of $4,250 if filing
singly, $6,250 filing as head of household, or $7,100 if married
filing jointly.
</P>
<P>
   If you did not have the mortgage interest deduction, would you
still benefit by itemizing deductions? If so, the arithmetic above
pertains. But if not, you'll have to calculate the net tax effect
of the prepayment after using the applicable standard deduction,
and it could be that the arithmetic would change.
</P>
<P>
   But even if that calculation brings the numbers closer, and even
if it means you'd even gain a small amount of money by prepaying,
there's one final factor you should consider.
</P>
<P>
   This is the additional financial flexibility that you would have
by retaining the savings and continuing to plug away at the
mortgage. It sounds as if you've got your financial planning pretty
well worked out, but why not retain that additional financial
security, providing the cost is small?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are both 54 and we hope to retire in six
months. Our combined pensions will amount to $42,000 annually. Mine
has a modest cost-of-living adjustment and my wife's does not. We
estimate our post-retirement annual requirements at $72,000, and
that I will earn $20,000 a year from part-time employment during
the first five years of retirement. At age 60, we would go into
full retirement, and at age 62 my wife would be eligible for $8,000
a year in Social Security benefits. We have a $750,000 portfolio of
which $200,000 is in taxable large-cap stock accounts and the
remainder is in tax-deferred accounts, all but 15 percent of which
is also invested in large-cap stock funds. The rest of the
tax-deferred accounts are in utilities, fixed accounts, and the
technology sector. What do you think of our plan?
</P>
<P>
   E.L., Orange, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It sounds to me as if you've got the world by the tail. Since
you'll need to draw only $10,000 a year from your savings during
the first five years of your retirement, you can simply divert
about $160,000 of your taxable holdings to fixed-income
investments.
</P>
<P>
   If you realized an average 6.5 percent from the fixed-income end
of the portfolio, that would supply the requisite $10,000 in yield
alone, and you wouldn't have to worry a great deal about
withdrawing principal against a sour market.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave you with $590,000 to continue growing during
those first five years of retirement. You might expect those
accounts to be worth about $867,000 by the time you enter full
retirement (based on 8 percent annual growth in that segment of the
portfolio).
</P>
<P>
   At that point (when you would be allowed to withdraw from the
tax-deferred accounts without penalty) you could divert half of
that pool, or roughly $433,500, from the stock investments to
fixed-income funds. This would bring your fixed-income yield up to
$38,177, giving you a total income stream of $80,177, plus whatever
cost-of-living adjustments have been made on your pension.
</P>
<P>
   With luck, those adjustments would be sufficient to bring the
total to $83,467, because that's the amount of money you would need
after five years to deliver the same buying power as $72,000 today,
based on an assumption of 3 percent average inflation.
</P>
<P>
   When your wife's Social Security kicks in two years later, you
could use part of it to bring you up to $88,550 (which continues
the ugly trail of that assumed inflation) and the balance . . .
well, a special vacation, a treat, or you could emulate the
grasshopper and shovel it into those stock accounts, providing more
insurance against inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But the point is, with the stock accounts amounting to $433,500
at age 60 and presumably continuing to grow as the years progress,
you should have a very, very handsome buffer against most of the
financial slings and arrows that life provides.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, I'm going to nag you about your lack of
diversification.
</P>
<P>
   I edited much of your list of investments, but it works out to
$82,500, or 11 percent of the total portfolio, that is invested
outside the large-cap stock sector. Even if you immediately moved
$160,000 into fixed-income securities as I suggest above, you would
still be too reliant on the large caps.
</P>
<P>
   The prescription is the usual one: Keep no more than 60 percent
of the stock portfolio in large caps, spreading the balance among
small- and mid-caps, international stocks, and sector funds.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite in the latter is the health-care sector; you already
have a relatively small position in a technology fund, and I like
that idea as well. Why not go with 10 percent each in small-cap
stocks, mid-cap stocks, and international stocks, and 5 percent
each in technology and health-care funds?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What do you recommend: term life insurance, or whole life? I
always thought that for young and healthy people, whole life is
best.
</P>
<P>
   A.S., West Hills, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm not an expert on life insurance, but I would provide this
general point of view: If you are a disciplined saver, over the
long haul you would almost certainly do better if you bought term
life insurance and at the same time invested the difference in cost
between term life and whole life in a conservative no-load stock
mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   But the key word here is disciplined. The advantage of whole
life over term life is that the former builds cash value _ whole
life is more expensive, but a portion of the premium goes into your
cash value account.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have the discipline to maintain a regular savings
program on your own, buying whole life insurance is a fairly
painless way to build your net worth, simply by paying your whole
life insurance premiums as they fall due.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, over the last 30 years or so dozens of different kinds
of hybrid life insurance policies have been developed, some of
which allow you to specify how your cash accumulation will be
invested. So it's now no longer a term vs. whole life debate. Me, I
still like term.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
