<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1819 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-WILSON-BOS &LR;      03-08 1519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-WILSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIAN WILSON'S GETTING GOOD VIBRATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ High in the Hollywood hills, tucked in a private,
gated neighborhood, lives Brian Wilson, the composer and child-like
spirit behind the Beach Boys. A white, contemporary Corvette sits
in the driveway of his impressive stone mansion, which sits across
the street from the fortresslike home of Shaquille O'Neal of the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just met him once,'' says Wilson, a devoted, stay-at-home
basketball viewer.
</P>
<P>
   Up the street is the home of rocker John Fogerty, though Wilson
doesn't see much of him, either.
</P>
<P>
   As the afternoon sun starts to set, Wilson, a noted recluse, is
tapping away at one of the three pianos in his ornately furnished,
antique-filled home. He has just finished a phone call, then dashed
to the piano to unwind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sort of glued to the piano,'' he says after a few minutes.
``I can't do anything without a piano. I have to be at a piano all
the time. It's something I have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Widely perceived as an eccentric genius, Wilson, 56, even has a
piano in his garage. He has never studied classical music (``except
for the `Switched-On Bach' album that I play now and then,'' he
says, laughing), but instead cites such pop influences as Phil
Spector, the Four Freshmen, Rosemary Clooney, and ``of course Chuck
Berry _ you can't forget him.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is very open about his emotional problems _ he's been
called an LSD casualty and reportedly suffered physical abuse as a
child _ but is heading out on a concert tour that stops at the
Berklee Performance Center June 21. (No ticket information is
available yet). The date was announced at a recent Berklee
function, but Wilson says he does not yet know of it. His wife,
Melinda, who coordinates his business affairs, says the show has
been booked, but that Brian is only told of the next three or four
dates in his schedule, so as not to worry him that the tour could
be too long.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson will be backed by the band the Wondermints, with possibly
a horn section added. He'll dip into songs from last year's solo
album, ``Imagination'' (which saw one tune cowritten with Jimmy
Buffett), but the bulk of the set will consist of Beach Boys hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are familiar with them and they're good tunes. I'm
proud of my tunes,'' says Wilson, sitting on a couch with a blanket
drawn across his legs. With his nervous, darting eyes, he looks
vulnerable, and he tends to answer questions with short, sometimes
awkward, replies. But he's also extremely polite and gives the
impression that he still loves music, even if he has a right to be
cynical, since his solo albums have sold much less than his Beach
Boys records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected my last solo album to sell a lot better than it
did. I don't know what to do. I'm just heartsick about it,'' Wilson
says. ``I was so hurt that it didn't sell, but dammit, maybe the
next one will.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next one, he says, ``Maybe we'll make a real rock 'n'
roll record if we can get up the nerve. More uptempo stuff, like
Phil Spector's things.''
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for his tour, Wilson has changed his diet to include
more vegetables and fruits (``I have to get off red meat pretty
soon'') and is doing a lot of walking to build stamina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get my life in a niche,'' he says. ``I walk on a
treadmill and I walk uphill in the neighborhood. I've been doing
that for three or four months now. I'm in pretty good shape. My
body is feeling strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my emotions are still tattered and screwed up,'' he adds.
``I've got a lot of screwed-up, mixed-up feelings about life. I
can't figure it out, so I just go and keep doing my exercises and
think, `This is good for me. This is good for me. Keep doing this.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's continued search for stability includes a new family.
He has two grown-up daughters (Carnie and Wendy were in the
early-'90s group Wilson Philips) from a previous marriage. He and
his new wife, Melinda, adopted two young girls, Daria and Delanie,
each 3 years old. They were running around the house as he spoke,
though each was with a nanny.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who is no longer involved with controversial therapist
Dr. Eugene Landy, has been seeing another psychiatrist weekly for
the past five years and uses two anti-depressants.
</P>
<P>
   Although known for having experimented with the hallucinogen LSD
in the '60s, Wilson now advises young people, ``Don't do that.
Don't take acid. . . . Acid shattered my head to pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   About his overall mental health, he says, ``I'm trying to figure
out when I was happy in my life, because I feel a little bit
confused at this time. . . . But things are better than they were a
few years ago. I was dumping (emotional baggage) real heavy back
then. But I'm getting through it. I'm getting through this last
phase of dumping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are going pretty well, except for the scared feelings
that I get. I get my fair dose of scareds. It's just something I
have to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   He termed his last album, ``Imagination,'' a record ``that can
heal emotional wounds.'' It featured a collaboration with former
Bostonian Andy Paley (with whom Wilson wrote another batch of songs
that may be released eventually) as well as the Buffett
collaboration, ``South American,'' about a man longing to chase his
dreams in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real experience to work with (Buffett), one I'll
remember for quite some time,'' says Wilson. ``He wrote the lyrics
to the song and sang on the record. He's a quick study. He's
good.''
</P>
<P>
   The album, which runs the gamut from the poignant ``Cry'' (a
ballad penned after a quarrel with Melinda) to the uplifting
``Happy Days'' (``my favorite song on the album,'' he says) also
contains the masterful vocal harmonies for which he is known. He
multi-tracked the lead vocals and harmonies many times to get the
trademark sound he first carved out with the Beach Boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very tedious. Oh boy, it was something else,'' he says.
``Every five seconds, I'm going, `Oh, I can't get these notes
right.' I'd stop the machine, roll it again, then stop again. As I
remember, there were some days that I never thought I'd get through
it and get the session done, but I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson remains blissfully unaware of most modern trends (``I
listen to oldies-but-goodies stations,'' he says) and is ``totally
out of touch with hip-hop.'' But his name keeps popping into the
spotlight _ most recently when the popular rock band Garbage won
his permission to use his Beach Boys lyric ``don't worry, baby'' in
one of their songs; and when the boxed set of the sessions for
``Pet Sounds'' (his most famous Beach Boys album and an
experimental precursor to the Beatles's ``Sgt. Pepper's Lonely
Hearts Club Band'') was nominated for a Grammy this year for best
historical album.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul McCartney sent me a message congratulating me for `Pet
Sounds' being nominated,'' says Wilson. ``I was really pumped up by
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is also pumped up by the thought of rejoining the Beach
Boys after his tour: ``I've had dreams about going back and
rejoining them _ of starting a brand new life and career.''
</P>
<P>
   He was shocked by the sudden death last year of younger brother
Carl (another Beach Boy founder), apologizing that ``Carl and I had
drifted apart. . . . We were close in 1966 when we did `Good
Vibrations,' but he and I later kept our distance from each other
for some crazy reason.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also had his ups and downs with Beach Boys singer Mike
Love, his cousin. Love successfully sued him three years ago,
claiming that he wrote a number of lyrics for Beach Boys songs for
which Brian got credit. Still, Wilson calls him a ``genius singer''
and someone he'd like to work with again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike got me good. I had to give him some money,'' says Wilson.
``But he deserved it. There are no hard feelings. Hard feelings
just drag you down at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BRIAN WILSON ON THE RECORD:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _On ``Pet Sounds,'' his 1966 masterpiece with the Beach Boys:
``When I hear it today, I say, `Oh my God, I did that? How could I
do that?' In your youth, you burn off a lot of energy and get down
to the nitty-gritty.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _On his influence: ``I run into people on the street and at
restaurants. They'll walk up to me and say, `Brian, you'll never
know what your music has meant to me.' It's such a pump-up, such a
great feeling. It makes me very proud that I've made someone
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _His favorite artists: ``I still like Paul McCartney. I think
his music is so good. And, of course, I mention Phil Spector at
least 100 times a day, thinking of his great records.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Top Ten hits by the Beach Boys (in chronological order):
``Surfin' U.S.A.,'' ``Surfer Girl,'' `Be True to Your School,''
``Fun, Fun, Fun,'' ``I Get Around,'' ``When I Grow Up (To Be a
Man),'' ``Dance, Dance, Dance,'' ``Help Me, Rhonda,'' ``California
Girls,'' ``Barbara Ann,'' ``Sloop John B,'' ``Good Vibrations,''
``Wouldn't It Be Nice,'' ``Rock and Roll Music,'' ``Kokomo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
