<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1820 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-LOCK-BOS &LR;      03-08 1401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LOCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIME AND COMEDY DO PAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the piquant vernacular of his native England, Guy Ritchie's
life these days ``is the nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   His first film, ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels,'' has
been the biggest thing to come out of his homeland since the Spice
Girls, recently nominated as best British film by the British
Academy of Film and Television Arts. It was also one of the few
films to emerge from this year's snow-capped Sundance Film Festival
with an avalanche of well-deserved hype.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie's gaudy filmmaking style and sharp ear for dialogue are
drawing favorable comparisons to Martin Scorsese and Quentin
Tarantino. And in the tabloids at home and abroad, he has been been
linked in lust _ which he strenuously denies _ with none other than
Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' said Ritchie with a smile, ``I suppose it's all
downhill from here, d'ya know what I mean?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels,'' which opens Friday, is
the 30-year-old filmmaker's swaggering debut. A London crime-caper
comedy, the film stars Jason Flemyng, Nick Moran, Jason Statham,
and Dexter Fletcher as a quartet of would-be players who get played
when Moran's card shark Eddie loses a rigged high-stakes poker game
against vicious underworld boss Hatchet Harry (P. H. Moriarty).
Eddie not only loses the 100,000 pounds raised by his buddies to
get him into the game, but finds himself 500,000 pounds in the hole
to Harry. Either the boys pay up within a week, or Harry's debt
collector, Big Chris (Vinnie Jones), will start removing fingers as
collateral. Singer Sting also has a featured role, as Eddie's
tough-as-nails bartender father.
</P>
<P>
   It's a slice of ``Mean Streets,'' seasoned with ``Reservoir
Dogs,'' plus a zesty dash of ``GoodFellas''; of course, movies
about witty, razor-tongued lowlifes will always draw such
parallels. But ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels,'' written and
directed by Ritchie, is as quintessentially British as royal
inbreeding. This is the England of soccer hooligans, the Krays, and
way too many pints hoisted in bloodied fists. Set in London's
ferocious East End, this is bare-knuckle Britian stripped of its
Merchant-Ivory manners and mores, revealing all the nasty little
things that happen behind the queen's back.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ritchie steered clear of turning his film into a bloodfest _
which is saying a lot, given that various folks are knocked off
with everything from car doors to sex toys to very noisy, very big
guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like gratuitous violence, and I didn't think we needed
it,'' Ritchie said. ``I don't like when people have to cover their
eyes and turn away from the screen; it's a nasty trick to pull on
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, his characters have a definite taste for violence, and
they're the sort of colorful thugs and mugs Ritchie and the film's
stars have known most of their lives. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bare-knuckle Britain &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``These are characters we've all met along in our travels, and
Guy decided to stick them in a film,'' said Statham, who plays
Bacon. He was recently in Boston, along with Ritchie and Flemyng,
to talk up the film. ``These are stories we've heard just by living
life in London. It's a pretty colorful place, and you're gonna meet
all kinds of blokes.''
</P>
<P>
   With his closely buzzed hair and voice like steel wool, Statham
is one of those blokes. He's new to this acting thing, having spent
a good chunk of his 31 years as a street huckster with an eye for
suckers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to sit on a crate with a suitcase full of jewelery and
perfume. That's a trade I've been involved in since I was 9 years
old,'' said Statham, who re-creates his former life in the film's
opening. ``That's how I put bread on the table. I'm not proud of
it, but I'm not unproud of it either.''
</P>
<P>
   Statham was not Ritchie's only unconventional casting choice.
For Big Chris, Ritchie got Vinnie Jones, a notorious British soccer
star who once chomped a journalist on the nose _ think Dennis
Rodman with a rap sheet. And for thick-necked Barry the Baptist,
named for his propensity for drowning his victims, Ritchie cast
Lenny McLean, a well-known British boxer. (McLean died last year,
and the film is dedicated to him.)
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie wanted his cast to create a ``perfect balance'' of
acting expertise and streetwise experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this movie, I wanted authenticity. I'm more interested in
him,'' he said, pointing at Statham, ``than your stereotypical
English thespian. In America, you have Al Pacino, who can play a
gangster, but it just doesn't work that way in the UK. You have to
have people that are from a working-class background and understand
that ethic. You pretty much have to hire gangsters to play
gangsters.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the blending of professionals and novices never undermined
the production, said Flemyng, who plays Tom. If anything, he said,
it added to the film set's loose ambience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people, when they're filming, think a serious set is
conducive to productive work and anything else is trivializing,
which is so not true,'' said Flemyng, 32, an established actor who
has appeared in such films as ``Alive and Kicking'' and ``Rob
Roy.'' ``If you're working out of joy, excitement, and fun, the
work reflects that. And that mood is set from the top down.''
</P>
<P>
   At the top was Ritchie, who admitted the film's crew had far
more experience than he himself. He always knew he wanted to make
feature films, even when he was spending his days directing what he
called ``crappy'' videos for German rave bands.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the UK, we don't have film school like films school over
here, so there's only one option, and that's videos. They're
basically short films and narrative-based. I did them for a year,
and I think it's important not to do them longer than a year,
because then you're only recognized as a video director.''
</P>
<P>
   With his video days in a rearview mirror, Ritchie is now
mentioned alongside Scorsese and Tarantino, even though he isn't
sure how to take such comparisons. ``It depends how they mean it,
doesn't it? If it's thought to be a derivative thing, then it's not
good; if it's `in the same arena as,' then it's much better. People
like to compartmentalize these things, and I understand that.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Not affected by Boyle &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But he scoffs at those who liken his film to Danny Boyle's edgy,
hilarious 1996 junkie opus, ``Trainspotting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's one thing I'm confident of it's that I had no
influence from `Trainspotting,' '' he said. ``As far as influence
goes, Tarantino has, Scorsese certainly has, the Coen brothers
have. But I'm not influenced by Danny Boyle's filmmaking techniques
in the slightest.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, like Boyle's film, ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking
Barrels'' was a small film that blew up with moviegoers. It cost a
measly $1.6 million, and has pulled in more than $20 million _ a
ransom by British standards, Ritchie said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came out in August in the UK, and it's done better than any
other English film this year,'' said Ritchie. ``Obviously, that
puts pressure on No. 2. To a degree, I didn't want too much stink
on the first one because then it seems like you can only slide on
the second film.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie has begun work on that second film, tentatively called
``Diamonds,'' a James Bond-esque thriller. He wanted to call it
``Helter Skelter,'' but thought audiences would confuse it with the
Vincent Bugliosi book, and 1976 TV miniseries, about the August
1969 murders by Charles Manson and his ragtag ``family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's a great name, and I've always loved the
track (by the Beatles),'' he said. ``I just think `Helter Skelter'
for the name of a film is the nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he can't get the film title he wants, Ritchie finally
has something he has never enjoyed before _ job security. Beyond
``Diamonds,'' he has guarantees for two more films. That means,
Ritchie says, he'll be drawing a salary for the next five years,
which isn't bad for a man who less than a year ago was so broke he
was resigned to ``kipping'' (that's ``sleeping'' to us Yanks) on
the floor of a friend's flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all been pretty gratifying, but after all the struggle,
it now seems like everything is happening very fast,'' Ritchie
said. ``But I'm not complaining. This is where I want to be. It's a
good thing, d'ya know what I mean?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
