u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SENATE-HNS &LR;      03-08 0356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON WOULD HAVE TOUGH RACE IN NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TADHG DOOLEY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ President Clinton is still popular among New
Yorkers, but First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton would not have a
free ride to the Senate is she decides to run for the seat being
vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan in 2000, according to a recent
Siena College poll.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, which surveyed 556 New Yorkers in February before the
televised Monica Lewinsky interview, revealed that President
Clinton's approval rating was still comfortably high at 68 percent.
However, only 43 percent of those polled approved of the first
lady's possible bid for a Senate seat in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   This was the most surprising result of the survey, said Thomas
O. Kelly II, codirector of the Siena Research Institute in Colonie,
N.Y., an Albany suburb.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this means is that she won't have a head start in the
race should she run,'' Kelly said. ``(The race) might not be quite
the cakewalk that supporters of Hillary Rodham Clinton believe.''
The poll's margin of error was plus or minus 4.2 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The First Lady has said she is considering a run for the Senate
seat, even though she is not a resident. New York City Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani is widely considered to be the frontrunner for the
Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also found that some of President Clinton's proposals,
such as investing some Social Security funds in the stock market,
were poorly received.
</P>
<P>
   On that issue, 61 percent disapproved of the president's plan,
while two thirds of the respondents favored the Republican
suggestion that people be allowed to manage a percentage of their
own Social Security accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But on Clinton's plan of using some of the federal surplus to
support Social Security, those polled backed the president.
</P>
<P>
   On a state level, 61 percent approved of the way New York Gov.
George Pataki was handling his job. This number is down from 74
percent in December, the first of the monthly polls taken by the
research institute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1321EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1823 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UGANDA-ANTI-US-BOS &LR;      03-08 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGANDA-ANTI-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAYING OF TOURISTS SHOWS ANTI-US SENTIMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ The killing of eight foreign tourists in Uganda
provides grim new evidence of rising hostility against Western
interests in a region fragmented by diverse and intertwined
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   The victims _ four Britons, two Americans, and two New
Zealanders _ were abducted and slain Monday in Bwindi National
Park, the forests that draw visitors hoping to see rare mountain
gorillas. Notes attached to their bodies read: ``Americans and
British, we don't want you on our land. You support the enemy.''
Hutu extremists are suspected.
</P>
<P>
   That enemy: Rwanda and Uganda, neighboring states entangled in
three overlapping African wars. Washington regards the two
countries as strategic allies.
</P>
<P>
   But Rwanda and Uganda are surrounded by nations and diverse
rebel militias that despise Rwanda's and Uganda's governments and
would prefer to see them overthrown. All blame Washington and
Britain for keeping the two states afloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is strong resentment for anybody with unquestionable
support for Uganda and Rwanda,'' said Jan van Eck, an expert on
Central African conflict at the University of Cape Town. ``The US
and Britain have become the enemy in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   That US policy in Africa could bring retaliation was made clear
by the bombs that ripped through American embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania last August. Such acts of terrorism were previously
unheard of in the region, and many African analysts believe the
attacks were sparked by Washington's stance against Sudan, which it
has branded as a sponsor of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The attack in Uganda last week, analysts say, reflects a
different strain of anti-American hostility. But the two attacks
may have a common denominator. Washington sends military and other
assistance to Uganda and Rwanda primarily to bolster them against
Sudan, which shares Uganda's northern border. That support is
unpopular in the region, particularly among displaced Rwandan Hutu
militias and at least seven African states that regard Uganda and
Rwanda as the aggressors in a seven-month war in the Democratic
Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
   The Hutu militias suspected of attacking the tourists in Uganda
belong to a group known as the Interahamwe. In 1994, these rebels
led a three-month spree in Rwanda that killed from 500,000 to a
million people, most of them ethnic Tutsi. When the Tutsi-led
military took power, the rebels fled to eastern Congo.
</P>
<P>
   The Interahamwe have launched cross-border attacks into Rwanda
and Uganda, whose president, Yoweri Museveni, they regard as the
main Tutsi sponsor. They are also suspected of carrying out attacks
against Westerners in retaliation for US support of the two states.
</P>
<P>
   The Hutu ``have seen the US as the bogeyman ever since the Tutsi
came to power,'' said Peter Rosenblum, director of Harvard
University's human rights program. ``They have been threatening
Americans and other Westerners in Rwanda ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 18, 1997, for example, four armed men suspected of being
Hutu rebels attacked a house in Uganda run by the aid agency
Doctors of the World. Three Spanish health workers were killed, and
an American, Nitin Madhav, was shot eight times and subsequently
lost his leg.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, abducted four foreign tourists and seven Congolese
guides were abducted during a gorilla trek in Uganda's Bwindi
National Park. Two Swedes and one New Zealander are still missing.
Hutu rebels are suspected.
</P>
<P>
   In the attack last week, 31 foreign tourists were abducted from
Bwindi early Monday, allegedly by Hutu rebels. The attackers took
14 of their captives on a long trek toward Congo, and killed eight
with clubs and machetes. The remaining six were released with a
message warning the West to stop supporting Rwanda's government.
</P>
<P>
   Ugandan officials, working with FBI officials who flew into the
country, launched a massive search into eastern Congo for the
abductors. Lieutenant Colonel Benon Biraro of the Ugandan Army said
Rwandan troops killed 15 rebels in Congo Wednesday. There was no
independent confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the Hutu threat, Rwanda and Uganda are embroiled in a
deepening multinational war in the middle of the African continent.
The two countries covet eastern Congo, across their borders, as a
security buffer against attacks by Hutu, Sudanese, and other
militia groups.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Rwanda and Uganda sponsored a rebel insurgency
against President Laurant Kabila of Congo. A handful of countries
rallied to Kabila's defense, and, once again, the countries now
fighting Rwanda and Uganda have deepening reasons to despise their
Western backers.
</P>
<P>
   During a tour of the region last year, Susan Rice, the US
assistant secretary of state for African Affairs, was repeatedly
rebuffed by one head of state after another. The Zimbabwean
president, Robert Mugabe, for example, made her wait outside his
office for hours before admitting her.
</P>
<P>
   Rice and her advisers ``were shaken by the response in a fair
number of African capitals,'' said Peter Takirumbudde, a Ugandan
director of the Africa program for Human Rights Watch. ``The
response was so hostile in Mozambique, Zimbabwe, Namibia, and
Angola.'' In backing Kabila in opposition to Rwanda and Uganda,
``those countries see the role they are playing in Congo as pay
back,'' Takirumbudde said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hutu make up 85 percent of the Rwandan population, Tutsis 14
percent. The Hutu struggle against Rwanda and Uganda is based on a
desire to regain power over a tiny ruling minority, backed by the
United States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   But some African leaders have more personal reasons. During his
tour of Africa last year, President Clinton praised the vision and
courage of Uganda's Museveni, who is seen in Washington as one of
the two or three most influential and promising African leaders.
</P>
<P>
   That makes Zimbabwe's Robert Mugabe furious. Having freed his
own country from white rule in 1980, Mugabe sees himself as a
father of African liberation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mugabe is very sensitive to any overshadowing,'' Van Eck said.
Mugabe backed Kabila, at least in part, because ``he sees Museveni
as attempting to build a Tutsi empire'' in eastern Congo, Van Eck
said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and Western diplomats are hesitant to read too much
into the latest attack on the tourists. Even if it fits into a
pattern of violent Hutu extremism, it is too soon to say whether it
indicates that that violence is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   But James Woods, a former senior US military adviser on Africa,
says it is cause for concern. ``There is a strong strain of
anti-Americanism in the Congo. They are asking, `Why are you
Americans doing this to us?' '' Woods said, referring to US backing
for Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
