<SLUG> BC-POCKET-ROCKETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN MAKERS THINK SMALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With 30 states now allowing concealed weapons, gun
makers, including Massachusetts' Smith &AMP; Wesson, are mounting a
major marketing effort to sell powerful new pistols that fit in the
palm of the hand.
</P>
<P>
   These ultracompacts are less than 7 inches long and can hold as
many as 10 large-caliber cartridges. They are being pitched by the
industry as ``Modern Mini-Mines,'' ``Stealth Weapons,'' and
``Glock's New Babies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have more killing power per ounce, per bullet, per buck,
than any other gun,'' said David Kairys, a Temple University law
professor and a researcher on gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of these ``pocket rockets'' is no coincidence,
according to the National Rifle Association, which credited its
successful drive for state concealed-weapons laws in the mid-1990s
with creating a new market for guns. Earlier models lacked the
firepower or were harder to conceal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Easy to conceal. Easy to Fire. Easy to acquire,'' says a
Beretta ad for its new Cougar pistol. ``Small in a very big way,''
reads the new ad for the Glock 26 and 27. ``Lighter. Completely
concealable. Plenty of fire power,'' it says.
</P>
<P>
   The latest ad from Smith &AMP; Wesson, which is based in
Springfield, highlights the new 9mm Chief's Special as smaller than
a cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   Recent government statistics show that the number of compact
weapons used in crimes almost tripling since 1995, a fact that
gun-control advocates say is likely to be used by cities such as
Boston that plan to sue gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The cities are expected to argue in court that these types of
pistols are part of an industry trend toward designing, marketing,
and selling weapons with bigger firepower and greater wounding
potential, according to academics and lawyers familiar with gun
industry litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guns incorporate all the features of enhanced lethality
that contributed to the upsurge of violence that began in the late
'80s,'' said Tom Diaz, author of ``Making a Killing: The Business
of Guns in America,'' and a former congressional staffer
specializing in gun-control issues.
</P>
<P>
   Requests for comment from Smith &AMP; Wesson were referred to trade
industry representatives. Other Northeast manufacturers of ``pocket
rockets'' are Connecticut-based Colt's Manufacturing Corp., and
SIGARMS of Exeter, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Painter, executive director of the National Shooting Sports
Foundation, said the gun industry is not making more-dangerous or
more-lethal guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like any industry, we are producing more-efficient products,
as all industries do when they develop new technologies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the smaller pistols would be attractive to criminals,
Painter said, that does not mean the industry targets that
population. ``It is one of the most absurd notions that any
industry would market a product to criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Feldman, president of American Shooting Sports Council,
another gun-industry trade group, said, ``It's not the
manufacturer's responsbility to keep guns out of the hands of
criminals, it's the responsiblity of the criminal justice system.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry literature reveals that the real boost in sales and
technological innovations that led to the small-pistol revolution
started three years ago when the NRA wrapped up a drive to pass
state ``right-to-carry'' laws, allowing gun owners to legally carry
a concealed weapon.
</P>
<P>
   According to the literature, these law changes across the nation
created an economic windfall for the industry at a time when sales
of hunting and sport-shooting guns were declining.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Interarms Inc., a handgun-marketing firm, called the
concealed weapon movement ``the most important star on the
horizon.'' It released a nationwide survey of dealers that found
more than 80 percent were selling more firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Shooting Industry magazine reported, ``The guns
that are selling during this sales trough in the industry'' are
because of the new concealed weapons laws.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA campaign continues, and legislation to allow concealed
weapons continues in many states, including Minnesota, Kansas, New
Mexico, Nebraska, Colorado, and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of compact pistols already are being tied to crime,
according to data from the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ATF does not categorize its statistics by gun size
or caliber, an analysis by the Violence Policy Center, a Washington
gun-control research group, showed that in 1995, 2,497 guns that
fit the definition of a ``pocket rocket'' were recovered by the
ATF.
</P>
<P>
   By 1997, that number had almost tripled, with 6,909 such weapons
traced to crimes. A total of 13,681 were traced to crimes between
1995 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Vince, former director of the ATF's gun-tracing unit who
runs a Maryland consulting group called Crime Gun Solutions, said
he believes the agency's figures are conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just beginning to see criminals gravitating toward these
weapons that are smaller and more powerful and easily
concealable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've done for criminals is increased their chance of
being more effective, of hitting their target and hitting it
repeatedly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
