<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATCHEZ-SCHOOL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUN AIMS TO SAVE MISSISSIPPI SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATCHEZ, Miss. _ Its thin-walled classrooms were put up to
educate ``Negroes'' at a time when emancipation was a
quarter-century old, but integration was still a dream deferred.
</P>
<P>
   As Holy Family School, it endured for decades, held together by
the firm love of its nuns, and now calls itself the oldest black
Catholic school in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   When the orders of nuns began to die out, the school hired lay
teachers and raised tuition. Yet the parents paid, despite their
poverty, despite the fact that most weren't Catholic, because even
after desegregation, Holy Family was still the best education in a
city that clung to its antebellum past.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years, the factories left, and with them, many
students. After 109 years, Holy Family faced its first real threat
of closing. Everything, it seemed, had left the school behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except the problems,'' says Sister Marie Santry.
</P>
<P>
   The problems, and Sister Marie.
</P>
<P>
   A compact bustle of gray hair and bright eyes, she arrived here
from Ipswich, Mass. 18 months ago because she asked the church to
send her where she was needed most. As much schmoozer and
saleswoman as nun, she has made it her mission as principal to save
this ramshackle success story, in steps however small. It was that
mission that brought her knocking at the door of Boston College
last summer, wondering whether that Catholic institution _ one of
the nation's wealthiest _ could help one so much less well-endowed.
</P>
<P>
   Two vanfuls of BC students arrived in early March, driving 48
hours straight to spend spring break here. They brought with them
$6,000 in donations. They put paint on walls that hadn't seen a
fresh coat in years, built a sandbox on a playground that is
otherwise a barren stretch of cement, repaired two sets of fallen
stairs. And they left having hatched plans to solicit more money,
schoolbooks and supplies, as well as to set up a scholarship fund
and an endowment to help pay back a $100,000 loan the school took
out to stave off closing last fall.
</P>
<P>
   As the uniformed Holy Family students, ages 2 to 12, watched
their visitors from the north sweep in with paintbrushes and
hammers, Sister Marie insisted that the BC students are her
school's best hope for survival. The BC students, and the families
here, marvel more at the miracle of Sister Marie.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the grounds _ the fact that people would send
their children here says something about the quality of the
education,'' said Jeanenne Angelini, a junior at BC's School of
Education. ``As far as teaching, it's the best school I've ever
seen. The teachers have such a rapport with the students.''
</P>
<P>
   The grounds have never been grand. The classrooms, serving 120
preschool to grade 6 pupils, are in three uninsulated halls behind
the faded facade of Holy Family Church, on a corner of Natchez far
removed from the town's exquisitely preserved Civil War-era
mansions.
</P>
<P>
   A staircase outside the kindergarten classroom had to be sealed
off with tape, so dilapidated that it can lead only to danger.
First- and second-graders learn in a dank basement. Upstairs,
bricks burst out of a crack in the wall outside the fifth and sixth
grades. In the library, the map and encyclopedias are dated 1949,
and in classrooms, teachers have carefully taped together torn
pages in books that were cast-offs. Teachers' salaries range from
$7,000 to $13,000, full time.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even the decorations seem defiant against decay. The
shutters outside a preschool classroom are so brightly yellow one
could almost miss the peeling paint on the walls behind. And each
year, city officials say, students continue to score higher on
standardized tests than those in the public schools. Its reputation
is such that some families have sent five and six generations to
Holy Family.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons of discipline and self-sufficiency start early.
</P>
<P>
   In a kindergarten classroom, Sister Carmen Molina, the only nun
beyond Sister Marie to still teach here, is leaning over a table of
students reading first-grade books.
</P>
<P>
   She gets up and pauses over students looking up words in the
dictionary to match photographs on the wall. Diandra Young, newly
6, stumbles sounding out ``exercise.'' Another student jumps in,
and Sister Carmen gently scolds, ``Children, you can't wait for
someone else to give you the answer. You have to sound it out
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is the best school in the city,'' says Charles
Toussaint, whose son is in kindergarten. ``I'll be reading a book
with him, I get ready to help him with a word, he knows it already.
That's the result of what the teachers are doing here. The kids
like learning. That tradition of studying carries on.''
</P>
<P>
   Legend has the seeds for Holy Family planted by a black porter
working the docks on the Mississippi when the first bishop of
Natchez arrived by steamer in 1841. Carrying his bags, the porter
asked the bishop to teach him to read.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop started a black school, but it closed during the
Civil War. Then in 1890, a Dutch priest brought three nuns from
Pennsylvania to help him start a new one. While the sisters went
door to door enrolling students, he went north looking for money to
build the school.
</P>
<P>
   Schools in Mississippi were still segregated until the 1960s.
This being the poorest state in the country, even white schools
were underfunded, and black schools even more so. Holy Family,
which was open to whites but remained all-black, became the school
parents wanted to send their children to, whether or not they were
Catholic. Today, 89 percent are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents send their children here because they know that the
students who come here are always the best students when they
leave. They're the ones that become the student leaders,'' says
Larry L. ``Butch'' Brown, mayor of Natchez for 8 years. ``This
ought to be the model for American early childhood education, it
could be the model. It's just woefully unfunded.''
</P>
<P>
   That was how Sister Marie found it when she arrived in August
1997. The basic problem was the same as in many Catholic schools
today: not enough young women entering religious orders. The
Sisters of the Holy Spirit, who staffed Holy Family for 80 years,
have begun to die off, and are stretched thin to attend to as many
schools as possible. Holy Family was down to three nuns teaching in
1996, and now one. Lay teachers require salaries, and that means
higher tuition, which is currently $1,700 a year.
</P>
<P>
   But in Natchez, the problems are complicated by the local
economy. Several paper and rubber factories have closed during the
past few years, and last year, Mayor Brown says, the town took a
hit when Fidelity Tire laid off 400 people. The town's biggest
industry is now the tourists strolling the verandas of the
antebellum homes.
</P>
<P>
   By last year, several students could no longer pay tuitions and
left. Others moved with their families toward better jobs. Then
there were problems particular to the school, such as the tax
bills. When the school hired lay teachers, it had to pay payroll
taxes. ``The way (the parents) saw it, they could pay the taxes or
they could pay the teachers,'' said the priest at Holy Family
Church, Father John Tyne. ``They thought it was more important to
pay the teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Marie arrived from her native Ipswich, having returned
from a mission in Japan, and immediately set about fixing the books
as well as the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old enough to be too old to ask,'' as she describes herself,
she slams her hip to open doors stuck in the humidity, and briskly
straightens the curtains she bought at Wal-Mart (``just to freshen
things up for the children.'').
</P>
<P>
   She fixed the tax problem, borrowing $100,000 from the Josephite
order that runs Holy Family Church to pay the bill. The IRS, she
said, forgave the penalty portion of the bill, deciding there was
no malfeasance intended. (``Faith moves mountains and the IRS,''
she says, smiling.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The teachers do such wonderful work here, and without this,
the students won't have the same opportunities,'' she says.
Ideally, she would like to do more than recruit paying students;
she would like to have scholarships. ``I don't want to have to turn
away any student.''
</P>
<P>
   She has used her world connections to get donations of all
sizes: $700 from a family in Japan who had heard about her travails
from a nun who came to visit here, another $200 from a Navy base
where she once worked in Hawaii. And when she went to BC for a
principal's leadership training, she asked whether anyone there
could help. BC sent her to the School of Education, where the
students jumped to the challenge. Forty-two applied to make the
trip, and 20 were chosen.
</P>
<P>
   The week at Holy Family provided them lessons, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have a lot, but what they have they make so much
of,'' says Natalie Corrigan, a junior from New Jersey. ``In my
elementary school, there was always a storage closet full of
supplies. They don't have storage closets here.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home, the students have started a campaign to allow
students to contribute points on their meal cards toward helping
Holy Family. They have gotten donations from potluck suppers, and
from soliciting parents.
</P>
<P>
   At Holy Family, one preschool classroom sits empty, a reminder
that it still can't afford the teachers it needs. And without those
students coming in, some parents and teachers fear the school won't
have enough students to feed the higher grades.
</P>
<P>
   Others, though, have watched Holy Family triumph before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really in tough financial shape,'' says Joyce Trask, who
came here after 30 years in the public schools. ``But every time we
get in a tight spot, we have some sort of blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, it might be in the form of a tiny nun and her 20
young helpers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
