<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW UNDERMINED MOST BY STARR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there is anything Republicans have learned, it's that a vote
to extend the soon-to-expire independent counsel law is also a vote
of confidence for the person who turned the law into a big
political liability for the GOP: Kenneth W. Starr.
</P>
<P>
   And the last thing Republicans need is to be perceived as a
supporter of the man with the lowest favorability rating of any
public figure involved in the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Starr arguably did more damage to the Republican Party than to
Clinton by taking the virtually unlimited independent counsel's
mandate so far beyond previous self-imposed boundaries that it
represented a modern-day Inquisition, one that spawned more terror
than justice.
</P>
<P>
   If not for Starr's massive misuse and abuse of the law during a
five-year investigation that began with Whitewater and degenerated
into a stained blue dress, five Republicans might not have lost
their seats in the House of Representatives last November, two GOP
House speakers might not have been forced to resign, and some
Republicans might not have had certain aspects of their private
lives exposed.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Republicans and Democrats have been holding joint
press conferences and issuing joint statements saying the
independent counsel law, due to expire at the end of June, should
not be renewed _ in any form.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, some Republicans ostensibly tried to separate Starr
from the law, defending his actions while condemning the law for
not remaining apolitical _ as if that were its fault. Indeed, it
was Starr's misuse of the OIC that has cost the law its political
support.
</P>
<P>
   There's no need to explain why most Democrats, including the
Clinton administration, are opposed to the same law they backed for
renewal the last time around. While US Attorney General Janet Reno,
who approved more independent counsels for investigations than any
of her predecessors, is currently silent on the issue, President
Clinton knows that opposing the law has the approval of the
electorate. He need not worry about a public backlash if he agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the public apparently views Starr's out-of-control
exploitation of the law as more of a threat to the nation than the
shameful, reckless, adulterous affair Clinton had with Monica S.
Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Republicans, there are basically two reasons so many
of them oppose the law so strongly.
</P>
<P>
   One is that they were hurt by the political fallout from Starr's
report, which was the basis of the GOP-led impeachment campaign
against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Second is that the Republicans know that the Democrats, when it
is their turn to control Congress, could use the independent
counsel against them in the same way Starr used it against Clinton,
Hillary Rodham Clinton, and their friends, associates, and
appointees.
</P>
<P>
   While there are some members of both parties who favor amending
or modifying the law rather than ending it, that possibility has
grown increasingly remote. With so many different ideas likely to
emerge during debates over changes, it is more likely that a
congressional debate could break down along party lines, creating
yet another schism between the Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest, and perhaps wisest, approach to the law is to
simply allow it to expire without much debate or fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, ending this law would be a quiet but fitting way to
bury a sad and shameful chapter in our history. Perhaps that is
what members of both parties have in mind _ a short, brief ceremony
to note its death and move on to the business of the American
people.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move would send Starr a message that both parties, as
well as the nation's populace, want him to disappear as quietly as
they expect the independent counsel law to disappear. But if he
continues his obsessive pursuit of the Clintons _ amid rumors that
he might still consider seeking indictments against them _ Starr's
fall could be harder than any other Republican who sought to bring
down the president.
</P>
<P>
   Current investigations of possible criminal violations by the
OIC could easily escalate if Starr continues his pursuit of the
Clintons and their associates.
</P>
<P>
   As the GOP House and Senate members found out, there is very
little public support for such partisan use of taxpayers' money.
And there is even less public support for a man who humiliated the
nation before the rest of the world as he helped to lead a failed
Republican movement to bring down a president the GOP could not
defeat at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, with the burial of this ugly law, a more efficient,
nonpolitical law to investigate high-level allegations might arise.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Starr's prosecutorial career, and the law he abused,
is relegated to history, there is that hope.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
