<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERS-TELECOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAITHFUL CUSTOMERS DEMANDING BETTER DEALS _ AND GETTING THEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After aggressively pursuing new customers with perks and
discounts, telecommunications and credit card companies are waking
up to the cry of loyal customers who say they're being taken for
granted and want some of these special deals.
</P>
<P>
   Faithful customers say they are being treated as fools and they
are lighting up company phone lines and clogging e-mail files after
hearing about neighbors and colleagues getting $100 ``win-back''
checks, free cell phones and low introductory credit card rates
just for being new _ not old _ customers.
</P>
<P>
   And while the extravaganza of deals has created a new breed of
fickle consumer, who jumps from one deal to the next, loyal
customers can't help but feel slightly ripped off even as they
grumble that all these bargain-hunters ought to get a life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bread and butter customers are finding out about these
deals,'' said Susan Fournier, associate professor of marketing at
the Harvard Business School. ``And they start to feel alienated and
aggravated.''
</P>
<P>
   Fournier said she was miffed four months ago when she discovered
a friend was getting AT&AMP;T's long-distance plan of a dime a minute
with no monthly charge for the first six months. She was paying $5
a month for the same 10 cents a minute plan.
</P>
<P>
   She got on the phone with AT&AMP;T and demanded, ``I want the same
deal or I'm outta here.'' (She got it.)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed some companies are starting to respond, especially as
they feel more secure in the marketplace. Bell Atlantic Mobile last
year started offering longtime wireless customers the same
promotions, such as free off-peak calling time, as new recruits.
</P>
<P>
   In its new emphasis on rewarding loyalty, John Palmer, marketing
director for Bell Atlantic's Northeast region, said longtime
customers are also being given greater benefits, such as two months
of free voice-activated calling. New customers get one month of
that perk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to take the risk that our customers are looking
for other deals,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   In a program like the airlines' frequent-flyer programs, AT&AMP;T
plans this spring to debut a new loyalty rewards offer that will
cut across all of its long-distance, local, Internet and wireless
services, said marketing director Vincent Raguseo. Loyal customers
will get financial perks for their longevity with the company and
for the amount of their usage in different services.
</P>
<P>
   Raguseo said AT&AMP;T heard loud and clear from loyal customers who
weren't happy about being ignored. He said the company itself
wasn't pleased about the chronic switchers or ``churners,'' as they
are known in the telecommunications world.
</P>
<P>
   One of the country's largest credit card issuers, First USA,
based in Wilmington, Del., began offering in the past couple years
special cards for long-term cardholders who are jazz enthusiasts,
bicyclists or scuba divers.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Unkle, spokesman for First USA, said members received
discount tickets and hobby newsletters. In the next year, he said,
the company hopes to unveil other new loyalty programs to reduce
the number of ``rate-hoppers'' who jump from one low-introductory
teaser rate to another.
</P>
<P>
   The howl of the loyal customer isn't usually heard in business
world, said many marketing specialists. In the past, companies
assumed, often accurately, that most people were too lazy to
switch.
</P>
<P>
   Also, consumers in generations past were less aware of what
their neighbor was paying for the same product or service,
according to marketing executives. They didn't live in today's
information-saturated environment where the news media and Internet
offer many price comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Bund, senior lecturer at the Sloan School of Management
at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, who specializes in
marketing, said there is a new respect for the ``good buyer'' who
knows how to research information for monetary advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's culturally acceptable to talk about, even admirable, to
talk about how smart a shopper you are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   John Deighton, a marketing professor at the Harvard Business
School, agreed that consumers are more knowledgeable about the
marketplace and companies realize they can't just bank on inertia
to keep a customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies need to use price to retain customers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially so in industries such as long-distance or
cellular phones, where switching is so easy. It's not like Internet
or cable services, where switching means you get a new e-mail
address or wait for a visit from an installer.
</P>
<P>
   James Levine, a retired engineer, said he had always heard about
bargain-hunting in the telecommunications world, mostly from a
colleague who got about $130 in checks within two years after
switching back and forth between AT&AMP;T and MCI.
</P>
<P>
   Levine got into the deal-hunting game with his new cell phone.
After getting a free phone with a one-year contract with Bell
Atlantic Mobile last year, he shopped around and found a better
deal with Cellular One at $9.95 a month. Cellular One also offered
him $50 to switch. Bell Atlantic Mobile couldn't match the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Levine believes, however, that marketers are making a mistake if
they don't start thinking about ``loyal-customer presents.'' He
said customers like him will always be hunting for the best deal.
When his cell phone contract expires in June, he'll be on the phone
with competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it's fun,'' he confessed. ``You actually haggle.
It's a game. It's a marvelous game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1840 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SATELLITE2-BOS &LR;      03-08 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SATELLITE2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ROCKET SCIENCE AT BU'S PHYSICS LAB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MAC DANIEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Daniel Cotton, a 34-year-old assistant research professor at
Boston University, is coming down with something. His shirt is
wrinkled, his tie is askew, and he's coughing.
</P>
<P>
   His mind, however, is not on his health. It's pondering his
satellite. With a few short weeks to launch day, Cotton said
space-based nightmares are keeping him awake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dream about the launch and see it tip over and go out of the
control,'' he said of the satellite, which currently sits in a
locked room at Boston University's Center for Space Physics. ``On
launch day, it's either going to be fat and happy or there's going
to be something wrong. And that's all I really think about.''
</P>
<P>
   About 4 1/2 years ago, Cotton came up with a novel idea, a means
of surveying the earth's ionosphere and thermosphere in three
dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   It was an experiment that could help advance solar-terrestrial
studies and provide a better understanding of space weather, as
well as the ionosphere and the thermosphere, the ever-changing
outer layers of atmosphere that play large roles in ground-based
communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like going from an X-ray to a CAT scan,'' said Cotton.
``We'll be seeking far more detail.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the only reasonable means to perform such research
was through suborbital rocket launches, packages that returned to
earth after 10 minutes of flight, snatching small amounts of data
from the skies. An orbital satellite would be perfect, but
prohibitively expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton and other BU officials knew this, and consequently timed
their proposal to jibe with NASA's announcement of a new program to
provide money to have universities build, test and operate
inexpensive scientific satellites.
</P>
<P>
   It was precedent-setting news at BU when Cotton's proposal,
co-written with his peers at BU's Center For Space Physics, won
approval from NASA. But then came the hard part. They had to
actually build the device that, up to then, was just an idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was a huge task,'' said Cotton, whose passion is
tweaked more by research than the wonkish detail involved in
building a satellite. ``Here I am, a research scientist, and I was
suddenly in charge of getting a space bus built.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the TERRIERS satellite (Tomographic Experiment using
Radiative Recombinative Ionospheric EUV and Radio Sources) sits on
the fifth floor of a Boston University building on Commonwealth
Avenue. Stored in a ``clean room'' to avoid instrument
contamination by dust or hand oils, it is being tested and readied
for liftoff on April 7 from California's Vandenberg Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   Downstairs, where Steely Dan songs are playing and a picture of
the Star Wars character Yoda adorns the computer, is the
satellite's command center. The mission commander is 23-year-old
Janine Lyn, and the room is often packed with a select group of
physics or astronomy students who came to BU never thinking they'd
have a chance to play such vital roles in a major space research
program _ let alone to operate a satellite.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guidance counselor said to me during summer orientation:
Would you rather flip burgers at the student union or control a
satellite?'' said Emily Lyman, a 19-year-old freshman from Albany,
N.Y. ``I chose the satellite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an amazing experience for a freshman year,'' said Jeremy
Coombs, 18, a freshman from New Britain, Conn. ``It's awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   The program would have been unheard of just a few years ago.
Students rarely got involved in such expensive projects. But
through NASA's Universities Space Research Association _ which
hopes to demonstrate that successful satellites can be built
cheaply and differently _ the dream for students like Lyman and
Coombs has become reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some students started at zero,'' Cotton said. ``It's a
completely student-run project.''
</P>
<P>
   BU officials said the program is already a success, even though
the satellite is still on the ground. With the awarding of the
TERRIERS satellite grant, the university built the research tools
while an outside contractor built the ``bus,'' the satellite
vehicle on which the experiments will be carried.
</P>
<P>
   And while all of BU's instrument package came in under budget
and on time, the contractor that made the satellite was both late
and over budget.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of BU's satellite project is about $4 million. If this
had been contracted more traditionally, the project could have been
10 to 20 times more expensive, according to Dr. Supriya
Chakrabarti, an associate professor of astronomy at BU and co-head
of the TERRIERS program with Cotton. BU was the primary contractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the program first began, colleagues had said that for $4
million all you cold build were toys,'' said Chakrabarti. ``So now
we've proved them wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But the crux of the program _ and the real worry _ has yet to
begin. In 1996, when an Ariane 5 rocket blew up seconds after
liftoff, 10 years of work by researchers at the University of New
Hampshire blew up with it.
</P>
<P>
   The TERRIERS satellite will be sent out to California later this
month in a huge purple container. It will be launched much like a
guided missile from an aircraft at 50,000 feet. Launch is scheduled
for 8 p.m. Pacific time on April 7.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, the satellite will orient itself to the sun,
begin charging its batteries and start feeding data back to a BU
rooftop. And Prof. Cotton may finally get some rest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1332EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
