<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
60 MINUTES OF SHAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Make no mistake: Edward R. Murrow, Fred Friendly and Dick Salant
are dead _ and spinning.
</P>
<P>
   If you tuned in to CBS Sunday night you saw the squandered
legacy of newsmen who used television to bring depth and texture to
the most difficult issues of our times. The McCarthy hearings.
Migrant workers. Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   If you watched ``60 Minutes'' you saw just how high a price CBS
News was willing to pay, in journalistic integrity and human
decency, to score a larger market share.
</P>
<P>
   Watch Mike Wallace interview Louise Woodward if you must, but
understand what you are seeing: This is not a serious inquiry into
the violent death of 8-month-old Matthew Eappen. This is a cheap
skirmish in the networks' rating war.
</P>
<P>
   ABC gets the presidential mistress; CBS hits back with the
killer nanny. Barbara Walters scores Monica; Mike Wallace snags
Louise. The infamous get their platform; the shameless get their
exclusive. And broadcast news courts blindness from yet another
journalistic black eye.
</P>
<P>
   There is no longer a pretense that these ``interviews'' are
designed as anything other than marketing tools for TV shows
addicted to celebrity, earned and unearned. Viewers knew what they
were watching Wednesday night was not news; it was pre-packaged
entertainment, the promotional kickoff for a quickie book to let
Monica and the media bottom-feeders cash in.
</P>
<P>
   People tuned in, not because they expected Barbara Walters to
elicit news. They tuned in because they knew she'd elicit tears.
When the cameras stopped rolling, Monica offered Barbara one of the
scarves she now knits in her spare time; Barbara offered Monica a
slot on the vacuous chat show she now co-hosts in her spare time. A
fair exchange: one piece of fluff for another.
</P>
<P>
   But Louise Woodward is not Monica Lewinsky. She is a felon, not
a flake. She did not leave a tawdry mess in her wake; she left a
tiny coffin. A new haircut and a new round of teary denials will
not alter the fact that a jury convicted her of killing an infant
in her care.
</P>
<P>
   ``60 Minutes'' would have viewers believe that it operates on a
higher journalistic plane than TV news magazines that stage gas
tank explosions. To slap a veneer of newsworthiness on its
interview with Woodward, CBS hides behind a ``new'' opinion of the
cause of Matty's death on Feb. 9, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that this theory is offered by a doctor who came no
closer to the case than some medical records provided by ``60
Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the conclusion that Matty died of strangulation,
not a fractured skull and shaken baby syndrome, is unsupported by
any testimony at trial. Not from Matty's treating physicians. Not
from the medical examiner. Not from medical experts called by
prosecution or defense.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Floyd Gilles of Children's Hospital in Los Angeles is
entitled to hold any opinion he likes about the evidence against
Louise Woodward. Or O.J. Simpson. Or Julius and Ethel Rosenberg,
for that matter. But what makes his opinion worthy of our attention
more than two years after Matthew Eappen was laid to rest, more
than one year after Louise Woodward was convicted in his death,
more than one month after she settled a wrongful death suit?
</P>
<P>
   What makes his speculations any more newsworthy than the vile
assertion by one of Woodward's lawyers a while back that the
``evidence'' did not rule out Brendan Eappen, age 2 at the time of
his brother's death, as the killer?
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when CBS and Mike Wallace were better than
this. He did not make his reputation, as Walters and Diane Sawyer
did, wringing confessions out of leggy blondes. (Walters on
``20/20'' asking Donna Rice where she had sex with Gary Hart:
``What everybody wants to know, of course, is, Donna, whether it
was aboard the yacht, the Monkey Business?'' Sawyer on ``Prime Time
Live'' asking Marla Maples about Donald Trump: ``Was it the best
sex you've ever had?'')
</P>
<P>
   Wallace admits to being 79. Don Hewitt, ``60 Minutes'' executive
producer, is 76. Is this really how they want to wind up their
careers, inflicting pain on a family that, after more than two
years in the spotlight, is still capable of being shocked by what
passes for journalism in America?
</P>
<P>
   The Eappens should know there's no statute of limitations on
this stuff. Last week _ I kid you not _ Diane Sawyer interviewed
the women who killed for Charlie Manson _ 30 years after the
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1336EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
