<HEADER>
A1851 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-TEENS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     03-08 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TEENS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... innocence now.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rimes is one of the lucky ones who seem destined, on the
strength of very real talent, to make a grown-up career in the
music business. The vast majority of teen sensations are being
groomed to make someone a fast buck as the flavor of the week.
Trans Continental, the Orlando. Fla., teen hit factory that's
turned out the Backstreet Boys, 'N Sync, and Britney Spears, has
four new and very familiar-sounding pop acts coming through the
mill: Lyte Funky Ones, C Note, Take 5, and Innosense.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning we took it real seriously,'' says Kid David
Corey, program director at KISS-108 FM, of the teen pop acts. ``Now
I react differently, hearing the fifth, sixth group. C Note sounds
just like the Backstreet Boys. BWitched sounds just like the Spice
Girls. These artists are so producer-driven _ they sing and dance
well, but it takes more than that to have a career. I give it
another six to eight months.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright has now worked with two consecutive waves of teen
musicians, and he believes there will continue to be a market for
teen acts. ``There's a new crop of kids _ 7-, 8-, and 9-year-olds _
who are too young for Backstreet Boys, and they'll need music of
their own. And it's so supported by parents. We had a gansta-rap
situation, with killings, and a lot of negativity. Hard rock was
in. There was a cry in America for more positive images. Pop radio
is finally pop again. And parents are giving their kids more money
to buy records and go to concerts.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Greater expectations &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The problem facing the slew of up-and-coming performers, Wright
says, is that the bar has been raised so high. ``Backstreet Boys
have sold 10 million records, and 'N Sync has done 7 million. Based
on those numbers, a lot of the majors are going to say, `If you're
not doing that kind of business, we're not going to continue to
fund you.' Plus, a traveling entourage for a young act _ with
tutors, chaperones, etc. _ involves 15, 16 people. There are vocal
coaches and choreographers. It can be very expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   So, paradoxically, time is not on the young star's side. Neither
are the statistics for enduring success, or emotional well-being.
When, at the height of the New Kids' success, Joey McIntyre saw his
face on a toy marble rolling down the hall, he was scared to death:
``It felt prophetic. It felt like that was my proverbial head
getting cut off.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, in psychologist Berglas's view, is that the
young stars ultimately begin to see themselves _ and their value _
as a product, not a person. And the only way to circumnavigate
these psychological pitfalls, in Berglas's experience, is
``subordination of the ego to a greater good. Real religious
involvement, or real community involvement. Family. There's a
religious and familial asterisk that seems to keep people
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the advantage of a strong, supportive family, it has
taken McIntyre years to reclaim his identity. ``I was so anxious,''
he says. ``I had no idea why I was doing anything. Did I want to be
famous, back on top again? Did I want to get love that way? Then I
finally relaxed, and let it be. That kind of patience gave me the
energy to get what I needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Patience, however, is not a defining feature of youth. Spears is
fretting over the time lost while she's been recuperating. ``After
I make up for all the stuff I've missed _ I had a talk-show
performance in London every day, and we had to cancel everything _
I'll come back to the US.'' There's a video to finish. And then ``I
start my own tour in July,'' says Spears, who's been on the road
opening for 'N Sync. ``I'm really, really excited about that! Then
after that I'll start a new record.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Spears finds time, she says, to attend church every
Sunday, and is planning a slumber party with her friends before
jetting off to Europe. At the suggestion that she seems to be
keeping her feet on the ground amid the sudden onslaught of fame,
Spears says ``Oh, yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   And then she adds, ``But call me a year from now.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT'S NEW IN TEEN ACTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the new teen acts are clearly created in the
market-tested image of Britney, 'N Sync, and the Backstreet Boys;
some seem poised to break the mold. Release dates are all subject
to change. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Moffats &QL; 
Age: Triplets Bob, Clint, and Dave are 14; big brother Scott is 15 &QL; 
Sound: Modern country-pop &QL; 
Album: ``Chapter One: A New Beginning,'' June 1 &QL; 
 &QL; 
