<HEADER>
A1860 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-SWEENEY-BOS &LR;      03-08 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SWEENEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAYING AFLOAT IN A SEA OF SORROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If &UR;  &LR; the old Yiddish saying _ ``If you want to make God laugh,
tell him your plans'' _ is true, then Julia Sweeney must have made
the heavens rumble with gales of guffaws a few years ago. It was
1994, and Sweeney, newly divorced and still smarting from the
critical and commercial bludgeoning of her first film, ``It's
Pat,'' had just moved into a new Los Angeles home.
</P>
<P>
   Then her younger brother Mike was diagnosed with lymphoma. With
no insurance and his health deteriorating, he moved in with
Sweeney. Her parents then left their Spokane, Wash., home, and also
moved in with Sweeney to help take care of Mike. And if coping as a
thirtysomething suddenly invaded by her parents, and the
devastating decline of her beloved brother, weren't enough, three
weeks before Mike's death Sweeney herself was diagonosed with
cervical cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Humor kept Sweeney afloat in this sea of sorrow, and the wry,
poignant observations about the most difficult year of her life
became an acclaimed one-woman show, ``God Said `Ha!' '' _ the title
of which was inspired by that Yiddish adage. Her performance, which
played for six weeks on Broadway, is now a film, which opens
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people ask me if the show helped me get over it, I say,
`No, it didn't, it didn't help at all, it had nothing to do with
it, it's completely separate,' '' said Sweeney with mock shrillness
during a Boston visit last fall. ``But in a way it did; I took this
sad experience, and this is what I made it into. Yet in some ways,
it's still going on, so it's not like it ever really came to an
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, I resist saying it's been cathartic,'' she said. ``I
don't like people who do stuff because it's cathartic to them. I
don't want to be like Suzanne Somers starring in my own life
story.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Sweeney, ``God Said `Ha!' '' was created
``organically.'' Shortly before learning of her brother's illness,
Sweeney was invited by her friend Kathy Griffin (of TV's ``Suddenly
Susan'') to join an alternative comedy group. ``We had to tell
stories for 15 minutes, the stories had to be true, and it had to
be the first time you used it as material,'' she recalled. ``It
didn't have to be recent, but you couldn't know where the jokes
were, and it couldn't have the rhythm of stand-up. It was like
group therapy with really funny people doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   After her brother and parents moved in, Sweeney would slip off
to the group and perform. At first, she wouldn't discuss the
details of her life, because she ``didn't want to bring the
audience down.'' But as the pressures at home began to mount,
Sweeney found she couldn't avoid talking about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't give a (expletive) anymore,'' she said. ``I
needed to get up there and rant. My parents didn't even know where
I was going.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Genesis of a show &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her performance became such a rave, Sweeney put together a
45-minute tape as a showcase for television casting directors. With
the encouragement of friends, Sweeney turned the performance into a
one-woman stage show. After her brother's death, the show premiered
in San Francisco to enthusiastic reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got into show business because I saw Lily Tomlin'' do her
one-woman show, ``The Search for Signs of Intelligent Life in the
Universe,'' Sweeney, 39, said. ``So I always wanted to do something
like that. I just never thought I would just talk as myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of talking about herself meant talking about her parents,
Bob and Jeri Sweeney, and how their presence in her home thoroughly
disrupted her life. That included her mother's controlling
tendencies, and her father's drinking. But Sweeney assumed her
parents would never find out about the show _ until a review of her
performance found its way to Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently, a bunch of their friends had moved to San
Francisco, so that's how they found out about it,'' said the
refreshingly pleasant Sweeney with a laugh. ``They didn't hear it
from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Her parents soon booked a flight to San Francisco to see the
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was having heart attacks that day,'' Sweeney said. ``I kept
thinking I had to work myself into this big, `You know, this is my
art, and I can't worry about hurting your feelings because this is
what I have to say, and in the end, it's more important for me to
express myself than worry about hurting your feelings.' That's what
I really believe as an artist and writer, but who wants to say that
to their parents?''
</P>
<P>
   Before the show, she took them to dinner and read parts of the
performance she thought might offend them. When her mother finally
said, ``You know, we can handle a lot,'' Sweeney said their
reaction became ``one of the best parts of this whole story. They
just wanted me to do well. My mom would even make jokes like,
`Well, I'm going to put together my own one-woman show.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney's brother died in April 1995, at 31. But her
performance, and now the film, have helped to keep him alive, she
said. He is present in her performance, including his quip after
her diagnosis that Sweeney had a case of ``sympathy cancer.'' After
several surgeries and radiation treatments, Sweeney said, she is
now cancer-free.
</P>
<P>
   Yet looking back on her experience, Sweeney wishes she had
spoken more about her own ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel emotionally that much about my cancer until this
last year. My cancer experience was so colored by Mike's cancer
experience that I never got to feel sorry for myself, or say, `Oh,
that was (expletive) for me,' '' she said. ``At the time, all I
could think was how it wasn't nearly as bad as what Mike had to go
through. So I think I sound too flip about my cancer, just a
little. I just wish I had a couple less jokes about it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
`The kid thing' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She also wished she addressed ``the kid thing.'' Her surgeries,
which included a hysterectomy, left her unable to have children.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time I didn't have anything where I needed to have a
biological kid. But now I wish I could just be pregnant. I feel
like I'm missing this really important life experience for women,
this `real woman experience' that I don't get to have,'' she said.
``It's not like I'm really down about it, but I just wish in the
show I had addressed that. It would have been OK to let that be
sad. I think that was part of my defense then, that I wouldn't let
myself let that be sad.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sweeney conducted this interview, she was still reeling
from the loss of her longtime friend Phil Hartman, the actor and
fellow ``Saturday Night Live'' alum who was shot to death last May
by his wife, Brynn, who then killed herself. Hartman, who had been
Sweeney's mentor since their days with the famed LA comedy troupe
the Groundlings, helped Sweeney deal with her brother's death and
her own illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still talk about Phil all the time. He was really a big part
of my life, a really important person in my life,'' she said. ``My
boyfriend, Carl, said to me that in the last year, we'd spent the
Fourth of July, Labor Day, Thanksgiving, New Year's Eve, and Easter
with the Hartmans. Their kids played with my boyfriend's son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I still can't believe it, I just can't believe it.
It's still like, `What?' '' Sweeney said. ``I can't make sense of
it. I think I'll just still be figuring it out for the rest of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartman is casually mentioned in the film when Sweeney frets
about finding something polite to say about his 1994 comedy,
``Houseguest,'' which she hated.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I thought about it, I felt bad because I say something
derogatory about `Houseguest,' '' Sweeney said. ``But you know
what? Phil thought `Houseguest' was bad, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
