<SLUG> BC-TV-STRAGNE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STRANGE WORLD' SEEMS QUITE FAMILIAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
STRANGE WORLD 
Starring: Tim Guinee, Vivian Wu, Krisin Lehman 
On: ABC, four-week Tuesday run Tuesday at 10 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someone ought to produce a TV show called ``The Xerox-Files.''
At its center would be a Hollywood renegade, gloomy and handsome,
whose obsessive mission in life is to investigate ``criminal abuses
of script cloning.'' In his heart, this laconic hero would know
that behind every ``Friends'' rip-off, behind every blue-lit cop
show with blurry moral lines, behind every office ensemble sitcom
set at a media outlet, there is a conspiracy, a massive and demonic
plot by a syndicate of entertainment honchos, to make the public
believe they actually have imagination. He would even have in his
possession taped evidence of the abduction of the muse and papers
that verify a bankruptcy of inspiration. But, steeped in the
mellow, decaf-latte-soaked world of Southern California, our secret
agent would be only a green pawn in their green game, a helpless
jump-roper in a Lala land of bottom lines.
</P>
<P>
   Cloning _ of people, not of TV series concepts _ is actually one
of the themes of ``Strange World,'' a dreary new ABC series that
aspires to be another ``X-Files.'' The show, which premiered Monday
night at 10, is a shameless Attempt by former ``X-Files'' producer
Howard Gordon to replicate his hugely successful Fox
science-fiction series. It's a ponderous hour filled with portent,
paranoia, and muddy political intrigue, and it contains enough dim
lighting and rainfall to give you a prolonged case of Seasonal
Affective Disorder. And it also has its very own version of
Cigarette Smoking Man, a magically elusive and mysteriously
powerful person whom we know only as Asian Woman.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Strange World'' plot turns around Paul Turner, a former
Army scientist employed by some shady military officials to look
into ``criminal abuses of science.'' Those investigations will
comprise the episode-by-episode story lines, but then, in true
``X-Files'' fashion, there will be an ongoing conspiracy drama
about Turner himself. During the Gulf War, he was exposed to
chemical weapons that have left him with an unnamed degenerative
disease involving anemia and skin lesions. His only hope is a
miracle drug, supplied to him on a dose-by-dose basis by Asian
Woman and her syndicate of Enigmatic People. We can only wait,
probably, in the manner of ``The X-Files,'' until the 12th of
Never, to find out who ``they'' are and why ``they'' have their eye
on Turner.
</P>
<P>
   As Turner, Tim Guinee is perfectly gaunt, haunted, and unshaven,
giving his drug-dependent character a tinge of junkie affect. He
looks like a pained Michael J. Fox after a year on the streets, and
you may find yourself wishing him some fast relief. ``There is a
reason you were chosen,'' Asian Woman tells him, but only the most
patient viewers will want to stick around to learn what it is. The
fate of ``Strange World'' is uncertain, once ``NYPD Blue'' returns
in April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1348EST &QL; 
