<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1867 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-GOD-BOS &LR;      03-08 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWSING IN THE NEW RELIGIOUS MARKETPLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
WORKING ON GOD 
By Winifred Gallagher 
Random House, 340 pp., $24.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This rich and intelligent book treads on some very familiar
ground. The idea that material success doesn't necessarily add up
to personal happiness has become a recurring theme in the
cornucopia of books about America's yearning for spiritual
fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   But Winifred Gallagher, a New York-based writer struggling to
find her own spiritual niche, leads us on an intimate and revealing
pilgrimage into America's restless soul. The result is an honest
and sometimes poignant appraisal of a religious revolution afoot in
this country.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher comes up with a useful term to describe a population
of spiritual seekers who aren't always found inside the
neighborhood church, synagogue, or mosque: neoagnostics.
</P>
<P>
   As Gallager explains at the beginning of ``Waiting on God,''
these people ``are well-educated skeptics who have inexplicable
metaphysical feelings. They regard religion as belief in the
unbelievable. Yet they sense something important that eludes their
most trusted tools of intellect and learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Science and technolgy, which we are led to believe can
eventually provide the answers to most (if not all) of our
problems, have left us further disconnected and alienated. The age
of reason has not quieted our clamoring souls. And at the end of
the day, as Gallagher skillfully chronicles, a hefty paycheck, a
late-model luxury sedan, even our families aren't enough to
eliminate the gnawing sense of emptiness that has come to
characterize the lives of many comfortable Americans.
</P>
<P>
   This sense of societal anomie has fueled a spiritual crusade
that extends in many directions: to Buddhist retreat centers, to
healing services in Christian churches, and to contemporary Shabbat
services in synagogues. It is a quest for meaning that is often
messy, often complex, and very hard to define.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neoagnostics are America's most subdued, neglected religious
group, yet they are one of its most powerful,'' Gallagher writes.
``They are everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   What Gallagher does very well is document how a vast slice of
America is no longer interested in or willing to be bound by
institutions, creeds, or family tradition. They want experiences
that touch them to the core. Meanwhile, she notes, the religious
services in many houses of worship have become rote, dull, and
lifeless.
</P>
<P>
   While Gallagher's childhood religion was Roman Catholicism, she
also finds comfort in a Zen monastery, a conservative Jewish
synagogue, and a liberal Episcopal congregation. Though clergy in
the pulpit may not like it, this type of blending or layering of
religion is rapidly becoming a central hallmark of our nation's
religious landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``In religion as in politics, scholarship and the arts,
sophisticated citizens of a global society no longer look to a
single source for all the good ideas, much less Truth,'' Gallagher
shrewdly notes.
</P>
<P>
   America's growing diversity _ with immigrants from Asia, Africa,
and Latin America _ has brought with it a dizzying array of faith
experiences and created a huge religious marketplace in which many
Americans are eager to browse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than being a complete worldview or infallible arbiter
of right and wrong, each tradition has become a `toolbox,' ''
Gallagher writes. ``A person roots through a chest labeled
`Christianity' or `Judaism,' or even `Catholic' or `Orthodox,'
ignores the elements that don't seem significant or `right' _
perhaps second-class status for outsiders _ and uses the ones that
do _ sacraments, say, or keeping kosher.
</P>
<P>
   ``With them people build up-to-date, customized religious
structures that, like a renovated Victorian house or a brand-new
log cabin, retain the oomph of tradition. Other individuals borrow
elements from an Asian faith, or from the new `theologies'
developed by women, say, or gay people.''
</P>
<P>
   The one shortcoming of Gallagher's otherwise fine effort to
cover this postmodern spirituality is that in the rush to show the
eclectic nature of today's spiritual journeys she occasionally
bounces from topic to topic so quickly she loses the reader. In a
few breathless paragraphs, we're sailing with the spiritual leader
of the world's Orthodox Christians on the Black Sea, listening to
renowned Harvard sociobiologist E. O. Wilson preach in New York,
and hearing the challenges facing the founder of a bank for the
poor in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   We're left trying to catch our breath. But that's just a minor
quibble in an outstanding piece of writing that shows the strength
and beauty of America's beating religious heart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
