<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1868 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-WORRIES-BOS &LR;      03-08 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-WORRIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I'M OK, YOU'RE OK, Y2K? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The message, it seems, is everywhere. A sign outside a church
asks, ``Are you ready for Y2K or the Rapture?'' The past week's
newspapers were full of warnings from US Senator Robert Bennett, a
Utah Republican, that the Y2K issue ``exposes the vulnerability of
nearly every major sector of the economy.'' And The Drudge Report
recently posted the screaming headline: ``Americans Urged to Stock
Up Before Y2K Strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   The century-flip computer problem that could conceivably wreak
havoc on everything from our banking system to Russia's nuclear
arsenal clearly has us worried. In a recent survey by the Media
Studies Center, 53 percent of the respondents said Y2K is one of
the most important issues facing the country. A smaller study
released by Dr. Michelle Weil and Dr. Larry Rosen, coauthors of the
book ``TechnoStress,'' indicated widespread fear about the safety
of credit cards and bank accounts as our sophisticated, high-tech
nation battles the bug. It's might versus byte.
</P>
<P>
   But is that all there is to the Y2K scare? Or has the computer
bug become a convenient catchall for channeling our free-floating
anxiety about the unknown? Is it a manageable, even face-saving way
for a modern people to express their most primitive fears about the
future?
</P>
<P>
   Y2K is the ``first apocalyptic prediction in history (in which
we know) that something will happen on that date,'' says Stephen
O'Leary, an associate professor of communications at the University
of Southern California. ``It becomes the perfect blank slate on
which to project our millennial fears.''
</P>
<P>
   The mental health industry is already gearing up to deal with
Y2K. Jerilyn Ross, president of the Anxiety Disorders Association
of America, says, ``People are uncomfortable with change and the
unknown,'' and those ``who are normally anxious people are going to
have heightened sensitivity and anxiety.'' Carol Goldberg, a
clinical psychologist who focuses on stress management, concurs,
saying, ``People may project some of their anxieties and fears and
blame Y2K as a scapegoat.''
</P>
<P>
   At a January public forum on Y2K held in New York City, one
speaker rose to propound the socially acceptable view of the issue.
``I don't think Y2K is a religious problem,'' she declared. ``It is
a technological problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet at the same forum _ sponsored by the Media Studies Center _
the very first citizen speaker sounded less than cooly rational.
She asserted that if everyone withdrew $3,000 from their savings
accounts, ``The banks would all go under, and the people are not
being told that. . . . Nobody knows what's going on with anything.
Out of town, they've already stocked up with money, food, water.''
</P>
<P>
   That same brand of fear _ ostensibly rooted in a computer
dilemma, but tinged with a more fundamentalist panic _
characterizes a substantial amount of the Y2K alarm. It's obvious
in the the words of Y2K analyst Gary North, who counsels on his Web
site that Y2K ``may be the biggest problem that the modern world
has ever faced. I think it is.''
</P>
<P>
   It's embedded in the advice of Jim Lord, a retired Navy officer
and software engineer whose survival recommendations include
everything from buying gold to leaving population centers. Whatever
it is that he envisions people running from, it's bigger than a
computer bug.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had in the last 40 or 50 years a number of events which
have provided support for an apocalyptic worldview by shifting the
evidentiary base for the apocalyptic argument,'' says O'Leary,
citing the founding of the state of Israel, the development of
nuclear weapons, and growing environmental fears. Now, he says, Y2K
``is kind of the classic. . . . They're secularizing that religious
fear by focusing on the computer panic as the trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Landes, a history professor at Boston University, is the
director of the Center For Millennial Studies, which was founded in
1996. ``One of the things that motivated us to start the center
(is) that there is nothing more important to anyone alive than what
the future is,'' says Landes. He believes ``a fairly high level of
concern is appropriate,'' in the case of Y2K. Yet, he characterizes
some of the fear as ``a modern secular version of religious stuff
that some of us think happened around the year 1000.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Quinby, the author of ``Millennial Seduction: A Skeptic
Confronts Apocalyptic Culture,'' says Y2K is a fitting millenn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1351EST &QL; 
