<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1872 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-TEENS-2TAKES-BO     03-08 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TEENS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW KIDS ON THE CLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It began, like all fads, without much fanfare. Several years
ago, teenage singers began trickling onto the pop music scene. A
Brandy album here. A Fiona Apple record there. Then, in 1997,
Hanson opened the floodgates with the astonishing success of
``MMMBop.'' In the last 12 months the trickle has become a
full-blown gush, as the latest wave of teen musicians crests in a
massive pop music trend.
</P>
<P>
   Five of last week's Top 10 singles on the Hot 100 Billboard
charts are by teen artists _ R &AMP; B singer Monica; pop sensation
Britney Spears; a pair of harmonizing quintets, Backstreet Boys and
'N Sync; and the R &AMP; B singer/TV star Brandy. On the R &AMP; B charts,
19-year-old Foxy Brown was in the No. 2 position, just behind
Lauryn Hill. Even classical music has two new teen stars:
12-year-old Welsh singer Charlotte Church and 19-year-old violin
prodigy Hilary Hahn.
</P>
<P>
   We're watching the latest teen-idol craze, and if history is any
indication, the window of opportunity is a small one. The mad dash
to cash in on the phenomenon is in full stride, and music-industry
suits are out to break the next Britney or 'N Sync before the trend
reaches its inevitable saturation point. At least a dozen
major-label debut albums by under-20 performers are slated for
release in the coming months (see accompanying story). The small
percentage with genuine talent may make the transition from teen
sensation to adult artist; most of the wannabes will have a
painfully brief shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they sustain careers or bottom out fast, all of them
will have to deal with the unique challenges of achieving stardom
at a tender age. Ogled, handled, insulated, and rich, teen stars
grow up outside conventional reality and everyday experience. And
according to both the experts and the historical record _ remember
Tanya Tucker? or Leif Garrett? _ well as some of the underage icons
themselves, the social and emotional fallout can be debilatating.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting perky atop the latest teen-dream heap is 17-year-old
Britney Spears, a button-cute veteran of the new-defunct Mickey
Mouse Club television show (as are two members of 'N Sync and Keri
Russell of TV's ``Felicity''). Spears's album of funky-lite
dance-pop, ``. . . Baby One More Time,'' and its first single
debuted at No. 1 on Billboard's album and single charts
simultaneously; that's a first for a new artist. Five weeks later
the album, which has posted record-breaking sales gains each week,
was still at No. 1. The single was just last week bumped out of the
top spot _ by 18-year-old Brandy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have worked so hard and have totally dreamed of this,''
Spears says on the phone from home in Kentwood, La., where she's
nursing a twisted knee. ``I'm like, God has totally blessed me.''
These two weeks at home to recuperate are a godsend as well, says
Spears, a polite, bubbly teen who peppers her conversation with
``Yes, ma'am'' and ``No ma'am.'' Normally Jive, her record label,
lets her come home for a visit every six weeks. ``I've slept and
slept and slept. When I'm on the road, no matter where I was, I'd
wake up early and do phoners (telephone interviews),'' Spears says,
when asked to describe a typical day. ``In London, I'd do TV show
after TV show and interview after interview. I eat lunch in the van
while someone's doing my hair. At night, I'd come in and sleep from
around 2 to 6. They could work me to death and I wouldn't say
anything. But I was like, `Y'all, I get delirious if I don't get 10
hours.' I was feeling really sick. I finally said, `Look, I need to
rest more.' So they're gonna give me a day here and there to
rest.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pleasing the starmakers &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spears seems happy to put in the long hours required to fuel the
starmaking machinery _ after all, girls who dress up to look like
you and boys who scrawl prom invitations on their bare chests make
for powerfully flattering stuff. Not to mention the thrill of
capping a trip to Jack-in-the-Box with a stop at Cartier.
</P>
<P>
   But the suddenly and massively successful teenager pays a price,
according to Harvard Medical School psychologist Steven Berglas.
``The young stars are totally amazed at themselves,'' says Berglas,
whose books include ``The Success Syndrome: Hitting Bottom When You
Reach the Top'' and who has worked with prominent rock bands,
models, and executives. ``They're kids. They have no idea where
their power comes from. There's not a sense of self-esteem
predicated on picking yourself up and dusting yourself off, as the
song goes. Success that is hard-won is rewarding, but success that
appears to be an act of God is frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the fact that these youngsters are cultivated by
those closest to them for public consumption, says Berglas, and
you've got a recipe for disaster. ``They walk into an interview and
have their hair pushed, they're told to walk that way, to change
their clothes, their look,'' Berglas says. ``They become observers
of themselves. It's not a comforting experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Former New Kid on the Block Joey McIntyre, who just released his
first post-Kids solo album, concurs. ``The ride up was great, but
once you're there it's crazy,'' says the 26-year-old McIntyre, who
was 15 when the Boston-based New Kids became global superstars.
``It gets so big. Everybody's tugging at you and you want to be
everything to everyone. Everybody's telling you, and you're even
telling yourself, that it's a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity. But
part of me just wanted to have a regular life. I couldn't wait to
get out on the corner and hang out.''
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre credits strong family ties, especially consistent
parenting, with keeping him grounded. Johnny Wright, who manages
Britney Spears and 'N Sync and was tour manager for the New Kids,
has seen it go both ways. ``Back in the New Kids days it wasn't
bad,'' Wright says on the phone from Orlando (a Cape Cod native,
Wright moved south five years ago). ``We had a `friends bus' that
came out with us, and family came out on the road, too. So even
though they didn't go to the prom and football games, they were
surrounded. It's the same with 'N Sync. But I've seen situations
where teens start making money and the parents simply stop being
parents. They become friends. They stop saying no, because they
don't want to stop the money flow.''
</P>
<P>
   And what of actual friends? Spears says she ``doesn't really
have time to meet anybody. It's kind of good because I'm so busy.''
She did have a boyfriend, she explains, ``but it just didn't work
out with me traveling. I'm not good on the phone. I don't know . .
.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
More fame, less love &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The more popular you are, paradoxically, the less affection
can break through,'' Berglas explains. ``The hardest thing for the
star to discern is `do they love me for what I am?' In a way, the
feeling of human connection is destroyed by having this universal
appeal. It's hard to forge a relationship.'' That complex
psychological dynamic is compounded by the simple logistical
restrictions of being a performer on the road _ where teens have
tutors rather than attending school, and a busload of grown-up
handlers instead of classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen-year-old country singer LeAnn Rimes, who recorded her
first record when she was 11, left public school in sixth grade.
She's just now beginning to look back. ``I'm really just learning
to make friends,'' says Rimes on the phone from Los Angeles, where
she's recently begun work on a new record. Rimes was 14 when her
album ``Blue'' debuted at No. 1 on the country charts. ``For the
last few years I was around the same group of people _ my band, my
mom and dad. It was great. They were my best friends. But I'm not
the same as a normal 16-year-old. I feel 30. I'm trying to get back
some of that innocence now.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
