   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The N.Y. Times plans three pages of stories in connection with
the death of Joe DiMaggio:
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-DIMAGGIO (Undated) _ Joe DiMaggio, the flawless center
fielder for the New York Yankees who, along with Babe Ruth and
Mickey Mantle, symbolized the team's dynastic greatness across the
20th century and whose 56-game hitting streak in 1941 made him an
instant and indelible American folk hero, has died. By Joseph
Durso. (3500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved)
</P>
<P>
   Plus OBIT-DIMAGGIO-ABRIDGED (1250 words)
</P>
<P>
   (Moved)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-DIMAGGIO-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times: For years,
Joe DiMaggio had fresh flowers placed at Marilyn Monroe's grave;
now he has taken her memory to his grave. During the baseball
memorabilia boom, he sold himself as an icon for the millions of
dollars he never made as a player, but he never sold his memories
of the Hollywood goddess he was married to for 274 days. By Dave
Anderson. (750 words)
</P>
<P>
   (Moved)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-DIMAGGIO-STREAK (Undated) _ Remembering the color and drama
of DiMaggio's 1941 streak of hitting safely in 56 straight games.
By Murray Chass. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   (Moved)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-DIMAGGIO-YANKS (New York) _ Reaction from current Yankees.
By Buster Olney. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-DIMAGGIO-OLDSTERS (Undated) _ Reaction from former players.
By Jack Curry. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   DIMAGGIO-HOMETOWN (San Francisco) _ When Joe Dimaggio went home
to San Francisco he went to North Beach and kept quiet with old
friends. If he stepped out of the old neighborhood, he had to face
being Joe Demaggio again. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   For other sports, see the separate BC-SPORTS-NYT-BUDGET.
