<P>
   SALVADOR-FLORES (San Salvador) _ A man-in-the-news profile:
Francisco Flores, the ``moderate'' rightist who will be El
Salvador's next president and who invoked death-squad leader
Roberto d'Aubuisson at victory rally. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-TERROR (Paris) _ A French anti-terrorism court put six
high-ranking Libyan officials on trial in absentia today on charges
of ordering the bombing of a French DC-10 that killed 171 people in
1989. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-BIHAR (New Delhi) _ The Indian government, facing defeat
in upper house of Parliament, reverses its decision to take over
violence-plagued Bihar state. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ With circuit courts split on immigration,
and thousands of cases bulging the federal court system, the
Supreme Court declines the opportunity to interpret the 1996
immigration law. The cases they avoid taking raised statutory and
constitutional questions. Other high court action. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-PRIVATIZE (Washington) _ Liberal constituency groups like
labor unions, women's groups and black organizations are gearing up
for a big grass-roots campaign to keep Social Security from being
privatized. But while the ostensible target of their efforts is
Republicans, they are just as worried about being sold out by the
Clinton administration in the name of bipartisan compromise. By
Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   STARR-RENO (Washington) _ Kenneth Starr, the independent
counsel, and Attorney General Janet Reno file briefs with the
judges who appointed him, on the question of whether she has the
right to investigate him. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-EDUC (Washington) _ The Senate finally votes on
education bills, while Majority Leader Trent Lott conducts a town
meeting in Chester, Pa., to prove Republican Party's commitment to
schools and learning. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ILL-PROSECUTORS-CHARGED (Chicago) _ In what is believed to be
the first time ever, prosecutors will be put on trial for felony
conspiracy, obstruction of justice, faking and withholding
evidence. Three well-respected prosecutors _ one is now a judge _
and four sheriff's officers will go on trial Tuesday in a wealthy
suburban Chicago. The case in which they are accused of doing this
involves two people who were convicted and sentenced to death row
for 1983 murder of 9-year-old-girl. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   MO-EXECUTE (Kansas City, Mo.) _ A month after bowing to a plea
from the pope and commuting the death sentence of a confessed
triple killer, Gov. Mel Carnahan of Missouri faces the clemency
petition of a condemned man who has submitted to a lie detector
test to buttress his claim of innocence. By Shirley Christian.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-PRIZE (Undated) _ The Intel prizes (formerly Westinghouse)
for high school seniors are announced. By William H. Honan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Intel reaches an agreement with
staff lawyers at the Federal Trade Commission that would settle the
antitrust charges against the chip maker. Developing. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   CITIGROUP-DIMON (New York) _ Jamie Dimon, former Citigroup
president, received a severance package with an estimated value of
at least $30 million on the condition that he agree to restrictions
of as long as three years on his ability to lure Citigroup staff to
work for him at any new employer. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   CIT-NEWCOURT (Undated) _ CIT Group, which makes consumer and
business loans, purchases Newcourt Credit for $4.2 billion in
stock, paying a per-share premium of nearly 10 percent. By Timothy
L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   WASTE-BROWNING (Undated) _ More about the acquisition of
Browning-Ferris by Allied Waste. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   FORTIS-AMERICAN (Undated) _ Fortis buys American Bankers
Insurance Group for $2.6 billion in cash, plus $194 million in debt
assumption, making the Dutch-Belgian financial company one of the
biggest insurers of consumer and credit-card loans in the United
States. Under the terms of the deal, which is the latest
acquisition in this country by a European insurance company, Fortis
is paying $55 a share, 19 percent above American Bankers' closing
price Friday. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Rio de Janeiro) _ Details of the IMF's agreement
with Brazil, including new targets for spending limits. By Larry
Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   SIEMENS-INTERNET (Undated) _ As expected, Siemens buys two
manufacturers of Internet equipment, Argon Networks and Castle
Networks, and will take a stake in a third, Accelerated Network. By
Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks are mixed, with technology shares
rising, and bonds are higher following Friday's sharp gains. At
midday, the industrial average was down 10 points, or 0.1 percent,
and the Nasdaq index was up 32 points, or 1.4 percent. Elsewhere,
prices fell 0.8 percent in Tokyo and rose 0.2 percent in Hong Kong.
They declined 1.2 percent in Frankfurt and increased 0.2 percent in
London. Shares were up half a percent in both Brazil and Mexico. On
the American debt market, the long bond was up 14/32 point, with
the yield at 5.57 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
