<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1888 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VAIL-TRAVAIL-LADN     03-08 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VAIL-TRAVAIL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAIL STRUGGLES THROUGH A DOWN YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Note use of italics in graf 4. HAS ART)  
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ Like most of Colorado's ski resorts, Vail fidgeted
nervously through the first two months of the winter season.
Because of the peculiar La Nina effect, storms slammed California's
Sierra Nevada but left the Rocky Mountains high, dry and relatively
free of snow.
</P>
<P>
   When the snowstorms finally began to arrive with regularity in
January _ light dustings, not the powder dumps common to the
Rockies _ Vail knew it would be fighting an uphill battle on
perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   There's 5 feet of snow at Vail? How could that possibly stack up
to the 15 feet at Lake Tahoe or the 13 feet at Mammoth? Why even
leave California?
</P>
<P>
   But Vail officials feel they can build a strong case for
consideration. It's based on their effort in recent years to
broaden the appeal of the ski area, one of the most popular in
Colorado. (BEGIN ITALICS)Yes, there may not be six inches of new
powder out there every other day, but the skiing is still very
good, and are you aware of everything else there is to do out
there?(END ITALICS)
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that people were taking fewer vacations and spending
more time in one destination,'' Vail Resorts spokeswoman Chelsea
Stewart said of recent surveys conducted by the company. ``They
were also bringing more family members. We tried to create more
options, so if Grandma comes along to watch the little one, there's
something for her to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe so, but if you can talk Grandma into sprawling onto
an inner tube for a precipitous plunge down a banked sledding run,
you're one persuasive soul.
</P>
<P>
   The tubing run is one of the more popular attractions at
Adventure Ridge, a play park in a reasonably flat area at the top
of Vail's gondola lift. On a recent Sunday afternoon, it teemed
with activity _ skiers accounting for only a small portion of it.
</P>
<P>
   In a relatively confined area, there is an ice-skating rink,
guided snowmobile tours, laser tag, rentals of snowshoes and snow
bikes, and a racetrack for miniature snowmobiles. Students in ski
and snowboard school tumble this way and that, their equipment
often a hopeless tangle.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the tubes.
</P>
<P>
   On a steep hill, several runs have been laid out, each with
banked sides like a bobsled track. Vail officials said they had a
lot of visitors asking about sledding opportunities in the area.
This attraction, in its third year, was the response to that.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most bothersome aspect of sliding down a
snow-covered hill on any device is having to lug it back to the
top. That issue is addressed here by a cable tow that latches onto
a strap and tugs each tube to the top of the run.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, it's not unusual for first-timers to balk at
plunging off the edge until a few more tubers have slid safely to
the bottom, offering evidence that mayhem is not imminent. Personal
experience attests to the fact that those tubes fly down that face,
but beyond the initial terror, the primary effect is a peeling off
of years. On this particular afternoon, in fact, dads and moms
seemed to be racing their little ones to the cable tow for another
go at it.
</P>
<P>
   Vail keeps the area at the top of the gondola open until 11 p.m.
_ and then provides ample reasons to be there. One restaurant,
sponsored by Kendall Jackson wines, offers dinner on white
tablecloths with wait service _ a refreshing break from the
cafeteria monotony of most on-mountain eateries. Another
establishment, sponsored by Baileys, serves as kind of an adult
warming hut. Outside, near the ice-skating rink, a giant fire pit
blazes.
</P>
<P>
   There is a sun deck _ which features live entertainment most
afternoons _ a bar, a pizza joint and an evening buffet. And for
those revelers who can't quite leave the office entirely behind,
there is even a business center with access to e-mail, faxes,
teleconferencing and other modern-day intrusions.
</P>
<P>
   A nonski gondola pass costs $15 daily ($10 for children under
12), but there is no charge to ride to the top after 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Vail's mind-boggling array of alternatives to skiing
itself, skiers and snowboarders don't exactly get short shrift. The
mountain here is really more like a broad ridge. There are runs
down the front, down the west side and even off the back, where
advanced skiers can negotiate one of eight bowls. The entire layout
covers 4,644 acres and features 174 trails.
</P>
<P>
   Another Vail strategy has been an aggressive targeting of the
international market. Resort officials report that foreign visitors
to the company's four major properties (Vail, Breckenridge, Beaver
Creek, Keystone) represented 15 percent of last year's lift-ticket
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Vail and Beaver Creek played host to the 1999 World Alpine
Skiing Championships _ Europe's winter-sports Super Bowl _ in early
February. That meant the presence of ABC's cameras, ESPN's cameras
and a media contingent that numbered in the quadruple digits. The
overseas TV market alone was estimated at a half-billion people.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the benefit is not immediately felt, Vail stands ready
to greet the international ski vacationer. Its ski and snowboard
school offers instruction in more than 30 languages, including
Croatian and Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   The layout of this area is attractive, too. Although Vail does
hug I-70 (detractors in more secluded resorts refer to it as ``A
Freeway Runs Through It''), the long, narrow strip of village
between the interstate and the base of the mountain has plenty of
charm.
</P>
<P>
   Most of it was laid out in a European mountain theme, with
narrow, winding streets along which stand small eateries, bars,
shops and galleries. Gore Creek babbles down the middle. But
perhaps the most appealing feature is the lack of cars: Most of the
streets are designated for pedestrians only, and a free shuttle
transports visitors along the edge of the village.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether these attributes and Vail's broad range
of winter-sports offerings have been sufficient to attract visitors
in customary numbers this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Vail Resorts' Paul Witt said business was off about 7 percent at
the end of December. He could not provide figures for subsequent
attendance; the company is privately held, Witt said, and only
reveals such numbers quarterly.
</P>
<P>
   It is his sense, however, that Vail has rebounded from the blahs
of early season. ``Certainly, the world championships were
extremely successful for us,'' Witt said, ``and the new snow always
draws more people to the slopes.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as people find out about it.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Jacob of the Vail Valley Tourism and Convention Bureau
said of the perceptions battle: ``It's hard for us because people
all want it to be a dump every day. Unfortunately, Mother Nature
doesn't work that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent mild storms _ usually dropping two or three inches at
a time _ have generated good conditions, even though the snow
levels have been lagging about 5 percent to 10 percent below
normal.
</P>
<P>
   At least one recent event helped perk up spirits around here. On
the first day of the world championships, a race had to be
postponed ... because snow was falling so heavily.
</P>
<P>
   Fate has been known to have an impeccable sense of timing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
