A1890 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-08 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK WITH UNDERGROUND CAVES REOPENS IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Can you imagine exploring a park where you
actually go underground? Actually walking 400 feet into a hole that
has been bored miles into the Earth?
</P>
<P>
   With the opportunity to explore another half dozen cave-like
tunnels?
</P>
<P>
   The tunnel trails at Black Diamond Mines Regional Preserve
reopened last weekend. It is like no other park in the San
Francisco Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   This adventure has been off-limits for nearly 10 years, since
the Loma Prieta earthquake of October 1989, which damaged the
tunnels. That damage has been repaired and the mines have passed
recent inspections, offering visitors an adventure at one of the
bay area's most unusual destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Black Diamond is located in the Mount Diablo foothills near
Antioch, but no matter where you live, this getaway is worth
checking out, and one that you will never forget (especially if
your flashlight goes out).
</P>
<P>
   Historically, this was the largest coal mining area in
California, hence the name ``Black Diamond.'' The park is built
around a complex network of mining tunnels, once used to mine coal
and silica sand. The coal was used for heating and fueling
California's industrial revolution, especially to power railroads
and riverboats. The silica sand was used to make glass, most
popular for canning jars, ketchup bottles and drinking glasses.
</P>
<P>
   It was closed as a coal mine in the early 1900s and ended
operation as a silica sand mine in the late 1940s. It became a
regional park 25 years ago, but since the earthquake and the
closures of the tunnel trails, it has largely been overlooked by
all but nearby residents.
</P>
<P>
   No more now that the tunnel trails have been reopened along with
an underground chamber that has been converted to what is called
the ``Greathouse Visitor Center.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two great trails here, completely different in scope.
</P>
<P>
   The new highlight is the Hazel-Atlas Mine, where visitors can
walk 400 feet into the earth, an eerie sensation. This trip is
expected to be popular and reservations are advised, with a tour
fee of $2.50 per person. The trip will take about 45 minutes and
tours will depart hourly. Participants must be at least seven years
old. Visitors will be in a group of 15, led by a naturalist. For
reservations, phone (510) 562-2267.
</P>
<P>
   On this trip, you will enter an abandoned silica sand mine,
passing the office of the old mine boss, various ore chutes, and
ancient geological features that were uncovered by the tunneling.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent of these features are wave erosion marks from
a long-buried, ancient seashore. On this trip, hard hats and
flashlights are provided. However, you must bring your own canary.
</P>
<P>
   Another great attraction is the Prospect Tunnel Loop, a do-it-
yourself trip. No reservations required, just the parking fee of
$3.50, charged only on weekends. This is a loop hike that takes a
few hours, featuring the Prospect Tunnel, a 400-foot hole bored by
the coal miners in the 1860s. About 200 feet of the tunnel is
accessible, where you must have your own flashlight, preferably one
with fresh batteries.
</P>
<P>
   There are also small cave-like holes, about a half dozen of them
accessible to the public, sprinkled about the park's 5,000 acres. A
map/brochure of the park indicates specific areas that can be
explored without guides, and it is available free by mail or phone
and also at the park.
</P>
<P>
   The Greathouse Visitor Center is named after R. Marvin
Greathouse, who was a pioneer silica sand miner. It's the only
visitor center at any park in Northern California that is
completely underground.
</P>
<P>
   It is located in a chamber that Greathouse dug out to extract
the silica sand, and, for being underground, the room is quite
spacious. Lighting is provided, of course, but the whole setting is
surreal.
</P>
<P>
   The park will be open on weekends, with the visitor center
operating from 9 a.m. to 3:30 p.m. on Saturdays and Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   A map/brochure is available for free at the park entrance at the
end of Somersville Road, and also by phone at (510) 635-0135, ext.
2200, or by mail by writing Map/Brochure, East Bay Parks, 2950
Peralta Oaks Court, P.O. Box 5381, Oakland, CA 94605. The park can
be reached directly by phone (925) 757-2620.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1415EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
