<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SALARIED' WORKERS WANT THEIR OT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Rocky Mountain News) 
 
By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When Ida Basha worked for MCI Telecommunications Corp.
in Sugar Land, Texas, she arranged for the placement of new phone
and Internet lines.
</P>
<P>
   It was mostly clerical work, she said recently, describing how
she'd print out orders and file the requests.
</P>
<P>
   However, MCI called her an engineer even though she did no
engineering work, didn't have an engineering degree or any
experience as an engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Basha believes the company classified her and her colleagues as
engineers solely to avoid paying overtime. She said she often
worked 80 to 90 hours a week, seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Federal labor law requires employers to pay workers not exempt
from the overtime law time and a half for every hour over 40 hours
worked in a week.
</P>
<P>
   Workers not legally entitled to overtime include outside sales
people; computer analysts, programmers and software engineers who
earn at least $27.63 an hour; professionals (with an advanced
degree such as doctors, lawyers and some engineers); executives
(such as first-line supervisors); and administrative workers
(that's the murkiest category but typically requires the employee
to make corporate policies and exercise discretion).
</P>
<P>
   But many employers misclassify their workers, telling them
they're ``salaried'' and not eligible for overtime pay, said Gregg
Rosenberg, a Houston employment lawyer who is representing Basha
and another former MCI employee.
</P>
<P>
   Some common jobs that are typically misclassified, according to
Shirley Gardner, district director of the Wage and Hour Division of
the U.S. Department of Labor in Houston, include inside sales
representatives, customer service representatives,
computer-assisted designers, assistant managers who work alongside
their subordinates in fast-food outlets and construction foremen
who swing hammers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SUIT GIVEN CLASS-ACTION STATUS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein Jr. recently gave Basha's
lawsuit preliminary class-action status for the 20 or so order
arrangers in the Houston-area city of Sugar Land, who work for a
division of a corporation now known as MCI WorldCom. Rosenberg
hopes to expand that class to include employees who do similar work
in other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Basha, who earned $47,000 a year, figures she's got a chunk of
change coming.
</P>
<P>
   The work had to get done, said Basha, who recounted the pressure
she felt to fill those orders and the illnesses she suffered as a
result of the stress. Some days, she said, she'd stay until 11 p.m.
and would return by 4 a.m., but was refused overtime pay.
</P>
<P>
   That workload didn't go unappreciated: Basha was named to the
company's Ring of Champions, the highest honor within network MCI
Services, which is reserved for the top 1 percent of the division.
She was sent to Cabo San Lucas, Mexico, in August along with dozens
of other winners.
</P>
<P>
   But a week after she was added to an overtime lawsuit, Basha
said she was fired for ``no longer meeting the MCI WorldCom
standard.'' She explained her termination as she showed off a big
commemorative trophy with her name etched in crystal along with
letters heralding her nominations for other performance-based
awards.
</P>
<P>
   An MCI WorldCom spokeswoman said the company doesn't comment on
pending litigation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CASES EASIER TO PROVE IN COURT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suing companies for overtime pay is becoming increasingly
popular. That's because it's a lot easier to get a judge to certify
a class of employees on an overtime pay issue than on a race or
gender discrimination case, Rosenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The way a company classifies its employees is typically a
corporate decision, he said, which makes it relatively easy to
prove the company sought to keep its employees from overtime
whether they're in Wisconsin or Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to prove a race or sex discrimination class-action case
is much more difficult, especially when employees work for
different supervisors and in different locations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Overtime cases also are easier to present. Many times a lawyer
can go to a judge and establish corporate liability for
misclassification without having to try the case before a jury,
said Jack Wisdom, an expert on overtime pay issues and lawyer for
Bracewell &AMP; Patterson in Houston. Lawyers fees are then tacked on
top of the back-wage awards, said Wisdom, who is not familiar with
the MCI case.
</P>
<P>
   Wisdom said he tells his corporate clients if they're in doubt
whether a job is exempt, go ahead and pay the overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The downside can be substantial, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
