<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANT TO COMPLAIN ABOUT SCHOOLS? TALK TO THE MIRROR 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ He's a father. He lives in an Albany suburb. He
loves his kid, and he was upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son is 9,'' he told me. ``On Dec. 11, they had a substitute
teacher in his fourth-grade class who threatened him. She said to
him, `If it wasn't against the rules, I would kill you.' She raised
her hand up to him, threatening to hit him, although she didn't
actually do that.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked the obvious question: ``What did your son do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the class wasn't completely in her control. She kept
them all in from going out for their recess break after lunch.
Apparently, they were talking ...
</P>
<P>
   ``She asked another child _ apparently he wasn't listening to
her the way she wanted him to _ if he was deaf. She told him he
should get a hearing aid. She told another kid that he was acting
like he was blind. She was making a lot of derogatory remarks like
that. But to my son, specifically, there was that threat.''
</P>
<P>
   The father called the school to complain. He wanted this
substitute kept out of the place forever. He was told that would
happen, but the father never got that pledge in writing, despite
his calls to the schools superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   So, he called in a complaint to the child abuse hotline. Then
the father swore out a criminal complaint against the substitute
teacher on a charge of harassment. The police, he said, promised to
issue the teacher an appearance ticket that would require her to
appear in court. He wanted me to know about this because he was
disturbed at how unconcerned everybody seemed to be over this
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Well, nobody wants teachers abusing kids. One of my kids came
home once with a story about being roughed up by a substitute
teacher. Rather than take my kid's word for it, I called a half
dozen other kids in the class to verify what had happened. Then I
raised hell with the school. Roughing up my kid, I insisted, was my
personal pleasure and nobody else's.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, I invite you to take a walk down a high
school hallway sometime, especially if you haven't been inside a
high school for a while. You'll hear language that'll blister your
eardrums. It's bellowed out without regard for who might be around
_ like the pope, maybe. You'll see a student body that's largely
out of control and, essentially, has been ever since kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because parents no longer back the schools in imposing
discipline on their kids. Instead, parents who haven't taught their
kids how to behave seem more or less determined that anybody who
tries to hold their kids to any behavioral standard will find that
chore much more trouble than it's worth.
</P>
<P>
   So, we end up with cases like this one in the Albany suburb of
Rensselaer where a teacher with a decade in the district now faces
a misdemeanor charge of endangering the welfare of a child. Her
crime? Allegedly sticking a student with a pencil that didn't break
the skin.
</P>
<P>
   One PTA board member suggested that the parents might be
over-reacting. Really? No kidding? Now we have this complaint sworn
out by a loving suburban father who figures that any teacher who
speaks harshly to his kid for misbehaving must be a criminal.
</P>
<P>
   I spoke to the substitute teacher. She's only a few years out of
college and badly shaken by this. She says that she and the kids
were just fooling around. She also mentioned that this particular
kid isn't exactly a model of scholarly decorum.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you want to know why the schools don't work any more _
why kids you see everywhere seem ruder, cruder and disturbingly
dopier _ just look in the mirror. And, while you're at it, stop
complaining about how much teachers get paid. How else could they
afford the legal fees?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
