 ART ADV.: A photo with NATCHEZ-SCHOOL is being transmitted to NYT
Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-RACISM (London) _ A rare act of racial violence has led
many Britons and the British government to confront racism like
never before. By Kevin Cullen. 1700 words.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-ANTI-US (Johannesburg) _ Attack on tourists has roots in
the conflict between Hutus and Tutsis in Rwanda. But it also
demonstrates a deep-seated anti-US sentiment. By Kurt Shillinger.
1180 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLIPHANT-COLUMN (Washington) _ The great Steven Spielberg, it
seems, is starting his victory lap a tad early. By Thomas Oliphant.
(w and k coding.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POCKET-ROCKETS (Washington) _ With 30 states now allowing
carrying of concealed weapons, gunmakers have launched a marketing
effort to sell powerful new pistols that fit in the palm of the
hand. By Louise D. Palmer. 960 words.
</P>
<P>
   NATCHEZ-SCHOOL (Natchez, Miss.) -- Oldest African-American
school in the country is in deep trouble. But a nun from
Massachusetts has for two years been striving to save the school.
By Kate Zernike. 1700 words. PHOTO
</P>
