<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1927 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLACK-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-08 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLACK-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORY THROUGH THE EYES OF THE BEHOLDER 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARY CLACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ It's been said that journalism is the first draft
of history. But there are priceless times when a piece of
journalism is so rich and enduring that it becomes history itself.
</P>
<P>
   Thucydides' ``History of the Peloponnesian War'' is journalism,
an account of a war by a participant and observer that's been a
classic for more than 2,000 years. It succeeds because it tells a
story and tells it well.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the journalism selected as the century's top work by
experts assembled by New York University will endure as long is
unknown. But the great list of books, articles, photographs and
broadcasts representing the top 100 of American journalism in the
20th century reminds us that for all the unpopularity and distrust
of journalists, this century has produced a trove of journalistic
excellence.
</P>
<P>
   The list sparkles with the jewels that are discovered when an
issue or subject lends itself to the talent, passion and ambition
of the journalist. The works are a testament to the power of
journalism to educate, expose and expand the constituency of
concern for a particular issue.
</P>
<P>
   Few journalistic efforts accomplished this better than the one
that leads the list: John Hersey's ``Hiroshima,'' the story,
through the eyes of survivors, of the dropping of the first atomic
bomb on Japan. Hersey's masterful account is an example of how
journalism can be literature.
</P>
<P>
   Other choices on the list include books by Norman Mailer, Truman
Capote and Taylor Branch's ``Parting the Waters: America in the
King Years.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the artistic possibilities of journalism, at its
heart is the service of informing the public of problems and
injustices. Second on the list is Rachel Carson's book ``Silent
Spring,'' her warning of the danger of pesticides. Also in the Top
Ten are works by two of the original muckrakers: Ida Tarbell,
documenting the evils of Standard Oil, and Lincoln Steffens,
exposing corrupt city government.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of race, there's the elegant, almost detached
writings of W.E.B. DuBois and the searing and passionate prose of
James Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   H.L. Mencken, with his pyrotechnic writing style, is on the
list, as is I.F. Stone, the greatest independent journalist of the
century; Murray Kempton, the standard for all newspaper columnists;
and A.J. Liebling, who wrote well about everything from war,
boxing, food and the press.
</P>
<P>
   Documentaries by Edward R. Murrow on Sen. Joseph McCarthy,
R-Wis., and the exploitation of migrant workers are reminders of
the heights broadcast journalism can reach.
</P>
<P>
   Herblock's cartoons on McCarthyism showcase the withering power
of ridicule, while the photograph of the Marines raising the flag
on Iwo Jima is more stirring than any writer's words.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the reporting on this list deals with historic events
or famous people. Much of it is about people on the margins of
society, obscure people living obscure lives that could just as
easily gone unchronicled, as such lives often are.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, journalism not only documents a century through
covering the big events and personalities but also by celebrating
and lamenting the lives of those people whose significance is
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   What this list of some of America's finest journalism of the
century says is that all around us there are stories waiting to be
told _ and told well.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cary Clack is a columnist for the San Antonio Express-News,
P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
