<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1949 &Cx1f; sci-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-     03-08 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, March 9:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS (Undated) _ Mars is coming into much better focus, so
clear that scientists think they now see in the towering mountains,
layered canyon walls and meandering channels telling traces of the
planet's early history, when volcanoes belched gases into a denser,
warmer atmosphere and rivers flowed across the russet plains. Over
the last year, the Mars Global Surveyor spacecraft looked down from
orbit and snapped hundreds of pictures of the landscape that are 20
to 40 times more detailed than anything obtained by previous
explorations, and those images are giving scientists a spectacular
new view of the geological processes that shaped the Martian
surface. By John Noble Wilford. (1375 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AGING (Los Angeles) _ Science is on the brink of being able
to stretch the human life span, perhaps dramatically, a recently
assembled group of academics said. Future generations, they said,
might be able to avail themselves of scientifically established
techniques to stretch the human lifespan like a piece of taffy
until it reached 150, even 200 years. By Gina Kolata. (2100 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COLD-FISH (Undated) _ In the frigid waters at the bottom of
the Antarctic Ocean, scientists have uncovered what appears to be
an evolutionary explosion that has generated an unexpectedly
impressive array of cold fish. New research suggests that primitive
species have given rise to a menagerie of cold-hardy descendants
that span the spectrum in size and shape, ranging from small,
schooling herring-like fish to 250 pound shark-like creatures. By
Carol Kaesuk Yoon. (1375 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-REP-BROWN (Undated) _ Conversation with Rep. George E. Brown
Jr. of California, the ranking Democrat on the House Committee on
Science and the former chairman of the House Committee on Science,
Space and Technology. He has been a crucial supporter of manned and
unmanned space exploration. In addition, he wrote legislation
creating an Environmental Protection Agency, was a prime mover
behind efforts to include ozone-layer protections in the Clean Air
Act and supported restructuring the national weapons laboratories
to the needs of a peacetime economy. By Claudia Dreifus. (1630
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Short items on science: dealing with the
way asteroids leap from a Mars obit to one near Earth, the tectonic
rift in Africa and a baby mouse that breathes mostly through its
skin. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TYING-TIES (Undated) _ Seeking a marriage of science and
beauty, Thomas M.A. Fink and Yong Mao, research fellows at
Cambridge University, have applied the rigors of mathematics to
that most basic of fashion statements, the necktie knot. In the
process they have come up with six new ways of tying a tie. By
Henry Fountain. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GLOBAL-WARMING (Undated) _ The Northern Hemisphere has been
warmer in the 20th century than in any other century of the last
thousand years, according to a reconstruction of the hemispheric
temperature record by scientists at the University of Massachusetts
and the University of Arizona. By William K. Stevens. (375 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BANDAGE (Undated) _ Blood loss through wounds claims tens of
thousands of lives each year, but researchers are working to change
that by developing a new type of bandage that clots blood
instantly. Scientists with the American Red Cross have teamed with
U.S. Army researchers to produce bandages and other dressings that
they say can seal a severe, bleeding wound in seconds with a tough,
artificial scab. After about eight years of research in the
laboratory and with animals, the researchers say the sealants are
about ready for human trials. By Warren E. Leary. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CATHARSIS (Undated) _ Though pop psychology books and
articles perpetuate the notion that ``getting your anger out'' is
cathartic and can help dissipate hostility, the researchers have
found just the opposite: Venting anger on inanimate objects _
punching a pillow or hitting a punching bag, for example _
increases rather than decreases aggressive behavior. By Erica
Goode. (625 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: Ten
percent to 15 percent of breast cancers do not show up on a
mammogram, so women with any suspicious area in the breast should
be biopsied even when the mammogram is negative. Times health
columnist Jane E. Brody writes of her own recent experience among
that 10 to 15 percent and her lumpectomy. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FERTILITY-HERBS (Undated) _ Many women trying to become
pregnant are careful to avoid ingesting any substance that might in
any way impair their fertility or damage a developing embryo.
According to findings of a new study, several popular herbal
remedies should be added to the list of substances that could
interfere for men and women with conception and a healthy
pregnancy. By Jane E. Brody. (695 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Shorts on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _Wearing tight, form-fitting shorts, also known as compression
garments, increases an athlete's power output and endurance, two
key measures of athletic performance, by an average of 12 percent _
and by as much as 30 percent. Researchers said the form-fitting
fabric exerts pressure on muscles, and that increases blood flow
and helps flush away lactic acid and other fatigue causing waste
products quickly and efficiently. It also reduces muscle vibration,
another principle cause of muscle fatigue. (350 words)
</P>
<P>
   _Should patients be allowed to sue their health maintenance
organizations? (350 words)
</P>
<P>
   _Many children as young as 10 years old want to know more about
sex than just where babies come from, but parents often shy away
from discussing sexuality, finds a national survey conducted by the
Kaiser Family Foundation and Children Now, a children's advocacy
group. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-CAPOEIRA (Undated) _ Learning to perform capoeira, a
martial art created by Africans taken as slaves to Brazil. It
involves an unusual method of self-defense. A few moves, like
spinning on one's head seemed straight out of break dancing; others
seemed worthy of an Olympic gymnastics competition. By Eric V.
Copage. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: Can a person
live without a stomach?
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
