<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1955 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-08 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS IN KENYA ARE FULL OF ENTHUSIASM BUT SHORT ON BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Sorting out the impressions of a two-week trip
through rural Kenya will take time.
</P>
<P>
   The assimilation of a multitude of sensations and feelings of
the ranging countryside, the bountiful variety of wildlife, the
people, and, most elusively, the culture that embraces and
rationalizes them, requires time.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing from among the vivid experiences, the initial high
point is not the dramatic: Being within spitting distance of a
pride of lions ingesting their morning feast of hartebeest, or a
herd of elephants or giraffes almost within hand's reach.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would it be the transcendence of caravaning over the
undulating savanna stretching as far as the eye can see, here and
there studded by the umbrella-like formations of acacia trees, or
the varieties of shrubbery that also provide food and shelter for
the gazelles and cape buffalo and the other plant-eating beasts.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would it be of the Kenyan people, united in what aspires to
be a modern nation-state which is based on an amalgamation of some
42 tribes, each speaking its own language, each invested in its own
history and customs.
</P>
<P>
   All of these impressions were extraordinary and are sure to
remain to be savored in memory for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   But for all their vividness, the experience that stands out from
the rest is a visit to a government primary school in the city of
Njoro, northwest of Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   We were taken there _ a group of 30 Canadian and American
visitors _ by officials associated with Egerton University, where
we had spent most of the day hearing presentations on the status of
women in Kenya and on the land use policies that defined the Kenyan
economy and politics.
</P>
<P>
   The visit to the school rounded out the day. Kenyans, it needs
to be noted, are devoted to the idea of education, and as you
travel the rough roads, you come across school after school or to
road signs pointing the way to them. Sometimes kids in their
uniforms are glimpsed. As in most countries, those who have means
fare better, the wealthiest best of all. Some send their kids to
England for schooling or keep them at home attending the very best
of prep schools.
</P>
<P>
   But for the vast majority of people there are only the
government schools, and they are a different story altogether,
judging from what we saw and what we were told. The school property
comprised a fairly large area, with perhaps five or six
considerably sized stone buildings.
</P>
<P>
   These were set on a dusty and mostly unkempt ground and housed
one class of perhaps 30 to 40 kids and one teacher. Inside, the
classroom buildings were dark. There was a blackboard with the
lesson for the day written out in elegant cursive script. (Our
Kenyan lecturers without exception wrote a legible hand that any
American could justly envy.)
</P>
<P>
   As visitors had been expected, preparations had been made. In
one classroom, the kids sang a couple of welcoming songs that they
had obviously practiced with success. They were a pleasure to hear.
All the kids were attired in that school's particular uniform,
consisting of a yellow shirt or blouse, and dark blue jumpers or
shorts. Many wore no shoes.
</P>
<P>
   As a small number of us were making our way from one classroom
to another, kids hanging out of a window (all without glass panes)
implored us to visit them. When we got into the room, the teacher
had just left to attend to one child's particular problem. The kids
swarmed around us, perhaps 6 or 7 years old, avidly reaching out to
shake hands, demonstrating their eagerness and their friendliness.
</P>
<P>
   Vitality exuded from them and infected a visitor with optimism
for the future. Yet their reality was harsh. The classroom was
without artificial light. Few kids actually had a desk top to sit
at. The furniture hardly deserved the name, being less than basic.
The dirt floor of the classroom was littered with debris.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, the kids had no implements of learning. They
shared well-worn sheafs of paper that served them collectively as a
text. They had no paper upon which to write and no pencils or pens
to do it with. They had no books. Their teachers were high school
graduates.
</P>
<P>
   What they had amply was enthusiasm and an all-too-obvious
personal niceness. They also were tough by our standards, walking
miles by themselves to and from school, and sticking with it
although there was so little for them in that school. It was the
gap between the possibility that those kids personified and the
reality that faced them that brought home the poignancy of the
enormous hurdle that Kenyans have to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   In this they have not been well served by governments notorious
for the inventiveness of their corruption.
</P>
<P>
   It is said that Kenya has been independent for only three
decades or so and one must not judge it by inappropriate or
impossibly high standards, which is fair enough. The capital of
Nairobi outwardly looks like a metropolitan city, although a little
ramshackle upon close examination.
</P>
<P>
   Surely if the capacity exists to build expensive condo
developments and towering office buildings, the culture should be
capable of supplying its public schools with pencils, books and
paper.
</P>
<P>
   Kenya's hope for a better future resides in its avid young
people. If they are not prepared for that challenge, who else will
there be to meet it?
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany, N.Y., Times.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
