<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DIMAGGIO-PHOTOS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS: The N.Y. Times Photo Service has moved the following
photo package to accompany your stories about Joe DiMaggio.
DiMaggio died Monday after a long battle with lung cancer. He was
84.
</P>
<P>
   Photo clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
888-603-1036 or 212-556-4204 or our Photo Sales department at
212-556-1243.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) HOLLYWOOD, Fla. -- March 8, 1999 -- OBIT-DIMAGGIO-8,
03-08 -- Joe DiMaggio during an interview with the Times in Sept.
1998. In his 13 seasons as a Hall of Fame center fielder from 1936
to 1951 (with three years out for Army service during World War
II), he had a career average of .325 with 361 home runs and 1,537
runs batted in while the Yankees won 10 American League pennants
and 9 World Series. ``Joltin' Joe'' DiMaggio died Monday morning at
his home in Hollywood, Fla. He was 84. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) HOLLYWOOD, Fla. -- March 8, 1999 -- OBIT-DIMAGGIO-7,
03-08 -- At the Joe DiMaggio Children's Hospital at Memorial
Regional Hospital, DiMaggio signs autographs for some young fans.
The hospital's moto is ``Whether rich or poor, no child is turned
away.'' The former Yankee Clipper, whose 56-game hitting streak is
of baseball's greatest records, died at his home Monday in
Hollywood, Fla. He was 84. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) HOLLYWOOD, Fla. -- March 8, 1999 -- OBIT-DIMAGGIO-6,
03-08 -- Joe DiMaggio wearing a 1936 World Series ring, the one he
won his rookie year with the New York Yankees. All of his other
Series rings were stolen in 1960. As a surprise on Joe DiMaggio Day
in Oct. 1998, Phil Rizzuto, the Hall of Fame shortstop who was his
teammate for a decade, presented DiMaggio with a gift from George
Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner: replicas of his eight
diamond-studded World Series rings that were stolen. DiMaggio died
Monday at 84 after a battle with lung cancer and pneumonia. (Fred
R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) HOLLYWOOD, Fla. -- March 8, 1999 -- OBIT-DIMAGGIO-5,
03-08 -- ``I'm not one of those guys who looks to be in the
limelight,'' said Joe DiMaggio during an interview with the Times
in Sept. 1998. The baseball legend and former husband of Marilyn
Monroe, died Monday at 84. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- March 8, 1999 -- OBIT-DIMAGGIO-4, 03-08 --
The Yankee Clipper, Joe DiMaggio, taking a spin around Yankee
stadium in a 1956 Thunderbird on the last day of the Yankee's 1998
season. ``Like his many fans across America, and indeed, around the
world, the Yankees are deeply saddened by the passing of Joe
DiMaggio, one of our own and one of the greatest of all time,''
said the team's owner George M. Steinbrenner about DiMaggio's death
Monday. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- March 8, 1999 -- OBIT-DIMAGGIO-3, 03-08 --
Joe DiMaggio throws the first pitch to open the Yankees 1998 season
with a game against the Oakland A's. David Cone watches from the
mound. DiMaggio died early Monday morning after a battle with lung
cancer and pneumonia. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- March 8, 1999 -- OBIT-DIMAGGIO-2, 03-08 --
Joe DiMaggio walks out onto the diamond at Yankee Stadium to
deliver the first pitch against the Oakland A's in April of 1998.
DiMaggio, who played 13 season with the Yankees, had been battling
lung cancer since October. He died early Monday morning. (G. Paul
Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- March 8, 1999 -- OBIT-DIMAGGIO-1, 03-08 --
Former Yankee, Joe DiMaggio, acknowledges the crowd at Yankee
Stadium after throwing the first pitch of the last day of the 1998
season. DiMaggio, who underwent lung cancer surgery in October and
had been battling its complications, died early Monday morning. He
was 84. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
