<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1980 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLIDERS-VETERANS-HNS &LR;      03-08 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLIDERS-VETERANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLIDER PILOTS WERE THE SILENT HEROES OF WORLD WAR II 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM BOWER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ They flew clunky-looking, blunt-nosed aircraft and
took part in some of the biggest battles of World War II. They wore
silver wings with a ``G'' in the middle that designated them as
glider pilots.
</P>
<P>
   But among the men who flew the engineless planes, the ``G''
stood for something else: Guts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were there, then you know it's true,'' said Ray Welty,
commander of the Texas wing of the National World War II Glider
Pilots Association.
</P>
<P>
   While gliders played a pivotal role in defeating the Germans on
the western front, their contribution and the men who flew them are
often overlooked by modern filmmakers and historians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The glider pilots were kind of looked down on, and I got kind
of teed off that we were ignored,'' said retired Air Force Lt. Col.
Arn Granheim, who now lives in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   During the war, one of the most-used American gliders was the
CG-4A, with a wingspan of 83 feet and a capacity to carry 13
soldiers or one jeep or one howitzer. It was towed to invasion
targets by a twin-engine C-47 transport.
</P>
<P>
   Over the target, the glider pilot would release the tow rope and
glide to a landing in a field, where the troops or cargo would be
unloaded. In Operation Market Garden on Sept. 17-19, 1944, during
the Allied invasion of Holland, more than 2,500 gliders were used
to ferry in troops and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, during Operation Varsity on March 24, 1945,
more than 17,000 glider infantry troops and paratroopers were
landed east of the Rhine River near Wesel, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Market Garden was the largest wartime use of gliders,
while Operation Varsity was the largest single-day airborne mission
in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``That train of aircraft took 2-and-1/2 hours to pass by,''
Granheim said of Operation Varsity. It was Granheim's only glider
mission of the war. The rest of the time, he piloted C-47s,
ferrying in supplies and personnel to the continent from England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Operation Varsity was going to be a `milk run,''' he
said. ``That's the only time I volunteered (for that duty).''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling that the mission was anything but routine, Granheim
said the cargo in his CG-4A was just a jeep's trailer with a canvas
tarp over it, along with three soldiers from the 17th Airborne
Division. After a successful landing in a field, Granheim said he
pulled back the tarp to discover he had been carrying nearly a ton
of C-2 plastic explosive.
</P>
<P>
   The only other glider carrying the same payload was hit by
anti-aircraft fire on landing approach and ``disintegrated in the
air,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During D-Day, June 6, 1944, Lt. Col. Mike Murphy was flying the
lead glider with Brig. Gen. Donald F. Pratt, the general's aides
and a jeep loaded with communications equipment and fuel. Murphy
didn't know at the time that armor plating had been installed on
the aircraft to protect the general, making it too heavy. Upon
landing, the glider crashed. Murphy survived, but not Pratt, making
him the highest ranking Allied casualty of D-Day. The incident,
with a few details changed, was included in the Stephen Spielberg
film ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were the bone-headed things that happened,'' Granheim
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Welty, who participated in five major airborne invasions, said
his most frightening experience came during Market Garden, when his
glider was among 13 that landed behind German lines about 11 miles
east of Groesbeek, Holland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't blame the navigator because it was overcast and we had
low clouds,'' he said, explaining the gliders apparently landed
unnoticed by the Germans in the middle of the second day of the
invasion.
</P>
<P>
   The unit, which numbered more than 100, eventually made its way
through enemy territory to return to its original destination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1539EST &QL; 
