<SLUG> BC-CHORES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT: BOYS AND GIRLS DO SAME AMOUNT OF CHORES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ American boys and girls do the same number but
not the same kind of chores, according to a survey in the
March/April is sue of Zillions, the excellent magazine for kids
from Consumer Reports.
</P>
<P>
   According to the survey of 1,000 children, gender roles continue
to apply in the assigning of tasks. Boys mowed lawns and took out
the trash more, while girls dominated in caring for younger
siblings, meal preparation and housecleaning. All children surveyed
did at least one chore weekly, and more than half performed five or
more.
</P>
<P>
   Room-cleaning was most common, followed by pet care; least
common were laundry and dusting. Finally, fewer than half received
payment; chore-related allowances averaged, for both boys and
girls, $5 to $6.
</P>
<P>
   Find the $2.95 Zillions on newsstands, or order a bimonthly
annual subscription, for $16, by calling (800) 234-2078.
</P>
<P>
   WINE WORRIES:
</P>
<P>
   Oenophiles should read no further. The news contained herein may
be dismaying in the extreme. First was a report this week in The
New York Times that some sommeliers who need to warm a cellared red
wine up to room temperature rapidly have resorted to zapping it in
a microwave oven. Good heavens.
</P>
<P>
   And then we find, in Chef's, a cook's catalog, a thing called
the Vintage Enhancer. The device employs a ``patented
electromagnetic process'' to change the pH level of the vino. A
mere half-hour's use will make a wine taste as if it has been aged
for years, says the catalog.
</P>
<P>
   The mind curdles, as might, we suspect, the wine. Why would
anyone spend $60 for the Vintage Enhancer and risk ruining a $50,
long-living cabernet when a perfectly tasty bottle, drinkable right
now, is available for $7.99? We can't imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Order the product by calling Chef's at (800) 338-3232.
</P>
<P>
   EXPENSIVE TOY:
</P>
<P>
   A company called BSG Labs has released the Intensor LX, an
updated version of its ``sensory gaming chair,'' which is basically
a loudspeaker that you wear while playing a videogame. The chair
transmits soundwaves and tactile sensations directly to the user's
body.
</P>
<P>
   The new model has extra features, such as a locking connector to
keep the chair from coming unplugged, which gives you an idea of
how vigorously some people play their computer games.
</P>
<P>
   The Intensor LX works with all videogame platforms, such as the
Sony PlayStation and Nintendo 64, as well as PC-based games. You
can even plug it into your stereo, should you feel the need to be
thumped directly in the kidneys by a hip-hop record or caressed by
'N Sync's coos.
</P>
<P>
   The chair costs $199, the base an extra $99; for real boom, add
the $169 subwoofer. Order any or all by visiting the Web site,
http://www.intensor.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
