<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2018 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-DiMAGGIO-HNS &LR;      03-08 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-DiMAGGIO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT THE GREATEST, BUT THE GRANDEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Nobody ever said that Joe DiMaggio was the
greatest player in baseball history. That honorific might go for
differing reasons to Honus Wagner, or Ty Cobb, or Babe Ruth, or
Jackie Robinson, or Willie Mays.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio would make anyone's top 10 with ease, and probably even
top five, but not the best.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio's command of our attention for fully six decades was
due to something else. He was the shining example of that rarest
kind of athlete, in his prime and now at the day of his death _ a
man who evoked words like ``elegant,'' ``stylish,'' and ``regal.''
</P>
<P>
   Most athletes owe their hold on us to the frenetic power of
their body or will. Even Michael Jordan, the athlete of our age,
could be all those things we ascribe to DiMaggio off the court, but
on it, Jordan is an animated, viscerally engaged, even domineering
presence. He yanks you to him forcefully, whether you resist or
not.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio's gift, as described by his contemporaries of the '30s
and '40s and reiterated now at his passing, was that he subtly
gained your attention and held it merely with his presence rather
than his visible energy.
</P>
<P>
   When those who saw him play say with complete seriousness, ``He
made every play look easy,'' they are using what is surely a
falsehood to explain a greater truth. His control of his gifts
allowed him to seem omniscient as well as omnipotent. He somehow
knew where the ball would be before it got there, and what he
needed to do to get there.
</P>
<P>
   More unusual, his off-stage presence only supported what he
showed on the field. He placed enormous personal stock in that
elegance, that style, that sense of royal prerogative. He was off
the field what he was on it, a perfect symbiont in a field that
normally demands a dual personality.
</P>
<P>
   He will be remembered mostly as a son of New York, the
definitive Yankee, and as definitions go, that can work. But he
came from here, and he had that sense of self long before he went
east.
</P>
<P>
   He may not have been a pure fit for the San Francisco of his
day, but he surely was an exact match for what San Franciscans have
always thought of themselves _ again, elegant, stylish and slightly
aloof from the maddening rush of New York or Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   If he could only have been himself as a Yankee, we hold just as
fervently that he could only have developed this way as a San
Franciscan.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the way with cultural icons. We can reinvent them to
meet our own needs and prejudices. There are so few of those (maybe
Ruth and Robinson in baseball, Jordan in basketball, Billie Jean
King in tennis, Arnold Palmer in golf) that when one passes, it is
a matter for all of society to stop and remember.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio's image, though, seems more a statement about his own
time, out of place with the frenetic, chest-thumping, sound-biting
age of ours.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth lived the contemporary star's life, Robinson the
contemporary's easy-to-feel heat, King the social crusader's
passion and stridency, Palmer the star-turned-conglomerate's
single-mindedness _ and all have modern equivalents, many of them
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, no DiMaggio clone out there now for the
terminally young among us to use as a reference point. He left us
no single compelling oration, no signature gesture, no single
moment to define his career or life. Those who say ``marrying
Marilyn Monroe'' forget that at the time he was the more famous
figure.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio leaves behind something harder to accurately define but
easier to feel _ that all-enveloping aura called ``presence.'' His
friends felt it precisely the same way his teammates did, and both
sets seemed genuinely overwhelmed by it.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have to do anything to win their admiration and
respectful distance. He just had to be Joe DiMaggio, and he was
that in every sense. He defined himself, rather than be defined by
others, and he never strayed from that basic structure.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is gone, and although nobody should ever say, ``We shall
never see his like again,'' we can say that since he began his
career, we haven't. In 60-plus years, there hasn't been another
DiMaggio, and it could easily take another 60-plus years to see
another of his equal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
