<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2023 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANGER-CATHARSIS-NYTSF     03-08 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGER-CATHARSIS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYZE THIS: CATHARSIS MAY FUEL ANGER RATHER THAN RELEASE IT  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 BY STEPHANIE PELTZER  
 c.1999 Medical Tribune News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  &QL;  &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to popular belief, ``letting off steam'' by watching a
violent movie or hitting a punching bag may not release aggression.
In fact, it may add fuel to the fire.
</P>
<P>
   In a study led by Dr. Brad Bushman, an associate professor of
psychology at Iowa State University in Ames, students who read an
article stating that catharsis was a healthy way to relieve anger
and were then presented with the opportunity to exercise cathartic
measures actually became more aggressive. They expressed increased
aggression toward both the people who had angered them and toward
``innocent bystanders.'' Bushman's report appears in the latest
issue of the Journal of Personality and Social Psychology.
</P>
<P>
   Catharsis theory holds that repressing anger is unhealthy, and
encourages people to redirect hostility by beating up pillows or
punching bags.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred college students were presented with messages
constructed to look like newspaper articles either supporting or
debunking catharsis theory. They were then given insulting
critiques, designed to anger them, of essays they had written.
Finally, the researchers asked them to rank their preference of a
list of activities. Angry students who were exposed to a
pro-catharsis message showed the highest desire to hit the punching
bag.
</P>
<P>
   In a related study of 700 students, similarly angered students
were asked to spend two minutes either hitting a punching bag or
just sitting alone quietly. Subjects then engaged in a computer
game that would allow them to ``punish'' their opponents with
blasts of noise of a volume and duration of their choosing.
Students assigned to hitting the punching bag chose to blast longer
and louder, regardless of whether they were told their unseen
opponent was the person who had criticized them or a third
unrelated person.
</P>
<P>
   ``People wanted to hit the punching bag. They reported feeling
better after hitting the punching bag, but this did not translate
to less aggression _ it reinforced it,'' Bushman commented.
Particularly interesting was the tendency to lash out at
``innocent'' victims, he said. ``It's like they don't discriminate
between a punching bag and a person,'' Bushman said.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the counterfeit newspaper article's influence on behavior
in a clinical setting, Bushman expressed concern over pro-catharsis
attitudes in culture and in the media that might justify losing
self-control. Terms like ``get it off your chest'' and ``let off
steam'' promote the violent release of aggression, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bushman suggested that mass media and pop psychologists endorse
the views that expressing anger is healthy and repressing it is
unhealthy. For example, in a trailer for the movie ``Analyze
This,'' therapist Billy Crystal tells a client that when he gets
upset he hits a pillow. After shooting the pillow with a gun, his
client agrees, ``I feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Redford Williams, director of behavioral medicine at the
Research Center at Duke University in Durham, N.C., also cited
studies that linked television to violence by viewers. For
already-hostile people, he said, catharsis may be a particularly
dangerous message.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who report more levels of anger at age 25 are four to
seven times as likely to be dead by age 50,'' Williams said. He
added that hostility could bring blood pressure up even more.
</P>
<P>
   Bushman offered alternative methods for dealing with anger,
including finding a distraction, such as working on a puzzle or
taking a walk, counting to 10 or higher and taking deep breaths.
``If you're angry, you're better off doing nothing,'' Bushman
advised.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists agreed that there are better ways of handling
anger than catharsis. ``A lot of people walk around confused about
what they're feeling,'' said Dr. Eleanor Cole, a licensed
psychologist in private practice in Hoboken, N. J. ``But if you're
going to deal with it by hitting a punching bag, you don't get to
the root of the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams suggests people evaluate their anger and decide whether
to take action. ``Ask yourself, is the situation important to me?
Is my anger appropriate to the facts of the situation? Is the
situation modifiable? Would it be worth it to take action? If the
answers are all yes, act assertively, not aggressively.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jefferson had his own advice: When angry, count to 10,
when very angry, count to 100.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Journal of Personality and Social Psychology (1999;76:367-376)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
