A2037 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-NUCLEAR09-COX     03-08 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-NUCLEAR09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENTISTS WARN Y2K BUG THREATENS NUCLEAR SECURITY
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States and Russia should respond to the
risk of a false missile attack warning triggered by the Year 2000
computer bug by placing their nuclear arsenals on lower alert, a
group of legislators and scientists said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In anticipation of a Jan. 1 electronic 'El Nino,' we shouldn't
take the risk of nuclear weapons or nuclear power plants going
awry,'' Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., told a day-long nuclear
security conference on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Markey called on President Clinton to quickly cut a deal with
President Boris Yeltsin of Russia aimed at reducing the chances of
accidental launches. A letter that Markey and Sen. Tom Harkin,
D-Iowa, sent Clinton last week warned that ``the Russian military
clearly lacks the resources to correct the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The glitch occurs when computer hardware or software programs
that use two digits to mark a year misread the year 2000, and
either fail or spew out bad data.
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear experts who spoke at the session noted that the
``millennium bug'' could neither cause a spontaneous missile launch
nor cause a warhead to explode in its silo.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Russian early warning network is particularly
susceptible to the Y2K problem,'' said Bruce Blair of the Brookings
Institution, a Washington research center. Blair, the author of a
recent book entitled ``The Nuclear Hair Trigger: Dangers and
Solutions,'' said ``the only real cure is to take the weapons off
high alert.''
</P>
<P>
   In talks with Russian defense officials in Moscow last month,
the Pentagon proposed that before the end of the year the former
Cold War rivals set up a joint missile-warning center aimed at
minimizing the chances of a false alert.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Kraig, a nuclear policy expert, told the session
that the Russians have dragged their feet on the U.S. initiative
because they lack the funds to move forward and because they fear
that such an exchange would expose the decline in readiness that
has occurred since Soviet times.
</P>
<P>
   The new U.S. proposal would implement an accord signed last
September by Clinton and Yeltsin. That deals calls on both sides to
share data on the missile launches and payloads.
</P>
<P>
   According to Markey, a top Russian missile official, Vladimir
Dvorkin, has told the U.S. negotiators that it would take about $4
million in outside aid to upgrade his nation's early-warning
systems so they are Y2K-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering the many billions of dollars we've spent over the
years to ward off the threat a of Soviet missile attack, it seems
to be a prudent investment,'' Markey said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States relies on a highly sophisticated system of
radars and satellites to monitor Russian nuclear activity on a
``real time'' basis.
</P>
<P>
   While both sides reduced have their arsenals over the years, the
Pentagon estimates that Russia's current total nuclear firepower
amounts to the equivalent of 100,000 atomic bombs of the type
dropped on Hiroshima, Japan, in August 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the Pentagon continues to maintain large parts of
the remaining U.S. nuclear force in a high state of readiness,
including Trident submarines stationed in the Atlantic and Pacific
Oceans.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
