<SLUG> BC-PHARMACISTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUGGISTS REPORT DISSATISFACTION WITH WORKLOAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CECILIA BALLI  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Although job satisfaction has improved, the
nation's staff pharmacists continue to report burdensome workloads
and many say they would not enter the field if given a second
chance, a survey of the American Pharmaceutical Association has
found.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 39 percent of the 1,200 pharmacists who responded said
they likely wouldn't choose the same career if they were just
beginning college today. That figure is down from results of a
similar study done in 1987. But industry representatives said the
numbers show there still is much to do to improve the work
environment of practicing pharmacists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this indicates that there is a feeling of uncertainty
about the profession within the minds of our colleagues,'' said Ben
Gruda, who serves on the association's task force for environment
and worklife quality issues.
</P>
<P>
   Findings of the survey, conducted by researchers at George
Washington University, were presented at the association's 146th
conference being held here through Tuesday. About 5,500 association
members are attending the event, which includes panels, continuing
education courses and more than 300 exhibits on the industry's
newest drugs, products and therapies.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacists surveyed said heavy workloads cut deeply into time
for counseling patients on prescriptions. They also reported too
many interruptions, problems with processing third-party insurance
prescriptions and little discussion with their peers about clients
and work practices.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, employees at chain and supermarket pharmacies, as well
as those in hospitals and other institutional settings, are less
satisfied and more likely to leave the profession, the survey
found.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five percent of those who would be permitted under labor
laws to vote for a union said they would favor one.
</P>
<P>
   The president-elect of the Pharmaceutical Society of the State
of New York said a separate job satisfaction survey in that state
found pharmacists are not complaining about long days and
infrequent bathroom breaks. They are simply unhappy they're ``not
practicing pharmacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of workload today has reached a point of absurdity,
and that's what our surveys tell us,'' Lee Joffee said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Board of Pharmacy found in its own survey that work
schedules, hours, sites, salaries and benefits are mostly
satisfactory to the 15,000 pharmacists practicing in the state.
They are most upset about their workloads, time allowed for
clinical services and patient interaction, amount of breaks and
support for staff training.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, pharmacies are required to inform clients in writing
that a pharmacist is available for counseling. They also must
provide a toll-free number to contact the Texas board with
complaints. In discussing the amount of errors pharmacists report
happening in the workplaces, Joffee described pharmacies as
sometimes dangerous places for customers whose lives may depend on
their accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pharmacists are challenged, and the issues that we're talking
about are very serious,'' said Jann Hinkle, director of
professional practice development for the American Pharmaceutical
Association. The association will use the survey results to draft
guidelines for employers and employees as part of a larger
undertaking of redefining standards of practice nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The findings will be published in the July-August issue of the
Journal of the American Pharmaceutical Association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
