<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2077 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENVIRONMENTALIST-BOMB     03-08 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIRONMENTALIST-BOMB-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE OF BLAST THAT NEARLY KILLED ENVIRONMENTALIST STILL UNSOLVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner   SAN FRANCISCO _ When radical
environmental activist and organizer Judi Bari died of cancer on
March 2, 1997, the question that had obsessed her for the last
seven years of her life remained unanswered: Who built and planted
the bomb that blew up in her car and nearly killed her?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today the FBI's investigation is in mothballs. The Oakland
Police Department's ``open file'' on the bombing is moribund. The
case is no closer to solution than it was when the pipebomb filled
with nails exploded in Oakland on May 24, 1990, shattering her
pelvis.
</P>
<P>
   But while law enforcement's attention is elsewhere, an
ill-tempered argument over who-done-it has erupted among radical
activists in California's so-called North Coast _ Mendocino and
Humboldt Counties.
</P>
<P>
   Two alternative publications have called on the FBI to reopen
the investigation and question Bari's ex-husband. That suggestion
has brought forth a furious denial from him and ridicule and
denunciations from Bari's close friends.
</P>
<P>
   They charge that her adversaries connected to the timber
industry _ with the connivance of or tacit support from the FBI _
were responsible for the bombing that left her in constant pain.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the two key agencies that might investigate, the FBI and
the Oakland police, are being sued by Bari's estate, alleging a
conspiracy against her. The FBI referred all calls on the fresh
accusations to the lawyer defending its agents in court.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department Attorney R. Joseph Sher said the new
accusations ``obviously raise an interesting question,'' but not
one that the FBI needs to investigate. It's ``of interest to me in
defense of the civil case'' against the FBI, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland police Lt. Paul Berlin said, ``There are no leads we are
actively pursuing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bari, who was 47 when she died, was the preeminent radical voice
of the North Coast. She was the leader of an environmental group
called Earth First and the organizer of Redwood Summer in 1990, a
national consciousness raiser on the threat to California's last
remaining privately owned virgin redwoods.
</P>
<P>
   She and an Earth First colleague, Darryl Cherney, were driving
through downtown Oakland when the homemade bomb exploded under the
driver's seat of her car. Oakland police immediately arrested the
pair, alleging that they were transporting the bomb. But the
Alameda County district attorney's office refused to file charges,
citing lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Now a freelance reporter named Ed Gehrman, who is also a peace
activist and a special education teacher in Plumas County, and
Vassar College English Professor Don Foster say an analysis of
writing styles suggests that a letter claiming to be from the
bomber was written by Bari's ex-husband, Mike Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, who studies textual and linguistic analysis, compared
the writing styles of several people close to Bari with the style
in three letters perhaps linked to the bomber: a warning addressed
to Bari, an offer to Ukiah police to inform on Earth First, and a
letter from the ``Lord's Avenger,'' claiming to be from the bomber,
sent to Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat reporter Mike Geniella.
It was filled with details about the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Foster wrote in Flatland, an alternative magazine in Mendocino
County, that ``among the examined documents, only one writer
emerges from the pack as a plausible author of the Lord's Avenger
letter: Mike Sweeney.'' Gehrman wrote a lengthy article in the same
issue alleging that Sweeney had the motive and opportunity to put a
bomb in Bari's car.
</P>
<P>
   The two articles have attracted so much attention that Bruce
Anderson, editor and publisher of the Mendocino County weekly, the
Anderson Valley Advertiser, last week urged the FBI to reopen its
investigation and question Sweeney for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a total hoax,'' counters Sweeney, a Mendocino County
waste management company executive who lives in Ukiah with his and
Bari's two daughters. ``A total black propaganda thing. It's a
tragedy that good old Judi isn't here to take care of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherney, Bari's close associate who was also injured in the
bombing, says the Flatland report is nothing more than a wild
accusation by ``a bunch of nut cases, disrupters.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherney, who remains a high-profile activist with Earth First,
added, ``I have no great love for Mike Sweeney, but we've looked at
him through and through, and we know he's innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney's name had surfaced as one of several possible suspects
in 1991, but Bari denounced the report then and insisted on
Sweeney's innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Gehrman said he began his investigation after Bari herself cast
suspicions on an acquaintance of his, a left political activist.
Convinced that his friend was wrongly accused, Gehrman spent three
years on research but did not interview Bari, who was alive when he
began his research, or Sweeney or Cherney.
</P>
<P>
   Gehrman said he first brought his suspicions to the FBI, which
didn't seem interested. Then he sought help from Foster, whose
literary sleuthing into writing styles identified former Newsweek
columnist Joe Klein as the anonymous author of the political novel
``Primary Colors.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Foster emphasized that ``I'm not accusing Mike
Sweeney of anything, but from a bunch of possible suspects . . . he
was the one whose writing forms the best match. That is not to say
he bombed Judi Bari.''
</P>
<P>
   On his Web page, Sweeney has posted his own lengthy critique of
Foster's and Gehrman's work.
</P>
<P>
   Bari's supporters share her belief that law enforcement was
either involved in the bombing, or tacitly encouraged others to
act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under normal conditions, the husband would be a suspect, but
these were not normal conditions,'' Cherney said last week. ``We
received about three dozen threatening events _ personal attacks,
death threats, phony letters. There was a concerted effort against
us. Within five minutes after the bombing, the FBI shows up and
blames us for bombing ourselves. Clearly, this all happened in a
political context. The timber industry and some disinformationists
set us up, and the FBI tried to frame us afterwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Bari, author of a book called ``Timber Wars,'' which attacked
the industry, complained that her car had been run off the road by
logging trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Cherney and Bari sued the FBI and Oakland police in 1991,
seeking compensatory damages of $1 million each _ plus punitive
damages _ for false arrest, fabricating evidence and violating
their civil rights. They contended that an examination of internal
FBI documents shows the agency never conducted a serious
investigation to find out who carried out the bombing. Instead,
they said, the agency spent its energies checking out Earth First
contacts in order to discredit them.
</P>
<P>
   That lawsuit now languishes in the U.S. District Court of Judge
Claudia Wilkin in Oakland, with pieces of it on appeal by both
sides. No trial date is on the horizon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
