</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ The ethnic Albanian rebel army in
Kosovo has told the United States that its leaders are ready to
sign a peace agreement intended to end months of fighting in the
troubled province and to allow for the entry of a NATO peacekeeping
force, the State Department announced. If the rebel leaders are
true to their word, the decision would allow the United States and
its NATO allies to raise the diplomatic and military pressure on
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia, whom they have always
attempted to paint as the principal villain in the fighting in
Kosovo. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON (Managua, Nicaragua) _ President Clinton opened a
four-day visit to Central America in Nicaragua to survey the
devastation left by Hurricane Mitch and promote stable democracies
in a region once shattered by civil wars. When Air Force One landed
on a warm, windy morning at Augusto Cesar Sandino International
Airport, Clinton became the first U.S. president to visit Nicaragua
since Lyndon Johnson in 1968. (Early summary by wires).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ With circuit courts split on immigration,
and thousands of cases bulging the federal court system, the
Supreme Court declines the opportunity to interpret the 1996
immigration law. The cases they avoid taking raised statutory and
constitutional questions. Other high court action. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ILL-PROSECUTERS-CHARGED (Chicago) An extraordinary trial will
begin Tuesday in a well-heeled Chicago suburb, a trial that could
have reverberations throughout the nation's criminal justice
system. In a case that is considered virtually unprecedented, three
former prosecutors in affluent DuPage County are being tried on
charges that they and four sheriff's deputies conspired to frame an
innocent man, sending him to death row for the 1983 rape and murder
of a 10-year-old girl. The sheriff's deputies have also been
charged in the case, known as the trial of the DuPage Seven. By Pam
Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-ANTITRUST (Washington) The federal government announced
that it has reached a tentative settlement in its antitrust case
that was to begin this week against the Intel Corporation, the
world's largest producer of computer chips. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
</TEXT>
