<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2085 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDLAND-DECLINE-2TAKE     03-08 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDLAND-DECLINE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECLINE IN OIL PRICES LEAVES MANY TOWNS IN WEST TEXAS DEVASTATED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDLAND, Texas _ They've seen it all before, the moving vans and
U-Haul trailers streaming toward the exits, the graveyards of steel
sprouting along the desert roadsides, the dust darkening the
windows where lustrous deals had been done and the long, weathered
faces in the unemployment line.
</P>
<P>
   The last time was in 1986, when the price of oil dropped from
$30 a barrel to $10 almost overnight, and people left town so fast
they didn't pause to lock up behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are seeing it again, although this time it is
different. This time, the rot spread slow and deep across the
Permian Basin, crept in so gingerly that it was almost
imperceptible until the foundation buckled and the roof sagged.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a year and a half, oil prices receded in increments
that minimized panic _ a buck here, half a buck there _ until a
barrel of crude was worth less than a bucket of fried chicken.
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of February, the spot price for West Texas
Intermediate fell to as low as $8 a barrel _ the lowest
inflation-adjusted price since the Great Depression _ and the broad
consequences set in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty ugly out here,'' said Marshall Watson, an
independent producer, who recently laid off six of his eight
employees and shut in half of his 150 stripper wells. ``This crash
is 10 times worse than the '86 crash. Back then, the price dropped
and came right back. This has been a long drought. It costs $12 to
lift a barrel of oil that we can sell for $9. We're down to the
bare knuckles.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is betting on a quick recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Oil is abundant around the globe, and troubled economies in Asia
and South America have reduced demand.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, alternative energy and renewable motor fuels have
achieved such prominence in the marketplace that Arco Chairman Mike
Bowlin recently said the world is seeing the beginning of the end
of the Oil Age.
</P>
<P>
   Watson also believes that the ``long drought'' that began in
November 1997 and accelerated late last year may be the death
rattle of the Permian Basin, which, in its heyday, produced more
oil than any field in the lower 48 states and was the well that
irrigated the Texas economy.
</P>
<P>
   Now, exploration is almost nonexistent, scores of pumps have
been turned off and the crude flows from the basin at a relative
trickle. Service companies that once thrived on drilling now
survive by plugging holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once those wells are plugged,'' Watson said, ``they'll never
be reopened. The workers are leaving and they won't come back. This
is a friendly ghost town.''
</P>
<P>
   Alarmist hyperbole? Maybe. Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, cities such as Midland and Odessa appear far
from dressed for a funeral. In fact, a regional economic index
prepared early this year by Ingham Economic Reporting shows only a
fractional decline during 1998, thanks mainly to strong retail
sales, motor vehicle sales and motel/hotel revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath that gloss, however, are more troubling numbers: Permits
for new home construction fell nearly 2.3 percent, the value of all
building permits declined by 25 percent and sales of existing homes
dropped from 2,290 to 1,642.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate jumped from 3.8 percent to 6.5 percent
during the year and reached 9 percent at the end of February. More
than 1,900 jobs were lost last year in Midland and Ector counties
and hundreds more vanished in the other 15 counties of the Permian
Basin.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the downward spiral of those key indicators was the oil
and gas activity index, which tumbled 32 percent during the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things were going extremely well here,'' Dennis Clayton,
economic development director of the Midland Chamber of Commerce,
said of the years following the 1986 calamity. ``There was a good
recovery and people were smarter at using technology in getting oil
out of the ground cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Oil never went back to $30 a barrel, but producers and their
communities learned to live, and prosper, with $20 to $22. Even
when prices settled into the $15 to $16 range, Clayton said, there
was only a small scratch on the basin's economic EKG, because
Midland and Odessa, the major population centers, had begun to wean
themselves from oil dependency.
</P>
<P>
   Development along Loop 250 north of Midland brought in large
retailers and a string of casual-dining chains. A new terminal was
built at Midland International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Law firms that had once wallowed exclusively in oil contracts
branched out with offices in Dallas and Austin. Westwood Medical
Center joined the older Memorial Hospital to help turn the city
into a health care center.
</P>
<P>
   Oil, which had accounted for 50 percent of the city's economy in
1986, began to play a smaller role, declining to about 25 percent
to 30 percent by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Still, according to the Texas comptroller's office,
Midland-Odessa remained among the most oil-dependent metro areas in
the state. When prices slipped below $10 a barrel late last year,
the bills for that dependency came due.
</P>
<P>
   During January and February of this year, 248 bankruptcy
petitions were filed in Midland, compared with 115 during the first
two months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year,'' said Christy Carouth, deputy in charge of the
bankruptcy court, ``we started out higher than any year in history,
and they were all personal bankruptcies _ no companies. The
companies have nothing to reorganize with. They have no hope now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`IT'S GOING TO BE TOUGH' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about to destroy the communities in West Texas,'' said
John Bell, a resident of one of the most endangered. Kermit, west
of Midland-Odessa, sits in the middle of Winkler County, 841 square
miles of sand dunes, prairie and wells that now sip from the earth
rather than drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools are in danger of being closed out here,'' Bell said.
``We may lose our hospital. Parts of county government may have to
shut down. Thousands have been laid off. We're backed into a real
corner.''
</P>
<P>
   There are only two towns in the county of 8,626 _ Wink is the
other _ and, but for oil, neither had a reason to exist.
Unemployment has hit 17 percent in the county and a shrinking tax
base threatens to nearly halve the county's $8 million budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our tax base is 86 percent minerals and ancillary
industries,'' said County Judge Bonnie Leck. ``The county provides
virtually all services _ airport, swimming pools, library, parks,
hospitals, senior citizen services, everything. When you're facing
a decline of 40 percent in values, it is not business as usual.
Severe cuts will be necessitated.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Raising taxes to fund government is not an option, she said.
``Counties have a cap on how much they can tax,'' she said, ``and
even if we raised them, people wouldn't be able to pay them.''
</P>
<P>
   All across the basin, the story is the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``The financial shortages facing some school districts ... are
staggering,'' said state Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander. She
said the hardest-hit district probably will be Iraan-Sheffield in
Pecos County, which could lose $8 million of the $18 million it
normally collects in ad valorem taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough,'' agreed Jeff Bright, business manager
for the district. ``We have enough fund balance to get through a
year or two, but that's all unless the Legislature helps us out.''
</P>
<P>
   Since oil prices are a function of the global market, West Texas
producers are finding political relief hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's solution is to raise oil prices. To that end, he has
testified before congressional committees and organized a march on
the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Results have been minimal.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has promised to take some oil off the market
by replenishing the Strategic Petroleum Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature is moving toward a $45 million tax break that
would exempt small producers _ those whose wells produce fewer than
15 barrels a day _ from the 4.6 percent severance tax when the
price of oil falls below $15 a barrel. That exemption would apply
to 83 percent of the wells in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly would apply to Bell, whose nine wells combined
produce only 12 barrels a day. He does not believe it will be
enough to save the West Texas oil industry, however.
</P>
<P>
   Bell and many other producers want the government to impose
import restrictions to keep OPEC nations from ``dumping cheap
foreign oil into the U.S. market.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been disappointed in the reception that idea has
received,'' he said. ``Sometimes our politicians fiddle while Rome
burns.''
</P>
<P>
   Oilmen recognize that most of the country, enjoying cheap
gasoline and heating oil, prefers the fiddling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oil industry doesn't have any allies,'' Watson said. ``We
can't expect much help from the government. There are more
downstream workers (refiners, chemical processors and the like)
than there are upstream. They would get hammered by an import
tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with an unsympathetic government, some independent oilmen
have discussed the possibility of going to court.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't deal with predatory pricing in Washington, we may
be able to deal with it at the courthouse,'' independent oilman
John Houghton told the Midland Reporter-Telegram recently. ``We are
told (it) would be complicated, difficult and costly, but there
could be grounds for such a suit.''
</P>
<P>
   It could also be time-consuming _ and many in the Permian Basin
feel that time is running out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billions of dollars are being taken out of our industry,''
said Jim Henry, who, with 800 wells, is one of the larger of the
so-called small independents. ``We're losing investment capital.
We're losing experienced personnel. When the time comes to turn
around, it will be very difficult to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`WE ARE BRACING FOR THE CRUNCH' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Throughout downtown Midland, ``For Lease'' signs hang in the
windows of buildings once occupied by banks and major oil
companies. They are remnants of the '86 bust, not the current one,
but they are a reminder of something lost forever.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years ago, big oil left town, or severely restricted
its presence here. Even in the happy years of recovery, the
occupancy rate for commercial real estate never rose above the 65
percent level it reached that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It absolutely collapsed and never came back,'' said Don Davis
of MRO Management Inc., the city's leading broker in commercial
space. ``It just stayed there all these years.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't expect the vacancy rate to change much in the next
couple of years because ``the damage has already been done.''
</P>
<P>
   But the longer oil prices remain depressed, the less certain
anyone here is of the future.
</P>
<P>
   The Midland County Commission recently adopted a series of
policies to deal with the ``financial crisis'' _ a hiring freeze,
curtailing overtime _ and even considered the elimination of an
entire county department.
</P>
<P>
   The school district, facing a $2.5 million shortfall after
mineral values dropped by $250 million, is also reaching for the
scalpel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are bracing for the crunch,'' said Superintendent Joe
Garessi. ``We will probably scale back across the board. We will
spend some money out of reserves but we are going to be very
conservative in hiring. A high number of teachers are leaving
because their husbands are going elsewhere to work. We may not
replace some of them.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the price of West Texas oil moved back above $12
on the New York Mercantile Exchange. That was little consolation,
however, since most stripper well operators sell at the ``spot''
price, which tends to trail futures prices by $3 a barrel or so.
</P>
<P>
   Henry said the current slump is likely to continue until the
global balance of supply and demand is restored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to plan and try to survive with low oil prices,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
