<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLEY-VALLEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILICON VALLEY AND SILICON ALLEY MEET VENTURE CAPITALISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hoping to drum up funding from some of the
world's preeminent venture capital firms, New York City multimedia
start-ups are expected to strut their wares before Bay Area venture
capitalists this week at a conference titled ``Alley to the
Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   The name was taken from Silicon Alley _ the region of Manhattan
from the Flatiron Building on 41st Street to the southern tip of
the city _ and Silicon Valley, the mother lode of technology in
Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   About 360 Silicon Alley firms, Bay Area venture capitalists and
private investors are expected to attend the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The East and West coasts need to do business together,'' said
Anna Wheatley, editor in chief of AlleyCat News, a New York-based
magazine targeted at Silicon Alley firms and co-host of the
conference. The New York City Economic Development Corp. is also
hosting the event.
</P>
<P>
   Wheatley said Silicon Alley, which began earlier this decade, is
now a force to be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   A Coopers &AMP; Lybrand report estimated that the number of jobs in
Silicon Alley, which is made up primarily of Internet content
providers, will reach 100,000 by the beginning of next year.
</P>
<P>
   According to Price Waterhouse Coopers Money Tree, which tracks
venture capital investments, venture funding for Silicon Alley
firms increased nearly five-fold from 1995 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, the total dollar amount, which had been
secured mainly from East Coast investment sources, went from $51.7
million to $249.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Wheatley would not disclose all the Bay Area firms attending
``Alley to the Valley,'' but said a number of major venture
capitalists would be present.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lax, a partner at Softbank Technology Ventures in San
Jose. Calif., said the conference will allow his firm to see who's
doing what in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an aggressive reach-out mode,'' Lax said. ``What they're
obviously trying to do is take the best (Silicon Alley companies)
and expose them to the best VCs.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Silicon Alley firms agreed the conference will be a useful
networking opportunity. But they weren't optimistic about getting
funding from Bay Area VCs.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Burns, chief executive of New York-based AdOne LLC, the
parent of ClassifiedWarehouse.com, said Bay Area venture firms
don't have much incentive to invest outside their region.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, there is a tremendous amount of start-up activity
on the West Coast,'' Burns said. ``For the most part, the (Bay
Area) VC firms don't have to travel. Some say, `I don't even go to
San Francisco.' When you take a statement like that, you say what's
the justification for someone to invest on another coast?''
</P>
<P>
   Bahar Gidwani, CEO of Index Stock Imagery, a Silicon Alley firm
that sells stock photos over the Internet, said some Bay Area VCs
don't take investing in Web content companies as seriously as they
should.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why a lot of the West Coast (VCs) have
invested in certain things,'' such as hardware infrastructure,
Gidwani said. ``How can you do anything interesting if you don't
have good (Internet) content? The VCs out there don't get it. It's
content.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Millard, president of the New York City Economic
Development Corp., said that even if Silicon Alley firms don't
secure funding this week, there are other ways they can make
valuable business connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies that come here seek a number of things'' in
addition to funding, Millard said. ``They seek strategic partners,
potential acquirers and relationships with other companies in the
Internet space. The first goal is funding, but our other goals are
just as important.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gorenberg, a partner at Hummer Winblad _ which has invested
in a few Silicon Alley firms, including The Knot, an on-line
wedding registry business, and BizTravel.com, a travel reservations
site for business people _ said location doesn't drive his firm's
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We invest everywhere,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
