<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-CZAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATION'S FIRST PRIVACY CZAR IS A COMPUTER WHIZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ When Peter P. Swire was a student at the Albany
Academy, a private preparatory school here, he excelled in math and
half a dozen sports. But at home one of his biggest interests was
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, nearly a quarter century later, Swire will have a big say
in the use of electronic information in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Ohio State University law professor was named by
Vice President Al Gore to be the nation's first ``privacy czar.''
</P>
<P>
   Swire, a 1976 graduate of the academy, is an expert on financial
privacy and the protection of electronic personal information that
is used by seemingly every business in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``With new technology, there's new privacy issues all the
time,'' said Swire in a telephone interview. ``Privacy's been a
controversial political topic in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Swire also co-wrote the book ``None of Your Business: World Data
Flows, Electronic Commerce and the Internet Privacy Directive.'' He
has written dozens of papers and delivered speeches on the issue.
Now he will divide his time between his professorship in Ohio and
his new position in Washington, D.C. as chief counselor for privacy
at the federal Office of Management and Budget. At the end of the
spring semester, he will move his family to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At Albany Academy, Swire was one of the top students in his
class. According to Bob Olcott, a retired teacher, Swire was a
problem-solver with an active mind and plenty of creativity. He not
only helped lead the school's math club, he also played tennis,
soccer, ran cross-country and wrestled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was solving problems out there on the mat at the same time
he was dealing with the physical side of the sport,'' Olcott said.
</P>
<P>
   William Swire of Albany, the 72-year-old father of Peter Swire,
said his son's interest in electronics began in high school. The
elder Swire owned the Mayfair furniture company here and developed
a software program that he later sold to businesses around the
country. On his summer vacation, Peter would tinker with the
program and had a hand in perfecting it.
</P>
<P>
   At Princeton University, Peter Swire wrote his senior thesis on
how technology was going to change the world. After college and law
school, he married Anne Putney, a graduate of the Albany Academy
for Girls. He began his career as an associate lawyer for a
Washington, D.C. firm with an expertise in environment, banking and
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Swire, now 40, taught at the University of Virginia from 1990 to
1996 before moving to Ohio State University College of Law.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Swire said Gore's staff called him last year because of
his expertise in cyberspace, and invited him to apply for the
position Gore had created. The job, which pays $125,000, will last
until the end of the Clinton administration, when Swire will return
to Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Swire says he will help get the federal government to discuss
with states different privacy issues, such as New York's
contemplation of selling Department of Motor Vehicle names to
private companies. He will also have a hand in the creation of
privacy bills and other issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1654EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
