  THIS IS THE STATES NEWS SERVICE BUDGET FOR MARCH
8, 1999. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT 202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA-SCHOOLS-FUNDING. California's schools are losing more
than $3 million a year in funding because the federal government
misallocates Title I dollars, according to a congressional research
arm. More than 40 members of the state delegation sent a letter
last week to the U.S. Education Department urging the reform of
three federal programs that undercount California elementary
students. By Mark Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-MUNICIPAL. Representatives of Maine's cities and towns are
in Washington this week to ask Congress to keep its promise to help
local governments pay for expensive, federally mandated programs
they say pose a threat to municipal budgets. By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN-DRIVE-STUDY. A new study shows that Detroit ranks 18th
of major U.S. metro areas in aggressive driving deaths. By C.J.
Karamargin
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN-BROWN-AUTOS. EPA Administrator Carol Browner told the
Council for Urban Economic Development today that new auto emission
standards will be released next month. By C.J. Karamargin
</P>
<P>
   MULTICHANNEL-FIRST. The judicial branch was a strong defender of
the broadcasting and cable industries' freedom of speech in 1998,
while Congress and the Clinton administration fell short, according
to an evaluation by a First Amendment advocacy group. By Laura
Maggi
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY-JUDGE. The White House nominated Judge Julio M.
Fuentes, Superior Court of New Jersey, Essex County, for the Third
Circuit Court of Appeals. If confirmed, Fuentes will be the first
Hispanic to sit on the Third Circuit bench, which is one step below
the Supreme Court. By Paul Kane
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY-LAUTENBERG-RETIRE. Sen. Frank Lautenberg stamps out
any speculation that he was reconsidering his retirement, as
reported Monday by a Capitol Hill publication. By Paul Kane
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-IMMIGRATION. The 60-day reprieve from deportation for
Salvadorans and Guatemalans ended Monday, but immigrant advocates
say it would be better to let them stay here and work so they could
send money back to their homeland. By Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-SURPLUS-SOCSEC. While the Wisconsin delegation agrees
that at least 62 percent of the projected budget surplus must be
used to ``save Social Security,'' the details beyond that may
create enough conflict to prevent Congress from passing legislation
this year to keep the ailing retirement fund solvent past 2030.
(Working.) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
