<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-BOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OH, MONICA, THIS IS MORE THAN WE WANTED TO KNOW
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by LEWINSKY-OTHERS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rarely, but sometimes, the publication of a book is a sad
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   It happens when a wretched sequel follows a fabulous novel
(''Texasville'' after ``The Last Picture Show''), or when a gifted
author turns out unreadable gibberish (Norman Mailer's ``Ancient
Evenings''), or when obvious fluff is accepted by hundreds of
thousands of readers who want push-button answers to their problems
(any printed prattlings of Mars-Venus author John Gray).
</P>
<P>
   But the arrival of ``Monica's Story'' may be the saddest moment
yet in modern publishing.
</P>
<P>
   It is not, in any literary sense, a very good book. Andrew
Morton can put words together decently, but his role here is more
as translator than anything else. Morton is relating this tawdry
tale from a third-person perspective, but everyone who reads it
will assume Lewinsky is the author. Subjects of books do not
receive $600,000 advances from publishers.
</P>
<P>
   So the book's ``voice,'' what the reader hears in his head as
his eyes fix on the printed pages, is stilted. Morton isn't telling
us what he thinks, but what Monica thinks, and obviously what
Monica thinks is that this is her best chance to make people feel
sorry for her and mad at the same individuals she's mad at,
particularly Linda Tripp and Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   So, via Morton, Monica spills her guts, and, as great American
wit Fran Leibowitz once pointed out, for onlookers that's just
about as attractive as it sounds. We must know it all, Monica
believes, and so it includes messy details about her parents'
divorce, how future TV star Tori Spelling invited everybody in
class but Monica to her birthday party (and Michael Jackson and the
world's tiniest pony were going to be there!), how Monica could
signal Bill Clinton she ``knew the rules'' about affairs with
married men because she'd already had such an extended one with
somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   There's much detail about Monica's ongoing fixation with her
weight and the book's intended bombshell: that while involved with
Clinton she also dallied with another man, becoming pregnant with
and subsequently aborting his baby.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is sad because anyone's private life and private
demons seem demeaning when offered for examination by the rest of
the world. The definition of maturity is not doing things you very
much want to but shouldn't. So in that way, ``Monica's Story'' is
the equivalent of a kindergarten kid confessing cookie-jar sins to
Mommy and Daddy, hoping they'll still love her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica's Story'' is also sad because its very existence is
testimony to how judgmental our society has become. Like the O.J.
Simpson case, Clinton-Monica has become less a topic for discussion
than for labeling. You can have any opinion on either, and to a
large, loud-mouthed percentage of the American public you've just
proved you're a moral and intellectual loser. Like her superficial
TV interrogation by Barbara Walters, ``Monica's Story'' will be,
for too many people, just another chance to say ugly things about
somebody else. (''I can't believe this moral degenerate/spoiled
brat said that in her book!'' ``I can't believe how this poor sweet
girl has suffered so unfairly at the hands of Bill Clinton/Kenneth
Starr/Linda Tripp/the media.'')
</P>
<P>
   But I think ``Monica's Story'' is saddest because it really has
no heroes. Nobody in this book comes off well. It won't make any
Clinton-bashers think they maybe were wrong about ol' Bill, or
Starr-haters decide Ken really meant well, gosh darn it. If
Lewinsky disgusted you before you read the book, she'll still
disgust you afterward. Revealing everything has, predictably, the
same effect as revealing nothing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Book: ``Monica's Story''
</P>
<P>
   Author: Andrew Morton
</P>
<P>
   Type: Biography
</P>
<P>
   Publisher: St. Martin's Press, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
