<HEADLINE>
IT TAKES A SCIENTIST TO TIE A NECKTIE, 85 DIFFERENT WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists are constantly striving to do good for the common
man. Now, two physicists in Britain have come to the aid of the
well-dressed one.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking a marriage of science and beauty, Thomas M.A. Fink and
Yong Mao, research fellows at Cambridge University, have applied
the rigors of mathematics to that most basic of fashion statements,
the necktie knot. In the process they have come up with six new
ways of tying a tie.
</P>
<P>
   Fink, who in his more serious moments investigates protein
folding, and Mao, who specializes in colloids and polymers, felt
that the world might be ready for a new knot or two.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four in common use, the four-in-hand (so named because it
was used by drivers of four-in-hand carriages) dates from the 19th
century, while the Windsor and its smaller cousin, the
half-Windsor, were popularized in the 1930s by the Duke of Windsor.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Pratt knot, which was publicized about a decade ago,
has a more recent history, and there are some people who dismiss it
as simply a reverse Windsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought there are probably unknown knots that have yet to
be stumbled upon,'' Fink said in a telephone interview. Their idea,
he said, was to create a mathematical framework that captured the
elements of knot-tying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficult part was converting esthetic criteria into
mathematical constraints,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, who described their research in the current
issue of the journal Nature, used as their knot-tying model the
idea of a random walk on a triangular lattice.
</P>
<P>
   Such a lattice has three axes, and movements along them
correspond to the three possible movements of the business end of a
tie: to the left, to the right or to the center.
</P>
<P>
   A random walk is just that. It is as if a drunk were reeling
around a room, unable to control the direction of each step. The
trajectory that results satisfies certain mathematical properties,
making random walks useful in explaining physical phenomena like
the diffusion of gases.
</P>
<P>
   Fink and Mao used a variant, known as a ``persistent'' random
walk, in which consecutive moves could not be made in the same
direction (for the obvious reason that in knot tying, a move such
as passing the wide end of the tie to the right over the narrow end
cannot be made twice in a row). They also had to take into account
another characteristic of tying a necktie: the moves alternate
between heading toward, and away from, the shirt.
</P>
<P>
   In their work, a map of a walk corresponds to the movements of
the wide end of the tie. Using an upper limit of nine moves (based
on practical considerations of tie length) the researchers
determined that 85 different knots are possible. But once they
allowed for esthetic qualities like symmetry (whether the number of
left and right moves are equal) and balance (the order of moves,
with a good mix being better), the list narrowed to 10, including
the four in common use. Knots with even numbers of moves begin with
a move toward the shirt, while those with odd numbers start with a
move away from it (and must begin with the tie inside out).
</P>
<P>
   The key to their analysis, Fink said, was making the connection
to the idea of a random walk. ``We played around with ties in the
office, but it wasn't obvious at first that there was this
mathematical simplicity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The more they experimented (switching eventually to short pieces
of rope because it was easier to see what was going on), the more
they recognized that tying a tie was like wrapping it around the
hub of a three-spoke wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you make that realization,'' Fink said, ``it becomes
apparent that a walk on a triangular lattice captures the math
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Fink wears a tie often around the office, and always at meals,
as Cambridge still requires jacket and tie in the dining halls. He
used to opt for the half-Windsor (which, he and Mao note, is really
three-quarters of a Windsor).
</P>
<P>
   But these days he often finds himself sporting one of the new
knots, known simply as ``7, 2,'' the 7 denoting the total number of
moves (but not including the final move through the loop that
cinches the knot) and the 2 denoting the number of center moves.
</P>
<P>
   It's not much of a name, Fink acknowledged. ``But when you have
six knots, you run out of names, so we haven't named any of them,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers will leave that to others. Their foray into
fashion is over; now it's back to proteins and colloids and other
theoretical matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really sort of went as far as one could,'' Fink said. ``I
certainly don't think we'll be moving into bow ties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
