<HEADLINE>
HOW ASTEROIDS JUMP  
 AFRICA PARTING  
 THE SKIN AS LUNGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most asteroids lead a benign existence, content to linger in
their main belt between Mars and Jupiter, following an elliptical
orbit around the Sun. But some wind up nearer Earth, where the
potential for a life-threatening collision inspires fear and film
scripts.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how an asteroid jumps across Mars orbit to near-Earth
space has always been something of a mystery. Now, scientists from
Italy and the Czech Republic, writing in the journal Science, offer
an explanation as to how small asteroids and asteroid fragments
make the leap.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, the scientists have dusted off a phenomenon first
described a century ago. It is called the Yarkovsky effect, for the
Russian engineer who discovered it, and holds that spinning bodies
warmed by sunlight gain heat in a nonuniform manner, which in turn
leads to small orbital shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Using simulations, the scientists showed that over millions of
years, the effect can cause an asteroid's semimajor axis (half the
long axis of the ellipse) to drift a few million miles or so. That
is enough to bring some asteroids in the inner part of the main
belt close enough to Mars that other forces take over, slinging the
rocks into orbits that bring them near Earth. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A more down-to-Earth drift concerns two scientists at Rice
University, who have provided further understanding of how the
Earth's crust is moving in Africa, where things are coming apart.
</P>
<P>
   The split is occurring at the East African rift, a 2,400-mile
zone that runs north-south from Djibouti to Mozambique and is
dramatically revealed in the rift valleys of Kenya and Tanzania.
The zone is the boundary of two tectonic plates, the Nubian on the
west and the Somalian on the east.
</P>
<P>
   But the boundary continues south of the zone, where there is no
evidence of rifting. The Rice scientists, who reported on their
work in the journal Nature, found the first evidence of movement in
this part of the boundary, in the Indian Ocean where the two plates
meet a third, the Antarctic plate. Their findings explain why there
is no evidence of a split south of the rift zone: in this area, the
two plates are converging.
</P>
<P>
   By studying measurements of sea floor spreading, the scientists
determined that the Nubian and Somalian plates are rotating
slightly with respect to each other, so that the same force that is
causing the plates to separate in the rift zone at a rate of about
one-quarter of an inch a year is making them come together, at a
slightly slower rate, at the southern end. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who needs lungs? Not a tiny Australian mouse that in its first
days after birth breathes mostly through its skin.
</P>
<P>
   The mouse, a marsupial called the Julia Creek dunnart that lives
among cracks in the bone-dry soil of northeastern Australia,
produces offspring that are among the smallest newborn mammals
known, about one-sixth of an inch long and weighing slightly more
than half an ounce.
</P>
<P>
   The newborn mouse is not very well developed, with cartilage for
bones and a small number of spherical air sacs for lungs. In the
first few days after birth, the animal's body movements do not seem
to expand the air sacs appreciably.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not seem to matter, according to the Canadian and
Australian researchers who studied the animal and reported on their
findings in Nature. The young mouse's skin is hairless and rich in
blood, providing a convenient means for gas exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Using an apparatus that included a tiny jury-rigged mask to
cover the mouse's mouth and nostrils, the researchers measured the
exchange of oxygen and carbon dioxide both through the sacs and
through the skin. For mice up to about four ounces in weight,
respiration through the skin exceeded that through the lungs. As
the mice grew more, the lungs took over; at three weeks old and
about 10 ounces, exchange through the skin was about a third that
through the lungs. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
