u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FITNESS-CAPOEIRA-     03-08 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FITNESS-CAPOEIRA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZILIAN MARTIAL ART FOR MIND AND BODY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
 (The Science Times)  
(lh) 
 By ERIC V. COPAGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It had been over two years since my last visit to the gym, and
it was beginning to show. While on a business trip last December, I
was dismayed when I stepped out of the shower into a bathroom that
could have doubled as a shrine to Narcissus. I noticed that the
abdominal six-pack I once maintained almost effortlessly was
threatening to become a keg. The shoulders that had given my body a
horizon line, sagged so that they were hard to differentiate from
my lower trunk. And the arms, while never pythons, were once sinewy
cobras that could have belonged to a dancer. Now they were garden
snakes.
</P>
<P>
   I resolved to do something about my physical deterioration. But
one reason I quit running, rowing, walking and lifting free weights
was because of the mind-numbing repetition. And I lacked the time.
What I needed was one exercise that would address cardiovascular
fitness, grace, balance, flexibility, muscular strength and that
was also, well, kind of fun.
</P>
<P>
   I remembered seeing many years ago a demonstration of capoeira
(cop-WAY-ruh), a martial art created by Africans taken as slaves to
Brazil. A few moves, like spinning on one's head seemed straight
out of break dancing; others seemed worthy of an Olympic gymnastics
competition. Though I was amazed by capoeira's unusual method of
self-defense, what struck me was the practitioners' nimble, yet
steely bodies.
</P>
<P>
   So recently I called up the Brazilian consulate to find out
more. The first thing I learned was that capoeira was developed in
Brazil by enslaved Africans hundreds of years ago. To the casual
observer, the practice looked like innocent dance. But at a
privotal moment, when the plantation owner was alone or distracted,
the capoeirista would take that same dance-like gesture, move it a
crucial inch or two nearer the opponent's body and strike a blow
for freedom. It was also once used by street gangs, and its
practice at various times has been outlawed in Brazil. Despite the
self-defense aspect of the activity, when two capoeiristas get
together, they call it ``play.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two basic styles of capoeira: Angola is slower, nearer
to the ground and more closely resembles dance or slow t'ai chi.
Regional (hay-jhon-AL) is faster and flashier, with a repertoire of
swift ankle sweeps and chin-high kicks that one can easily imagine
settling a bar bet.
</P>
<P>
   I decided to attend a class in regional at the White Street
Center, a dance/exercise studio in New York City, given by Edna
Lima, 36, who has been teaching capoeira since she was 14. She is
one of the few mestrandas, or female capoeira masters, in the
world. (Capoeira is historically a male preserve, but in the
classes I observed up to half of the students were women.) Ms.
Lima, who specializes in regional style, was resplendent in
waist-long braids and an easy smile. Her gait was one of feline
grace and confidence, which I assumed emanated from growing up to
the sound of samba in Brasilia. Or perhaps it came from being not
only a capoeira master, but also a fourth-degree black belt in
karate. Yet, as the other 12 members of the class straggled in, I
noticed they had a similar gait: shoulders back, women a slight
catwalk sashay, men a subtle swagger.
</P>
<P>
   For this lesson, I wore Navy-blue sweats and a Reebok T-shirt. I
felt, but was not made to feel, like a blasphemer, as the class
came dressed, like Ms. Lima, in baggy white draw-string pants and
loose fitting T-shirts. Wearing white dates back to the
capoeiristas of hundreds of years ago, Ms. Lima said. They would
wear their best clothes, white linen, to church or to a party, and
then take part in capoeira afterward, she explained. ``If you can
keep your clothes clean _ it means you weren't taken down _ it
shows your skill,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Asian martial arts, capoeira is not just a physical skill,
but also a mental exercise and a cultural and spiritual discipline.
Music, mainly chanting accompanied by percussion, is an integral
part. In our class, an assistant played the berimbau, an ancient
stringed instrument, which is the central symbol of capoeira. This
instrument, along with drums, a cowbell and tambourine, provide
accompaniment for the roda (ho-da), the last part of each class
when the students form a circle and ``play'' capoeira with one
another.
</P>
<P>
   After a 20-minute warm-up that included stretching and a little
jogging, Ms. Lima asked us to turn away from the wall-wide mirror.
``Staring at your reflection teaches you to look outside,'' Ms.
Lima later told me. ``I want my students to feel the correct body
position. It takes longer, but once they get it right, it stays
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, she began calling out moves, which I came to understand
are the building blocks of the sport. The basic move is called,
ginga, which acts as a thread from one movement to the next. Most
of the movements are described by Portuguese words, though some
come from African languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ginga,'' Ms. Lima says, and I watch and imitate the class: We
sink into a lunge position, arms with elbows down, forearms up to
block a phantom attack. We slide our feet on the hardwood floor,
bobbing like boxers, staying in constant motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meia lua de Frente,'' Ms. Lima says, and we swing our right
feet in a semicircle, face high. Then we go back to the ginga.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rasteira de chao,'' Ms. Lima commands, and we drop to a squat,
our hands touching the floor and extend one leg full-length on the
ground, and swing it so it resembles an arc.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Lima demonstrates a move to the class, she describes what
it is used for. ``The hand is up so that it can block,'' she said.
Or ``the sweep is not a ballet move, but is to knock your
opponent's feet from under him.'' Despite the talk of knocking and
blocking, Ms. Lima explained: ``It's not a fight. In a fight there
is a winner and loser. Capoeira is a game, a game of wits. The idea
is not to outmuscle your opponent, but to outfox him. The ultimate
goal is to reach some kind of harmony.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After 45 minutes it is time to put all the parts together. The
students gather into a roda, or circle, in which the capoeiristas
``play.'' Clapping and the soft syncopation of drumming rise like
incense and fill the room. I try to add my voice to the chant in
Portuguese that goes up from our roda: ``Now is the time to show
your skills.'' As we chant, I imagine another scene. It is the
slave quarters on plantations in Brazil where capoeira is believed
to have taken root, when knowing capoeira was a matter of freedom
and captivity, life and death.
</P>
<P>
   Though I was not ready to actually ``play,'' I watched with awe
as two of my classmates faced off. With the rest of us circled
around them, each kneeled on one leg before the drums, facing one
another other. They made the sign of the cross, then tumbled and
literally cartwheeled into the center of the circle. Their eyes
were wide, smiles beamed from their faces. Despite rocket kicks
that can injure, the ``play'' looks less like mortal combat and
more like two people searching for convergence in a joyful ebb and
flow of motion. After no more than three minutes, someone from the
circle tapped one of the participants on the shoulder and took on
her opponent, tag-team style. A couple of minutes later, the
opponents switched again _ over and over for 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning I wondered if my capoeira class had been a
dream. But my thighs ached from remaining in a semi-squatting
position, and my arms and shoulders were sore from warding off the
blows of my shadow opponent. Yet I also felt a strange
exhilaration. Capoeira is indeed a one-stop discipline, and there
was an unexpected spiritual aspect.
</P>
<P>
   Once my body acclimates to capoeira, I think it will give me the
muscle strength, grace, endurance I want. But for the time being,
I'm still avoiding full-length mirrors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
