<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN COX EDs: Palm Beach Post OUT.
 &HT;    CLINTON PROMISES AID TO NICARAGUA AT START OF CENTRAL AMERICAN
TOUR
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANAGUA, Nicaragua _ President Bill Clinton began a four-day
trip Monday to Central America with an emotionally wrenching visit
to an area devastated by mudslides caused last fall by Hurricane
Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after arriving in Nicaragua, the first leg of the trip
that will also include El Salvador, Honduras and Guatemala, Clinton
flew by helicopter to the Casita Volcano area near Posoltega, about
70 miles northwest of Managua. More than 2,000 people were killed
and thousands left homeless there when torrential rains spawned a
wall of mud covering 60 square miles that obliterated two small
communities, leaving only one badly damaged house still standing.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing the house, Clinton and Nicaraguan President Arnoldo
Aleman walked through the heat and dust to the spot where a
6-year-old girl's body was found encased in the mud. Clinton laid a
wreath of flowers where a silhouette of the girl's body still
remains pressed into the tan dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``No picture can convey the feeling of seeing the outlines of
that small child's body by her grave and seeing the remnants of her
skeleton,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a high school where 20 students were killed -- and
another 60 students lost parents -- Clinton, speaking in Spanish,
said: ``We are brothers and we help each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the bitter civil war that killed tens of thousands
during the 1980s, Clinton said, ``Not so long ago, your country
overcame a terrible war and emerged even stronger. You will
overcome this adversity as well. And we will work with you every
day until the task is done.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived with a planeload of school supplies and $120
million in aid allocated as part of the U.S. Agency for
International Development's budget.
</P>
<P>
   However, he came without congressional approval for a $956
million emergency relief package to Central America. Clinton wants
to provide the aid by using the federal budget surplus, but
Republican leaders in Congress want the money to come from domestic
programs including foods stamps and welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also pledged to try to convince Congress to support his
effort to expand the Caribbean Basin Initiative to allow Caribbean
and Central American countries to compete, in terms of trade, on a
near-parity basis with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who was accompanied by Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla.
and former Florida Gov. Kenneth ``Buddy'' MacKay, the newly
appointed special envoy for Latin America, will visit El Salvador
and Honduras on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
