<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, March 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The northern edge of a large winter storm will stretch from
south of Chicago to the suburbs of Pittsburgh eastward across
southern Maryland. A swath of moderate to heavy snow, about 75
miles wide, will leave more than 6 inches of accumulation Tuesday
in central Ohio and northern West Virginia. Snow and sleet will
cause difficult travel in Virginia and northern North Carolina.
Heavy snow should fall in the central Appalachians and across
northern Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Light snow will fall on the northern periphery of the storm from
Wisconsin and eastern Minnesota across southwest Michigan, northern
Ohio and into southern Pennsylvania. Its shield of clouds will edge
into the New York metropolitan region. A slice of sunny, but chilly
weather will cover much of New England; however, clouds and light
snow will circulate back into Maine as last weekend's storm, now in
the Maritimes, drifts toward the west.
</P>
<P>
   A new low-pressure system will develop along the Carolina coast
when a line of heavy thunderstorms reaches the Southeast shore
Tuesday afternoon. Cold air will be wedged between the southern
Appalachians and the Coast leading to a chilly rain, mixed with ice
on the Piedmont plateau. Gusty showers and a few thunderstorms will
mark a cold front's passage through Georgia and northern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure in Oklahoma will sponsor dry and milder weather in
the central and southern Plains. A cold front moving through Idaho,
Nevada and California will produce some snow inland and a few
showers in California. The Northwest will stay dull and rather
cool.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Frozen Rochester
</P>
<P>
   Adding insult to injury, Rochester, N.Y., tied its lowest
reading ever for March on Monday morning when the mercury fell to
minus-7 degrees. The previous record for the date was minus-1
recorded in 1943. The only other occasions of minus-7 degrees
occurred last century in 1872 and 1885. The deep snowpack, now
measuring over 30 inches, combined with clear skies, light winds
and a gelid air mass to bring the record chill. Fortunately, the
next potent disturbance should pass south of western New York
Tuesday, and its shield of high clouds will keep nighttime readings
from falling to record levels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1742EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
