<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2226 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSSTAND09-COX     03-08 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Entertainment Weekly On Campus: R.E.M.'s Michael Stipe talks
about fashion.
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eric Rudoph has worries. Not only is the FBI on his tail, but
the folks at Plaza Video in Murphy, N.C., would like to have a word
with him. It seems that Rudolph rented ``Krull the Conqueror'' on
Jan. 30, 1998, the day after he allegedly bombed an abortion clinic
in Alabama. Rudolph had to disappear for a while, and the tape is
now overdue to the tune of $975.20 in late fees, according to Tony
Horwitz, who writes about the Rudoph manhunt in this week's The New
Yorker ($3). Horwitz reports on the effort to bring Rudolph to
justice and the radical groups in southwestern North Carolina that
have embraced him as a folk hero.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Up with Michael: Michael Stipe, R.E.M. front man with a
fondness for wraparound skirts, says his greatest weakness when it
comes to clothing is ``keeping them on.'' Stipe is on the cover of
Entertainment Weekly's quarterly On Campus publication, a free
24-page handout that will be inserted into school newspapers at 100
colleges and universities, including Georgia State and Emory (but
not the University of Georgia, R.E.M.'s old stomping ground). Stipe
says he relates to the Peanuts character Pigpen, ``because I
attract dirt magnetically. So my clothes, no matter how beautiful
or expensive or sublime, always get trashed really easily.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Teach your children: Termed a ``review of academic life,''
Lingua Franca ($4.95) sounds painfully dry but is actually quite
approachable. The March issue includes an engaging meditation on
the mindlessness of secondary school and the occasional reprieve
that comes in the form of an irresistible teacher. Mark Edmundson
was a disaffected conformist jock at Medford High School near
Boston until Doug Meyers came there to teach philosophy. In ``My
First Intellectual,'' Edmundson tells how Meyers, an
unprepossessing, droopy-mustached rebel, turned him into a thinker
and a writer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Listen to your Mother: The latest issue of unapologetically
leftist Mother Jones ($3.95) offers a panoply of readable goodies,
including a quick interview with ``Simpsons'' creator Matt
Groening, a visit with pie-throwing protesters the Biotic Baking
Brigade (who recently pied San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown) and a
thoughtful piece on how the supporters of convicted cop killer
Mumia Abu-Jamal are missing the point by insisting on his
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Teen zines: Critics of magazines for teenaged females consider
such periodicals to be primers for anorexia and low self-esteem.
But a new generation of teen magazines promises to offer a more
inclusive, more humane view of this manipulated demographic, and
they deliver, more or less. ``The only teen fashion magazine for
girls all shapes all sizes all cultures'' is the way Girl ($2.95)
describes itself. The current issue features most of the familiar
staples of the genre, with features on prom dresses, makeup,
``amazing hair rules'' and little known facts about Leonardo
DiCaprio. But not all the models are rail thin and there are nods
to cross-culturalism, such as a visit to Buenos Aires. Jump ($2.95)
tells girls to go ahead and order seconds, because guys like girls
who like to eat. We suppose that's an improvement over the endless
diet advice. Sure there are the typical features _ ``Does your
romance need rehab?'' and ``how the famous have fun'' _ but these
are balanced with views of girls as something more than a date
waiting to happen, including profiles of a 14-year-old one-legged
sprinter who runs with an orthotic device and a 16-year-old judo
champ.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
