<HEADER>
A2228 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARBIE09-COX     03-08 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBIE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Milestone for an icon
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lordy, Lordy, Barbie's 40.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel, the corporation that owns Barbie, calls today her 40th
``anniversary.'' No mention of the b-word.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not fooling anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie's reached midlife, all right. She's having some nips and
tucks _ plastic surgery on that famous plastic body. Last year, she
got a face lift. She even has a tattoo _ albeit a not-so-daring
butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   She's also hanging out with a cooler crowd, including one new
pal with a pierced nose.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Barbie's no longer the teenage fashion model who, in
1959, strutted into America's rec rooms in high heels and a
zebra-striped bathing suit. Even before reaching the Big 4-0, she
had multiple face resculptings, sports cars and wedding dresses
(although she's never actually married). She's changed careers 75
times. She's done disco and played doctor, changing friends and
fashions to stay abreast of the cultural Zeitgeist.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she's over the hill just yet. In an industry where toy
fads pass as quickly as you can say ``pogs,'' she's got legs.
American girls own an estimated eight Barbies on average, and more
than 1 billion dolls have been sold worldwide. The six top-selling
computer games for girls in 1998 were Barbie titles.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a hint of trouble in Pink Paradise appeared last year, when
retailers cut back orders for the doll. At the same time, Mattel
announced that some Barbies would be getting breast reductions and
tummy augmentations to give them a more realistic figure. This
year, a new line of Barbies aimed at older girls will come with a
different name, Generation Girls, and packaging that's hipster
black rather than preschool pink. For the first time, Mattel is
giving these Barbies an age: 15.
</P>
<P>
   Is this what 40 looks like?
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids have changing interests and are no longer playing with
toys as long as they used to,'' says Marianne Szymanski, editor of
Toy Tips magazine. ``Twenty years ago, girls played with Barbies
until age 12. Now it is difficult to find a 9-year-old who is still
interested _ e-mail and Internet surfing has replaced that.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's a golden gal to do?
</P>
<P>
   Barbie's got a bit part as a tour guide in ``Toy Story 2,'' due
in theaters around Thanksgiving. Yet the Valley of the Dolls can be
hard on an older actress.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this town . . . at 40 you are over the hill and
opportunities are limited,'' deadpans Dr. Toni Bernay, a Los
Angeles psychologist. ``It's going to be hard for her, because what
she's been focused on in the past is what she looks like, and
that's going to fade rapidly. I presume she's going to be 40 for
the next 30 years, like the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Harsh words, but not as harsh as the contents of a jokey e-mail
making the rounds of Barbie collectors. Bifocals Barbie or
Hot-Flash Barbie, anyone? How about the services of the Reroot
Queen, a for-real Las Vegas flight attendant who fluffs up balding
Barbies?
</P>
<P>
   Zack McDonald of Atlanta, a hairdresser and collector, wants her
to stay glamorous. ``She's always been a model, which is cool,'' he
says. ``Maybe a Victoria's Secret Barbie, there you go.''
</P>
<P>
   But not a B-cup Barbie. ``If you took that away from Barbie,''
he says, ``you would completely lose the doll and the point.''
</P>
<P>
   And about this ``40th anniversary'' business. According to the
10 commandments for preserving babedom, Barbie should never lie
about her age, says Linda Stasi, co-author of ``Boomer Babes: A
Woman's Guide to the New Middle Ages'' (St. Martin's, $12.95). ``My
mother always told me that the 40s are the sexiest time of a
woman's life,'' Stasi says. ``When you hit this decade, for the
first time, for me at least, I really hit my stride.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattel's putting its money on surgery, however. It just gave
Barbie a younger-looking face. ``We just felt she needed to be more
contemporary, more up-to-date,'' says spokeswoman Lisa McKendall.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Burton of Tucker, who makes a living customizing Barbies
for collectors at $200 a pop, would like to see the doll return to
her roots. She should wear the kind of sophisticated outfits that
real women might wear _ no ball gowns, no pink pumps. And just one
more wedding dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite honestly, Ken either needs to pee or get off the pot,''
he says. ``If he can't commit by now, come on.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe they'll load their offspring _ like the two sets of
identical twins that sister Skipper baby-sits _ into the back of
the pink Ford Explorer and set off on a reality trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let her be a woman,'' Burton counsels. ``She's not a little
girl anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
