<HEADER>
A2229 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DIMAGGIO-REACT     03-08 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DIMAGGIO-REACT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Current players, coaches react to DiMaggio's death
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ Bobby Cox's most vivid memory of Joe DiMaggio
didn't come from his early childhood, when DiMaggio was wearing
Yankee pinstripes. It wasn't the time the extremely private
DiMaggio agreed to have his picture taken with Cox, then a rookie
for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   It came less than 20 years ago, when Cox was eating at a New
York deli and looked out the window to see a gray-haired DiMaggio,
dressed in a pin-striped suit, cause a commotion on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stopped the city,'' Cox said. ``Everybody ran out of
restaurants, hotels. He looked like some elder statesmen.''
</P>
<P>
   News of DiMaggio's death saddened those around Tiger Town Monday
morning. A moment of silence was requested in DiMaggio's honor
before the 1:05 p.m. start of the Detroit-Atlanta spring-training
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Class guy,'' Cox said. ``All I think of Joe D. is class. A
very private guy, commanded respect somehow without asking for it.
A different type of guy. Real dignified, graceful, all his
mannerisms were graceful. He was different from any superstar I've
ever known. His presence was that of a statesman, a president. . .
. He was truly a hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves hitting coach Don Baylor, who played for the Yankees
1983-85, got acquainted with DiMaggio at old-timers' games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of all the players, when he walked in the locker room, he
was the guy everybody had their eyes on _ young players, old
players,'' Baylor said. ``Pete Sheehy (the Yankees clubhouse man
for 60 years) stopped what he was doing when Joe D. came in. He sat
down over in the corner, and I know they talked about old times.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor said he always liked to ask Sheehy which of the Yankees
players was the best he ever saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I could get it out of my mouth,'' Baylor said, ``it
was, 'Joltin' Joe.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor was a pall-bearer at Sheehy's funeral. He said DiMaggio
didn't show up until the last possible minute and sat on the back
row, presumably to keep the attention off himself and on Sheehy,
where it belonged.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a special, special guy,'' Baylor said. ``He had such a
dignity about him.''
</P>
<P>
   To Braves players from the New York area, especially those of
Italian heritage, DiMaggio's legend was huge, and the loss was
large.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hero, especially in the Italian community,'' said
Braves second baseman Tony Graffanino, who grew up in Amityville,
N.Y. ``I never saw him, but I grew up hearing about him. His
parents were immigrants and poor, and here he was a legend in
baseball. Everybody looked up to him. . . . Fifty-six games? That's
crazy. To hit in every game for two months?''
</P>
<P>
   Braves minor-league shortstop Mark DeRosa thought it was amazing
that DiMaggio was able to hit safely in 72 games during a 73-game
stretch in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, when you hear he hit safely in 72 out of 73 games,
you have to be amazed at what he was able to accomplish,'' DeRosa
said. ``But you never got a chance to really see the guy for
yourself. I just appreciate what he did growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   DeRosa said DiMaggio was a name he heard throughout his
childhood in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my grandfather's favorite player,'' DeRosa said.
``Being in a 100 percent Italian family, Joe D. was constantly
talked about. No one ever compared to him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be remembered, that's the good thing,'' Cox said.
``There are names that just never go away. Two of them are Ruth and
DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
