<HEADER>
A2232 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      03-08 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER DRESSING ON THE PLAYING FIELD HMO PATIENTS: TO SUE OR NOT TO
SUE GETTING BEYOND THE BIRDS AND THE BEES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Pa.)   (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Linda Cherny played a mean game of volleyball at the Empire
State Games in Syracuse a few weeks back. A 36-year-old day care
provider from Kingston, N.Y., she spiked hard and jumped high. And,
she says, she owes it all to her shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists believe her. In a five-year study, Dr. William
Kraemer, the director of research and a professor of applied
physiology at Pennsylvania State University, tested hundreds of
male and female athletes of all ages, abilities and fitness levels
and found that wearing form-fitting shorts, also known as
compression garments, increases an athlete's power output and
endurance, two important measures of athletic performance, by an
average of 12 percent and by as much as 30 percent. The study,
which tested athletes after they jumped and ran, was sponsored by
DuPont, the maker of Lycra Power garments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intent of the research was to understand the relationship
between compression and muscle performance,'' Kraemer said. ``We
hypothesized a relationship existed because of the anecdotal
reports from athletes who had tried compression garments and liked
the way they felt and performed.''
</P>
<P>
   That stretchy, form-fitting fabric exerts pressure on muscles,
he said. That pressure, in turn, increases blood flow and helps
flush away lactic acid and other fatigue-causing waste products
quickly and efficiently. And, he added, the pressure reduces muscle
vibration, another major cause of muscle fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   The garments also seem to be effective, according to the study,
because of improved proprioception, or awareness of body movements.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a sense of where your joints and muscles are,'' said
Dr. Gilbert Gleim, the director of Research at the Nicolas
Institute for Sports Medicine and Athletic Trauma at Lenox Hill
Hospital in New York City, who was not involved with the garment
research. ``This is feedback you don't normally get when you wear
loose clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LIZ NEPORENT
</P>
<P>
   PRO &AMP; CON:
</P>
<P>
   Q. Should patients be able to sue their health maintenance
organizations?
</P>
<P>
   If somebody is hurt as a result of the improper decisions of an
HMO, he should be able to sue that HMO and be compensated for the
damage. The purpose of the right to sue is to serve as a deterrent
against conduct by an HMO that is in reckless disregard of a
patient's needs. The Erisa (Employee Retirement Income Security
Act) statute, enacted in the 1970s, keeps states from establishing
causes of action and keeps patients from suing in state courts. But
the statute also says a person can sue in federal court. If the
patient prevails, though, he can get only the service that was
originally denied or its dollar value.
</P>
<P>
   The statute made a great deal of sense when it was enacted.
Then, people had very little in terms of HMOs and managed care, and
disputes between consumers and insurance companies occurred after a
service was provided. The contest: Will the insurance company pay?
Today, the contest is whether a patient gets the service to begin
with and whether he will be denied needed health care. The harm is
considerably greater. Liability is not retribution; I view it as
deterrence.
</P>
<P>
   _ RON POLLACK, executive director, Families USA Foundation
</P>
<P>
   The issue of coverage denial drives the liability debate. Now,
while every denial is viewed as a significant problem, it is
important to recognize that there are times that patients are hurt
by medical services that are not the right ones for them. Some have
estimated this to be higher than 30 percent of the total health
care delivered in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, we saw a report from a House of Representatives
committee finding that 12,000 Americans died as a result of
unnecessary surgeries, with the unnecessary surgeries numbering 2
1/2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, not covering a service that is recommended by a
physician is the right thing to do, because that service may be
harmful to the patient.
</P>
<P>
   Managed care was invented to try to bring better medical
evidence into private practice.
</P>
<P>
   Our ability to do that would be severely compromised if each
time a physician recommended a treatment, and we questioned it, the
case ended up as litigation in court. That does not sound like
quality care to me.
</P>
<P>
   _ RICHARD SMITH, vice president, public policy and research,
American Association of Health Plans
</P>
<P>
   BEHAVIOR
</P>
<P>
   Many children as young as 10 years old want to know more about
sex than just where babies come from, but parents often shy away
from discussing sexuality, according to a national survey conducted
by the Kaiser Family Foundation and Children Now, a children's
advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Topics that may have parents blushing even in discussions with
teen-agers have filtered down to children ages 10 to 12. In a
random-sample telephone survey of 161 children in that age group
and 447 parents, more than 40 percent of the children said they
wanted to know how to handle peer pressure, how to know when they
were ready for sexual activity and how alcohol and drugs might
affect their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet half of the parents surveyed said they had never talked to
their children 10 to 12 years old about readiness and 46 percent
had never discussed either how to handle pressures or how drugs or
alcohol influenced choices.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 percent said they had never talked to their
preteen-agers about how to avoid pregnancy or sexually transmitted
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as easy as just giving the birds-and-the-bees talk,
but getting down to the nitty-gritty of talking about the
pressures,'' said Dr. Richard Gallagher, director of the Parenting
Institute at the New York University School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Experts interviewed said the Lewinsky matter had increased
sexual awareness, although talk about sex among younger children
had been increasing gradually. ``Today discussions begin as early
as third grade,'' said Dr. Jeanne Brooks-Gunn, professor of child
development and education at Columbia University's Teachers
College, who has studied puberty issues over the last 25 years.
``My guess is if you talk to 12-year-olds, they could tell you
exactly about the different sex acts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What this survey is suggesting,'' Dr. Brooks-Gunn concluded,
``is that after you have had the sex talk, mechanics and all, it is
time to start talking about peer pressure and how to help kids
withstand that pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   _ NANCY BETH JACKSON
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
