<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2236 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWEEPSTAKES-SENATE-HN     03-08 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEEPSTAKES-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE CONSIDERS REGULATING SWEEPSTAKES MAILINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Eustace Hall, age 65, is a retired medical
technologist. But the Brandon, Fla., man told a Senate panel Monday
he is now working at AT&AMP;T to pay off thousands of dollars in debts
he incurred in an effort to win millions in sweepstakes promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Hall became so upset while trying to tell his story before the
Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations that his daughter
Angela had to read most of his prepared testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Hall estimated that he has spent from $15,000 to $20,000 since
1992 in sweepstakes purchases with American Family Publishers and
other promoters. He said wanted to win so that he could contribute
toward his daughter's law school education. She eventually
graduated from law school anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always made purchases because I believed that through
purchases, I increased my chances of winning,'' Hall said. ``The
sweepstakes always used phrases that made me think I was a winner
and that the prize was guaranteed and bonded.''
</P>
<P>
   Most sweepstakes mailings contain information advising
recipients that ``no purchase necessary.'' However, that disclaimer
usually is printed in small type on the back of a cover letter
telling Hall and millions of other Americans that ``you are a
winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweepstakes companies aim to entice people to buy magazines,
compact disks and other products by offering contests that give
people the chance to win prizes like cars, stereos and millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, age 46, chairman of the
subcommittee on investigations, said she couldn't read the small
print on letters promoting sweepstakes. And Sen. Carl Levin,
D-Mich., age 64, said he couldn't make out the small print even
with reading glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Collins and Levin are authors of legislation that would ban
companies from telling people they are winners when they haven't
actually won anything. The bill also would require promoters to use
much larger print in describing such details as the long-shot odds
of winning a contest.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing from Hall and five other people who told stories
of their parents or parents-in-law spending thousands of dollars to
purchase magazines and other items, Levin said he is considering
adding a provision in the bill that would require companies to
clearly state that making a purchase does not increase a person's
odds of winning.
</P>
<P>
   Karol Carter, from Troy, Mich., said her father is upset that
she testified before the Senate because ``he is concerned that I am
ruining his chances of winning a... sweepstakes when he, and I
quote `am getting close to winning.'''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said her father's problem began about 15 months ago when
he first entered a sweepstakes. He is now inundated with contest
mailings.
</P>
<P>
   She said one sweepstakes letter stated, ``You Allan Carter are
guaranteed to receive a brand new automobile or cash award...there
is no mistake and your award is waiting to be claimed.'' It
required that Carter send in $14.98 to have the title of a
Chevrolet Malibu transferred to him. Carter sent in the money, but
never got the car.
</P>
<P>
   Another ``gimmick'' that entices seniors to purchase magazines,
Carter said, is the fact that there are different return mailing
addresses for a contestant not making a purchase and for a
contestant making a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Patti McElligott, of Tyler, Texas, said she had her
father-in-law's mail forwarded to her when he moved into a
retirement center last year. She said she received as many as 20
magazines a day, including duplicates of the same magazine that he
had ordered through Publishers Clearing House and Reader's Digest,
among others.
</P>
<P>
   She later discovered canceled checks totaling more than $50,000
made out to American Family Publishers, United States Purchasing
Exchange and other firms that operate sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Bernstein, vice president of marketing services for
American Family Enterprises, said in testimony prepared for a
hearing Tuesday on sweepstakes, that the primary focus of their
mailings is to sell magazines. The company uses Ed McMahon and Dick
Clark to promote its sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of our mailings is not to convince people they've
won a sweepstakes, but rather to be excited about the possibility
of winning and to consider our products,'' she said. ``The vast
majority of people who receive our mailings understand them and do
not believe either that they have won or they must order to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein also said 11 of the past 17 ``grand prize'' winners
were people who did not purchase any magazines.
</P>
<P>
   American Family Enterprises, commonly known as American Family
Publishers, recently made changes to its sweepstakes promotions
including allowing people to cancel magazine subscriptions at any
time and receive a refund.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein said she has some concerns about some of the wording
in the Collins-Levin legislation but supports standards for the
entire industry. Officials from Publishers' Clearinghouse have also
said they support national standards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
