<HEADLINE>
THEY COULD WRITE A BOOK
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies LEWINSKY-BOOK) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With ``Monica's Story,'' Monica Lewinsky is only the first major
player in the Clinton/Lewinsky scandal to come out with a book.
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek reporter Michael Isikoff, who used Linda Tripp as a key
story source, has his book-length recollections coming out in
April. From there, it's Bob Woodward in June and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   What we don't know yet is how many Monicagate
celebrities-of-the-moment also will get their stories into print.
Whether Tripp and the others will get book deals will depend in
large part on how well ``Monica's Story'' sells. Should it do well,
these people are most likely to publish books:
</P>
<P>
   KENNETH STARR: The good news for the special prosecutor, if he
hopes for a seven-figure publishing contract, is that fully
one-third of the American public thinks of him as an icon. The bad
news is two-thirds don't. He's still controversial enough for some
publisher to sign him up.
</P>
<P>
   LINDA TRIPP: If there's one thing the world agrees on, it's that
everybody dislikes Tripp. Major publishers would be concerned about
a publicity backlash. Tripp's only hope is that some smaller
publishing house will decide it's got nothing to lose, and that
even bad publicity is better than no publicity.
</P>
<P>
   HENRY HYDE: The Illinois congressman is the perfect author for a
book detailing the perspective of the House prosecutors in
Clinton's Senate trial. He'd appeal to the same audience that made
books by Dan Quayle and Rush Limbaugh bestsellers. Expect a
big-name publisher to announce a Hyde book deal soon.
</P>
<P>
   KATHLEEN WILLEY: If Monica's book sells, it's a near cinch we'll
hear in print soon afterward from another woman who claims she
encountered Clinton's advances. Willey's a good bet; she'd be
considered attractive enough for the TV-author circuit, where
glamour is every bit as important as on ``Baywatch.''
</P>
<P>
   NEWT GINGRICH: Don't laugh. Newt will resign his congressional
seat soon, and there's no reason now for him to observe
statesmanship in book form.
</P>
<P>
   BOB BITTMAN: Who? Well, Bittman was Starr's day-to-day manager
during the Lewinsky investigation. He has now left Starr's staff,
and he undoubtedly has lots of dirt to dish on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   BILL CLINTON: Someday he'll write his memoirs, and, like Richard
Nixon before him, he'll give his side of the bad times _ but in a
presidential way, which means it will somehow be deadly dull. A big
house will publish it, but there won't be any real juice to it.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY CLINTON: The woman every publisher wants. The first lady
can have it all from any publisher, even if she says nothing but,
``I wish my husband hadn't done it.'' The only reason we might not
see it is if she decides to run for the Senate, in which case
decorum and a stiff upper lip will mean more than a $5 million
advance and financial relief from those tacky Whitewater legal
bills.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
