<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBIE-40TH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO BARBIE ON HER 40TH BIRTHDAY ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Babs,
</P>
<P>
   I can't sing it loud enough or often enough. Happy Birthday,
dear Barbie, Happy Birthday to you.
</P>
<P>
   Forty! Can you believe it? My voice fairly squeals when I say
it.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry I can't be there for your big party tomorrow. I'm sure Ken
and all your friends at Mattel will do something spectacular. I can
just imagine it _ Barbie's 40th-birthday-and-face-lift party.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe you should take this opportunity to rethink your
personal style, have your colors done. All that pink is a little
over the top for a woman of your age. I mean, what if people start
mistaking you for a Mary Kay salesperson?
</P>
<P>
   Now, you know, I'm only suggesting this because we've been
friends since the '60s. But the first thing I'd recommend is taking
about 2,000 of your ball gowns to the consignment shop. Next, buy
some nice black slacks. They're very slimming. Like you've ever
worried about your figure _ but you will. Oh, how you'll worry.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to go is your waist, or your hips, or your waist
AND hips. Before you know it, you'll be fat and sweating like a
stevedore.
</P>
<P>
   While you're ditching the dresses, lose the shoes. Those spikes
you've worn for the past four decades have permanently crippled
your feet. If you don't know a good podiatrist, I do, and I can get
you a good deal. Let me warn you though; she'll tell you to get
down off those high heels and into something sensible.
</P>
<P>
   Once you wear flats, it's amazing how easy it is to quit wearing
mascara and eyeliner. You have to abandon the eyeliner anyway. You
have no choice; it starts creeping into the little lines and
crevices and overnight you'll see why they call them crow's feet.
After that, who needs eye shadow?
</P>
<P>
   Soon, you'll discover the true beauty of the lipstick 'n'
leggings look. Put a Bedazzled sweat shirt on the top, and you'll
never miss the Bob Mackie gowns or the cruel underwear you needed
to wear with them.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to simplify. Trade in your sports car. It sends out
the wrong message. Maybe a minivan would be more appropriate. Or at
least a Volvo station wagon.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of trade-ins _ Haven't you wondered why Ken has never
come through with the Big Rock? Catch the clue bus. He's either
gay, or he has some serious commitment issues.
</P>
<P>
   This is probably more than you want to deal with right now. I
know turning 40 has all this extra baggage attached to it. Like
dealing with your diminished sex appeal, and the fact there is no
Baby Barbie, and how you never found a satisfying career. You've
worn so many hats in your day, I can't believe you never found one
you liked.
</P>
<P>
   But let me tell you, dear Babs, getting past 40 is positively
liberating. The playing field levels dramatically as experience
makes up for all sorts of imagined shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you've never had any shortcomings, have you? But now,
you're 40. Next year, you'll be Over 40. Can you feel the ground
leveling? You would if you were wearing flats.
</P>
<P>
   Have a wonderful birthday, Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   Love, Gaile
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
