<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2245 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTHRAX0309-COX     03-08 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHRAX0309-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONTROVERSY OVER PENTAGON ANTHRAX VACCINE WON'T GO AWAY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington category
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Army Spec. Joseph Jones, 22, of Austin, Texas, says
he ``had a bad feeling'' about the anthrax vaccine he was required
to take a year ago when the Army sent him to Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the medic I didn't want to take it, but he said, 'It's
okay. Take it and don't worry about it,' '' Jones said Friday in a
telephone interview from the Georgia Army hospital where he was
sent because of a succession of increasingly serious medical
problems that he and his family are convinced were caused by the
vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said other Army officials gave him an even stronger reason
for taking the controversial vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in formation and they announced to everyone that if we
refused to take it they would give us an Article 15 (misconduct
proceeding) and the MPs would hold us down while they gave it to us
anyhow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones took the vaccinations, four of them, beginning March 17,
1998. And a day or two after receiving each vaccination, he said,
he became ill, beginning with ``flu-like symptoms'' following the
first and growing progressively worse with subsequent shots.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the aches and fever, Jones said the shots have
been followed by sometimes bloody diarrhea, terrible headaches and
occasional fainting spells. He recently was moved from Ft. Benning,
Ga., where his outfit is based, to Eisenhower Army Medical Center
at Ft. Gordon, near Augusta, Ga. Scans revealed a ``mass'' behind
his sinuses and surgery has been scheduled to drain it, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Army doctors don't believe Spec. Jones' medical problems have
anything to do with the anthrax shots. His mother, Mrs. Theresa
Jones of Austin, responds to that with a mother's logic. ``He went
in the Army healthy, and he's sick now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she also is concerned that the Army is about to
discharge her son for medical reasons and leave him with the burden
of lingering medical costs.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Food and Drug Administration-approved label for
the vaccine, fewer than 0.2 percent of recipients of the material,
which is manufactured from non-virulent strains of anthrax
bacteria, experience ``malaise and lassitude.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chills and fever have been reported in only a few cases,'' the
label states. ``In such instances, immunization should be
discontinued.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is one of 209,949 persons -- including Secretary of
Defense William Cohen -- who had received at least one of the six
injections required to induce immunity to anthrax as of last week,
said Pentagon Office of Health Affairs spokesman Jim Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Before the five-year immunization campaign is over, 2.4 million
active duty and reserve personnel are to be vaccinated against the
dread disease. Military personnel are being vaccinated because of
concern in the Defense Department about the emerging threat of
biochemical warfare. Government officials have stated anthrax was
being used by Iraqi President Saddam Hussein and some terrorist
organizations to in efforts to develop biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said the campaign did not begin until the safety, purity
and potency of the vaccine had been verified.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' case has been picked up by activists who have declared an
Internet war on the Defense Department anthrax immunization
program. In addition to posting Food and Drug Administration
documents that raise questions about the practices at the Michigan
plant where the vaccine was produced, opponents publicize stories
like those of Spec. Jones and promote the views of some scientists
who question the safety and efficacy of the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they have promoted the causes of active duty
personnel who have been punished for refusing to take it.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Air Force announced that an airman at Travis Air
Force Base in California was being discharged under ``other than
honorable conditions'' for disobeying a direct order to take the
vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Airman First Class Jeffrey Bettendorf had a ``choirboy'' service
record but was given an excessive punishment because top Air Force
officers were angry over the publicity his case generated, his
lawyer charged. Typically, troops that refuse to take the vaccine
are punished with a demotion and a month's restriction to base when
they refuse the vaccine a first time, said the lawyer, Mark Zaid.
He said the second refusal often results in a general discharge
under honorable conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Zaid said he receives several calls a week from U.S. military
personnel around the globe asking him what will happen to them if
they refuse to take the vaccination series. Some Air Force Reserve
pilots in California and Connecticut have chosen to get out of the
reserves instead of taking the shots.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine was manufactured in a Lansing, Mich., laboratory
originally owned by the Michigan State Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials said a routine inspection of the facility in 1996
found ``good management practices'' violations in connection with
production of vaccine in general and anthrax vaccine in particular.
As a result, the FDA notified the department that it intended to
revoke the federal license of the facility, then known as the
Michigan Biologic Products Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The state presented a plan for correcting the deficiencies, said
John Taylor, an official of the FDA Office of Regulatory Affairs. A
follow-up visit found some of the problems had been corrected and
some had not, Taylor said, so the FDA notified the state that the
facility still was not in compliance with federal standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six months later, when we visited the site again, we were not
about to note with any accuracy how much progress had been made,
simply because the company had stopped manufacturing anthrax
vaccine,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the state has sold the Michigan Biologic Products
Institute to a private company, Bioport Inc., which is headed by
retired Navy Adm. William Crowe Jr., a former chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Theresa Jones is convinced that other mothers of
military personnel are hearing of problems with the vaccine and
don't know where to turn. She urged them to study an Internet site,
</P>
<P>
   http://www.dallasnw.quik.com/cyberella/index.htm. (cq)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
