<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    International soccer: History of tensions looms large for U.S.,
Mexico
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Neither coach has experienced it, and a majority of players on
both sides will be new to it. The increasingly fierce rivalry
between the U.S. and Mexico, especially when it's renewed in
southern California, has become one of the most acrimonious in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   And when they take the field for the 40th time against each
other Saturday in the U.S. Cup in San Diego's Qualcomm Stadium
(3:30 p.m., ABC), the Americans once again will feel like strangers
in a strange land.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S., unbeaten in four matches under coach Bruce Arena,
hasn't been able to turn out supporters to match the pro-Mexican
fans living in California. Last year, American players were
showered with debris as they emerged from the tunnel of a packed
Los Angeles Coliseum in the finals of the CONCACAF Gold Cup won by
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   atemala (8:30 p.m., ESPN) at the L.A. Coliseum. Bolivia also is
entered in the four-team field.
</P>
<P>
   England: Le Saux Redux
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea's Graeme Le Saux and Robbie Fowler of Liverpool are
being cast as equally culpable for an ugly incident last week that
has dominated the sports pages in Britain. LeSaux knocked Fowler to
the ground after the latter made obscene gestures in a match. An
unidentified friend of Le Saux said last week the player has been
labeled, falsely, of being gay because he collects antiques, visits
bookshops and cafes and reads the left-leaning Guardian newspaper
instead of tabloids. . . . The day after setting up both goals in a
2-0 Champions League win over Inter Milan, Manchester United
midfielder David Beckham became a father. Beckham and fiancee
``Posh Spice,'' a.k.a. Victoria Adams, gave birth to a son,
Brooklyn Joseph, named, presumably, because the lad was conceived
while the couple visited New York. . . . Tough-guy Vinnie Jones,
red-carded 13 times as a player, is retiring to turn his attention
to an acting career. Jones, 35, is getting good reviews for his
role as a debt collector in the new film ``Lock, Stock and Two
Smoking Barrels.'' . . . Wimbledon manager Joe Kinnear will miss
the rest of the season after suffering a heart attack before a game
last week. . . . Manchester United and Chelsea tied 0-0 in the F.A.
Cup on Sunday and will replay the match Wednesday. Holders Arsenal
advanced with a 1-0 win over Derby County.
</P>
<P>
   Italy: 'The Animal' returns
</P>
<P>
   When he disappeared during Carnival last month, Brazilian enigma
Edmundo ignored the fury from his Fiorentina bosses for missing
several critical Serie A matches. Now, he won't be going back home
any time soon, not after receiving a 4 1/2-year prison sentence for
the deaths of three people in a car accident in Rio de Janeiro last
year. Edmundo, nicknamed ``The Animal,'' insists he was not drunk
behind the wheel at the time of the mishap. His lawyers are
appealing the verdict. . . . Juventus rallied to defeat Sampdoria
2-1 to remain undefeated under new coach Carlo Ancelotti. . . .
Marcelo Salas had two goals as Serie A leaders Lazio routed
Salernitana 6-1. . . . Bologna is in a European semifinal for the
first time, thanks to two goals by Guiseppe Signori in a 3-0 win
over Olympique Lyon in the UEFA Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Scratch my back . . .
</P>
<P>
   German interior minister Otto Schilly wants the government to
provide financial aid to South Africa if it will withdraw its bid
for the 2006 World Cup. Germany then would support South Africa for
a later World Cup, a move also advocated by the German soccer
federation. . . . Not even two years into the job, Bayern Munich
manager Ottmar Hitzfeld might be on the move to Italy or Spain.
Bayern is poised to win its second Bundesliga crown in a row, and
the team wants him to sign a four-year contract extension. ``At the
moment, I can't imagine myself doing that,'' said Hitzfeld, who led
Borussia Dortmund to the 1997 European Cup. ``At my age (50), you
need a little sunshine.''
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Boys will be boys
</P>
<P>
   Real Madrid has fined midfielder Clarence Seedorf $33,000 and
sweeper Fernando Hierro half that amount for a locker-room fight
after the team's 1-1 draw with Dynamo Kyiv in the Champions League
last Wednesday. The feud began during an argument over which player
should take a free kick.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America: Abduction suspects held
</P>
<P>
   Four members of a Mexican street gang have been charged with the
kidnapping of the father of national team goalkeeper Jorge Campos
last month. The family paid a $63,000 ransom to the kidnappers, who
detained Alvaro Campos for six days before releasing him unharmed.
. . . Vasco de Gama, winner of the last two Brazilian national
titles, won the Rio-Sao Paulo pre-season tournament last week with
a 2-1 victory in the finals over Santos. . . . So much for giving
the Peace Cup a chance. Two players were given red cards and 10
others were booked in a 3-2 win by eventual champion Paraguay over
Guatemala in the inaugural tournament in Guatemala City. . . .
Defending Libertadores Cup champion River Plate is in danger of
being eliminated in the first round after a 1-0 loss to Deportivo
Cali.
</P>
