<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALEXANDER-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAMAR ALEXANDER HOPES TO BE THE LAST GOP CANDIDATE STANDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, who plans to
announce his candidacy Tuesday, has a scenario for wrapping up the
Republican 2000 presidential nomination that goes like this:
</P>
<P>
   It is March 2000. His better-known GOP rivals _ such as Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, two-time cabinet secretary Elizabeth Dole and
conservative commentator Patrick Buchanan _ have either failed to
take off or fizzled in mid-flight.
</P>
<P>
   With a boost from the Iowa caucuses and New Hampshire primary _
political soil he has tilled virtually non-stop since 1996 _
Alexander is poised to grab the nomination. He clinches it with a
better-than-expected showing on Super Tuesday, March 7 _ primary
day for a dozen or so major states including California and New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Crazy? Or maybe just crazy like a fox in a plaid shirt,
Alexander's favored garb in the 1996 campaign that now for the most
resides in his closet.
</P>
<P>
   The 58-year-old candidate, who will officially launch his
campaign at a rally in his home town of Nashville Tuesday, insists
it can be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an air of unreality about'' perceptions that he has no
chance, Alexander said in a telephone interview. ``Mrs. Dole
resigned from (her job as president of the American) Red Cross, and
within one day she was ahead of Governor Bush in the polls in New
Hampshire. That's how rapidly things can change. They can also
change when I do better than expected in Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Alexander has taken 60 or more trips to Iowa and
has enlisted former Gov. Terry Branstad to head his effort there.
Iowa is the first to play its card in next year's political
sweepstakes, holding caucuses on Feb. 7. The primary in New
Hampshire, where Alexander is similarly dug in, follows the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he will really get a significant bounce coming out of
Iowa and New Hampshire is problematic. With those crucial dates 11
months away, Bush and Dole already have sprinted to commanding lead
positions in most polls.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Bush and Dole, Alexander must compete with Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, and magazine
publisher Steve Forbes for the votes of Republican fiscal
conservatives and moderates.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Buchanan, Forbes, former Vice President Dan Quayle,
former Reagan administration aide Gary Bauer, and Sen. Robert
Smith, R-N.H., are vying for GOP social conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's strength, to the extent that he has any, resides
partly in his resume _ governor of Tennessee from 1978 to 1987,
president of the University of Tennessee from 1987 to 1990, U.S.
education secretary from 1991 to 1993 _ and partly in his ability
to stay afloat in the political money race.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he has close to $1 million in the bank and says he can
raise another $14 million this year. That's short of the $20
million most political pros say a candidate needs to weather the
primary season, but it is nonetheless respectable.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander sees another hidden asset: His affable-but-bland
personality. ``I am myself,'' he said. ``Maybe after President
Clinton's electrifying charisma, we'll want charisma based on words
and deeds.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalls his surprising third-place finish in Iowa in 1996
when, he says, for a short time the media treated him ``like some
Beatle.'' The lesson? Charisma ``has a lot to do with whether
you've won the last caucus ... I've got to be myself. My goal is to
bring out the best in our country, not to be some swashbuckling
leader on a horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's not bashful when it comes to criticizing the
competition. When Bush described himself as a ``compassionate
conservative,'' Alexander accused him of mouthing ``weasel words''
even though Republican National Chairman Jim Nicholson has called
for a moratorium on intraparty attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander styles himself the ``education candidate'' who has the
most experience on the issues of ``broken families and substandard
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   He is downplaying his one-time support for dismantling the
Department of Education. In speeches, he talks about greater pay
for teachers, flexibility for disciplining students, ending tenure
for poor-performing teachers and ``fixing schools.''
</P>
<P>
   On the family front, he wants an end to the ``marriage
penalty,'' which forces married people to pay higher taxes than
singles with the same income, and a boost in ``national
leadership'' that helps parents teach children right from wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he will start a 2004 effort if he loses next year,
Alexander laughed. ``I'm planning on running for re-election in
2004,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But he also talked about his ``rich, full life'' apart from
presidential campaigning, how he plays the piano and intersperses
business dealings with book authorship (``Lamar Alexander's Little
Plaid Book,'' 1998, Rutledge Hill Press) and hosting a cable
television series on ``great schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Although 1996 was his first campaign, he says he first became
interested in the presidency after Clinton's election in 1992.
Alexander scoffs at suggestions that he has been running too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only people who have run longer and harder than I have are
named Nixon, Reagan and Bush,'' he said. ``They're ones who have
won.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander recalled how he lost his first gubernatorial race in
1974, only to win in 1978 after a 1,022-mile campaign walk across
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people have forgotten American history if they think
that's odd,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
