<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAKESPEARE-BOOK-REVI     03-08 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAKESPEARE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHAKESPEARE: A LIFE': SHAKESPEARE IN FACT (BUT ALAS, NO LOVELY
VIOLA) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Publication notes are at the end of the review) 
(Matt Wolf is London theater critic for Variety) 
 (HLW)  
 By MATT WOLF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever else one thinks of ``Shakespeare: A Life,'' the latest
and by no means last contribution to the Bardic industry, the
timing of Park Honan's impressively researched biography cannot be
faulted. When better to reconstruct the goings-on of the newly
named Man of the Millennium? His singularity, after all, doesn't
just reverberate afresh in the pages of Harold Bloom's
``Shakespeare: The Invention of the Human,'' an assessment as
spiritual as Honan's is factual. Hollywood, too, has enlisted in
the cause with ``Shakespeare in Love,'' which has been nominated
for 13 Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder, then, that Honan speaks of ``our William'' with
the affectionate familiarity appropriate to someone who is part of
the collective imagination. As one reads this painstaking
re-creation of a life whose facts seem forever to be unavailable or
in dispute, it's difficult not to imagine scenes from the film,
with the doe-eyed Joseph Fiennes, quill ever at the ready, charging
about the intrigue-laden, plague-infested London that Honan so
thoroughly animates. But there's no Viola De Lesseps on offer here
(notwithstanding entirely separate musings on Shakespeare's
possible homoerotic infatuations) and, to be honest, there's not a
lot of drama, either.
</P>
<P>
   On Honan's evidence, it was both Shakespeare's blessing and his
curse to exist at an ever-self-effacing remove from the enmity,
turbulence and sheer nerve that marked contemporaries like Greene,
Marlowe and Jonson. ``He found it wise to be `open' and simple,''
Honan writes of his subject, emphasizing the glover's son as a team
player: ``It is clear enough that Shakespeare coveted the normalcy
of being a group member,'' free from the ``quirky egotism'' that
defines many a life in the theater. In 1596, he was being viewed as
a mere ``functionary, or a minor cause of a troupe's ability to
endure.''
</P>
<P>
   But who wants to hear of a theater person divested of quirks and
ego, an apparently normal guy possessed of far-from-normal
abilities? Given Shakespeare's benignity and his ``calm, fine
control,'' one can hardly be surprised that the book's real
dramatic juice resides in talk of the plays, which may explain (not
for the first time) why Shakespeare the man is never as interesting
as Shakespeare the poet-dramatist.
</P>
<P>
   At times, and not for want of countless statistics and figures
down to the last penny of Shakespeare's arrears, he once again
seems to elude his biographer. (Anthony Holden, the English
journalist and author, will deliver his own version in the fall.)
Phrases like ``incomplete, uncertain evidence,'' ``no sign that''
and ``only a possibility'' testify to the eternally elusive nature
of a life that some have famously made an industry out of denying
altogether in favor of the Oxford-Bacon school of authorship that
posits Edward de Vere, 17th Earl of Oxford, or Francis Bacon in
place of Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   It may be in the spirit of triumphant reaction, then, that Honan
gives us what facts (or, at one point, furlongs) he has in all
their minute detail, whether they be the measurements of structures
built for the royal entry into London of Shakespeare's new patron,
James I, in 1604 or the nearly exact dimensions of the Anne
Hathaway cottage in Stratford that remains on view to visitors.
Larger revelations, and they exist, generally pertain to
Shakespeare's earlier years and to his domestic life.
</P>
<P>
   Filling gaps in a chronology that has come down to us over time
mostly as a variably opaque set of lawsuits and wills, Honan links
young Will to one ``William Shakeshafte,'' an ``angular and
graceful'' teen-ager who may have traveled north to Lancashire
where he found work as an unlicensed schoolmaster. Back home in
Stratford, Shakespeare's mother, Mary, is said to be literate, just
as Shakespeare is reported to have gained an understanding into the
violence that courses through his plays from having purchased his
Stratford home from a man later murdered by his son.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, perhaps inevitably, the direct links between writer and
work are what fascinate most, starting with the news that
Shakespeare the actor preferred to take on the smaller (and senior)
parts in his plays: Old Adam in ``As You Like It'' or the Ghost in
``Hamlet.'' Honan writes intriguingly of actual analogues or
sources for certain parts right through to the bear that gives
chase in ``The Winter's Tale.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere there's something delicious about imagining the
specifically Jonsonian traits that Shakespeare folded into his
portrait of Ajax, the ``beef-witted'' Greek commander in ``Troilus
and Cressida.'' But as befits an emeritus professor of English at
Leeds University in the north of England, Honan is on far happier
ground as critic than as chronicler, especially once he veers away
from hackneyed generalizations about an entire bequest (``His works
transcend their time'') and moves through the canon play by play.
</P>
<P>
   Honan is particularly good on ``The Merchant of Venice,'' citing
an ``evasively estheticized'' last act that even during the
Renaissance could be seen to back away from issues and debates
raised earlier in the play. And to describe the ``lurid charm'' of
Lady Macbeth is to encapsulate character with a precision and
lucidity absent from vague encomia later on to Shakespeare's mind
as ``a complex thoroughfare of contradictions and extreme
feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Is ``Shakespeare: A Life'' the last word on its subject?
Unlikely, insofar as it engages with a reconstruction that runs
from Anthony Burgess, A.L. Rowse and Samuel Schoenbaum, among many
others, straight back to John Aubrey's fascinatingly piecemeal
glimpses from the 17th century.
</P>
<P>
   If Shakespeare's plays are transcendent, perhaps there exists
some essential way in which their author is, too. Or maybe no
portrait of a man capable of so much can correspond to the myth
surrounding him. For all its scrupulous scholarship, this book
leaves no doubt that the quest for the genius at its heart will go
on.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SHAKESPEARE: A Life'
</P>
<P>
   By Park Honan
</P>
<P>
   479 pages. Oxford University Press. $30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
