<HEADER>
A2261 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VETERANS-HEPATITIS-50     03-08 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETERANS-HEPATITIS-500&AMP;ADD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERANS CONFRONT NEW FOE _ HEPATITIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 N.Y. Times Regional Newspaper Group   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ George Gramlich admits he wasn't too careful about
coming in contact with blood during his stint in the Army,
especially during his year in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a firefight, we used to drag our wounded out,'' said
Gramlich, bemused at the notion of hygiene during the chaos of
jungle warfare. ``Nobody knew anything about no hepatitis C.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramlich, a 50-year-old Sicklerville, N.J., man who won two
bronze stars for valor during his service in Southeast Asia in
1967-68, is learning plenty about the liver disease now.
</P>
<P>
   He knows it has a long latency period. He knows the disease
could be contracted through transfusions and exposure to infected
blood. He knows the incidence of hepatitis was high in Southeast
Asia and that no effective test for it was available until 1992.
</P>
<P>
   He knows it can disable and kill. And he knows he has it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the war was over,'' he said. ``It is not for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramlich is one victim of a growing epidemic of hepatitis C
among U.S. veterans. New studies show that veterans, particularly
Vietnam-era veterans, appear to be at much higher risk of carrying
the virus than the population at large.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control estimates that hepatitis C
infects slightly less than 2 percent of the population _ about 3.9
million people _ and active military personnel seems to have an
even lower incidence. But patient surveys at Department of Veterans
Affairs hospitals have found an infection rate between 10 percent
and 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In raw figures, the number of cases at VA medical centers has
risen from 6,100 in 1991 to 18,850 in 1994 to more than 21,000
counted last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is becoming a veterans' disease,'' said George Duggins,
president of the Vietnam Veterans of America. ``Many of our
veterans who received no obvious injuries in the war are now
discovering that they are carrying this virus.''
</P>
<P>
   Initial symptoms of the disease can be mild and difficult to
detect. They include fatigue, low-grade fever and muscle and joint
aches. But it can progress into cirrhosis, liver failure and
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation over why Vietnam veterans are prone to this strain
of hepatitis centers on the blood supply of the time and combat
transfusions, contact with blood spilled by comrades, unsanitary
living conditions, prevalence of the disease in the region, sexual
activity, even tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   The VA recognizes the epidemic and is moving to contain it.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the agency announced it was establishing two
hepatitis C research centers in Miami and San Francisco to
coordinate research and treatment. Agency medical authorities also
said they would make available to veterans with hepatitis C a
complex new drug treatment regimen at costs of up to $12,000 to
$15,000 per patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made a policy decision that we are going to
aggressively identify patients and deal with the problem,'' said
Dr. Kenneth Kizer, VA undersecretary for health. ``Frankly, I think
we are taking a more aggressive approach than any other health care
system I have seen.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But veterans advocates and some members of Congress are worried
there won't be enough money available for treatment that could cost
the financially stretched VA up to $500 million next year. They
want the agency to take another step _ give any veteran who suffers
from hepatitis and meets certain other criteria the ``presumption''
of infection during time in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans with such ``service-connected'' status receive top
priority for treatment and qualify for disability benefits.
Advocates say many veterans with hepatitis have been denied such
service-connection in the VA system since they are often unable to
prove how they got hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say this is the day and time we got it,'' said
Gramlich, who has been denied any disability for his hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes a proof problem for veterans,'' agreed Rep. Vic
Snyder, D-Ark., a physician and author of a House measure that
would establish the presumption.
</P>
<P>
   The potential cost of the bill has not yet been estimated, but
any new expenses for the VA will be hard to absorb given its
financial situation. Veterans groups are already attacking the
Clinton administration budget proposal for the agency, saying it
falls as much as $3 billion short.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the hepatitis bill say it could actually save the VA
money in the long-run by eliminating hepatitis disability appeals
from the backlogged VA system and treating the disease earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The alternative is much more costly treatment of end-stage
liver disease and the associated complications, or other disorders
_ treatment often provided at federal government expense,'' said
Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, chief sponsor of the bill in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans warn there are other costs as well, including spreading
the infection to the general public. If it goes unchecked in
veterans, it can be passed to veterans' relatives and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not just us,'' said Terry Baker, a Vietnam veteran
undergoing the new drug therapy. ``It is our children and our
wives. We don't want to see our country infected by us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramlich already gave hepatitis to his wife, Lauren, before he
knew he had it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It breaks my heart,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
