<HEADER>
A2266 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MOORE-COL-DIMAGGI     03-08 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MOORE-COL-DIMAGGIO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Even in the end, DiMaggio called his shots
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He died exactly the way he lived. So when Joe DiMaggio left
Monday to join Ruth, Gehrig, Mantle and the rest of those
pin-striped greats in the baseball heavens, the Yankee Clipper did
so quietly and gracefully.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't surprising. It was appropriate that during the latter
portion of DiMaggio's three-month stay at a Florida hospital before
his release in January, he adjusted the breathing tube in his
throat to tell listeners, ``I want to get the hell out of here and
go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, you figured DiMaggio would get his wish without
objection from doctors or deity, because nobody ever told DiMaggio
what to do. Folks didn't want to. They didn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was hitting in 56 consecutive games or demanding to
be the last person announced at old-timers' games as ``the world's
greatest living ballplayer,'' DiMaggio operated on his terms.
</P>
<P>
   Death had other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Still, nothing ever will kill what DiMaggio left behind, and
that is his nearly unparalleled presence for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   Among the living, only Muhammad Ali matched DiMaggio's ability
to transcend sports in making the bulk of society feel something at
the mention of his name. Otherwise, DiMaggio was the stuff of his
contemporaries in other fields, such as John Wayne, Jacqueline
Kennedy Onassis and even Winston Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   Charisma isn't developed. Charisma just exists, and charisma was
Joseph Paul DiMaggio. It was true right down to his elegant way of
walking, even near the end of his 84 years.
</P>
<P>
   I've mentioned this before, but it is worth repeating,
especially since those eternal words of Simon and Garfunkel
(''Where have you gone, Joe DiMaggio?'') keep dancing in my head.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few gah-gah moments I've had as a journalist came
during the latter 1970s, when I encountered DiMaggio preparing to
leave an elevator at the Oakland Coliseum. It was just the two of
us. He looked to his left and then to his right for something or
somebody.
</P>
<P>
   Then DiMaggio nodded, and then I nodded, and then we both moved
inside the elevator, where I promptly shared a wonderful lifetime
with a legend for only a few seconds. Not only was DiMaggio tan and
fit, but his eyes sparkled, and every silver hair was in place.
</P>
<P>
   We never spoke. I mean, what do you say to Joe DiMaggio? Even
so, in addition to Simon and Garfunkel, I had a lengthy
conversation in my mind with DiMaggio about everything from those
pin-striped legends to his brief marriage with Marilyn Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   Now DiMaggio is gone. You won't know as much after what we'll
experience during the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   We'll see endless black-and-white film of his glorious 13 years
with the Yankees. There will be stories about his days with Monroe,
about his stint as Mr. Coffee, about his insistence to remain in
the shadows when the majority of the world wanted him to do more
than grin and nod.
</P>
<P>
   Then they'll officially lay DiMaggio to rest in his native San
Francisco, but it won't matter. After all, Joe, even in death, with
an impeached president, and with a fluctuating stock market, and
with terrorist threats everywhere, a nation still turns its lonely
eyes to you.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
