<HEADER>
A2274 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAAMEN-NOTES-COX     03-08 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAAMEN-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FAMU, Duke may be historical mismatch
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The largest margin of victory in the NCAA Men's Basketball
Tournament occurred in the first round in 1963 when eventual
champion Loyola of Chicago beat Tennessee Tech by 69, 111-42.
</P>
<P>
   We might have a similar mismatch in store Friday when No. 1 Duke
(32-1) meets MEAC champ Florida A&AMP;M (12-18) in the first round of
the East Regional in Charlotte (7:40 p.m.). Duke brings a 27-game
winning streak into the game and has beaten 19 ACC opponents by an
average of 24 points. The Blue Devils are a prohibitive favorite to
cut down the nets in St. Petersburg on March 29.
</P>
<P>
   The Rattlers, on the other hand, lost their first 10
regular-season games and were 7-18 before winning their last five,
including the MEAC Tournament and the automatic bid. Seeded seventh
in the conference tournament, they beat the top three seeds to get
in.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin George, FAMU's 6-10 center, said his team will not be
intimidated by Duke and its wealth of high-school All-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go in there and play with a lot of heart and
courage,'' said George, who will guard Duke's Elton Brand, a strong
candidate for national player of the year. ``We have to play our
game and go at them like they're regular guys.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's Valpo?
</P>
<P>
   Delaware (25-5), which plays fifth-seeded Tennessee in Friday's
first game in Charlotte, sees itself as this year's Valparaiso, the
Cinderella team that made it to the Sweet 16 in 1998. Last week,
coach Mike Brey, a former assistant at Duke, had scenes from the
movie ``Hoosiers'' spliced into the scouting tape of Drexel, which
Delaware played for the America East tournament championship. The
Blue Hens won 86-67. Delware is hoping for a better showing than it
had in last year's tournament, when Purdue crushed the Blue Hens by
39.
</P>
<P>
   Hoosier hysteria
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of ``Hoosiers,'' the state of Indiana placed four
schools in the NCAA Tournament: Indiana, Purdue, Evansville, and
Valparaiso. Purdue is the most fortunate to get in; the
Boilermakers enter the tournament with five losses in its last six
games.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA to MSU: Play somebody
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State won seven of its last 11 games, and three of
those four losses were to Arkansas and Auburn, both of which made
the tournament. Still, the Bulldogs were left out of the NCAA field
with a 20-12 record. The message: Play a decent non-conference
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs had an RPI of 90 and a schedule ranking of 142.
Their non-conference schedule included Arkansas-Pine Bluff,
Belmont, Centenary, and Tennessee-Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the way we finished and the people we got beat by. . .
. I don't
</P>
<P>
   understand why we weren't selected,'' first-year coach Rick
Stansbury said. ``We won 20 games in one of the best leagues in the
country.''Phelan at the dance
</P>
<P>
   Mount St. Mary's Jim Phelan has won 800 games in his 45 years as
a coach. On the career-victory list, he trails only Dean Smith
(879), Adolph Rupp (876) and Clarence ``Big House'' Gaines (828).
</P>
<P>
   But Phelan, now 69, will be making only his second appearance in
the NCAA Tournament on Friday when his team goes against top-seeded
Michigan State in the Midwest Regional.
</P>
<P>
   Phelan, who became coach in 1954, has spurned numerous offers to
leave the tiny school in the hills of western Maryland. He says he
has no plans to retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my wife had her way,'' he said, ``I'd be doing it until I
was 85, just so I'd be out of her way at home.'' Tony Barnhart
writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
