<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2275 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-08 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CULTURE WAR BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leaders of the major religious right organizations,
whose interests greatly overlap but are not always identical, are
in a cranky mood these days. They have good reason to be.
</P>
<P>
   Confused by a Republican presidential field overloaded with
social conservatives, they have been unable to unite behind a
single candidate and may lose their electoral clout. Frustrated by
a GOP-controlled Congress that has not lived up to their
expectations, they are turning against their past political patrons
and groping blindly for new ways to find support.
</P>
<P>
   Like spoiled children, they are seriously considering packing up
their marbles and leaving the establishment's game.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party should get so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   The season of the religious right's discontent comes after a
remarkable two decades in which they captured control of the GOP
apparatus in several states and powerfully influenced the elections
of hordes of U.S. senators and representatives. Yet the social
conservatives have not become more than a political irritant. They
never managed to translate their narrow concept of morality and
self-righteousness into public policies that could win majority
support nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   And new questions have arisen about just how active their
activists continue to be these days. Some of their leaders are
saying the darndest negative things.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the Senate to convict President Clinton and his
continuing public support in the polls are the immediate cause of
their disgust with government and the country. But many in the
Christian Coalition, Focus on the Family and other right-wing
groups are also finally conceding privately that widespread voter
resistance to their dearest causes may be permanent.
</P>
<P>
   The light dawned slowly after the Republicans seized control of
both houses of Congress in 1994. The religious right had been
promised the moon if only the Democrats were defeated. Demands
included constitutional amendments to balance the federal budget,
outlaw all abortion, ban flag desecration and allow school prayer
in addition to granting public subsidies for private schools and
eliminating the Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   But most Republican lawmakers did not give their issues a
priority, and their agenda is dying. For instance, efforts to end
abortion held up dozens of unrelated legislative initiatives yet
did little but add to the partisan acrimony that infects Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   After voters last fall cut back the GOP House majority, the
shocked Republican Party examined its soul and its image. Most
party leaders think that moving toward the middle and away from
rigid ideology is essential, which is one reason that
inclusion-preaching Texas Gov. George W. Bush immediately became
the heavy frontrunner.
</P>
<P>
   The religious right also got a message but is not sure just what
it is or what to do about it. The movement's leaders have always
been torn between those willing to compromise to gain a voice in
GOP policymaking and those who insist on going down in flames to
make a statement for their principles. That division is now more
intense and public than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious way to regroup and reassert their influence is to
unite behind a presidential candidate who can articulate their
basic agenda and move it ahead. They had tentatively coalesced
behind Missouri Sen. John Ashcroft, but he decided against the
race. Now they confront a range of right-wing candidates who pander
madly to their views but lack popular appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The best known is television commentator Pat Buchanan, a former
Richard Nixon aide who was a conservative favorite when he ran
unsuccessfully in 1992 and 1996. But even Buchanan wins only 4
percent support in this week's Newsweek poll, and many Republicans
feel his past campaigns denouncing so-called cultural
permissiveness have contributed to two successive GOP White House
losses.
</P>
<P>
   The others look like losers too _ Lamar Alexander, still a
nobody after seeming to run for an eternity; Gary Bauer, a lobbyist
who has never been elected to public office; Steve Forbes, best
known for being rich and wanting tax breaks for himself; Rep. John
Kasich of Ohio, a federal budget maven whose figures don't compute;
Dan Quayle, a former vice president and perpetual laughing stock,
and Bob Smith, a New Hampshire senator with delusions of grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Arizona Sen. John McCain and former Cabinet officer
Elizabeth Dole, Bush represents the GOP establishment that believes
in coalition over confrontation. It's those three against the many
right-wingers. In such a sea of candidates, it is unlikely a
divided religious right can deliver a crucial bloc of votes.
</P>
<P>
   This confusion has given credence to grumblings about pulling
out of the political system altogether. Free Congress Foundation
President Paul Weyrich set off a firestorm when he suggested that
the religious right give up trying to take over the government and
other existing institutions and instead build a new, parallel
world.
</P>
<P>
   He envisions the creation of new systems that would coddle
conservatives and protect them against wicked ways. Since he
loathes the public schools that are the backbone of American
education, he touts schooling pupils at home so parents can
directly control what their children learn.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Weyrich is mushy about the separate environment in
which he would have religious purists live. Although he is tapping
into a mood of discouragement, this is loony tunes.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican Party should encourage such fantasy. The
minute the religious right walks away, the GOP is free at last to
reach out to the rest of the country. And perhaps win the
presidency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1814EST &QL; 
