<HEADER>
A2285 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENO-STARR-HNS &LR;      03-08 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-STARR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO URGES COURT TO APPROVE HER INVESTIGATION OF STARR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno on Monday urged a
special three-judge panel to allow the Justice Department to
continue its investigation into whether prosecutors for Whitewater
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr abused their authority while
questioning Monica Lewinsky in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel, which appointed Starr in August 1994, had
directed Starr and Reno in February to file legal briefs on whether
the department has jurisdiction to investigate an independent
counsel's practices.
</P>
<P>
   The court order was in response to a petition filed on Feb. 11
by the Landmark Legal Foundation, a conservative law group based in
Herndon, Va., which asked the court to stop Reno's inquiry into
Starr's office.
</P>
<P>
   Landmark contended that the attorney general does not have the
authority to investigate an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-January, the Justice Department told Starr that it would
begin an investigation into whether his office's prosecutors were
guilty of misconduct. Investigators would also look into whether
Starr's office withheld information from department lawyers about
possible conflicts of interest at the outset of the Lewinsky
inquiry in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In her 10-page brief, Reno argued that because the independent
counsel law gives the attorney general sole responsibility for
dismissing an independent counsel, the department should be able to
investigate possible misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``The act clearly contemplates that the attorney general has the
authority to conduct such investigations, since it requires (her),
upon removal of an independent counsel, to report ... to the
Judiciary Committee of the Senate and House, `specifying the facts
found and the ultimate grounds for such removal,''' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Reno also argued that because the law gave her the power to
remove Starr, the three-judge panel _ also known as the special
division _ did not have the authority to stop her investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in the law remotely suggests that the special division
has authority to prevent the attorney general from inquiring into
whether ... to remove an independent counsel,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's brief was unavailable from either his officer or the
three-judge panel.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Starr and Reno met to negotiate a plan for how the
Justice Department investigation would be conducted. According to
department officials, Reno assured Starr at the meeting that the
investigation was not ordered by the White House and that it would
be done in a fair manner.
</P>
<P>
   Starr reportedly was willing to accept the investigation so long
as its impartiality could be assured, while Reno was willing to
accept a negotiated plan for the investigation so long as she
retained authority over the inquiry, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation likely will delve into allegations of
misconduct by Starr and his deputies in several areas, including
claims that:
</P>
<P>
   _ Their aggressive interrogation of Lewinsky last year without
her lawyer present violated ethics rules;
</P>
<P>
   _ His office leaked secret grand jury material to the media;
</P>
<P>
   _ Starr aides misled Justice officials and failed to reveal a
potential conflict of interest when _ as they sought authority to
investigate the Lewinsky matter _ they denied receiving information
about it from the Paula Corbin Jones legal team, which was suing
President Clinton for sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Starr and his deputies have defended their initial encounter
with Lewinsky, saying she was free to leave. They also have denied
trying to mislead the attorney general about their sources of
information.
</P>
<P>
   If Reno concluded that Starr had engaged in prosecutorial
misconduct, she could remove him or issue a reprimand that would
taint his inquiry. Her finding could also serve as an official
endorsement of the view of the president's lawyers that Starr had
abused his prosecutorial powers in a relentless pursuit of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel is headed by Judge David B. Sentelle of
the District of Columbia Court of Appeals, who pushed for Starr's
appointment as the independent counsel. The other two judges are
Richard D. Cudahy of the Seventh Circuit and Peter T. Fay of the
Eleventh Circuit. Starr replaced Robert B. Fiske Jr., who had been
appointed by the Reno.
</P>
</TEXT>
