<HEADER>
A2287 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     03-08 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY LEAH GARCHIK
</HEADLINE>
   c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE FIGHT TO PUBLISH FICTION ON FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   New York publisher &UR; Barney Rosset &LR;  is fighting with the son of
novelist  &UR; Vladimir Nabokov  &LR; over Rosset's proposed publication of
an English-language version of ``Lo's Diary,'' an Italian novel
spun off from ``Lolita.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dmitri Nabokov &LR;  is citing copyright infringement in France and
the United States in an effort to squelch further publication of
the book, which already has come out in five countries. Knopf had
planned to publish an English version but backed out, as did
Macmillan U.K. and Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. ``I think it's a
mistake morally,''  &UR; Roger Straus  &LR; told the Observer. ``It smells
wrong to me. It's poaching on someone else's territory.'' Nabokov's
lawyer, &UR; Peter Skolnik &LR; , said the book is ``bad,'' ``vulgar,''
``cheap and crass.''
</P>
<P>
   First Amendment lawyer  &UR; Martin Garbus &LR; , on behalf of Rosset and
his Foxrock Books, says the book is `` `Lolita' from a feminist
perspective.'' The matter will be heard in federal court in
Manhattan on March 19, reports the New York Observer.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody had to fight the case, Rosset said. As to previous
publishers who had backed away, ``their birthright as publishers is
to publish,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `TALES' TRAVELS NORTH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   rt,10p10 The Seattle Men's Chorus will premiere its musical
version of  &UR; Armistead Maupin &LR; 's ``Tales of City'' at Benaroya Hall
in Seattle this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The music in ``Tunes From Tales (Music for Mouse)'' will include
some originals _ including ``Michael's Letter to Mother,'' a
coming-out letter set to music; several Disney songs (``Someday My
Prince Will Come'' among them); ``Que Sera Sera''; and ``Stand by
Your Man.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Robert De Niro &LR;  and  &UR; Martin Scorsese &LR;  are going to present
 &UR; Elia Kazan &LR;  with his lifetime achievement award at the Oscars, says
the New York Post. The award is controversial because Kazan named
names during the McCarthy era. De Niro and Scorsese, both known as
left-wingers, apparently were chosen to thwart protest.
</P>
<P>
   - The Sun reports that  &UR; Prince Edward &LR;  has crossed  &UR; Camilla &LR; 
 &UR; Parker Bowles  &LR; off the guest list for his wedding because he
doesn't want to make his mummy angry.
</P>
<P>
   - The stars keep on shining: &UR; Oliver Stone &LR;  is shooting ``Any
Given Sunday'' in Miami Beach, and reports are that he and star
 &UR; Cameron Diaz &LR;  have become very close pals. Meanwhile, the Jewish
Bulletin of Northern California reports that  &UR; Gwyneth Paltrow  &LR; is
descended (on her father's side) from ``a distinguished rabbinic
dynasty.''
</P>
<P>
   - Republican National Committee Chairman  &UR; Jim Nicholson &LR;  made
reporters giggle last week when he criticized Vice President &UR; Al &LR; 
 &UR; Gore &LR;  for ``flying around the country at taxpayers' expense,
ostensibly talking abut policy but really campaigning and exposing
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter from the National Journal asked if he wanted to
rephrase the last two words, says the Hill, he said the Republicans
had rejected calling their new elections committee the Office of
Presidential Affairs, opting instead for the Office of Presidential
Planning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Don Thompson  &LR; is the former musical director and friend of
 &UR; Dusty Springfield &LR; 's described here on Monday; Jim Thompson is his
imaginary twin, dreamed up erroneously by Personals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Julian Lennon  &LR; told Rolling Stone that he receives a card
every Christmas and every birthday from  &UR; Paul McCartney &LR; . ``He
never misses.''
</P>
<P>
   - Literary agent-provocateur &UR; Lucianne Goldberg  &LR; has signed a
deal with Talk News Radio for ``Lucianne!,'' her own talk show.
According to the Post's  &UR; Neal Travis &LR; , the show, which will be
broadcast from 2 to 4 p.m. on Saturdays and Sundays, has already
been signed by 60 stations.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg also told Travis that ``Monica's Story'' is ``sheer
fairy tale. She's still covering up for Bill Clinton, which is why
he wished her a wonderful life the other day.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Cheech Marin  &LR; told  &UR; Bill Boggs  &LR; of the Food Network that he
and his wife crashed the dinner that  &UR; Ann &LR;  and  &UR; Gordon Getty &LR; 
hosted for  &UR; Bill Clinton &LR;  a few weeks ago. Marin said they just
smiled at one of the security guards and were allowed to come
inside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Will you turn off that f_ phone, please?'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - &UR; Laurence Fishburne &LR; , interrupting a performance of ``The Lion
in Winter'' in New York on Saturday night after an audience
member's cell phone beeped for about 20 seconds. The New York Post
reported that the rest of the theatergoers gave Fishburne ``a
thunderous 30-second ovation'' and the show went on.
</P>
