r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     03-08 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY LEAH GARCHIK
</HEADLINE>
   c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE FIGHT TO PUBLISH FICTION ON FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   New York publisher &UR; Barney Rosset &LR;  is fighting with the son of
novelist  &UR; Vladimir Nabokov  &LR; over Rosset's proposed publication of
an English-language version of ``Lo's Diary,'' an Italian novel
spun off from ``Lolita.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dmitri Nabokov &LR;  is citing copyright infringement in France and
the United States in an effort to squelch further publication of
the book, which already has come out in five countries. Knopf had
planned to publish an English version but backed out, as did
Macmillan U.K. and Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. ``I think it's a
mistake morally,''  &UR; Roger Straus  &LR; told the Observer. ``It smells
wrong to me. It's poaching on someone else's territory.'' Nabokov's
lawyer, &UR; Peter Skolnik &LR; , said the book is ``bad,'' ``vulgar,''
``cheap and crass.''
</P>
<P>
   First Amendment lawyer  &UR; Martin Garbus &LR; , on behalf of Rosset and
his Foxrock Books, says the book is `` `Lolita' from a feminist
perspective.'' The matter will be heard in federal court in
Manhattan on March 19, reports the New York Observer.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody had to fight the case, Rosset said. As to previous
publishers who had backed away, ``their birthright as publishers is
to publish,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `TALES' TRAVELS NORTH &LR;
</P>
<P>
