<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIMMERMAN-WRITING-725     03-08 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMMERMAN-WRITING-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FIGHTING JOURNALIST FINDS HIS ROOTS IN A FEARFUL CHILD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUNTA DEL ESTE, Uruguay _ After Argentina's junta freed him in
1979, Jacobo Timerman's testament of prison life, torture and
anti-Semitism stirred comparisons to Dostoyevsky, Camus and Hannah
Arendt. ``Prisoner Without a Name, Cell Without a Number'' brought
Timerman lasting fame and fortune, and he went on to write
critically acclaimed books on Chile, Cuba and Israel's invasion of
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Since the death of his wife, Risha, eight years ago, however,
Timerman has been virtually silent. At 76 he speaks of depression,
drinking and the constant pain in his legs.
</P>
<P>
   But finally the haze seems to be lifting, Timerman said in an
interview, and he is finding his writing powers again. A memoir he
has worked on fitfully for a decade is finally taking form in
unexpected ways, not as the story of his life as a crusading
journalist but as the story of his early years in Buenos Aires,
Argentina, as a poor, immigrant Jewish boy from Ukraine. And as he
plods through a few pages a day in longhand _ a little bit in the
morning and bit more after his siesta, between puffs on a Havana
cigar or walks in his garden with the help of a cane _ he seems to
be finding a second wind to get on with his life.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of writing a memoir came years ago from Ashbel Green,
his longtime editor at Alfred A. Knopf, which has published all his
books in the United States. But Timerman said he hit a wall trying
to write about his years publishing newspapers and challenging both
right-wing generals and left-wing terrorists. The frustrations
grew, he said, as other Argentine writers began writing biographies
about him, and he came to the realization that his life story would
be defined by people who he believed really did not know him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked myself who am I,'' Timerman said, as the requests for
interviews from his would-be biographers came in and he denied them
all. ``To me, my life as a journalist is like a cowboy movie. I
didn't discover anything, I didn't create anything. It was not
anything unusual. So I went to prison and was tortured?''
</P>
<P>
   The power of negative thinking can overwhelm a writer. And
negative thoughts still bubble through Timerman's conversation as
persistently as the fizz in a bottle of seltzer. Never mind that
his exile in Uruguay is voluntary. Never mind that he lives in a
large, graceful house near the beach, complete with a swimming pool
shaded by palm trees. He persistently enters the dark side of life
as he speaks of his best friends inhabiting cemeteries, and as he
laments surrounding himself with photographs of relatives who
rarely visit. He says he has no interest in socializing, and is
destined ``to live surrounded by ghosts.''
</P>
<P>
   What perks him up is the subject of his memoir, which he says
``is beginning to become an inspiration.'' He takes particular
delight in saying he will totally surprise Green and the publishing
world with this new book. He refuses to say how much he has written
or when his work will be finished. But his son Hector, also a
journalist, predicted it would be done by July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to write a memoir of my life as people think of
what my life was: the life of a fighting journalist,'' he said.
``People think my life began when I went to prison. But I went to
prison because of the way my life began much earlier. Thinking
constantly about this book I discovered that I wanted to write
about my fears and dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``My question is, how do you construct a life despite the fears?
Who can say whether the story of a soul _ not only of a life _ but
the soul that becomes a life might not be an inspiration for many
people?''
</P>
<P>
   The creation of Timerman's life, soul, fears and dreams occurred
between the ages of 5 and 16, he said, and they are part of the
larger story of ``the great experience of immigration, the biggest
adventure the world has seen in the last two centuries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My story is that of an immigrant child who goes to school only
speaking Russian in Argentina, an endemically anti-Semitic
country,'' he said. ``Every day I feared when people spoke to me,
even looked at me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was worse than prison, he said, adding, ``I don't fear
torture, but I still fear entering a dark room, just as I did as a
child.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The sources of Timerman's fears are personal, not political. And
they are wrapped up in not only his early experiences with
prejudice, but with poverty as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day was 24 hours of terrible difficulties for a child to
see his parents discussing if there was anything to eat,'' he
recalled. ``We had one bed for four people. You can get love as a
child only from your parents, but if your parents are so troubled,
disturbed and traumatized, the relationship is quite difficult and
you can feel very lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   Loneliness came up repeatedly during a six-hour conversation.
But, surprisingly, Timerman said the loneliness of being in a
prison was not so bad because he was reinforced by ideals and
dreams rooted in his adolescent years discovering Zionism among his
fellow teen-age Argentine Jews. It was among young progressive Jews
that Timerman learned of his love for sports and politics, a
confidence around the girls, a passion for literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were with the Republicans in Spain, but as Jews, socialist
Jews,'' he recalled. ``It made me feel strong, complete, capable of
doing great things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am talking about identity,'' he said. ``How a little, shy
immigrant boy becomes a superman journalist by discovering his
identity. Thanks to being Jewish, I lost all of my fears. I never
thought of that before I started writing the memoir.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Timerman is having a cathartic experience, one in which
writing down his feelings can only do him good. He said that he did
not understand psychology, but that he knew that not even Freud
could explain exactly what he was going through.
</P>
<P>
   ``You begin to feel things you want to see again,'' he said. ``I
feel much more strongly involved with those faraway years than with
those of the last 20. Why? That's something I still have to
discover.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be something for his biographers to ponder as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
