<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2297 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      03-08 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOLTIN' JOE HAS LEFT AND GONE AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The longest unbroken streak by a professional athlete
in any sport ended quietly Monday. After 84 years, 3 months, 1 week
and 4 days of uninterrupted dignity, the great Joe DiMaggio died.
</P>
<P>
   I've marked time by DiMaggio all my life. I was born Nov. 25,
1954, the day DiMaggio turned 40.
</P>
<P>
   By then, he'd been out of baseball for three years. He'd been
divorced from Marilyn Monroe for almost two months. The 56-game
hitting streak for which he was best known (and which still stands)
already was 13 years in the past. Still, DiMaggio was as famous
then as he had been during his playing days.
</P>
<P>
   He must have been.
</P>
<P>
   In the second or third grade, I found out that we shared a
birthday from one of the Sisters of St. Joseph, who announced it to
our class at St. Titus Elementary School as if it were better than
a ``saint's day.'' Because to her, it was.
</P>
<P>
   In the last of the '50s, DiMaggio attended a middleweight title
fight between Sugar Ray Robinson and Carmen Basilio. He went with
his lawyer, Edgar Bennett Williams, and with New York nightclub
owner Toots Shor and novelist Ernest Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   Williams remembered later how DiMaggio was surrounded by
autograph seekers as the group entered the arena. After one young
man had gotten the former ballplayer to sign a program, he looked
at Hemingway and said, ``Hey, you're somebody too, ain't ya?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Hemingway said, pointing at DiMaggio. ``I'm his
doctor.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A peaceful transition &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio died at home. It was a peaceful transition, as should
happen when a man passes from one state of grace into another.
DiMaggio was the greatest center fielder of his time. But it was a
long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   He remained well-known in spite of the fact that we know little
about him. Or maybe because of it.
</P>
<P>
   He never wrote a tell-all book, though he was married to the
most famous sex symbol in history. He never gave a teary-eyed TV
interview or spilled his guts to the tabloids. He never allowed
himself to become a movie of the week.
</P>
<P>
   The one-time Detroit Tigers slugger Hank Greenberg said of
DiMaggio, ``I guess I know Joe almost 40 years now. We've played
hundreds of games against each other. I've talked to him hundreds
of times at banquets and at Shor's and places like that. In a way,
though, I guess I really don't know him. I don't know if anybody
knows Joe DiMaggio.''
</P>
<P>
   All through the years, we've only gotten glimpses.
</P>
<P>
   During his final days with the Yankees, he was asked why he
continued to play as hard as he did when he was a rookie. DiMaggio
said it was because ``there might be a kid in the stands who has
never seen me play.''
</P>
<P>
   The 56-game hitting streak began on May 15, 1941, and ended July
15. In the middle of it, a summer high school history class in
Cincinnati took a poll to name the greatest Americans. Abraham
Lincoln finished third. George Washington was second. DiMaggio was
first. &QL; 
 &QL; 
I remember it, Joe' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many years later, at an old-timers game, a man approached
DiMaggio and said he'd been at Cleveland the night the streak
ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just a kid then,'' the man said, ``and I was rooting for
you to get a hit because it would have been fun to see you go all
season with a hit in every game. I remember it, Joe. I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do too,'' DiMaggio said.
</P>
<P>
   It's as big a personal disclosure as DiMaggio was willing to
make. He must have known a legend can't survive without mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Lefty Gomez, a teammate and friend, once explained it this way:
``He knew he was Joe DiMaggio and he knew what that meant to the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   It meant even more to certain families, like ours, for which
DiMaggio's greatness was magnified by the fact he was Italian.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in San Francisco, but his parents were from Italy,
like all of my grandparents. They were all American citizens, but
in the first half of this century, some citizens, like some
citizens now, were made to feel like foreigners. Even someone like
DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   In 1939, as he was coming into his own as a ballplayer, ``Life''
magazine did a profile of DiMaggio. It read in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``Italians, bad at war, are well-suited for milder competition.
. . . Although he learned Italian first, Joe, now 24, speaks
English without an accent, and is otherwise well adapted to most
U.S. mores. Instead of olive oil and smelly bear grease, he keeps
his hair slick with water. He never reeks of garlic and prefers
chicken chow mein to spaghetti.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder he preferred privacy to publicity. &QL; 
 &QL; 
His days with Marilyn &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gay Talese is the only writer to come close to separating
DiMaggio the Person from DiMaggio the Persona. Talese wrote a
profile of the retired ballplayer for ``Esquire'' magazine in the
1960s. Three paragraphs from that article tell the whole story of
DiMaggio and Monroe. They are:
</P>
<P>
   ``He was then 39, she was 27. They had been married in January
of that year, 1954, despite disharmony in temperament and time: He
was tired of publicity, she was thriving on it; he was intolerant
of tardiness, she was always late. During their honeymoon in Tokyo,
an American general had introduced himself and asked if, as a
patriotic gesture, she would visit the troops in Korea. She looked
at Joe. `It's your honeymoon,' he said, shrugging, `go ahead if you
want to.'
</P>
<P>
   ``She appeared on 10 occasions before 100,000 servicemen, and
when she returned, she said, `It was so wonderful, Joe. You never
heard such cheering.'
</P>
<P>
   `` `Yes I have,' he said.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time I got around to reading that story, it was the
1970s. DiMaggio had been out of baseball for more than 20 years.
Monroe had been dead for more than 10 years. Sometime in there,
Joltin' Joe, the Yankee Clipper, started doing Mr. Coffee
commercials. Even that didn't hurt his image.
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't. After he retired, DiMaggio lived his life the way
he'd played the game, as if there might be a kid out there who'd
never seen him before. He did it year after year, his strength and
speed waning, but never his form, until the streak ended early
Monday morning. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1831EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
