<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2300 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DIMAGGIO-ESSAY-BO     03-08 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DIMAGGIO-ESSAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIMAGGIO: DEMANDING TO THE END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was on the top of the grandstand roof at Fort Lauderdale
Stadium that I saw Joe DiMaggio play. I heard him sing, too.
</P>
<P>
   This was out of sight of the crowd that had come to his annual
charity game for the children's hospital in South Florida that
bears his name. DiMaggio was 81 then, and he was tossing a soft,
padded ball back and forth to his great granddaughters, Valerie and
Vanessa. They called him Big Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like these cookies,'' Vanessa had said to her great
grandpa as they snacked on finger sandwiches and shrimp and cookies
in a private box.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about getting me one?'' Big Joe said. ``Give me one with
walnuts.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was time to sing, ``Take Me Out to the Ballgame,'' Big
Joe joined in, his voice softer than those of the children and his
granddaughters, Paula and Cathy, but he knew all of the words.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one baseball displayed in DiMaggio's home,
according to DiMaggio's close friend and attorney, Morris
Engelberg. It was the one signed by Vanessa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe's a relatively frugal man,'' Engelberg said, ``but
anything Vanessa wants is hers.''
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken Jr. threw out the first ball that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks for inviting me to come,'' Ripken told DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio was in Baltimore the night Ripken broke Lou Gehrig's
record for consecutive games played.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it on my own,'' DiMaggio said. ``I wanted to see it
because Gehrig was my teammate. I was invited by Mr. (Peter)
Angelos (the Orioles' owner).''
</P>
<P>
   Also present that night in Florida was Tommy Henrich, the Old
Reliable who broke in with the Yankees one year after DiMaggio, in
1937.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank God I saw the best of DiMaggio,'' Henrich said.
``You've got no idea how great he was. Let me sum it up this way:
DiMaggio was the best winner I ever saw in my life. It was so
doggone important to him to finish ahead of somebody by the end of
the day.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio, Engelberg said, was a man who still wore a jacket and
tie everywhere, including to the dentist's office. Most mornings,
he was up at 5 and out the door by 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very tough to be Joe DiMaggio's friend _ he's a very
tough guy to deal with,'' Engelberg said. ``He's on the point. You
can't be late a second. If he says, `Call me at 8 o'clock,' and you
call one minute after 8, he goes crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Age had made him no less demanding, of himself and those around
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a second life,'' said Joe Nacchio, one of
DiMaggio's closest friends who was at his bedside when he died,
``there are three things I don't want to come back as. Joe's
chauffeur. Joe's barber. And Joe's tailor.''
</P>
<P>
   No one, Engelberg said, ever asked DiMaggio to pick up a check
in a restaurant. He had stacks of clothes still unopened in boxes
in his apartment. Engelberg's secretary, Valerie, cleaned
DiMaggio's apartment _ he wouldn't trust a housekeeper with his
possessions _ and did his shopping for him.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, he played golf, at least three or four times a
week, despite the arthritis in his back, then had a steam bath
before dinner. He also made visits to his hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``His personality changes with children,'' said Frank Sacco, the
hospital administrator who used to accompany DiMaggio on his rounds
through the neonatal unit, and the cancer ward, and the rooms of
children hooked up to machines as frightening-looking as they are
life-giving.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very reserved,'' Sacco said, ``but when he sees children,
all of a sudden something happens to him.''
</P>
<P>
   His was a male-dominated world, according to those who knew him
best. One friend said he hadn't seen DiMaggio on a date in years.
Evenings, when he was home, DiMaggio watched TV. He liked Westerns
and war pictures and CNN. He'd watch a ballgame, but much the way
many of us do, he'd channel surf with the remote control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still a fan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I saw DiMaggio for the last time in September in Chicago, where
he was receiving an award from the Italian-American Sports Hall of
Fame. Engelberg said he couldn't promise me an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't write this,'' he said, ``but Joe has walking pneumonia.
Nothing serious, but we're probably going to leave the dinner, go
upstairs and watch the fights on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   I never did talk to DiMaggio that night. The next day, he flew
to New York and made an appearance at Yankee Stadium, but did no
interviews that day, either. Before the week was out, he was in the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Less than six months later, he was dead. Two little girls had
lost their Big Joe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1834EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
