<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2301 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-BOND0309-COX     03-08 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-BOND0309-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JULIAN BOND LINKS INTERESTS OF AFRICAN-AMERICANS, HISPANICS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) Political categories
 &HT;    with photos
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NAACP Chairman Julian Bond, assessing the
importance of political alliances among minority groups in the 2000
election, said Monday that African-Americans and Hispanics, in
general, ``think and vote the same'' on basic issues of civil
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, ``I don't think it's going to pay off'' if there
is any attempt by Republicans, and especially by Gov. George Bush
of Texas, to target Hispanic voters as a way of offsetting
overwhelming Democratic advantages among African-Americans in next
year's presidential and congressional elections, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Hispanic community generally - and this is a big
generalization - is aligned with the black community on these
issues,'' Bond said during an interview with Cox News Service. ``I
do think a candidate like Governor Bush, who speaks Spanish, who
has attracted a large Hispanic vote in his native state of Texas,
is going to be attractive, because he knows this community, he's
familiar with this community, he's not coming to it brand new.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as a general proposition _ although I can't say what the
percentage is going to be _ on civil rights issues, blacks and
Hispanics, generally speaking, think and vote the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a ``major priority'' of every one of the NAACP's 2,200
local branches is to reach out to the local Hispanic community and,
in preparation for next year's election, to conduct voter
registration drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We very badly want to swell our numbers, because we think the
more the merrier,'' Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights, a
Washington-based lobbying organization for dozens of civil rights
groups, has expanded from blacks and labor groups to include
Hispanics and Asians - ``the whole spectrum of who we are as
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Polling data by the Tarrance Group, a well-known Republican
polling firm, show that while Hispanic voters are closer to the GOP
on issues of education, family values and entrepreneurship, an
overwhelming majority also view the Democratic Party as ``standing
up for the people.''
</P>
<P>
   And since last fall's election, Republican strategists have
focused on how to win back Hispanic voters from the Democratic
Party. They frequently cite Bush's performance among Hispanics. He
won 49 percent of the Hispanic vote, 14 points above the national
average.
</P>
<P>
   According to television network exit polls, in last year's
congressional election, 59 percent of the Hispanic vote went
Democratic, 35 percent Republican. By way of comparison, 88 percent
of African-Americans voted Democratic, about 11 percent Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not Democrats because Democrats are so great,'' Bond
said, referring to African-Americans in general and not, he
emphasized, the NAACP, which is nonpartisan. ``We're Democrats
because the Republicans are so bad on these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond, a one-time Democratic member of the Georgia Legislature
and candidate for Congress in Atlanta, said he does not know Bush,
but is interested ``to see how his campaign (for president)
develops,'' particularly in terms of reaching out to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the newspaper coverage of Bush's announcement of an
``exploratory committee'' Sunday, which included photographs of
Bush standing with African-Americans and Hispanics, Bond said, ``I
hope it's more than a photo op, that it means something.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond, in a wide-ranging interview, also said that:
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP would spend ``as much money as it takes'' in order to
defeat any statewide initiatives to end affirmative action
programs. The organization spent $70,000 in Washington last fall,
where such an initiative passed.
</P>
<P>
   There has been an ``abdication of responsibility'' on the part
of most white Americans to help solve the problem of race in
America, and that he would like to see more whites join the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   A debate is underway within the NAACP about its future role,
with Bond trying to ``tip the scale'' away from social services to
social justice efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Racism is ``pervasive'' in America today, although it does not
``exhibit itself daily with hoods and sheets and horrendous
incidents'' like the death of James Byrd in Jasper, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi should lead a
``loud and clear condemnation'' of the Council of Conservative
Citizens, a white supremacist organization whose leaders have been
hosted by Lott.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau should conduct two counts, if necessary, to
produce ``as fair and as inclusive'' a census as possible.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's racial initiative ``discovered or created''
what he termed ``cross-racial dialogue'' that should improve
understanding between whites and blacks.
</P>
<P>
   The president will be ``fondly remembered'' by African-Americans
for his defense of affirmative action but would be ``less fondly
remembered'' for welfare reform. ``It's a mixed record, but on
balance, it's a good record,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
