<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO FURTHER DISCIPLINE FOR CHECK BY BELANGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Ken Belanger expected the worst Monday but wound up
with the best-case scenario when he learned he wouldn't receive any
supplementary discipline from the NHL for drilling Rangers
defenseman Ulf Samuelsson into the boards in the first period of
Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   The league office reviewed videotape of the hit, which knocked
Samuelson out of the game, but felt the five-minute major for
boarding and game misconduct were the proper punishment for
Belanger.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to finding out he would be eligible to play against
Florida Tuesday, Belanger was clearly expecting the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the puck in his skates, his shoulder was on the
boards,'' said Belanger. ``As I was going in, I don't know if he
kind of saw me and he turned back. If his visor doesn't cut his
face, it's not a major. If he gets up right away, it's not a major.
Maybe if I'm not so big, I hit him and it's not a call.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you do? Do you poke-check the puck out of his skates
or do you hit him? It's hockey. I never hit anyone from behind
before and got a major. It's not like it was intentional. I never
meant to hurt him, I was just finishing my check. It's just the way
he kind of turned I guess. There was no intent to injure.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuelsson suffered a concussion and was scheduled to be
evaluated in New York Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The hit wasn't particularly vicious, though Belanger wouldn't
have been surprised by a suspension (``I never get off easy on
anything,'' he said).
</P>
<P>
   The FleetCenter fans cheered when Samuelsson went down and booed
when he finally got up after several minutes and had to be helped
to the bench and dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   Samuelsson, of course, is blamed in these parts for cutting
short Cam Neely's career as a result of a hit in the 1991 playoffs
when Samuelsson played for the Penguins. But Belanger said he
wasn't aware of all the history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't here when all that stuff went down,'' he said. ``It
wasn't revenge. It was just a coincidence that it happened to be
him. I guess he's not well liked here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not out there to hurt guys. Everyone is playing hard and
doing their jobs. It's just unfortunate that he got hurt. I'm sure
there are a lot of happy people out there but I'm not happy about
what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Belanger expected to be assessed at least one game and thought
that since Colin Campbell, the former Rangers' coach, was meting
out the punishment, he might be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's Ulf Samuelsson and he's hurt a lot of players,'' said
Belanger. ``It's good having a reputation as being tough, but
referees always look for that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the situation comes up again where the guy has the puck
along the boards, I'm not going to say, `I can't hit him because
I'm going to get suspended.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There has been some confusion about Tuesday's game because of
the original schedule. The Bruins host Florida Tuesday night, not
Wednesday, at the FleetCenter . . . Forward Peter Ferraro cleared
waivers and was demoted to Providence. In 45 games with Boston,
Ferraro had 6 goals and 14 points. ``I'm very unhappy the way it
turned out,'' said Ferraro. ``Certainly, I got a great opportunity
to play here and play under a great coaching staff and with some
great teammates. I have to go to Providence with a positive
attitude and do the best I can down there and hopefully I'll be
back.'' . . . Forward Steve Heinze's run of less-than-stellar luck
continued. He had to leave practice a little early Monday because
he was struck in the jaw by a puck and needed several stitches . .
. Defenseman Darren Van Impe, who has been out of the lineup since
suffering a separated shoulder Feb. 9, is closing in on a return,
perhaps as early as this weekend. ``If not this weekend, then not
too long after that,'' said Van Impe. ``We'll just have to see over
the next couple of days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
