<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGG-PERKIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EG&AMP;G TO BUY PERKIN DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EG&AMP;G Inc. said it plans to acquire an instruments unit from
Perkin-Elmer Corp. for $425 million in cash and debt.
</P>
<P>
   EG&AMP;G also said it may sell or spin off its technical services
unit, which manages a chemical weapons disposal plant and other
facilities for the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Both steps are part of a strategy to concentrate on commercial
businesses with higher profit margins, said EG&AMP;G's president and
chief executive Gregory L. Summe. ``We're clearly shifting the
profile and narrowing the focus,'' Summe said in an interview at
the company's headquarters in Wellesley, Mass. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The federal contracting unit, he said, is ``not synergistic from
a customer or from an employee standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   With about 6,000 employees scattered around the country, the
technical services unit's 1998 revenue of $553 million made up 39
percent of EG&AMP;G's total 1998 revenue of $1.4 billion. In addition
to the chemical weapons destruction plant in Utah, other operations
include services for the US Navy and a contract to oversee
redevelopment work at Kelly Air Force Base in San Antonio, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   This year the unit's revenues are expected to fall to $450
million, mainly because it failed to obtain a major contract to
operate the Kennedy Space Center in Florida. Profits are also low,
a chief reason Summe has steered EG&AMP;G to focus on private sector
work since he was named to head the company 13 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Perkin-Elmer's Analytic Instruments Division
is also meant to complement EG&AMP;G's existing instruments unit. Based
in Norwalk, Conn., the Perkin-Elmer unit has 3,100 employees and
reported sales of $569 million in its last fiscal year. Its devices
are used in the manufacture of drugs and to test food, water, and
materials purity.
</P>
<P>
   No layoffs are expected to result from the purchase, Summe said.
Under the terms of the transaction, EG&AMP;G will pay $275 million for
the unit and will assume $150 million worth of debt from
Perkin-Elmer.
</P>
<P>
   If the transaction is completed as expected before June, EG&AMP;G
expects to write off about $30 million worth of Perkin-Elmer
research now under way, Summe said.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise the transaction is not expected to to affect 1999
earnings and will add to earnings beginning in 2000. Both
companies' boards of directors have approved the transaction, which
still requires approvals from various US agencies and from some in
Europe, where the Perkin-Elmer unit conducts 40 percent of its
business.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, EG&AMP;G will assume control of the Perkin-Elmer brand
name for use with the new unit. Perkin-Elmer Corp. will change its
name to PE Corp. after one year, Summe said.
</P>
<P>
   EG&AMP;G said it has hired Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. ``to explore
strategic alternatives'' for its technical services Unit. Summe
declined to discuss what price he hopes the unit might receive if
it were sold outright.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in EG&AMP;G rose 5/16 to 27 7/8 in New York Stock Exchange
trading. Shares in Perkin-Elmer Corp. fell 1/4 to 92 1/2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1837EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2307 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     03-08 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS: `I NEVER, EVER COMPARED MYSELF TO HIM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Theirs was a two-man club. They knew things
no one else could know. They had experiences no one else shared. In
their time, baseball's golden age, Joe DiMaggio and Ted Williams
were the best players and ultimate American heroes. Never teammates
or even friends, they were measured against one another from
opposite ends of the New York-Boston corridor.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio-Williams was something more than Russell-Chamberlain,
Bird-Magic, or Ali-Frazier. It was more like FDR and Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   The comparisons and questions never stopped. Photographs,
statistics, and memories tracked them into their 80s, and Monday,
when DiMaggio died, the hardball world waited for word from Ted.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was in bed in Hernando, Fla., watching the History
Channel and talking on the phone when an employee came into his
room with word that the great DiMaggio had died at his home in
Florida at the age of 84.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friend came into my room in the morning and said, `I got
some news,' and I knew what it was right away,'' Williams said. ``I
can only tell you that I'm sad, but I'm happy Joe's not suffering
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an American hero and a legend for sure. I never, ever
compared myself to him. I thought there never was a greater player
in the history of baseball. For me just to be mentioned in the same
breath, boy, I always felt like I was two steps below him. I
thought I could hit with anybody, but he was in my opinion as good
as any that ever played this game. There's only one guy I saw you
could mention in the same breath, and that was Willie Mays. I felt
that just to have my name mentioned with Joe, it elevated me. I
never thought I was ever as good.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly they were different. DiMaggio was a graceful center
fielder, a righthanded batter who rarely struck out. He was the
complete player who rarely showed any emotion. It was noteworthy
just to see Joe D kick the dirt after an outfielder made a
spectacular grab to rob him of a hit. Williams, meanwhile, lived to
hit. Everything else _ fielding, throwing, running the bases _ was
stuff you had to do to stay in the lineup and get a chance to hit.
Ted was combustible, sometimes spitting in the direction of his
hecklers and smashing equipment after frustrating plate
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   They did not have many conversations or share many laughs when
they dominated baseball in the 1940s. DiMaggio was the quiet,
dignified son of an Italian immigrant from San Francisco. Williams
was the cocky slugger from San Diego. Joe played for the perennial
world champion Yankees. Ted played for the runner-up (or worse) Red
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Ted was the fire. Joe was the ice. And often their greatness
intersected. DiMaggio was American League MVP when Ted hit .327
with 31 homers and 145 RBIs as a rookie in 1939. When Ted hit .406
(baseball's last .400 season) in 1941, Joe D hit in 56 straight
games and won the MVP again. When Ted hit the home run off Claude
Passeau to win the 1941 All-Star Game in Detroit, Joe D was
standing at home plate to congratulate Boston's young slugger.
</P>
<P>
   When Williams's Red Sox went to New York for the final two games
of the 1949 season, needing a single victory to clinch the American
League pennant, DiMaggio's Yankees won both games and went to the
World Series. Ted was MVP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never did dislike him,'' said Williams. ``I liked him. I
wasn't jealous, but I was envious. He had great complements with
him, too. One guy can't do it. All they have to do is walk you.''
</P>
<P>
   There were five DiMaggio brothers, and three became major
leaguers. Williams's longtime Red Sox teammate was Dominic
DiMaggio, Joe's baby brother who was at his bedside when he died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have so much admiration and strong feeling about the
DiMaggio family,'' Williams remembered. ``I played (in the minors)
with Vince, who was a good ballplayer and a wonderful person. Then,
of course, I played with Dominic for 10 years, and everybody knows
what I thought of him. Joe I saw for a lot of years, and nobody was
any better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I actually saw him was in Yankee Stadium,
Opening Day in '39. I had been in the (Pacific) Coast League in
'37, and he had just left the league and was making major league
history. I remember I always played him deep, I'll tell you that.
He didn't say much to me. He'd just say, `You're doing a great job
with that ball club.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Franchise players from rival teams often get to know one another
during the midsummer All-Star Game. This wasn't the case when Ted
and Joe teamed up for the American League.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't talk much, even then,'' remembered Williams, now 80.
``Joe would come early and never talk to anybody. I'd talk more
with Hank Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I do remember one thing from one of those games. I was
playing left and he was playing center, and we were in Brooklyn.
Jackie Robinson hit a line drive to left center that bounced up
against the fence and came to DiMaggio. Joe didn't look like he was
rushing or anything, but he took that ball and ripped it into
second base. It was a bang-bang play and Robinson was safe, but I
thought to myself, `Jesus.' I was impressed with that, with the way
he made that play so close without even hurrying.''
</P>
<P>
   (itals)Williams, Robinson, DiMaggio. Converging on a single
play. There's a little hardball history buried in that All-Star
anecdote.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   It's hard for him to talk about the passing of his longtime
rival. Williams is scheduled to appear with Tom Brokaw on NBC
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Dom,'' said Williams. ``He knows how much I
thought of the DiMaggio clan. The last several months, every time I
talked to Dom, it was always, `How's Joe today?' I admired them all
because they were all good players. It's a sad day to think that
Joe DiMaggio is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
