<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, March 9. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The federal government announces
that it has reached a tentative settlement in its antitrust case
that was to begin this week against Intel Corp., the world's
largest producer of computer chips. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-DIMAGGIO (Undated) _ Joe DiMaggio, the flawless center
fielder for the New York Yankees who, along with Babe Ruth and
Mickey Mantle, symbolized the team's dynastic greatness across the
20th century and whose 56-game hitting streak in 1941 made him an
instant and indelible American folk hero, has died. By Joseph
Durso. With photos. 3,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: See also OBIT-DIMAGGIO-ABRIDGED and
BC-DIMAGGIO-ADVISORY-NYT for list of stories and photos.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ With circuit courts split on immigration,
and thousands of cases bulging the federal court system, the
Supreme Court declines the opportunity to interpret the 1996
immigration law. The cases they avoid taking raised statutory and
constitutional questions. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-LAND-TRUST (Wetumka, Okla.) _ The federal government,
which holds more than 10 million acres in trust for up to
half-a-million individual Indians, seems incapable of keeping track
of the money from the land, which is often leased to oil and gas
companies. By Timothy Egan. With map. 2,000 words. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-JEWS (Moscow) _ After a promising new chapter when the
Soviet Union expired, Russia's Jews are now facing growing
anti-Semitism. By Michael R. Gordon. 2,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   ILL-PROSECUTORS-CHARGED (Chicago) _ A trial will begin Tuesday
in a well-heeled Chicago suburb that could have reverberations
throughout the nation's criminal justice system. In a case that is
considered virtually unprecedented, three former prosecutors in
affluent DuPage County are being tried on charges that they and
four sheriff's deputies conspired to frame an innocent man, sending
him to death row for the 1983 rape and murder of a 10-year-old
girl. The sheriff's deputies have also been charged in the case,
known as the trial of the DuPage Seven. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
</TEXT>
