<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-CABINET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISARMAMENT DISPUTE FORCES DELAY IN CREATING NORTHERN IRELAND
CABINET 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Britain announced a three-week
postponement Monday in the effort to create an executive cabinet
that is to give the Roman Catholic minority more power and return
home rule to this British province.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Mowlam, the British Northern Ireland Secretary, said the
delay was needed to give the politicians more time to seek
compromise in the dispute over disarmament of the Irish Republican
Army. But Gerry Adams, president of Sinn Fein, the IRA's political
wing, clearly anticipating the delay, blamed it on the British
government and said, ``now we're into crisis time, big time.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive cabinet, which was to have been formed by members
of the Northern Ireland Assembly this Wednesday, was delayed by the
dispute over the disarmament of the IRA. The Protestant first
minister of the Assembly, David Trimble, has ruled that until the
IRA begins ``credible'' disarmament, Sinn Fein will not be allowed
to take its two places in the new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Adams says, accurately, that the agreement setting up the
Assembly does not require disarmament before May, 2000. He says the
IRA's current 19-month cease-fire is evidence that it supports the
peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   The police of the Royal Ulster Constabulary declined to comment
Monday night on a report in Monday's editions of the Belfast
Telegraph newspaper that the police had warned Adams of a threat to
his life by an unspecified IRA splinter group that opposes his
participation in the peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach a compromise failed again Monday as Adams met
in Dublin with Prime Minister Bertie Ahern of the Irish Republic.
Generally, northern Catholics look to Dublin to the overwhelmingly
Catholic Irish Republic to support their demands. But Ahern has
said that it is unrealistic to expect Protestants to sit in a
cabinet with Sinn Fein until the disarmament dispute is settled.
</P>
<P>
   Adams and Trimble are to meet in Belfast on Tuesday, but
officials and experts said a breakthrough in the dispute was
unlikely. In announcing the delay, Ms. Mowlam said she was dropping
the March 10 deadline and extending it to the week starting March
29.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean that the politicians would be talking about it
as the first anniversary of approval of the overall peace agreement
approached on April 10, presumably increasing public pressure for a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mowlam said the delay would give the northern political
parties ``the time and space to find a way forward.'' She noted
that many Assembly members would be in Washington next week for St.
Patrick's Day ceremonies at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, whose involvement in the peace effort has
been crucial, is widely expected to urge the politicians to end the
disarmament dispute. In Washington, Ms. Mowlam said, ``There will
be opportunities to build confidence and talk informally
together,'' in preparation for an intensive round of discussions in
Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, in Dublin, Ms. Mowlam and Irish Foreign Minister David
Andrews signed four treaties legalizing the previously approved new
political structures that would permit the transfer of governmental
powers to the Assembly by the British government, which has ruled
directly since a power-sharing body of Protestants and Catholics
collapsed in 1974.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
