A2326 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-08 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WAS THE MYSTIQUE THAT SET HIM SO FAR APART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He made it look easy. That's what they all said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know of no athlete who gives you quite the same sense of
effortless ease that DiMaggio does in the performance of his
baseball tasks.''
</P>
<P>
   So wrote Grantland Rice in his foreword to Joe DiMaggio's
autobiography, ``Lucky To Be A Yankee.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Cannon agreed. ``The long-boned grace was there from the
beginning and that shaped his style, but the purity was Joe
DiMaggio's baseball talent,'' observed the legendary writer in a
1956 piece for Sport magazine. ``The game of baseball was simple
for him, and he never attempted to make it complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point in that same memorable piece, Cannon makes
reference to DiMaggio ``drifting back after a fly ball with that
marvelous certainty.'' There was clearly something distinct about
Joe DiMaggio, something unique to him, that moved the great
craftsman of the sportswriting profession to reach only for
superlatives in describing the play of the wondrous Yankee center
fielder, who died early Monday at age 84.
</P>
<P>
   In the alleged egalitarianism of American society, DiMaggio was
royalty. Others played; DiMaggio performed. In England, he would
have played his last several years as (itals)Sir(unitals) Joseph
DiMaggio, no questions asked.
</P>
<P>
   We Americans do not confer knighthood. We settle for nicknames.
The Voice. The Schnozz. The Great Profile. In DiMaggio's case, The
Yankee Clipper. Imagine being compared to a graceful 19th-century
sailing ship.
</P>
<P>
   When Hemingway needed a sports reference, it was DiMaggio. When
Paul Simon needed an American heroic reference, it was DiMaggio.
When Sport magazine wanted to attract attention for its inaugural
issue in 1946, the only choice for the cover was DiMaggio. When
that same magazine wanted a centerpiece story to celebrate its 10th
anniversary, the only choice was DiMaggio, who was then five years
into retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Many players have had an aura, Ted Williams included. DiMaggio
alone had a mystique. He had it as a ballplayer and he had it for
the rest of his life, starting with the fact that after his
retirement, he married Marilyn Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folk idols,'' said Cannon. ``The whole country's pets.''
</P>
<P>
   The marriage lasted nine months, but we know that Joe carried
his torch to the grave.
</P>
<P>
   And never spoke about it publicly.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is part of the DiMaggio mystique. DiMaggio was
eternally conscious of being DiMaggio. You might say it was his
life's calling.
</P>
<P>
   No one that accomplished at his trade could be unaware of his
stature. Consider his reaction to the celebrated Al Gionfriddo
catch in front of the visiting bullpen in Game 6 of the 1947 World
Series. ``He was playing me wrong,'' DiMaggio fumed. ``What right
does he have to play me that shallow? If he'd been playing me
right, he wouldn't have had to run that far.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio's career is proof that style and inherent professional
class are more important than numbers. He forever will be
associated with the 56-game hitting streak, but his other primary
career numbers (.325 batting average, 361 home runs, 2,214 hits,
1,537 runs batted in) are reasonably modest in context. The most
impressive number, aside from 56, is 369. That was his lifetime
strikeout total.
</P>
<P>
   With DiMaggio, it was never about the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Stengel: ``He had the greatest instinct of any ballplayer
I ever saw. He made the rest of them look like plumbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Luke Appling: ``He could do everything better than any
ballplayer I ever saw. He was without weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Cronin: ``He was the greatest I ever saw or hope to see. He
was just about the perfect ballplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe McCarthy: ``I don't think anyone can ever put into words the
great things DiMaggio did. Of all the stars I've known, DiMaggio
needed the least coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Hank Greenberg: ``Name a better righthanded hitter or a better
thrower or a better fielder or a better baserunner. That's right, a
better baserunner. Did you ever see him slide when he hooked the
bag with his toe? Absolutely perfect!''
</P>
<P>
   Stan Musial: ``There was never a day when I was as good as Joe
DiMaggio at his best. Joe was the best, the very best I ever saw.''
</P>
<P>
   The big DiMaggio autobiography, the one that would not only have
DiMaggio talking about baseball as only he could but also would
have given us insight into his relationship with Marilyn, was the
Holy Grail of publishing. ``The price tag was around $2 million 10
years ago when he actually held discussions with us about doing
it,'' explains Simon &AMP; Schuster editor Jeff Neumann. ``Today it
would be worth $4 million or $5 million.''
</P>
<P>
   It never came out. No amount of money was ever worth it to
DiMaggio if the cost were the surrender of his soul. ``He was not
interested in `setting the record straight,' '' recalls Neumann,
``nor in settling history. He was only considering it because he
knew we wanted it. And in the end, he just couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Game 6 of the 1951 Series was his final game, and he lived out
the next 47 years as Joe DiMaggio, the Ultimate American Superstar,
and the Yankees' Yankee. He was accessible to the American public
only when he chose to be, and in so doing, he created a Garbo-like
demand for his presence that separated him from every other similar
sports icon.
</P>
<P>
   In Broadway musicals, there is always supposed to be a
showstopping number. At Old-Timers' Days, the showstopping number
was Joe DiMaggio, and it was no accident.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the deal at any public gathering of ballplayers was that
Joe DiMaggio would be introduced last, and that he would referred
to as ``the greatest living ballplayer.'' He insisted on it.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever objected.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
