<SLUG> BC-EAPPEN-LAWYERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER DA DENOUNCES `60 MINUTES' FOR AIRING EAPPEN REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Saying CBS had inflicted unnecessary pain on a family
that has suffered enough, Attorney General Thomas Reilly denounced
``60 Minutes'' Monday for broadcasting a segment suggesting Matthew
Eappen died of strangulation rather than a head injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have lost all sense of decency, and all for the sake of a
sensational story that is really a sideshow that has very little to
do with what happened in court,'' Reilly said of the Sunday segment
on the CBS news magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, who in his previous role as Middlesex County district
attorney brought the charges resulting in the conviction of British
au pair Louise Woodward for killing Matthew Eappen, added: ``I hope
they are satisfied with themselves. All they have done is cause
further harm and pain.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kevin Tedesco, spokesman for ``60 Minutes,'' said the news
magazine had aired a legitimate story providing new information
about a case that has generated tremendous national interest. ``He
is entitled to his opinion, just as we are entitled to do a story
about forensic evidence in such a high-profile trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Tedesco denied that CBS had broadcast its story as a ratings
bid. `We don't do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``60 Minutes'' segment featured Dr. Floyd Gilles, a
child-abuse specialist at Children's Hospital in Los Angeles, who
said his examination of the medical record made him believe Eappen
died from strangulation. At the 1997 trial, prosecutors said the
baby died from violent shaking and having his head slammed against
a hard object, which caused fatal brain swelling.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, in an interview with the Globe Monday, said the ``60
Minutes'' executives should have weighed the relevance of the story
against the pain it would cause the Eappens before airing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't determine people's guilt or innocence based on a
20-minute story by Mike Wallace,'' Reilly said. ``They have lost
sight of the family and lost sight of their pain. To continue to
torment them like this is terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he rejected it, Reilly said that even if Gilles's
theory were true, it wouldn't exonerate Woodward because ``she
could have done that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Harvey Silverglate, one of Woodward's attorneys, said the
new theory, if true, actually could help exculpate Woodward,
because that scenario expands the period during whic the injury
could have occurred. On the CBS program, Gilles said the actual
injury could have occurred as many as two days before the fatal
brain swelling.
</P>
<P>
   If delayed effects of strangulation caused the baby's death,
Woodward would be no more likely a suspect than any other member of
the household that had access to the baby in that period,
Silverglate said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was as much or as little evidence against them as there
was against her, because they are all in exactly the same
position,'' Silverglate said. ``Under these circumstances it would
be unfair to suspect any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Silverglate said Woodward's defense team would now try to have
its experts meet with Gilles and another physician who shares his
view. If the experts concur, he said, Woodward's lawyers will ask
Martha Coakley, the new Middlesex County district attorney, to
allow further examination of the medical evidence, particularly
tissue samples.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward, now a law student in England, was released from prison
last year after Judge Hiller Zobel reduced her sentence from
second-degree murder to involuntary manslaughter and sentenced her
to time already served.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
