<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2329 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KUBRICK-APPRECIATION-     03-08 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KUBRICK-APPRECIATION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICK'S FILM LEGACY LIMITED YET OVERPOWERING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By   BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The one comforting thought about Stanley Kubrick's
death on Sunday is that it probably hasn't robbed the world of too
many great films. He only made four features during the last
quarter century, including the just-completed erotic thriller
``Eyes Wide Shut,'' which is scheduled for release in July.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the 70-year-old genius' first production in 12 years,
so how many more could we reasonably expect?
</P>
<P>
   The loss of even one more Kubrick film, however, is an
incalculable tragedy. Kubrick directed only 13 feature films during
a 46-year career. But that relatively modest body of work was
arguably the most accomplished and influential of any American
filmmaker's beside Orson Welles.
</P>
<P>
   Always a technical innovator and more often than not a
breathtakingly original conceptualist, Kubrick pioneered _ and at
the same time perfected _ much of what late 20th-century American
cinema came to be about.
</P>
<P>
   On the formal front, the photo-realistic special effects of
``2001: A Space Odyssey'' (1968) set the standard for the universe
of science-fiction films that followed (though nothing in the genre
has come near approximating the film's visual poetry and
intelligence). Kubrick integrated music for dramatic emphasis and
irony into his movies in a whole new way while MTV directors were
still in diapers. And even if the historical satire ``Barry
Lyndon'' (1975) was designed on an epic pictorial scale, its
groundbreaking use of natural, low light sources paved the way for
much of the intimately focused independent filmmaking that
followed.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick was no less canny when it came to subject matter. He
found expression for such driving themes as contempt for authority
and the fragile, illusory nature of civilization in a kaleidoscopic
variety of styles and genres. Each new film was completely fresh
and different from the others, yet most of them spoke with a
remarkably sharp, often prescient voice to the issues of Kubrick's
radically changing times.
</P>
<P>
   After some noirish explorations that culminated in the
masterful, multiviewpoint heist caper ``The Killing'' (1956),
Kubrick's fourth feature, ``Paths of Glory'' (1957), was an
outraged indictment of military mismanagement years before the
Vietnam War heated up. In 1964, at the height of America's plunge
into that quagmire, Kubrick dropped ``Dr. Strangelove,'' the
blackest, funniest and smartest of Cold War comedies.
</P>
<P>
   In between, with the unavoidably self-censored but still
ruthlessly witty ``Lolita'' (1962), Kubrick challenged society's
self-congratulatory plunge into the sexual revolution, pointing out
way ahead of his time that personal freedom had its limits, both
morally and emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   With ``2001,'' Kubrick broke all the rules of Hollywood
narrative, literally shifting a story through time and space with
no effort to explain the connections. Yet the implications he
coolly, elliptically touched on were as profound as any film ever
has achieved.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other Kubrick film, ``2001'' explored the link
between mankind's destructive and creative impulses. It looked at
how our minds (represented at the extreme by the mad computer Hal)
and our souls (the star child) controlled our destinies _ and by
doing so became one of the few truly spiritual films ever made.
</P>
<P>
   And it was, as the hippies instantly realized, a trip. Not only
did ``2001'' approximate the psychedelic experience better than any
film before or since, it established the concept of movie-as-ride,
a primarily sensory entertainment. That approach has come to
dominate big-budget filmmaking in the decades since; but in all
that time and footage, the abstract elegance of Kubrick's original
design never has been equaled.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Clockwork Orange'' (1971) foresaw the violent disintegration
of urban youth culture _ and the reactionary social policies that
went right along with it. It also predicted the saturation of
media, and the sometimes frightening efforts to manipulate it, that
has come to define the Information Age.
</P>
<P>
   Many feel ``Clockwork'' was Kubrick's last great film. But the
three we've seen since _ ``Lyndon,'' ``The Shining'' (1980) and
``Full Metal Jacket'' (1987) _ all possess high degrees of design
genius and thematic consistency. All three are wisely
disillusioned, steeped in the chilling realization that madness is
a stronger force than idealism or rationality _ especially when,
whether in the guise of 18th-century aristocrats, Jack Nicholson's
father figure or a pathological drill sergeant, the insanity rests
in figures we invest with power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' if stars Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman and
the few Warner Bros. executives who've seen it are to be believed,
could be Kubrick's crowning statement on the subject. From what
little we know, it's about psychiatrists succumbing to their own
obsessions _ a story Kubrick hadn't previously made a movie about,
but a subject he certainly understood intimately.
</P>
<P>
   As controlling a perfectionist as he was a dyed-in-the-wool
maverick (the New York-bred director moved to England in the 1960s
in order to remain as far away as possible from studio
interference), Kubrick oversaw every aspect of his productions from
inception to marketing campaign. He kept his sets closed and his
artistic strategies to himself and the few collaborators he needed
to help realize them. He was known for driving actors mad with
upward of 100 takes, sometimes of the simplest shots. Indeed, the
shooting schedule for ``Eyes Wide Shut'' is believed to have been
the longest in movie history.
</P>
<P>
   Some have noted rather ghoulishly that Kubrick died within days
of completing the first (and now, last) ``Eyes'' cut he felt was
worth showing to anybody _ as if the effort required all the life
left in the aging artist. That's a little too cozy a connection,
especially in regard to a tough-minded individualist like Kubrick.
</P>
<P>
   There is some hard irony, though, in the thought that Kubrick
died a year shy of the millennium, never to see the 2001 he so
unforgettably imagined decades earlier. That vision will inspire
filmmakers and audiences well into the next century, perhaps
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   If anybody was a filmmaker for the ages, it was Stanley
Kubrick.!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
