</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAIR TRADE WITH CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   China's recently disclosed use of espionage to develop
miniaturized nuclear warheads suggests many flaws in US
counterintelligence that need to be corrected. There has been a
certain amount of confusion, however, about the proper lessons to
draw from this lapse of security.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report Saturday in The New York Times, beginning
in the mid-1980s a Chinese-American scientist at Los Alamos
pilfered design secrets for an advanced US missile, the W-88.
</P>
<P>
   The espionage at Los Alamos was first detected in 1995 after
intelligence analysts deduced from Chinese missile test results
that Beijing had been able to emulate the US W-88 missile. The
suspect was identified the following year, but the White House was
not informed of the extent of the problem until 1997. Six months
later President Clinton ordered that security be tightened at Los
Alamos and other nuclears weapons labs.
</P>
<P>
   There is no excuse for Los Alamos's lax security, which dates
back to the Reagan and Bush administrations. There can also be no
justification for the dilatory behavior of the Clinton
administration Energy Department, which was first alerted to the
Chinese penetration of Los Alamos in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Congress will be performing its oversight functions if it
investigates allegations that policy makers in the Clinton
administration were slow to take action because they did not want
to do anything that might compromise trade relations and the goal
of a ``strategic partnership'' with China.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, says China
should be denied entry into the World Trade Organization because of
its espionage, he is practicing the politics of the non sequitur.
Winning lower Chinese tariffs for US exports does not become
inimical to US interests because Beijing stole the design of the
W-88 missile. By the same token, there is no reason Clinton can't
get tough with Beijing on the issue of espionage while pursuing
trade relations with China and cultivating a strategic partnership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1851EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0348 </DOCNO>
