<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2334 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-DIMAGGIO-BO     03-08 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-DIMAGGIO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOE DIMAGGIO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After he retired, Joe DiMaggio became a cultural icon who was
made to stand for the imagined virtues of a vanished American era.
Yogi Berra stated in plain terms the predicament of being a myth
and a man at the same time. ``I don't think many of us would want
to have tried to be Joe DiMaggio all our life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before he became a mythic figure _ the dignified, grieving
husband of Marilyn Monroe _ Joe D. had been a ballplayer. His true
domain was the original Yankee Stadium. Fans who saw him pursue a
long drive to center field had the impression that DiMaggio knew
where the ball was going before it left the bat. When he got there,
running in those long, effortless strides that defined his
gracefulness, he would make the catch look easy.
</P>
<P>
   In his prime the Yankee Clipper could throw from center field as
well as anyone who ever played that position. He ran the bases not
like one of today's prima donnas but like the son of an immigrant
Sicilian fisherman who knew that a pennant race was a Darwinian
struggle for survival.
</P>
<P>
   Today's baseball mercenaries talk about the numbers they put up,
as if statistics can be translated into monetary evaluations as
crude as the price of pork bellies on the commodity exchange.
DiMaggio, who died Monday at age 84, had stats worthy of the
diamond's pantheon, but stats alone do not tell the story of his
achievements.
</P>
<P>
   He led the American League in 1939 with a batting average of
.381. In '37 he led the league in RBIs with 137, in runs scored
with 151, and in total bases with 418. His lifetime slugging
percentage _ in the capacious Yankee Stadium _ was sixth of all
time, behind Babe Ruth, Ted Williams, Lou Gehrig, Jimmy Foxx, and
Hank Greenberg. And of course he left behind his record 56-game
hitting streak of 1941. Williams spoke the truth when he said,
``DiMaggio was the best player I ever saw.''
</P>
<P>
   But Joe DiMaggio was not about stats or individual excellence.
He was about winning. He carried his teammates to 10 pennants in 13
seasons and to victory in nine of 10 World Series. On the field,
the myth and the man were one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1852EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2335 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-BANANAS-BOS     03-08 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BANANAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAIR TRADE WITH EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One thing about international trade conflict: There is no
shortage of childish behavior to relieve the monotony of an issue
full of grinding detail.
</P>
<P>
   A long conflict between the European Union and the United States
over bananas _ which neither party grows in any consequential
numbers _ has spilled over and threatens to escalate into something
serious.
</P>
<P>
   Europe wants to give a special break to some of its former
colonies by restricting banana imports from other Central American
nations dominated by US corporations. The United States appealed to
the World Trade Organization, which said the Europeans broke
international rules. The Europeans made some changes, sent them to
the WTO for approval, and are waiting for a ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The United States got impatient and on Mar. 4 said it would
impose punitive tariffs on a wide range of European goods unrelated
to bananas. The list is short on the necessities of life: Bath
preparations, plastic handbags, cashmere sweaters, electric coffee
and tea makers, uncoated felt paper, Pecorino cheese (soft),
plastic pocket accessories, candles.
</P>
<P>
   Not much of anyone would care _ except for the folks who make or
want them. The cashmere sweaters, for example, come from the
English-Scottish border country, which depends heavily on sales to
up-scale American retailers. This is the time of year when they
gear up for the Christmas trade. Even the threat of the 100 percent
tariffs the United States is talking about is enough to kill US
interest. No wonder the British Foreign Office summoned the US
ambassador twice to deliver sharp complaints about the threatened
tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it will all blow over. Trade fights have a way of seeming
unsolvable until the last moment, and the United States has said it
won't impose the tariffs until the WTO has ruled on the modified
banana rules. But the maneuver alone feeds European protectionists
who accuse the United States of bullying. And it has prompted
protests from others that it's getting in the way of real issues.
</P>
<P>
   One might think the time has come to get some adults dealing
with these problems. Enough whining, everyone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
