<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-LUNCHEON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOMINEES RELAX, REFLECT AT LUNCHEON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARLA MATZER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
LOS ANGELES _ ``Affliction'' co-stars Nick Nolte and James Coburn
looked dapper, while ``Saving Private Ryan'' director Steven
Spielberg and Billy Bob Thornton of ``A Simple Plan'' dressed down.
Brenda Blethyn and Lynn Redgrave were radiant, a far cry from their
unattractive characters in ``Little Voice'' and ``Gods and
Monsters,'' respectively.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That's the nice thing for nominees at the Academy Awards
luncheon: It's come as you want. It's not nearly the high-pressure
event that the actual Oscars show, upcoming on March 21, is.
</P>
<P>
   The 18th annual nominees luncheon was held at the Beverly Hilton
on Monday. Nearly 100 nominees from 22 categories dined on roasted
sea bass and beef tenderloin and were presented with certificates
of nomination. Still, those in attendance admitted the pace has
already picked up. ``Shakespeare in Love'' actor Geoffrey Rush,
asked whether this time around is any less dizzying than when he
was nominated for ``Shine'' two years ago, replied simply: ``No.''
Rush said, ``It's a little more familiar this time than the first
time I went on this ride. This time, at least I know where the
scary twists are coming, where they hang you upside down.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush is among three Australians nominated for acting Oscars this
year. Also in attendance were Aussies Cate Blanchett, up for her
role as the queen of England in ``Elizabeth,'' and Rachel
Griffiths, nominated for best supporting actress in ``Hillary and
Jackie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have more nominations per capita than any other
country,'' joked Blanchett, now a stunning blonde after her redhead
role in ``Elizabeth.'' Brazilian Fernanda Montenegro, nominated as
best actress for ``Central Station,'' said she was proud that four
nominated foreign films are from a ``Latin heritage'' (from Brazil,
Italy, Argentina and Spain). Still, she said, she hopes her
countrymen are not getting their hopes too high. ``To win the
Oscar, it has become like winning the World Cup ... to be like
seeing God,'' said Montenegro. ``I'd like to tell my country, it's
almost impossible to win. I'm very stressed, but the moment is also
very beautiful,'' allowed Montenegro, in halting English.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the actors up for Oscars were in attendance. Kathy
Bates, nominated for her role in ``Primary Colors,'' admitted to
being dazzled by the company. ``I'm just trying to keep a cool
head. It's amazing to be in the company of these women,'' said
Bates, whose fellow supporting-actress nominees are Redgrave,
Blethyn, Griffiths and ``Shakespeare's'' Judi Dench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gods and Monsters'' star Ian McKellen, nominated for his
portrayal of gay film director James Whale, was asked whether he
thought ``doors were opening'' for homosexuals in Hollywood.
``Sometimes I'm optimistic, and sometimes I'm not,'' said McKellen,
who was recently knighted by the Queen Elizabeth II. ``We did it
right, we had a gay director, a gay writer and a gay lead actor ...
you have to keep pushing at your own closet door _ and into the
world beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   Actress Emily Watson was also somewhat philosophical when asked
about the controversy surrounding her film, ``Hillary and Jackie,''
especially in England. Some musicians who knew the late Jacqueline
Du Pre, who Watson portrays, have protested that the film is
inaccurate and disrespectful to the brilliant cellist. ``It
surprises me that people think it's not sympathetic to her ... when
you have someone so talented, who starts to lose that talent, would
you expect her not to rage against that?'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   Nolte admitted to having ``a little trouble with awards ... I
just don't think there is a best actor or a best film,'' Nolte
said. ``They're all unique, all different.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Spielberg said it never gets any easier to be up
for an Oscar. ``I had the best time at the Golden Globes last year,
when I was up for `Amistad,' because I knew they were going to read
Jim Cameron's name for `Titanic,' and I could just relax,''
Spielberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you actually have a shot at something, it's
torture.'' The director declined to comment on the very competitive
and aggressive ad campaigns being waged by both ``Shakespeare'' and
``Private Ryan'' for Academy votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to get up in the morning and like myself ... I need to
take the high road,'' said Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   On a lighter note, triple-nominated composer Randy Newman joked
that if precedent holds, he doesn't expect to bring home any
Oscars. ``I think getting all three would be good. But I don't
think my track record would indicate my chances are very good,''
said Newman, who wrote music for ``Pleasantville,'' ``A Bug's
Life'' and ``Babe: Pig in the City.''
</P>
<P>
   But Newman said with a wink that he won't be too upset if he
ends up empty-handed on Oscar night. ``I've never gone home and
wept and got drunk ... because of THIS,'' he added, to a roar of
laughter from the press. &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
