<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-INTERNET-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINERIES WELCOME E-WINE IDEA 
</HEADLINE>
 (mk) 
 By JIM HAMMETT  
 WineToday.com 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Winery organizations embrace the basic idea
of a national Internet wine-locator service but argue that it is
not the solution to problems of conflicting state regulations
related to direct shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Naxon Corp. announced last week that it was creating an Internet
site for wine, and that it had picked up support from the Wine and
Spirits Wholesalers Association and was being backed by an
investment group, Kleiner Perkins, Caufield &AMP; Byers, that helped
fund America Online, Netscape and Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``We applaud any effort that would open up the market for
consumers,'' said Patrick Campbell, president of the Coalition for
Free Trade. ``We wish them the best of luck, but it doesn't solve
the core issue of direct shipping.''
</P>
<P>
   Naxon CEO Peter Sisson declined to comment on speculation that
Naxon was working with Amazon.com, the Internet bookseller that
quickly became the darling of Wall Street when it filed its initial
public offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of a publicly traded company, I can't comment,''
he said, referring to Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   There are obstacles that could hamper efforts to provide wine
nationwide, winery organizations said. Some of them are logistical,
involving the varying requirements in each state for selling
alcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, 22 states have laws that automatically enter a
winery into a binding business agreement with a distributor upon
the first transaction between the companies. Regardless of the
distributors' performance, one consumer order could lock a winery
into a business arrangement without the recourse of normal business
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   In some states, the state itself is the wholesaler and retailer
of alcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have already been in touch with several control states and
we have found them quite receptive to making special arrangements
to support our system,'' Sisson said. ``In general, control state
regulators are very interested in acting in the best interest of
their consumers''
</P>
<P>
   Such regulations were stumbling blocks for some predecessors in
trying to establish a wine e-commerce site, like Cellar Masters of
America. Naxon bought Cellar Master's subsidiary Virtual
Distribution, Inc., to obtain its 37 state licenses to operate in
those states, Sisson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also kept four of their employees because of their
tremendous experience with regulatory issues. Other than that, we
have nothing in common with them,'' Sisson said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Winetoday.com is a daily Internet wine publication of The New York
Times Co. and The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif. The Web
address is http://www.winetoday.com. This story was distributed by
The N.Y. Times News Service.)  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
