<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2341 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATIONSBANK-COX     03-08 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONSBANK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New president named to Georgia territory
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Michael H. Dulan today was named president of
NationsBank in Georgia, making the company veteran the bank's
pointman in this state.
</P>
<P>
   Dulan, 47, had been working here as consumer banking executive
for Georgia and Tennessee since arriving in late 1996 from the
NationsBank office in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   He will continue in that role, in addition to his new duties,
said James R. Lientz Jr., NationsBank Midsouth president, who
announced the appointment. Dulan will report to Lientz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident the bank will grow in its leadership in the
state of Georgia under the guidance of Mike Dulan,'' Lientz said.
``With more than 25 years of experience with the bank, he knows the
industry and knows the business of banking.''
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank is the largest player in Georgia banking, with more
than 600 ATMs and 293 offices, including 81 in Kroger stores.
</P>
<P>
   Dulan will focus on Georgia, much as Lientz has done in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   In putting the Georgia operations in Dulan's hands, Lientz taps
a consumer banking veteran who started his career in 1974 at First
National Bank of Dallas, which was later taken over by NationsBank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our task over the next few months and years is to keep the
emphasis on good service and provide an even wider array of
products,'' Dulan said. ``We will have to continue, and place even
more emphasis on, training and coaching of the staff to be more
service minded.''
</P>
<P>
   And immediately, the task is to prepare for the August rollout
of the ``new'' Bank of America, the merged bank that includes the
far-flung NationsBank and Bank of America organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Lientz said Dulan came to his attention nearly three years ago,
when he observed the good job the native Oklahoman was doing with
community banking in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got thoughts of changes here in Atlanta, Dulan
immediately came to mind,'' Lientz said. He brought Dulan to
Atlanta in November of 1996 to be consumer bank executive.
</P>
<P>
   Dulan comes from an Oklahoma City family of achievers, including
two strong parents as role models, he said.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Hurlon J. Dulan, was the chief personnel officer for
the Oklahoma City post office and previously was an Army field
captain during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of learning principles of leadership, I learned at
the feet of a master,'' Dulan said. ``And my mom, who played
softball, taught us how to be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Play to win,'' she said, ``and we did.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most important personal inspiration to young Dulan was
an older brother, Hurlon Jr., who graduated from Princeton and
Harvard Business School and became a manager in training for
Citibank in the early 1970's. He is now in private business in
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I firmly subscribe to the view that effective role models are
not ball players and celebrities, but family members and people in
the community who teach values,'' Dulan said.
</P>
<P>
   Young Mike Dulan, who played two years of football at Oklahoma
as a cornerback, decided on banking and finance early on.
</P>
<P>
   ``After it became clear that I wasn't going to crack the
National Football League, I decided to major in finance, and that
started my move into banking.''
</P>
<P>
   No sooner than Dulan arrived in Atlanta in 1996 did he become
involved in Atlanta community affairs, particularly becoming active
in the Atlanta Neighborhood Development Partnership, Leadership
Atlanta and 100 Black Men of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   He is particularly excited about his new membership on the board
of the Trust for Public Lands that has embarked on establishing the
narrow bands of parkland on both sides of the Chattahoochee River.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very concerned about preservation and for protecting the
environment,'' Dulan said.
</P>
<P>
   And so how has Dulan and his family adapted to the change from
Dallas to Atlanta, two cities often seen as competitors for
business prominence?
</P>
<P>
   ``We love it hear,'' said Dulan, ``and my wife told me recently
there is no way she intends to go back to Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   Lientz also made it clear he plans to remain deeply involved in
Georgia affairs , even as his responsibilities now include the huge
small business portfolio of NationsBank all across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue my roles with the Metro Atlanta Chamber of
Commerce, the Woodruff Arts Center and the Super Bowl committee,''
Lientiz said. ``I'm not going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
