<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2343 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-OBITUARY-DIMAGGIO     03-08 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-OBITUARY-DIMAGGIO-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... he was 14.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three years later, in his first game for the minor league San
Francisco Seals, he hit a double and a triple. The next season, he
set a Pacific Coast League record _ and gave a hint of things to
come _ by hitting safely in 61 consecutive games. There was talk of
a major league team buying his contract for $75,000 until a freak
knee accident sustained whle hopping off a bus put Mr. DiMaggio's
career in jeopardy. Only two teams remained interested: the Yankees
and Red Sox. As usual, the Yankees got there first, gaining Mr.
DiMaggio's services from the Seals in return for $25,000 and five
players.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived at Yankee Stadium in 1936 _ and less than three
months into the season was on the cover of Time. A year later, he
was appearing in a movie (``Manhattan Merry-Go-Round''), and four
years after that, Les Brown's big band had a hit record with the
refrain, ``Joe, Joe, DiMaggio/We want you on our side.''
</P>
<P>
   The song came out in the summer of 1941, during the two months
and two days of ``the streak.'' Mr. DiMaggio hit .408 during that
period (Williams, it might be noted, hit .412 over the same span).
When his run finally ended, on July 17, it took two standout
defensive plays by Cleveland Indians third baseman Ken Keltner, and
another by shortstop Lou Boudreau, to keep Mr. DiMaggio hitless.
``Well, I'm glad it's over,'' he said afterward, and proceeded to
hit safely in the next 16 games. The oddest footnote to the streak
is that the Yankees tried to reduce his salary for the following
season by $5,000 (he ended up with a $5,000 raise).
</P>
<P>
   Mr. DiMaggio enlisted in the Army Air Force early in 1943, doing
all his service Stateside or in Hawaii. He returned to the Yankees
in 1946, his talents undiminished, but the three seasons he lost
contributed to the relative disparity between the adulation Mr.
DiMaggio inspired and his impressive but not overwhelming career
statistics. Another factor was his having had to take half his
at-bats in a ballpark whose oceanic left field was unforgiving to
righthanded hitters.
</P>
<P>
   There were also his frequent visits to the trainer's room. For
all the fluid elegance of his play, injuries plagued Mr. DiMaggio
throughout his career. Besides the career-threatening knee injury
in San Francisco, he battled bone chips in his throwing arm, bone
spurs in his heels, chronically sore shoulders, a bad ankle, a
blinding eye inflammation, and even tonsillitis. Seven times he
missed a season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. DiMaggio's perfectionism was notorious. Asked once by Cannon
why he never let up on the field, he replied, ``Because there might
be somebody out there who's never seen me play before.'' Age and
injuries took an increasing toll, and after the 1951 season, he
retired from baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever chance Mr. DiMaggio had for obscurity once he left the
Yankees ended when he married Marilyn Monroe two years later, on
Jan. 14, 1954. Whatever chance the marriage had for success ended a
few minutes after that when she told reporters, ``I'm going to
continue my career, but I'm looking forward to being a housewife,
too.'' The idea of Monroe being a housewife was as unlikely as that
of Mr. DiMaggio taking a back seat to his wife's fame.
</P>
<P>
   There is a famous story of an exchange between them after she
went on a USO tour in Korea. Monroe said, ``It was so wonderful,
Joe. You never heard such cheering.'' His reply: ``Yes I have.''
</P>
<P>
   There had long been a contradiction in Mr. DiMaggio. The
reserved, dedicated athlete who stood alone in center field was so
personally reticent that he once turned down $2 million to write
his memoirs when he realized he'd need to describe his private
life. Yet the adored celebrity with the liquid eyes and chiseled
good looks (``Gentlemen,'' the gossip columnist Dorothy Kilgallen
informed her readers, ``he's divine'') was the toast of New York
nightlife.
</P>
<P>
   His first marriage had been to an actress, Dorothy Arnold. Their
union lasted 4 1/2 years and produced Mr. DiMaggio's only child,
Joe Jr. The marriage to Monroe lasted barely nine months. ``No man
could be a success in two national pastimes,'' the actor Oscar
Levant quipped when they divorced.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. DiMaggio never got over Monroe, whom he once described as
``a warm, big-hearted girl that everybody took advantage of.'' In
times of trouble, she would turn to him for support, and prior to
her death, in 1962, there was talk of their remarrying. For the
next 15 years, he had a half-dozen roses placed next to her
cemetery crypt three times a week, finally stopping the ritual only
because souvenir seekers kept making off with the flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the marriage revealed an emotional vulnerability
that had long been evident to Mr. DiMaggio's intimates. The
pressure he performed under, a pressure imposed as much by himself
as his public, had always been great. Its effects could be seen in
the cigarettes he chain-smoked, the ulcers he developed, and the
endless cups of coffee he drank (appropriately enough, he later
served as spokesman for Mr. Coffee products). As his Yankee
teammate Yogi Berra put it, ``I don't think many of us would want
to have tried to be Joe DiMaggio all our life.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, DiMaggio received the nation's highest civilian honor,
the Medal of Freedom. An even more singular tribute had come his
way a decade earlier when Paul Simon wrote ``Mrs. Robinson'' and
young Americans found themselves singing the words, ``Where have
you gone, Joe DiMaggio?/A nation turns its lonely eyes to you.''
(Simon had originally wanted to use the name of his childhood idol,
Mantle, but the syllables didn't scan.) Asked by an interviewer in
1974 about the recording, Mr. DiMaggio was enthusiastic, if
bemused. ``You mean that `Mister Robinson' song? I was really
flattered. I was surprised that those young fellows would think of
an old guy like me . . . I don't have a copy. I think my sister
might. But it really made me feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   The discipline that had marked Mr. DiMaggio's playing days
carried over into retirement. When he was well into his 60s, his
trim physique and erect carriage suggested he could still step onto
the diamond and hold his own. Henry Kissinger once shared the
owner's box with Mr. DiMaggio at Yankee Stadium during a playoff
game. The home team was losing, and the former Secretary of State
saw an obvious solution to the Yankees' plight. ``Joe, put on a
uniform _ they can use you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. DiMaggio's friend Toots Shor, the New York restaurateur,
once made a prediction: When Mr. DiMaggio died, his open casket
would lie in St. Patrick's Cathedral and thousands of mourners
would file past saying, ``Joe, you look great.'' Even the premature
silvering of his hair merely served to heighten Mr. DiMaggio's air
of distinction.
</P>
<P>
   It was in a dual capacity, as senior statesman of the game and
former teammate of Gehrig's, that he participated in the ceremonies
honoring Cal Ripken on the night in 1995 when the Baltimore Orioles
shortstop broke what had long been considered a record as
unreachable as Mr. DiMaggio's 56-game hitting streak, the Yankee
first baseman's string of 2,130 consecutive games played. Also
present was President Clinton. It takes nothing away from the
president to suggest that, had a visitor from outer space been
asked which of the two men appeared to be chief executive of
Earth's greatest nation, the interplanetary traveler would surely
have indicated the immigrant fisherman's son from San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio's body will be flown to Northern California for burial
in his hometown of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his brother, Dominic, and son, Joe Jr., survivors
include two grandchildren, Paula and Cathy, and four
great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
