<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2345 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBITUARY-DIMAGGIO-2TA     03-08 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-DIMAGGIO-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOE DIMAGGIO, 84; BASEBALL LEGEND WHO EPITOMIZED ATHLETIC GRACE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe DiMaggio, the New York Yankees' Hall of Fame center fielder
who uniquely personified athletic grace and patrician bearing, died
early Monday at his home in Hollywood, Fla. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio had undergone surgery for lung cancer in October and
during a 99-day hospital stay battled many complications.
</P>
<P>
   Among American athletes, perhaps only Michael Jordan has enjoyed
a mystique comparable to Mr. DiMaggio's. Ted Williams, the Red Sox
Hall of Fame outfielder who was his archrival and sole peer, once
said, ``I've never seen anyone who played the game with more
perfection. He was the best player I ever saw. He seemed to do
everything right.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. DiMaggio's hold on the American imagination was not limited
to the sports page. The hero of Ernest Hemingway's ``The Old Man
and the Sea'' hopes to be ``worthy of the great DiMaggio who does
all things perfectly.'' Simon and Garfunkel fastened upon him as a
symbol of lost American innocence in their 1968 song ``Mrs.
Robinson.'' And Marilyn Monroe made him her second husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``This son of Italian immigrants gave every American something
to believe in,'' said President Clinton. ``He became the very
symbol of American grace, power and skill. I have no doubt that
when future generations look back at the best of America in the
20th century, they will think of the Yankee Clipper and all that he
achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, the owner of the Yankees, said in a
statement, ``Like many fans across America, and indeed around the
world, the Yankees are deeply saddened by the passing of Joe
DiMaggio, one of our own and one of the greatest of all time. It
was the class and dignity with which he led his life that made him
part of all of us. I will forever treasure the close friendship we
shared over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bud Selig, the commissioner of baseball, called DiMaggio ``the
personification of grace, class and dignity on the baseball
diamond.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As an immigrant's son, he represented the hopes and ideals of
our great country,'' Selig said.
</P>
<P>
   The flag at the Baseball Hall of Fame flag in Cooperstown, N.Y.,
was lowered to half-staff Monday and a wreath was placed around
DiMaggio's plaque.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. DiMaggio's most storied feat was hitting safely in 56
consecutive games in 1941. Considered by many the baseball record
least likely to be surpassed, the hitting streak exemplified the
unflappable consistency of his play. (The closest anyone has come
since is Pete Rose's 44-game streak in 1978.) Mr. DiMaggio won the
American League's Most Valuable Player Award in 1939, 1941, and
1947. Twice he led the league in home runs, 1937 (46) and 1948
(39). Twice he won the batting title, 1939 (.381) and 1940 (.352).
Twice he led in runs batted in, 1941 (125) and 1948 (155).
</P>
<P>
   Yet statistics barely suggest what a nonpareil figure he cut.
Mr. DiMaggio was named to the American League All-Star team in each
of his 13 major league seasons and was elected to the Baseball Hall
of Fame in 1955. Fourteen years later, the Baseball Writers
Association of America voted him ``greatest living all-time
baseball player.''
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, there was an aura about the man variously known
as ``the Yankee Clipper,'' ``Joltin' Joe,'' and ``the Big Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When he walked into that clubhouse,'' said his teammate Billy
Martin, ``it was like a president or senator walking in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrolling center field in Yankee Stadium from 1936 to 1951
(with three years away for military service during World War II),
he gained a reputation for near-flawless performance that didn't so
much recall any other ballplayer's as it did that of another master
of poetic motion, Fred Astaire.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you saw him play,'' wrote the sportswriter Jimmy Cannon,
``you'll never forget him. No one ran with such unhurried grace.
His gifts as an athlete were marvelous because they were subdued.
Here was an outfielder who followed a fly ball with a deft serenity
. . . concerned only with the defeat of awkwardness.''
</P>
<P>
   Great as were Mr. DiMaggio's accomplishments on the diamond, his
persona far exceeded them. Among baseball players, only Babe Ruth,
whose larger-than-life personality rescued the sport after the 1919
``Black Sox'' scandal, and Jackie Robinson, who presaged the coming
of the civil rights era with his breaking of the major leagues'
color barrier in 1947, surpass him as a presence in the American
psyche.
</P>
<P>
   The boisterously Dionysian Ruth was a throwback to an earlier,
more raucous America. Robinson, with his intensity and
extra-athletic significance, looked ahead to a more complex,
self-aware society. Mr. DiMaggio embodied America at mid-century _
or at least America as it liked to see itself _ his Apollonian
reserve off the field and the seeming effortlessness of his play
epitomizing an invincible nation at the height of its power,
gracious in victory and all but impossible to imagine in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. DiMaggio further differed from Ruth and Robinson in having a
name that ended in a vowel. This, too, helped make him such an
evocative figure for mid-century America: the first truly national
hero to come from other than northern European stock. (His parents,
who emigrated from Sicily in 1898, did not become US citizens until
the 1940s.) For millions of immigrants and their children, Mr.
DiMaggio's mastery of the national pastime symbolized their own
arrival as full-fledged Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Here was an ethnic version of Gary Cooper or James Stewart:
soft-spoken, matter-of-fact, supremely capable. In his loner
status, Mr. DiMaggio also resembled the classic American heroes
those actors portrayed. Few individuals have so excelled at a team
sport, but there was always a remoteness about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was and has remained an interior man, ever distant,'' the
writer Gay Talese once observed, ``a kind of male Garbo.''
</P>
<P>
   A Yankee teammate, pitcher Eddie Lopat, once said, ``Joe was the
loneliest man I ever knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Red Sox' Williams, he gave an impression of intrinsic
apartness. ``The essential American soul is hard, isolate, stoic,''
the English novelist D.H. Lawrence famously argued. Mr. DiMaggio's
special status in the national psyche derives at least in part from
his so clearly demonstrating the force of Lawrence's remark.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this feeling of otherness he communicated, no small part
of Mr. DiMaggio's renown sprang from affiliation. Besides the bond
of ethnicity that made him a revered figure among
Italian-Americans, there was the renown of the team he played for.
Mr. DiMaggio, who appeared in 10 World Series, found his fame
enlarged through association with what was already the United
States' most fabled professional sports franchise.
</P>
<P>
   He wore No. 5, an explicit acknowledgement of his being the
legatee of Ruth (No. 3) and Lou Gehrig (No. 4), Ruth's successor as
team leader. Mr. DiMaggio proved eminently worthy of the
responsibility. Where Ruth and Gehrig had brought the Yankees
unparalleled success, he made that success a tradition, one
continued by his Yankee heir, Mickey Mantle.
</P>
<P>
   Another affiliation, this one fraternal, contributed to the
legend: He was one of three DiMaggio brothers who made it to the
major leagues. Vince played 10 seasons with a total of five teams,
and Dominic played 11 with the Red Sox. It was as if there were so
much DiMaggio magic, it couldn't be contained in just one player.
</P>
<P>
   There were nine DiMaggio siblings in all, four sisters and two
other brothers. Joseph Paul DiMaggio, the next to youngest, was
born in Martinez, Calif., on Nov. 25, 1914, the son of Giuseppe
Paola DiMaggio and Rosalie (Mercurio) DiMaggio. A year after his
birth, the family moved to the North Beach section of San
Francisco. The two oldest DiMaggio boys took up their father's
trade of fisherman. Not young Joe. ``I'd get seasick when the water
was rough,'' he later explained. ``And I couldn't stand the
smell.'' Instead, he led his Boys Club baseball team to a
championship when he was 14.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
