<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-TERROR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE PUTS 6 LIBYANS ON TRIAL IN ABSENTIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A French antiterrorism court in Paris put six
high-ranking Libyan officials on trial in absentia Monday on
charges of ordering the bombing of a French DC-10 airliner that
killed 171 people in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from tight international economic sanctions
imposed because of Libyan support for terrorism, Col. Moammar
Gadhafi, the Libyan leader, allowed a French investigator into the
country in 1996 to take evidence against the six suspects. They
include Gadhafi's brother-in-law Abdallah Senoussi.
</P>
<P>
   Gadhafi, who has called the destruction of the plane an
accident, offered no objection to the trial in absentia, which is
expected to conclude this week with guilty verdicts against all
six. They are, as far as anybody here knows, at liberty in Libya.
Under French law, since they are absent, they cannot have lawyers
contest the charges against them at their trial.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Jean-Louis Bruguiere, the investigator who built the case
against them, said international arrest warrants for the defendants
would insure that they never set foot out of Libya again if they
were convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence against them includes a Samsonite suitcase _ armed
with explosive and provided to Bruguiere by Libyan authorities two
and a half years ago _ that Bruguiere said was identical to the one
that blew up the airliner.
</P>
<P>
   Other evidence, the judge said, showed that Libyan operatives
had bought explosives and detonators and plotted to blow up a
French airliner in retaliation for French intervention on behalf of
Chad in a war Libya had been fighting there in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Senoussi, then chief of foreign operations for the Libyan secret
service, is accused of ordering one of the other defendants to
provide a rigged Samsonite suitcase to a Brazzaville, Congo,
passenger who checked it onto the plane, UTA Flight 772 to Paris.
The airline no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb went off while the plane was over Niger, killing all
aboard. The wreckage came down in the desert, and investigators
were later able to piece it together in a hangar at Le Bourget
Airport outside Paris and determine the cause of the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   If found guilty of conspiracy to commit murder and setting off
destructive explosions as part of a terrorist plot, all six could
get life jail terms. These would most likely be only symbolic,
though French officials have said they expect that Gadhafi might
agree to pay reparations to the 232 relatives of the victims with
legal standing in the case.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar case, that of Pan American Flight 103, which blew
up over Lockerbie, Scotland, on its way to New York from London in
December 1988, the United States and Britain have not been willing
to settle for trial in absentia of the two defendants. That
explosion killed 270 people in the plane and on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects, Abdelbaset Ali Mohmed Al Megrahi and Al Amin
Khalifa Fhimah, worked for Libyan intelligence. Three years after
the explosion, Scottish authorities charged them with conspiracy
and murder, asserting that they had rigged an explosive device in a
suitcase and checked it onto the aircraft via a connecting flight
from the Mediterranean island of Malta.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year the United States and Britain had insisted that
the sanctions against Libya, which include a ban on international
flights to and from there, would remain in place until the
defendants were extradited for trial in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   But now the two countries agree that the men can be tried before
a special Scottish court in a third country, the Netherlands, which
is ready to make available a secure compound in Zeist, outside of
Utrecht. The U.N. secretary- general, Kofi Annan, along with
President Nelson Mandela of South Africa and Saudi and Egyptian
leaders, has been trying to get Gadhafi to agree to send the
defendants there for trial with the understanding that sanctions
would be lifted immediately if he did.
</P>
<P>
   Gadhafi, now traveling in Egypt, said over the weekend that
agreement might be reached soon, but he has said this many times
before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
