<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAAWOMEN-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lady Jackets stung by NIT news
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Georgia Tech women did not have as much at stake
Sunday as some teams, because they were not anticipating an NCAA
bid, but the news that they didn't make the women's NIT was
disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Jackets, who finished 13-14 after their quarterfinal
loss to North Carolina in the ACC tournament, were passed over
because of their losing record. The NIT field, which expanded from
16 to 32 teams this year, includes a number of high-profile
programs such as Washington, Colorado, Wisconsin and Baylor, last
year's runners-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us they weren't going to take any teams with losing
records,'' Tech coach Agnus Berenato said. ``We're disappointed,
but we know that every game counts. If we win one more game, then
maybe we're in. We're just going to try to come back next year and
do better.''
</P>
<P>
   Boys' bracket?
</P>
<P>
   Call Mulder and Scully. For several years now, there's been a
growing conspiracy theory that top male-coached teams are being
lumped together in the same bracket. The conspiracy theorists will
have a field day if all four top seeds in the Mideast advance to
the Sweet 16 in Cincinnati. UConn, coached by Geno Auriemma, is the
top seed, followed by Jim Davis' Clemson team and Georgia with Andy
Landers. The No. 4 seed is Iowa State, which is enjoying its
greatest success under Bill Fennelly.
</P>
<P>
   In the West are the other two Top 16 seeds coached by men: No. 1
Louisiana Tech, with Leon Barmore, and second-seeded Colorado
State, led by Tom Collen. The East and Midwest regionals are all
women in the top four seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma, whose status as the most recognizable and
controversial male coach in women's basketball is examined in the
current issue of Sports Illustrated for Women, was asked by the
Hartford Courant about the composition of the Mideast bracket:
``Let's just say there are some very experienced gentlemen in that
regional.''
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, underestimate us
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the attention Tennessee gets these days, UConn is
still the darling of the East Coast media. And it sure helps when a
national television commentator is only four years removed from
your program. ESPN studio analyst Rebecca Lobo, who led the Huskies
to the NCAA title in 1995, promptly tagged UConn the favorite in
what she termed a ``weak'' Mideast regional.
</P>
<P>
   That elicited a chuckle or two from Davis of Clemson, whose team
is seeded No. 2, the best in program history. ``I guess the rest of
us are just going to have a good time and then concede to Geno and
the girls,'' he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of slight doesn't seem to bother Davis. After North
Carolina coach Sylvia Hatchell complained that Davis' starting
guards, Itoro Umoh and Amy Geren, should not both have been
selected first-team All-ACC, Clemson whipped the Tar Heels in the
ACC tournament finals.
</P>
<P>
   SEC coaches 'stunned'
</P>
<P>
   The inclusion of eight SEC teams in the NCAA _ a women's record
for one conference _ certainly took league coaches by surprise. In
fact, they were so surprised they didn't have time to spout off the
``I told you sos'' that usually accompany their complaints that
they should have gotten more teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stunned it happened, but also very pleased,'' said coach
Sue Gunter of LSU, whose team is the No. 4 seed in the West. ``I
thought there were eight teams that deserved to go, but I didn't
think it would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida (19-13), which became the first women's at-large team to
get in despite a losing conference record, was considered out of
the tourney until the brackets came out with the Lady Gators as a
No. 11 seed in the Midwest Regional, where they play Arizona on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never thought we were a bubble team,'' said Florida coach
Carol Ross , whose team had the fourth-toughest schedule in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
