<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2403 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ART-570&AMP;ADD-N     03-08 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ART-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NICARAGUA, CLINTON COMMISERATES WITH HURRICANE VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANAGUA, Nicaragua _ Beneath a volcano still scarred by the
hurricane-induced mudslide that occurred last October, President
Clinton vowed Monday to help Nicaraguans reclaim their lives and
ravaged land.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hurricane, a mudslide, they can destroy lives, they can
destroy homes, they can destroy a life's work,'' the president said
as blinding dust swept through a schoolyard in the town of
Posoltega where he spoke. ``But they must not be allowed to destroy
hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced that the United States would provide an
additional $120 million to build temporary shelters, repair roads,
provide medical care and remove land mines uprooted by the
torrential rains and mudslides of the hurricane. But Clinton's
request for nearly $1 billion in additional disaster relief for
Central America is stalled in Congress in a partisan dispute over
the source of the funds.
</P>
<P>
   Casitas volcano, near Posoltega, 70 miles northwest of Managua,
was the scene of the deadliest disaster wrought by the hurricane
last October: a 30-foot torrent of mud that buried two villages, El
Porvenir and Rolando Rodriguez. Some 2,000 people were killed in
the mudslide, many of them buried alive. Thousands were left
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of a four-day, four-nation tour of Central
America, Clinton saw the remnants of the disaster in Nicaragua,
including the single house that remains of the two villages and the
shallow graves of hundreds of victims of the storm. Thousands of
residents are still in temporary shelters of plastic sheeting and
corrugated metal atop the packed brown dirt left by the volcanic
mudslide.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton placed a spray of flowers at the grave of one victim, a
6-year-old girl crushed by the slide. She was one of many victims
who for public-health reasons were not buried but cremated where
they lay, their remains then strewn with dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Clinton said he had not appreciated the extent of the
catastrophe until he saw the scene himself.
</P>
<P>
   In his public remarks, made on the grounds of the Jose Dolores
Toruno Lopez High School, Clinton alluded to Nicaragua's revolution
and counterrevolution of the 1980s and its two democratic elections
since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this decade,'' the president said, ``with courage and with
strength you have created a new Nicaragua. You have earned the
world's admiration and now you deserve the world's support in this
moment of need.'' The aid that Clinton announced Monday is to come
from Agency for International Development funds already included in
the current year's budget. An aid proposal worth $956 million is
stalled in Congress in a dispute over how to pay it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had hoped to deliver the nearly $1 billion in aid during
his trip this week. But House and Senate Republicans voted last
week to attach conditions to the relief bill that the White House
finds unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute will most likely take weeks or months to resolve,
forcing Clinton to dip into aid agency coffers to pay for a much
smaller effort. The country is to get help on housing, health care,
education, road and bridge repair and the removal of land mines
left from the civil wars of the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has already given about $300 million in
disaster aid to the region, through civilian relief agencies as
well as the Defense Department, which provided earth-moving
equipment and temporary bridges for the hundreds of spans washed
out by the rains.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The administration also temporarily suspended deportations of
Central Americans who illegally entered the United States to escape
the effects of the hurricane. But preparations are under way to
force the return of many of those refugees, a development that has
created friction with the region's governments, which say they
cannot provide housing or sustenance for them.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton promised Monday to seek a ``fair solution'' to the
refugee issue but gave no details.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its disaster relief program, the administration also
deferred for two years all bilateral debt payments owed to the
United States by Nicaragua and Honduras. That concession would
relieve the two countries' obligation to pay $54 million in
interest payments. The administration is also asking other nations
holding debt from Central America to forgive or defer payments.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Peace Corps is expanding its presence in the
region to help rebuild, according to Mark Gearan, the Peace Corps
director, who accompanied Clinton on the trip. The 500 Peace Corps
volunteers already working in the countries hardest hit by the
storm will be reinforced by as many as 100 workers for short-term
emergency aid.
</P>
<P>
   They belong to the Crisis Corps, a new Peace Corps program that
enlists former volunteers to return for six-month stints to the
countries where they served, sometimes decades earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``They go back to their country or region of service,'' Gearan
said aboard Air Force One Monday morning, ``because they know the
language, the people, the culture, and they're literally ready at
Day One to make a difference in disaster relief.''
</P>
<P>
   In a small gesture, White House staff members collected pencils,
pens and pads of paper to distribute to Posoltega schoolchildren
whose classrooms were destroyed. Aides unloaded six boxes of the
supplies from Air Force One in Managua and transferred them to the
helicopters that took the president's party to Posoltega.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was greeted at Sandino Airport in Managua and introduced
in Posoltega by Arnoldo Aleman, president of Nicaragua. Clinton is
the first American president to visit the country since Lyndon
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Aleman, a former coffee grower who leads the center-right
Liberal Alliance, said American and other international assistance
had allowed Nicaragua to begin clearing roads, planting fields,
building housing and reopening schools. ``Most importantly,'' he
said, ``hope and faith in our national destiny have returned.'' He
added, ``Welcome, President Clinton, to Nicaragua, a beautiful and
brave land that does not surrender to its sorrows.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
