<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-KILLERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT REFUSES TO BLOCK `BORN KILLERS' CIVIL SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Supreme Court Monday refused to stop a lawsuit charging that
the 1994 film ``Natural Born Killers'' incited a Louisiana couple
to shoot and seriously injure a woman.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, brought by the shooting victim's family, accuses
director Oliver Stone, Time Warner Entertainment Co., and others of
intentionally inspiring a real-life crime spree that mimicked the
plot of the film, in which a couple played by Woody Harrelson and
Juliette Lewis embarked on a series of murders and robberies.
</P>
<P>
   Without comment or dissent, the court cleared the way for the
case to proceed by letting stand a Louisiana appeals court ruling
that the film was not subject to free-speech protection because it
allegedly incited ``imminent lawless activity.''
</P>
<P>
   While Monday's action was not a ruling but simply a denial of
review, the case challenges First Amendment precedents and could
redefine standards of liability in the entertainment industry,
opening the door to similar suits against book publishers, film and
television producers, musicians and other artists. Entertainment
industry leaders are watching the case closely, and the filmmakers'
appeal was supported by a friend-of-the-court brief signed by 27
media groups, ranging from ABC, Inc., to the Freedom to Read
Foundation to the Video Software Dealers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to defend vigorously the constitutional
rights of artists and directors to express their creative ideas
without fear of liability,'' said John Schulman, general counsel
for Warner Bros., the division of Time Warner that produced the
movie. ``We are fully confident that the courts will ultimately
uphold those rights in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit is being brought by the family of Patsy Ann Byers, who
was shot and paralyzed during a March 8, 1995, robbery at a
convenience store in Ponchatoula, La. The suit alleges that the
assailants, Sarah Edmonson and Benjamin Darras, watched the Stone
movie before launching their violent spree. Byers died last year of
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Simpson, one of three lawyers for the Byers family, said
he estimates the damages could be as high as $5 million to $6
million. But he conceded the case would be difficult to prove:
``Put it this way, we have a rough row to hoe, since we ing a phone
interview from his office in Amite, La. The plaintiffs, he said,
are basing their case on an April 1996 interview in which Stone
said, ``The most pacifistic people in the world said they came out
of this movie and wanted to kill somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, which depicts a violent, celebrity-driven culture, has
been a center of controversy nationwide. A 1995 murder in Avon,
Mass. was dubbed the ``Natural Born Killer case'' after one of the
three men accused of killing a disabled veteran allegedly said,
``Haven't you seen `Natural Born Killers' before?'' when he was
confronted about his bloody clothing. That case sparked Bob Dole,
then Senate majority leader, to lash out against violence in
popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   A 1969 Supreme Court decision ruled that people can only be
prosecuted or punished for advocating illegal action if they
specifically incite ``imminent unlawful action.'' In several
precedent-setting cases, in which the families of teenagers who
died sued over media influence, the courts have ruled in favor of
Hustler Magazine, NBC, Inc., and the heavy metal group Judas
Priest.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``Natural Born Killers'' case and a lawsuit pending in
Maryland could push the boundaries of free expression law, some
legal scholars said. Last April, the Supreme Court allowed a case
to proceed against Paladin Press, which published a book called
``Hit Man: A Technical Manual for Independent Contractors.'' A hit
man in Maryland read the book and killed three people, and their
families are suing the publisher, alleging that the book incited
the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Supreme Court says that the (1969 precedent) may not
apply fully in some of these cases, then there is at least some
greater risk of liability,'' said Frederick Schauer, Frank Stanton
professor of the First Amendment at Harvard's Kennedy School of
Government. Schauer, however, cautioned that Monday's ruling does
not imply a change in precedent; the Supreme Court agrees to hear
fewer than 100 of the more than 6,000 appeals it receives each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Stone could not be reached for comment Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
