<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAPPEN-THEORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILD ABUSE EXPERTS DEBUNK NEW EAPPEN DEATH THEORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS AND PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new and legally explosive theory that Matthew Eappen died not
from shaking but from strangulation as much as 48 hours previously
came under intense fire Monday from child abuse experts who called
it illogical and medically unsound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on e-mail all day'' with other child abuse experts
``and everybody's scratching their heads and saying, where did he
get this time frame _ there's nothing in the literature to support
it,'' said Dr. Robert Reece, director of the New England Medical
Center's Child Protection Program.
</P>
<P>
   His and others' criticism of the strangulation theory, put
forward on the CBS-TV show ``60 Minutes'' show Sunday, again
highlighted the stunningly divergent opinions of the same evidence
that scientific experts, even in the same field, can reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on who's doing the interpreting, and with what
incentive,'' said Dr. Marcia Angell, executive editor of the New
England Journal of Medicine. ``In any legal case, there are plenty
of incentives, and I smell a lot of legal activity here.'' Angell
said she was not familiar with the specifics of the evidence in the
death of Matthew Eappen.
</P>
<P>
   The new theory by Dr. Floyd Gilles, a neuropathologist at
Children's Hospital in Los Angeles, not only brings an entirely new
putative cause of death into the case, but suggests that it may
have been caused by someone other than British nanny Louise
Woodward, who was convicted of involuntary manslaugther of the
baby.
</P>
<P>
   Reece, who served as a prosecution consultant during the
Woodward trial but did not testify, said he was familiar with a
1987 journal article in which Gilles and others reported on the
deaths of three children by strangling. But Reece said that paper
does not support Gilles' argument that strangling in young children
can have such a delayed effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't account for the fact that Matthew was fine at
11:30'' the morning of his death, said Reece in an interview. ``You
don't lie around for 24 or 48 hours with brain damage and then
collapse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Cindy Christian, head of the child abuse program at
Children's Hospital in Philadelphia, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying to imply that the baby would be (seemingly
health) for 48 hours and then would go, kerplunk,'' said Christian.
She also objected that Gilles's argument failed to explain other
injuries noted by doctors who examined Matthew, including broken
blood vessels in the retina of the eye, a skull fracture and a
swelling and blood accumulation, or hematoma, on his brain.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Eli Newberger, a pediatrician and director of family
development programs at Children's Hospital in Boston and who
testified for the prosecution against Woodward, said Monday that
although the editing of his comments on ``60 Minutes'' seemed to
suggest he found Gilles's theory plausible, this wasn't the case.
``I never gave that any serious credence,'' he said. ``It makes
absolutely no sense.
</P>
<P>
   Reece, who in addition to his New England Medical Center
position is director of professional education for the
Massachusetts Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children,
attacked Gilles's credibility, saying his expertise isn't in child
abuse and he doesn't see patients clinically.
</P>
<P>
   Gilles's turn in the media limelight, said Reece, ``is highly
irresponsible and a reflection of academic hubris.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillis, and a colleague, Dr. Marvin Nelson, defended their
findings at a press conference Monday, saying they would stand up
to independent scrutiny. But as the latest tempest swirls around a
case that has worked its way through both the criminal and civil
court systems, it seems more likely that this newest theory may
simply fade away because the legal reality of testing it is so
risky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great downside to moving for a new trial is you may get
it,'' said Marc Perlin, associate dean and professor at Suffolk Law
School in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the lawyers for Woodward are a long way from
taking that step _ one that could only be taken at Woodward's
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the decision for the client to make,'' Harvey
Silverglate, a member of Woodward's defense team, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing Silverglate said he wants to do is to speak to
Dr. Gillis and his colleague, Dr. Marvin Nelson, who told the CBS
news program that he'd found evidence that the baby had fractured
ribs and had been punched hard in the abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with the Los Angeles doctors, Silverglate said he
would like to bring all of the duelling experts together in one
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have preferred that the review of the evidence be
done by an independent organization like the National Academy of
Science or some other independent, prestigious medical or
scientific organization,'' said Silverglate. ``Instead, it was done
by `60 Minutes,' which in our view is better than nothing. . . . We
are very interested not only because of Louise Woodward, but
because other people have been convicted with fallacious
evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   But Middlesex (Mass.) District Attorney Martha Coakley, who
helped prosecute Woodward before becoming district attorney,
dismissed Silverglate's suggestion of a meeting of the scientific
minds as ``a crazy idea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see if there's anyone else in the country who has a
theory as to how Matthew Eappen died,'' Coakley said caustically.
``Because one doctor on the West Coast has a new theory?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 1942EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2411 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ILL-PROSECUTORS-CHARG     03-08 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILL-PROSECUTORS-CHARGED-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
CHICAGO: the girl. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trial here will offer an unusual look inside the process
that prosecutors and the police go through when tackling a
complicated investigation, in this case one of the area's most
grisly and frightening murders, one that law enforcement officials
were under tremendous pressure to solve.
</P>
<P>
   One impression that comes through is that the investigation and
prosecution of Cruz was unwieldy and bedeviled from the outset.
Cruz was someone who initially was courted by detectives as a
source of rumors about the killing. He was not indicted until 13
months after the murder. Nine months after Cruz was arrested, a
detective resigned after expressing doubts about the case. In 1992,
a lawyer in the Illinois attorney general's office in charge of
fighting Cruz's appeals, resigned, saying she believed Cruz was
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is coming at a difficult time for the Illinois justice
system, which has seen 11 death row inmates freed after
investigations found evidence of their innocence. Defense attorneys
and critics of the criminal justice system across the country say
this case may pull a veil off unacceptable prosecutorial and
investigative practices that they believe are not uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   Some prosecutors worry that the case could have a chilling
effect, causing prosecutors to hesitate as they second-guess their
actions. Others say these allegations, if true, are an aberration.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Kent Schaffer, director of the National
Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers, said ``the important thing
about this case is it's going to tell prosecutors that they are not
immune from prosecution if they hide evidence, if they suborn
perjury or if they go after somebody who has not committed the
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether the special prosecutor in the case,
William J. Kunkle Jr., known for prosecuting John Wayne Gacy, the
serial killer, will argue that some or all of the defendants knew
Cruz was innocent, or honestly believed he was guilty but cut
corners to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   The men, known as the DuPage Seven, have all pleaded not guilty.
The parents of the murdered girl, Tom and Pat Nicarico, are
supporting the DuPage Seven and have praised their work and
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   The four sheriff's officers, James T. Montesano, Thomas E.
Vosburgh, Dennis Kurzawa, and Robert L. Winkler, are still working
for the sheriff's department. One of the former prosecutors,
Patrick J. King Jr., is now an assistant U.S. attorney in Chicago.
Another, Thomas L. Knight, has a private law practice; and the
third, Robert K. Kilander, is a DuPage County judge.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The DuPage Seven case emerged out of the long, intricate
prosecution of Cruz, now 38, and another man, Alejandro Hernandez,
now 35, for the sexual assault and murder of Jeanine Nicarico, who
was home alone from school with a cold one February day when
someone kicked in the front door of her house in the affluent town
of Naperville and abducted her. Her body was found two days later
in a wooded area about six miles away and the crime, in a suburb
hardly used to such inexplicable violence, stunned the community.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was also convicted of the murder, sentenced to death
and then, in a second trial three years later, sentenced to 80
years in prison. He, too, was exonerated in 1995, but a judge ruled
that the DuPage Seven case should focus only on allegations in the
Cruz case.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those allegations involve the main strategy used to
convict Cruz and Hernandez: testimony by two of the sheriff's
deputies, Vosburgh and Kurzawa, that Cruz told them he had had a
dream about Jeanine's killing and revealed details the deputies
said only the killer could know.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz and his lawyers have repeatedly said that the deputies
fabricated the dream, and that there was no written investigator's
report about it. In 1995, in Cruz's third trial (his two previous
convictions had been overturned on appeal), another sheriff's
officer, Montesano, said he had testified falsely that the deputies
had informed him about Cruz's dream. As a result, the judge
acquitted Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   Vosburgh's lawyer, Brian Telander, said on Monday that he would
present testimony from six of the grand jurors who originally
indicted Cruz, all of whom say that, although there is no written
record, Cruz babbled to them that he had had a dream about the
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler is charged with falsely testifying that Cruz told him
about acquiring and disposing of a car used in the murder. King and
Knight are accused of presenting the false testimony, knowing it
was false. Kilander is charged with failing to inform defense
attorneys that a lawyer for a convicted child rapist and murderer
named Brian Dugan had told him that Dugan admitted to killing
Jeanine.
</P>
<P>
   Kilander's lawyer, Ronald D. Menaker, suggested that his client
had fulfilled his obligation because he had told defense attorneys
about an interview he had with Dugan shortly after he talked with
Dugan's lawyer. Lawyers for the other defendants either declined to
comment or did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Dugan, serving a life sentence for two rapes and murders, was
linked to the Nicarico murder by DNA testing in 1989, but has not
been charged in the case. He has said he will only talk with
authorities if they promise to spare him from execution.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say Kunkle and his team have a tough task ahead of them.
They will not only have to prove that the sheriff's deputies
fabricated evidence, but that the prosecutors knew the evidence was
false. They also have to convince a jury to believe _ over the
assertions of upstanding law enforcement officers _ the contention
by Cruz, known at the time to be a street punk, that he never
described a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got very difficult problems because he's trying some
people of significant stature who are well-respected,'' said
Terrance A. Norton, a former federal prosecutor who is now a
clinical professor of law at Chicago-Kent College of law.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest job of all, however, may be to make the case that
the prosecutors, perhaps because they were under pressure to solve
a horrifying crime, behaved in a way that was criminal and not just
mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a difference between incompetent prosecutors and
criminal prosecutors,'' Allen of Northwestern said, ``and I think
that's going to be difficult to prove.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
