<SLUG> BC-SALVADOR-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVES NEAR VICTORY IN EL SALVADOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR _ Despite widespread voter apathy that resulted in
a low turnout during Sunday's presidential elections, El Salvador's
ruling conservative party appeared headed toward an outright
victory over leftist opponents Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Figures released Monday by the country's Supreme Electoral
Tribunal showed that 39-year-old Francisco Flores, candidate of the
Republican Nationalist Alliance, garnered almost 52 percent of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Flores's closest rival, 44-year-old Facundo Guardado of the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, had 29.3 percent with
about 93 percent of the votes counted. Flores needed 50 percent to
avoid an April runoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a victory for all Salvadorans,'' Flores said in a
press conference Sunday night, where he claimed victory less than
three hours after polls closed. He said his campaign had been
conducted in a ``positive way.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 40 percent of El Salvador's 3 million registered voters
cast ballots Sunday in the peaceful and orderly elections.
Observers blamed the lower-than-expected turnout on the country's
arcane registration process, a lackluster campaign, and economic
frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   The victory marked a dramatic triumph for the former philosophy
professor who studied at Amherst College and in California. His
campaign announcement a year ago had surprised many.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Flores portrayed himself as a more
independent voice in the party, staying away from the anticommunist
themes that became the Republican Nationalist Alliance's trademark
during the civil war years. Instead, Flores focused on El
Salvador's growing crime and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The margin of victory marked a dramatic turnaround for the
Republican Nationalist Alliance and the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front, the former guerrilla group that became a
political party after the civil war ended in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   During midterm elections two years ago, momentum seemed to favor
the Front, captured the San Salvador mayor's office and came within
one seat of matching the ruling party's power in the assembly.
</P>
<P>
   But the Front was split between hardline socialists and
moderates during the candidate selection process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
