<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-AWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUNRO TAKES FICTION AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A &UR;  &LR; harrowing account of the 1994 Rwandan genocide has earned the
National Book Critics Circle Award for nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   The winning author was Philip Gourevitch, a staff writer for The
New Yorker, for ``We Wish to Inform You That Tomorrow We Will Be
Killed With Our Families: Stories From Rwanda,'' published by
Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing the book last year, Globe book editor David Mehegan
called it ``absolutely revealing in its detailed account'' of the
ethnic slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Readers, Mehegan said, may experience the same ``vacant feeling
and sense of overwhelmed emptiness'' that was produced by John
Hersey's classic, ``Hiroshima.''
</P>
<P>
   Canadian author Alice Munro won the fiction award for her
collection of stories, ``The Love of a Good Woman,'' published by
Knopf. Globe chief book critic Gail Caldwell wrote that the Russian
short story master Anton Chekhov ``would have admired this humble
acknowledgement of the human condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Winner Monday for criticism was Village Voice contributor Gary
Giddins, for ``Visions of Jazz: The First Century,'' published by
Oxford. Former Globe book editor Robert Taylor said Giddins
``shared an elusive individual tone'' with such classic jazz
critics as James Agee and George Frazier.
</P>
<P>
   The winner for biography was Sylvia Nasar for ``A Beautiful
Mind'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster), the story of troubled mathematical
genius John Forbes Nash Jr., and for poetry, Marie Ponsot, for
``The Bird Catcher'' (Knopf).
</P>
<P>
   The awards were presented at New York University Law School's
Tishman Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   The other finalists were:
</P>
<P>
   In fiction: Michael Cunningham, for ``The Hours'' (Farrar,
Straus &AMP; Giroux); David Gates, for ``Preston Falls'' (Knopf); and
Lynne Tillman, for ``No Lease on Life'' (Harcourt Brace).
</P>
<P>
   In general nonfiction: Ira Berlin, for ``Many Thousands Gone:
The First Two Centuries of Slavery in North America''
(Harvard/Belknap); Adam Hochschild, for ``King Leopold's Ghost: A
Story of Greed, Terror, and Heroism in Colonial Africa'' (Houghton
Mifflin); Roy Porter, for ``The Greatest Benefit to Mankind: A
Medical History of Humanity from Antiquity to the Present''
(Norton); and Simon Winchester, for ``The Professor and the Madman:
A Tale of Murder, Insanity, and the Making of the Oxford English
Dictionary'' (HarperCollins).
</P>
<P>
   In biography/autobiography: Ron Chernow, for ``Titan: The Life
of John D. Rockefeller Sr.'' (Random House); Homer H. Hickham Jr.,
for ``Rocket Boys: A Memoir'' (Delacorte); David Remnick for ``King
of the World: Muhammad Ali and the Rise of an American Hero''
(Random House); and Amanda Vaill for ``Everybody Was So Young:
Gerald and Sara Murphy: A Lost Generation Love Story'' (Houghton
Mifflin).
</P>
<P>
   In poetry: Anne Carson, for ``Autobiography of Red: A Novel in
Verse'' (Knopf); Pamela White Hadas, for ``Self-Evidence: A
Selection of Verse, 1977-1997'' (Triquarterly/Northwestern); Yusef
Komunyakaa, for ``Thieves of Paradise'' (Wesleyan); and Thylias
Moss, for ``Last Chance for the Tarzan Holler'' (Persea).
</P>
<P>
   In criticism: Harold Bloom, for ``Shakespeare: The Invention of
the Human'' (Riverhead); Geoff Dyer, for ``Out of Sheer Rage:
Wrestling With D. H. Lawrence'' (North Point); Nelson George, for
``Hip Hop America'' (Viking); and Robert Pinsky, for ``The Sounds
of Poetry'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux).
</P>
<P>
   The Nona Balakian Award for Excellence in Reviewing went to
freelance book reviewer Albert Mobilio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
