<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2421 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-NICARAGUA-HNS     03-08 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NICARAGUA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON `HUMBLED' BY DEVASTATED AREAS OF NICARAGUA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANAGUA, Nicaragua _ Kicking off a four-day tour of Central
America, President Clinton on Monday toured one of the worst
horrors left by Hurricane Mitch, but offered a fraction of the
reconstruction help he had hoped to deliver to the region.
</P>
<P>
   The president walked through the ruins of two neighboring
villages where 2,000 people were killed when 40 feet of mud crushed
their communities in late October.
</P>
<P>
   The visit was the first by a U.S. president to Nicaragua since
1968, when President Johnson visited the country. President Clinton
was not accompanied by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, who was
sidelined with a recurring back injury.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton arrived with little aid to offer. Some Central
American leaders also are rankled over U.S. immigration policy,
which began this week forcing thousands of illegal immigrants to
return to the stricken region where little shelter and no jobs
await them.
</P>
<P>
   While the visit to Nicaragua, Honduras, El Salvador and
Guatemala helps turn attention from the president's scandals, which
seem to get new life each week, it also helps burnish his image as
a caring international leader.
</P>
<P>
   It also will freshen in the American public's mind the images of
the devastation from Hurricane Mitch, the worst national disaster
to hit the Americas. The storm left more than 9,000 dead, thousands
more homeless, and as much as $10 billion in infrastructure damage
in the region.
</P>
<P>
   No area was hit harder than Posoltega, an agricultural area near
the base of La Casita volcano.
</P>
<P>
   Along the road that Clinton took to one of the two villages,
small wooden crosses dotted the hard, brown dirt. The landscape was
broken only by twisted trees and scattered encampments of tents
made from plastic sheeting and corrugated tin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am moved, I am humbled,'' Clinton said moments after he and
Nicaraguan President Arnoldo Aleman placed flowers at the shallow
grave of a 6-year-old student. The youngster was buried at the spot
where she died when the mudslide smothered part of her school as it
spread over 60-square miles northwest of Managua.
</P>
<P>
   Even vivid news coverage of the late-October storm's damage
``cannot convey the depth of destruction,'' Clinton told reporters.
``No picture can convey the feeling of seeing the outline of that
small child's body by her grave and seeing the remnants of her
skeleton.''
</P>
<P>
   At Jose Delores Toruna High School, Clinton met with the
homeless and jobless survivors, many of whom still live in plastic
tents. Mitch swept away their villages or encased their homes in
mud four months ago.
</P>
<P>
   An intact portion of the building was covered with soot,
indicating where survivors sought shelter, using students' desks
and chairs to build fires for cooking. The homeless villagers were
relocated four weeks ago so classes could resume.
</P>
<P>
   To help reopen the school, Clinton delivered 3,000 pounds of
supplies, including six boxes unloaded from Air Force One. The
boxes contained pens, pencils and writing tables collected from
White House staff members.
</P>
<P>
   The president also announced that the U.S. government would
spend $120 million in the region to improve health care, build
temporary shelters and support schools. Immediately after the
storm, the United States sent about $350 million in disaster aid.
</P>
<P>
   For Nicaragua, U.S. aid will amount to:
</P>
<P>
   _ $10.6 million from the Agency for International Development to
repair, equip and staff health clinics, and $12.5 million for
elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ Another $1.5 million in AID money for the International Red
Cross to build 4,000 temporary homes starting this month.
</P>
<P>
   _ $1.8 million from the State Department to find and remove land
mines remaining from Nicaragua's civil war. The task of removing
the mines from Nicaragua and neighboring Honduras was complicated
when floods and mudslides associated with Mitch shifted mapped
areas where explosives had been deployed.
</P>
<P>
   Similar aid packages for El Salvador, Honduras and Guatemala
will be announced at Clinton's subsequent stops this week, when he
engages in talks with regional leaders on immigration and ongoing
efforts to strengthen ties between the isthmus nations and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the aid he announced Monday totals far less than the
$956 million Clinton is trying to secure from Congress. The
disaster aid, which Clinton wants to fund from the anticipated
budget surplus, was stalled last week by Republican congressional
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of using the federal budget surplus, the GOP leaders
proposed raising money to finance the disaster aid by cutting
programs for the poor and the environment that Clinton historically
has fought to protect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somos humanos nos ayudamos,'' Clinton told hundreds who
gathered in the hot sun. ``We are brothers and sisters, neighbors
and friends. We must help each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating Clinton's arrival, thousands of people poured into
Posoltega by truck, bus or on foot. Many carried U.S. flags or
signs greeting the president. ``Welcome Bill Clinton,'' said one
sign held aloft in the mass of people.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Jose Ronaldo Romero, 40, a cane worker who earns
about $53 a month, who wanted Clinton's help obtaining a coffin so
he could re-bury his father-in-law. Romero also wanted eyeglasses
for his daughter Escarlina, 9, whose vision was damaged when she
and her mother were buried in mud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is in solidarity with us,'' Romero said. ``We want to
thanks him for his visit to our humble town.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, Clinton flew to El Savador, where Salvadoran
President Armando Calderon Sol has already made clear his
displeasure with the U.S. president's decision not to extend a stay
of deportations of illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The stay, issued in the wake of Hurricane Mitch to help
alleviate pressure on the strapped Salvadoran and Guatemalan
governments, expired Monday.
</P>
<P>
   To have them return now ``would cause us tragic problems of
stability,'' Calderon said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3 million Central American citizens live in the United
States, about one-third of them illegally. The money they earn,
and, in most cases, send home is a major element in the regional
economy. In Guatemala and El Salvador, it is the principal source
of currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision is frankly hard to fathom,'' Guatemalan
President Alvaro Arzu said in a letter to Clinton last week asking
that the suspension be extended. ``It is strange and
contradictory,'' Arzu wrote.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Michael Hammer said the administration has
determined the region is capable of ``beginning to receive their
nationals'' who entered the United States illegally. At the same
time, Hammer said, deportations are not expected to begin
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
