<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta fans gobble up Thrasher tickets
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The most expensive ticket in Atlanta sports apparently
hasn't scared off ticket buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers, still seven months away from their inaugural NHL
season, satisfied the league's mandate for season-ticket sales by
surpassing the 12,000 mark this past weekend. If the team didn't
sell another ticket, it still would average more than the Flames
did in their last three seasons in Atlanta, 1977-80.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows there's a tremendous amount of interest in the sport
in this area,'' Thrashers president Harvey Schiller said. ``At each
stage, we'll see more interest. The biggest push will be when we
start naming players.''
</P>
<P>
   The 90 suites in the still-unfinished Philips Arena are sold out
and account for approximately 1,600 seats. The majority of seats in
the top price ranges _ $70 and $65 _ are sold out. The Thrashers'
average price of $45 per ticket is the highest among Atlanta's four
pro sports teams, although team officials are quick to make mention
of 1,000 day-of-game tickets at $10.
</P>
<P>
   Schiller said he was not concerned about reaching the sales
minimum as much as doing it by the NHL's March 15 deadline, which
the Thrashers reached by only a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only concern was the time period,'' he said. ``You have to
remember we were sitting here in an unusual position. We're the
only expansion club that didn't have an arena or a team. It's like
Quebec (Nordiques) moving to Denver or Winnipeg moving to Phoenix.
The issues of sight-lines and seats have had to be (communicated)
through computers or visualization.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flames' topped out at an attendance average of 14,162 in
their second season of 1973-74 but dropped to a low of 10,024 in
their final year before moving to Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   Schiller said he would be ``pleased'' if the Thrashers exceed
14,000 season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to his joking remark that he would fire his son, Derek,
the team's vice president of marketing and sales, if 12,000 season
tickets weren't sold, Schiller said, ``The poor kid has an ulcer
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
