<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARR-GUNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barr to offer legislation preventing state gun suits
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) plans to unveil legislation
today that would block cities and states from suing gunmakers,
saying they are fast becoming victim to a rash of ``unfair''
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Barr, a board member of the National Rifle Association, said he
was prompted to introduce the legislation after watching Atlanta
and four other cities file lawsuits that seek to hold the firearms
manufacturers accountable for gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``These lawsuits are a frontal assault on lawful manufacturing
of products in America,'' Barr said. ``This is a shameless effort
by certain cash-strapped cities to grab a bag of money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta is not a cash-strapped city, and Mayor (Bill) Campbell
(of Atlanta) did not file this suit for monetary gain,'' said Nick
Gold, spokesman for the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the suit was to get gunmakers to make their
products safer. We feel there is technology available today where
that could be achieved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barr's bill is drawing controversy even before it has been
introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Groups advocating gun control say Barr's bill would offer the
industry special legal protection and that it is time for gunmakers
to be responsible for the damage caused by their product.
</P>
<P>
   ``This amounts to political obstruction of justice,'' said Bob
Walker, president of Handgun Control, a Washington-based
organization that pushes gun violence prevention. ``Barr is trying
to use political means to stop lawsuits. If these cases are so
frivolous, let the courts throw them out.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits filed by Atlanta; Bridgeport, Conn.; Chicago,
Miami-Dade; and New Orleans seek to force the gun industry to take
steps that ensure that guns are used properly and not distributed
into the hands of criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly this is the next shoe to drop,'' said Barr, comparing
the lawsuits against the gun industry to the slew of lawsuits filed
against the tobacco industry by the states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trial lawyers have eaten their Cheerios and gotten the
tobacco industry to cave in looking around for another industry to
go after,'' Barr said. ``They've found shameless mayors who are
looking for a windfall.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr's bill builds on what already is happening at the state
level. The Georgia Legislature passed a bill last month that would
ban local governments from suing gunmakers and distributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We filed the suit before the Georgia General Assembly passed
its bill,'' said Gold. ``We feel it's up to a court of law to
determine the validity of this lawsuit, not Mr. Barr or the General
Assembly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Legislature is looking at a law that would make it a
felony for a local official to file a lawsuit against the gun
industry. And several other states are considering prohibiting
anti-gun lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Even the unveiling of the legislation is expected to be
controversial. Barr is to introduce his legislation at a news
conference that will feature Wayne LaPierre, executive vice
president of the gun owner's organization.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA's presence at the bill's unveiling spawned a round of
attack from handgun control groups who see it as a conflict of
interest for a board member to sponsor legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barr takes his marching orders from the NRA,'' said Desmond
Riley, the program director for the Educational Fund to End Handgun
Violence, based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Riley finds it ironic that Barr crafted legislation that seeks
the federal government's intervention on a local gun control issue
when he is constantly arguing that the federal government should be
less intrusive in people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   Barr is unmoved by the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how these gun control people operate,'' Barr said.
``If anyone disagrees with them they raise the bogeyman. People are
going to criticize me no matter what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr said several Democrats have vowed to support his bill, but
he would not disclose their names. One group that is unlikely to
back it is the U.S. Conference of Mayors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel strongly that mayors will stand united in opposing the
federal government or any state entity in prohibiting the rights of
a municipality from filing a lawsuit on guns or any other issue,''
said Katie Cullen, the organization's associate executive director
of public affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Carr writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
