<SLUG> BC-MA-ELDERLY-INSURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW RULES PROPOSED ON LTC INSURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In an attempt to curb consumer confusion and insurance
industry abuses, Massachusetts insurance regulators Monday proposed
new rules on insurance to cover the cost of nursing home stays and
other long-term care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long-term care insurance is often sold on a fear basis,''
Massachusetts insurance commissioner Linda Ruthardt said in an
interview. ``These new regulations try to make it possible for
consumers to understand what they're buying.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is the first revision in long-term care regulations
in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   So far fewer than 50,000 of Massachusetts elders, or 4 percent
of that population, are believed to have purchased such coverage.
However, insurers and regulators expect the market to increase
substantially with the aging of the baby boom generation. The
number of companies offering such coverage in the Bay State has
jumped from three in 1992 to at least 32 today.
</P>
<P>
   State officials and consumer advocates say that many low- and
middle-income elders are talked into buying expensive long-term
care insurance they can't afford and don't need.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many people who really don't have sufficient assets
to be buying long-term care insurance, but for one reason or other
they're scared into it,'' said Joanna Connolly, an assistant
attorney general who served on a state task force to develop the
new regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``A third of the people in this market are probably unsuitable
applicants,'' agreed Al Norman of Mass Home Care, a group of 30
nonprofit elder services agencies. ``They're people who are scared
about being left penniless by a nursing home stay and they
mistakenly think they couldn't qualify for Medicaid. So they buy
long-term care insurance when they can barely afford it. As a
result, many of them don't hang onto it.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a state survey, nearly one in three consumers who
bought coverage for long-term care let it lapse within four years.
The great majority forfeited the money they had paid.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rules would require salesmen to let consumers know
if they have assessed their need for coverage, and what the
assessment says. But agents are not required to do the
``suitability'' assessment in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations would require agents to offer coverage that
adjusts for inflation and returns premiums if the policyholder lets
coverage lapse. It would require agents to be trained in selling
the complex coverage.
</P>
<P>
   However, the proposal does not standardize benefits to make it
possible for consumers to comparison shop. And unlike current
regulations, the new ones do not require policies to cover home
health services, an omission that Norman plans to contest.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed regulations will be the subject of a public hearing
March 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
