<HEADER>
A2453 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-STATEOFSTATE-COX     03-08 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-STATEOFSTATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taft to deliver first State of State
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Dayton, Ohio's Kimberly Brown today will help
Gov. Bob Taft use his first State of the State address to
demonstrate that education can transform the lives of Ohioans who
are willing to study and work.
</P>
<P>
   After 18 years of living on public assistance, Brown, 37, used
the Job Training Partnership Act to return to school and become a
licensed practical nurse. Since October, she has been working at
the Riverside Nursing Center where she earns $17 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love nursing, just dealing with people,'' said Brown, a
single mother of four children ranging in age from 16 to 21.''
</P>
<P>
   Her two youngest children as well as a 12-year-old niece still
live at home with Brown.
</P>
<P>
   She was selected as one of three special guests for the speech
and was scheduled to spend Monday night at the Governor's Mansion
in suburban Bexley, Taft aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said her own transformation began when she concluded that
she was ``not getting any younger.''
</P>
<P>
   She passed the General Educational Development Test - qualifying
her for the equivalent of a high school diploma - and then studied
nursing at the Miami Valley Career Technological Center. Brown's
education was financed by the Job Training Partnership Act, a
federal program administered at the state and local levels.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said she realizes the value of what she has accomplished
``every time I see my pay check.''
</P>
<P>
   Taft considers her an excellent example of someone who went back
to school and got the necessary training to get a good job, said
Mary Anne Sharkey, Taft's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   During the speech, the 57-year-old governor will emphasize
``education, education, education,'' Sharkey said. Taft also will
discuss health care reform and will unveil plans for a statewide
urban revitalization task force to help the economies of cities
such as Dayton, said Scott Milburn, Taft's press secretary. The
task force will be led by Lee Johnson, Taft's development director.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has said that he considers education the key to
conquering what he calls the ``frontier of knowledge and
technology,'' a frontier that Taft considers even more challenging
than the geographical frontier that challenged earlier generations
of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican governor from Cincinnati will reinforce his
campaign pledge to make paying for primary and secondary education
the top priority of his administration, said Milburn, the press
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   His school funding plans will have to be considered against the
backdrop of Perry Count Judge Linton Lewis' Feb. 26 decision last
month that threw out the plan former Gov. George Voinovich and the
legislature had come up with to pay for schools. Lewis said the
plan failed to meet the Ohio Supreme Court's 1997 order to create a
``thorough and efficient system of public education.''
</P>
<P>
   Taft, Senate President Richard Finan, R-Cincinnati, and House
Speaker Jo Ann Davidson, R-Reynoldsburg, have said they will appeal
the decision to the Ohio Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has said he wants to do all he and the legislature
can do to improve the system while the appeal is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Taft's fellow Republicans both say they are eager
to hear what he has to say about the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to provide leadership to correct the ills in our
education system,'' said David Leland, chairman of the Ohio
Democratic Party. ``He needs to step up to the plate and talk about
education funding.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Robert Netzley, R-Laura, the senior member of the the
Ohio House, said the challenge Taft faces is not a new one for Ohio
governors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll probably talk about the same thing all the governors
talk about - education. They don't know what to do. Nothing has
changed in 40 years,'' said Netzley, who came to the legislature in
1961.
</P>
<P>
   The time is right for Taft, Netzley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a golden opportunity,'' Netzley said. ``I don't know if
he can figure it out or not.''
</P>
<P>
   William Hershey writes for The Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
