<SLUG> BC-HILTON-DALEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILTON RETURNS TO DOWNTOWN BOSTON WITH HOTEL BUY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD KINDLEBERGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Nine years after he bought the Back Bay Hilton, James
A. Daley is selling the 385-room hotel to Hilton Hotels Corp. _
apparently for a multimillion-dollar profit _ and exiting the hotel
business.
</P>
<P>
   Daley declined to reveal the sale price in advance of a planned
April 30 closing, but industry observers suggested he would get
about $200,000 a room, or almost $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel was purchased by Daley for $34.5 million in November
1989. He said Monday it carries only $30 million in debt. A 44-room
expansion, completed last July, and a top-to-bottom overhaul were
mostly financed out of income, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A purchase-and-sale agreement was signed last Friday, according
to Daley. Mark Grossman, a Hilton executive, confirmed the chain
agreed to buy the hotel but declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed in his office in the hotel, Daley said he will miss
the people he has worked with but said, given the strength of the
market, ``this is a time to sell.'' He said he has no immediate
plans except to work on his golf game and play with his
grandchildren. He did not rule out another business venture if the
right opportunity arose.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel deal will give the Hilton chain its first downtown
Boston hotel since it sold the Statler-Hilton, now the Park Plaza
Hotel, in 1976. It plans to open a 600-room Logan Airport Hilton
later this year to replace an older airport hotel.
</P>
<P>
   If Hilton had not exercised its right of first refusal to buy
the Back Bay hotel, it would have run the risk of losing its only
downtown flag, according to Daley. Its franchise agreement was due
to expire in three years, and the hotel's owner could then have
chosen another operator.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the hotel, Hilton will acquire plans for a major
expansion that would nearly double the size of the hotel. Daley
said the plans, which call for building a 40-story glass tower over
a garage behind the current structure, is regarded favorably by
city officials and the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The sale caps a remarkable rise to riches for Daley, 57. Born
the son of a Boston truck driver, he dropped out of a chiropractic
school and never went to college.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he got into the nursing home business, buying ``an old,
broken-down nursing home in bankrupcty.'' He cleaned it up and got
it back on a solid financial footing. His wife, Kathleen Yvonne,
ran it while he served six months of active duty in the US Army
Reserves.
</P>
<P>
   After two decades in the business, he sold off the last of his
16 nursing homes and got into hotels. He bought the Bradford Hotel
on Tremont Street, now the Tremont House, in 1986. Two years later
he bought the Copley Plaza. He sold his interest in the Copley two
years ago, and the Tremont the year before that.
</P>
<P>
   It has not always been a smooth ride. Coming out of recession,
Daley couldn't keep up the payments on the Copley and had to give
up his majority stake to Harvard Management Co. in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   As he contemplated his move toward at least temporary retirement
Monday, Daley took satisfaction in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked very hard for the 20 years I was in the nursing home
business to develop the best nursing homes in the state,'' he said.
``I like to think I've done the same thing with the hotels. I'm a
lucky kid. It's takes luck along with a lot of hard work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
