A2461 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-SCHOOLS-NEWTESTS     03-08 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-SCHOOLS-NEWTESTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State in a hurry to get new tests to schools
 &HT;    By Lynn Hulsey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A Xenia, Ohio newspaper story containing Ohio
Proficiency Test questions is the worst security breach since the
test's inception nine years ago, according to the Ohio Department
of Education.
</P>
<P>
   But a Xenia school official criticized the state's practice of
letting year-round schools test students earlier than most other
schools because it makes maintaining test security more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's to say kids taking it early aren't going to tell their
friends or neighbors who go to another school?'' said Judy Lowrey,
the superintendent's administrative assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the state department of education invalidated both
writing questions on the fourth grade test and both on the sixth
grade test after the Xenia Daily Gazette published the questions.
</P>
<P>
   The state is rushing to come up with four new questions, reprint
the writing portion of the exam and mail it to schools in time for
proficiency tests scheduled for the week of March 15 or 22, said
Dottie Howe, a department of education spokesperson. District's
planning to administer the test next week will be asked to delay
the writing portion to the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the modified writing tests will go to 270,000 fourth and
sixth graders, Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   Howe said the state has not decided how to handle the six Ohio
schools giving the test this week, and she believes students in
those schools are taking the now-invalidated writing test. Howe
didn't know whether any Miami Valley schools would be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Howe didn't know what it will cost to re-do questions and mail
them to school districts. The entire proficiency test booklet,
which includes all five portions of the test, costs $16.20 each to
produce.
</P>
<P>
   By law school districts keep questions confidential until July 1
because students take the test throughout the school year and the
same question may appear on more than one test, Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope the media understand that once they publish
writing topics and test questions, they're breaching this security
as well,'' Roger Trent, department of education director of
assessment and evaluation, said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Christie Gilpin, Xenia Daily Gazette city editor, declined
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's March 2 article quoted students who were
interviewed after taking the writing portion of the test at
McKinley Elementary, a year-round school permitted to administer
the test early. Test results for McKinley will not be invalidated
by the department of education action.
</P>
<P>
   Lowrey said reporters often have been allowed to interview
students during the week of testing and the assumption has always
been that they would not print the questions.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Hulsey writes for The Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio. Mark
Fisher contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
