<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-PATIENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES TO HEAR FORMER MENTAL PATIENT'S CASE AGAINST
PSYCHIATRISTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court agreed Monday to decide if a
former mental patient can sue Dallas psychiatrists who he claims
kept him hospitalized against his will for care he did not need.
</P>
<P>
   Federal courts in Texas have rejected, on procedural grounds,
Mark Rotella's claim that doctors needlessly admitted him to
Brookhaven Psychiatric Pavilion in Dallas in February 1985, when he
was 16 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Rotella, who spent 479 days in the hospital on what he calls a
trumped-up diagnosis of borderline personality disorder and major
depression, alleges the unnecessary hospitalization was part of an
illegal scheme in which the doctors were paid to fill hospital
beds.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. District Court in Fort Worth, Texas, followed by the
5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans, ruled that
Rotella waited too long past the four-year window to sue the
doctors under the federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt
Organizations Act. He waited 11 years since his release from
Brookhaven in 1986 before suing in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, when it hears Rotella's case this fall or
early next year, will consider whether the Texas federal courts
measured too strictly the four-year time limit for filing a lawsuit
under RICO. If it agrees with the argument by Rotella's lawyer,
Kevin Dubose of Houston, that the four-year deadline should be more
relaxed, the high court could order Rotella's lawsuit to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are expected to render their decision in the case
by July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Rotella's lawsuit against the doctors is part of the nearly
1,000 civil cases brought by former patients at Brookhaven and
other psychiatric hospitals once owned by National Medical
Enterprises Inc. NME pleaded guilty in 1994 to federal fraud and
conspiracy charges and paid a $350 million fine.
</P>
<P>
   Tenet Healthcare Corp. took over for NME in March 1995, closed
Brookhaven Psychiatric Pavilion and inherited the company's legal
problems. Last summer, Tenet paid $100 million to settle 700
wrongful hospitalization lawsuits filed in Texas, The New York
Times reported.
</P>
<P>
   Rotella, of Fort Worth, resolved his dispute with Tenet before a
lawsuit was filed. His attorney Robert Andrews, also of Fort Worth,
declined to disclose any details of that resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Dubose, Rotella's Supreme Court lawyer, argued that the lower
courts were wrong to count the time to file under RICO from when
Rotella was released from the hospital. He said the four-year clock
began eight years later, when NME admitted its guilt. The company
acknowledged that it had paid incentive bonuses to doctors based on
the number of patients at NME's hospitals and cut deals with
physicians who admitted patients to its health care facilities.
</P>
<P>
   This public guilty plea in 1994 put Rotella on notice that he
had a potential racketeering claim against the doctors, Dubose
argued. Rotella then filed his lawsuit three years later.
</P>
<P>
   Under the courts' flawed rationale, Rotella ``would have been
required to make judgments about his doctors' conduct when he was
being treated by those very doctors, who provided his only contact
with reality,'' Dubose wrote in his brief to the high court.
``Moreover, he would be charged with discovering an elaborate
scheme of deception so carefully disguised that federal prosecutors
considerably more knowledgeable and sophisticated than Mark Rotella
were not able to expose it until 1994 _ four years after Mr.
Rotella's (filing) period would have expired under (the lower
courts') rule.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for the doctors, Debora Alsup of Austin, Texas,
failed to convince the justices to let the lower courts' decisions
stand. Alsup argued that Texas law, not the federal racketeering
statute, should apply to the personal injuries which Rotella claims
to have suffered at the hands of the doctors, including abuse and
intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
