<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-ANTITRUST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL, FTC SETTLE ANTITRUST CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Only a day before the opening gavel was to sound,
Intel Corp. averted a lengthy antitrust trial by settling federal
charges that it had abused its commanding position in the computer
chip market to hurt competitors, including Digital Equipment Corp.
of Maynard.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the agreement Monday will not be revealed until the
deal is approved by the four-member Federal Trade Commission,
expected within two weeks. However, a source said the settlement is
``very, very narrow'' and affects only a limited number of Intel's
business practices.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the settlement, the FTC was seeking far more limited
constraints on Intel than the Justice Department is likely to
demand from Microsoft Corp., the defendant in another high-profile
antitrust case. However, government action against either company
is closely watched in the computer industry, which has long
operated in the shadow of the so-called ``Wintel duopoly'' _ a
reference to the overwhelming market power of Microsoft's Windows
software and Intel's computer chips.
</P>
<P>
   Many antitrust specialists said Intel was carrying a strong hand
into the trial, which was due to begin Tuesday before an
administrative law judge. But had a court ruled that Intel is a
monopoly, other companies would have had an easier time bringing
private antitrust actions against Intel. Moreover, the government
might have gained new ground to bring additional charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view this compromise agreement as a win-win for both
parties,'' said Craig Barrett, president and chief executive
officer of Intel. The company still faces a separate and ongoing
federal investigation into whether it illegally used monopoly
powers to push into new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The case settled Monday turns on the what rights a company has
to control its own intellectual property _ in this case, ``color
books'' in which Intel shares sensitive technical information about
its chips with other companies. The books have red, orange, or
yellow covers, signifying the level of competitive value of the
information.
</P>
<P>
   Like other high-tech firms, Intel routinely shares proprietary
information about the products it is developing so that other firms
can design compatible products to be ready at the same time. A
computer maker, for example, cannot design a computer to run on a
new Intel chip unless it has technical details about the chip.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, based in Santa Clara, Calif., says it has the right to
control who gets its color books and under what circumstances. But
last June, the FTC said Intel acted illegally when it denied three
of its customers access to the books, after those companies filed
lawsuits against Intel or its partners to assert patent rights in
unrelated cases.
</P>
<P>
   Those companies were: Intergraph Corp., an Alabama maker of
industrial computers; Compaq Computer Corp., the giant Texas
computer-maker; and Digital, which was purchased by Compaq last
year. The government said that if Intel could use its monopoly
position to prevent companies from enforcing their legal rights,
then those firms would be scared away from challenging Intel's
dominance.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the trade commission said, Digital sued Intel in
May 1997 for allegedly violating Digital's patents on the Alpha
chip, the speedy microprocessor that Digital hoped would revive the
company. In response, Intel cut off Digital's access to information
about Intel's Pentium chip, which Digital needed to develop
computers powered by the Pentium.
</P>
<P>
   Intel restored the flow of information only after the two
companies settled Digital's suit, the trade commission said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has acknowledged taking most of the actions alleged by the
trade commission, but it said they are perfectly legal.
</P>
<P>
   According to one person familiar with the FTC, the settlement
bars Intel from denying technical information to a company that
brings a patent lawsuit against Intel.
</P>
<P>
   However, Intel is free to deny information to companies that
take other aggressive actions against Intel, this person said. If a
company announces plans to develop a rival to Intel's Pentium chip,
for example, Intel could legally withhold color books or other
information, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very narrow order,'' the person said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect this to have zero impact on Intel on a day-to-day
basis,'' said Rich Gray, a Silicon Valley antitrust lawyer who
followed the case.
</P>
<P>
   It is highly unusual for the commissioners to reject a
settlement that had been fashioned by FTC staff, said Daniel
Schwartz, a former deputy director of the trade commission's Bureau
of Competition, now a partner with the law firm Bryan Cave LLP in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts said that the government faced long odds in making
its case. To begin with, it might have failed to prove that Intel
is a monopoly _ and therefore failed in its claim that Intel abused
its monopoly powers.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's share of the chip market for personal computers has long
been pegged at more than 80 percent; the company posted sales of
$26.3 billion last year. But at least one rival company, Advanced
Micro Devices Inc., is making strong gains, and Intel chips powered
only 40 percent of the computers sold in January, according to PC
Data Inc.
</P>
<P>
   According to papers filed by Intel in the case, the government's
own economic expert, Frederic M. Scherer of Harvard University, has
said that Intel's high market share has not thwarted innovation or
competition in the chip market. His testimony might have hindered
the government in proving that Intel is a monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   However, the ongoing Microsoft trial may have helped encourage
Intel to settle the case. A wide variety of observers have said
that Microsoft made many missteps in its own antitrust trial, which
is on recess after nearly six months of testimony. Some say the
missteps are so serious that Microsoft is in danger of losing the
case, and that the court could impose sweeping restrictions on its
business practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel had a very, very strong case and would probably have
won,'' said Gray, the Silicon Valley lawyer. ``But any time you go
into litigation there is some risk, and what Intel is doing by
reaching this settlement is taking all risk off the table.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is prosecuting Microsoft, rather than the
FTC. The two agencies share responsibility for enforcing antitrust
law.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Mulloy, an Intel spokesman, said the Microsoft case did
not color Intel's decision to settle. ``We believe we made a
decision in the best interests of our shareholders. . . . We looked
at the possibility of a prolonged, expensive trial,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mulloy said it became clear two or three weeks ago that the
company might find common ground with the government, and that the
deal was struck Sunday afternoon. ``As a case gets ready for trial,
it gets clearer and you get to see what the case is on the other
side, and the lawyers get to know each other,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company still faces antitrust charges from its competitors.
Intergraph, one of the computer firms involved in the trade
commission litigation, vowed in a statement Monday ``to continue to
pursue our private lawsuit against Intel.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel shares climbed more than 4 percent Monday, rising 5 points
to close at 119 5/8 in Nasdaq trading. Microsoft shares rose 4 and
1/16 to close at 159 on Nasdaq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
