<HEADER>
A2478 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KUBRICK-COX     03-08 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KUBRICK-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   D'Rays
</P>
<P>
   bisher for monday: (3/8/99)
</P>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. --- Any guy who has a hankering for
baseball, but doesn't know its history is missing half the fun.
This all came to me when I peered into the Atlanta Braves dugout
and saw a familiar face looking back at me. It had been probably 35
years since I last saw Ray Boone. He was then a Milwaukee Brave, a
darkly handsome man just around the corner from the end of a good
career, a very good one.
</P>
<P>
   He had not come here to see Cinderella, Mickey Mouse or ride the
rides. He was here watching the progress of a latter-day edition of
the Boones wearing Braves haberdashery. John Schuerholz made a
daring move to heal all the Braves wounds at second base when the
Braves' CEO traded Denny Neagle, Michael Tucker and a very good
pitcher out of the farm system, Rob Bell, for Bret Boone, Ray's
grandson. A pitcher, Mike Remlinger, was thrown in like the baker
adds a 13th roll.
</P>
<P>
   Bloodlines have never been as important in baseball as in horse
racing, but just through natural courses several family trees of
distinction have developed. The Griffeys, the Bondses, the Sislers,
the Berras. Some turned to other games, like Bob of the Friend
family and Chris of the Perrys, now playing on the PGA Tour. Some
deeper research may be required, but let it stand now, that the
Boones are the only third family generation of all-stars in the
history of the major leagues. All-stars three deep, from Ray to Bob
to Bret.
</P>
<P>
   The grandpa, Ray, came to Cleveland as a catcher, but was
converted to shortstop to follow the great Lou Boudreau. He was
traded to Detroit, became a third baseman and led the American
League in runs batted in 1955. Bob, his son, had a run of 19
seasons catching for California, the Phillies and Kansas City, and
later managed the Royals. As irony would have it, he was sitting at
the right hand of Jim Bowden when the Reds general manager traded
his son to Atlanta. Bob Boone is Bowden's assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born too late to see my grandfather play, but I saw a
lot of my father,'' Bret Boone said. ``I got good baseball genes, I
guess.''
</P>
<P>
   He is the runt of the litter, so to speak. Grandpa is still
stalwart of 6 feet. Bob Boone was well-constructed, six feet two,
tall for a catcher. Bret has a kid brother, Aaron, an infielder
with Cincinnati, who is 6-2. He is advertised as five-feet-10, but
grandpa spoke of him as a ``lot of talent in a five-nine body.''
</P>
<P>
   You know what they say, ``It's not the size of the dog in the
fight, but size of the fight in the dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Bret Boone has built some kind of reputation for crustiness in
his seven years in the majors. There is a certain self-assuredness
in his walk, the way he carries his body, the way he communicates
his mood. That's the line that has followed him from Seattle to
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they think I'm arrogant, but I'm just the way I am.
I'm confident of what I can do and I don't back off from anything
or anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   He wears braces on his teeth, to correct an overbite. ``I've got
a year to go, then they break my jaw, actually, and reset it. There
are probably some guys who'd be happy to break it for me.''
</P>
<P>
   He has had a jaw-breaking mood or two when the Gold Glove teams
have been announced. Those are the fielding all-stars. One season
he made only two errors and set a record for second basemen, yet
Craig Biggio of Houston got the call. Finally, last year, he made
it. He was beginning to lose his good disposition about it, ``But,
I guess they had to get used to me being around.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the trade, and how much the Braves gave up to get him,
Bobby Cox says this: ``Boone is the best second baseman in
baseball. He has no equal. He has a live bat and had a big year
last year. Look at that, 24 home runs and 95 runs batted in; that's
big for a second baseman.''
</P>
<P>
   The party line is that be brings needed fire to the Braves, adds
to their chemistry. ``No reflection on him,'' Manager Cox said,
``but we've got a lot of guys with fire. And we've already got good
chemistry. We got him to play second base.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, he goes on adding to the six decades of the Boone
Family in the Big League. Not only that, he's just before carrying
them into another millenium. Let some other family try to tie that
record.
</P>
<P>
   (et
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
