<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-EAPPEN-WALLACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALLACE STANDS BY EAPPEN BABY REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week, it is CBS's ``60 Minutes'' and Louise Woodward. Last
week, it was ABC's ``20/20'' and Monica Lewinsky. The week before
that, it was NBC's ``Dateline'' and Juanita Broaddrick.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, TV newsmagazines are making front-page news _
and substantially enlarging their audiences in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, that prompts questions as to whether a hunger for
ratings is driving a search for sensational stories, especially at
a time when newsmagazines have become a profit engine for the
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wallace scoffs at such questions, at least as they pertain
to ``60 Minutes'' and the broadcast that has created an uproar in
Boston: Wallace's report suggesting Louise Woodward was wrongly
convicted in the death of Newton infant Matthew Eappen. But Dr. Eli
Newberger of Children's Hospital in Boston, who maintains ``60
Minutes'' twisted his words out of context Sunday night, calls the
broadcast ``hype in the guise of investigative journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a program that drew a higher-than-usual audience of
453,000 households in the Boston area on Sunday night, according to
Nielsen Media Research. (National numbers were not available
Monday.) Wallace, during an interview with the Globe in which he
vigorously disputed criticisms of his report, said it would be
foolish to impute a ratings motive to ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to worry very much about market share; for 20
years, we've been in the top 10,'' Wallace pointed out. ``I'd be a
fool to suggest that we aren't interested in a broad circulation,
just as (newspapers) are. But to suggest it was done for that
reason, and in those circumstances, well. . . . '' He paused, then
added sarcastically: ``I guess we should have done it in sweeps.''
</P>
<P>
   In or out of viewership sweeps periods, there is little question
of the vital importance of ``60 Minutes'' to CBS, or of other
newsmagazines to their networks, which raises the stakes for
controversial broadcasts. Tom Rosenstiel, head of the Project for
Excellence in Journalism, said that revenues from ``60 Minutes''
help ``subsidize not just all the other news shows, but helps
subsidize sports programming at CBS also.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The lion's share, something like 40 percent of the profits at
NBC, come from NBC News, and most of that from `Dateline,' '' added
Rosenstiel. ``Increasingly, news is relied upon to make money as
the cost of sports and entertainment programs goes up and up.''
</P>
<P>
   Just four months ago, another Wallace report created a
controversy when ``60 Minutes'' broadcast a tape of a man's being
administered a lethal injection by Dr. Jack Kevorkian. Now comes
the Woodward report. It hinged largely upon two physicians who
argued that the baby died from strangulation, not from being shaken
and suffering a blow to the head. Dr. Floyd Gilles and Dr. Marvin
Nelson of Children's Hospital in Los Angeles said the strangulation
may have occurred up to 48 hours before the baby's death.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said that although the physicians examined medical
records for more than six months, at the request of ``60 Minutes,''
they were not paid ``a dime'' for their research. He admitted that
he was ``astonished'' at their findings.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said the Woodward story originated with Katie Leishman,
a freelance journalist who specializes in medical issues. Leishman
sent Wallace ``some material'' about a year ago, and after reading
it, he turned it over to a ``60 Minutes'' producer for
investigation. According to Wallace, several stories a year
originate with freelancers or via viewer suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after it aired, the ``60 Minutes'' report prompted
Woodward's attorneys to call for a new investigation. But it also
prompted cries of foul from prosecutor Martha Coakley, who called
its findings ``outrageous,'' and from Newberger, a pediatrician and
director of family development programs at Children's Hospital in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Newberger was quoted during the broadcast as calling the
strangulation theory ``speculative but potentially valid.''
However, the doctor said that his answer was to a question from
Wallace about evidence of possible prior abuse of the baby. He said
that while he discussed the possibility that Matthew Eappen
suffered neck injuries during his fatal assault, he did not lend
any support to the notion that strangulation was the cause of
death.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Wallace Monday stood by his report, saying of
Newberger's comments: ``I make of that that he was conceivably
distressed at his own candor.''
</P>
<P>
   Newberger replied: ``That's baloney. I was with Wallace for two
hours or so. My best recollection is that I never gave any credence
to this theory. It makes no sense. . . . The quote that they used
was in response to a different question.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilles is chief of neuropathology and Nelson is chief of
radiology at LA's Children's Hospital. Asked why ``60 Minutes''
relied on two experts from the same hospital, Wallace said that
Gilles and Nelson are both highly respected leaders in their
fields, and their analyses complemented each other.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he noted that Gilles's name was given to ``60
Minutes'' by a prosecution witness in the Woodward trial, Dr.
Umberto De Girolami, who described Gilles as ``the best totally
independent individual, having nothing to do with either defense or
prosecution, to go over this material,'' according to Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   But Newberger said the report was unbalanced. He said Woodward
and her defense attorney, Barry Sheck, ``were given too much
exposure,'' and Gilles was not pressed to explain holes in his
theory, such as how Matthew Eappen's skull had been fractured, or
``the profuse retinal hemorrhage.''
</P>
<P>
   Newberger's conclusion is that the ``60 Minutes'' story ``shows
the extent to which the Fourth Estate has descended into the
standards of entertainment and hype.'' Wallace, meanwhile, stands
by his story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 2031EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
