u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AEROSPACE-LEAN-2TAKES     03-08 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AEROSPACE-LEAN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AEROSPACE, FOLLOWING TOYOTA'S EXAMPLE, GETS LEAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass.)  (mk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHULA VISTA, Calif. _ Two years ago, B.F. Goodrich Co.'s
aerospace division factory here fell so far behind schedule
producing parts for the new Boeing 737-700 that Boeing Co.
threatened to terminate the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had rafts of Boeing people coming down here helping us get
on schedule,'' recalled Martin Lodge, an executive here.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Boeing people are still coming _ but to help get
themselves back on schedule. This factory has significantly
improved its efficiency using so-called lean production, the
collection of techniques first perfected by Toyota Motor Corp. And
Boeing, facing serious production problems of its own, has sent
more than 300 people here to learn how it's done.
</P>
<P>
   A decade after American automakers and many other companies
began adopting just-in-time delivery and other lean manufacturing
techniques, the aerospace industry is embracing the concept to cut
costs in the face of reduced military spending and, in commercial
aircraft, stiff competition from Europe's Airbus Industrie.
</P>
<P>
   Executives are now bandying about Japanese terms like kaizen
(continuous improvement; pronounced KI-zen) and kanban (the
just-in-time system; pronounced CON-bon). They often mispronounce
them horribly, but are applying them well enough to achieve some
startling efficiency gains in an industry long known as much for
high costs and wasteful procedures as for cutting-edge technology.
</P>
<P>
   At the Boeing factory in Long Beach, Calif., for instance,
production of the C-17 military transport has been doubled in the
last three years without raising the head count. That has helped
save the Pentagon hundreds of millions of dollars, said Richard
Harstad, the Air Force's chief of manufacturing and quality for the
C-17. Boeing's C-17 operation, which initiated the improvement when
it was part of McDonnell Douglas, recently won the Commerce
Department's Malcolm Baldrige National Quality Award.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives and analysts said aerospace manufacturers
lagged behind in adopting lean techniques mostly because Pentagon
contracts generally reimbursed them for their costs and they were
insulated from foreign competition that hit other industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The automobile industry had the advantage, if you can call it
that, of an early threat,'' said Thomas Allen, a professor of
management at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology who is
co-director of the Lean Aerospace Initiative, an MIT program
supported by the Air Force and many aerospace companies to spread
lean manufacturing techniques across the industry. ``The aerospace
industry hasn't until now had that kind of a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   The term ``lean'' is vaguely defined and refers to many
different techniques. But it generally focuses on manufacturing
things in smaller batches to meet demand, rather than in large
quantities. Parts are delivered just as they are needed and
problems are corrected as they occur. The idea is to cut out
operations, such as storing parts, that do not directly contribute
to the value a company is providing.
</P>
<P>
   Done right, lean manufacturing not only saves time and money
directly, but also helps a company quickly identify flaws in its
overall production process.
</P>
<P>
   Still, what the aerospace industry often calls lean, others
would call common sense, such as preparing kits of necessary tools
in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Northrop Grumman Corp. videotaped a mechanic whose job was to
apply about 70 feet of tape to the B-2 bomber. The mechanic walked
away from the plane 26 times and took three hours to gather the
chemicals, hoses, gauges and other material she needed just to
start. When the factory made kits with all the needed parts, the
mechanic did not have to leave the plane at all and time for the
job dropped to 1.62 hours from 8.4 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting the time needed to design and manufacture aerospace
products could have great economic impact. It now takes so many
years to design and build a fighter that the military threat can
change in the meantime. Commercial aircraft take so long to build
that Boeing has to order parts and materials years in advance. When
it reduces its production rate, as happened recently, it and its
suppliers are stuck with unneeded material.
</P>
<P>
   How much lean production will save is still open to question.
Despite some claimed successes in individual factories, it is
difficult to separate any cost savings from those achieved simply
because of big industry mergers and layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, lean production is no panacea. Boeing is suffering
huge production glitches despite supposedly putting into effect
some lean techniques for years. Skeptics say leanness could become
just the latest in a series of short-lived cost-cutting initiatives
by the Pentagon and its contractors.
</P>
<P>
   James Womack, co-author of ``The Machine That Changed the
World'' (Rawson Associates), the 1990 book that introduced the term
and crystallized the Toyota production system for American
managers, said that aerospace was the industry most in need of lean
approaches. ``It's the most sclerotic industry out there,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Womack, who now runs the Lean Enterprise Institute, a
nonprofit organization, said most companies were merely ``spray
painting'' lean techniques onto their existing procedures instead
of making fundamental changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whole square miles of factories have to be blown up,'' he
said. Pratt &AMP; Whitney, the engine maker owner by United
Technologies Corp., revived itself with such a radical shift, but
most executives are not ready for that, said Womack, who was
dismissed as a consultant to Boeing for being, as he put it,
``disruptive and obnoxious.''
</P>
<P>
   While Boeing would not discuss the reason for Womack's
departure, it said it remained committed to lean manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   The Toyota system, designed for factories that make hundreds of
thousands of cars a year, is not perfectly adaptable to an
aerospace factory that might make only a dozen, highly complex
objects annually. In aerospace, which generally does not use moving
assembly lines, becoming lean means putting jobs that follow in
sequence next to one another.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In many aerospace factories, parts move in big batches to
various centralized production centers _ from metal pressing to
heat treating to cleaning and so on. Parts can travel miles, either
within a factory or around the country to different factories. It
can take years from the time a part is started until it ends up in
a functioning airplane.
</P>
<P>
   But most parts are actually being worked on less than 5 percent
of the time, according to a survey by researchers at MIT. The rest
of the time they sit idle. That contributes to excess inventory,
which takes up capital and is costly to manage.
</P>
<P>
   Here at the Chula Vista factory, which makes parts for engine
housings known as nacelles, work had been done in five separate
buildings spread over a mile. A map of how a part once traveled
through the production process looks like a plate of spaghetti.
Sometimes parts were even packaged in paper and loaded onto dollies
to be shipped from one building to the next, adding time and
expense. The factory was cluttered with excess inventory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years ago I would have been embarrassed to bring a
family member into this plant,'' said Harold Rhodes, a longtime
worker who has moved to factory management.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the company is rearranging production in cells. Instead of
one big centralized degreasing center, for instance, there are now
dishwasher-size degreasers placed where needed in the various
cells.
</P>
<P>
   Metal skins for the Boeing 717 fan cowls, a part of the nacelle,
used to travel 17,000 feet and take 43 days to make. Now they
travel 4,300 feet and are made in 7 days. Two years ago, the
factory could not produce enough parts for even two Boeing 737-700s
a month. It now produces enough for 23, with only 14 employees
instead of 18.
</P>
<P>
   Production is being consolidated in two buildings, so that the
company will be able to give up half the land it is leasing and
still have room to spare.
</P>
<P>
   There are other changes as well. The manufacturing manager and
many engineers have been moved from carpeted office buildings out
onto the factory floor, making them more accessible to workers and
closer to the job.
</P>
<P>
   Layers of management have been flattened and the number of job
classifications, as defined by the union contract, has been cut
from 200 to 28. Workers no longer have to sit idle, unable to do a
nearby job because they lacked the proper classification.
</P>
<P>
   The Toyota production system almost seems as if it were a
religion here, even though only one factory manager ever visited a
Toyota plant in Japan. (The company learned from Toyota's American
operations and from consultants.) The conference rooms above the
factory floor are named after former Toyota officials.
</P>
<P>
   Some workers greeted the introduction of lean production with
suspicion, in part because the word suggested layoffs. Others saw
it as just another passing phase. But most seem to appreciate it
now.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Fugate, the shop steward, said the number of grievances
filed through union procedure had fallen from several a day to only
one or two a month because workers were happier and managers were
more responsive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe my eyes when I go through here,'' said Fugate,
a top representative of the International Association of Machinists
and a 25-year veteran of the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Lean production can lead to job losses. While Chula Vista's work
force has grown to 1,030 union workers from 700 four years ago, it
is benefiting from cuts elsewhere. In December, Goodrich announced
that it would close four factories in its aerostructures division,
eliminating 775 jobs. Some of the work will move to Chula Vista,
such as consolidating assembly of parts once shipped to Arkansas.
This is already occurring here with fan cowls for the Boeing 717.
</P>
<P>
   The division, which includes the Chula Vista factory, was an
independent company called Rohr Inc. until its acquisition in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies, however, are experiencing more worker
resistance to lean manufacturing as well as resentment about the
use of Japanese expressions.
</P>
<P>
   When workers who make composite parts for the Air Force's F/A-18
attack fighter at Northrop's factory in El Segundo, Calif., were
first organized into cells last October, they compared it to the
cells in the Los Angeles County jail, said Joe Geer, a team leader
in the section. But costs and time have been reduced 40 percent
since October, he said, so workers are coming to like it.
</P>
<P>
   Owing in part to lean production, operating profit margin for
Goodrich's aerostructures division has risen to 15.6 percent in
1998 from 9.9 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But Lodge, director of continuous improvement in Chula Vista,
says that rearranging the factory furniture is the easy part. The
big challenge is to apply lean thinking to the company's entire
operations, including the engineers and office workers. One aim is
to speed product design and design products that can be more easily
maintained and manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're scratching the surface,'' said Lodge, who is already
spouting new terms like hoshin kanri (policy management; pronounced
HO-sheen KAHN-ree). ``It's daunting, daunting, daunting. Daunting,
with no alternative.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
