<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATH-PENALTY-2TAKES-     03-08 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATH-PENALTY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH PENALTY OPPONENTS FIND CAUSE FOR FRESH HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ They petition. They pray. They rally. They litigate.
</P>
<P>
   And mostly they lose.
</P>
<P>
   In a movement without generals, the fight to end the death
penalty is left to the foot soldiers: the lawyer in North Carolina
and the laborer in Indiana, the computer worker in Texas, the
electrician in Ohio, the writer in New York, the Roman Catholic nun
in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   But after protesting in futility the more than 500 executions in
the United States in the last quarter-century, the
anti-death-penalty movement sees fresh inspiration for its cause.
The denunciation of capital punishment by Pope John Paul II in St.
Louis, together with the temporary halt on executions in Illinois
and a stay for a murderer in Nebraska, has brought a flicker of
hope to a battle some thought had been lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like there's light at the end of the tunnel,'' said
Lorry Post, a 67-year-old death penalty opponent in Florida. ``It
seems like we're seeing our best chance for a long while.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, that chance is a slight one. Surveys generally show that
at least two-thirds of Americans support the death penalty. And
since Mario Cuomo lost his re-election bid as governor of New York
in 1994, there is virtually no lawmaker with national stature who
speaks forcefully against the state executions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over and over, we lose,'' said Doug Magee, a 52-year-old
writer in New York, who has devoted his career to the issue of
state executions. ``There is this sense of impotency, the feeling
that you're beating your head against the wall. It grinds you down,
but you keep on.''
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to know the precise size of the
anti-death-penalty movement, which includes the volunteers who
collect petitions in little Midwest towns, and the top-shelf legal
teams of groups like the American Civil Liberties Union and Amnesty
International.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of groups, sometimes no more than a handful of people
each, belong to the National Coalition to Abolish the Death
Penalty, an organization in Washington that keeps people informed
about debates and upcoming executions.
</P>
<P>
   The size and power of the movement vary greatly by state, said
Richard Dieter, the executive director of the coalition, noting
that death penalty opponents in California often rely on big-money
contributors and Hollywood supporters, while the movement in Iowa
depends on a strong network of churches. In Texas, which leads the
nation by far in executions, death penalty opponents can scarcely
keep pace with executions.
</P>
<P>
   It does not make it any easier when the political climate makes
opponents of the death penalty seem so far removed from the
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being a black sheep,'' said Patsy Alenik, 65, who
organized protests last year against the execution of Karla Faye
Tucker, the first woman executed in Texas since the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-eight states have the death penalty, although some, like
New York, have not put any inmate to death in more than 30 years.
States without a death penalty are: Alaska, Hawaii, Iowa, Maine,
Massachusetts, Michigan, Minnesota, North Dakota, Rhode Island,
Vermont, West Virginia and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Some anti-death-penalty leaders, lamenting that their movement
has failed to change public opinion in the last generation, have
criticized the traditional tactics, especially focusing on
individual cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five people out vigiling on the corner doesn't help the
movement, it marginalizes it,'' said Carter Van Pelt, 29, the
leader of Nebraskans Against the Death Penalty. ``I don't need to
befriend people on death row, read their poetry or look at their
artwork, to have a philosophical and moral objection to state
killing. These people are murderers. And I want them in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Others argue that some on death row are innocent, as the
Illinois cases demonstrate. These cases, some argue, highlight the
risks inherent in the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Some protests have been highly organized, like the virtual
machine that has developed around Mumia Abu-Jamal, a former radio
journalist who was convicted in the 1981 murder of a Philadelphia
police officer. Abu-Jamal has written extensively about his case
from prison, arguing that the court system is racist, and his
cause, emblazoned on posters across the country, has attracted the
interest of celebrities around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Abu-Jamal, who was granted an indefinite stay of
execution in 1995, demonstrates how some inmates stir passions,
while others languish in obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the stay, an Amnesty International official
acknowledged that Abu-Jamal was ``pulled out of the pack'' partly
because of his profession.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's statement in St. Louis in January _ the most explicit
condemnation of the death penalty that the pope has made in the
United States _ has created the most excitement lately among death
penalty opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no asterisks in the pope's statement,'' said Sister
Donna Schneweis, the head of Amnesty International in Kansas. ``He
was being very clear.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sister Schneweis and others say the pope's action could
profoundly change the political calculus in the national debate,
not just because he heads a church with tens of millions of
American followers, but because of his standing as a social
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a liberal,'' said Sister Schneweis, 40, noting
that conservatives in the Catholic Church have sometimes dismissed
the teachings of nuns and priests they see as being allied with the
political left. ``But the pope is seen as being in the court of the
conservatives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For Catholics who have labeled themselves as part of the
pro-life community,'' especially those who invoke the pope's
support, she added, ``this is a piece they're really going to have
to grapple with.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the anti-death-penalty movement has sometimes
seemed an abstraction, an idea that had no real political
application.
</P>
<P>
   Among people who might be expected to be allies, said Magee, the
New York writer, support for the movement is often lukewarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in leftist circles,'' he said, ``this is seen as a
secondary issue.''
</P>
<P>
   But Magee and others say they see a turning point.
</P>
<P>
   A conference at Northwestern University in November, which
brought together about one-third of the more than 75 people freed
from death row since the nation resumed executions in 1972,
provided a graphic portrait of the irrevocable risks inherent in
the death penalty. One after another, the former death row inmates
told the conference, ``If the state had its way, I'd be dead
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Bar Association called for a moratorium on
executions in 1997, saying the penalty was not being fairly
implemented. In the recent Nebraska case, an American Indian's
execution was halted based on a state constitutional amendment that
calls for equal rights. And the release of 11 death row inmates in
Illinois over a dozen years, two of them in February, has prompted
state officials to issue a moratorium on executions, saying cases
slated for an execution need further study.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, thousands of opponents of the death penalty do
what they have been doing for years.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Miller, a delivery route driver in her 50s, collects
signatures opposing the death penalty in Indiana, even though she
acknowledges that the state Legislature seems steadfast in its
support of executions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do something to counter the bloodthirsty attitude
in this country,'' Ms. Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Van Daneker, a 19-year-old student at the University of
Notre Dame, stands with other opponents of capital punishment
outside prisons, sometimes singing softly, ``Be Not Afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Trafton, a 19-year-old sophomore at Colorado University in
Boulder, is putting together a weeklong schedule of events to
highlight the death penalty, including a rally, panel discussions
and perhaps a concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this is just sitting in a dorm room having a
debate,'' Ms. Trafton said, ``trying to persuade people one at a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Patti Brown, 42, the leader of Iowans Against the Death Penalty,
meets with death penalty opponents in rural restaurants, at church
groups and service clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we only talk to six or eight people, we've left some
seeds,'' Ms. Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lucero, a 53-year-old psychologist in Topeka, Kan., simply
sits down with anybody he can, and explains why he opposes the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was murdered,'' Lucero said, ``and I just don't
think it does any good to kill more people.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
