<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CENTRAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFFERS LITTLE TO CENTRAL AMERICAN NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR _ President Clinton arrived here Monday on a
mission of hope and support for the recovery efforts in the region
despite having little to offer in tangible benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The president began a four-day, four-country trip in Nicaragua,
one of the countries hardest hit by Hurricane Mitch, which
barrelled through the area in October. Nearly a week of torrential
rains caused flooding that uprooted families, killed 9,000 people,
and buried entire communities under mud.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, accompanied by Nicaraguan President Arnoldo Aleman,
knelt at the spot where the imprint in dried mud of the body of a
small girl is all that remains of 2,000 victims who were covered by
a massive mudslide caused by the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``No picture can convey the feeling of seeing the outline of
that small child's body by her grave, and seeing her skeleton,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The visit by the president is intended to soothe anxieties among
many Central American officials that the ongoing struggles to
rebuild may create serious economic and political instability. They
are worried that the slow process of rebuilding may frustrate
victims of Mitch, worsen poverty and threaten to destabilize the
region's fledgling democracies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many bruises that we have to heal, many unpleasant
memories to erase,'' Aleman said at a stop in the village of
Posoltega. ``But we trust in God, in our friends like you, and in
our work and sacrifices.''
</P>
<P>
   But many leaders also hope to have the administration's ear on
other issues important to them, such as immigration and stronger
economic ties.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, 15,000 Salvadorans and Guatemalans who illegally entered
the US after the hurricane but were granted a six-month exemption
from deportation became eligible for deportation. Immigrant
advocates and some members of Congress _ including Massachusetts
Rep. Joe Moakely _ tried to have the exemption extended, but
Clinton has refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have provided temporary immigration protection for Central
Americans in our country and I will seek a fair solution to all the
immigration issues this tragedy has heightened,'' Clinton said in a
speech to about 1,000 people north of the capital city of Managua.
</P>
<P>
   But Salvadoran President Armando Calderon Sol, who greeted
Clinton Monday night when the US delegation arrived in San
Salvador, said a flood of returning refugees ``would cause us
tragic problems in terms of stability.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at the presidential palace in San Salvador last
week, Calderon Sol warned that massive deportations would result in
``an explosion in Central America and in El Salvador,'' and said he
would ask for the same 18-month extension given to immigrants from
Nicaragua and Honduras, which were hit harder.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman said that although deportations were not
expected to begin immediately, the administration argued that the
nations have recovered sufficiently to resume accepting their
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit to the region was the first by an American
president since Lyndon Johnson visited Nicaragua and El Salvador in
1968.
</P>
<P>
   It underscored the political and economic changes that the
region has undergone since the turbulent years of the 1980s, when
nearly all of Central America was immersed in civil wars and Cold
War-era politics. All of the region's seven countries have
democratically-elected governments.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has already spent $305 million for Mitch
recovery in the region and the Clinton administration has been
trying unsuccessfully to get Congress to approve a $956 million
emergency aid package. The measure remained tangled in Capitol Hill
politics over domestic spending.
</P>
<P>
   During his visit Monday to Nicaragua, however, Clinton announced
an additional $120 million in aid, including to repair health
clinics and rebuild damaged schools, and find and remove civil-war
era land mines buried in Nicaragua and Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will announce similar packages at other stops in El
Salvador, Honduras, and Guatemala. But what some officials say they
want more than aid is enhanced trade agreements with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton introduced a proposal to Congress last week that would
increase trade under the Caribbean Basin Initiative. But leaders in
the region, including Calderon Sol, say they want market building
initiatives like the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Candido Cruz, a 51-year-old auto mechanic in Mejicanos, a
northern suburb of San Salvador, said he appreciated the attention
from the American president, but hoped the visit would lead to a
brighter economic future for his country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not everyday that we get a visitor like this,'' Cruz said
on Sunday afternoon. ``He'll see that we're trying to make our
lives better. But maybe he'll see that we can't make it alone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
