<SLUG> BC-DATE-RAPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD WRESTLES WITH DATE RAPE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Content in 12th graf may be offensive to some readers.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has become a familiar problem on campus: one student alleges
rape, the other says it was consensual. Public relations and angry
students demand that the university react swiftly and strongly to
punish the accused and be sensitive to the accuser.
</P>
<P>
   But a group of faculty at Harvard University is standing up to
those pressures, and for the accused, arguing that political
correctness should not get in the way of fairness.
</P>
<P>
   As the undergraduate faculty at the nation's oldest college
votes Tuesday on whether an undergraduate accused of rape should be
dismissed, a small group of faculty, including some women, are
arguing for a lesser punishment, one that would allow the student
to be readmitted to the university. The encounter was consensual
sex, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our rules state there are a range of penalties for rape, and
that range of penalties should match roughly to the commission of
offenses,'' said William Paul, a physics professor and one of the
faculty members proposing the alternate punishment. ``There's a
difference between jumping someone in a dark alley and date rape,
and you've got to calibrate those two together. What we are arguing
is that this gets into one of the categories that is properly
adjudged by going to a lesser penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Many students have responded with outrage, saying that the
alternate proposal proves Harvard's longstanding pattern of
minimizing rape victims' complaints. Students expect hundreds at a
rally outside the faculty meeting, and spent much of the weekend _
Junior Parents Weekend _ getting parents to sign letters decrying
the proposal and demanding that the student be expelled.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of this student ``being allowed to return to Harvard is
very disturbing,'' said Alexis Karteron, a sophomore. ``It just
shows that they're not in tune with what students are thinking.
This person is not someone we want as a member of the Harvard
community.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is especially difficult for a college trying to address
a self-acknowledged ``women problem'' _ one that has left Harvard's
women feeling alienated as students and unwilling to donate as
alumnae.
</P>
<P>
   But the faculty behind the alternative punishment say those
concerns are getting in the way of the rights of the accused.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a problem, that if you say anything that puts some
reponsibility on the woman, it is seen as blaming the victim,''
Paul said. ``And that is what is happening here.''
</P>
<P>
   The faculty say students are demanding the expulsion of the
accused based on innuendo and rumor about the incident. Even the
students admit they do not know the details, because federal
confidentiality laws prohibit universities from making the
students' statements in the case public.
</P>
<P>
   The five faculty members proposing the alternative punishment,
two women and three men on the elected faculty council, say they
will ask their colleagues to agree to lesser punishment based on
the students' statements.
</P>
<P>
   The incident took place in April 1998. According to faculty who
have read the statements, the two students were lying in bed for
about four hours. They had been friends for some time, and had been
drinking much of the evening. There was some sexual interaction at
first, but not intercourse at that point. The woman drifted in and
out of sleep, and as she did, the man penetrated her.
</P>
<P>
   The next day the woman was upset. According to the man's lawyer,
he slid a letter under her door, apologizing and taking
responsibility for his actions. Later, she asked him to meet her by
the Charles, and again he apologized.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was her friend, he felt very bad that he had offended
her,'' said his lawyer, James L. Sultan.
</P>
<P>
   The woman took the case to the college's administrative board,
and in statements and rebuttals, the two agreed that there had been
penetration, and the man took responsibility. The board recommended
dismissal. In Harvard code, that is essentially expulsion, allowing
for readmission only in the unlikely event that significant new
evidence exonerates the student, and the full faculty votes to
allow it.
</P>
<P>
   But the woman wanted him expelled outright. When the board
refused to expel him, she took the case to court.
</P>
<P>
   In court, the man pleaded guilty to indecent assault, which
Sultan characterized as ``improper sexual touching,'' and was
sentenced to 18 months house arrest at his home in Wisconsin, and
five years probation. The rape charge was not heard, and will not
be unless he violates probation. If he returns to Massachusetts, he
must register as a sex offender.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing a student requires a vote by the full arts and
sciences faculty _ with 650 eligible. But at a faculty meeting in
October, the question of whether the incident was consensual proved
so contentious that the faculty tabled the question. The
alternative would be a ``withdrawal,'' which would allow the
student to reapply after five years. The faculty members said they
could not predict whether it would pass.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Baker, a spokeswoman for the college, said Dean Harry
Lewis is recommending nothing short of dismissal. ``We take this
very seriously,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The case and the conflict over the punishment captures the
difficulties of campus rape, even beyond the thorny question of
what constitutes consent.
</P>
<P>
   It is often difficult to determine what happened between two
students _ alcohol is involved, memories become hazy. It is often
difficult to get women to report assaults; they may blame
themselves for subtly encouraging sex, or they may not want to put
themselves through the stress. Campuses try to project an image of
being understanding so that students will feel freer to come
forward.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, they want to be fair to the accused.
But with federal law forbidding them from discussing details of
cases, it is hard to explain to outraged students why the facts
might not present a clear cut case of rape. In the vacuum, gossip
fuels the idea that the school is weak on rape.
</P>
<P>
   The furor over the April rape erupted publicly a few weeks ago,
when a liberal campus weekly published interviews with the rape
victim and another woman whose case has not come before the
faculty. That set off demands from a campus coalition against
sexual violence that the college adopt a firm policy stating that
any student convicted of rape be expelled, and accusations that
Harvard's services for rape victims do not match those at other
schools of its caliber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvard's a pioneer in every other field, if an overwhelming
amount of students are being affected, you need to address it,
bring it up to the rank of your other institutions,'' said Brina
Milikowsky, a member of the coalition. ``I'm suspicious of what
could be behind this proposal. Is it just a backlash against
accusations of rape?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
