<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBEL ARMY IN KOSOVO IS READY TO SIGN PEACE TREATY, U.S. SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The ethnic Albanian rebel army in Kosovo has told
the United States that its leaders are ready to sign a peace
agreement intended to end months of fighting in the troubled
province and to allow for the entry of a NATO peacekeeping force,
the State Department announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The department welcomed the decision but acknowledged that there
was still far to go in the peace effort and that there was no date
for the ethnic Albanians to actually sign the document. The rebels
proved themselves maddeningly unpredictable during peace talks last
month in Rambouillet, France.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I will conclude that the agreement has been signed
when it's been signed,'' said James P. Rubin, the department
spokesman, expressing the wariness of many administration
officials. ``We would want it signed as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   With less than a week to go before the scheduled resumption of
peace talks in France, the peace agreement also has not been signed
by the Yugoslav leader, Slobodan Milosevic, who insisted again on
Monday that he would never accept a settlement that called for the
presence of foreign peacekeeping troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   If the rebel leaders of the Kosovo Liberation Army are true to
their word, the decision to sign the accord would allow the United
States and its NATO allies to raise the diplomatic and military
pressure on Milosevic, whom they have always attempted to paint as
the villain in the fighting in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said that Richard C. Holbrooke, the veteran
diplomat who has served as the Clinton administration's principal
emissary to the Yugoslav leader, was leaving on Monday for Belgrade
to meet with Milosevic and pressure him to join in signing the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The department said that leaders of the Kosovo Liberation Army
conveyed their decision to sign the peace agreement during a
meeting in Kosovo with Ambassador Christopher Hill, the American
envoy to the region. But almost as soon as the announcement was
made in Washington, there was evidence that the guerrillas might
not live up to the promises made on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press said in a report on Monday that it had
interviewed a senior rebel commander, Ramush Hajredinaj, and that
he had vowed not give up his weapons, a key requirement of the
peace plan. Clinton administration officials acknowledged that it
was unclear whether another key guerrilla leader, Hashim Thaci, had
signed off on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me say what we need to do is get the maximum clarity from
the Kosovar Albanian side so that we are in a position to put the
necessary pressure on the Serbs,'' Rubin said. ``The point is that
until an agreement is signed, it's not signed.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bob Dole, who was sent to the Balkans last week as a
White House emissary to the ethnic Albanians, said he spoke by
telephone on Monday with one of the Kosovo Liberation Army
commanders ``who assured me again that they were going to sign the
document.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, well, just sign it, sign,'' he said at a news
conference in Denver, where he was delivering a speech to a local
business group. ``It's frustrating when you should have signed this
in France two weeks ago.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The administration will bring pressure on Milosevic in the
person of Holbrooke, the architect of the 1995 Dayton peace
agreement that ended the war in Bosnia and President Clinton's
nominee to be the chief American delegate to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who hammered out a cease-fire agreement in Kosovo
last fall that has since collapsed, is expected to meet with
Milosveic in Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, on Wednesday. Before
leaving Washington, Holbrooke met at the State Department on Monday
with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to discuss tactics in
dealing with the Yugoslav leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ambassador Holbrooke will convey to the authorities in
Belgrade the necessity for full compliance with all of their
commitments to the international community and for maximum
restraint in the period leading up to the March 15 conference,''
the State Department said in a statement, referring to the planned
resumption of peace talks in Paris next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Senior administration officials, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said that Holbrooke would remind Milosevic in forceful
terms that the United States and its NATO allies still held out the
threat of air strikes against Yugoslav forces if he did not abide
by the peace accord or if there were further human rights abuses by
his troops.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav leader has continued to object strenuously to the
main element of the plan, the deployment of 28,000 NATO-led
peacekeepers to Kosovo, including 4,000 American soldiers. On
Monday, the official Yugoslav news agency quoted him as saying that
any political accord for Kosovo must ``exclude foreign troops.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Clinton administration has said that the presence of a
NATO military force in Kosovo is non-negotiable, a viewpoint also
expressed on Monday by Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain during
a ceremony in London to mark the 50th anniversary of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make an agreement work, to bring stability to Kosovo, an
international force is an indispensable element,'' he said.
``Political agreement is not enough. The Balkans are littered with
agreements that are signed but not implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaker of the House J. Dennis Hastert announced that he had
scheduled a debate in the House this week on whether American
troops should be included in a peacekeeping force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become increasingly clear that the president is
planning to send approximately 4,000 U.S. troops to Kosovo in
support of a negotiated interim agreement,'' Hastert said in a
letter to House members. ``I have admitted frankly to the President
and his senior advisers that I have reservations regarding the
wisdom of deploying additional U.S. troops to the former
Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has said that while it welcomes
expressions of support from Congress for the deployment of American
soldiers to Kosovo, the move does not require a congressional vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
