<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY STOCKS SURGE, BLUE CHIPS DROP 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks were mixed Monday as technology issues surged
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index set a new high. But
blue-chip securities, which soared to new records on Friday,
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a consolidation type of day'' for the stocks that make
up the Dow Jones industrial average, said Bryan Piskorowski, a
market analyst at Prudential Securities. ``But there is pent-up
demand for technology stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said a number of factors were helping to power big-name
technology issues like Microsoft, Cisco Systems, EMC and Intel.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate catalyst Monday was word that Intel and the
Federal Trade Commission had reached a tentative agreement to
settle the FTC's suit against the chip maker.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, however, a broad array of technology stocks were
battered in February and early this month, as investors were jarred
by worries about earnings as well as rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``These stocks had a sharp decline, and it kind of put a damper
on them,'' said Richard McCabe, chief market analyst at Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co. ``I guess they were entitled to a bounce-back, and the
Intel news was sort of a trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   At the close, the Nasdaq composite index was up 60.50, or 2.6
percent, to 2,397.61. The index is well below its all-time high of
2,510.09, set on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Strength in technology shares and in energy stocks helped to
push the S&AMP;P 500 index to a record close of 1,282.73, up 7.26
points, or six-tenths of 1 percent. Oil stocks like Exxon gained on
speculation that weekend talks between Iran and Saudi Arabia could
spur production cuts by members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries, or OPEC, later this month.
</P>
<P>
   After rising so sharply late last week, analysts said it was not
surprising that the Dow Jones industrials took a bit of a breather.
The Dow closed at 9,727.61, down 8.47 points.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume on the New York Stock Exchange was fairly light,
at 714.6 million shares. On the Nasdaq market, 970.6 million shares
changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   Among individual issues, word of the Intel settlement lifted the
stock 5, to 119 5/8. Shares of Intel recorded a high of 140 15/16
on Jan. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Other big-cap technology issues also soared. Microsoft gained 4
1/16, to 159. Cisco Systems was up 3 3/4, to 104 9/16. Dell
Computer gained 2 3/8, to 45 3/8. Hewlett-Packard, a Dow component,
climbed 1 3/4, to 69 7/8. And EMC soared 6 7/16, to 111, a new
high.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks also moved sharply higher. TheStreet.com's
Internet index gained 37.07, or 7 percent, to 571.43.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement late Monday from Advanced Micro Devices may
cause doubts about the sector's earnings power to reappear.
</P>
<P>
   After the market closed, Advanced Micro, a chip maker that has
been gaining market share but losing money in the process, said it
would report a significant loss for the current quarter and would
cut about 300 jobs over the next two quarters as part of a
restructuring program.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Advanced Micro closed at 18 15/16, up 1/2; in
after-hours trading, it slipped as low as $17.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's push into record territory last week, and its weak
retrenchment Monday, had traders and analysts speculating about
when the index would broach the 10,000 level.
</P>
<P>
   McCabe, the Merrill Lynch analyst, expects that to be
accomplished in the next couple of weeks. But unless the
composition of the market changes, a move above 10,000 probably
will not last long, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless the market broadens out, I think you have two or three
weeks of advance to work off the technical overselling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But going through 10,000 itself would not mean much. It's a
nice, big, round five-digit number, but unless there is breadth
accompanying it, it wouldn't mean much. Often these rallies above
big magical numbers tend to be anticlimactic.''
</P>
<P>
   The last three times the Dow has broken through a new 1,000
barrier, it has inched a bit higher and then fallen back, McCabe
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless the breadth gets better, the same may be true here,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
