<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS DEBATE POPULAR `ED-FLEX' BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate bogged down in debate Monday over
whether to earmark $11 billion to hire more teachers as lawmakers
tried to wrap up a bill to give local school districts more
flexibility in spending federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 54-41, the Senate refused along party lines to
allow Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., to attach the teacher amendment
to the so-called ``ed-flex'' measure.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans accused the Democrats of playing politics with the
popular ed-flex bill _ which has the support of all 50 governors
and most Democrats and Republicans _ to push through some of
President Clinton's favorite education proposals. They said there
would be plenty of time to vote on the teacher spending measure
when Congress takes up the education reauthorization bill later
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is being held hostage ... to the political agenda of
Democrats,'' said Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H. ``It is inappropriate, to
say the least, because everybody supports this ed-flex bill.''
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle described the cloture
vote as ``a referendum on whether we want to reduce class size,''
and predicted that the Republican leadership would continue to
oppose Clinton's plan to hire 100,000 more teachers over the next
seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Republicans view this as Democrats trying to invoke
some sort of an agenda here on education,'' Daschle said. ``It has
nothing to do with an agenda as much as it has to do with a
senator's right to offer a legitimate education amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite opposition from Republicans, Murray insisted that her
amendment was ``necessarily timely,'' as she put it, because school
districts are in the process now of deciding what their budgets
will look like for next year. She said for senators to suggest that
more funding for teachers will be considered later in the year is
an empty commitment that no governor or school district
administrator will rely on, given Congress' record of not
delivering on some of its promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need a commitment now so they can put those budgets
together and hire those teachers,'' said Murray, a former teacher
who has long been an advocate of hiring more teachers to help
reduce class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Debate on the ed-flex bill started off last week in a
noncontroversial way, with both sides hailing it as a step forward
in reducing federal restrictions on education money that the states
receive each year. But Senate Majority Leadert Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
told his colleagues Monday that it's in danger of ``being bogged
down'' in fights over various amendments that both Democrats and
Republicans are now trying to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a raft of amendments starting that threatens to
unravel the bipartisan agreement on ed-flex,'' Lott said. He warned
Democrats that unless they back off on their attempts to amend the
bill, Republicans ``will have no choice but to introduce amendments
of our own.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's free the ed-flex bill,'' Lott declared.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., however, said Democrats are
worried that the ed-flex bill may well turn out to be the only
vehicle for ``serious debate on education for the whole year''
because the current education spending bill doesn't expire until
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The ed-flex bill, as it stands now, does not contain any new
funding for education. It would simply allow states and local
school districts to spend up to $12 billion in federal aid to the
states as they see fit. Modeled after a pilot program begun several
years ago in 12 states, it would grant waivers to all 50 states
that allow them to experiment with spending without the hassle of
federal red-tape.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over ed-flex is expected to continue for two more
days and spill over into the House later this week when a similar
measure is introduced there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
