<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MARATHON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIND OVER MATTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Someone once asked Jeremy NC Newman what he would do if he lost
the use of his legs, and he thought about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he said, ``I rely on the use of my legs for
everything I do . . . I'd probably put a gun in my mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks later, it happened.
</P>
<P>
   A skydiving accident left the 31-year-old Reseda resident with a
ruptured aorta, two collapsed lungs, head trauma, a spinal-cord
injury as well as broken bones and torn muscles. He had to be
resuscitated twice. Within a few months, he was back at work as a
personal trainer but was now wheelchair bound.
</P>
<P>
   Newman redirected his passion from extreme sports such as
skydiving, bungee jumping and motorcycle riding. On Sunday he
competes in his second L.A. Marathon. The race is part of his
preparation for a transcontinental triathlon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was faced with that (reality), (suicide) wasn't an
option for me, because I'm not a quitter,'' Newman said. ``I don't
give up. I look at what's happened to me as just one in a series of
hurdles that I have to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York native played competitive sports all his life. He
was on the rowing team at Columbia University and went into the
personal-training business 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The skydiving incident occurred during Memorial Day weekend
1997. Newman's plan was to release the ashes of his recently
deceased cat in what he calls ``my favorite playground.'' His first
jump of the weekend was his last. He has no memory of the accident
or the month that followed, but believes he hit a thermal, which
sucked the air out of his parachute and sent him into a free fall.
</P>
<P>
   While Newman recovered, his co-workers at the Sherman Oaks gym
where he still works trained Newman's clients and gave him the
money. His job was waiting for him whenever he was ready. The gym's
continued support of Newman includes purchasing special equipment
to help him train and allowing him time off for endeavors such as
the triathlon that starts next month. The cross country event is
expected to last two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big inspiration,'' said Lance Fessler, the gym's owner.
``He shouldn't be alive. When I saw him in the hospital and the way
he looked, I never thought he'd be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some of his clients had doubts after he returned to
work, Fessler said no one questions Newman's ability now.
</P>
<P>
   When he's not training others, Newman spends the majority of his
time training himself. He competed in four marathons as an
able-bodied athlete. He always thought about triathlons but never
attempted one prior to the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in his current situation, even though he enjoys his
occupation, the aspirations he had before he was in a wheelchair
are still there,'' Fessler said. ``This is a good way for him to
fulfill them.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman finished last year's L.A. Marathon in 2 hours, 42
minutes. He hopes to break 2:30 this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dictate what my body's going to do,'' Newman said. ``I don't
let my body dictate what I'm going to do. By convincing myself that
the pain I'm experiencing is temporary, I can keep going. If I
convince myself that I can't stop, not only because I've got so
many people expecting me to do it, but also because I've got this
other thing coming up in a month. It's just another challenge that
I refuse to give into.''
</P>
<P>
   He's using his participation in the marathon and triathlon to
benefit his other love: children. Newman is raising money for the
the Try 4 Life organization and the Challenged Athletes Foundation,
which purchased his racing chair. He hopes his participation in the
events inspires disabled children and other people with the bleak
outlook he once possessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that I thought (after the accident) was that my
life was over,'' Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really have not only adjusted well to my situation, but I
really have embraced the fact that I'm in a wheelchair. My life is
completely changed and I love it. I love my new life and love who I
have become.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
