<HEADLINE>
A CLEMENCY CASE PUTS A GOVERNOR ON THE SPOT
</HEADLINE>
   (See also DEATH-PENALTY) 
(sw) 
 By SHIRLEY CHRISTIAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Little more than a month after bowing to a
plea from the pope and commuting the death sentence of a confessed
triple killer, the governor of Missouri faces the clemency petition
of a condemned man who has submitted to a lie detector test to
buttress his claim of innocence.
</P>
<P>
   The test, given on Feb. 19 to Roy Roberts, who is to be executed
early Wednesday morning for the fatal stabbing of a prison guard,
showed no deception in his denial of involvement. It was
administered by a former officer on the police force here who was
described by Roberts' lawyer, Bruce D. Livingston, a federal public
defender, as a ``reputable, well-respected polygrapher not known as
defense-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   The killing for which Roberts was sentenced to death occurred
during a riot in 1983 at the Moberly Training Center for Men, about
midway between Kansas City and St. Louis. Roberts, who was then
serving an 18-year sentence for an armed robbery in St. Louis four
years earlier, was charged with holding the guard, Thomas Jackson,
while other prisoners killed him.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, now 45, contends that he could not have had a role in
the slaying because he was brawling with another guard when it
occurred. At the trial, Livingston's clemency petition notes, this
guard confirmed that he and Roberts fought during the melee,
involving 25 to 30 prisoners. But three other guards identified
Roberts as the man who had held Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston says these three guards failed to identify Roberts
when the state initially investigated the riot. They did so, he
says, only after they underwent hypnosis in an intense pretrial
effort by prosecutors. ``Such `evolving' testimony is inherently
suspect,'' Livingston said in the clemency petition, delivered to
Gov. Mel Carnahan last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 28, Carnahan, a Democrat who supports capital
punishment, commuted the death sentence of Darrell J. Mease to life
in prison without parole, granting the personal appeal of Pope John
Paul II, who had just visited St. Louis. Mease, who had admitted
killing a 19-year-old paraplegic and that victim's grandparents,
was widely considered a very weak candidate for clemency. But he
was the prisoner next scheduled for execution in Missouri, and the
pope, in a demonstration of the church's opposition to the death
penalty, urged the governor to spare his life.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Ashcroft, a Republican whom Carnahan intends to
challenge in the elections next year, criticized the governor's
decision. Although the senator has said nothing about the Roberts
case, Livingston's clemency petition urged the governor to show
``courage'' and said he hoped that ``fear of additional political
fallout will not prevent Governor Carnahan from granting clemency
in this much more deserving case.''
</P>
<P>
   When Carnahan acted in the Mease case, he had allowed 26
executions to proceed during his six years in office and had
granted clemency only once. Since then, he has allowed one
execution, that of James Edward Rodden, put to death on Feb. 24 for
the fatal stabbing of a woman in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   In the Roberts case, Livingston argues, the outcome of the lie
detector test and conflicting witness accounts justify clemency, or
a delay of sentence for further investigation.
</P>
<P>
   His argument has received strong support in recent days from a
long editorial and a column in The St. Louis Post-Dispatch. Bill
McClellan, a columnist for the paper, reported that it was possible
that Roberts was innocent not only of the prison killing but also
of the robbery for which he had been sent to prison in the first
place. McClellan quoted an old acquaintance of Roberts as having
said in an interview that he himself had committed that robbery,
which involved restaurant receipts of $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston said Roberts had insisted on taking the lie detector
test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous about his doing it,'' Livingston said. ``I told
him, `If you fail, it's all over.' I also told him we had to have
it done by someone whose reputation will mean something to the
governor. Roy said: `I don't care. I didn't do this.'''
</P>
<P>
   The man who administered the test was Donald I. Dunlap, who
before retirement served for 30 years in the Kansas City Police
Department. Dunlap's written report says that Roberts showed ``no
deception'' in his answers denying involvement in the killing and
that he specifically denied holding the victim during the stabbing.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts was one of three prisoners charged with the killing of
Jackson. All &UR;  &LR; the defendants' lawyers won changes of venue out of
the town of Moberly, where the prison is situated, and each of the
trials was held in a venue different from the others. In one case,
Rodney Carr, identified by guards as having stabbed Jackson, was
sentenced to life in prison. In another, Robert Driscoll was
sentenced to death, but his conviction was overturned after it was
discovered that there was no blood on the knife he carried during
the uprising; he awaits a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who was not armed, was charged with grabbing the
victim, pulling his hair and forcing him against a window as the
stabbing ensued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus, Roberts is the only person who was sentenced to death
for the crime, even though he is the least culpable, even under the
state's version of the evidence,'' Livingston's petition said.
``This disproportionality pales in comparison, however, to that
which arises if, as we contend, Roberts is indeed innocent of the
crime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
