<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2512 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DIMAGGIO-BICKERING     03-08 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIMAGGIO-BICKERING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR AND MAYOR BICKER OVER HOW TO HONOR DIMAGGIO 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also OBIT-DIMAGGIO, BBO-DIMAGGIO-STREAK, BBO-DIMAGGIO-COLUMN,
BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN, BBO-DIMAGGIO-OLDSTERS, BBO-DIMAGGIO-HOMETOWN) 
(lh) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The mourning and the tributes for Joe DiMaggio had
hardly begun Monday when a rhubarb of sorts swirled up _ this one
with political overtones _ over renaming a New York City highway
for the Yankee Clipper.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani wanted it to be Manhattan's West Side
Highway, while Gov. George Pataki was said to favor the Major
Deegan Expressway in the Bronx. In Albany, a bill that might have
settled the matter _ the mayor's way _ was held up, apparently
because neither side wanted an unseemly brouhaha on a day of
solemnity for DiMaggio's family and multitudes of fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will work out with the city, with the Yankees, the
appropriate tribute at the appropriate time,'' the governor said
when asked about the rival plans at a news conference in Manhattan.
Pataki, effusively lauding DiMaggio, said his family should also be
consulted.
</P>
<P>
   The governor did not express a preference or even acknowledge a
difference with the mayor over which road to rename. But an aide to
Pataki, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the Major Deegan
was the obvious choice because it runs past Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was anything but obvious to the mayor, however. For months,
as DiMaggio's health has faded, Giuliani, a longtime New York
Yankee fan and DiMaggio devotee, has pressed his case for renaming
the West Side Highway after DiMaggio. He cited it in his State of
the City address in January. And at his behest, state Sen. Serphin
Maltese, R-Queens, introduced a bill to get it done.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative aides said that talks among leaders of the
Republican-controlled Senate, the Democratic-controlled Assembly
and the governor's office had concluded that any change should be
ceremonial, rather than formal, because the latter would
necessitate changing hundreds of road signs.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver of Manhattan agreed to sponsor
the bill, and until recently it seemed that both houses were ready
to pass it. Then, the aides said, Pataki's office objected, saying
it had encountered opposition from West Side residents. Assemblymen
from the West Side said they had heard no such objections, however.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side seemed concerned about the honor of Major William
F. Deegan, an architect who served in the Army Corps of Engineers
in New York in World War I, and later as Mayor James Walker's
commissioner of tenement housing. He died in 1932, and political
friends gave his name to the expressway completed in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   There was, as usual, a subtext to the Giuliani-Pataki
disagreement. The mayor's Joe DiMaggio Highway would run down the
Hudson River shore past the sprawling West Side site where Giuliani
has proposed a major sports complex with a domed stadium _ and
which he had once touted for a new Yankee Stadium, an idea he has
since backed away from.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's Joe DiMaggio Highway would run down the Bronx bank of
the Harlem River, right past Yankee Stadium, which the governor has
favored keeping in the Bronx. Geopolitics aside, the governor has
often quietly contradicted the Mayor in a rivalry that goes back to
Giuliani's endorsement of Gov. Mario Cuomo in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the differences, the mayor's bill had picked up support
in both houses recently, and legislative leaders had made tentative
plans to release it from committee and have it put to a vote in the
wake of DiMaggio's death.
</P>
<P>
   But the plans were put on hold Monday. Some officials cited
Pataki's opposition; others said Giuliani had asked for the delay.
It was clear that neither wanted to seem combative on a day of
mourning. But it was also clear that neither was backing down.
</P>
<P>
   As he extolled ``the personification of Yankee pride,'' the
mayor said, ``I'm comforted, as are all New Yorkers, that we
informed him before he died that the West Side Highway will be
renamed the Joe DiMaggio Highway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
