r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLAN     03-08 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY'S MRI SHOWS ONLY MUSCLE STRAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ The Angels breathed a collective sigh of relief
Monday after learning the results of pitcher Chuck Finley's MRI
were normal.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels decided Finley would have the MRI because of
continued discomfort and stiffness in his upper back and neck. But
with nothing wrong other than the initial diagnosis of a muscle
strain, Finley will continue to get treatment. However, there is no
timetable for his return.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no big spurs, no disc problem, it was just
normal,'' trainer Ned Bergert said. ``He might toss a little bit
(today). Basically, it's `spring-training neck.' When he feels his
shoulder is ready, he and (pitching coach) Dick Pole will decide
when it's time to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does not start a Cactus League game by this weekend, his
opening-day start would be in jeopardy. But Finley might jump into
the starting rotation within the first five games, meaning he
really wouldn't miss a start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck Finley deserves to be the opening-day starter,'' Angels
manager Terry Collins said. ``If he can't, we won't worry about it.
Once we start the season, it doesn't matter as long as Chuck's out
there in the rotation and we run him out there 35 times. That's all
that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Joltin' Joe remembered: Joe DiMaggio's death didn't come as a
surprise but made some reflect on the type of hitter he was. Angels
hitting coach Rod Carew, a seven-time batting champion and Hall of
Famer, said he doesn't expect to see another hitter come along like
DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's probably on a team up there with all the Yankee
legends,'' Carew said. ``He's got to be one of the best (hitters of
all-time).''
</P>
<P>
   As far as DiMaggio's record 56-game hitting streak, Carew said
it's not likely to be broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' said Carew, whose longest hitting streak
was 25 games. ``With all the specialty of today's game, it's going
to take someone special to do it. But we didn't think someone could
hit 70 homers either.
</P>
<P>
   ``(In order to break the record) it's going to take a line-drive
hitter, a guy who can bunt for a base hit if he's struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started playing baseball in the '50s, DiMaggio was the
guy everybody talked about,'' Collins said. ``Everybody was going
to be compared to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariners manager Lou Piniella played for the Yankees and met
DiMaggio several times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always enjoyed when Joe would come over to our clubhouse and
talk to us when I was there,'' Piniella said. ``He talked about the
championship clubs and it was always a thrill for me. He epitomized
what baseball is all about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
