<SLUG> BC-U.S.-CRUISESHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SHIPYARD TO BUILD 2 LARGE PASSENGER VESSELS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A shipyard in Mississippi is planning to announce
on Tuesday that it will build two cruise ships, the first big
passenger ships built in this country since 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Ingalls Shipbuilding of Pascagoula, Miss., a subsidiary of
Litton Industries, and American Classic Voyages Inc., based in
Chicago, plan to announce a contract for the shipyard to build two
1,900-passenger cruise ships, for $440 million for use in the
Hawaiian Islands, according to people involved with the deal. The
contract includes an option for four additional vessels.
</P>
<P>
   American Classic Voyages already operates one cruise ship in the
Hawaiian Islands, the S.S. Independence, the only cruise ship that
flies an American flag. The two new ships will also be registered
in this country, which is a requirement for picking up and
discharging passengers in U.S. ports without visiting a foreign
port in between.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for agreeing to order the ships, Congress gave
American Classic Voyages special rights that will make it difficult
for other companies to join it in the Hawaiian cruise market. With
those rights, included in a 1997 military appropriations bill,
Congress reaffirmed 19th-century rules that limit the presence of
foreign-flag carriers. Foreign carriers can continue to take
passengers between Hawaii and the West Coast by stopping in Canada
or Mexico in between, or can stop in Hawaii on trans-Pacific
voyages.
</P>
<P>
   American-flag ships must be built and registered in this
country, use an American crew, be owned by Americans, and meet
certain Coast Guard regulations. Such ships are much more expensive
to build and operate, and most oceangoing ships that maintain
American-flag status do so because the cargoes they carry must
travel on American-flag vessels.
</P>
<P>
   The existing American-flag ship, the Independence, made its
maiden voyage in 1951, although she has been refurbished twice in
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The last two big passenger ships built in this country were the
Brasil and the Argentina, both built for Moore-McCormack Lines, in
1958, according to George C. Devol, the publisher of Ocean and
Cruise News, a monthly magazine published in Stamford, Conn. The
two new ships, he said, will ``probably be the largest ever built
in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Most passenger ships are built in Finland, Italy, Germany or
France. One industry executive said that the two ships could have
been built for about 20 percent less in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of Ingalls' current business is ships and submarines
for the U.S. Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials are expected to be present at the announcement on
Tuesday. Defense officials say the civilian contract will reduce
the shipyard's dependence on military procurement. The 1997
appropriations bill also included $250,000 for initial design, but
not construction, of civilian ships.
</P>
<P>
   The two ships, each 72,000 gross tons and 840 feet long, have
not yet been named; the company refers to the construction of both
as ``Project America.'' The first is scheduled for delivery in
2003.
</P>
<P>
   While the first two are expected to cruise within the Hawaiian
Islands, if more are ordered, they could provide the only direct
routes from West Coast ports to Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   American Classic Voyages, which also operates paddle wheel boats
on the Mississippi River, is controlled by the investor Sam Zell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
