<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW IMF AID PACT FURTHER RESTRICTS BRAZIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ The Brazilian government and the
International Monetary Fund announced a revised loan agreement
Monday that commits Brazil, Latin America's largest economy, to
more stringent conditions for receiving further aid.
</P>
<P>
   The new accord, reached after more than a month of negotiations,
requires this country to produce a bigger budget surplus than was
initially agreed upon and restricts the Brazilian central bank's
ability to spend dollars defending the value of the real, the
national currency.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil and the IMF originally signed a $41.5 billion rescue
package in November aimed at helping the country avoid the kind of
economic collapse that has ravaged Asian and the Russian economies.
The accord was aimed at applying pressure on Brazil to reduce
spending and ease increasingly burdensome debts.
</P>
<P>
   But the Brazilian decision in January to end controls that had
kept the value of its currency artificially high against the dollar
led to a decline of nearly 40 percent in the currency's exchange
value. The currency decline caused notable increase in interest
rates and inflation and required a resetting of the IMF's
performance targets from last fall.
</P>
<P>
   The new agreement calls for Brazil to increase its budget
surplus, excluding interest payments on debt, to 3.1 percent of the
gross domestic product, compared with 2.6 percent agreed upon
previously.
</P>
<P>
   It also requires Brazil to reduce overall public debt to a level
below the 46.5 percent of the gross domestic product specified in
the original agreement. The new level has not been specified.
</P>
<P>
   Once approved by the IMF's board, the new agreement will enable
Brazil to draw on a second aid installment, worth $9 billion, from
the loan package agreed upon in November. Although the money is not
expected to be deposited until early in April, assurances of the
new financing are seen as giving an important psychological boost
to investors and creditors here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Arminio Fraga, the new president of the central bank, said last
week that he intended to use part of the IMF loan to protect the
real against speculative selling, by purchasing reais with dollars
in the foreign-exchange market. But the terms of the accord just
reached limit the bank's ability to intervene in the currency
markets, establishing a ceiling of $3 billion this month, $2
billion for April and $1.5 billion each for May and June.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of the announcement of the revised agreement,
the real strengthened slightly Monday in light trading on Brazilian
currency markets, settling at 1.97 to the dollar after dropping as
low as 2.22 to the dollar last week. Brazil's main stock index rose
3.39 percent in Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech Monday morning, President Fernando Henrique Cardoso
described the revised agreement as an important step in restoring
confidence in the economy. ``The accord will set the conditions for
a resumption of growth in our economy, a revaluation of our
currency, encourage exports and finally, it will put Brazil on the
right track,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview with Epoca magazine published Monday,
Cardoso also warned the nation's nearly 165 million people that
``the first half of 1999 is going to be very tough.'' Indeed, the
agreement foresees a decline of as much as 4 percent in economic
activity this year and inflation of just under 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Brazil's inflation rate in 1998 was below 2
percent, and as recently as mid-January Finance Minister Pedro
Malan was predicting that it would remain ``in single digits'' this
year. Hoping to calm fears of a spurt of price increases, Fraga
said at a news conference Monday that he intended ``to repeat ad
nauseam'' a single phrase: ``central bank, low inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   With the new agreement in hand, Fraga, a former aide to
financier George Soros, along with Malan and other senior members
of the government's economic team, are to leave this week for
meetings with bankers in the United States, Europe and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Their objective is to regain access to foreign credit, which has
all but dried up in the last two months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
