<SLUG> BC-MCDOUGAL-TRIAL-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SUSAN McDOUGAL BACK IN ARKANSAS FOR TRIAL  
(sw) 
 By STEVE BARNES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ A still-defiant Susan McDougal returned to
Little Rock on Monday to stand trial on charges she attempted to
block the Whitewater investigation by refusing to tell a grand jury
about the personal and political finances of President Clinton and
his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As she has for more than four years, Mrs. McDougal, who was
jailed for 18 months after a federal judge cited her for civil
contempt for an earlier refusal to cooperate, maintains that the
independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, is interested only in
statements from her that would incriminate the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   She has said she has no such information and that, despite a
grant of immunity, she feared being charged with perjury should her
statements not meet Starr's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become a personal vendetta'' on Starr's part, Mrs.
McDougal told reporters on Monday morning as she made her way into
the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   But W. Hickman Ewing, Starr's principal deputy in the Arkansas
phase of the investigation, said: ``We have to show that she had
relevant information and withheld it, and we're prepared to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal and her lawyer, Mark Geragos of Los Angeles, have
long promised to turn the tables and place Starr on trial,
insisting that his investigation is politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted her to lie,'' Geragos said. ``She wouldn't do it,
and she's innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal's present difficulty has its genesis in
Whitewater, the 20-year-old Arkansas real-estate venture that has
become an umbrella term for Starr's investigation of the Clintons
and several of their Arkansas associates.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal and her former husband, James B. McDougal, were
convicted in 1996 in a fraud conspiracy case in which Jim Guy
Tucker, a former Arkansas governor, was also found guilty.
</P>
<P>
   The McDougals and the Clintons were partners in the Whitewater
resort, which federal prosecutors have said hastened the collapse
of a federally insured savings and loan association owned by
McDougal, who died last year while serving a federal prison
sentence for his conviction. Neither of the Clintons was charged.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's investigation spread into Clinton's conduct in the White
House after it was revealed that the president had a liaison with a
White House intern, Monica Lewinsky, and sought to conceal it.
</P>
<P>
   Court papers show that among the questions Mrs. McDougal refused
to answer was whether Clinton had testified truthfully when he
rebutted a prosecution witness who said that Clinton, while
governor of Arkansas, pressured him to make an improper $300,000
loan to Mrs. McDougal.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said at Mrs. McDougal's trial that a portion of the
loan was illegally diverted to the Whitewater project, which, like
McDougal's savings and loan, ultimately failed.
</P>
<P>
   Upon finishing her 18-month jail term for civil contempt last
year, Mrs. McDougal had barely begun the two-year prison sentence
she received for her fraud conviction in the Whitewater trial when
she was set free by the Federal District Court judge who sentenced
her, George Howard Jr. Howard said he had become convinced that
Mrs. McDougal's continued incarceration would aggravate a
degenerative spinal disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal was acquitted of embezzlement charges in
California in an unrelated case stemming from her employment
several years ago as a bookkeeper and personal assistant to the
symphony conductor Zubin Mehta and his wife, Nancy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Under questioning on Monday, prospective jurors expressed
conflicting views of Starr, the president and Mrs. McDougal.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion of Kenneth Starr is that he has, at all costs,
pursued President Clinton, and has sacrificed a great deal in that
pursuit,'' said one potential juror, a white man in his 30s.
</P>
<P>
   But another prospective juror said that Starr had been
``misunderstood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I disapprove of Bill Clinton,'' the man said. ``I consider him
an ultra-liberal, almost a socialist.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as for Mrs. McDougal: ``She could have talked. She could
have avoided this whole thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
