<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2524 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-IMPACT-NYT &LR;      03-08 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-IMPACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH SIDES APPEAR TO HAVE EMERGED WITH PARTIAL VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With INTEL-ANTITRUST) 
(sw) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The government's proposed antitrust settlement with Intel Corp.
is viewed as a careful compromise that seeks to clarify the ground
rules for how a powerful company can wield its intellectual
property as a weapon in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Both Intel and the Federal Trade Commission, according to
industry executives and antitrust experts, seem to have emerged
with partial victories. And both sides, they say, had incentives to
reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The precise terms of the planned settlement have not been
disclosed, but the agreement does set guidelines for when Intel has
to disclose its technology to other companies. The FTC complaint
contended that Intel, the dominant producer of microprocessors that
power personal computers, had unfairly withheld its technical
information from the Intergraph Corp., the Compaq Computer Corp.
and the Digital Equipment Corp. (now a division of Compaq) as a
bullying response to patent disputes it had with the three computer
makers.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1980s, the courts have tended to protect the right of
dominant producers to use their patents to exclude competitors. The
three companies cited in the FTC complaint, however, are customers.
And the issue that most alarmed the commission staff and its
chairman, Robert Pitofsky, according to people close to the case,
was that Intel was cutting the computer makers off from trade
secrets they needed to bring new products to market.
</P>
<P>
   Intel routinely provides this advance information to computer
makers in thick books marked ``Highly Confidential'' and coded by
color _ yellow, orange and red, with red being the most
confidential. ``It was pulling back the trade secrets that the FTC
felt was too strong a move by Intel,'' one person close to the case
said.
</P>
<P>
   The government's concern over that form of retaliation, industry
analysts say, is understandable. ``Intel essentially has the power
to devastate a personal computer company by refusing to deal with
it on the same terms as other computer companies,'' said Michael
Slater, the principal analyst for Microdesign Resources, a research
firm in Sebastopol, Calif. ``If a company does not get the prior
disclosure from Intel, it will trail way behind its competitors in
getting products to the market.''
</P>
<P>
   That is precisely what happened to Intergraph, a maker of
powerful work stations using Intel chips after it filed a patent
infringement suit against Intel in November 1997, according to the
FTC. And it took the company several months to make its work
station products competitive with rival products after a federal
judge ordered Intel last April to treat Intergraph the same as it
treated other customers, said Keith Britnell, an Intergraph
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has not disputed the facts in the FTC suit but asserted
its right to withdraw access to its intellectual property from
companies that were suing it. Antitrust experts say that while
Intel was aggressive in cutting off the three customers, the chip
maker's use of its intellectual property as a negotiating tool was
common in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after Jack Kilby, an engineer for Texas Instruments,
invented the integrated circuit in 1958, the industry realized that
patent disputes could hobble this emerging high-technology
industry. All new semiconductor designs build on earlier, patented
technology, so rather than getting bogged down in endless court
cases two industry practices emerged.
</P>
<P>
   First, the major semiconductor makers, including Intel, National
Semiconductor and IBM, all agreed to broad cross-licensing pacts _
``the intellectual property equivalent of mutually assured
destruction,'' one industry executive noted. Second, the standard
industry practice became for the major companies to invoke their
intellectual property claims mainly ``defensively,'' if they were
sued.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that ``a pretty efficient barter market in
intellectual property has become part of the foundation of the
semiconductor industry,'' observed Mit Spears, a former general
counsel of the FTC, who is a partner of Shook, Hardy &AMP; Bacon in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   With its settlement, the FTC apparently wants to avoid any
heavy-handed intervention that would threaten the industry's brisk
trade in intellectual property. Still, it does ``want to insure
that there is a more democratic sharing of information in the
semiconductor industry,'' said Richard Doherty, president of
Envisioneering, a technology research firm in Seaford, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Intel seems to have received the assurances that
its concessions would not devalue its intellectual assets. In a
statement on Monday, Craig Barrett, president of Intel, noted
pointedly, ``We are satisfied that the agreement gives us value for
our intellectual property rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel, according to a person close to the case, was most
concerned that any settlement with the government not force it to
disclose what it calls ``definition stage'' technology development
_ products that might be two or three years from the market. By
contrast, the company was more willing to compromise on
intellectual property that was at the center of the complaint,
which was sharing information with customers on chips that would go
into computers in three to six months.
</P>
<P>
   The commission had its own reasons for being willing to reach a
settlement. Antitrust is meant to protect competition and
consumers, while the FTC complaint focused on Intel's dealing with
its customers _ not rivals or potential rivals who might challenge
Intel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply playing hardball is not an antitrust violation,'' said
Carl Shapiro, a professor at the University of California at
Berkeley. ``You have to show an actual effect on competition or a
likely effect on competition in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By settling this case,'' added Shapiro, a former senior
official in the Justice Department's antitrust division and a
consultant to Intel, ``the commission avoids putting the debatable
theory behind its complaint to the test.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 2126EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
