<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2528 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-ANTITRUST-1STLD     03-08 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-ANTITRUST-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. REACHES TENTATIVE SETTLEMENT WITH INTEL IN ANTITRUST SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to correct to to 'Monday' sted `this morning' in 12th graf;
changes to `today' sted 'Monday' in 6th graf)  (ART ADV: Graphic _ highlights in Intel's past and its growth in
market share _ is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(wg) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Trade Commission announced Monday that
it had reached a tentative settlement of its antitrust suit against
Intel Corp., the world's largest producer of computer chips, a day
before opening arguments were set to begin in the case.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was Intel's refusal to share technical details of its
microprocessor chips with companies that build computers unless
those companies agreed to turn over their own technologies in
exchange. The government suit asserted that such practices violated
federal antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   Microprocessors are the brains of computers. Without information
about how the chips work, manufacturers cannot design their next
generations of personal computers and work stations. As part of the
proposed deal, Intel agreed to abide by an order that prohibits it
from pressuring computer manufacturers to turn over their own
technology in exchange for technical information about Intel's
chips, people involved in the case said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Although government officials and Intel executives said they
could not disclose the precise terms of the proposed settlement
until it had been formally submitted to the Federal Trade
Commission, officials did say that it achieved the purpose of the
lawsuit. Lawyers for the commission had asked an administrative law
judge to order Intel to end its practice of withholding valuable
technology from computer manufacturers as a weapon in patent
disputes with those companies. The government had not sought
monetary penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission sought to establish a principle, and the staff
believes the proposed agreement achieves that goal,'' said Victoria
Streitfeld, the agency's top spokeswoman. ``The staff got the
relief it wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel's clout in the industry is derived from the fact that its
microprocessors power more than 80 percent of personal computers in
use today. Although it has lost some market share to competitors in
the last two years, it still sets the technological standards for
the chip industry with each new generation of its Pentium
processors.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Justice Department's trial against Microsoft
Corp., the Intel case has been widely viewed as among the most
significant antitrust lawsuits in recent years. The two companies _
known as the ``Wintel duopoly'' because of their domination of the
personal computer industry with Microsoft's Windows operating
system and Intel's microprocessors _ have been accused of
maintaining monopolies in their respective industries by stifling
competition and bullying computer makers, who are their biggest
customers.
</P>
<P>
   In the Intel case, government lawyers accused the company of
stifling innovation by existing and potential rivals by trying to
force three other companies _ Compaq Computer Corp., Digital
Equipment Corp. and Intergraph _ to surrender their patent rights.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has acknowledged that it withheld information about its
chips from the three companies. However, Intel executives said that
practice was not part of a larger effort to coerce rivals into
giving up technology but a legitimate defense in response to patent
claims asserted by those companies.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed order at the center of Monday's agreement contains
specific provisions that describe when it would be appropriate for
Intel to withhold such technology in the future, said lawyers and
others involved in the case who spoke on condition of anonymity. By
setting guidelines that determine when cutting off customers is
based on a valid business decision rather than as part of a
monopolistic scheme, the agreement provides a clarity that Intel's
executives and lawyers found to be particularly attractive, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   While the proposed settlement, once approved, will resolve a
government case that some antitrust experts said could have gone
either way as a matter of antitrust law, the deal provides several
significant benefits for Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Barrett, president and chief executive of Intel, issued a
statement Monday morning praising the proposed deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view this compromise agreement as a win-win for both
parties, and we are satisfied that the agreement gives us value for
our intellectual property rights,'' Barrett said. ``This is
acceptable to both parties and was the result of constructive
dialogue between Intel and the FTC.''
</P>
<P>
   The company will avoid the spectacle of a two-month trial that
could have become a public forum for airing its dirty laundry.
Intel executives and lawyers had been closely watching Microsoft
take a public relations beating in its antitrust case in a federal
district court here. That suit was filed by the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   With Intel taking the position that it was not a monopoly, FTC
lawyers were preparing a legal strategy similar to that employed by
Justice Department lawyers in the Microsoft case. That strategy
entailed introducing as much evidence as the lawyers could find to
support assertions that the company used strong-arm tactics to
dominate the chip business.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, as part of the proposed agreement, the commission staff
reached no legal conclusion that Intel is a monopoly, a finding
that would have had significant legal and practical consequences
for the company in other cases. Incriminating evidence in the FTC's
case, for instance, could have been used in a separate civil case
brought against Intel by Intergraph, a producer of specialized
computer workstations.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, Intergraph has accused Intel of fraud, theft of
trade secrets and anti-competitive conduct. Last year, the federal
district judge hearing that case tentatively concluded that Intel
had engaged in monopolistic practices. A trial in that proceeding
is set to begin next February.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Intel's shareholders applauded the proposed agreement. The stock
closed at $119.625, up $5 a share, in heavy trading, and it was
widely credited with boosting much of the technology sector,
driving the Nasdaq up 60.51 points, or 2.6 percent, to 2,398.62 on
a day when the Dow lost ground.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the tentative settlement announced Monday does not close
the FTC's books on other Intel inquiries. Government officials
emphasized that issues arising out of a broader investigation that
has been under way for the last year have yet to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   There are remaining issues under investigation by the
commission,'' said William Baer, director of the agency's bureau of
competition, which brought the case that was settled Monday. The
commission's staff is committed to working expeditiously to resolve
those concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency has been examining a variety of Intel's business
practices, including the contract restrictions imposed on customers
through nondisclosure agreements, Intel's control of industry
standards and the special pricing arrangements and restrictions
required of computer makers as part of Intel's highly successful
``Intel Inside'' marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers said that Monday's proposed settlement will permit
the agency merely reassigned the lawyers involved in the lawsuit to
focus more heavily on other aspects of the agency's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Federal Trade Commission has not disclosed the details
of the proposed settlement, computer makers and Intel rivals said
they could not assess its long-term impact on the computer
industry. But they said that any restraints on Intel's dominance of
the industry could only help encourage competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that is a settlement that forces Intel to make
concessions basically supports the case that we have filed,'' James
Meadlock, the chairman and chief executive of Intergraph, said
shortly after emerging from a briefing at the Federal Trade
Commission here. ``It has to be a positive development for our
case.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Siekman, senior vice president and general counsel at
Compaq, which last year acquired Digital Equipment, also praised
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident that the interests of Compaq, Intel and our
customers will be satisfied through the ultimate approval of the
settlement by the FTC,'' Siekman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
