<HEADLINE>
KINGS SELF-DESTRUCT AS DUCKS MOVE AHEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At times when visiting the Pond, it is easy to forget that you
went there to watch a National Hockey League game.
</P>
<P>
   Maple Leaf Gardens, this ain't.
</P>
<P>
   Stuffed animals roam the stands, lasers beam, and when Mighty
Ducks goalie Guy Hebert makes a routine stop on an unscreened
75-foot lob by an opposing team's fourth-liner, a few fans shriek
as if they'd just seen Dominik Hasek stone Jaromir Jagr in the
seventh game of a playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the Pond these days is the site of the most
compelling hockey seen in these parts in six years, since Wayne
Gretzky and his crew led the Kings on their two-month march to the
Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   When the officials actually get around to dropping a puck, Paul
Kariya and Teemu Selanne _ and a solid supporting cast _ are
putting on a show.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks have chemistry, they have skill and, at the moment,
they have a club-record seven-game winning streak. They aren't
going to win the Stanley Cup or even reach the finals, but at the
moment, they hold the promise of a fun ride on a dark horse when
the playoffs begin in six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When everybody believes you can beat anybody,'' Selanne said
the other day after the Ducks beat the Stanley Cup champion Detroit
Red Wings, ``you have a really strong team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks believe.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe that one short year ago, the Ducks were
enduring an abysmal season and the Kings were heading to the
postseason. The reversal of fortunes for the local teams provide a
vivid example of just how fragile success is.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, Kariya has stayed healthy, new coach Craig
Hartsburg has built good chemistry and taught a sound defensive
system, Hebert often has been impenetrable, defenseman Fredrik
Olausson has contributed 14 goals, the power play is the best in
the league, many players not named Kariya and Selanne are making
major contributions, and the Ducks are beating the teams they're
supposed to beat.
</P>
<P>
   Remove any one element and maybe it all falls apart. Right now,
it's working.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've still got a long way to grow,'' Hartsburg said. ``We're
a young team. A lot of the players are still learning. As a group,
we're still trying to gain more confidence and stay on the path we
have to stay on, and that's hard, simple hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Stay cool: Rob Blake's dismay at the state of the Kings is
understandable. Here's hoping he doesn't let it get the better of
him.
</P>
<P>
   Blake's hotheaded response to a third-period high stick by
Calgary's Clarke Wilm killed any hopes the Kings had of rallying
against the Flames. Whether referee Mick McGeough made the correct
call _ assessing Blake an instigator penalty for retaliating with a
hail of punches _ is immaterial.
</P>
<P>
   And Blake sent a discouraging message to his teammates after the
game when he defended his actions by saying, ``We're far enough out
of the playoff hunt that you're not going to sit there and take
that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they wake today, the Kings are only seven points out of
the playoffs with 18 games left. They have two games remaining with
San Jose, the team they are chasing. It is unlikely the Kings will
make the playoffs, but they are not so far out that they can take
the attitude that anything goes.
</P>
<P>
   __ Sigmund Fraud?: The Flyers were 16-1-7 from Dec. 16 to Feb.
6, but since then, they've posted a record of 2-9-3.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia general manager Bob Clarke swung into action,
recalling goalie Jean-Marc Pelletier from the minors to fill in for
struggling John Vanbiesbrouck.
</P>
<P>
   Also, before a game against Ottawa, Clarke called in team
psychologist Dr. Joel Fish to address the players. Fish's powerful
words had this effect: The Flyers lost to the Senators 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   __ Waning Gretzky:Not including Monday night's game against
Toronto, the New York Rangers were 4-0-1 since Wayne Gretzky left
the lineup and Petr Nedved began centering the first line. The New
York Daily News conducted a survey of its readers, asking the
question, ``Are the Rangers better off without Gretzky as the No. 1
center? Of the 315 readers to cast votes, 61.6 percent said yes.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fleury-less Flames:The big question now that Theoren Fleury
is with Colorado is whether he will stick to his word and test free
agency on July 1. If he does, the Kings are expected to be among
the bidders for his services.
</P>
<P>
   Avalanche general manager Pierre Lacroix said, ``I told his
agent (Don Baizley) that the next few months will give us a chance
to talk about (a contract), and he totally agreed. We know Theo is
in a unique situation, with a chance to be a total free agent, and
we respect that. But as far as we are concerned today, the thrill
that we have is that he is going to bring to our club what we need
to have to try and accomplish our ultimate goal (the Stanley Cup).
That's why we did it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
