<P>
   SEATTLE-SPILL (Seattle) _ The Alaskan activists who accurately
warned of a major oil spill before the 1989 Exxon Valdez disaster
brought a message to Seattle on Monday: It could happen here. They
argued that Puget Sound residents should demand the same safety
measures _ notably tug escorts _ put in place after Prince William
Sound was fouled by 11 million gallons of oil. The wreck of the
freighter New Carissa, whose oil-laden bow was being towed out to
sea for the second time, was cited as evidence that the Pacific
Northwest is not ready to quickly deal with a marine accident in
which a ship loses power or runs aground.
</P>
