<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOVERNMENT AND INTEL REACH ANTITRUST SETTLEMENT
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission reached a tentative settlement with
Intel, the world's largest producer of computer chips, a day before
opening arguments were set to begin in the Government's antitrust
suit against Intel. Although government officials and Intel
executives did not announced the precise terms of the proposed
settlement, it does set out guidelines for when Intel has to
disclose its technology to other companies. Intel's refusal to
share technical details of its microprocessor chips with three
companies was at the heart of the government's complaint.
</P>
<P>
   CHAIRWOMAN NAMED AT THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Beers, often called the most powerful woman in
advertising, is becoming a top leader at a giant agency for the
third time. Effective immediately, Ms. Beers is joining J. Walter
Thompson in New York as its chairwoman. Her two previous stints as
a chairwoman were at Euro RSCG Tatham in Chicago and Ogilvy &AMP;
Mather Worldwide in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ALLIED WASTE FOCUSES ON GROWTH
</P>
<P>
   Allied Waste, which will be the No.2 trash hauler behind Waste
Management, with its $7.3 billion leveraged takeover of
Browning-Ferris _ plus the assumption of $1.8 billion of
Browning-Ferris debt _ is betting that its integrated and focused
approach to handling solid waste can produce high-double-digit
profit growth. Market Place.
</P>
<P>
   SONY PLANS TO CUT 17,000 JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Sony said it would eliminate about 17,000 jobs, or 10 percent of
its work force, by March 31, 2003, and buy back shares in
subsidiaries, turning them into wholly owned units, to increase
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   FORTIS TO ACQUIRE MIAMI INSURER
</P>
<P>
   Fortis, one of the biggest insurance and banking companies in
Europe, said that it would buy American Bankers Insurance Group, a
Miami insurer that was the object of a bidding war by two big
American companies last year, for $2.6 billion plus the assumption
of nearly $200 million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN, SACHS VOTES TO GO PUBLIC
</P>
<P>
   The partners of Goldman, Sachs reaffirmed their decision to take
the firm public but learned that the man behind the plan, Jon S.
Corzine, left, would leave as soon as the firm sold shares,
probably by this summer. Henry M. Paulson Jr. will remain as the
chairman and chief executive. The firm hopes to sell 10 percent to
15 percent of its shares at a price that would value the firm at
$21 billion to $25 billion.
</P>
<P>
   CIT GROUP TO BUY TORONTO CONCERN
</P>
<P>
   The commercial finance concern CIT Group said that it would
acquire Newcourt Credit Group, a Toronto company, in a stock swap
valued at about $4.2 billion. The deal will create one of the
largest commercial finance companies in the country.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-EUROPE BANANA FIGHT WORSENS
</P>
<P>
   The United States accused the European Union of worsening a
fight over banana imports by failing to provide the World Trade
Organization with data needed to determine sales lost by American
companies in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS MIXED; S&AMP;P SETS RECORD
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were mixed as technology issues surged and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index set a new high, rising 7.26 points, to
1,282.73. The Nasdaq composite index rose 60.51 points, or 2.6
percent, to 2,397.62. The Dow Jones industrial average took a bit
of a breather, closing down 8.47 points, to 9,727.61.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices were little changed as the yield on the benchmark
30-year issue fell to 5.59 percent from 5.60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   SIEMENS ANNOUNCES PUSH INTO U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens of Germany became the latest European maker of
traditional telephone equipment to push into the market for data
communications gear when it announced that it had acquired two
private United States companies and invested in a third.
</P>
</TEXT>
