<HEADLINE>
CENTER-FIELD COLLISION A SETBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ Trenidad Hubbard is considered the
Dodgers' fifth outfielder. And Hiram Bocachica is trying to unseat
him. On Monday, the two collided in left-center field at Fort
Lauderdale Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, neither one will be able to prove his worth
for the next few days after both were taken to Coral Springs
Medical Center for precautionary X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard, the center fielder, escaped with a bruised right thumb
and a contusion on the right side of his forehead. Bocachica,
playing left field, walked gingerly to a waiting ambulance with an
ice pack on his right side. He has bruised ribs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like my ribs are broke,'' Bocachica said. ``I called
and he said he called it. He said maybe we called it at the same
time. I don't really know what happened, then I was just lying on
the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Both players' X-rays were negative and they returned to
Dodgertown with team photographer Jon SooHoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't hear me at all,'' Hubbard said. ``I called and the
ball was coming back toward me because it was a right-hander
hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   The first Dodger on the scene was shortstop Mark Grudzielanek,
who said he didn't hear either player call for the ball but added
that the gusting wind made it difficult to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ran right into each other. It was Trenidad's head into
Bocachica's ribs, and Bocachica's knee hit Trenidad's thumb,''
Grudzielanek said. ``I thought both of them were kind of dizzy at
first.''
</P>
<P>
   Hairston wound up with an inside-the-park homer.
</P>
<P>
   __ Young has MRI: Second baseman Eric Young, bothered by a stiff
lower back, underwent an MRI on Monday afternoon. Results are
expected today.
</P>
<P>
   Young is the only projected starter not to appear in the
Dodgers' four spring- training games. His back has been bothering
him since last week, but he has improved enough to take grounders
and hit in the batting cage the last two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a continuation,'' Dodgers physical therapist Pat
Screnar said. ``Dr. (Frank) Jobe just wanted to have the test and
check it out.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Park's pleased: Right-hander Chan Ho Park has devoted some of
this spring to working on his change-up, a pitch that could make
his fastball seem almost unhittable.
</P>
<P>
   In his spring-training debut he pitched three innings and
allowed one unearned run against the Orioles, and he did so by
using his change-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to improve my confidence in the change-up,'' Park
said. ``I felt good and had good concentration. I had a good curve
and a good change-up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
