<HEADLINE>
SIEMENS SPENDS $550M FOR 2 MASSACHUSETTS FIRMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Siemens A.G., the giant German telecommunications and
electronics firm, Monday said it had acquired two Massachusetts
start-up companies to help it enter the lucrative market for data
networking and Internet communications.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens confirmed it acquired Argon Networks Inc. of Littleton,
a 2-year-old developer of data switches, and Castle Networks Inc.
of Westford, which builds networking equipment that can more easily
separate voice and data calls.
</P>
<P>
   The two firms will form the core of a new Siemens subsidiary, to
be based in Burlington. Sources close to all three companies said
Siemens spent about $240 million in cash for Argon and about $310
million for Castle Networks.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's venture capital investors reaped a bonanza, receiving
about $160 million from Siemens after investing $18.25 million over
the last 13 months. Most of the remaining $150 million will go to
Castle Networks' founders and a good portion of the company's 70
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike its North American rivals, which have grown substantially
by acquiring a mix of telecom start-ups and established companies
to gain a significant market share and brand identity among
telephone carriers in the United States, Siemens is a relative
latecomer to the fast-moving field of voice, data, and Internet
products.
</P>
<P>
   And while Siemens has strategic product development and
marketing partnerships with 3Com Corp. and others, it is reportedly
spending around $1 billion in cash to buy companies developing
voice and data networking products that its 26,000-strong worldwide
sales force can sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have crafted a string-of-pearls strategy, where we will
acquire small companies with the kinds of technology, products, and
people we need in Boston and in Silicon Valley,'' said Thomas
Rambold, president of the broadbands networks unit within Siemens'
Public Networks Group, which is based at company headquarters in
Munich.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens also said it has invested $30 million in return for a 20
percent stake in Accelerated Networks Inc. of Moorpark, Calif.,
which is creating a switch to quickly capture voice and data.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies, along with some existing Siemens operations
in Florida, Canada, and Germany, will become the core of a new,
wholly owned subsidiary called Unisphere Solutions Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The new company _ the first not to carry the Siemens name _ will
have 500 employees, most of whom will continue to work at existing
facilities and at Siemens plants, according to Martin Claque, the
Unisphere president. Claque previously worked as vice president of
IBM's global industrial-solutions sales unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I foresee us doing about $200 million (in sales) within two
years,'' Claque said.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Anderson, president of the Yankee Group of Boston,
questioned whether Siemens was ``late by three years'' in pursuing
its data networking and Internet strategy, following competitors
such as Lucent Technologies Inc., Northern Telecom Ltd., and Cisco
Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Lucent bought Ascend Communications Inc., and
Northern Telecom acquired Bay Networks last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a real player, Siemens has to aim higher and try to go
after 3Com,'' said Anderson, citing how other European and American
telephone-equipment manufacturers have pursued bigger companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
