<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILL-PROSECUTORS-CHARGED-475&AMP;ADDS(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILLINOIS TRIAL EXPECTED TO JOLT CRIMINAL JUSTICE SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs lede for rewriting; moves 8th graf up to become 3rd graf;
tightens writing in 2nd take)   (wg)  
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In a case being closely watched by lawyers and
investigators, a group of seven prosecutors and sheriff's deputies
are to go on trial on Tuesday on charges that they conspired to
frame an innocent man.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, charged with perjury and conspiring to obstruct
justice, are accused of knowingly using false evidence or
withholding evidence in order to convict a man of the 1983 rape and
murder of a 10-year-old girl in DuPage County, outside Chicago. The
man, Rolando Cruz, was exonerated in 1995 after spending 10 years
on death row when one of the sheriff's officers recanted his
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the charges involve allegations that deputies fabricated
a story that Cruz had told him about a detailed dream he had had
about the slaying, and that prosecutors presented that testimony
knowing it was false. Other charges contend that a prosecutor
failed to tell defense attorneys that another lawyer had told him
in 1985 that a client admitted to killing the girl.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say it is almost unheard of to put prosecutors on trial
for these kinds of offenses, in part because it is considered so
difficult to covincingly explain to a jury why prosecutors would
accuse someone if they had doubts about the person's guilt. If the
prosecutors in this case are convicted, experts said, they would be
the first prosecutors found guilty of a felony for this kind of
prosecutorial misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is extremely rare,'' said Ron Allen, a professor of
criminal law at Northwestern University, who added that this case
was different from accusations of bribery or corruption that have
resulted in indictments of prosecutors in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``This prosecution emerged out of the everyday actions of the
prosecutors,'' Allen said. ``When you're solving a crime,
especially a crime like the one they were investigating, you have
to make difficult decisions often based on ambiguous information
and those decisions are what led us here. The fact is, the system
makes mistakes; and the question being asked here is, how do you
deal with those mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is hard to track cases going back decades, a search by
the Chicago Tribune turned up only six other instances nationally
in this century in which prosecutors have faced criminal charges
alleging similar misconduct. Of those prosecutors, the newspaper
reported, two were convicted of misdemeanors and fined $500; two
were acquitted; and charges were dropped against the other two
before trial.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The trial here will offer an unusual look inside the process
that prosecutors and the police go through when tackling a
complicated investigation, in this case one of the area's most
grisly and frightening murders, one that law enforcement officials
were under tremendous pressure to solve.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation and prosecution of Cruz were unwieldy and
bedeviled from the outset. Cruz was someone who initially was
courted by detectives as a source of rumors about the killing. He
was not indicted until 13 months after the murder. Nine months
after Cruz was arrested, a detective resigned after expressing
doubts about the case. In 1992, a lawyer in the Illinois attorney
general's office in charge of fighting Cruz's appeals, resigned,
saying she believed Cruz was innocent.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is coming at a difficult time for the Illinois justice
system, which has seen 11 death row inmates freed after
investigations found evidence of their innocence. Defense attorneys
and critics of the criminal justice system across the country say
this case may pull a veil off unacceptable prosecutorial and
investigative practices that they believe are not uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   Some prosecutors worry that the case could have a chilling
effect, causing prosecutors to hesitate as they second-guess their
actions. Others say these allegations, if true, are an aberration.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Kent Schaffer, director of the National
Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers, said ``the important thing
about this case is it's going to tell prosecutors that they are not
immune from prosecution if they hide evidence, if they suborn
perjury or if they go after somebody who has not committed the
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear whether the special prosecutor in the case,
William J. Kunkle Jr., known for prosecuting John Wayne Gacy, the
serial killer, will argue that some or all of the defendants knew
Cruz was innocent, or honestly believed he was guilty but cut
corners to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   The men, known as the DuPage Seven, have all pleaded not guilty.
The parents of the murdered girl, Tom and Pat Nicarico, are
supporting them.
</P>
<P>
   The four sheriff's officers, James T. Montesano, Thomas E.
Vosburgh, Dennis Kurzawa, and Robert L. Winkler, are still working
for the sheriff's department. One of the former prosecutors,
Patrick J. King Jr., is now an assistant U.S. attorney in Chicago.
Another, Thomas L. Knight, has a private law practice; and the
third, Robert K. Kilander, is a DuPage County judge.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The DuPage Seven case emerged out of the long, intricate
prosecution of Cruz, now 38, and another man, Alejandro Hernandez,
now 35, for the sexual assault and murder of Jeanine Nicarico, who
was home alone from school with a cold one February day when
someone kicked in the front door of her house in the affluent town
of Naperville and abducted her. Her body was found two days later
in a wooded area about six miles away and the crime, in a suburb
hardly used to such inexplicable violence, stunned the community.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was also convicted of the murder, sentenced to death
and then, in a second trial three years later, sentenced to 80
years in prison. He, too, was exonerated in 1995, but a judge ruled
that the DuPage Seven case should focus only on allegations in the
Cruz case.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those allegations involve the main strategy used to
convict Cruz and Hernandez: testimony by two of the sheriff's
deputies, Vosburgh and Kurzawa, that Cruz told them he had had a
dream about Jeanine's killing and revealed details the deputies
said only the killer could know.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz and his lawyers have repeatedly said that the deputies
fabricated the dream, and that there was no written investigator's
report about it. In 1995, in Cruz's third trial (his two previous
convictions had been overturned on appeal), another sheriff's
officer, Montesano, said he had testified falsely that the deputies
had informed him about Cruz's dream. As a result, the judge
acquitted Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   Vosburgh's lawyer, Brian Telander, said on Monday that he would
present testimony from six of the grand jurors who originally
indicted Cruz, all of whom say that, although there is no written
record, Cruz babbled to them that he had had a dream about the
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler is charged with falsely testifying that Cruz told him
about acquiring and disposing of a car used in the murder. King and
Knight are accused of presenting the false testimony, knowing it
was false. Kilander is charged with failing to inform defense
attorneys that a lawyer for a convicted child rapist and murderer
named Brian Dugan had told him that Dugan admitted to killing
Jeanine.
</P>
<P>
   Kilander's lawyer, Ronald D. Menaker, suggested that his client
had fulfilled his obligation because he had told defense attorneys
about an interview he had with Dugan shortly after he talked with
Dugan's lawyer. Lawyers for the other defendants either declined to
comment or did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Dugan, serving a life sentence for two rapes and murders, was
linked to the Nicarico murder by DNA testing in 1989, but has not
been charged in the case. He has said he will only talk with
authorities if they promise to spare him from execution.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say Kunkle and his team have a tough task ahead of them.
They will not only have to prove that the sheriff's deputies
fabricated evidence, but that the prosecutors knew the evidence was
false. They also have to convince a jury to believe _ over the
assertions of upstanding law enforcement officers _ the contention
by Cruz, known at the time to be a street punk, that he never
described a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got very difficult problems because he's trying some
people of significant stature who are well-respected,'' said
Terrance A. Norton, a former federal prosecutor who is now a
clinical professor of law at Chicago-Kent College of law.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest job of all, however, may be to make the case that
the prosecutors, perhaps because they were under pressure to solve
a horrifying crime, behaved in a way that was criminal and not just
mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a difference between incompetent prosecutors and
criminal prosecutors,'' Allen of Northwestern said, ``and I think
that's going to be difficult to prove.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
