<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2566 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMEDY-FESTIVAL-2TAKE     03-08 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMEDY-FESTIVAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO DECODE THAT ENIGMA CALLED HUMOR, AND FAILING GLEEFULLY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASPEN, Colo. _ At one point, the question before the group was
whether there was any subject too dark to be claimed by humor. The
Holocaust? Cross burning? AIDS? And Martin Short, the actor and
sketch comedian, brought up the case of Doug Tracht, aka the
Greaseman, the radio shock jock who was fired by a Washington
station after playing a song by the Grammy winner Lauryn Hill, a
black singer, and dismissing the music with a reference to the
racially motivated murder of a black man in Jasper, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``No wonder people drag them behind trucks,'' the Greaseman said
on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Joyner, an actor, stand-up comic and the only black person
at the table, shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't funny, though,'' he said. ``You could talk about
that and have it be funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Janeane Garofalo, the actress and comic, put in, ``You mean find
the joy in it?''
</P>
<P>
   Short said: ``But that's the question. Was it not funny because
it could never be funny?''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner said: ``Depending on how you say it, you can say
something funny that's racial without angering black people.'' He
paused briefly, and laughed. ``I do speak for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Short looked mock curious. ``And why would that be?''
</P>
<P>
   And the others around the table _ the playwright Neil Simon, the
film and television director James L. Brooks, the actress and
director Penny Marshall, and the stand-up comic Moon Zappa _
convulsed in giggles. The moment, which had been serious and
threatened to become tense, swiveled as the group members returned
to an informal discussion. And although they hadn't settled the
issue of taboo _ not even for themselves _ the point had been made
that the question of what is or is not funny is hugely informed by
context: time, place, circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion, which was organized at the request of The New
York Times, took place on Friday night here at the U.S. Comedy Arts
Festival. The event, in its fifth year, is a jamboree of comedy
performances, films and entertainment-industry panels, sponsored by
HBO. This year, Simon was honored with the festival's annual
writing award, Brooks was honored by the American Film Institute,
and SCTV, the comedy troupe that Short helped found in the 1970s,
was featured in a tribute. (Jerry Seinfeld and Larry David,
creators of the ``Seinfeld'' television show, were also honored,
but declined to participate in the panel.)
</P>
<P>
   With participants ranging in age from 31 (Ms. Zappa) to 71
(Simon), the subject, ostensibly, was ``What's funny now?'' But it
became perfectly clear that no one really knew. So it was obviously
a bad question. After all, if THEY didn't know, who would?
</P>
<P>
   At a tribute to Brooks _ the director of films like ``Broadcast
News'' and ``As Good as It Gets,'' and the creator of the
television series ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show'' and ``Taxi'' _ the
audience howled at the screening of a 1970 episode of ``Mary Tyler
Moore'' in which her character tries to stay calm in a job
interview in the early days of feminism while being hounded by her
prospective boss, Lou Grant (Edward Asner), about her personal
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Afterward, I was talking to Jay Sandrich, who directed that
episode,'' Brooks said. ``And we were amazed at how funny people
still think that is.'' Asked if the audience members were laughing
out of nostalgia, because they recognized the period, the
58-year-old Brooks was certain they weren't. ``Period is never
funny,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What emerged from a wide-ranging, wisecrack-filled,
profanity-saturated 90-minute chat is that what makes people laugh
is a mystery, and that the art of comedy is the quest, lifelong for
these people, to solve it. One issue that returned was taboo, and
if there is such a thing as a subject beyond humor.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks called ``Life Is Beautiful'' ``a movie about the comic
spirit,'' and said he was dumbfounded by criticism from people
offended by what they have perceived to be its lighthearted
treatment of the Holocaust. Ms. Garofalo, who had not seen the
film, said a friend was offended.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt that as a subject there was no way to put a positive
spin on it,'' she said, to which Brooks responded, ``I swear to
God, when you see the film, you'll drop the friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zappa said, ``I don't think I've ever seen something so
joyful,'' and Simon was lukewarm on the movie, but not because of
its subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it the subtitles?'' Short asked.
</P>
<P>
   So can you make a joke about dragging someone behind a pickup if
it is clever enough?
</P>
<P>
   ``The flip side of this Greaseman thing would be if he had some
really boffo great jokes about being dragged behind the truck or an
HIV guy staggering around,'' Short said, thinking out loud. ``I
still don't think it would play.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said, ``It's impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon agreed. ``Impossible,'' he said. ``And about the
Holocaust, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But Joyner, who is 37, sounded another note. ``You can tell a
joke if it happened to you,'' he said. ``You'd have to live through
it in order to write jokes about it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Simon reiterated, ``No, I'm positive you can't.'' Then he
paused. ``Well, it depends on what kind of truck it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Brooks waffled. ``Wait a minute,'' he said. ``If Richie
Pryor was the person being dragged, I can conceive of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zappa suggested a contest. ``We should take out an ad and
find someone who can make being dragged or HIV funny.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Garofalo, sheepish and prompted by Ms. Zappa, intoned in
the voice of a radio pitchman, ``Have you been dragged or had
HIV?''
</P>
<P>
   And the group convulsed again.
</P>
<P>
   What was evident throughout the discussion was how the comics
engaged one another, listening with interest and seemingly genuine
curiosity. This was particularly true when the talk turned to their
generational comedic worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Garofalo, 34, said the boom in the comedy business, with
clubs overflowing with copycat comics seeking their own sitcoms,
had lowered audience expectations and poisoned the circuit for
serious comedians. But Simon seemed surprised that there had even
been such a boom. And when Ms. Garofalo and Ms. Zappa discussed the
emerging venues for alternative comedy _ ``I sometimes drive
through the streets on a flatbed truck,'' Ms. Zappa said _ Brooks
asked for the names of places he could visit.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation worked the other way as well. Ms. Marshall, 55,
played Laverne on the television show ``Laverne and Shirley'' and
has directed films like ``Big'' and ``A League of Their Own.'' She
recalled that in the early '70s, when she was married to Rob
Reiner, gatherings in their living room would include the likes of
Brooks, Albert Brooks (who is no relation), Charles Grodin and
Harry Shearer, who did bit after bit for one another. The younger
comics on Friday's panel seemed entranced as if by a fairy tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim, Albert, they were all at my house,'' Ms. Marshall said.
``You would've loved it. I didn't talk. Only the guys talked.
Everyone was very successful, but no one talked about that. No one
was saying: `You have a top show'; `you're the head writer.' They
were all just spritzing, playing off each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks recalled the scene as well. ``I remember Harry Shearer
getting up with Rob, just doing straight for Rob,'' he said, ``and
it would be like a concert, people playing musical instruments and
jamming. And we were all just in her living room.''
</P>
<P>
   Less discernible were generational attitudes about what
constitutes appropriate material. The younger comics came of age in
a performance era distinctly less civil than that which fostered
Simon, Brooks and Ms. Marshall. Enactments of sex, bodily functions
and criminal behavior are all regularly on display; there were many
examples at the weekend festival.
</P>
<P>
   The work of Ms. Zappa, whose father was Frank Zappa, the
literate and often shocking rock musician, shows that she has
inherited her father's gift for challenging, profane wordplay. In
discussing shock comedy, she seemed to shock many at the table with
a simple confession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was brought up in a bizarre household,'' she said. ``My
earliest memories are of women wearing black masking tape on their
nipples offering me a baby bottle. So when a comic wants to take
his penis out on stage, this is so boring for me. I truly like the
mundane. I like people being absolutely themselves. The stuff
that's shocking to people means they didn't have enough craziness
in their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Short jumped in. ``That's true,'' he said. ``There's something
often condescending about trying to shock the audience. `See, I'm
so hip and you're so square, and I'm going to do this and you're
going to freak out and run.'''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said: ``But why talk about what's bad? Some people did it
great, people who broke through and did things no one ever did
before. Andy Kaufman raised it to an art form.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zappa smiled sweetly. ``Hello, half-full,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, continuing to be an optimist, generated the liveliest
debate when he asserted of ``There's Something About Mary,'' a film
by Peter and Bobby Farrelly, that ``You almost can't not talk about
that movie if you're talking about comedy now.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon agreed: ``It is so today.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Garofalo added, ``Somehow, it works shockingly well.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics were cooler on the film, believing that even though
there were many successful, broad jokes, it didn't hold together
and its overall spirit was childish. Of its two famous jokes, one
is about a boy in a bathroom who catches his penis in a zipper, the
other about a bodily fluid that ends up as hair gel. The discussion
that ensued was lively.
</P>
<P>
   Simon: ``It wasn't consistent, but when it was funny, it was
really funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks: ``I just think it has more big jokes in it than anything
I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marshall: ``How many people came into the bathroom before
they cut to his zipper? How many people? How long did they milk
that before they cut to him? Now that was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't really about anything, was it?
</P>
<P>
   Brooks: ``But who made that rule?''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner: ``It just has to be funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marshall (sheepishly): ``I did. I made the rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks: ``But what about the Marx brothers? What did they make
movies about?''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner: ``Being the Marx brothers and being funny in the
movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marshall: ``The opera. Soup.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks: ``It's true, I think, that when you have jokes that
great, you're great. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon: ``Billy Wilder said to me once, `If you've got three
great scenes in a movie you have a hit.' One of the reasons the
picture may have been so funny is because when it wasn't funny you
dropped off for a minute and then it hit you again, so it becomes
bombastic, it hits you so strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Short: ``You can feel that in a play. In a well-crafted play,
you can sometimes feel the audience gets exhausted from laughing.
You'll think, `How come this scene isn't playing?' And there's
nothing wrong with the scene, they just need a break.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks: ``I think that's your manager who's saying that to you,
Marty.''
</P>
<P>
   When the howling died down, Short had the last word.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest stupidity,'' he said, ``is trying to figure out
what's funny.''
</P>
</TEXT>
