<HEADER>
A2569 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CITIGROUP-DIMON-NYT &LR;      03-08 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITIGROUP-DIMON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIGROUP CO-CHAIRMEN PAID MORE THAN $26 MILLION EACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While last year was hardly a stellar one for the financial
services giant Citigroup Inc., the newly merged company paid its
co-chairmen, John Reed and Sanford Weill, handsomely for their
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Each executive received more than $26 million in total
compensation and stock options, according to a proxy statement
Citigroup filed Monday. Reed's compensation totaled about $26.4
million, while Weill received about $27.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were surprised at how lushly the executives were
compensated given the lack of success Citigroup had managing the
global financial turmoil that battered many companies last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two of them appear to be sharing the compensation of about
five CEOs because I think you could hire very good executives to
run these companies for about $10 million,'' said Graef Crystal, a
compensation expert and publisher of The Crystal Report, a
newsletter. ``You clearly don't want to extend this policy too far
down in the organization or they'd be declaring Chapter 11.''
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup's operating earnings fell 27 percent in the fourth
quarter, to $1.4 billion, from $1.93 billion in the comparable
quarter a year earlier. For the year, Citigroup had operating
earnings of $6.3 billion on revenue of $49.8 billion, compared with
earnings of $7.8 billion on revenue of $47.8 billion in 1997.
Figures for 1997 were computed as if the merger of Citicorp and
Travelers Group had been completed then.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, which has announced thousands of job cuts and layoffs
affecting lower-level employees, said its criteria for determining
the compensation awarded its co-chief executives included the
successful completion of the merger; ``disappointing earnings
performance in some businesses'' but a strong showing from the
bank's consumer business; early and active completion of
cross-selling initiatives, and an aggressive approach to
restructuring the company and cutting expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps to blunt any discomfort shareholders might feel over the
compensation of Reed and Weill, Citigroup sent a letter to
shareholders and the news media Monday saying that the company
would try to double its earnings every five years and achieve a 20
percent return on equity.
</P>
<P>
   The company also pointed out in its proxy that it would pursue a
new stock incentive plan to allow more employees to own shares. It
also said that the bank's top 70 senior executives had agreed to
retain ownership of at least 75 percent of their shares during
their entire tenure as senior executives.
</P>
<P>
   Reed's pay included a $1.7 million salary, a $7.8 million bonus,
and options worth more than $16.9 million. Weill's draw included a
$1 million salary, an $8.5 million bonus, and other stock and
options worth about $17.7 million. Weill's compensation, excluding
options, was no higher than in 1997, while Reed's compensation,
excluding options, more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Reed was one of my minor heroes because he never used to
take huge salaries,'' Crystal said. ``The minute Sandy Weill turned
up, John Reed started turning G-R-E-E-D positive. So much for
synergy.''
</P>
<P>
   A Citigroup spokesman declined to comment on Crystal's
observations.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the bounce Reed enjoyed in his compensation last year,
Weill remains the more deep-pocketed of the two when it comes to
their Citigroup stakes. Weill currently owns about 21.2 million
Citigroup shares valued at about $1.3 billion at the close of
trading Monday, making him one of the company's top 15
shareholders. Reed currently owns about 4.7 million shares valued
at about $291.4 million. Weill's retirement benefits are currently
worth about $618,251 annually upon retirement, while Reed's
retirement package is valued at about $6.4 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   A shareholder resolution outlined in the proxy aims at
Citigroup's executive compensation practices. The resolution said
that chief executives' cash compensation nationally jumped 82
percent between 1990 and 1997, while chief executives' average
total compensation including stock options rose 298 percent, to
$7.8 million. During the same period, the resolution stated,
factory wages rose just 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution cited Weill as the highest-paid chief executive
in the country in 1997 and asked Citigroup's board to place a cap
on executive compensation calculated as a multiple of the earnings
of Citigroup's lowest-paid worker.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup is recommending that shareholders vote against the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup's proxy also divulged the final compensation awarded
James Dimon, whose forced resignation as Citigroup's president last
year was highly publicized. An outline of Dimon's compensation was
first reported in Monday's Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Dimon will receive a bonus of $4.3 million, a separation payment
of $1.3 million, and retain stock and options that bring the total
value of his severance package to about $30 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
