<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2574 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PSE-SFCHRON &LR;      03-08 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Pacific Exchange Ending an Era   By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Sometime early in the next decade, an era will end when the Pacific
Exchange abandons its Pine Street home, leaving San Francisco
without a central stock market for the first time in more than a
century.
</P>
<P>
   The shutdown, quietly disclosed in connection with a regulatory
filing several weeks ago, is inevitable economically and
technologically.
</P>
<P>
   With most stock transactions now handled by computer, dealers
and brokers no longer need to do business face-to-face. A stock
trading floor, with traders scurrying from post to post to place
orders, is simply obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bizarre it's still there,'' said Sandy Robertson, the
former chairman of San Francisco investment bank Roberston
Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   Though the move makes sense as a business decision, the brokers
for whom the frenzy of the trading floor is in their blood say that
life will never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``The floor is jazz, the adrenaline in your body,'' said
independent floor broker Frank Gallagher, whose coffee-stained
workstation is a jumble of papers and risque newspaper clips. ``I'm
not looking forward to sitting in an office. I like my little
world.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Pacific Exchange isn't going away as a
stock-trading institution. When it shuts its trading floor, dealers
and brokers will operate from separate offices rather than a
central site.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, buying and selling of stock options will continue
for the foreseeable future at a less historic but far more active &LR; 
 &LR; Pacific Exchange trading floor in the Mills Building on Montgomery
Street.
</P>
<P>
   As a preliminary step toward phasing out its stock trading
floor, the exchange asked the U.S. Securities and Exchange
Commission last month to let its specialists operate off the
exchange floor. Specialists are the firms that promise to buy or
sell the shares of specific companies, ensuring that a market in
those stocks is always available.
</P>
<P>
   If it gets a go-ahead, Pacific will move two of its 38
specialists off site as a test. Presuming that goes well, the
exchange will close down its Pine Street site as well as a second
trading floor in Los Angeles within two or three years, Pacific
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific's lease expires in 2008, but the exchange can break the
contract earlier than that. The exchange's below-market rent is
scheduled to rise in 2001, which gives it added incentive to move
out.
</P>
<P>
   With San Francisco already reeling from the loss of its biggest
banks and brokerages, many see the closure of the city's equity
emporium as another psychological blow.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange's massive, granite edifice was built in 1915 to
house U.S. Treasury offices in the city. The exchange acquired it
just as the Great Depression set in and began operating there in
1930.
</P>
<P>
   With its broad steps, heroic ``Progress of Man'' sculptures and
imposing columns, the building became a sort of ground zero for the
Financial District, a symbol of the city's monetary might.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physical location of the stock exchange in the Financial
District is very important,'' said John Regin, a broker for the
firm Herzog Heine Geduld who has worked on the exchange floor for
13 years. ``It's something that gives the district its character as
a financial center.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's status as the seat of an important regional
stock exchange gave the city cachet. ``San Francisco had the name
`Financial Capital of the West,''' said Warren Berl, retired
chairman of the brokerage firm Sutro &AMP; Co. and the exchange's chief
in 1960 and 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all its physical and symbolic weight, Pacific's Pine
Street trading floor has become an expensive anachronism. Only
about 5 percent of the 17.5 million shares traded daily on the
exchange involve personal contact between a buyer and seller on the
exchange floor, said Robert Greber, Pacific's chief executive. The
rest are processed by computer.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of PSE09 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``Tradition and custom were costing us an awful lot of money,''
Greber said.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific's trading floor is a cavernous hall covered by a vaulted
roof and skylight, a room with one foot in the past and the other
in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Old-fashioned chalkboards for displaying prices, now unused,
line the walls. Electronic ticker tapes have been slapped on top of
the boards.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden counters arranged in a horseshoe fill the floor. Computer
terminals crowd the countertops, from which spaghetti strands of
wiring spew in all directions. The floors are covered with order
slips, candy wrappers and discarded newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers in shirt-sleeves sit on stools at workstations with
banks of phones and terminals in front of them, bantering with
their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the exchange's floor brokers say they accept the
shutdown. ``It's a good move for us,'' said Jonathan Werts,
president of the San Francisco Specialists Association.
</P>
<P>
   Stock trading has been losing money for Pacific in recent years
as bigger, more-powerful markets such as the New York Stock
Exchange and Nasdaq Stock Market use their muscle to take a bigger
share.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, all stock exchanges, including Pacific, are losing
business to so-called electronic communication networks,
proprietary systems such as Reuters Holdings Instinet that match
buy and sell orders by computer, eliminating the need for an
exchange as middleman.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with daunting competitive threats, Pacific nearly
abandoned its stock business. When it agreed to merge with the
Chicago Board Options Exchange last year, it said it would sell or
spin off its stock exchange business.
</P>
<P>
   CBOE pulled out of the merger two months ago, citing delays
caused by a federal antitrust probe. That prompted Pacific to dust
off a plan aimed at making the exchange competitive in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of Pacific's stock strategy is a cutting-edge, and
much-hyped, electronic trading system called OptiMark. Pacific is
the first U.S. exchange to adopt OptiMark, an order-matching system
that lets traders handle large orders anonymously, avoiding the big
price moves that can occur when a large block of stock is put up
for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of cost savings from shutting the trading floor
and new business attracted by OptiMark should make Pacific's stock
business profitable again, exchange officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the building itself, its owner said his plans are open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a definite answer except that we will take care
of it architecturally,'' said Martin Brown, president of the Empire
Group, which specializes in managing historic buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange building is a unique space, real estate experts
said, a wide open hall with a mixture of Classic and Art Deco
design in the middle of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The building could get leased by a law firm, as was the old
Federal Reserve on Sansome Street, realty specialists said. Brown
said he favors some kind of public as well as private use of the
building.
</P>
<P>
   That would represent a change from the current situation in
which public access to the building is restricted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than the stairway, with guys hanging around eating their
lunch, there's not a lot of public use today,'' said Hamid
Moghadam, chief executive of AMB Property Corp. in San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of PSE09 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 2206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
