<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2575 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-401K-SFCHRON &LR;      03-08 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-401K-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Getting 401(k) Investing Advice Online  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
There are 30 million U.S. workers whose hopes for a comfortable
retirement will hinge largely on how well they invest their 401(k)
pension funds.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the vast majority of them know next to nothing about
investing.
</P>
<P>
   To address this need, a couple of young, privately held
investment advisory firms _ Financial Engines of Palo Alto and
401(k) Forum of San Francisco _ have recently begun providing
401(k) participants with bargain-priced advice on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The online advice isn't available to just any Web surfer. Your
company has to sign up with the adviser, which then will give you a
user ID and password that let you obtain advice on funds approved
for your 401(k) plan.
</P>
<P>
   The programs first grill participants about how soon they plan
to retire and their level of risk tolerance, then suggest what
portion of their portfolios should be invested in growth funds,
value funds, fixed-income funds and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Because their services are computer-based rather than
labor-intensive, the advisers can charge the employer as little as
$10 to $50 per employee per year.
</P>
<P>
   That is a far cry from the $200 to $400 per employee per visit
that investment advisers have traditionally charged companies for
hands-on tutelage.
</P>
<P>
   Employers themselves are barred by federal law from giving
employees specific advice about how to allocate their 401(k) funds.
Most companies have ``an intense paranoia'' about violating the
law, says Dallas Salisbury, president of the Employee Benefits
Research Institute in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   But they can't just turn their backs on their employees. They
might get sued in coming years by employees who find that they
haven't accumulated enough assets to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Although they have only one and three corporate clients
respectively, Financial Engines and 401(k) Forum are the leading
independent companies in their field.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``independent'' is key here, because some of the big
mutual-fund companies _ among them Fidelity, Vanguard and T. Rowe
Price _ offer essentially the same services on their Web sites _
mainly, though not exclusively, to their own 401(k) plan clients.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of 401(K)09 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The mutual fund companies, however, could be perceived as having
a conflict of interest when a 401(k) plan offers funds from several
different fund groups, including their own. The independents
wouldn't have that problem.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Some of the nation's most savvy venture capitalists are
betting that Financial Engines and 401(k) Forum will be big winners
because they offer impartial advice and strong expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Engines has received venture capital from New
Enterprise Associates, Foundation Capital, Charter Venture Capital,
Thomson Corp. and Financial Technology Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   401(k) Forum's backers include Arthur Andersen, Media Technology
Venture Partners, Norwest Venture Capital and GE Capital Services.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither company has scheduled an initial public
offering, both will almost certainly go public.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Engines was founded two years ago and 401(k) Forum
four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   They say their growth has been modest mainly because potential
clients have been skeptical about the value of investment advice
spewed out by a computer.
</P>
<P>
   The one client Financial Engines has in the bag is Alza Corp.,
the Palo Alto pharmaceuticals maker.
</P>
<P>
   401(k) Forum's three clients are Blue Shield of California,
Fujitsu America and Southwest Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The value of computer-based investment advice depends on the
quality of the underlying software, and on the investment expertise
of the people who created it.
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, Financial Engines _ whose Web site is at
 &LR; www.financialengines.com &UR;  &LR; _ seems to have an edge.
</P>
<P>
   It was co-founded by Nobel Prize-winning economist William F.
Sharpe, a Stanford University professor, and the advice it gives is
based on his staggeringly complex, computerized asset-allocation
models, which have been used for years by many of the nation's
largest pension funds.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Fethe, Alza's senior vice president for human resources,
says he was attracted to Financial Engines because ``Bill Sharpe is
the 800-pound gorilla in portfolio theory. Numerous objective tests
of portfolio theory have ratified his approach.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of 401(K)09 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The Financial Engines asset-allocation model is based on a score
of economic variables, says Jeff Maggioncalda, the company's chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take into account things like inflation, interest rates,
bond returns, equity returns, dividends and the expected returns of
large-cap, small-cap, mid-cap, international and domestic funds.''
</P>
<P>
   To use the model, you must key in answers to a long string of
questions about your existing portfolio, income, retirement plans
and risk tolerance. You can revisit the Web site for updated advice
as your circumstances change.
</P>
<P>
   After you have made all the entries, the Sharpe model spits out
a vital statistic: the percentage probability that you will have
the retirement income you want at the time you want it.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't like the result _ if the probability is, say, only
20 percent _ you can go back and adjust your input: such as your
risk tolerance, expected retirement date or retirement income
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the new entries, Financial Engines will recalculate the
probability that you will have a satisfactory income at retirement.
</P>
<P>
   When the probability is high enough, you receive specific
instructions for changing your portfolio. You will be told to buy
or sell precise numbers of shares in the mutual funds available in
your 401(k) plan.
</P>
<P>
   401(k) Forum  &LR; (www.401kforum.com) &LR;  provides advice based on
models developed by a team led by Scott Lummer, former head of
international asset consulting with Chicago's Ibbotson Associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our employees like using their product,'' says Susie
Hasselkuss, benefits administrator with Blue Shield of California.
``They are learning a lot more about investing and doing a better
job of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 401(k) Forum's program asks users many of the same questions
as Financial Engines' model.
</P>
<P>
   401(k) Forum makes specific recommendations for altering your
portfolio. But it doesn't state the odds that your current
financial course will prove successful.
</P>
<P>
   However, Julie Annette, 401(k) Forum's marketing manager,
insists that her company's product is less dependent on ivory-tower
computations than Financial Engines.'
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of 401(K)09 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``We're not just putting numbers into a black box,'' she says.
``We question fund managers about how they make decisions, and we
look carefully at the makeup of their portfolios. A fund that may
claim to be a value fund may in reality be leaning toward a growth
strategy. We make sure we have a good feeling for all the funds we
recommend.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 4 of 401(K)09 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
