<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Deducting Educational Expenses  &HT;       
 By Arthur M. Louis  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I own and manage a small business. I am applying for a
university program leading to a doctorate in a different field. The
tuition is expensive, of course. Can I deduct my educational
expenses?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  I'm afraid not _ and the reason is that you will be
studying outside your present field. If you have decided on a new
career, the full financial burden is on you.
</P>
<P>
   As sad as this may seem, it makes sense. Would you like to see
your own taxes rise so that fuzzy-cheeked future lawyers and
investment bankers can deduct the cost of going through law school
or business school? I thought not.
</P>
<P>
   However, the tax rules are liberal for working people who incur
educational expenses in their current fields. Self-employed people
who study to expand their knowledge or skills in their present
businesses can deduct the costs of tuition, books and other
research and study materials.
</P>
<P>
   For example, physicians who take courses to keep up with
advances in medicine, or lawyers who go back to school to study the
latest legislative or judicial changes in the law, can claim
education deductions.
</P>
<P>
   The education deduction also is available to employees whose
employers require them to take courses as a condition for keeping
their jobs or maintaining their salaries. Employees also can take
courses on their own and claim deductions if the courses are
designed to help them maintain or improve their job skills.
</P>
<P>
   Taxes on Barter
</P>
<P>
   Q: We are letting a couple of starving artists occupy part of
our house rent-free. In exchange, they perform repairs and
maintenance on the house. Do we owe taxes on the value of their
work? And do they owe taxes on the value of the rent?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: It's possible that all of you owe taxes. What you have
there is a bartering transaction, which is subject to income tax.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how to figure it:
</P>
<P>
   _You, the homeowners, must declare as income the fair market
value of the services your tenants perform for you. However, you
can deduct from that a portion of your household expenses because
you are alloting partial use of your home in exchange for the
services.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if the tenants occupy one-fourth of your house, you
can deduct a fourth of your mortgage interest, property taxes and
homeowners' insurance costs. However, your deduction can be no
larger than the value of the services you receive.
</P>
<P>
   _Your tenants must declare as income the fair market value of
the rent on the space they occupy. They can deduct from this any
out-of-pocket expenses they incur in working for you, such as the
cost of paint, lumber and other materials used to fix your house.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Started
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a college student, 24 years old, with no job. I recently
received a money gift from a relative and would like to invest it.
People suggest that I buy stocks or mutual funds, but I am new to
investing and know little about it. I have read books on the
subject and have scanned the Internet, but I find the jargon hard
to follow. How should I proceed?
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MONEYBAG () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR;  A: You are in the same boat as a lot of other people. The
mutual fund industry was created to serve people like yourself.
Because you are still young, you probably can safely invest your
gift entirely in equity mutual funds _ those that invest almost
entirely in stocks. Stocks have been the most lucrative securities
investment over the long term, rising 9 to 10 percent a year on
average over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   When you buy shares in a mutual fund, you pool your money with
other shareholders, and all of you get the services of expert
investment managers working full time to analyze and trade
securities on your behalf. For this, you pay a small fee, typically
about 1 percent of your assets each year.
</P>
<P>
   That still leaves you the task of choosing a fund or funds.
</P>
<P>
   Bear in mind that for many years, only about 20 percent of
equity mutual funds have performed better than the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index _ the principal U.S. measure of investment
performance. If that trend were to continue, the best strategy
would be to buy shares in a mutual fund that emulates the index,
such as the Vanguard Index 500 Fund. Index funds require minimal
management and therefore charge relatively small management fees _
typically, 0.25 percent of assets or less per year.
</P>
<P>
   Notice that I said ``if that trend were to continue.'' Neither I
nor anyone else can say for certain whether, or how long, the S&AMP;P
500 will continue to beat the majority of mutual fund managers.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the fundamental fact that investing, no
matter how much or little you know about it, will always be partly
a gamble.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
