<HEADLINE>
TAYLOR SAYS TRADES POSSIBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ With the NHL trading deadline approaching
and his team's playoff hopes flickering, Los Angeles Kings general
manager Dave Taylor said Monday that deals are possible in the next
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be interested in talking to any team if it means helping
our club for the short term, but in particular for the long term,''
said Taylor, whose team takes a four-game losing streak into
tonight's meeting at the Forum with the two-time defending Stanley
Cup champion Detroit Red Wings. ``We wouldn't be very interested in
giving up any of our young kids at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Reading between the lines, it appears that housecleaning _ or at
least some light dusting _ is likely around the March 23 trading
deadline if the Kings' playoff hopes have completely deteriorated
by then.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor insisted he hasn't given up on this season. The Kings
(23-36-5) are seven points out of the last Western Conference
playoff berth with 18 games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'll look beyond this year as long as we have a
chance to make the playoffs, and we still have a chance,'' he said.
``But we can't afford too many losses, and we could play great and
still not get in.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Back in town: Taylor returned Sunday after nine days in
Finland, where he scouted several Kings prospects, including Aki
Berg, who chose to play in his native country after failing to
reach contract terms with his NHL club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'd like to come back and we'd like to have him
back,'' Taylor said. ``It's a matter of working out a contract.
He's a very good young defenseman.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Burning Staples A pile of insulating material on the roof of
the under-construction Staples Center caught fire Monday morning
and burned for about 30 minutes before it was put out by
firefighters. The cause of the blaze was under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Said Michael Roth, spokesman for the new arena, which is
scheduled to open in October, ``It's not going to slow down
construction at all, and there's no reason it should delay the
opening. No one was hurt and no one was sent home.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Loose pucks The Red Wings will be without center Sergei
Fedorov, who is serving a five-game suspension for a slashing
incident last week. The suspension cost Fedorov $386,178 in salary.
. . . Long Beach Ice Dogs goalie Ryan Bach practiced with the Kings
on Monday because Jamie Storr was ill. Storr's availability for
tonight's game will be determined today, as will that of defenseman
Mattias Norstrom, who also has a virus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 2208EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
