r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      03-08 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Homestake Sees Golden Opportunity With Canadian Company  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Once upon a time, a San Francisco 49er was something other than an
inside linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Long before Super Bowls, cioppino and silicon chips, a Niner, of
course, was a miner. And San Francisco was awash in gold _ and all
of the wealth and commerce that came with it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the historic weight that the precious metal bears on
this city, its presence in San Francisco's modern economy is as
rare as a nugget in a stream. With at least one exception:
Homestake Mining.
</P>
<P>
   Homestake's pedigree is guilded. The 122-year-old mining company
was founded in part by William Randolph Hearst's father, George
Hearst, who dominated the company from the outset, according to
company history. And it was Homestake proceeds passed from George
to William that enabled the son to build his newspaper empire.
</P>
<P>
   Homestake is so ``old San Francisco'' that it still makes its
living digging for gold. What's more, it is the oldest publicly
traded company (in its original business) listed on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to those fun-facts, CQ &LR; Homestake is worthy of note
because it did a deal yesterday. The nation's fourth-largest gold
producer agreed to buy a Canadian-owned company, Argentina Gold
Corp., for about $200 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The initial reaction by the Street wasn't, uh, golden.
Homestake's shares, which were already slumping, slipped about 6
percent to close at $8.88. What's worse for Homestake fans is that
its drop came in the face of about a $3 rise in the price of gold,
which closed at $292.70 an ounce on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised that the stock is down, I'm surprised its
price is down as much as it is'' in the wake of gold's price jump,
says financial analyst Todd Hinrich of ABN AMRO in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that investors think Homestake is paying too much
for a promising South American mining operation. Homestake agreed
to pay the U.S. equivalent of $5.14 a share for Argentina Gold,
which is a whopping 63 percent above the company's close on Friday.
Homestake's bid is also significantly higher than a previous failed
bid by a Canadian competitor, Barrick Gold.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of STREET09 (85201 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  A vexing problem for gold mining companies is that they have to
always find more gold in order to stay in business. And there's
only so much of the glittery stuff in the ground. So they have to
pay up. And Homestake's management is banking that it is buying low
(despite being up yesterday, gold prices have been on a downward
slide since the crash of 1987) and will be able to sell high.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is take advantage of the low price of
gold and make acquisitions when they are cheaper,'' says Homestake
chief executive Jack Thompson (no relation to the Throwin' Samoan,
a former Washington State quarterback of the same name).
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like these acquisitions to lower our costs of
exploration and development,'' Thompson says.
</P>
<P>
   As you might guess, slugging it out in the global gold mining
business isn't the easiest way to make a buck. Long-term gold
prices have been under pressure as bears argue that gold has lost
its monetary value and has become just another commodity. What's
more, drilling holes through South American mountain ranges is
slightly more complicated and capital-intensive than, say, building
an e-commerce Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, the CEO for nearly three years, has received high
marks from some Wall Street analysts for slashing Homestake's
operating costs by investing in technology and employee training
and for taking some calculated risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hallmark of Homestake is the leadership of John
Thompson,'' says ABN's Hinrich.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the analyst rates Homestake a ``hold'' mostly because of
his pessimistic outlook for gold prices. ``I'm not exactly a raging
gold bull,'' Hinrich says.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are many of his peers when it comes to Homestake. Nine out
of the 15 financial analysts that cover the company rate it a
``hold.'' But if you believe in gold's future, Homestake's Thompson
thinks his company is where you want to park some of your
speculative assets.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of STREET09 (85201 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Now that Homestake has shaved its operating costs, it's easier
for his company to earn a profit when gold prices are listless.
However, should gold prices ever begin to gain momentum, Thompson
contends that Homestake shares are a sophisticated way to play any
potential resurgence of the gold market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price of gold doesn't have to move very far'' northward
for Homestake to benefit, Thompson says.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Homestake fans, there is no guarantee that
gold will regain its luster.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LUCID POINT &LR; : A well-informed reader pointed out that Lucent
Technologies largely consists of what was AT&AMP;T's Western Electric
division. In an earlier column, Street Smarts referred to Lucent as
the successor to Bell Labs. While Bell Labs is indeed a part of
Lucent, the former Western Electric operation is a bigger chunk of
the business.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
