<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT ASSERTS RIGHT TO INVESTIGATE SPECIAL PROSECUTOR
</HEADLINE>
   (lh) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department said in legal papers filed
Monday that only the attorney general had the authority to
investigate or remove an independent counsel like Kenneth Starr,
the Whitewater prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   The filing to the three-member panel of federal appeals court
judges that appointed Starr asserted that the special division, as
the panel is known, had no authority to intervene in a disciplinary
matter like the Justice Department's pending investigation of
possible improprieties by Starr's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in the act grants the Special Division authority to
prohibit the attorney general from inquiring into whether `good
cause' exists to remove an independent counsel,'' said the brief
signed by Solicitor General Seth Waxman.
</P>
<P>
   The government legal papers represented the first time that the
Justice Department had addressed the issue of its powers to
investigate an independent counsel. They were filed at the panel's
direction after a conservative Virginia legal group, the Landmark
Legal Foundation, asked the judges to order the Justice Department
inquiry stopped, arguing that Reno did not have the authority to
investigate an independent counsel and that Congress should be
responsible for any disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel law gives the attorney general sole
responsibility for removing an independent counsel, and Justice
Department officials have told Starr that inherent in that power is
the authority to conduct a fact-finding investigation necessary to
reach a judgment on whether Starr should be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, in a separate filing Monday, argued that Landmark did not
have any legal standing to ask the panel to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Landmark has no legally cognizable interest in the case or
controversy presented by its application,'' said the brief.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear where the filings Monday left the matter.
Landmark intervened after news reports disclosed that the Justice
Department had notified Starr that it intended to open an
investigation into whether his prosecutors improperly coerced
witnesses like Monica Lewinsky or withheld possible conflicts of
interest from Justice Department lawyers at the outset of the
Lewinsky inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks Reno and Starr have considered a separate
counsel to conduct the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Other legal documents related to the Starr case, unsealed last
week by Judge Norma Holloway Johnson of U.S. district court here,
shed light on the behind-the-scenes battle over how far Starr could
go in restricting what Ms. Lewinsky would say in her interview with
ABC's Barbara Walters, which was broadcast Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's lawyers argued that the independent counsel's
imposition of a prior restraint provision in Ms. Lewinsky's
immunity agreement was legally indefensible, given her full
cooperation with his grand jury and with Congress' impeachment
inquiry, as well as the fact that thousands of pages of material in
the case had already been released.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr's office countered that her duties under the agreement
had not been completed, saying ``she has not yet testified at any
trials.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the two sides negotiated the interview's parameters.
</P>
</TEXT>
