<HEADLINE>
SHORT NOTES ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cheap Air Fares: Bidding on the Web &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York tour operator and airline-ticket consolidator has
opened a Web site to accept bids on domestic and overseas tickets,
and the owner says that no bid _ not even $1 _ is too small to
start. Many of the fares have limited windows of availability;
others, particularly for students, offer a round trip to anywhere
in the United States to be used in a wide period of time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company, Magical Holidays at 501 Madison Avenue, set up
www.skyauction .com with no minimum price for any air ticket,
package tour or hotel stay. Registration to bid is free, with
payment by credit card or check.
</P>
<P>
   The president, Michael Hering, said that Magical Holidays was
begun in 1981 and, like other consolidators, has contracts with
most major airlines to sell tickets below advertised prices when
seats are not filling up at regular rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site, which has a student section with domestic tickets
and overseas tickets for long stays, opened Feb. 17. Among the
brands identified in the auctions are Virgin Atlantic, Continental,
United and Alitalia.
</P>
<P>
   One couple won an auction of two tickets to South Africa on
Virgin Atlantic for $685 each, plus tax, as against $1,299, plus
tax, for a 21-day advance purchase quoted by the airline. Bids can
be canceled by e-mail to the company, support(AT)skyauction.com.
There is a hypertext line on the site. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Skyauction bids can be based on how much has been bid _ bids in
the ball park are posted _ and how many tickets are available. In
each sale, the price necessary to get a ticket at a given moment is
posted, and others that qualify are listed.
</P>
<P>
   Most auctions go on for a week, but some of the offers, Hering
said, represent deals that airlines provide for particular dates
that are selling badly. These may last only a day. Some winning
bids are a loss for his company, Hering said, in that he pays the
airline more for them than they fetch. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   El Greco's Legacy To Three Countries &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition of El Greco paintings, which opened in Madrid on
Feb. 4 and is due later this year in Rome and Athens, covers three
main stylistic periods, starting in Crete, where the artist was
born in 1541, to his introduction to the Renaissance in Italy in
1567 and finally to his many years in Spain, where he died in 1614
in Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Greco, Identity and Transformation'' features 70 of his
works, including 11 paintings that have never before been part of
an El Greco exhibition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Domenikos Theotocopoulos became known as El Greco (The Greek)
after he moved to Spain in 1577. The exhibition includes three of
his early works from Crete, including ``The Adoration of the
Magi,'' circa 1565, on loan from a Greek museum. From his Italian
period there are ``The Modena Triptych'' from 1569, depicting the
life of Christ, on loan from an Italian museum, and the ``Adoration
of the Shepherds,'' circa 1570, on loan from a private English
collection. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the works on view _ such as ``St. Francis
Receiving the Stigmata,'' from 1580, from a private Spanish
collection _ are from his Spanish period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition continues through May 16 at the
Thyssen-Bornemisza Museum in Madrid. Admission is $3.30; telephone:
(34) 91-420-3944. From June 2 to Sept. 19, it will reverse El
Greco's westward journey and travel to Rome, to the Palazzo delle
Esposizione, but with up to 20 paintings substituting for some that
will not leave Spain. Continuing to Athens, the show will display
57 works at the National Gallery, from Oct. 18 to Jan. 17, 2000. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Poets Will Converge Upon Manhattan &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lower Manhattan has played host to poets and their movements for
more than two centuries. Edgar Allan Poe, Dylan Thomas, Allen
Ginsberg and e.e. cummings all embellished their talents, and
occasionally their habits, in the East Village, SoHo, the West
Village, and the Lower East Side. Next month poets from around the
world will visit these historic neighborhoods for the first
People's Poetry Gathering. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From April 9 to 11, professional poets, amateurs and the curious
will partake in over 50 poetry recitations, conversation groups,
competitions and workshops. Although the festival is anchored at
Cooper Union (East Seventh Street between Third and Fourth
Avenues), events will take place throughout the downtown area. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Presented by City Lore, a New York cultural center, and Poets
House, a literary center and home to a 35,000-volume poetry
library, the festival will explore two primary themes: ``Masters of
Oral Tradition'' and ``Emerging Forms and Formats.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Masters of Oral Tradition'' events will feature a performance
by Utah Phillips, Grand Master of the Rose Tattoo, a dispersed
troupe of hobo poets; Gabriel Segura and Rafael Perez Lopez,
Colombian decima (10-line verse) improvisers; and a picnic with the
cowboy poet Don Edwards, a former rancher and rodeo chaser. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 10-round ``Heavyweight Poetry Bout'' between Sherman Alexie
and Patricia Smith and ``Braggin' Rights,'' a free-style
street-corner rapping contest, are planned for ``Emerging Forms and
Formats.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other featured poets will include Robert Pinsky, the Poet
Laureate of the United States; John Cephas, the Piedmont blues
musician and National Heritage Award winner; and Galway Kinnell,
winner of the Pulitzer Prize and National Book Award. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also planned are a supper in honor of Robert Burns, midnight
readings of erotic poetry and Edgar Allan Poe, a workshop for
renga, a collaborative 36-stanza poem (saki provides inspiration
after the sixth stanza) with masters from the Spring Street Haiku
Group, and a literary tour and pub crawl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information: (800) 333-5982, extension 5, or
www.peoplespoetry.org. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Danish Conquest: Legoland Comes to California &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Junior builders of America take note.
</P>
<P>
   Legoland California, a theme park inspired by those brightly
colored plastic bricks found in toy boxes the world over, is
scheduled to open Saturday in the seaside community of Carlsbad,
Calif. This will be the third Legoland, and the first in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The original opened in 1968 in Billund, Denmark _ Lego's
corporate headquarters _ and in 1996 a second park followed in
Windsor, England. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Designed for children between the ages of 2 and 12, Legoland
California occupies 128 acres and features 40 mostly interactive
rides, shows and attractions, as well as restaurants and shops,
spread among six theme areas.
</P>
<P>
   Fun Town, for example, has driving and boating ``schools'' for
children, while on Castle Hill visitors will participate in
simulated jousts. Thirty million Lego bricks have been used to
create the park's 5,000 models, which range from life-sized
giraffes and a dinosaur nine feet tall to highly detailed
scale-model versions of American landmarks like Mount Rushmore and
Grand Central Station. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lego plastic bricks were first made in 1947, and since 1949 more
than 200 billion Lego pieces have been produced. The first two Lego
theme parks have proved popular, with 1998 attendance reaching 1.4
million in Denmark and 1.5 million in England. At Legoland
California, 1.8 million visitors are expected during the first year
of operation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Legoland California is off the Cannon Road exit of Interstate 5
in Carlsbad, about 30 miles north of San Diego. It will be open
daily 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. Admission is $32, $25 seniors and children
3 to 16; two-day passes cost $36 and $29. Parking is $6.
Information (760) 918-5346.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Hall
</P>
</TEXT>
