<HEADLINE>
SENATE EDUCATION BILL STALLS DESPITE BIPARTISAN SUPPORT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An education bill with bipartisan support got
bogged down on the Senate floor on Monday as Republicans feuded
with Democrats over President Clinton's initiative to reduce class
sizes.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans failed in their effort to cut off debate and
force a final vote on the bill, an attempt that they will make
again on Tuesday. The vote Monday to end debate was 41 against and
54 in favor, well short of the 60 required. It was strictly along
party lines.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan bill, dubbed ``ed flex,'' is supported by all 50
governors and, with some modifications, by Clinton. It would give
local schools more flexibility in the way they spend some $11
billion in federal assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first bill of the year that has broad bipartisan
support, and it is approaching gridlock,'' the Senate majority
leader, Trent Lott of Mississippi, said in chastising the
Democrats. ``Let's not do that.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the legislation has been greatly overshadowed by a
Democratic amendment that would trim class sizes by authorizing
federal spending to pay for the hiring of 100,000 teachers in
grades one though three. For days now, Republicans have worked to
keep the amendment off the Senate floor, arguing that while they
support the idea, it should be dealt with later this year, after
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday a procedural oversight by the Republicans left the
door open for Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., to force a test vote
on the proposal on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is more important to the families of this country than
the issue of education?'' Kennedy said after seizing the unexpected
opportunity. ``What is more important than having a debate on the
size of the classroom?''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans immediately fired back with their own amendment,
which would allow local governments to choose how to spend $1.2
billion that was authorized last year: using it for either special
education or hiring teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's an excellent compromise,'' said Sen. James M.
Jeffords, R-Vt., who heads the Senate education committee.
</P>
<P>
   With the two sides at loggerheads in the first major education
debate of the year, Republicans are accusing Democrats of placing
political priorities above the needs of schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   And, converging Monday on a crowded town hall meeting in
Chester, Pa., Republican leaders not only lashed out at their
Democratic counterparts but also underscored their own education
ideas, hoping to convince voters that the issue is as important to
them as are tax cuts and military spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a partisan issue,'' Lott said at the town hall
meeting. ``Democrats are injecting politics where there is a broad
bipartisan consensus. They think the directions, control and money
should all come from Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott, who shared the stage at the meeting with Sen. Rick
Santorum of Pennsylvania and other Republican notables, pointed to
his own bona fides as a onetime public school student and said he
would not ``cede this issue to people who didn't go to public
school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems in education are different than they were 10
years ago and require new kinds of solutions,'' Lott said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The battle on the ``ed-flex'' bill boils down to disagreement
over the Democratic amendment, proposed by Sen. Patty Murray,
D-Wash., to reduce class sizes by hiring 100,000 teachers over the
next seven years. A down payment of $1 billion for the teacher
proposal was approved by Congress last year as part of a larger
spending bill, but an additional $11 billion is needed to finance
the initiative fully.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy on Monday portrayed the Republicans as weak-willed on
education and said they wanted to ``gag'' the Democrats. He added
that ``Senator Lott told the governors that he was very willing to
have the Senate talk about education, but here in the Senate he's
much less willing.''
</P>
<P>
   The teacher-hiring proposal, which Democrats call crucial to
improving schooling for young children, has put Republicans in a
tough spot. While they envision the initiative's ultimate approval,
they had hoped to deal with it later, as part of a more sweeping
education bill.
</P>
<P>
   But with the amendment headed to the floor now for a test vote,
in which the backing of 60 senators will be needed for approval,
Republicans will most likely reject it, despite their fears that
doing so will leave them vulnerable on the education issue.
</P>
<P>
   The House is expected to take up its version of the bill, which
does not include a teacher-hiring proposal, later this week. If the
Senate is unable to end debate on its bill, Lott may be forced to
pull the legislation so the body can proceed to other business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing politics with the future of our children, with
our children's education,'' said Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., who
co-sponsored the ``ed flex'' bill.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing parents want, Frist said, is for Congress to
``stop playing politics and pass useful legislation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
