<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHER-MURDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAILERS WATCH MOTHER HELD IN 3 KILLINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A 41-year-old nurse was under a 24-hour suicide watch
after being jailed in the deaths of her three children, who had
been drugged and suffocated.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Marilyn Lemak, had been rushed to a hospital for
surgery for a severed artery in her arm on Friday after calling the
police to report the children's deaths. Ms. Lemak was released from
the hospital on Sunday, and a judge on Du Page County Circuit Court
ruled Monday that Ms. Lemak must remain in jail without bond, while
also receiving a psychiatric evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   A makeshift memorial has grown outside Ms. Lemak's home in
Naperville, a bedroom community west of Chicago, and on Sunday 500
people attended a Mass remembering the children.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lemak and her husband, David, are divorcing, and her
husband, an emergency room doctor, had moved out of the house
several weeks ago. A family member told reporters that Ms. Lemak
had been struggling with depression since the birth of her last
child three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said that when 7-year-old Nicholas Lemak and
6-year-old Emily arrived home from school on Thursday, Ms. Lemak
gave them and 3-year-old Thomas a mixture of prescription drugs to
make them sleepy. Once they were asleep, she suffocated each child
by placing one hand over the mouth and pinching the nose with the
other. She then took some of the same drug mixture and cut her arm,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday Ms. Lemak appeared in a wheelchair in court, where her
lawyer, Jack Donahue, requested permission for a psychiatric
evaluation. Judge Stephen Culliton of Du Page County Circuit Court
granted the request but said the evaluation could not be used to
determine if Ms. Lemak was fit to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lemak has not entered a plea to the three counts of
first-degree murder and is scheduled for arraignment on March 29.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators would not speculate on a motive for the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lemak's divorce lawyer, David Kuhn, described her as a
caring mother and an active member of the community. He did notice
some depression, which he said was common with divorce, but he
noted that the Lemaks' divorce was not an ugly one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 2215EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0463 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2590 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONNERLY-AFFIRMATIVEA     03-08 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONNERLY-AFFIRMATIVEACTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    California regent criticizes contracts deal, lends support to
Texas oppositionBy Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A recent legislative compromise to save a
program aimed at winning more state contracts for women and
minority business owners was nothing more than ``shuck and jive,''
says Californian Ward Connerly, a lightning rod in the debate over
affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still have a gun to your head if you're a contractor.
Good-faith efforts can still be quotas,'' Connerly said Monday in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The University of California regent drew national attention
after he successfully campaigned to eliminate affirmative action by
California state government.
</P>
<P>
   In a Capitol news conference, Connerly criticized a deal forged
last week by state senators that revised the state's Historically
Underutilized Business program. The deal, made by Sens. Royce West,
D-Dallas, and Bill Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant, saved the program but
gave it a new focus.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of concentrating on the number of contracts that state
agencies make with businesses owned by women and minorities, the
new program will focus on the efforts made by a state agency to
diversify its contracting.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly's appearance at the Capitol lent support to a bill
filed Monday by state Rep. Robert Talton, R-Pasadena, to prohibit
discrimination or preferential treatment in public employment,
contracting or education when that discrimination or preference is
based on race, color, gender, ethnicity or national origin.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, if enacted, would kill the Historically Underutilized
Business program.
</P>
<P>
   Both Talton and Connerly, standing beside him in front the State
Treasury office at the Capitol, called discrimination and
preferences morally wrong. With them was Edward Blum of Houston,
co-chair of the Campaign for a Colorblind America, which also
opposes affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly, who also was scheduled to speak at the University of
Texas School of Law Monday night, said preferences would not make
up for deficient schools. But he also said too much blame has been
put on schools for students' poor performance.
</P>
<P>
   The California businessman praised Gov. George W. Bush's plan to
end social promotion in public schools, saying it stands as an
integral component to ending preferences based on race, gender or
ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fits in beautifully,'' Connerly said. ``I hope the governor
will be willing to do the heavy lifting. When you're looking at
higher office, you may be more compromising.''
</P>
<P>
   Connerly said he had not met with Bush. But would he be a Bush
supporter if the governor makes a presidential bid? ``Maybe,'' he
said. ``Maybe. But we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Osler McCarthy writes for The Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
