<HEADLINE>
HOW SAFE IS THE HOTEL SAFE?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.J., Calif., Fla.)   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last Sept. 1, Dr. Odi Matityahu and his wife, Liat, arrived in
St. Thomas, the Virgin Islands, to celebrate her birthday. They
checked into the Renaissance Grand Beach Resort about 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Matityahu said that the hotel staff asked if they needed a safe
for their valuables, and they were given the key to a wall safe in
their room. They stored their valuables, including passports and
jewelry, and went swimming. When they returned at 5:20, the room
safe had been removed with a beer-can opener, which was left
behind. The room door had not been forced, they said.
</P>
<P>
   This situation, and a different problem that befell two other
hotel guests in Miami, illuminate aspects of hotel liability that
may come as unwelcome news to travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Matityahu said that he and his wife got a hotel and a police
report about the theft and that the resort manager said there was
nothing to worry about because the insurance company would take
care of them. After the couple returned home to Plano, Texas,
Matityahu said, an insurance adjuster called to say the couple
would be compensated for their losses _ up to a total of $200.
Since Matityahu's list includes more than $33,000 in jewelry, he
refused to accept.
</P>
<P>
   The $200 offer was not a random one. It is the limit of
``innkeeper liability'' in the Virgin Islands' legal code when
guests entrust their valuables to the hotel for safekeeping and the
valuables are lost through ``theft, damage, destruction or
otherwise.'' It is not that a hotel cannot pay more, but $200 is
the most it is obliged to pay.
</P>
<P>
   If valuables are not entrusted to the hotel, the guest is
entitled to no compensation in the event of a loss.
</P>
<P>
   Since the event, Matityahu said, he has received unsatisfactory
and ``rude'' responses from the hotel and some of its officers. He
turned the matter over to a lawyer at home and a suit was filed for
damages of $47,565, including losses caused by Matityahu's absence
from his chiropractic practice, airline tickets, new passports and
a replacement for his green card (he is an Israeli national). The
issue of whom to sue, in the age of real estate investment trusts,
franchising and hotel management companies, is difficult. George B.
Flint, the Matityahus' lawyer, filed the suit in Texas against
Marriott, which owns the Renaissance Group.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas lawyer representing Marriott in this case, Ellen
Presby of Mills, Presby &AMP; Associates, said ``they sued the wrong
company'' and that despite the name, the real owner of the hotel is
Hotel Property Investment Inc., whose address she did not know.
Flint has asked for this.
</P>
<P>
   The jewelry is carried on the family insurance policy, and
Matityahu is filing a claim. But he says his premiums will rise
sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Flint says that the case will hinge on negligence. ``That was
not a safe as `safe' is understood in Texas law,'' he said in an
interview. ``I think if you asked 12 members of a jury if something
you could remove with a can opener is a safe, the vote would be
12-0 against it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The matter of limiting innkeepers' liability goes far back in
law. A cap on what an innkeeper must pay if travelers lose their
belongings came about to protect those who provided shelter to
people on the road _ a desirable situation in the view of public
policy _ from being put out of business by visitors who sued after
being robbed on the premises.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, every state and territory has a law
limiting this liability, and each state requires that notices of
this be posted in a particular way. No federal law is involved.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these limits were set in the last century, and inflation
has made them out of date. In the last five years, some
legislatures have been pushed by consumers into raising the limits.
</P>
<P>
   John Hyland, a lawyer at Sherry &AMP; O'Neill in New York, which
specializes in hotel law, gave some figures for the limits in
states popular with tourists: New Jersey, $5,000; New York, $1,500;
Florida, $1,000; California, $1,000; Nevada, $750, and Illinois,
$500.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   John Sherry Jr., emeritus professor of law at the Cornell School
of Hotel Administration, whose father was an original partner of
Sherry &AMP; O'Neill, is more pragmatist than litigator. ``If you have
heirloom jewelry,'' he said, ``don't take it to a hotel, even for a
wedding. The best hotels attract the best confidence artists, and
they will get to you some way. You might as well wear good-quality
paste.''
</P>
<P>
   Another issue of hotel liability appears in the case of Jim and
Judith Whalen of Seal Beach, Calif., who describe themselves as a
senior couple. On Nov. 19, on a business trip to Miami, they
returned to the hotel, the Doubletree at Coconut Grove, at 8 p.m.
When they were 50 feet from the hotel entrance, they said, they and
a couple leaving the hotel with two young children were set upon by
four youths, knocked down and robbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the proximity to the hotel entrance,'' Mrs. Whalen
wrote, ``hotel security did not respond to our collective
screams.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that research by friends who were members of the
Florida bar showed that Florida law provided no shield to forbid
lawsuits against good Samaritans who made mistakes in pursuit of
their good intentions. This resulted in security officers' normally
refusing to go outside a hotel's entrance and driveway to help
guests in difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   It has a wrong-way sound to it, but a spokesman for the hotel
industry in Florida says hotels do not want their employees going
into the street to help people because of this liability issue. The
spokesman, Thomas A. Waits, president of the Florida Hotel and
Motel Association, said: ``Hotels have gone the extra mile, and
they can be held liable for these actions. Business does not win in
court.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that with tort reform, good Samaritans would be
supported by law.
</P>
<P>
   Tort reform, a sticky political issue everywhere, is opposed by
law groups because it makes it tougher for consumers to sue
businesses. The Florida Legislature approved tort reform last year,
but it was vetoed by Gov. Lawton Chiles, a Democrat. The new
governor, Jeb Bush, a Republican, has pledged himself to tort
reform.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whalen said that when she talked to clerks in the hotel
afterward, she was told the area was unsafe at night. Although she
had earlier received directions from the hotel desk, that does not
create liability. Repeated calls to Doubletree management yielded
no response.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Robert M. Jarvis, an author of ``Travel Law, Cases and
Materials'' (Carolina Academic Press), said that hotels had won
cases in situations where concierges gave directions to places that
proved unsafe. ``Even though the hotel sets the trip in motion,''
said Jarvis, who teaches at Nova Southeastern University in Fort
Lauderdale, ``if it happens outside the perimeter, the hotel is not
liable.''
</P>
<P>
   Both stories remind travelers that although one's home may be
one's castle, one's hotel is not one's home. Costly jewelry should
be insured and not taken to hotels, and guests who suspect that an
area may be of doubtful safety should call for a cab.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
