<HEADLINE>
TOURING LEBANON  
 LUGGAGE STORAGE IN MILAN  
 OKTOBERFEST AND SOCCER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RAY CORMIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I want to visit Lebanon, but I don't speak Arabic.
Are there agents who handle guided tours of Lebanon? _ Brad John,
New York, N.Y.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. A 10-year ban on Americans' traveling to Lebanon was lifted
in 1997, and last summer President Clinton authorized airlines to
sell tickets to Beirut in the United States. But there are still no
direct flights to Lebanon, and the government is not encouraging
travel there.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the State Department said the recent announcements
``should not in any way be construed as a determination by the
Department of State that it is safe for Americans to travel to
Lebanon.'' The official travel warning says the southern suburbs of
Beirut, the Bekaa Valley, and southern Lebanon should be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   But a few agents are handling tours to Lebanon, a country that
was once a popular vacation spot and that is trying to rebuild its
tourism industry after a brutal civil war marked by terrorism
against the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Since last summer, for example, Kutrubes Travel in Boston, has
arranged two group tours and 10 individual trips to Lebanon,
according to Kathy Kutrubes, the owner.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kutrubes said she went on her own group tour in November and
was ``pleasantly surprised'' at the sites and facilities. She saw a
lot of construction in Beirut, but noted that there were many
ruined buildings.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Kutrubes plans eight-day tours of Lebanon, which can
be doubled with a visit to Syria, departing April 15, May 12, Sept.
9, Oct. 7 and Nov. 4. Tour participants stay in Beirut at the
Napoleon Hotel or, for $200 more, the Summerland, and take daily
tours of the city and such sites as the Roman temples in Baalbeck,
the cedar forests of the north, the ancient city of Byblos and the
ruins at Tyre.
</P>
<P>
   The land price of $1,598 includes daily breakfast and several
other meals, transportation and guided tours. Air fares will be
about $900 to $1,200 more, Ms. Kutrubes said. Kutrubes Travel, 328
Tremont Street, Boston, Mass 02116; (800) 878-8566, fax (617)
426-3196.
</P>
<P>
   Also handling travel to Lebanon is Mill-Run Tours, 424 Madison
Avenue, New York, N.Y. 10017, (800) 645-5786 and (212) 486-9840,
fax (212) 223-8129. According to George Villarino, director of
tours and cruises, Mill-Run's business to Lebanon has mostly been
as addenda to trips to Israel, Egypt, Syria or Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   But he offers 12-day trips to Lebanon with group tours for about
$100 a day for ground costs, which includes daily breakfast, six
lunches and dinners, and admission to historic sites and museums.
Air transportation, usually on Air France, is extra. The tours are
usually in Arabic, French and English, Villarino said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I have got conflicting information about the
availability of short-term luggage storage at Central Station in
Milan, Italy. Have security precautions done away with lockers?
Will I have to rent a room for a half-day stopover to store my
bags? _ Bette A. Hahner, Westport, Conn.(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Save your money for the Monte Napoleon fashion district or
for some fine Lombard cuisine rather than spending it on a room for
your bags. The Central Station in Milan has a luggage storage room
(``deposito bagagli''), where you can keep bags for about $2.85
each for 12 hours (at 1,754 lire to the dollar).
</P>
<P>
   The State Railway says that all major stations have such storage
areas. They shouldn't be too hard to find, since they are marked by
large signs with a baggage symbol. Many stations in Italy _ and
thus the storage areas _ close from about 1 to 5 or 6 a.m., but the
one in Milan is open 24 hours (though it doesn't accept bags from 1
to 4 a.m.).
</P>
<P>
   These deposit rooms remained open even at the height of the
terrorism of the late 1970s and early 80s. In those years,
storage-room personnel were allowed to ask for identification and
even to open luggage for inspection. The few automated lockers in
train stations were removed.
</P>
<P>
   The self-storage lockers began to return in 1997 and 34 stations
now have some. But Milan is not one of the 34 (Rome's Termini
Station has the most, 441).
</P>
<P>
   You cannot reserve storage space at the deposit room, nor should
it be necessary, the office says. If you speak Italian and want
more information, you can call ahead to the Milan storage office at
(39-02) 6371-2212. The State Railway offers information numbers for
many stations on line at www.fs-online.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Four recent college graduates want to visit Germany
for Oktoberfest. How can we take in an occasional soccer match
while there? _ Bill Seibert, Lawrenceville, N.J.(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Oktoberfest means Munich, which for a soccer fan is a rich
destination, with three teams in the Bundesliga, the national
league. Two of them, the perennial powerhouse Bayern Munich and the
less successful Munich 1860, play in the top division; both use the
63,000-seat Olympic Stadium for home games.
</P>
<P>
   According to the German National Tourist Office, there are no
agents selling advance tickets to matches of the Bundesliga. Mike
Woitalla, senior editor of Soccer America magazine, visited Germany
last year for some games and said getting tickets to league games
was rarely a problem.
</P>
<P>
   But an exception is Munich during Oktoberfest (this year, from
Sept. 18 to Oct. 3) _ so you should contact the clubs for tickets
(the cheapest are for standing room) well in advance. Here's where:
</P>
<P>
   Bayern Munich, 51 Saebener Strasse, 81547 Munich; (49-89)
699-310, fax (49-89) 644-165; www &QC; .bayernmuenchen.de. Current
prices are about $11 to $28, at 1.8 marks to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   TSV Munich 1860, Ticket Management, 114 Grunwalder Strasse,
81547 Munich; (49-89) 6427-8560, fax (49-89) 6427-8585;
www.tsv1860.de (German only). Tickets, available in August with a
Visa card number, cost about $16 to $38.
</P>
<P>
   The second-division club Unterhaching (which has a good chance
for promotion to the top division) plays in a 20,000-seat stadium
in the suburbs. SpVgg Unterhaching, 1 Am Sportpark, 82008
Unterhaching; (49-89) 6155-9160, fax (49-89) 6155-91688. Tickets
are $7 to $14, for now.
</P>
<P>
   Another Bavarian option lies 95 miles north, where FC Nuremberg
plays in the 44,600-seat Frankenstadion. Contact it at 200
Valznerweiherstrasse, 90480 Nuremberg; (49-911) 940-790, fax
(49-911) 940-7977; www.1.fc.nuerenberg.com (German only). Tickets:
$22 to $47.
</P>
<P>
   The German soccer federation lists addresses, phone numbers and
schedules for Bundesliga clubs on www.dfb.t-online.de.
</P>
</TEXT>
