<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, MARCH 9
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-NUKE-SECURITY-NYT (moved on Saturday, Mar. 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, Mar. 6,
about assertions by Clinton Administration officials that China
stole nuclear secrets from an American Government laboratory owned
by the Department of Energy misspelled the given name of the Energy
Secretary who served for most of 1997 and 1998. He is Federico F.
Pena, not Frederico.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SALVADOR-VOTE (moved on Sunday, Mar. 7)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Mar. 7,
about the presidential election in El Salvador misidentified the
United States college attended by the winner, Francisco Flores. It
was Amherst College, not the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   BC-EMIR-BAHRAIN-OBIT-NYT (moved on Saturday, Mar. 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, Mar. 6,
about the death of Sheik Isa bin Salman al-Khalifa, the Emir of
Bahrain, misstated his age in some copies. He was 65, not 66.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CONGRESS-RELIEF-NYT (moved on Thursday, Mar. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Mar. 4,
about House and Senate bills for emergency aid to Central American
storm victims misstated the title of Representative Tom DeLay,
Republican of Texas. He is the majority whip, not the minority
whip.
</P>
<P>
   BC-EEOC-REFORM-NYT (moved on Sunday, Feb. 21)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Feb. 21,
about the workload of the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission
misidentified the defendant in a class action discrimination
lawsuit won by the agency. The suit resulted in a settlement with
the Mitsubishi Motor Corporation's American subsidiary, not the
Mitsubishi Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SOCSEC-POLITICS-NYT (moved on Saturday, Mar. 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, Mar. 6,
about Social Security misstated the party affiliation of
Representative Bill Archer of Texas, chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee. He is a Republican.
</P>
</TEXT>
