<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LEGIS-CAPITOLREPORT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exploratory panel adds to Bush sites on Web
 &HT;    By Austin American-Statesman staff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ There's a crowd of George W. Bush Web sites
clogging the Internet these days. Add one more.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush exploratory committee has launched georgewbush.com, the
official site of Bush's test of the presidential waters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Sunday introduced his 10-member exploratory committee,
which will raise money and determine whether there's enough
interest for Bush to jump into the race.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site includes Bush bios, news clippings, speeches and
recorded audio and video of Sunday's announcement.Keeping history
alive
</P>
<P>
   Clad in 19th-century soldier uniforms, a dozen history
re-enactors and Texas Historical Commission officials celebrated
Forts Trail Day at the Capitol on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love history, and I love explosives, so this was a natural
progression,'' said Robert Broene, who works at Fort Concho in San
Angelo. He wore boots, spurs and an 1881 helmet bedecked with a red
horsehair plume for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   The Historical Commission has worked to revamp eight forts and
one mission in West Central Texas to increase heritage tourism and
show off the region's sites.
</P>
<P>
   Health-care help proposed
</P>
<P>
   Texans could turn to an independent consumer ombudsman with
questions about health-care benefits and programs under legislation
introduced in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Elliott Naishtat, D-Austin, said the program would provide
advocates to help consumers understand and exercise their rights
when medical care or payment is delayed or denied.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investment increases
</P>
<P>
   Foreign direct investment in Texas increased 74 percent from
1987 to 1996, hitting $72.3 billion, according to the latest issue
of the state comptroller's Fiscal Notes publication. Texas jobs
created by foreign firms increased 51 percent to 317,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foreign corporations looking for political stability and
growth opportunities are looking towards the U.S., and many have
set their sights on Texas. More than 2,400 firms from abroad have
established operations in Texas,'' Comptroller Carole Keeton
Rylander said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush appoints regents, judge
</P>
<P>
   Bush announced Monday three appointments to the Texas State
University System Board of Regents and an intention to appoint a
new judge to the 215th District Court.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Diaz Dennis of San Antonio, Dionicio Flores of El Paso
and James Hayley of Texas City were appointed to the Board of
Regents. Their terms would end Feb. 1, 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Levi J. Benton of Houston was nominated to replace Judge Dwight
E. Jefferson, who is resigning from the Harris County court.
</P>
<P>
   All are subject to Senate confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
