   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- March 08, 1999 -- FALL-THEATER-REVIEW, 3-08
-- Matthew Broderick and Judy Parfitt in ``Night Must Fall,'' which
opened Monday night at the Lyceum Theater under John Tillinger's
direction. The greatest thrill of this new incarnation of the play,
even counting that moment in the second act when the whole audience
screams, is in seeing how a mothball-scented property can be turned
anew into agile and seductive theater. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- March 08, 1999 -- SCI-REP-BROWN, 3-08 --
With a degree in physics and experience as an engineer, Rep. George
E. Brown Jr. has served more than 30 years on the House Science
Committee and is currently its ranking Democrat. ``From my earliest
days, I was fascinated by science,'' says Brown, 79, who has been a
crucial supporter of manned and unmanned space exploration. ``I've
thought that science could be the basis for a better world, and
that's what I've been trying to do all these years.'' (Carol T.
Powers/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- March 08, 1999 -- BLACKMUN-FLOATER, 3-08
-- Justices of the U.S. Supreme Court, led by Chief Justice William
Rehnquist, upper left, watch as the coffin of retired Justice Harry
Blackmun is carried into the court building where it will lie in
repose on Monday. Justices looking on are, from left after
Rehnquist; Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony Kennedy, David Souter,
Clarence Thomas, Ruth Bader Ginsburg, and Stephen G. Breyer.
Blackmun, author of the 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision that legalized
abortion nationwide and more than 350 other Supreme Court rulings,
died Thursday at 90. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- March 08, 1999 -- DNA-TESTING, 3-08 -- Dr.
Margaret Wallace examines a quilt for semen evidence in the DNA lab
at the New York Medical Examiner' office. From such varied uses as
gauging the quality of caviar to tracing the lineage of the
nation's third president, DNA testing has gone from Orwellian
concept to common practice. But it is still a emotional issue,
pitting those who view it as a technological blessing against
others who see it as the ultimate invasion of privacy. (Chester
Higgins Jr. /New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- March 08, 1999 -- ONLINE-MONITORS, 3-07 --
James Alexander of Ewatch, a company that scans the Net for rumor
and innuendo. ``The chairman is a pedophile; the chairman is
arrested; the chairman has checked into a hospital under an assumed
name,'' Alexander says, rattling off recent examples of false
rumors from the dark corners of cyberspace. (Susan Farley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NATCHEZ, Miss. -- March 08, 1999 -- NATCHEZ-SCHOOL-BOS,
3-08 -- Jeanenne Angelini, a junior at Boston College School of
Education who volunteered to work at the Holy Family Catholic
School during her spring break, has an emotional farewell with
students from the third grade. The school, in continuous operation
since 1890, solicited assistance from students at Boston College
who arrived in early March to help renovate the school. (Michael
Robinson-Chavez/Boston Globe Photos) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) HOLLYWOOD, Fla. -- March 8, 1999 -- OBIT-DIMAGGIO-7,
03-08 -- Joe DiMaggio during an interview with the Times in Sept.
1998. In his 13 seasons as a Hall of Fame center fielder from 1936
to 1951 (with three years out for Army service during World War
II), he had a career average of .325 with 361 home runs and 1,537
runs batted in while the Yankees won 10 American League pennants
and 9 World Series. ``Joltin' Joe'' DiMaggio died Monday morning at
his home in Hollywood, Fla. He was 84. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) HOLLYWOOD, Fla. -- March 8, 1999 -- OBIT-DIMAGGIO-7,
03-08 -- At the Joe DiMaggio Children's Hospital at Memorial
Regional Hospital, DiMaggio signs autographs for some young fans.
The hospital's moto is ``Whether rich or poor, no child is turned
away.'' The former Yankee Clipper, whose 56-game hitting streak is
of baseball's greatest records, died at his home Monday in
Hollywood, Fla. He was 84. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) HOLLYWOOD, Fla. -- March 8, 1999 -- OBIT-DIMAGGIO-6,
03-08 -- Joe DiMaggio wearing a 1936 World Series ring, the one he
won his rookie year with the New York Yankees. All of his other
Series rings were stolen in 1960. As a surprise on Joe DiMaggio Day
in Oct. 1998, Phil Rizzuto, the Hall of Fame shortstop who was his
teammate for a decade, presented DiMaggio with a gift from George
Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner: replicas of his eight
diamond-studded World Series rings that were stolen. DiMaggio died
Monday at 84 after a battle with lung cancer and pneumonia. (Fred
R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) HOLLYWOOD, Fla. -- March 8, 1999 -- OBIT-DIMAGGIO-5,
03-08 -- ``I'm not one of those guys who looks to be in the
