<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2605 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMUGGLE-COX     03-08 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMUGGLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Latest search for Haitian survivors unsuccessful
 &HT;    By Mary Lou Pickel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The pleas of Haitian community leaders
in Miami prompted the U.S Coast Guard to launch a final search
Monday for 38 Haitian immigrants feared drowned in a weekend
smuggling disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But by 9 p.m. rescuers scanning the Atlantic Ocean as far north
as Cape Canaveral found no sign of survivors or bodies, and the
Coast Guard called off the search, Petty Officer Chet Darvy said.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Moise, a major in the U.S. Air Force Reserve who is of
Haitian descent, accompanied the Coast Guard jet on its search.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers fear as many as 40 immigrants drowned Saturday as two
boats carrying 43 people sank 26 miles east of West Palm Beach in
what could be the worst smuggling catastrophe in Florida history.
</P>
<P>
   Crew members on a passing freighter reported hearing screams
from the water around 2 a.m. Saturday. The Coast Guard rescued
three men clinging to wreckage between 5 a.m. and 8 a.m. Saturday.
They also recovered two bodies, Darvy said, and saw two more but
were unable to retrieve them.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators at the Palm Beach County Medical Examiner's office
are waiting for documents found on the two dead bodies to dry
before they try to identify them, a receptionist said.
</P>
<P>
   Fremiaud Basse, a bulldozer operator from Lake Worth, fears his
21-year-old girlfriend, Guerline Joseph, is among the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Basse, 44, who has a green card, planned to apply for American
citizenship and bring Joseph to the United States as his wife.
</P>
<P>
   He last saw Joseph on a visit to Haiti three months ago, he
said. ``Wait for me,'' he told her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Haiti and somebody (told) me my girlfriend is on the
boat,'' Basse said Monday, while waiting with others for news at
the Haitian-American Community Council in Delray Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Joseph, 35, of Pompano Beach and no relation to Guerline,
sought information on his nephew, Joel Estiverne, 21. A cousin
called Joseph Saturday night from Haiti to tell him Estiverne was
on the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph was angry that the Coast Guard had discontinued its
search Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe they'd do that to these people,'' he said. ``I
would like to bury him.''
</P>
<P>
   Art Bullock, head of the West Palm Beach Border Patrol Office,
defended the Coast Guard's decision to call off the earlier,
2,600-square-mile search. No one on board the two boats had a life
jacket, Bullock said, and it is unlikely anyone would have survived
past Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   As for the bodies, the swift Gulf Stream would have moved them
far away. ``They're up in Charleston, South Carolina, by now,''
Bullock said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard used night vision equipment to find the
survivors, Bullock said. One survivor waved a flashlight at
rescuers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only reason they saw him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the survivors are at Krome Detention Center south of
Miami and a third, Yvon Pierre-Louis, remained hospitalized in good
condition Monday at Good Samaritan Medical Center in West Palm
Beach. Border Patrol agents spoke to him once and planned to
interview him again today.
</P>
<P>
   The boats left from St. Marc, Haiti, for the Bahamas a week ago
and stopped in the Bahamas to rest on Thursday. They were expected
to reach the United States Friday night, according to a relative of
someone believed to be on board.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe smugglers were involved, but the survivors
would not say who set up the operation, investigator Kevin Douglas
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The financing (of smuggling) takes place here with
relatives,'' Bullock said. ``Hopefully, relatives will come forward
and give us information on who the arrangers are.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniella Henry, director of the Haitian-American Community
Council, said the smuggling won't stop until political and economic
conditions in Haiti improve.
</P>
<P>
   Guerline Joseph, for one, was anxious to come to the United
States, Basse said.
</P>
<P>
   When he saw her the last time in Port Au Prince, she asked him,
``Hey, Basse, what are you going to do for me?'' Basse said.
</P>
<P>
   The two wrote many letters in their two-year courtship, he said,
and she sent him a photograph of herself, which he held in his hand
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On the back she wrote, ``If you read this, you will think of
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Lou Pickel writes for The Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Joe Brogan contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
