<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0481 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2615 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TYPHOID-COX     03-08 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TYPHOID-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FDA announces voluntary recall of products linked to typhoid
patients
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General News and (l)
Lifestyle/Science-Medicine categories.)
 &HT;    By Peter Donald
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Citing evidence linking a frozen
tropical fruit to a typhoid fever outbreak in Florida, the Food and
Drug Administration on Monday announced a ``voluntary nationwide
recall'' of frozen mamey products distributed under two brand
names.
</P>
<P>
   Distributors agreed to recall the El Sembrador and La Fe brands
after those brands were found in the refrigerators of 13 people
with confirmed typhoid fever or in restaurants where they ate, the
FDA said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency warns consumers not to eat the recalled frozen mamey,
typically used to make shakes popular in the Hispanic community.
And officials urged consumers who have bought the recalled brands
to return them for a refund.
</P>
<P>
   The state agriculture department had already stopped the brands'
sale in Florida, but the FDA said they were still available in 13
other states until it announced the recall.
</P>
<P>
   Typhoid fever, a bacterial disease that can be treated with
antibiotics, can cause sustained fever, headache, constipation and
loss of appetite. Fifteen suspected or confirmed cases have been
reported in Florida since late December _three of them among Palm
Beach County residents.
</P>
<P>
   Businessmen in the frozen mamey industry said that the FDA's
conclusions were unscientific and that the recall unfairly targeted
just two of the brands on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Several hypothesized that the frozen mamey could have been
contaminated when it was processed and packaged in Guatemala. They
said that when Hurricane Mitch flooded Central America last year,
water used for crop irrigation became tainted.So other brands
supplied by Guatemala could also be affected, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the source is the problem, then anyone who was in any way
related to the source should be affected by the recall,'' said Luis
Hernandez, president of Miami-based El Sembrador, which distributes
more than 350 Hispanic food products.
</P>
<P>
   He also complained that the FDA had declined to give out test
results unless he filed a written request.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are they so secretive?'' he asked in frustration. ``I
can't get any information from anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez and others also questioned whether singling out the
two brands is warranted when tests have failed to isolate
Salmonella typhi _ the bacteria that causes typhoid fever _ in any
of the confiscated product samples.
</P>
<P>
   State agricultural officials have yet to find any typhoid fever
germs on the products. But they said the germs may have been
difficult to pinpoint because some samples were so infested with E.
coli bacteria _ a sign of fecal contamination. One official
described the frozen mamey products as ``filthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Leal of Jagua Trading in Miami, which is also affected by
the recall, said the contamination probably stemmed from unsanitary
water in the wake of last year's storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been in this business for 25 years and this is the
first time this has happened,'' Leal said.
</P>
<P>
   Jagua Trading sells frozen mamey produced by Agrodex of
Guatemala to El Sembrador, La Fe, other firms and retailers. The
recall affects the 5-pound, clear plastic bags that Jagua markets
to retailers without a brand name: Its label reads ``Mamey, Mammea
americana, Product of Guatemala.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done a voluntary recall on their (the FDA's) word,''
Leal said. ``The last thing I want to do is hurt the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Leal said his company has already lost half a million dollars
because of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   An FDA official said the agency zeroed in on the products after
they were connected to the typhoid fever outbreak in an
investigation by the Miami-Dade County Health Department. The
investigation found that people who got sick were far more likely
to have eaten frozen mamey than healthy people.
</P>
<P>
   The government and the companies had a responsibility to protect
the public from any further outbreak by pursuing a recall, the FDA
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Donald wrires for The Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
