<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2619 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-ANCIENT-SAMPLES-C     03-08 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-ANCIENT-SAMPLES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida stone circle may be 'culturally, archaeologically
significant'
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Charcoal at the Miami Circle dates to the
Mayan era _ approximately 2,000 years ago _ according to
carbon-dating results to be presented to Gov. Jeb Bush and the
Florida Cabinet today.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and the Cabinet are scheduled to vote today on whether to
approve $2 million or more in state money to help preserve the
stone circle found at a Dade County development site. The results
make eventual approval more likely, Cabinet aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the circle is related to Mayan culture, attorney
and archeologist Harvey Oyer in West Palm Beach said a date that
old means the site may well prove to be ``the most culturally and
archaeologically significant pre-Colombian site in Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Testing firm Beta Analytic Inc. of Miami put the age of two
charcoal samples from the site at between 365 B.C. and 415 A.D.,
according to a letter written by lab director Darden G. Hood and
shown Monday to state officials. The dates are consistent with the
time Mayan culture existed in Mexico, Belize and Guatemala, keeping
alive the possibility that the circle is somehow linked to Mayan
civilization, Oyer said. Artifacts of volcanic rock found at the
site raised the Mayan possibility earlier. A number of scholars say
it's unlikely Mayans lived in Florida and explain it by trade
between Mayans and Tequesta Indians or other native populations
capable of travel.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the circle may shed light on how people lived in
Florida at the time of Jesus. Bones and other objects show humans
existed for more than 20,000 years in Florida, yet there are few
clues about the culture of peoples in the state before the Spanish
came in the 1500s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone was on that site 2,000 years ago burning something,
whether it was a campfire, or tanning leather, or something else,
and that is significant,'' Oyer said. ``If the stones were there at
the same time the charcoal was produced, and not added later,
that's even more significant.''
</P>
<P>
   The stones may suggest some kind of religious or trading center
near the mouth of the Miami River.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Ron Silver, D-Miami, said he opposes the state's
spending any money until more is known. At issue is whether
government _ state, local or federal _ should be allowed to stop a
developer who stands to lose money on his investment.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will be briefed on the issue this morning and has not
indicated a position on the issue, a spokesman said. Aides believe
the Cabinet is leaning toward approving the money, but with plenty
of strings attached _ such as requiring more information and
research _ so that nothing is likely to happen quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Education Commissioner Tom Gallagher said he will support the
plan as long as the state is not taking on the financial burden by
itself, but is a partner with Miami-Dade County and others.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Elmore writes for The Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
