</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORTIS-AMERICAN-5707ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORTIS TO BUY AMERICAN BANKERS FOR $2.6 BILLION PLUS DEBT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ga.)  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fortis, one of the biggest insurance and banking companies in
Europe, said Monday that it would buy American Bankers Insurance
Group, a Miami insurer that was the object of a bidding war by two
big American companies last year, for $2.6 billion plus the
assumption of nearly $200 million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Fortis plans to combine American Bankers with its American
Security Group in Atlanta, giving the new entity an overwhelmingly
dominant market share of 30 percent in the business of selling
insurance that pays off credit-card balances and loans on such
things as furniture and major appliances when customers die, lose
their jobs or are disabled.
</P>
<P>
   This credit-related insurance is enormously profitable, but
Consumers Union and other critics say that instead of buying
coverage on specific kinds of debt, consumers should buy broader
coverage, like life or disability insurance, which is
proportionately less expensive and provides greater benefits.
Fortis executives say that many customers for credit-related
insurance cannot afford broader coverages and that the insurance on
their car loan or credit-card balance may be the only insurance
they think they can afford.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition by Fortis, which has headquarters in Brussels,
Belgium, and Utrecht, Netherlands, was the second by a big European
insurer in a little more than two weeks. In mid-February, Aegon NV
said it was buying TransAmerica Corp. of San Francisco for $9.7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts in Europe and the United States say more purchases are
expected as Europeans seek to expand in the world's largest
insurance market. Europeans have been able to strike better deals
in the United States than at home, said Stephen Dias, an analyst
for Goldman, Sachs in London. They are ``very optimistic'' about
growth prospects for variable annuities and other products aimed at
Americans who are approaching retirement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Henjo Hielkema, the Fortis executive in charge of its insurance
operations, said the deal with American Bankers, which had revenue
of $2.5 billion last year, would nearly double Fortis' insurance
revenue in the United States, to about $5.7 billion. Fortis bought
the holding company of American Security and a sister company in
1980 as its second acquisition in the United States after buying a
small group health insurers two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   It now has half a dozen units in the United States selling
coverage for such things as health care, funeral expenses and
protection for providers of small mortgages. The parent company,
which bought Generale Bank, Belgium's largest bank, last June, had
revenue of $37 billion last year, about 66 percent from banking.
</P>
<P>
   Fortis' offer, which must be approved by shareholders, works out
to $55 a share in cash. That is a nearly 19 percent premium over
American Bankers closing price on Friday. But it is $12 less than
Cendant Corp., a franchiser and direct marketer, agreed to pay
after edging out American International Group, the big
international insurer based in New York. Cendant made an
unsolicited offer of $58 a share after American International
Group, often referred to as AIG, announced an agreement with
American Bankers at $47 a share. AIG matched the $58 offer but
would go no higher.
</P>
<P>
   But Cendant was forced to back out of the deal last fall because
of an accounting scandal that sent its shares plummeting, and
American Bankers went back on the market.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Analysts in Europe and the United States said Fortis was paying
a top price _2.4 times the book value of American Bankers. But a
consistent return on equity of about 15 percent and annual growth
of about 20 percent make the Miami company ``quite attractive,''
said Michael Lindsay, an insurance analyst at Lehman Brothers in
London.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies with high returns and high growth don't come along
very often,'' he said, ``and when they are for sale they do tend to
command substantial multiples.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors appeared to approve of the deal. Shares of American
Bankers rose $5.625 Monday, to $52. Fortis is owned 50-50 by Fortis
of Belgium, whose shares rose 0.51 euro, to 34.01, and Fortis NV of
the Netherlands, whose shares increased 0.40 euro, to 35.05.
</P>
<P>
   Fortis said it expected to cut $100 million out of operating
expenses as it combines American Bankers and American Security
Group. Some of that savings, said Lewis Phillips, an insurance
analyst at Fox-Pitt, Kelton in London, is expected to come through
job cuts. American Bankers has 2,950 employees, and American
Security has 1,450.
</P>
<P>
   J. Kerry Clayton, an executive vice president at Fortis
headquarters in the United States, said, ``We think this will be a
very profitable acquisition for us.'' He said about half of the
savings would come from ``combining the infrastructure'' of the two
companies. He also said that ``significant operations'' would
continue in both Miami and Atlanta and that many of the job cuts
would come through attrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a cost-driven deal,'' he said. ``This is really
about putting together two high-growth, high-return companies so
they can achieve a greater leadership position.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, American Bankers agreed, without admitting
wrongdoing, to pay regulators in 39 states up to $15 million to
settle a range of accusations, including using unapproved marketing
materials and failing to make sure that all agents selling its
products were properly licensed.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton said Fortis spent more time on the regulatory questions
than on any other aspect of its review of American Bankers. ``We
have a good history with the regulators,'' he said, ``and we wanted
to make sure they had taken proper action so these things wouldn't
recur. And they have done that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
