<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIT-NEWCOURT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIT TO ACQUIRE NEWCOURT IN STOCK SWAP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CIT Group Inc., the commercial finance concern based in
Livingston, N.J., said Monday that it would acquire Newcourt Credit
Group Inc., a Toronto concern, in a stock swap valued at about $4.2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will create one of the largest commercial finance
companies in the country. CIT has specialized in lending primarily
to smaller and midsized companies, but the merger will give it
access to such well-known Newcourt clients as Dell Computer Corp.
and Lucent Technologies Inc. and also expand its operations in
Canada and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said no layoffs are currently planned, although a
hiring freeze is in place and attrition is expected to reduce the
size of the combined companies' work force, which currently numbers
about 8,200 people.
</P>
<P>
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Shares of CIT fell
56.25 cents, to $30.1875, while Newcourt's shares rose 81.25 cents,
to $26.625. According to the terms of the transaction, which had
already been unanimously approved by each company's board of
directors, each Newcourt share will be exchanged for 0.92 CIT
share. The acquisition valued Newcourt at $28.29 a share, a 9.6
percent premium to Friday's closing price of $25.8125.
</P>
<P>
   Albert R. Gamper, CIT's president and chief executive, will
become chairman and chief executive of the new company, which will
retain the CIT name. Steven K. Hudson, Newcourt's president and
chief executive, will be president of the merged company.
</P>
<P>
   CIT is regarded by analysts as a conservative, risk-averse
lender. It became a public company just last year after a large
Japanese bank, Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd., sold a big portion of a
stake it held in CIT.
</P>
<P>
   The merger is expected to be completed in the third quarter,
after which Dai-Ichi will own about 24 percent of the merged
company. Nomura Securities and Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce,
Newcourt's biggest shareholders, will respectively own 6 percent
and 5 percent of the new company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will have more than $50 billion in assets, $2.2
billion in annual revenue and after-tax profits of more than $500
million. Eleven of the new company's 20-member board will come from
CIT, with the remainder from Newcourt.
</P>
<P>
   Newcourt's shares have been pounded over the last year as
investors dumped the stock of companies like Newcourt that were
considered to be overly aggressive lenders. But recent merger
speculation fueled a rise in Newcourt's shares, although recent
market rumors had identified Germany's Deutsche Bank AG as
Newcourt's most likely suitor.
</P>
<P>
   CIT had been looking for a merger partner over the last year and
began seriously discussing the possibility of a deal with Newcourt
a little more than a month ago, according to analysts who were
briefed on the talks.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan advised CIT in the merger, while Goldman, Sachs &AMP;
Co. and Canadian Imperial Bank advised Newcourt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
