<HEADLINE>
SIEMENS BUYS 2 COMPANIES TO ENTER DATA NETWORKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Siemens AG of Germany became the latest European maker of
traditional telephone equipment to push into the market for data
communications gear when it announced Monday that it had acquired
two private U.S. companies and invested in a third.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens said it would fold the two acquisitions and parts of its
existing U.S. operations into a new subsidiary called Unisphere
Solutions Inc., based in Burlington, Mass. Siemens said it would
initially commit $1 billion to the venture.
</P>
<P>
   Makers of traditional telephone systems are rushing to meet the
fast-growing demand for data-networking equipment, which is being
fueled largely by the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Alcatel of France, one of Siemens' traditional
European rivals, said it had agreed to buy two U.S. data
communications companies, Xylan Corp. and Assured Access Technology
Inc., for more than $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Senior data-networking executives said Monday that Ericsson of
Sweden could be the next to attempt a big data-networking splash,
potentially within a week. Ericsson declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Siemens said it had acquired Castle Networks Inc.,
a private data-networking company based in Westford, Mass., and
Argon Networks Inc., a private data-networking company based in
Littleton, Mass., and that it had made an equity investment in
Accelerated Networks Inc., a private company based in Moorpark,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens did not disclose the terms of the deals. When asked
about the terms at a news conference in New York Monday, Anthony T.
Maher, a director of Siemens' information and communication
networks group, said, ``the best source is The New York Times,''
referring to an article published last week. Last week's article
cited executives close to Siemens' planning as saying that the
company had agreed to pay about $300 million for Castle, about $240
million for Argon and had agreed to invest $30 million in
Accelerated.
</P>
<P>
   The executives also said in the article that Siemens was in
preliminary discussions with the 3Com Corp. about paying $1.2
billion for the 3Com unit that sells advanced networking equipment
to telephone companies. Maher said at the news conference that that
contention ``wasn't entirely accurate.'' 3Com declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   In forming Unisphere, Siemens is trying to combine its strengths
as one of Europe's largest manufacturers with the agility of a
small independent company. To run the unit, Siemens hired Martin C.
Clague, formerly general manager for global network computing
solutions at IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to potential criticism that, as a 33-year IBM
veteran, he may not be well suited to running a small, nimble
operation, Clague said: ``There is nothing like experience in
managing a matrix and in managing an organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the evolution of data communications, he added:
``I've been in this Internet space for three years, and it was
network computers before that and client-server before that. So I
know this space.''
</P>
<P>
   Clague and Maher said Unisphere would consider additional
acquisitions. Jeff Matros, a former senior Siemens executive, said
that even if Siemens' new strategy did not pan out, at least
someone would benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was very positive,'' said Matros, who until June
was vice president for marketing and business development for
Siemens' data communications group and who is now a general partner
at Walden International Investment Group, a venture capital firm,
``certainly for the entrepreneurs in Massachusetts, having another
large traditional telecom company with lots of cash to burn on the
prowl in the Boston area.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
