<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-IPO-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTE AT GOLDMAN APPROVES LATEST PLAN TO OFFER SHARES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The partners of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. reaffirmed their
decision to take their firm public Monday but learned that the man
behind the plan, Jon S. Corzine, would leave as soon as the firm
sold shares.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, who had tirelessly nudged fellow partners to abandon
their longstanding opposition to issuing shares since he became
head of the firm in 1994, said he would give up his remaining
duties ``as of the close of the offering.'' Henry M. Paulson Jr.
will remain as the sole chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, 52, was forced to relinquish his executive
responsibilities at a meeting of the firm's executive committee in
early January, a rare mutiny at a firm known for management
stability. Corzine remained as nonexecutive chairman, nominally to
oversee Goldman's transition from a private partnership to a public
company.
</P>
<P>
   Though some people at the firm said that Corzine had continued
to help shape the share offering, others said that his role since
January had been mostly ceremonial.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's public offering is primarily about money, and when it
comes to money, people often do not have long memories. But the
paradox of Corzine's departure is still fresh. Goldman partners had
rejected the idea of going public half a dozen times over the last
two decades until Corzine, regarded by some at the firm as a
skillful communicator, quietly shepherded the issue to a favorable
vote last June.
</P>
<P>
   But he paid a price. To assuage some early qualms among senior
partners, Corzine promoted his No. 2, Paulson, to be his co-equal,
a move that backfired when the two did not work well together.
Other executives also soured on Corzine when the firm postponed its
public offering in September, a decision attributed in part to
heavy losses in bond trading last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a case of using all your chips to try to fashion a pact,
and then you don't have any chips left,'' said Samuel Hayes, a
Harvard Business School professor.
</P>
<P>
   Like some other past leaders of Goldman, including Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin, Corzine rose to the executive suite from
the bond-trading floor, and he may turn out to be the last of a
breed. As a trader, Corzine was long seen as more comfortable than
some other officers with taking risks in the capital markets, a
business that has generated more than 40 percent of Goldman's
pretax profits in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But stock market investors frown on companies that have
unpredictable profits, and trading, while at times hugely
profitable, is by nature volatile. Paulson, in contrast, comes from
the investment banking side of the business, which generates
steadier fee revenue from clients and does not require the firm to
take as many risks with its own money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trading is really anathema to a public investor; they pummel
any company that hands them a surprise,'' Hayes said. ``So it seems
unlikely that we will see another leader of Corzine's profile.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Corzine will still benefit from the two- to threefold increase
in the value of his shares that is expected when the firm goes
public because his equity stake will be converted into new Goldman
shares with the same premium other partners receive, said one
person close to the situation, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the firm's most senior partners, Corzine is thought to
hold shares that would be valued in the neighborhood of $150
million. Like other partners, however, he will have to wait several
years before he is eligible to sell the bulk of his restricted
stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The completion of the public offering will mark a logical and
appropriate point for me to move on in my career and life,''
Corzine said in a statement. He declined to comment beyond that
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The partners voted overwhelmingly Monday for a revised plan to
take the firm public, Goldman officials said. The firm hopes to
sell 10 percent to 15 percent of its shares at a price that would
value the firm at $21 billion to $25 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The firm announced the appointment of David Viniar as chief
financial officer and Barry Zubrow as chief administrative officer.
Goldman also said that its first board would comprise four
insiders, one alumnus and three outsiders. The insiders are
Paulson, Robert J. Hurst, John A. Thain and John L. Thornton. The
alumnus, a limited partner who led the firm in the 1980s, is John
L. Weinberg. The outside directors were not named.
</P>
</TEXT>
