<HEADER>
A2637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WASTE-MARKETPLACE-600     03-08 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASTE-MARKETPLACE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: SOLID-WASTE GIANT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Texas)  (mk) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA AND LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Allied Waste Industries announced Monday that it would
acquire Browning-Ferris Industries, a much bigger rival in the
trash hauling business, Allied's message was simple: We can better
manage those huge assets.
</P>
<P>
   With its $7.3 billion leveraged takeover of Browning-Ferris _
plus the assumption of $1.8 billion of Browning-Ferris debt _
Allied Waste will be the No. 2 player in the industry behind Waste
Management Inc., and it is betting that its more integrated and
focused approach to handling solid waste can create a fleet-footed
giant that produces profit growth in the high double digits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is, we're teaming our management with their
assets,'' Thomas Van Weelden, the chief executive at Allied Waste,
said in an interview Monday. ``The story here is not consolidation;
the story here is focusing on growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Although shares of Allied, which was the No. 3 trash hauler,
fell sharply on Friday on speculation about a possible stock deal,
the share price recovered some of that ground Monday, climbing
$1.9375, to $16.9375. Shares of Browning-Ferris, which traded just
above $30 a month ago, soared for the second day, up $4.125, to
$38.875.
</P>
<P>
   With the deal, the trash hauling industry, once run by small,
private operators, is further concentrating into a business
dominated by a handful of national companies with huge fleets of
trucks and enormous landfills. The big players, however, are under
growing pressure to become leaner and more profitable.
</P>
<P>
   So when the boards of Allied and Browning-Ferris voted on Sunday
night to create a company with about $6.6 billion in revenue, just
over half the $12 billion 1998 revenue of Waste Management,
executives at Allied also decided that significant cost savings and
layoffs would be necessary to generate profit growth in the high
double digits. They project a 30 percent profit gain in the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said the deal was good for shareholders of
Browning-Ferris, which had recently begun to turn around a slumping
business. But if Allied shareholders are to benefit, Allied
executives must now find a way to work their magic on a much larger
company while paying off the sizable debt load from the takeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my concern,'' said James Kelleher, an analyst at Argus
Research in New York. ``They're assuming the best of all possible
worlds to service the debt. There's a lot that could happen between
now and the $45-deal date in the third quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Although such a leveraged takeover is unusual, this is the
second time in less than a year that a giant trash hauler has been
taken over by a smaller rival. (A year ago, USA Waste acquired
Waste Management in a $13 billion deal.) Wall Street analysts say
that industry executives now realize that a focused strategy is
just as important as size in the waste management business.
</P>
<P>
   At Browning-Ferris, after years of aggressive acquisitions and
expansion into everything from recycling to hazardous waste
removal, shareholders had been pressing the company to focus more
closely on its North American business, and on Monday, Allied
executives said the newly formed company would do just that.
</P>
<P>
   The deal began last spring when Allied Waste and Browning-Ferris
discussed a stock merger. At the time, people close to the deal
said, Browning-Ferris executives were not eager to sell, hoping
instead to improve the company's profitability on their own. But
over time they became more open to the idea, in part, because a
handful of Browning-Ferris' board members supported it.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Negotiations heated up at the end of February. Goldman, Sachs &AMP;
Co. was hired by Browning-Ferris to advise on the transaction,
while Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, among others, advised Allied's
management. Browning-Ferris initially wanted cash, a person close
to the talks said, up to $49 a share. The companies agreed on $45.
Then Allied, along with its two majority shareholders, Apollo
Management and Blackstone Capital Partners, both of which supported
a deal, began arranging financing.
</P>
<P>
   Several banks were asked to commit funds for the deal at the end
of February and to agree to put up the money for the buyout
regardless of whether other investors could be enlisted. By March
3, one person close to the talks said, three institutions _ Chase
Manhattan, Citibank and DLJ Capital Funding _ had committed
themselves to provide the $9.5 billion that Allied needed to buy
Browning-Ferris.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to that, several investors said they would buy a total of
$1 billion in convertible preferred stock, including Apollo
Management, Blackstone Capital Partners, DLJ Merchant Banking
Partners and Greenwich Street Capital Partners. By Thursday, the
two companies had agreed in concept to a deal and to continue
talking over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Allied's stock plunged about $5 a share, or 25
percent. The company was asked by the New York Stock Exchange to
make a statement, but did not. Several bankers, along with Apollo
and Blackstone, double-checked their numbers to make sure the deal
was sound. After their analysis was finished, the two companies
hammered out the final details of the acquisition, meeting well
past midnight on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Van Weelden, the chief executive at Allied, which is based in
Scottsdale, Ariz., said he expected some layoffs, particularly in
Houston, where Browning-Ferris has headquarters, but that the key
to driving profits at the new company would be combining a
decentralized management style with a vertically integrated
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to own all the pieces,'' Van Weelden said. ``We
believe in vertical integration.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to those who worry about the leverage in the buyout,
Van Weelden cited his company's acquisition of Laidlaw Co., a trash
hauler about three times the size of Allied.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a kind of repeat; this is exactly what we did with
Laidlaw,'' he said. ``We know how to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Wall Street analysts, however, say that even after all
the cost savings, Allied may have to cope with a large debt load
and the possibility of an economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were to run into a recession, the deal could be
breached,'' said Melville Cody, an analyst at Sanders Morris Mundy,
a brokerage firm in Houston. ``But right now we're in a good
environment for waste management.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts, recalling the problems of Browning-Ferris and
the old Waste Management Co., before it was acquired by USA Waste,
wonder whether Allied could become too large and unwieldy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allied has a better management team and a better track record
than Browning-Ferris,'' said Charles Moody, publisher of American
Waste Digest in Pottstown, Pa. ``But any time you triple your size,
you're going to have new problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
