<SLUG> BC-BOOK-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL BOOK AWARD WINNERS NAMED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We Wish To Inform You That Tomorrow We Will Be Killed With Our
Families,'' Philip Gourevitch's account of the 1994 massacres in
Rwanda, on Monday was named the best nonfiction book of last year
by the National Book Critics Circle.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing the book for The New York Times, Wole Soyinka, the
Nigerian playwright, described it as a ``grim book this and a
burden on world conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   To understand what happened in Rwanda, Soyinka wrote, one must
imagine not only the Nazis' Final Solution but also that ``nearly
the entirety of the German population participated in the
liquidation of the Jews.'' The book was published by Farrar, Straus
&AMP; Giroux.
</P>
<P>
   The winner in fiction was Alice Munro's ``The Love of a Good
Woman,'' a collection of eight short stories published by Alfred A.
Knopf. In a review in The Times, Michael Gorra, who teaches English
at Smith College, wrote that ``Munro's feel for her own characters
is ... as pure as Chekhov's.''
</P>
<P>
   The collection's long title story, Gorra wrote, was typical of
Ms. Munro's artistry. On a Saturday morning in 1951, three boys
discover the body of the local optometrist, who has drowned, but
instead of notifying police, they first return home to eat lunch.
``In presenting the complicated reasons for their delay,'' Gorra
wrote, ``Munro manages to articulate the entire social structure
and moral history of the town in which they live.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner in biography was ``A Beautiful Mind,'' published by
Simon &AMP; Schuster. Written by Sylvia Nasar, an economics writer for
The Times, it is a biography of John Forbes Nash Jr., a
mathematical genius who laid the foundations for modern game theory
that influenced mathematics, economics and eventually Cold War
strategic thinking about nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   It is also an account of Nash's descent into schizophrenia for
three decades and his puzzling recovery in the 1980s, culminating
in his winning the 1994 Nobel Prize in Economics. Reviewing the
book for The Times, Simon Singh, the author of ``Fermat's Enigma:
The Quest to Solve the World's Greatest Mathematical Problem,''
called the biography ``a touching account of a man caught between
genius and madness.''
</P>
<P>
   The award for poetry was given to Marie Ponsot's ``The Bird
Catcher,'' published by Knopf. For criticism, the award went to
Gary Giddins' ``Visions of Jazz: The First Century,'' published by
Oxford University Press. The winner of the Nona Balakian Citation
for Excellence in Reviewing was Albert Mobilio, a New York-based
critic and poet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
