A2773 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     03-08 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOLTING JOE WAS MAN OF MYSTERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We will never know the real Joe DiMaggio because he guarded his
privacy all the way to the grave. But to appreciate him and
understand why countless others admired him, all you have to
understand is the times in which he played.
</P>
<P>
   If DiMaggio, who passed away Monday at the age of 84, had played
in this era, he'd have been Don Mattingly.
</P>
<P>
   Skillful and sophisticated, dignified but hardly deified. The
quiet carriage that passed for class and dignity in DiMaggio's day
wouldn't have passed muster in today's image-is-everything world.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio's personality, like his natty suits, was perfectly
tailored for the times. He was the unapologetic product of a
country in the throes of a depression, in the grips of a war, in
the embrace of immigrants, in the clasp of industrialization and
urbanization.
</P>
<P>
   From 1936 to 1951 _ minus the three years he served in the Army
during World War II _ he patrolled center field for the preeminent
team in the preeminent city in the preeminent sport in America.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees of DiMaggio's day were the Denver Broncos, Chicago
Bulls, Detroit Red Wings, Tiger Woods, Pete Sampras and Jeff Gordon
all rolled into one. Those Bronx Bombers were the first
uber-athletes of the urban age. And there in the center of it all,
literally, was DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   He was an Italian-American immigrant's son, a Californian by
birth and a loner by nature. It wasn't just his unfathomable
56-game hitting streak in 1941 that made DiMaggio larger than the
city in which he played, larger even than the sport he loved.
DiMaggio's stoicism played well in the pre-television era, before
athletes started adjusting their personalities to make them as
colorful as the pictures being beamed by satellite all over the
globe.
</P>
<P>
   How quaint it all seems now, the idea of affection being
showered on those who were self-made, not self-promoted.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio's hitting streak in 1941 captured the imagination of
the nation, much like Mark McGwire's home run derby did this past
season. A New York disc jockey penned the lyrics to a song that was
set to music by Les Brown and his band of renown. A sampling:
</P>
<P>
   ``Who started baseball's streak that's got us all aglow?
</P>
<P>
   He's just a man and not a freak, Jolting Joe DiMaggio.''
</P>
<P>
   Say this about sports celebrity: It certainly pulses to a
different beat these days. Listened to any of Shaquille O'Neal's
albums lately?
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing DiMaggio defended more fastidiously than
center field was his privacy. His first marriage was to an actress,
Dorothy Arnold; his most famous, to Marilyn Monroe, and yet we
already know more about Dennis Rodman and Carmen Electra than
DiMaggio ever revealed about either of his loves.
</P>
<P>
   His discretion would be called something different today: dull.
</P>
<P>
   As a prodigy in the Pacific Coast League _ he put together a
61-game hitting streak with the San Francisco Seals in 1933 _
DiMaggio developed a keen eye for more than pitches. He could spot
sycophants from five paces and he kept them at an arm's length,
along with just about everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   He'd sit in the clubhouse for hours so as not to have to face
the crowds waiting for him outside. What was tolerated then might
today cost him a few All-Star votes from disgruntled fans, to say
nothing of the reporters left cooling their heels on deadline.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio wasn't a recluse; he often was spotted at nightclubs,
in the company of esteemed figures such as Ernest Hemingway (thus
explaining Hemingway's reference to DiMaggio in the novel, ``The
Old Man and the Sea.'')
</P>
<P>
   If DiMaggio wasn't exactly a wallflower, neither was he a
pushover. He was one of the first players to hold out for more
money (he did so initially in 1938, sitting out for $45,000 before
settling for $25,000). He also was among the first to charge for an
autograph.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for DiMaggio's signature remained keen to the end and
therein lies a lesson for today's high-profile athletes. Never mind
full disclosure, there's nothing like a little mystery to sustain a
market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
