<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2776 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILAN-FASHION-ART-500     03-08 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILAN-FASHION-ART-500(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PRAISE OF SHORT MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ The bigger names in Italian fashion may lead
impeccably civilized lives up in their art-filled palazzi, but give
one of these titans of chic a rich, feel-good dish like risotto and
suddenly the napkin is under the chin and he's hogging the whole
platter of congealed rice for himself. Such a scene was recounted
last week after a lunch for a small group of magazine editors, and
while the witnesses said they didn't go hungry (the designer's cook
fed them pasta), the risotto story hints at the self-centered
isolation of Milan's Old Guard, who for too long have held onto the
pot.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the art on the walls, the fabulous homes, the ``poetry''
of the latest collection. Do any of these fashion biggies ever do
anything as normal as going out to the movies? They ought to. They
might learn something new.
</P>
<P>
   That thought lingered over the last days of the Italian fall
collections, which ended Friday night. Once-innovative figures like
Gianfranco Ferre seemed hopelessly mired in old glamour formulas _
hellions in black leather, in Ferre's case, throwing down their
chinchilla parkas and demanding star treatment, with Louis Prima in
the background. It was heavy weather: fattening mohair dresses with
feathery tufts sprouting along one sleeve; long split skirts in
overlapping panels of leather and tweed; chunky fur ponchos and
blazers lined in sheared mink, and a skintight black dress with a
wide elliptical collar fitted, if you can imagine, with a metal
plate.
</P>
<P>
   A final passage of broadtail and leather corsets with
gathered-up tartan skirts sprayed partly black were intriguing
enough, but Ferre treats glamour _ and fabric _ as something to be
wrestled into submission. Or as he said in his show notes, the tone
of his collection was ``as if a wild beast, suddenly turned docile,
were held on a belt-leash.'' Don't think we'll go there.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Donatella Versace, with her ironed hair and
wrist full of diamonds, grasps the point of being out in the world,
even if there's a limited market for her kind of outrageousness.
``You don't like green python boots?'' she said before her show as
models sipped Champagne through straws. ``OK. Then go somewhere
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Versace presented a fast-paced collection of disco velvet
dresses, rhinestone-studded white mink and turquoise-beaded gowns,
all played out in a mood-room atmosphere of dark draperies and a
glassy catwalk raised over a make-believe coral reef.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Versace thrives in the unambiguous world of high-strung
sexual glamour. On Friday night, as Juliette Lewis, the actress,
bobbed her well-shod foot to the thumping music, the upshot was
fairly devastating: sleek Prince of Wales tunics with girlish
Swiss-dot cuffs, pinstriped leather trousers and white mink jackets
salted with mother-of-pearl paillettes. Yet some of the clothes
looked poorly made, and although Ms. Versace has plenty of
attitude, one can't help wishing she had more of her late brother
Gianni's historical references. History was no burden to him, least
of all his own.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Stefano Gabbana and Domenico Dolce are also constantly on the
move _ nothing old-clothesy about their collection. The design team
sent out a dazzling montage of daisy-appliqued stilettos, tie-dyed
fur in electric cocktail lounge hues, winking hologram skirts in
``Fantasia'' blues and yellows, and cowhide jackets and buffalo
fleece pants recalling the delicious days of spaghetti westerns and
Sergio Leone.
</P>
<P>
   And so are Jil Sander and Miuccia Prada, who put their
individual spin on minimalism, with Ms. Prada doing in her Miu Miu
line what she had failed to do in her main collection earlier:
charming her audience with opal satin dresses with chiffon hems,
trousers with rib-knitted cuffs spreading out over the shoes like
pureed peas, and hilarious duck boots with heels and fat tongues _
nothing like L.L. Bean's at all.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Prada based the collection on a passage from a Tim Burton
short story about Stick Boy and Match Girl, whose gist is that each
thinks the other is hot. ``I think young guys are so charming,''
she explained. ``I like the way young people are different and so
sweet with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   That came through, as young men and women trooped out in
sweaters and hooded jerseys in woodsy greens, pumpkins and browns.
Bootleg trousers were tied at the ankles with cords so they spread
over the tops of shoes _ a new look. There were drizzles of
folkloric ruffles, fanny packs integrated into wool coats and many
coming-and-going clothes (which, for those not yet in the know, are
clothes with the front in one fabric and the back in another).
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when a Rifat Ozbek show signaled something new.
Ozbek still has his camp followers, but his current asymmetrical
hemlines, fuzzy coats, leggings and silver-glazed chiffon merely
endorse what's already out there. As for the idea of giving utility
clothes futuristic glamour, that might have been all right if his
message hadn't been delivered to the soggy timpani of the ``Star
Wars'' theme.
</P>
<P>
   Other collections rounding out the week were those by Marni and
Victor Alfaro, who competently ticked off the season's trends _
boiled wool skirts, minimalist separates with a crust of beaded
trim, high heels, forest hues _ but without bravura. Marni went
chaotically rustic, with charming variations on the Arts and Crafts
theme, including boiled wool blanket skirts, folkloric prints and
ruffles and quilted wraps of the bed jacket genre. The clothes had
a sweet, literate mayhem, as if Red Riding Hood had gone skipping
over to Grandma's and found frumpy old Virginia Woolf instead.
</P>
<P>
   But to the high points of the week. What Ms. Prada has in common
with Ms. Versace and Karl Lagerfeld for Fendi _ and, for that
matter, Tom Ford, whose Gucci show was a Xanadu of inspired flash _
is a restlessness with what's old and familiar. Collectively, they
have the attention span of a gnat, which isn't so bad in a business
where at least half the audience seems perpetually to be looking up
at the ceiling as if to say, ``Next.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Ms. Sander, whose clothes can sometimes seem caught in a
cerebral straitjacket, comes down from her ivory tower to push
fashion forward _ and play with periwinkle coats blocked out in a
grid of seams, asymmetrically pleated skirts in copper papery satin
silk, spongy new synthetics and an interlocking chain of seams that
resemble a genetic code, but is, in fact, just candy for the
ravenous eye.
</P>
<P>
   The Fendi show held nothing arty or serious. In fact, the
pressing question as the guests took their seats was whether
Carlyne Cerf's Jack Russell terrier, Jack, should have a Fendi fur
of his own. Ms. Cerf, a Marie Claire editor, had outfitted him with
an Hermes collar and leash; and on rainy days in Milan, Jack wore a
Burberry town coat. But she looked doubtful when Andre Leon Talley
of Vogue suggested a Fendi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, he might eat it,'' Ms. Cerf said.
</P>
<P>
   Talley laughed. ``But so what?''
</P>
<P>
   That remark would probably thrill Lagerfeld, Fendi's designer.
After all, he had taken out the linings in most of his coats,
except some in silver sable, so what more could a dog do to a look
that was, in effect, destroyed? Lagerfeld showed furs _ mink,
squirrel, summer ermine _ sheared so close to the skin, and then
dyed in sorbet hues of lemon, melon, pistachio, coffee and palest
blue, that they looked as indefinably glamorous as a woman running
out in the rain in a silk wrapper to fetch her paper. ``The idea
was to treat fur no different than fabric,'' Lagerfeld explained.
``Treat it like nothing, and it looks modern.''
</P>
<P>
   Lagerfeld has been in this deconstructivist territory before,
but rarely with more confidence. The results were beautiful. There
was Stella Tennant swooping out in a patchwork coat of sheared
mink. Mimsy-looking bed jackets with belled sleeves snuggled over
knit separates. Some coats were covered in a gauze cobweb, while a
birch-colored coat in sheared squirrel was trimmed at its raw edges
in gauzy filigree. The show was a testament to Lagerfeld's
far-flung brilliance, as well as to the Fendi workrooms, and
devotees of the ``baguette'' handbag can look forward to new
versions _ in beaded patchwork, sheared mink and a perfectly corny
fisherman knit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
