<SLUG> BC-TEN-EVERT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELES CLOBBERED BY NAGYOVA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   She remembered her racquet, but Monica Seles picked the wrong
day to forget her thinking cap when she headed to the stadium court
Monday for her third-round Evert Cup encounter with Slovakia's
Henrieta Nagyova. It was not the best tactic in a sport that prides
itself on being a mind game, and a dazed Seles paid for her
negligence: She found herself clobbered, 6-2, 6-4, in just over an
hour in Indian Wells, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   For Seles, it was a painfully long hour, as she became the
eighth seeded player to depart the women's half of this coed desert
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mind definitely wasn't there from the start till the end,''
said the third-seeded Seles, who reached the semifinals of her
previous two events in 1999, the Australian Open and Pan Pacific
Open in Tokyo, and was then hobbled by an ankle sprain for a month.
But on Monday her shortcomings were mental, not physical. ``My head
wasn't there; my game wasn't there,'' Seles said, sighing.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she nudged the ball across the net as if she wasn't
quite sure she wanted to part with it. ``I really was just pushing
the ball back today,'' said Seles, better known for pulverizing
balls.
</P>
<P>
   Seles performed like a runner whose sneakers inexplicably stuck
to the starting block. By the time Seles realized that something
significant was missing from her arsenal, the 27th-ranked Nagyova,
a ponytailed 20-year-old who had never beaten a top 10 player, had
sprinted to a 5-0 lead in a scant 18 minutes. Seles, whose 27
unforced errors included seven double faults, never came close to
catching up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, the first set went by in a blitz,'' she said of the
pinpoint playmaking by Nagyova, who next plays 12th-seeded Sandrine
Testud of France.
</P>
<P>
   Seles had not played in this event since she won it seven years
ago. She had hoped that after a depressed and distracted 1998, in
which she suffered through the decline and death of her father and
coach, this season would permit a revival of the on-court focus and
ferocity that once took her to No. 1. Seles drew a blank when asked
why those qualities were nowhere in evidence Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's for me to ponder why,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The men's event, the Newsweek Champions Cup, began Monday with
less than a bang: The two-time finalist Andre Agassi, who defaulted
his semifinal at the Templeton Classic in Scottsdale, Ariz., on
Saturday due to a strained hamstring, withdrew from this
tournament. The event also lost 13th-seeded Thomas Enqvist of
Sweden. The 1999 Australian Open runner-up was upset by Russia's
Marat Safin, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
