<HEADLINE>
MOTHER REGAINS CHILD IN RACIAL CUSTODY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In a tug-of-war over a toddler that embodied issues of
race, class and power in Chicago, a judge ruled Monday that Edward
M. Burke, a powerful alderman, and his wife, Anne Burke, a state
appellate judge, must return the child to the birth mother, who has
overcome an addiction to drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The mother, Tina Olison, who has been fighting to win back the
3-year-old child since he was taken into foster care after being
born with cocaine in his system, claimed that because of the
Burkes' positions, state child welfare authorities were improperly
siding with them in their effort to adopt the boy.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Judith M. Brawka of state Juvenile Court, had earlier
ruled that Ms. Olison was now a fit mother. Ms. Brawka said Monday
that in her ruling she must take into account the racial heritage
of the child, who is black. The child has lived since he was 8 days
old with the Burkes, who are white.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brawka said of the state Department of Children and Family
Services, ``Unless the position of the department is that there is
no such thing as African-American culture, this issue deserves more
attention than to check a box that says not applicable.''
</P>
<P>
   As an alderman, Burke became very unpopular among blacks in the
1980s, when he vigorously opposed the city's first black mayor,
Harold Washington. As a legacy of that bitterness, a black minister
once led a protest vigil outside the alderman's office, saying that
there were ``enough Irish-Catholic children'' for Burke to adopt.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported that Ms. Brawka did not order the
boy turned over to Ms. Olison immediately, setting up a 12-month
transition instead. There will be visits with the mother supervised
by a counselor, and then unsupervised visits.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered that Ms. Olison be monitored by a child
welfare inspector in the coming months, and that the child could be
removed again if the mother returned to drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In a stern warning to the mother to cooperate with the child
welfare monitor, the judge said: ``You may not like them. You may
not trust them. But ma'am, that is life.''
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls to the Burkes and Ms. Olison were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Children and Family Services Department, which selected
the Burkes as foster parents, can appeal. The agency has 30 days to
do so and has not yet made a decision, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Anita Rivkin Carothers, a lawyer for Ms. Olison, said her client
was considering filing a civil rights suit against the state
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were bound to carry out the wishes of the Burkes,'' Ms.
Carothers said, ``because the Burkes are who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Maudlyne Ihejirika, a spokeswoman for the department, said there
was no favoritism shown to the Burkes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department has managed this case as it has all others,''
said Ms. Ihejirika, noting that some experts had testified that the
child should stay with the Burkes. ``All that we have ever been
interested in is the best interests of this child.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Illinois Supreme Court, citing the political and legal
prominence of the Burkes, appointed Ms. Brawka, who sits in Kane
County, to preside over the case in Cook County, which includes
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The case dates from February 1996, when Alderman Burke, who has
been on the City Council for 30 years, and Judge Burke, an Illinois
appellate judge, took custody of the foster child who has come to
be known as Baby T.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Olison, 37, had a history of drug abuse. Two other children
had been taken by child welfare authorities, and placed in the
custody of Ms. Olison's mother, Cecile. When Baby T was born with
drugs in his system, Ms. Olison's mother decided not to take the
child, thinking that if her daughter were separated from him, she
would stop taking drugs.
</P>
<P>
   That is apparently what happened. Ms. Olison spent 18 months in
drug rehabilitation programs. State drug tests, administered to
monitor her progress, have shown no trace of drugs. She also went
to school and became a certified nursing assistant. She works for
an agency that cares for elderly patients.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two years ago, the Department of Children and Family
Services had intended to reunite Baby T with his mother. But in
August 1997, the agency changed its position and recommended that
the boy be placed for adoption. Ms. Olison's legal case helped
preclude that.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Murphy, the Cook County public guardian, whose office
served as legal counsel for Baby T, had initially argued that the
child should remain with the Burkes. About a year ago, the office
switched its position, saying the mother had taken the necessary
steps to win back her child.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said the child had bonded to the Burkes, who were, by all
accounts, good parents, and that the child would suffer as a result
of being taken from them. But he said the child, who would grow up
knowing the identity of his mother and grandmother, would also
suffer from the separation from his biological family.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said the case should have been resolved much earlier, and
that the time spent in the legal battle had only hurt the child.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no winners in this case,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
