<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0502 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2785 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DIMAGGIO-2NDWRITE     03-08 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DIMAGGIO-2NDWRITETHRU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DiMaggio: 'Persona extended beyond playing field'
 &HT;    (EDS: Corrects that relatives and friends were not at DiMaggio's
bedside when he died; they visited the day before.)
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A fisherman's son who came to define not just baseball but all
American sport for mid-century America, Joe DiMaggio once said
about his life's work, ``There's no skill involved. Just go up
there and swing at the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   At once modest and aloof, the words described how DiMaggio lived
his life as well, a rich and full existence that ended early Monday
morning, when the Yankee Clipper succumbed after a fight with lung
cancer. He was 84 when he died shortly after midnight at his home
in exclusive Harbour Island, Fla.; his brother Dom, two
grandchildren and family friends had visited him Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``His persona extended beyond the playing field and touched all
our hearts,'' baseball commissioner Bud Selig said. ``In many
respects, as an immigrant's son, he represented the hopes and
ideals of our great country.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio came close to death late last year and twice was
administered last rites while at a local hospital. He had been home
since Jan. 19, recovering from surgery and lived long enough to
suffer the indignity of seeing his death reported prematurely on
television several weeks ago. It had been hoped that he could throw
out the first pitch for the New York Yankees' home-opener April 9.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees owner George Steinbrenner visited DiMaggio last Tuesday
and said, ``He was weak but spirited and alert. I told him, 'Joe,
you have a date with the Yankees (on) opening day. We are counting
on you to throw out the first ball.' He just smiled.''
</P>
<P>
   Until his hospitalization, DiMaggio had remained vibrant and
made regular ceremonial visits to Yankee Stadium, where he was last
honored Sept. 26 on Joe DiMaggio day and presented replicas of the
10 World Series rings the Yankees won during his 13-year career.
</P>
<P>
   But he was unable to accept the club's invitation to throw out
the first pitch of the 1998 World Series and already had been
hospitalized five days when the Yankees-San Diego series began. He
was the last link to the first Yankees dynasty, having broken in
with the team in 1939, the same year Lou Gehrig was forced into
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was looked up to back then, since he and (Ted) Williams
were the best of their time,'' said Riverdale, Ga.'s Cecil Travis,
85, who for 11 seasons faced DiMaggio regularly as a shortstop, and
a career .314 hitter, for the Washington Senators. ``He could do
most everything. Yeah, he was a pretty good fellah to look up to. I
mean, you don't get too many bad things about him, the way you do
some of them these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Although linked forever to the 56-game hitting streak that
endures 57 years later, DiMaggio's grace in center field left a
stronger imprint on New York, which watched him rise as the first
Italian-descended sports hero the nation had produced. The fly ball
never seemed to fall until DiMaggio arrived beneath it, prompting
his detractors to gripe that he'd never had a tough chance out
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't compare him to anyone,'' Travis said. ``He just
glided. He didn't stand on his head or dive or things like that.
The plays looked easy to him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No outfielder is a real workman unless he can turn his back on
the ball, run his legs off and take the catch over his shoulder,''
DiMaggio once said. ``Back-pedaling outfielders get nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   He had come up a shortstop, one of three baseball playing sons
of Joseph DiMaggio, an Italian-born fisherman who settled in San
Francisco. He was 17 when he signed with the Pacific Coast League's
Oakland Seals, and the following year, DiMaggio put together a
61-game hitting streak for the Seals. He finally made it to the
Bronx to stay in 1939 at age 24. Except for three years of military
service, he was the Yankees' constant presence into the 50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one Ted Williams admired, respected and envied
more than Joe DiMaggio,'' Williams said in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio was a career .325 hitter, but batting average hardly
defined his exactitude at the plate. He went the entire 1941 season
with just 13 strikeouts in 541 at-bats. He finished his career with
369 strikeouts and 361 career homers. A three-time American League
MVP, some of his offensive statistics suffered from playing in
spacious Yankee Stadium. But DiMaggio's game was far more than
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball isn't statistics,'' New York writer Jimmy Breslin
once said. ``It's Joe DiMaggio rounding second base.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 14, 1941, DiMaggio singled off Chicago's Eddie Smith,
beginning a run that might never be equaled. Nearly a month later,
another single against the White Sox gave him a 29-game hitting
streak, breaking the Yankees' club record. Rogers Hornsby's NL
record of 33 fell, as did George Sisler's AL mark of 41. And when
historians insisted that Wee Willie Keeler had recorded a 44-game
streak in 1887, DiMaggio broke it, too, before three ground-outs
July 17 in Cleveland ended the run at 56 games.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, DiMaggio had 56 singles, 16 doubles, seven
triples and 15 home runs. The following day, he began a 16-game
streak that did not include a hit recorded in Detroit in the 1941
All-Star game. Pete Rose summoned a 44-game streak in 1978, but no
one else has come close.
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, DiMaggio's shadow was diminished purposely. He
often dined alone, was polite but distant with teammates and,
partly as a result of public criticism he received in a contract
hold-out, was wary of the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he said hello to you,'' Detroit's Hank Greenberg said,
``that was a long conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 37, slowed by back and foot injuries, DiMaggio turned
down a new $100,000 contract and announced his retirement in 1951
by saying simply, ``I no longer have it.''
</P>
<P>
   In his last World Series that fall, he shared the Yankees
outfield with a strong kid from Oklahoma, at least until he waved
Mickey Mantle off a fly ball in Game 2. Mickey Mantle slipped and
hurt his knee on the play, opening a new chapter in Yankees lore.
</P>
<P>
   A failed marriage to Marilyn Monroe broke his heart but only
increased his public persona in retirement. Celebrated in music and
literature _ Simon and Garfunkel's ``Mrs. Robinson'' and Ernest
Hemingway's ``The Old Man and the Sea'' _ DiMaggio's name came to
represent new things to each new generation, even as he was hawking
a coffee maker.
</P>
<P>
   He sold a lot of them too, which fit a larger pattern. When
asked once how DiMaggio excelled, New York teammate Tommy Heinrich
replied, ``He does everything better than anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. The Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
