<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2787 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-PEONY-SFCHRON &LR;      03-08 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-PEONY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELLARS' `PEONY PAVILION' OVERLOADS THE SENSES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSHUA KOSMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ It was midway through the second part of
``The Peony Pavilion'' _ director Peter Sellars' overstuffed,
overbearing music-theatrical extravaganza, which had its U.S.
premiere over the weekend _ that my neural circuitry began to feel
the effects of sensory overload.
</P>
<P>
   At that point the audience at Zellerbach Hall had witnessed
great swatches of traditional Chinese kun opera (delivered more or
less straight), a parallel ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' spoken version
of the same story, episodes of silent interpretive dance, banks of
video screens that relayed the proceedings in simultaneous
close-up, Western opera singing, a Gothic visit to the underworld,
some thunking rock 'n' roll drum explosions with prerecorded chorus
and pipa obbligato, and an indecipherable figure prancing about
with a velvet scourge like some white-clad dominatrix sprite.
</P>
<P>
   Still to come before Saturday's three-hour-plus performance ran
its course were lots more quasi-operatic recitative by composer Tan
Dun, a handful of ear-piercing amplified outbursts (the sure sign
of a composer fresh out of ideas), some vigorous but oddly unerotic
sexual couplings, stretches of bilingual spoken dialogue and a
stylized onstage drowning.
</P>
<P>
   But by that time there was no way to keep processing the
onslaught of theatrical effects _ and no very compelling motivation
to try.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, there was no reason ``The Peony Pavilion'' should not
have emerged as the invigorating multicultural blockbuster billed
by the presenters, Cal Performances. Sellars, brimming with ideas
as ever, might have been just the person to produce a 20th century
pan-Pacific take on the ancient traditions of Chinese opera.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the frenzied activity spilled across the Zellerbach
stage on Saturday (the second of three performances) the result was
strangely empty at the core. This grab bag of ancient and
post-modern tricks turned out to be considerably less than the sum
of its parts.
</P>
<P>
   The source for this production is a 1598 verse drama by the Ming
Dynasty poet Tang Xianzu, which is the basis for one of the
mainstays of Chinese opera (a traditional version of ``The Peony
Pavilion'' was to be performed in New York last summer by a
Shanghai troupe, but the visit was scotched by the Chinese
government after the failure of some high-level diplomatic
negotiations).
</P>
<P>
   The plot has to do with a pair of star-crossed lovers _ an
impoverished student, Liu Mengmei, and a well-born young girl, Du
Liniang _ who meet in dreams and death before (I think) living
happily ever after once he has successfully exhumed her corpse.
</P>
<P>
   During the first part, Sellars intercuts two renditions of the
story. One consists of scenes from the Chinese tradition, sung with
extraordinary flair by Hua Wenyi and Shi Jiehua, two stars of the
Shanghai operatic world, and accompanied by a sparse, evocative
trio of Chinese instruments. Hua, as Du Liniang, also engages in
some silent episodes with dancer Michael Schumacher, including an
extended seduction scene that comes as close to erotic power as the
evening ever does.
</P>
<P>
   The other, much flatter, strain features actors Lauren Tom and
Joel de la Fuente speaking Cyril Birch's English translation of the
text, while handheld cameras relay their faces to an array of video
monitors scattered around George Tsypin's spare, Plexiglas-laden
set.
</P>
<P>
   Things get even more dense, and less compelling, in the long
second half, with the addition of soprano Ying Huang and tenor Lin
Qiang Xu singing their hearts out in Tan's pretentious
East-meets-West score. For most of the second half, the story is
danced, sung and spoken in triplicate, like some bureaucratic
application form.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, by piling on the redundancies and the echoes,
Sellars doesn't amplify the story so much as bury it. There is
always a lot going on, but no way to focus on any of it (``The
Peony Pavilion,'' in fact, owes as much to the American tradition
of the three-ring circus as to Chinese opera). The dominant floral
image is not so much the peony as the gilded lily.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's best moments come from some of the individual
performers. As singer, dancer and purely regal stage presence, Hua
Wenyi is a knockout, an artist whose star power easily transcends
cultural boundaries. Ying Huang's pure lyric soprano outclasses the
uninteresting vocal lines Tan has given her, and the virtuosic
contributions of Min-Xiao Fen on the pipa (a sort of Chinese lute)
stood out amid the noise of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, ``The Peony Pavilion'' felt like a huge
opportunity missed _ an attempt to fuse disparate artistic
traditions that ended up drowning under the weight of unculled
excess.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
