<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-CSUNWOM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSUN GUARD REFUSES TO FAIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANEL LAJ  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tina Greer's philosophy is simple: failure is not
an option.
</P>
<P>
   That's why growing up in a tough neighborhood never concerned
Greer, a sophomore guard at Cal State Northridge. The gang
activity, drugs and apathy so prevalent around her Washington High
neighborhood were never an issue. Nothing would deprive her of
becoming a success, and none of this surprises her coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very much in control of her business off the court,''
said Cal State Northridge coach Frozena Jerro, whose team makes its
first Div. I NCAA Tournament appearance Thursday at Colorado State.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wants to be successful and works hard at it,'' Jerro said.
``I like her ambition. She knows what she wants and goes out to get
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer's collegiate career began at Xavier University, where she
experienced too many losses and too much apathy. She'd been on
winning teams throughout high school, and transferred to CSUN even
though that required her to redshirt last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that she was just homesick at Xavier and it
wasn't just the losing; I think it was more than that,'' said her
Washington High basketball coach, Julie Rousseau. ``I think she
lost a little when she went to Xavier. . . . I think she kind of
doubted herself and that hurt her a bit. She lost that tiger
instinct, but she worked really hard to get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer, who collected 84 assists and 43 steals in her 17 games
with the Musketeers, said she didn't fit into Xavier's program or
the role they wanted her to play. It was too structured for her
free-style and fast-paced game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (redshirting) allowed her to reflect on what was going
on,'' Rousseau said. ``She's not a quitter or the the kind of
person that retreats. She never lost sight of her goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer admits she was initially skeptical about the Matadors
program. Could a team that won only four games the entire 1996-97
season win a championship? But she's found success where no one
else thought to look.
</P>
<P>
   Greer, who leads the team in steals with 70 and is third in
scoring with 224 points, is known for her quickness and tenacious
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's our number one defender,'' said teammate Lynda Amari.
``When I see her, she makes me want to play defense. She's gotten a
lot better. . . . She listens very well when you try and tell her
things on the court. She likes to learn and I respect her because
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been easy at CSUN. Before she played her first game
for the Matadors, the head coach was arrested and controversy
swelled around a program that had received little publicity before.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the (coach) Michael Abraham situation happened, she was
probably the first player to say, `Look, things like this happen,
and we just have to get through it,' '' Jerro said. ``Giving up and
the option to fail was never there. It didn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer prides herself on this growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've grown a lot and matured not only as a player but
as a person,'' Greer said. ``Xavier just completely turned me
around. . . . I had to act more mature and I had to step my ways up
and stop acting so wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to look at myself as being self-striving. I don't need
to depend on anybody else. . . . If a difficult situation comes
along, you have to know how to approach it, deal with it and then
go on.''
</P>
<P>
   It's this type of attitude that helped Greer cope with one of
her biggest challenges: going to school and becoming independent.
She had to separate herself from a close-knit family.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's daddy's girl,'' said Dianna Greer. ``And when she went
away she had to learn to fend for herself and learn to do
everything. She learned to budget her money and deal with what
little she had. She has matured a lot. She's a very strong person
and we're really proud of her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
