<SLUG> BC-ALLIED-BFI.-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA TRASH HAULER ACQUIRES TEXAS-BASED BFI 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NELSON ANTOSH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Browning-Ferris Industries, the company whose garbage
trucks have been a fixture on Houston streets for decades, is being
acquired by Allied Waste Industries, which plans to move BFI's
headquarters to Scottsdale, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   The $9.1 billion deal, which includes assuming some debt, will
be the largest cash transaction ever in the trash-hauling industry.
Currently, Allied is the nation's third-largest hauler while BFI is
the nation's second-largest.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of BFI and Allied will be run by Allied's senior
management team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be job losses in Houston,'' said Thomas Van
Weelden, Allied's chairman, president and chief executive during a
news conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to say how many jobs will be lost here, he said.
However, operations such as accounting will likely to be moved to
Scottsdale. It will probably take a year after the deal closes to
sort out everything, Allied officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Houston BFI offices will probably function as a satellite for
the corporate offices in Scottsdale, a Phoenix suburb. As a highly
decentralized company, there are no trucks with Allied Waste
painted on their doors.
</P>
<P>
   BFI employs about 26,000 people in North America, including
2,500 in the Houston area.
</P>
<P>
   With the acquisition, Allied will have revenues of about $6.6
billion and own a national network of landfills, collection and
transfer operations.
</P>
<P>
   The younger, leaner and faster-growing Allied operates in 28
states, has 7,500 employees and generated annualized revenues of
about $1.7 billion. BFI has annualized revenues of $4.2 billion. It
operates in about 45 states and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The familiar BFI trucks will continue to roll down the city's
streets ``for years to come,'' Van Weelden said.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce its substantial debt load, Allied plans to sell about
$900 million in nonstrategic businesses. Based on recent mergers in
the waste industry, Van Weelden expects the Justice Department to
request that it divest some assets in certain markets.
</P>
<P>
   There is some overlap in 20 to 25 markets, Van Weelden said. BFI
operates in about 125 markets.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Waste, which started here in 1987 and in 1993 moved to
Scottsdale, said it will offer $45 a share for BFI's stock. In
addition, it will assume about $1.8 billion of BFI's debt.
</P>
<P>
   This is a hefty premium for stock that recently has been trading
for about $31 per share. BFI's stock started moving last week on
speculation of a takeover.
</P>
<P>
   The deal has already been approved by the boards of directors of
both companies. Closing is expected during the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   BFI was surprised by the offer, said Bruce Ranck, president and
chief executive. At $45 per share, in cash, it was ``simply too
good for use to ignore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Allied has doubled its size in the past year, mostly through
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, during fiscal 1998, BFI, which got its start in
Houston 30 years ago, spent $25.5 million acquiring 30 businesses.
Its strategy has been to earn customers rather than buy them.
</P>
<P>
   But during a period from about 1970 to 1987, said Van Weelden,
BFI's growth was spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   When that growth slowed, the Wall Street investors turned their
attention to younger competitors. Recently, BFI has been buying its
own stock to strengthen the price.
</P>
<P>
   Trash hauling is particularly well suited for consolidation
because there are so many duplicate costs that can be eliminated,
said Mel Cody, financial analyst for Sanders Morris Mundy in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   If you have two companies running routes in the same
neighborhood, he said, a merger can eliminate one of those trucks
and still produce the same tonnage.
</P>
<P>
   A misadventure in the recycling business was a factor in a
reorganization of BFI in 1996 and a shift in its focus to internal
growth. The company is one of the nation's largest recyclers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when the recycling business was at an all-time high,
BFI enjoyed its best year ever. But prices for recovered
commodities such as waste paper collapsed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The company has recovered during the past three years with
earnings increasing by double digits each year, Ranck said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very optimistic about our future,'' he said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   BFI has been under more pressure to sell since last year when
there was talk of an approach by Allied, Cody said. But there never
was a formal offer by Allied for BFI.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, USA Waste Services, then Houston's other major trash
hauler, gobbled up Waste Management of Oak Brook, Ill., which with
BFI were pioneers in putting together big companies by acquiring
small trash haulers by the hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   The Waste Management name was retained, making Houston the home
of a $13 billion per year giant that is the largest
garbage-collecting, landfill and recycling company in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   People were impressed when Waste Management cut costs by $800
million after the acquisition, Cody said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board had to sit up and take notice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And since that time BFI has had trouble implementing a new
software program that would have tied its operations together.
Plus, some feel that BFI is still ``a little cost-heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   Allied is predicting $290 million in cost savings during the
first 12 months after the acquisition is closed. Ultimately, it
expects savings of $360 million.
</P>
<P>
   Competitor Rod Proto, president and chief operating officer of
Waste Management, said Van Weelden understands that the garbage
business should be locally managed and that he would steer the new
company away from BFI's more centralized style of management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, the big companies have moved people around too
much, so they are not perceived as local anymore. If you are going
to compete locally, you've got to manage locally,'' Proto said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
