</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MAYOR-SCHOOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC SCHOOLS CHIEF DROPS THREAT TO QUIT OVER VOUCHER ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With Mayor Rudolph Giuliani standing at his side, New
York City Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew Monday withdrew his threat
to resign _ at least for now _ as the two men said they would try
to work out their differences over using city money to send
public-school students to private and religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   Crew had threatened to resign last week because Giuliani had
launched a feverish campaign to lobby members of the Board of
Education to approve a $12 million plan for the school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   The two men emerged smiling and joking Monday from a
face-to-face meeting at City Hall, but some strain showed beneath
the surface, and it was clear that their differences were far from
resolved. It was also clear that Crew had withdrawn his threat to
resign because the mayor had said that for now, he would not try to
bring the issue to a vote of the Board of Education, although he
reserved the right to do so later.
</P>
<P>
   Standing next to Giuliani in the ornate City Hall rotunda, Crew
said his threat to resign was ``held in abeyance.'' He added:
``Let's assume I don't want to resign, which I don't. But let's
assume that this is an issue that needs further discussion, which
it does.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani quickly interjected: ``He's not going to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew's promise to try to resolve the issue defused a six-day
standoff that threatened to destabilize New York City's
often-beleaguered school system, which has seen chancellors come
and go every few years.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between Giuliani and Crew broke into public view
last Wednesday evening, when aides to Crew said that he had told
the mayor he would resign if the board passed a vouchers program.
Crew has said that he sees vouchers as an assault on public
education. Giuliani sees his proposal as an attempt to provide
children in poor neighborhoods a choice beyond often troubled
public schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 2329EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0509 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2794 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NCAA-SUIT-375&AMP;ADD-NYT     03-08 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCAA-SUIT-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING RACIAL IMPACT, JUDGE DISCARDS NCAA TEST-SCORE RULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This is a late add to page 1 of the New York Times.)  
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: The following story is also being sent with
an ``a'' category code.) 
 (lh) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A U.S. District Court in Philadelphia on Monday discarded the
National Collegiate Athletic Association's minimum test score
requirement for athletic scholarships, throwing into disarray a
long-accepted criterion for establishing eligibility for
student-athletes.
</P>
<P>
   In a 54-page decision, the judge, Ronald I. Buckwalter, held
that the NCAA's SAT and ACT minimum test score requirement, as
outlined in Proposition 16, ``has an unjustified disparate impact
against African-Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge cited the NCAA's own research showing that the
practice harmed black students' chances of being declared
academically eligible and that the organization's goal of improving
graduation rates _ the reason it instituted Proposition 16 in the
first place _ could be achieved by other available methods.
</P>
<P>
   Elsa Kircher Cole, general counsel for the NCAA, said the
organization would seek a stay of the judge's ruling, perhaps as
early as Tuesday, so it could continue an ongoing review of
Proposition 16 in an ``orderly'' fashion. She acknowledged,
however, that the ruling takes control of athletic eligibility out
of the NCAA's hands and may create chaos for hundreds of schools
across the nation that routinely grant athletic scholarships based
on NCAA standards for test scores, grade-point average and core
curriculum. If the ruling stands, individual colleges and
institutions can make their own decision on the eligibility
requirements for athletic scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five hundred schools will go out and try to create their own
rule in an area they relied on us for expertise, and we don't think
that that benefits the student athlete,'' Cole said. ``The chaos
we're in is that there's no direction or consistency about who
qualifies.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based Trial Lawyers for Public Justice, an
advocacy group that was representing the plaintiffs in the
class-action suit, charged in its case that the minimum test
requirement was a violation of the 1964 Civil Rights Act. In his
ruling Monday, Buckwalter agreed, saying that the NCAA could be
sued under that act, which prohibits race discrimination by
educational institutions that receive federal funds.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The court's finding that the NCAA is covered by Title VI is
critical to ending discrimination in intercollegiate athletics,''
said the staff attorney for the Trial Lawyers for Public Justice,
Adele P. Kimmel. ``This effectively means that the NCAA can be held
accountable if it discriminates on the basis of race, sex,
disability or other impermissible factors,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the current suit, the NCAA has denied it receives any such
funds, but the plaintiffs developed evidence that they say shows
that the association is the indirect recipient of millions of
dollars targeted for a National Youth Sports Program fund. The NCAA
contends that it is just a pass-through mechanism to distribute the
money to schools throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 16 was instituted beginning with the April 1995 SAT
exam. It required students to achieve a minimum score of 820 out of
a possible 1,600. But the debate over the appropriateness of using
test scores to determine college eligibility extends beyond sports,
with many advocacy groups asserting that the tests are not free of
cultural bias.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was originally brought by two African-American
students, Tai Kwan Cureton and Leatrice Shaw. Cureton graduated
from Simon Gratz High School in Philadelphia in June 1996 and
ranked 27th in a class of 305. According to the lawsuit, he earned
academic honors and athletic honors in his sport, track. But he did
not do well on the SAT, and when he fell below the cutoff point, he
was not admitted to or offered athletic financial aid by any
Division I schools.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw also graduated from Simon Gratz in June 1996 and ranked
fifth in the class. She was, said the complaint, a member of the
National Honor Society who earned academic honors and also excelled
in track. But she, like Cureton, failed to meet the minimum score
required by Proposition 16. In the end, only one school offered her
financial aid, the University of Miami, which she now attends. She
was not permitted to compete on the track team during her freshman
year.
</P>
<P>
   A trial had been scheduled to begin this spring, but Cureton's
lawyers moved for summary judgment, contending that on the law
alone, the requirement could not be justified. On Monday the judge
agreed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 2331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
