<HEADER>
A2799 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DIALLO-SHOOTING-NY     03-08 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMISSIONER SAYS POLICE DID NOT SEEK TO TAINT CHARACTER OF SLAIN
MAN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police Commissioner Howard Safir acknowledged Monday
that police investigators entered the home of Amadou Diallo and
questioned his roommates in the hours after officers fatally shot
the unarmed man. But the commissioner strongly denied any
suggestions that they were trying to taint Diallo's character to
justify the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   At a brief news conference at City Hall, Safir rejected
accusations made over the weekend by lawyers for the Diallo family:
that soon after Diallo was killed on Feb. 4 in the vestibule of his
apartment building in the Bronx, investigators ransacked his
apartment and questioned his roommates at a police station house
for hours about Diallo's habits and character without telling them
that he had been killed by the police.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lawyers, Peter J. Neufeld, accused the police of
trying to find a piece of damaging evidence to ``dirty up'' Diallo
and help justify the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   But Safir took issue with such assertions. He said that the
detectives who handled the inquiry ``followed the normal procedures
they would follow in any shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir said that in going to Diallo's apartment, the officers
were searching only for identification and information that would
help them locate his relatives to notify them about the killing. He
said that Diallo's roommates went voluntarily to the station house
and were free to leave any time they wanted, and that they were
told that Diallo had been shot by police officers.
</P>
<P>
   The detectives, from a special Night Watch unit that handles
major investigations that break overnight, entered Diallo's
apartment only after they asked for permission, Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That permission was granted,'' Safir said. ``They did not
ransack anything. They were looking for identification of Diallo
and that was the extent of it. These charges _ of them intimidating
and ransacking an apartment _ are just not true.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of Diallo's roommates, Abdou Rahman Diallo, a cousin by
marriage, said in a telephone interview Monday that he never gave
the police permission to enter the apartment. ``I tried to close
the door, but they came in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Abdou Diallo said that although he was questioned for six
hours at the local station house, he did not learn that Amadou
Diallo had been shot by the police until he went home around 7 a.m.
and found out from a reporter's telephone call. He said that when
he got home, two wardrobes had been emptied of clothing, the
mattresses on the beds had been disturbed and the curtains had been
removed from a window.
</P>
<P>
   Neufeld questioned why the police would conduct such a thorough
search for a piece of identification.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suggestion that they were searching for identification is
ridiculous,'' Neufeld said. ``One, his wallet was found next to
him. Two, the roommates could identify him. And three, you don't
have to ransack people's wardrobes and pull their curtains from the
window in the hopes of finding an ID card.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior police official, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said that while Diallo's wallet was found next to his
body, it was possible that the detectives were looking for more
complete identification to help them find Diallo's parents.
</P>
<P>
   Amadou Diallo's other roommate, Momodu Kujabi, could not be
reached for comment by telephone Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
