</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DIMAGGIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE DIMAGGIO MYSTIQUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, March 9:
</P>
<P>
   It has been almost half a century since Joe DiMaggio turned his
center-field kingdom in Yankee Stadium over to a strapping
youngster named Mickey Mantle, but even now, in death, DiMaggio
still owns that green acreage. He roamed the great open spaces
there with a grace and grandeur that redefined the art of fielding.
Even more than the prolific hitting that earned him enduring fame,
his silky, seemingly effortless motion across the outfield grass
was the signature of his game.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio was one of those rare sports stars, like Babe Ruth,
Muhammad Ali and Michael Jordan, who not only set new standards of
athletic excellence but also became a distinctive part of American
culture. As stylish off the field as on, DiMaggio was an icon of
elegance and success, a name as recognizable on Broadway and in
Hollywood as at the ball park. Millions of baby boomers who never
saw DiMaggio play instantly understood the reference in the Paul
Simon song of the 1960s _ ``Where have you gone, Joe DiMaggio? A
nation turns its lonely eyes to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Other men have hit the ball farther and run the bases faster,
but few have excelled at so many elements of the sport. DiMaggio's
56-game hitting streak in 1941 remains untouched, one of the great
benchmarks of consistency and productivity in all of sports. In 13
seasons with the Yankees, DiMaggio produced a career batting
average of .325, hit 361 home runs and knocked in more than 100
runs in a season nine times. He played in 10 World Series, 9 of
which the Yankees won. He possessed one of the sweetest swings
baseball has ever seen, a hitting stroke of such precision that he
struck out only 369 times in his major league career.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers alone do not explain the DiMaggio mystique. Part
of it was his brief, turbulent marriage to Marilyn Monroe and his
taste for nightclubs and tony hotels. Part of it was his
$100,000-a-year salary, a small fortune in his days as a Yankee.
For younger fans, there was also an almost mystical link to the
past _ DiMaggio joined the Yankees in 1936, just two years after
Babe Ruth left and before Lou Gehrig retired. His appearance on
ceremonial occasions at Yankee Stadium in recent years was
thrilling for fans of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   His fame also flowed from the aura of quiet dignity that
DiMaggio carefully preserved throughout his career and retirement.
With the notable exception of his service as a pitchman for the
Bowery Savings Bank and coffee brewing appliances, he dodged the
celebrity limelight. The mystery only added to his allure.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio, who was 84, died with opening day a month away. Though
he will no longer return to Yankee Stadium to deliver the
ceremonial first pitch, his singular record of athletic achievement
and classy conduct will be long revered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-08-99 2336EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990308.0513 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-08 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2805 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-DIMAGGIO-OBIT-HNS     03-08 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-DIMAGGIO-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL HERO JOE DIMAGGIO DIES AT AGE 84 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe DiMaggio, the fisherman's son from San Francisco who set one
of baseball's most heroic records and became an almost mythic
figure in American culture, died Monday morning at his Hollywood,
Fla., home at age 84 after months of ebbing health.
</P>
<P>
   In October, DiMaggio underwent surgery for lung cancer in
Florida and rallied at least twice from serious infections during a
99-day hospital stay. He was released Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
   A ballplayer of uncommon grace, DiMaggio was an almost painfully
private man who resisted celebrity. Yet several events gave him an
aura of mystery and romance. He loved and lost actress Marilyn
Monroe, sex goddess of the 1950s. He was celebrated in a hugely
popular hit song of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   And his 56-game hitting streak, achieved in 1941 against a
backdrop of a nation on the brink of war, survives today, 58 years
later. In 1969, it was voted the greatest individual accomplishment
in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   His wedding to Monroe in 1954 was a union of Hollywood and
sports royalty. When the marriage failed a year later, humorist
Oscar Levant observed, ``It simply proves that no man can be great
at two national pastimes.''
</P>
<P>
   It was his greatness on the diamond that defined DiMaggio. He
was the link among three New York Yankees eras that fused into a
continuing dynasty. Joining the Yankees as a rookie in 1936,
DiMaggio followed Babe Ruth and preceded Mickey Mantle. He retired
after appearing in his 10th World Series in 1951, Mantle's first
season.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio was one of nine children of a father born in Sicily.
His brothers, Vince and Dominic, also played in the big leagues,
Dom becoming his rival as a center fielder with the Boston Red Sox.
The boys grew up around fishing boats and played minor-league ball
for San Francisco in the Pacific Coast League. Joe D. was an
introvert, but he never doubted his ability. He had trouble talking
about it, however, suppressing his emotions to such a point that it
caused him no small amount of suffering.
</P>
<P>
   From the start of his streak May 15, 1941, to its finish July
17, the Yankee Clipper developed stomach miseries that led to an
ulcer. He once confided he smoked up to three packs of cigarettes a
day, ducking into the dugout runway between innings. He would have
lit one in center field if baseball had let him.
</P>
<P>
   If he suffered, his performance did not, because DiMaggio was
beyond question one of the greatest players ever. Then he became
something more when Paul Simon wrote a song for the 1967 movie
``The Graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Robinson'' contained a haunting line that sent the
country on a mass identity search:
</P>
<P>
   ``Where have you gone, Joe DiMaggio?
</P>
<P>
   ``A nation turns its lonely eyes to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that you say, Mrs. Robinson?
</P>
<P>
   ``Joltin' Joe has left and gone away.''
</P>
<P>
   That one lyric became a lasting commentary on sports and its
role in our society and our fantasy lives. Was it a plaintive wail
for a more innocent time, or an ode to our youth, when heroes made
worshippers of all of us and baseball was boss?
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio wasn't sure. He thought it might be a putdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first heard the lines,'' he said, ``I didn't like it. I
didn't know what to make of it. Then the kids who wrote the song
called and said they meant it to be a compliment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It means,'' said Simon, who with Art Garfunkel took the song
to No. 1, ``whatever you wanted it to mean.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he added, ``It has something to do with heroes, people
who are all good, with no bad in them. That was the way I always
saw Joe DiMaggio.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio was tall, darkly handsome, custom tailored, always
reserved. In his later years, he was still lean and distinguished
in looks, and free of the tension that gripped him during most of
his existence. Once repulsed by cocktail parties and promotions of
any kind, he learned to cope, turning up at old-timers games and
celebrity golf tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   A new generation discovered him on television plugging Mr.
Coffee, but he turned down countless other offers. He was never
comfortable on TV, giving infrequent interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I be uncomfortable,'' he said, ``just for the
money?''
</P>
<P>
   In the worldly scheme of things, he felt it mattered little
whether anyone broke his 56-game hitting record. But in this age of
super youth and super science, it hasn't been done, and he politely
rejected the usual excuses.
</P>
<P>
   He did not believe modern travel to be more hectic and,
therefore, more draining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't buy that at all,'' he once said on a visit to Houston.
``Train travel wasn't easy. We would leave New York after a game
and ride 24 hours to St. Louis and sometimes go right from the
station to the park for a night game. Sleeping on trains never has
been easy. Air conditioning was poor. And if you raised a window,
you got soot and cinders in your face.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one will convince me that guys flying in jets are not more
rested than we were.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's hitters also benefit from artificial turf, weight
training and special diets. In DiMaggio's time, any player who
avoided boze and fatty foods was considered a health nut.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio had a lifetime batting average of .325 and was an
artist in center field, turning long fly balls into easy outs. He
hit 361 homers (while striking out only 369 times), playing half
his games in Yankee Stadium, a ballpark built for the lefthanded
Ruth. His teammates boasted that DiMaggio, a righthanded hitter
with a classic stride, would have hit 400 more home runs if he had
played in Boston's Fenway Park, with its short left-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   Yet no enduring record in baseball carries the weight and aura
of DiMaggio's streak. He was 26 that summer, and he belonged to the
whole country. He kept the fans sitting by their radios until the
war news _ from places like Stalingrad and Singapore _ had ended.
Then the announcer would advise them that, yes, Joltin' Joe had got
his hit today to keep the string alive.
</P>
<P>
   He would serve three years in the Army, but for one captivating
summer he provided a distraction from the outbreak of global
temper. On July 17, he got into a cab with his roommate, pitcher
Lefty Gomez, for the ride to Cleveland's stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The driver recognized me,'' DiMaggio recalled. ``He said,
`Joe, I think it will end tonight.' When he said that, Lefty jumped
all over him and really chewed him out. But he was right. Ken
Keltner made two great plays (at third base), and Lou Boudreau (the
shortstop) made the last one on a ball that jumped up and almost
hit him on the shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   The streak was over at 56 games, well beyond the previous record
of 44, set by Wee Willie Keeler in 1897.
</P>
<P>
   The record was no fluke. After the Indians stopped him, DiMaggio
hit safely in his next 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   His image is fixed in memory, gliding under long fly balls and
ripping another base hit. He was voted into the Hall of Fame in
1955, the year of his divorce from Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   His friends said he never stopped loving her, but their natures
and lifestyles were at odds. Gay Talese, writing in Esquire
magazine, described the movie star's return from Korea, where she
had entertained U.S. troops, drawing crowds of 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so wonderful, Joe,'' she said, breathlessly. ``You've
never heard such cheering.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I have,'' he said softly.
</P>
<P>
   When Monroe died in 1962 at the age of 36, DiMaggio ordered
fresh flowers placed on her grave weekly. When the florist asked
for how long, he took out a pen and wrote one word across the
invoice: ``Forever.''
</P>
<P>
   At DiMaggio's bedside when he died Monday were his brother,
Dominic; two grandchildren, Paula and Cathy; Morris Engelberg, his
neighbor and longtime attorney; and Joe Nacchio, his friend of 59
years.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio will be buried in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
