<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-POLICE-605&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT ACCUSES POLICE OF RACIALLY BIASED SEARCHES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By   BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A civil rights advocacy group asked a federal judge
in Manhattan on Monday to halt the operations of the New York City
Police Department's elite Street Crimes Unit, which it said had
illegally stopped and searched tens of thousands of people because
they were members of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   The accusation that the police were searching people because of
their race, a practice known as profiling, drew immediate denials
from police and city officials. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said he
``would not dignify'' the charges with a response.
</P>
<P>
   The city's top lawyer, Michael D. Hess, said that the police did
not search people on the basis of race, and that ``the
stop-and-frisks were carried out in a constitutional fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that ``it would not be surprising if the majority
of those stop-and-frisks'' took place in neighborhoods heavily
populated by members of minority groups, because of higher crime
rates in those neighborhoods and because the Street Crimes Unit
concentrates on drugs, guns and crimes of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murder statistics that involve dead bodies don't lie and
cannot be fudged,'' he said. ``If minority communities are going to
be properly protected, the stop-and-frisks must take place in those
communities.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed by the National Congress for Puerto Rican
Rights, asked Judge Michael B. Mukasey of federal District Court in
Manhattan to authorize a class action suit on behalf of all people
who had been subjected to the stop-and-frisk practices. Two people
were also named as plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Using police statistics, the suit estimated that the Street
Crimes Unit had stopped and searched 35,000 people and then
released them without further action during the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, which seeks unspecified damages against the city, also
accuses the unit of requiring officers to meet monthly quotas for
arrests and seizures of illegal guns. The policy intensifies the
pressure on officers to search, or ``toss,'' people
indiscriminately, the suit says, in hopes of finding a firearm,
without regard to whether the search was justified. The suit also
asks that the department be ordered to improve screening, training
and supervision of the unit's approximately 380 officers.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Daniels, executive director of the Center for Constitutional
Rights, whose lawyers filed the lawsuit, said the group had found
``a sweeping pattern of aggressive policing that is out of control
and, at the heart of it, we believe, unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed as calls have increased for greater
federal intervention in the investigation of the shooting death of
Amadou Diallo, who was killed by four officers from the Bronx
Street Crimes unit. Last Friday, the Civil Rights Commission in
Washington said it would open an investigation into the city's
police practices, at which Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard
Safir are expected to be asked to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Giuliani, Safir and other city officials seemed anxious
to squelch any suggestion that the officers were involved in
selecting members of minority groups, an accusation that has
surfaced less formally during previous criticism of the mayor's
quality of life efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Street Crimes does not engage in any racial profiling,'' Safir
said, ``nor do we anywhere else in the NYPD.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said the lawsuit was the first time he had heard
charges of racial profiling. ``I would not dignify it with a
comment,'' he added, ``because this could be somebody trying to
create a story when one doesn't have a right to exist at this
point.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The racial profiling issue has come under legal scrutiny in
other places, such as New Jersey, where the Justice Department is
conducting a civil rights investigation into whether state troopers
have been illegally singling out black drivers on state highways.
</P>
<P>
   In asking for an end to racial profiling, the suit against the
New York police contends that race and national origin have been
``an integral part'' of the Street Crime Unit's policy, and that in
many cases its searches have not been based on reasonable suspicion
that criminal activity is taking place, which is the standard set
by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Richie Perez, national coordinator of the National Congress for
Puerto Rican Rights, said the unit's practices have ``amounted to a
suspension of the Constitution in Puerto Rican and black
communities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Something has to be done about it,'' he said. ``If we don't
have constitutional protections, to whom does the Constitution
apply? Not us? Is the Constitution only applicable in white
communities?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
