<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SONY-DOWNSIZE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONY TO CUT 17,000 JOBS AND REORGANIZE 3 UNITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Use of ``Tuesday'' is CQ.) 
(mk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Sony Corp. announced a sweeping corporate overhaul
Tuesday aimed at decisively changing the company's identity from a
manufacturer of consumer electronics to a provider of digital
network services similar to Cisco Systems or Lucent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just a change in our organization but in the whole
Sony group,'' Norio Ohga, Sony's chairman, said at a hastily called
news conference Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Sony plans to eliminate 10 percent of its work force, or about
17,000 jobs, through attrition and a hiring freeze, and to close 15
manufacturing plants around the world by the end of March 2003 as
part of its reorganization. Sony will also reabsorb three publicly
traded companies _ Sony Music Entertainment Inc., Sony Chemicals
Corp. and Sony Precision Technology Inc. _ in which it holds
majority stakes, and reduce the number of internal group companies
to three, from 10.
</P>
<P>
   Nobuyuki Idei, Sony's president, said these steps would help to
restore the company's profitability, which has been battered by the
global economic slump, but that a change in focus was also needed.
Idei said Sony's new focus would be the network business _
essentially the business of linking consumers to a variety of
services either through their computers or their television sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make it possible for Sony's customers to directly
link themselves with our products and services and for Sony to
distribute its movies, music, games and personal finance tools and
services directly to its customers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the company intends to supply not only the
computers and television sets through which people will gain access
to its movies and music but also the pipeline. Idei said Sony would
invest aggressively over the next three years in research and
development, equipment, plants, and building the infrastructure
necessary to provide services for what he called a
``network-centric'' world.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and investors have been expecting Sony to take off in a
new direction as its bread-and-butter consumer electronics business
has slipped into the red, as the business has become more and more
competitive. The company's shares jumped 7.5 percent Tuesday
morning as news of the change in direction seeped out of the room
where Sony was holding its news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The company whetted appetites last week when it unveiled the
next generation of its immensely popular Play Station game console
and the cutting edge central processor that is its heart. The
processor was developed jointly with Toshiba Corp. ``Apparently,
the technology has applications beyond mere game machines, not only
in bringing digital consumer electronics to the home but also in
telecommunication and other areas,'' said Scott Foster, a high-tech
analyst at ING Barings in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Kutaragi, the president of Sony Computer Entertainment, the
subsidiary responsible for Play Station, described the new chip as
a ``technology driver'' for Sony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
