<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSTON-DRIVERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOP! EXPERTS CRITICAL OF STUDY ON AGGRESSIVE DRIVING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAN FELDSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A national group reported Monday that people are more
likely to be killed by aggressive, stressed-out driving in cities
like Houston that have few alternatives to the automobile.
</P>
<P>
   But several experts who reviewed the methodology said the report
showed very little _ except that when more people drive, more
people die driving.
</P>
<P>
   Houston has heard from the Surface Transportation Policy Project
before. Based in Washington, D.C., it monitors transportation
legislation and advocates alternatives to pavement, including bike
paths, sidewalks and public transit.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it released a report on vehicle-pedestrian deaths and
serious injuries, saying that sprawling cities like Houston were
more dangerous for walkers than compact cities in the Northeast
like New York and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Now it says that sprawling Southern and Western cities like
Houston also have higher rates of aggressive driving deaths. It
rated Houston 14th worst out of 37 major metropolitan areas and
rated Texas 15th out of the 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   In both the walking and driving studies, the solution is
providing more alternatives to the car, the group said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many Houston residents would say ``amen'' to that.
The Texas Department of Transportation and city of Houston seem
unable to start building a promised 360-mile bike network through
the city. And it is probable that residents will be voting on
construction of a light rail system this fall.
</P>
<P>
   But a comparison of the methodologies for the walking report and
the driving report seems to show that the fix is in against Houston
from the folks back east.
</P>
<P>
   In the walking study, the project took each major city in the
country and divided the number of pedestrian fatalities by the
amount of walking activity.
</P>
<P>
   In the driving study, however, it took the number of aggressive
driving deaths and divided by the total population _ not by the
amount of driving.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, one study showed the relative danger of
performing the activity (walking), while the other simply showed
the overall likelihood of getting killed by the activity (driving)
in a given city.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem obvious that cities with more driving _ or, as the
new report put it, fewer alternatives to driving _ would have more
aggressive driving deaths and more driving deaths overall, said
several experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if people in Boston and Houston have equally mean
drivers, people in Houston will die more because they drive more,''
said Charles Peters, associate professor of mathematics at the
University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In the walking study, a city like New York was found to have
nearly three times as much pedestrian activity as Houston, meaning
New York was excused for three times as many deaths per 100,000
population.
</P>
<P>
   If the Surface Transportation Policy Project were a pro-driving,
anti-walking group, it could have reversed the methods of its two
reports. Perhaps it would have found that pedestrians in the
Northeast need to jump into a car before they get run over.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there's alternative forms of presenting data, people
choose the ones that support their theory,'' said Stephen
Klineberg, Rice professor of sociology and author of an annual poll
surveying attitudes in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The transportation project's reports are self-published and
handed out to the press corps. That contrasts with studies in
academic journals that require peer review.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule of thumb is that the writer believes the theory more
than the data. So the reviewer looks at the data to see if it
justifies the theory,'' Klineberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Garland, a co-author of the driving report, said the
walking and driving reports were not meant to be compared.
</P>
<P>
   If a variable like vehicle-miles traveled in each city were used
in the comparison, ``it wouldn't demonstrate what we're trying to
say,'' Garland said.
</P>
<P>
   Peters, Klineberg and James Bradley of Calvin College in
Michigan, author of ``The Uses and Misuses of Data and Models,''
also had other concerns about the project's reports. The amount of
walking activity in each city was calculated using a U.S. Census
survey on the percentage of people who walk to work.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston it was 2.3 percent, and in the New York region it was
6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those may be the best walking statistics available, but they
don't represent recreational walking and jogging. The differences
in those numbers, if they existed, might be enough to change the
results, Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Defining ``aggressive driving'' raised a host of other problems.
The transportation project used federal fatality data, searching
for accident causes like improper lane changes, speeding over 80
mph, high-speed chases and failure to obey traffic signals. It did
not include deaths caused by drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   On police reports, failure to obey traffic signals is a huge
factor in fatalities, but that doesn't necessarily equate to
aggressive driving. Much of it is inattention, police say.
</P>
<P>
   The five worst metropolitan areas for aggressive driving deaths
were found to be Riverside-San Bernardino, Calif.; Tampa-St.
Petersburg; Phoenix; Orlando and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The five best were Boston, the New York area, Minneapolis-St.
Paul, Pittsburgh and the Norfolk, Va., area.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Faul, spokeswoman for the AAA Foundation for Traffic
Safety, said she was surprised that the report found Boston drivers
to be the least likely to kill each other by aggressive driving.
</P>
<P>
   In federally funded surveys of motorists, she said, New England
drivers were judged to exhibit double the rate of aggressive
driving habits when compared to the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this study proves what they say it proves,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
